<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VOTE OF CONFIDENCE IN SPAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 15:
</P>
<P>
   Something new and healthy is going on in Spanish politics, and
Sunday's election results provide tangible proof. Party loyalties
that were carried over from the civil war era and the long
right-wing dictatorship of Francisco Franco are finally breaking
down, yielding to a more pragmatic politics that judges governments
by their performance.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar is a clear beneficiary. He has
led his conservative Popular Party toward a more modern and
centrist outlook and achieved notable economic successes. Yet
pundits expected Aznar to emerge from last weekend's election with
only a narrow victory. Instead, his party won an absolute
parliamentary majority, the best performance by the Spanish
center-right since democracy returned almost 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago Aznar edged into power amid voter revulsion at
Socialist financial scandals. A colorless politician who had
dabbled in far-right causes during his youth, he won only a bare
plurality and depended on support from a Catalan regional party.
But Aznar has now established firm centrist credentials and drawn
support from traditionally Socialist voters with his achievements.
During his tenure Spain created 2 million jobs, as many as the 14
other members of the European Union combined. It also met the
rigorous fiscal and monetary tests for joining the European
Monetary Union. Aznar continued the privatization of state-owned
industries, cut government bureaucracy and promoted agricultural
exports.
</P>
<P>
   Despite charges that some of his closest personal associates
reaped large profits from privatization deals, Aznar's economic
policies proved so popular that the Socialist campaign promised to
follow a similar course. But voters showed little interest in
returning the Socialists to office, particularly after they formed
a disastrous electoral pact with the former Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from dependence on his former allies and their demands for
regional spending, Aznar can press ahead with fresh economic
reforms. Despite Spain's impressive job creation, unemployment, at
15 percent, is still painfully high, and incomes remain lower than
elsewhere in Western Europe. But his most important challenge will
be to manage the needs of Spain's distinctive regions. These have
spawned a multiplicity of parties and, in the Basque country,
terrorist violence.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the Basque terrorist group ETA broke off a
14-month-long cease-fire. Its bombings and threats marred this
otherwise positive election campaign. Renewing the cease-fire and
resuming peace talks will require a deft mix of firmness and
conciliation. Aznar's new majority could give him the strength to
succeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
