<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGED BY FATHER, BOY KILLS HIM, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. _ An argument between a father and his
10-year-old son about a missing container of chocolate frosting
escalated into a killing here Monday night, as the man challenged
the boy to stab him. The boy did so, with the 5-inch kitchen knife
his father handed him, inflicting a single fatal chest wound, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers responding to a 911 call found Andrew Harms, 38, a
welder and father of three, lying on the floor of his two-car
garage. He was pronounced dead at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Ocean County prosecutor, E. David Millard, said that after
detectives questioned the fourth-grader and other family members,
the boy was charged as a juvenile with manslaughter, and not
murder, because Millard said he thought the boy had been provoked
into the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Harms, who believed the boy had taken the frosting, took him to
the garage, away from the other children in the house, and there,
Millard said, ``the discussion became heated and emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the dispute, Harms put the knife in the boy's
hand and told him to stab him if he hated him so much, Millard
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant responded by plunging the knife into his
chest,'' Millard said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the stabbing occurred so quickly that another
family member watching the argument was unable to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the manslaughter charge carries a maximum term of three
years for a juvenile, Millard suggested he would not seek
incarceration because of what he called the underlying facts and
circumstances of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the investigation thus far had not turned up any
indication that the boy had had previous difficulties with the law,
at home or at school. At a news conference here Tuesday afternoon,
Millard identified the boy only as John Doe because of New Jersey's
juvenile privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was being held in the county youth shelter, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, the boy's parents separated. He and his two
siblings, who were not identified, lived with their father and his
fiancee and her three children in a modest, rented home.
</P>
<P>
   His mother lives in neighboring Monmouth County, Millard said.
He would not identify her.
</P>
<P>
   The family's immediate neighbors described the six children in
Harms' home as polite and eager to help residents mow their lawns,
rake leaves or shovel snow.
</P>
<P>
   John Gonzalez, who lives next door, called Harms a good
neighbor. ``I liked him and I liked the kids,'' Gonzalez said.
``They are all very polite.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Harms often played football with the children at a
nearby school playground. Last summer, he said, Harms owned a small
boat and sometimes took the children crabbing or swimming on
Barnegat Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife died a couple of months ago, and the whole family was
very helpful,'' Gonzalez said, tears brimming in his eyes. ``When
she died, they were the first ones I called.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
