<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUSPENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SUSPENDS 3 PLAYERS FOR OFF-THE-FIELD VIOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League, facing a growing public relations
problem as off-the-field violence by its players reached a new
level, suspended three players on Tuesday for two games each. It
was the first time that playing time has been revoked for
first-time offenders under the league's violent-crime policy.
</P>
<P>
   For their involvement in a bar fight last summer, the former
Jets Matt O'Dwyer and Jumbo Elliott were suspended without pay for
the first two games of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Denard Walker, a starting cornerback for the Tennessee Titans ,
was also suspended without pay for the first two games after
pleading guilty to assault on the mother of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elliott recently announced his retirement, the league
informed him he would have to serve his suspension first if he
decided to return to the NFL. O'Dwyer now plays for the Cincinnati
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Jets tackle Jason Fabini, who was also involved in the fight
last July at a Long Island bar, was fined $14,000, the equivalent
of his salary for one game.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1997, the league's anti-crime policy previously
led to fines or mandated counseling, or both, for players who had
pleaded guilty to violent crimes or accepted plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   But with Baltimore linebacker Ray Lewis and Rae Carruth, a
former Carolina wide receiver, accused of murder, Tuesday's
announcement seemed an attempt by the league to set a more
stringent course.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an organization whose continued success depends on
integrity and public confidence, the NFL simply cannot tolerate
conduct that victimizes other individuals and results in a loss of
respect for NFL players,'' Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said in a
statement. ``We instituted this policy during the 1997 season with
counseling only. In 1998, we began fining employees for violations.
Now that the policy has been in effect for three seasons, we are
raising the disciplinary standard in order to underscore that this
type of behavior will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Crimes that fall under the league's programs include the use or
threat of physical violence, the use of a deadly weapon, illegal
possession of a weapon, hate crimes, the destruction of property
and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Any NFL employee or player charged with one of these crimes must
undergo counseling. A conviction or guilty plea has subjected a
player to a fine or the possibility of a suspension without pay as
determined by the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, a longer suspension, and possibly banishment,
can follow a second conviction.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dwyer, Elliott and Fabini were arrested on July 10, 1999.
O'Dwyer later pleaded guilty to assault and disorderly conduct
charges and received three years of probation. He was also ordered
to pay $4,373 in restitution for kicking out a police car window.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also pleaded guilty to harassment and disorderly conduct
and received a $250 fine and was ordered to perform 50 hours of
community service. Fabini received a lesser sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Walker received probation after pleading guilty on Aug. 11 to
assault on Rhonda Lynn Chesser, the mother of Walker's 19-month-old
son. She alleged that Walker threatened, punched and tried to
strangle her.
</P>
<P>
   Walker told the police that he and Chesser argued and
``basically wrestled on the floor, with some punches thrown not to
be harmful.'' He said he received ``marks around my neck, with some
minor scratches'' in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
