<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER ACCUSED OF FALSE TESTIMONY KILLS HIMSELF, AUTHORITIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A veteran police officer who was facing possible
dismissal after testifying falsely in state court about a 1998
arrest shot and killed himself with his service weapon early
Tuesday, hours before he was scheduled to testify again about the
arrest in federal court, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, James Sullivan, 34, who had made nearly 100 arrests
and earned nearly two dozen commendations in his nine-year career,
was found in his car at 12:50 a.m. along the Sunken Meadow Parkway
and the Jericho Turnpike, police said. Sullivan was married and had
two children.
</P>
<P>
   About six hours before his body was found, Sullivan had been
served with a subpoena to testify Tuesday at a federal parole
revocation hearing in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn for the man
he had arrested in 1998, Stanford Francis, said senior police
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan and his partner, Officer Edward Melin, arrested Francis
on charges of attempted murder and gun possession on Dec. 30, 1998,
after a shooting in the East New York section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, who had three prior convictions, including one in
federal court for conspiracy to distribute cocaine, was tried in
state court and acquitted on all charges stemming from the 1998
arrest. Because it is illegal for a felon to possess a gun, federal
prosecutors obtained an indictment against Francis after the state
acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, during trial preparation for the federal case,
the prosecutor, Eric A. Tirschwell, said he learned that Sullivan
had testified falsely about the events that occurred immediately
after Francis was arrested in 1998, according to a March 9 letter
from Tirschwell to the judge in the federal case, Reena Raggi,
seeking to dismiss the indictment because of the false testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The government intended to go forward with a hearing to revoke
Francis' parole for a prior federal narcotics conviction because of
the gun arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In the state trial, Sullivan and Melin both testified that the
gun taken from Francis was transported back to the precinct station
house in the trunk of their patrol car, the letter said. Both men
also testified that Sullivan had picked up the .45-caliber
semiautomatic pistol from the ground where Francis had dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan told Tirschwell last Wednesday that in fact Melin
had picked up the gun and handed it to him and that he had put it
on the front seat of the patrol car, not in the trunk. He told the
prosecutor he had not been truthful in his testimony on these two
points, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Commissioner Howard Safir announced a policy that he
would fire any officer for lying to a superior or in an official
proceeding. Several officials said that Sullivan had been told to
bring a lawyer for his testimony Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior police official said state prosecutors had indicated
that they did not plan to pursue perjury charges because the lies
were not material to the case, but an official in the Brooklyn
district attorney's office said the case had not yet been reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was the second police officer to commit suicide this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
