<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXPERT' TOURNEY ANALYSIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idle thoughts and random opinions as Your Vaunted Hoops Expert
awaits the derisive laughter when he finishes last in the office
NCAA Tournament bracket pool behind the couple who let their
six-month-old toddler pick the teams:
</P>
<P>
   _ The more Kenyon Martin's season-ending injury is replayed in
my mind, the more difficult is to believe. Martin, a tremendous
athlete, snapped his fibula when, basically, he tripped and fell.
Now can Cincinnati get back up?
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin's injury did what few seemed possible _ turn the Big
Bad Bearcats into lovable underdogs. The day after his surgery,
Martin attended Cincinnati's practice. He intends to be there to
encourage his teammates during the postseason. A Cincinnati run to
the Final Four would make a great story because Martin has handled
his injury with grace and courage.
</P>
<P>
   _ They say it, but you don't have to believe it. NCAA Tournament
committee chairman Craig Thompson says the pairings are not made
based on personalities or matchups. But consider these: Missouri
(coached by former Duke assistant Quin Snyder) vs. North Carolina.
A possible South Regional semifinal between Ohio State and
Cincinnati (who haven't played each other since 1962). A possible
second-round matchup between Arizona's Lute Olson and Fresno
State's Jerry Tarkanian (who have never sent each other Christmas
cards).
</P>
<P>
   _ Kansas State naming Jim Wooldridge its next basketball coach
might not qualify as a ``sexy hire.'' But Iowa State didn't exactly
cause a stir when it hired Larry Eustachy from Utah State two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   There's no truth to the rumor that Kansas State football coach
Bill Snyder was asked if he might consider adding ``basketball
coach'' to his job description.
</P>
<P>
   Wooldridge's biggest challenge: removing the perception that
Kansas State is now a football school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nebraska is willing to pay big bucks for a top-flight coach.
Bill Self of Tulsa is its main target. Some say that Nebraska is a
great job. Others aren't so sure. Self must decide if he needs to
strike while the iron is hot (his Tulsa team went 29-4 this
season).
</P>
<P>
   _ Utah State _ basketball coaching factory. First, Eustachy
leaves to coach Iowa State after leading the Aggies to a 25-8
record his final season. Stew Morrill, his replacement, has Utah
State 28-5 and on a national-best 19-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   _ The off-the-court story this season involves the NCAA cracking
down on eligibility and amateurism issues. NCAA enforcement
administrators say they are just following up on tips they receive.
Translation: When a player from School A is suspended, the lead
that created the suspension typically comes from School B. Just
like they used to do it in the old SWC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Indiana State coach Royce Waltman had this to say about the
Sycamores being assigned to Salt Lake City: ``I've been there, and
it's a great place to go. As would Madagascar if that's where they
had scheduled our first round.'' Hey, Royce. Madagascar is the site
of this year's East Regional. It's just commonly known as Syracuse.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
