<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS FUTURE THREATENED BY LAWSUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that Major League Soccer has been in a long-standing
legal dispute with its players generally comes as news to even the
most devoted soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens after the jury trial of Ian Fraser, et al. v.
Major League Soccer, LLC _ set to begin Sept. 18 _ might signal the
beginning of the end for MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Ten MLS players, representing the league's original teams, head
a class-action suit, filed in February 1999, that claims MLS's
single-entity structure violates U.S. antitrust law. The players
claim the concept's goal is to control player movement and keep
salary levels low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome will determine whether MLS continues to move
forward or withers,'' Chicago Fire president Bob Sanderman said.
``I can't see how it would be possible to continue on if players
win the lawsuit. It's that simple, and I've told our teams that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would upset everything that we've spent five years
creating. There is a revenue sharing between the league and the
teams, and cost sharing. It would be back to square one, and I
don't think the investors would be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the financial future of MLS. If the players win in
court and this season does not produce significant increases in
attendance or television ratings, investors might not keep pouring
money into the league.
</P>
<P>
   The suit primarily focuses on the league's single-entity
concept.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1996, MLS is a centrally operated league, like the
former American Basketball League, which folded in December 1998.
Under the single-entity format, the league _ instead of its
individual teams _ controls all players' salaries, the lengths of
contracts, trades and transfers to foreign clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, players are looking for a free-agency system
similar to ones in Major League Baseball and the NFL, NBA and NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between a free market, and that's all that
people want in any business,'' said goalkeeper Mark Dodd, the
Burn's representative as one of the 10 players named in the suit.
Added Jeffrey L. Kessler, an antitrust specialist representing the
players: ``It is 100 percent complete elimination of competition.
If other companies tried to do this, they'd go to jail. Their
defense is that they are a single entity, but it's a complete
sham.''
</P>
<P>
   The MLS minimum salary for players is $24,000, and the maximum
is $247,200. On the larger scale of professional sports, those
paychecks are pocket change. The average income in the MLS is
around $90,000, much less than recent averages for the NBA ($2.6
million), Major League Baseball ($1.6 million) and the NHL
(approximately $1.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with financial responsibility and
salary-cap type things,'' Dodd said. ``Really, all the players are
saying is that by having the ability to negotiate with other teams,
it just means that you may change your salary, for better or for
worse. But you're not going to change the overall (league
salary).''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation and FIFA _ soccer's world governing
body _ are also named as defendants in the suit. The suit alleges
that the bodies ``conspired to eliminate such competition among
themselves, through among other things, group boycotts, concerted
refusals to deal except on uniform terms, combining assets and the
creation of a `sham' single entity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a concern about the outcome,'' MLS chief
operating officer Mark Abbott said. ``We know we're going to win.
That being said, we'd just as soon sit down and negotiate with the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand their (adamant stand about their chances to
win the lawsuit). We've spent years looking at this structure. ...
That isn't a concern for us.''
</P>
<P>
   If the players win, it could set a precedent affecting other
centrally owned sports leagues, such as the proposed women's soccer
league and Isiah Thomas' Continental Basketball Association. NFL
Europe also operates under the single-entity format.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the players' suit also say having free agency
would help bolster fan interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a concept where the league hires all its players
and disperses them to all the teams is un-American,'' said John
Kerr, executive director of the MLS Players Association. ``Not
letting each team make its way in the world and win or lose based
on choices it makes, that's not what fans like. I think it's
holding us back.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are being helped financially to press their suit by
the NFL Players Association, which is also the home of the MLS
Players Association. For various labor-law reasons, the suit was
not filed by the soccer players association but as a class
representing all current and future players in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Since the league's inception in 1996, players and MLS officials
held several meetings to discuss overall concerns with the
single-entity concept, Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was very excited when the league came into existence,
and then everybody was really taken aback when you find out that
there is one person controlling all the decisions with regards to
your salary, length of contract and your rights,'' Dodd said.
``Players obviously became very disgruntled with that sort of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the lawsuit was filed, the league has experienced
significant changes. Near the end of last season, former
commissioner Doug Logan was fired after the league's attendance
average from slipped to 14,282 from 15,375. Former NFL executive
Don Garber stepped in. Since Garber came aboard, the league has
eliminated the shootout, loosened its purse strings to keep
overseas-bound stars in the league and strengthened its television
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the pending suit, which had been in the discovery phase
until the court date was announced last month, brings about a
potentially unprecedented overhaul. To this point, it's still
fairly quiet; Sanderman said most of the players on the Fire's
roster were not completely aware of all the underlying issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes play for the love of game, but they also play for
financial incentive,'' Dodd said. ``If you take away the financial
incentive, you've taken away an important part of the motivational
process. And over 200 players, year after year, that adds up. As an
owner, I think you have to ask yourself, `Am I getting the most out
of my players?' And I'm not sure the answer would be yes.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
