<SLUG> BC-BKC-BRACKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS TO MAKE A SPLASH IN YOUR POOL PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Omens. Facts. Darts. Take your pick of methods to determine your
NCAA Tournament bracket office-pool selections. This year, with the
tournament expected to be more wide open than ever, any system
should work.
</P>
<P>
   But before beginning today's primer, a word about office pools.
Yes, it's three weeks of thrills or embarrassment (depending on the
accuracy of your selections). Yes, there are an estimated 640 Web
sites that you can visit to set up and track your brackets. Yes,
they're a form of gambling. And no, they don't allow bracket pools
in the NCAA offices (because it's a form of gambling).
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin, and please no wagering.
EAST REGION
</P>
<P>
   OMEN FOR: Duke. The last three times that Duke has been a No. 1
seed in the East Region, the Blue Devils have advanced to the Final
Four (1986, 1992, 1999). Each of those Final Four visits brought a
visit to the national championship game. Duke won the title in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS SUPPORTING: Temple. The Owls have won 17 of their past 18,
have a savvy point guard in Pepe Sanchez and a matchup zone defense
that is the Rubik's Cube of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   DART TOSS: Illinois. The Illini have won 10 of their past 12,
they're young and talented with an experienced coach (Lon Kruger),
and they don't have to face Michigan State (two losses by a total
of 40 points). SOUTH REGION
</P>
<P>
   OMEN AGAINST: Stanford. The South has been a graveyard for No. 1
seeds. Kentucky, riding a sizzling 3-point attack in 1993, is the
only No. 1 seed to advance out of the South _ and formerly
Southeast _ Region the past 11 seasons. Five of the past 11 years,
the South No. 1 failed to reach the regional final. The jinx has
claimed teams such as Duke, Kansas, Connecticut and Kentucky. The
average record of the South No. 1 seed the past 11 years has been
27-3; the Cardinal's record is 26-3.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS AGAINST: Connecticut. The Huskies have been inconsistent.
Their nine losses are the most for a defending champion who made
the next season's field since Villanova in 1986. UConn plays
12th-seeded Utah State. In each of the past 11 NCAA Tournaments a
No. 12 seed has beaten a No. 5 seed.
</P>
<P>
   DART TOSS: Cincinnati. Even with a No. 2 seed, the Bearcats are
considered a dark horse. MIDWEST REGION
</P>
<P>
   OMEN FOR: Michigan State. In the 1990s, the Final Four had
repeat teams eight times. The Spartans, who lost to Duke in last
year's semifinals, have a veteran team with a veteran point guard.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS SUPPORTING: Iowa State. Of the last 32 Final Four
entrants, 27 have won either their regular-season or tournament
titles. Six of those teams, like the Cyclones, pulled a league
double. Three of those teams have won national championships. Three
of last year's Final Four teams had a league double.
</P>
<P>
   DART TOSS: UCLA. The Bruins have won six consecutive games and
finally have their full roster. WEST REGION
</P>
<P>
   OMEN FOR: St. John's. The past three Big East Conference teams
to reach the Final Four all came out of the West Region _ Seton
Hall in 1989, Syracuse in 1996 and Connecticut last year. All three
of those teams reached the championship game, and the Huskies won
the title.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS SUPPORTING: Oklahoma. Teams such as Ohio State (1999),
Utah and Stanford (1998), Syracuse (1996), Florida and Arizona
(1994) have reached the Final Four after a season of playing well,
but not winning, in a strong conference.
</P>
<P>
   DART TOSS: Fresno State. The Bulldogs have a tournament-tested
coach (Jerry Tarkanian), the nation's leading scorer (Courtney
Alexander), five starters who can score (82.9 points per game) and
a favorable draw.
</P>
<P>
   So, there you go. Three types of advice to suit your bracket
pool tastes. If none of these methods works, please know that the
phone number and e-mail address that follows will be experiencing
technical difficulties for the next three weeks.
FINAL FOURSOMES
Players on a roll Iowa State's Marcus Fizer Arizona's Luke Walton
Fresno State's Courtney Alexander Arkansas' Joe Johnson
Teams to embrace Temple in the East St. John's in the West Iowa
State in the Midwest None in the South
Dark horses Miami (Fla.) in the South Illinois in the East UCLA in
the Midwest LSU in the West
Teams to avoid DePaul: Young, inconsistent North Carolina: Living
on reputation Tennessee: Talented but erratic Kansas: 8-7 since
mid-January
Four first-round upsets Utah State over Connecticut Butler over
Florida Gonzaga over Louisville Creighton over Auburn
Best first-round matchups Wisconsin vs. Fresno State Samford vs.
Syracuse Missouri vs. North Carolina UNLV vs. Tulsa
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
