<HEADLINE>
HOLDOUT DEFENDER JOINS BURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burn defender Jorge Rodriguez, who has been holding out
throughout the preseason, showed up at practice Monday and said
Tuesday he is attempting to renegotiate his contract with Major
League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had returned to his native El Salvador because he was
seeking to double his salary, which is believed to be at least
$70,000. However, he said he has returned to the team, at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn opens its season at 3:30 p.m. Saturday against the
Chicago Fire at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has asked me to show good faith and come back to
the team and start training and become part of the team again,''
Rodriguez said. ``We hope this leads to more open negotiations and
a development in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS executive vice president of player relations and operations
Ivan Gazidis said Rodriguez's return is a positive development.
Gazidis also said the league was considering reworking Rodriguez's
contract before his holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be where we were before all of this happened, but to
reward a player for holding out is not fair to the other players
who reported for training and honored their contract commitments,''
Gazidis said. ``We do not want to reward him for the tactic that he
employed, but we could be rewarding him in the way we were prepared
to do anyway, which is a new contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In other Burn news, defender Ricardo Iribarren said Tuesday he
plans to sign with the Burn this week. Iribarren, who played for
Columbus for two seasons, has trained with the Burn for most of the
preseason. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
