<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOLDSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH GOLDSTEIN, 76, AUTHORITY ON FAMILY LAW
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Spelling of Mariam is CQ.) 
(fb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Goldstein, a longtime law professor at Yale who was
widely known for his interdisciplinary approach to family law and
other legal fields, died on Sunday at a hospital in New Haven. He
was 76 and lived in Woodbridge, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said the Yale Law School's
director of public affairs, Elizabeth Stauderman.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who was also a psychoanalyst, was a co-author of
three books that, as Martin Guggenheim, a professor of law at New
York University, put it, became ``required reading for judges and
practitioners in the field of child custody and other legal issues
relating to judicial decisions concerning a child's future.''
</P>
<P>
   The books are ``Beyond the Best Interests of the Child'' (1973),
``Before the Best Interests of the Child'' (1979) and ``The Best
Interests of the Child'' (1986). Dr. Goldstein wrote them with Anna
Freud, the psychoanalyst and daughter of Sigmund Freud, and Albert
J. Solnit, the director of the Yale Child Study Center.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein joined the law school's faculty in 1956 and retired in
1993. He continued lecturing at the law school and doing research
until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Alan M. Dershowitz, the Felix Frankfurter Professor of Law at
Harvard Law School and a former student of Goldstein's, said that
Goldstein ``introduced, probably more than anyone else, real
interdisciplinary thinking in the law school and thus the legal
world in general.'' His influence was widely felt, Dershowitz said,
through both his writing and his influential students.
</P>
<P>
   Central to Goldstein's and his co-authors' thinking, Guggenheim
said, was the idea ``that courts should choose the alternative that
was the least detrimental to the interest of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   That principle, in the authors' view, followed from an even more
basic one: They were highly distrustful of the capacity of judges
to make intelligent decisions about custody arrangements. And so,
Guggenheim said, ``they wanted courts to have very limited
authority to intervene in a family.''
</P>
<P>
   The books also expressed the view that custody disputes should
be looked at from the point of view of children, especially their
perspective on time. For example, for very young children, six
months might be 100 percent of their life, not six months in the
life of a 40-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   In the foster care side of family law, Guggenheim said,
Goldstein and his co-authors encouraged the acceleration of
termination of parental rights in cases where children were in
foster care.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of their work,'' Guggenheim said, ``statutes were
rewritten to shorten the length of time children should be in
foster care before courts would terminate the right of the natural
parents, freeing the children to become eligible to be adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's work involving family law, Dershowitz said, was an
application of his thinking about the interface between psychiatry
and the law. Early in his career he began studying issues related
to the insanity defense. Goldstein went on to write ``The Family
and the Law'' (1965) with Jay Katz, a Yale Law School professor and
psychiatrist, and ``Psychoanalysis, Psychiatry and the Law'' (1966)
with Katz and Dershowitz. He finished his own psychoanalytic
training in 1968 at the Western New England Psychoanalytic
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed both law and psychoanalysis'' by bringing them
together,'' Dershowitz said. ``In the world of law, he made us all
think about the role of law as superego, how we internalize law,
how we make it part of our personality. And then, I think, he used
the concept of law to help broaden and make more meaningful
concepts like the superego and psychoanalysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Goldstein was born in Springfield, Mass. He received a
bachelor's degree from Dartmouth, a doctorate from the London
School of Economics and a law degree from Yale, where he was an
editor of the Yale Law Journal.
</P>
<P>
   He was a law clerk for Judge David L. Bazelon of the U.S. Court
of Appeals in Washington and taught briefly at Stanford Law School
before returning to Yale as an associate professor of law.
</P>
<P>
   He was also an author, co-author or editor of books on criminal
law, on the My Lai massacre and on constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   He was an Army code-breaker in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein is survived by his wife, the former Sonja Lambek, who
was one of his co-authors; three sons, Joshua, of Cambridge, Mass.,
Jeremiah, of Philadelphia, and Daniel, of Davis, Calif.; a
daughter, Anne Goldstein of Hartford, Conn.; eight grandchildren; a
brother, E. Ernest Goldstein, who lives in Texas, and a sister,
Mariam Sommer of New Haven, Conn..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 0009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
