<HEADLINE>
BRUINS, MARTIN TRYING TO SALVAGE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the start of the season, women's basketball
coaches and media predicted UCLA to repeat as Pacific-10 Conference
champions and reach the NCAA Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, they predicted forward Maylana Martin would be an
All- American (Women's Basketball News Service named her Preseason
Player of the Year) and a possible first pick in the WNBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't panned out that way. UCLA failed to win the
conference and, at a 10th seed, is a longshot to reach the Final
Four. To do so likely would mean having to beat Tennessee in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin, she put up her usual numbers: 17.8 points (tops
in the Pac-10) and 8.6 rebounds per game (second highest), all
while playing with a weak back (she had off-season surgery). She
made all-conference and has been invited to play in the Women's
Basketball Coaches Association All-Star Game on April 1 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the Associated Press All-America team came out Tuesday,
Martin had fallen all the way to honorable mention (there are three
teams of five players).
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA draft is weeks away, and Martin is more likely a
potential first-round pick instead of a No. 1 selection.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that isn't where Martin's focus is these days. She's
preparing for Friday's NCAA first-round game against George
Washington at South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she knows what could have been. If everyone was healthy,
then maybe UCLA would have won the conference and would be hosting
the first two rounds and would be in the West region instead of the
Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole year was hard for us,'' she said. ``We lost some bad
games, and we were all kind of focused on ourselves and how we can
help the team instead of each individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Memory loss: The excitement of seeing her school's name was so
great, Damaris Hinojosa forgot about the particulars.
</P>
<P>
   Hinojosa, a freshman from Moorpark, watched Sunday's selection
show with her Pepperdine teammates, then cheered mightily when she
saw the Waves had made their first NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, Hinojosa stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute,'' she said, ``Who are we playing and where are
we going?''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling Waves: Pepperdine's players claim coach Mark Trakh has
made their trip to Charlottesville, Va., longer than necessary
because of his fear of propeller planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves planned to leave this morning for Dulles Airport,
outside of Washington, then take a two-hour bus ride to
Charlottesville.
</P>
<P>
   The players wanted to fly a propeller plane, but Trakh wouldn't
hear of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those four tires are on the ground,'' Trakh said of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   To which Hinojosa taunted: ``He's afraid of the propellers. I've
flown in a couple. They're not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing homework: When Pepperdine drew Virginia, Trakh and the
coaching staff called all of the Cavaliers' nonconference opponents
seeking video (he didn't expect Atlantic Coast Conference teams to
help).
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday morning, Siena and Kent had responded. By Tuesday
afternoon, tapes arrived from Loyola (Chicago), Virginia Tech, Old
Dominion and Arkansas State, plus tapes of Boston College, a
possible second-round opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Trakh took his tapes and went home.
</P>
<P>
   To which Hinojosa responded: ``Don't forget to sleep, Coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
