<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NAVY-INJURED-BABY-NYT     03-15 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-INJURED-BABY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: AFTER INJURY, THE INSULT OF LATE AID
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. _ The horror began last Mother's Day. Sean
Tobin, a young hospital corpsman at the Navy submarine base in
Groton, told the police that he grew so frustrated with his
6-week-old son, who was crying and refusing a bottle, that he shook
him until his ``neck appeared very loose and his head was rolling
around.'' Then he slammed the baby on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the baby was unlikely to survive, and the family
removed life supports. But the baby, Vincent Tobin, lived. Nearing
his first birthday, he is almost totally blind, severely
hearing-impaired and unable to crawl or sit up on his own. Cerebral
palsy has been diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal case moved efficiently. Sean Tobin, 20, pleaded
guilty to assault. At an emotional hearing in Superior Court here
earlier this month, a judge sentenced him to 18 years in state
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The disposition for Vincent Tobin has been anything but
efficient. Born a healthy son of a Navy man, he is now the
medically needy son of a convict. Along the way, he lost one thing
he desperately needed, health insurance. A case that began with one
man's rage became a parable for the chronic frustration of
navigating the health insurance system.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, Tina Riggio, Vincent's mother, was suddenly the
unemployed mother of a baby who needed her constant attention as
well as specialized medical care. She moved in with her parents
near Orlando, Fla., and took her son to pediatricians, neurologists
and eye doctors. He began physical and speech and occupational
therapy five days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will eventually be in a wheelchair,'' Riggio said. ``If he
doesn't learn to use his hands, he will have a feeding tube. He
will never walk. He will never talk. He will actually get very
stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bills, many with notations like, ``For us to
continue providing medical services, you must pay outstanding
balance immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has a program to assist dependents of military
personnel who leave the service due to domestic abuse, which is
paying Riggio $1,078 a month for three years. The money helps,
since she cannot both work and care for Vincent. (She worked at a
Pizza Hut before he was injured.) But it doesn't begin to cover
Vincent's medical care. Riggio applied many months ago for health
insurance under the same program, and waited for the Navy to
respond, with unpaid bills approaching $5,000 as of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Stellabotte, an administrative assistant at the Easter
Seals clinic in Deltona, Fla., where Vincent received therapy, said
Tricare, the military medical plan, returned his bills, saying
without explanation that he was not covered. Medicaid, for which
Riggio and Vincent qualified, also refused, saying Tricare was the
primary insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Stellabotte said that Easter Seals often treated uninsured
children but that Riggio stopped taking her son for $55-a-day
sessions in December, fearing it would only add to the stack of
unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   Riggio arrived at her husband's sentencing carrying their
dark-haired, olive-skinned baby and a sheaf of his bills. But the
hearing concerned the crime, not the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Riggio, the baby's maternal grandfather and namesake,
told the judge: ``He has no idea who I am. He has no idea who my
wife is.'' Sean Tobin, he said, ``destroyed my grandson.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's mother, Renee, said, ``My son's not a bad man, he's a
good boy.'' She told the judge that ``I am the product of physical
abuse, sexual abuse, verbal abuse,'' and said that ``as parents we
don't recognize what we teach our children until it is too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent, cradled in his mother's lap, let loose with a cry. Then
his father was taken away to prison.
</P>
<P>
   There he will have a full range of medical, mental health and
dental services. For prisoners, at least, medical care is a right.
</P>
<P>
   For Vincent, it was far more complicated. ``I can really assure
you that the Navy is working with this family to help them get any
benefits, medical or monetary, that they are entitled to,'' was all
Lt. Sandra Johnson, assistant legal counsel for Navy Personnel
Command, would say about Vincent on Friday after several calls to
the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   That was news to Riggio, who felt alone against the Navy. Then,
Tuesday afternoon, a Navy official called Riggio to say she and
Vincent would receive Tricare. ``These things take some time,''
said Lt. Ingrid Mueller, a Navy spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In Vincent's case, it took nine months, or about three-quarters
of his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
