<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE TO START LATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ The good news for Pepperdine is that Friday's
NCAA Tournament opener against Indiana will be televised in prime
time locally, at 7:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that in Buffalo, N.Y., that's 10:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That's a long time waiting around for tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never played !off!that!ital! late before,'' Pepperdine
guard Brandon Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an edge to be found, perhaps this one goes to the
Waves. Their bodies should still be on West Coast time, and their
home games normally start at 7 p.m. anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess maybe it'll give us a chance to get over the hype of
playing in the NCAA,'' Armstrong said. ``We can calm down and
concentrate on getting ready.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, anyway, Pepperdine doesn't think it's a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to stay focused on the game and what we have to
do,'' guard Craig Lewis said. ``It doesn't matter what time it is.
It's a business trip so we've got to look at it like that. No
matter what time it is, we just have to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying through the weekend: Last week, Pepperdine's focus was
on making it to the tournament. Now, the objective is to stick
around. That's been one of the themes during practice the last
couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Waves would face either Oklahoma State or
Hofstra if they beat Indiana on Friday,
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we got in, all that's over with,'' Lewis said. ``Now
we want to stay as long as we can. We feel confident, and that's
good, that's what we need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
