A7142 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-15 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT CASTS RED SHADOW ON PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ A writer with a bit too much red in his shirt
sat in the stands, watching Pepperdine's basketball team go through
its pre-tournament maneuvers, when a student manager approached, a
counterintelligence officer on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure you're not one of Bobby Knight's
friends,'' he said with a sly laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Relax - there were no Friends of Bobby in Firestone Fieldhouse
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the presence of Bobby Knight was palpable during
Pepperdine's final practice before the team leaves for Buffalo and
its NCAA Tournament opener against Indiana on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Coach and legend, hero and antihero, Knight hung over the scene
like an overstretched red sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, more than any Pepperdine player, more than Indiana All-
American A.J. Guyton, is the star of this first-round matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, in the news again Tuesday because of an allegation of
violence by another ex-Hoosiers player, is going to be the story.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's face will be on TV Friday night more than Regis
Philbin's. Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff's face will be on
TV less than Gary Bauer's.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana and its coach have won three national championships in
the quarter-century it has taken Pepperdine to win three NCAA
Tournament games. He has, as he'd remind us, forgotten more about
the NCAA Tournament than the Waves will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   How can they fail to be intimidated by the thought of facing
Knight, distracted by the sight of the red sweater they've seen on
TV all their young lives?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely going to look,'' Pepperdine guard Tommie Prince
said. ``Actually, it's scary to me, because I watch Indiana a lot
on TV. To play them, it's a big situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Prince said, ``we can't be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight coached Isiah Thomas, who just happened to be Pepperdine
guard Tezale Archie's favorite player.
</P>
<P>
   How will that feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be dribbling any balls or taking any shots
or guarding any of us, so we'll leave the head games to coach van
Breda Kolff,'' Archie said.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the 24-8 Waves deserve their at-large berth in
the Final 64. Their coaches will drum home that point this week as
an antidote to intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-8 Hoosiers have no more right to be in Buffalo than they
do, and no more right to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana came in fifth in the Big Ten, not first,'' Pepperdine
assistant coach Chris Walker said. ``They're struggling a little
bit right now. They've lost four out of the last five times
(they've been to the NCAA Tournament) in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more worried about us than we are about them. They
have more to lose than we do. Our guys can go in relaxed. There's
no worrying about Bobby Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Walker pointed out, ``It would be a major coup for us if
we could beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pepperdine defeated Fresno State on the road in the second
game of the season, one of van Breda Kolff's assistants
congratulated the coach for beating Jerry Tarkanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You did a great job, you beat Fresno State, you beat
a coach who won a national championship,' '' van Breda Kolff
remembered. ``It never dawned on me ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We played Kansas (losing by 15) and we didn't look at that
game as `Gee, we're going up against Roy Williams.' Sometimes I
think coaching is overrated. Once the game starts, it's the players
who are going to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff, in his first season at Pepperdine after nine at
Cornell and Vanderbilt, doesn't know Knight personally, although
his father coached against Knight when Butch was at Princeton and
Bobby was at Army.
</P>
<P>
   But van Breda Kolff thinks he knows what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``His teams play hard. He's demanding of them. They're going to
get loose balls, draw charges, play a physical games and do the
things they need to do to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you worry about from a coaching standpoint is
you don't want a situation where he has a direct influence on how
the game is officiated. Watching him on TV, he's a boisterous
coach, and sometimes you see that ends up having an effect on one
or more than one official. Big Ten coaches say you've gotta be
careful of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that van Breda Kolff can do much if Knight decides to scream
at the refs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job as coaches is to get our players ready and not be too
concerned with the extraneous things like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably the refs, the chairs and Knight's own players who
should be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it was reported that Neil Reed, a guard who transferred
from Indiana to Southern Mississippi, claims Knight choked him
during a 1997 practice.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation enlarges Knight's reputation for volatility. That
reputation is the reason Knight's presence looms larger than, say,
Roy Williams'.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a source of inspiration, not intimidation, for the
Waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make Bobby Knight mad,'' Prince said with a smile,
``that would be really good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
