<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISTIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 McCAIN OFF BALLOT; POLL FAVORS DEMOCRAT; HATCH CHALLENGED; NADER (hm) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oregon officials have decided to remove Sen. John McCain's name
from the primary ballot in May, a move that has irked at least some
McCain supporters, who noted that he has not formally withdrawn
from the presidential race. McCain said last week that he was
suspending his campaign. The Oregon secretary of state, Bill
Bradbury, said voters would be presented with ``a false choice'' if
the senator's name remained on the ballot and that any die-hard
McCain supporters could still write in his name. The move leaves
two Republican candidates on the ballot, George W. Bush and Alan
Keyes, and two Democrats, Vice President Al Gore and Lyndon
LaRouche.
</P>
<P>
   POLL FAVORS FLORIDA DEMOCRAT
</P>
<P>
   A poll of registered voters in the U.S. Senate race in Florida
offered some encouragement to Bill Nelson, the lone Democrat and
the state insurance commissioner, and to Tom Gallagher, a
Republican and the education commissioner. It was less kind to Rep.
Bill McCollum, one of the House managers who prosecuted President
Clinton's impeachment trial. A survey of 621 registered voters
conducted by Mason-Dixon Polling and Research Inc. for The
Tallahassee Democrat found that Nelson would win a hypothetical
general election over McCollum by 43 percent to 33 percent. If
Nelson and Gallagher faced each other in November, the Democrat
would, hypothetically, win by just 39 percent to 38 percent. The
poll's margin of sampling error was four percentage points, making
that race too close to call. The poll showed McCollum and Gallagher
about even going into the Republican primary on Sept. 5. The
Republican incumbent, Connie Mack, is retiring after 12 years.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGING HATCH
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from an unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential
nomination, U.S. Sen. Orrin G. Hatch of Utah will not even have
clear sailing toward a fifth term. State Sen. Scott Howell, a
Democrat from Salt Lake City and state Senate minority leader since
1995, said Tuesday that he would oppose Hatch in November. For
Democrats, Howell is a lifesaver. After considering a run, Jan
Graham, the state attorney general and the only Democrat holding a
statewide office, said last month that she had decided not to
oppose Hatch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AN OPTIMISTIC NADER
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, who is running for president on the Green Party
ticket, told a group of students Tuesday that he planned to qualify
for the ballot in all 50 states. When he announced his candidacy
last month, Nader said he hoped to be on the ballot in 45 states
and win 5 percent of the vote. Speaking to students at the
University of Nevada in Reno, Nader said Tuesday that the Green
Party was ``growing quite readily'' as an alternative to the
Democratic and Republican parties, which he likened to ``one party
with two heads wearing makeup.'' Nader was on the ballot in less
than half the states as the Green Party candidate in 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES: GEORGE W. BUSH _ No events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Tallahassee, Fla.; Philadelphia; Pittsburgh; Moon
Township., Pa.; and Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
