</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GIBBS-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIBBS IS GLUE THAT HOLDS PEPPERDINE TOGETHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ It was a throwaway moment, the waning minutes
of a blowout victory for Pepperdine in a late-season game that had
no significant meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was the perfect opportunity for Kelvin Gibbs
to send a message.
</P>
<P>
   As the loose ball rolled toward the boundary, Gibbs raced over,
dove headfirst onto the floor, tapped the ball to a teammate, then
rolled out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine kept possession. Gibbs made his point.
</P>
<P>
   In the Waves' no-nonsense season, nothing is taken for granted,
not even 20-point leads in meaningless games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the writers came up to me after the game and asked, `How
do you get a guy, when your up by 20, to dive for the ball like
that?' '' Waves coach Jan van Breda Kolff said. ``It was a great
play, but he does things like that to ignite us. Our whole team
jumped up and we went on a 10-0 run and we were up by 30 in another
two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was typical Gibbs, a 6-foot-7 junior forward who set the tone
for the Waves' unselfish personality this year by sacrificing
individual statistics to help diversify the Waves' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (24-8) won the West Coast Conference regular-season
championship and earned a berth into the NCAA Tournament as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves open East Regional play Friday at 7:20 p.m. (West
Coast time) against Indiana in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   They might not be in the tournament had it not been for Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't make those sacrifices, I don't know where we'd
be,'' Pepperdine guard Tezale Archie said. ``We'd still be a good
team, but we definitely wouldn't be where we're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in then-Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar's
slow-it-down, grind-it-out offense, Gibbs was the team's
second-leading scorer and one of two main cogs offensively, along
with Jelani Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   It was a predictable attack that opponents could easily defend.
Stop Gardner, and you stopped Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was boring,'' Gibbs admits. ``It was a slugfest game.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff changed that when he took over after Romar left
for St. Louis. Pepperdine is now a pressing team that creates
turnovers and gets easy points in transition. When things slow down
to half-court sets, the Waves no longer rely on one or two players
for points. Everyone is urged to take advantage of open looks.
</P>
<P>
   It's been an easy sell for van Breda Kolff. The Waves prefer the
more wide-open offense, which is enjoyable to play and tougher to
defend. Besides, now there's six or seven happy players on offense
rather than two.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes at a price for Gibbs, whose points dropped from 11
points to nine. It could have been a delicate situation. Gibbs, who
averages 7.1 rebounds, was expected to score more, not less, once
Gardner graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he never made it an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the scoring wasn't a big thing,'' Gibbs said. ``I always
felt if I played the way I was capable of and did the things I
could do, I'd help my team win. I never thought about getting
numbers, I just thought about getting (wins).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the gesture was significant. Had Gibbs resisted the
change, it would have doomed van Breda Kolff's plan, and probably
the Waves' season. Once Gibbs embraced it, they developed into a
tournament team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't see (what Gibbs did) because it doesn't
get touched on,'' Archie said. ``But the guys in the locker room
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his scoring has dipped, Gibbs is more important to
Pepperdine now then at any point of his three-year career. On the
floor, he provided rugged defense and rebounding, medium-range
offense and an occasional 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Off court, his engaging personality blends well with
Pepperdine's diverse personalities, making him an ideal leader.
He's not afraid to speak up, but mature enough to chose his spots
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff picked up on those traits during meetings with
Gibbs in the offseason to discuss the changes. After talking with
Gibbs, van Breda Kolff was confident things would work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My first) week on the job he was in the office watching the
Gonzaga tape from last year when (Pepperdine lost) by 30,'' van
Breda Kolff said. ``He wanted to see what Gonzaga did to beat them.
He was already thinking about that six months before we played
them. He wanted to know what he could do to help the team, and said
whatever you want me to do I'll do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
