<HEADLINE>
PARK JUST THROWS, SUCCEEDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ So much of the Los Angeles Dodgers' success
this season rides on the right arm of Chan Ho Park, which explains
why manager Davey Johnson was so enthralled with what transpired
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After worrying about having the perfect mechanics in his first
two spring outings, the cerebral Park changed his focus to just
pitching. The results brought a huge smile to Johnson's face.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who had a 10.80 ERA, allowed one run in five innings. His
control, which was lacking, was much better as he struck out five
and walked one against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan Ho, that was large,'' Johnson said. ``His breaking stuff
is not where I'd like to see it, but he threw some breaking balls
over. That was a good, positive outing for him. He needed that. I
know that he's been a little confused at times with everybody
adding their two cents in there, but he went out there and threw
the ball for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Park spent the first few weeks of the season working with Sandy
Koufax and Orel Hershiser on his mechanics, particularly on keeping
his right leg straight to help his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my mechanics, I'm much more comfortable right now so I
don't have to worry about them on the mound,'' Park said. ``I can
just pitch. I don't know if I had good mechanics because I focused
on the pitches. But the pitching coach (Claude Osteen) and the
other guys told me I had better mechanics. I don't have to worry
about them on the mound anymore, maybe just in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Few chances remain: Several team officials said the Dodgers
front office is almost out of patience with left-handed Carlos
Perez, and his recent arrest for driving under the influence of
alcohol is just the latest piece in the disappointment pile.
Depending on his Friday start against St. Louis, Perez could be out
of the running for a starting spot by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will go with a five-man rotation after Perez and
Orel Hershiser pitch Friday, and who that fifth man will be depends
heavily on how Perez throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see progress,'' Johnson said. ``That's what spring
is about. It's not about having great outings. It's about having
better outings, stronger outings, sharper outings, going after the
hitters, keeping the ball down, being more pitch efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez has done none of those things in his first two outings. It
began with an abysmal five-run, two-inning outing, and was followed
by a four-run, three-inning process of extreme labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last time out - three innings, 73 pitches - we have to
improve on that,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Right-hander Gregg Olson, who last pitched March
7, threw on the side but still has minor irritation and
inflammation in his elbow, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``It seems like he's making progress,'' Malone said....
Right-hander Mike Fetters should make his Grapefruit League debut
Thursday.... Catcher Todd Hundley had his fourth straight day off
because of back spasms, but he said he plans to play today against
the Mets.... The Dodgers sent pitcher Chad Ricketts and infielder
Jorge Nunez to Triple-A Albuquerque and reassigned pitchers Jim
Bullinger and Maximo Nunez, infielder Adam Riggs and outfielder
Shawn Gilbert to minor-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
