<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW RECONSIDERS AND MAY SELL ITS MONEY-LOSING ROVER UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a startling about-face, BMW said Tuesday
that its supervisory board would consider selling most of Rover,
the money-losing British carmaker it bought six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Tuesday night, after a report in the
Munich newspaper Suddeutsche, BMW said that plans for a sell-off
were ``one of the imaginable scenarios'' that will be presented to
the supervisory board on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last month, BMW executives had been insisting
that they were not flinching from their commitment to Rover and
rejected overtures from Volkswagen and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Rover has consumed billions of dollars and brought the
German car maker a seemingly endless stream of problems. Rover lost
1.9 billion marks, about $1 billion, in 1998, and company
executives have already warned that the losses in 1999 were even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Rover is also running into unexpected problems in its
negotiations with the British government over a package of
subsidies to retrofit Rover's main British factory in Longbridge.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission raised new objections to the deal,
warning that the subsidies amounted to unjustified and illegal
government support of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The Longbridge plant outside Birmingham employs 9,000 workers,
and there has been persistent anxiety among Rover employees about
their future. Tens of thousands of supply-industry jobs that
indirectly rely on the Longbridge plant would also be vulnerable if
it was to be closed or sold.
</P>
<P>
   Many automobile analysts have argued for more than a year now
that BMW's strategy with Rover is misguided. The idea has always
been that owning Rover, which produces the popular Land Rover
sport-utility vehicle as well as a range of mass-market sedans,
would allow BMW to expand beyond its core business of making sporty
luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts argue that the strategy will only hurt
profits, not only because it consumes so much money but also
because profits are much lower in the mass-market segments than for
luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   The issue led to a huge boardroom fight more than a year ago and
to the resignation of BMW's previous chief executive, Bernd
Pischetsrieder.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Pischetsrieder's ouster and replacement by
Joachim Milberg, BMW seemed bent on pursuing exactly the same
strategy as before.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has begun freshening up and rethinking the Rover product
line. But the results have been modest, and company executives have
declined to predict when Rover will return to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from problems with the line-up of Rover sedans, the
company has been badly hurt by currency problems stemming from the
high value of the British pound.
</P>
<P>
   The pound has soared in relation to the euro, the currency for
most of Continental Europe, and one result has been that cars
produced in Germany, France and Italy are much cheaper than those
produced in Britain. British exports to the rest of Europe have
been strangled while imports into Britain have soared.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure has grown more intense as the global automobile
industry continues its relentless consolidation. Ford now owns
Volvo, not to mention Jaguar and Aston-Martin.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, General Motors announced plans to take a 20 percent
stake in Fiat.
</P>
<P>
   BMW, in which Germany's Quandt family owns a controlling stake,
has repeatedly refuted speculation that it might be willing to be
sold as well.
</P>
<P>
   But it is well known that many companies, from Ford to
Volkswagen, would jump at the chance to acquire BMW. Volkswagen,
headed by Ferdinand Piech, has been nudging the company but said
publicly last month that it had become convinced that BMW was not
interested in any deals.
</P>
<P>
   In its report on Tuesday, Suddeutsche said that Milberg would
present a plan to sell Rover's line of sedans to an unidentified
buyer that is not one of the ``established carmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   After first denying the report as ``pure speculation,'' BMW said
Tuesday night that some sort of sale involving Rover was among the
options under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The news had little impact on BMW shares, which rose 0.76 euro
on Tuesday, to 27.3 euros, or about $26.20, on the Frankfurt
exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
