<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SELE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELE A SURPRISING ADDITION TO MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Seattle Mariners manager Lou Piniella has seen
enough of 6-foot-10 left-hander Ryan Anderson's 95-mph fastball and
hard, biting slider. If he sees any more, Piniella might be tempted
to keep the 20-year-old phenom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd better get him out of camp quick,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella is joking. The temptation isn't that great. He loves
the thought of Anderson in the Mariners' rotation next year, or
perhaps late this season, but, for now, the Mariners can afford to
give their precocious prodigy more seasoning in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, if he'd pitched like this, he'd have made the
team,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Mariners didn't have Aaron Sele, who won 18
games for the Rangers last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had a decent pitching staff last season. Veteran
left-hander Jamie Moyer was his usual steady, consistent self and
went 14-8. Youngsters Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Gil Meche
combined to win 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the team finished 79-83, 16 games behind the Rangers in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to close the gap, the Mariners signed six free
agents in the off-season, including first baseman John Olerud, a
career .301 hitter, and former Rangers second baseman Mark
McLemore. The most important one, though, could be Sele, whom they
didn't think they had a chance to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a proven winner at the top of our rotation to go along
with Jamie is going to be a great addition,'' pitching coach Bryan
Price said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are trying to make up a 16-game deficit but had no
idea they would have a shot at signing the Rangers' top winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the season went, I assumed all along we'd quickly get
a deal done and I'd head back there,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   Sele was so certain he put down a deposit on a townhouse in
Colleyville. Why not? The Rangers wanted him. He wanted to pitch
for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he followed a strange, twisting road that took him to
the Rangers' divisional rivals. Rangers general manager Doug Melvin
began talking with Sele's agent, Adam Katz, during the World
Series. Before long, Melvin made a four-year, $28 million offer.
That offer, however, sat on the table so long it accumulated
several layers of dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no movement, and it didn't seem like there was any
real effort to re-sign me,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   That's his version. Melvin's version is that Katz never made a
counteroffer, and, without any other offers, there was no reason to
bid against himself. Tired of waiting, Melvin signed free agent
left-hander Kenny Rogers in December.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Rangers signed Rogers, Sele agreed to a
four-year contract with the Baltimore Orioles for a little more
money than Texas' original offer.
</P>
<P>
   But he never signed. The Orioles flew him in for a physical on a
Friday and began to backpedal when they didn't like the look of
something in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got your incumbent team offering you a four-year
contract, and the team you agree with questions your physical, it
was something else,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he flew to Los Angeles for a second opinion from Dr.
Frank Jobe. He received a clean bill of health and, five hours
later, agreed to terms with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way contracts are supposed to be done,'' said Sele,
who grew up and lives in the Seattle area. ``Get in, start a
dialogue and get signed. It was really nice after the way the whole
off-season went.''
</P>
<P>
   He got a two-year deal for $15 million, instead of the $28
million the Rangers offered, but said things worked out for the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy the way this whole off-season went,'' he said.
``To end up in Seattle, it's a wonderful thing. It's really a
blessing for my family. It worked out excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked out well for Sele, and it worked out well for the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Anderson might prove to be a Randy Johnson-type
ace. But for the present, the Mariners have an 18-game winner in
the rotation. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
