<HEADLINE>
CRABTREE, RANGERS DISCUSS CONTRACT EXTENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL AND T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ A contract extension could be forthcoming for
Rangers reliever Tim Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Baldwin, who represents Crabtree, called general manager
Doug Melvin on Monday to start discussions. Melvin indicated
yesterday that the organization would be interested, but any
conversations will be done discreetly to prevent any distractions
for the player, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree will earn $925,000 this season, and the Rangers hold an
option for the 2001 season at $1.3 million. Crabtree could become a
free agent after the 2001 season, but the right-hander appears
willing to forgo his first crack at free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like where I'm at,'' said Crabtree, who led the Rangers with
a career-high 68 appearances in 1999 and went 5-1 with a 3.46
earned-run average. ``I like the Rangers, and I'm very comfortable
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' acquisition of Crabtree from the Blue Jays for
catcher Kevin Brown ranks among one of Melvin's better trades.
Crabtree is 11-2 with a 3.53 ERA in 132 appearances for the Rangers
over the past two seasons. Brown has hit .277 in 54 games for the
Blue Jays during that period.
Lamb pressing
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates sees third baseman Mike Lamb pressing
during his at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb, the organization's 1999 minor-league player of the year,
went 0-for-4 yesterday as he battles Tom Evans in the competition
to become the Rangers' regular third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pressing,'' Oates said. ``I know he's not swinging the
bat like he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's average dipped to .240 (6-for-25) with yesterday's
performance. Evans is hitting .450 (9-for-20) with four home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure is the name of this game,'' Oates said. ``If he
thinks Evans is putting pressure on him, wait until he faces Pedro
\RMartinez\S.''
Trade talks quiet
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have reached the midpoint of spring training, and
little has developed in the way of trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some talk among major-league officials that the
Rangers might be interested in a second baseman _ Delino DeShields
and Mike Lansing are available _ but general manager Doug Melvin
shot that down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for a second baseman,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers scouts are keeping an eye out for left-handed relief if
Mike Venafro is slow recovering from a strained ligament in his
left middle finger. But the New York Mets have stopped trying to
trade Dennis Cook, and Melvin said there is little else available.
_ T.R. Sullivan
Greer closer to return
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer returned to Port Charlotte yesterday
and might resume playing as soon as Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Greer underwent a magnetic-resonance-imaging exam and bone scan
Monday in Dallas, and the results confirmed that the inflammation
in his right ankle is being caused by fluid. Greer received a
cortisone shot and is scheduled to resume workouts tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of the woods yet,'' Johnny Oates said.
``Hopefully, everything is OK, but you don't rest until it is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
