<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-HOOPSTV.COM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE OFFERS GONZO LOOK AT BASKETBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ From noon to 2 p.m. on most days, the dozen
or so employees at HoopsTV.com in Paoli, Pa., can count on a rough
and tumble board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Board meeting, in this case, means a meeting beneath the boards
_ as in playground basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at HoopsTV.com, a 1-month-old Internet startup company
that caters to hardcore basketball fans, use their two-hour window
for lunch to get in a few games of pickup basketball at a nearby
park in their western Philadelphia suburb.
</P>
<P>
   These long lunch hours don't bother the man in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is work, fun is fun and ball is ball,'' said Seth Burger,
the 32-year-old president and founder of HoopsTV.com. ``If nothing
else, the only reason to work here is to hoop from 12 to 2 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   And that pretty much explains the passion behind HoopsTV.com.
The site takes a gonzo approach to a sport that transcends all
kinds of demographics. HoopsTV.com bills itself as a 24-hour
basketball network, specializing in original programming from the
playgrounds to colleges to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And with the NCAA men's and women's tournaments ready to tip off
and the NBA playoff races heating up, HoopsTV.com offers an
interesting stop for basketball fans, especially for the site's
target audience of ball players ages 12 to 30.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can find multimedia clips, commentary from experts such
as Kenny Smith and Bill Raftery and gads of interactive features.
An example of the site's alternative approach: HoopsTV.com's latest
daily survey revealed that 80 percent of its members would trade in
their girlfriends for worldly possessions, such as a Range Rover or
Tyra Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a site for the casual fan,'' Burger said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott O'Neil, one of the company's vice presidents, said
HoopsTV.com isn't like NBA.com for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go where no one else can go,'' O'Neil said, referring to
the site's sections on playground and amateur basketball. ``Anyone
can turn on television to see an NBA game. We represent what the
culture of the game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Burger, who worked at a basketball sneaker company, said he came
up with the idea in June. He secured funding from sources he had
cultivated in the sports-apparel business, hired about 10 people
and it ``kind of grew from there.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Internet startups are positioning themselves for
alliances with bigger online companies, Burger said HoopsTV.com's
goal is to be ``strong and independent.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one way to ensure the lunch-hour pickup games.
Bytes
</P>
<P>
   Odds are: The odds of picking the winner at your office pool
probably aren't as long as those on a contest promoted by
Sandbox.com. For a $10 million grand prize, the winner must select
the winner of all 63 games. University of Southern California
mathematics professor Kenneth Alexander figured that someone has a
better chance of winning a pick-six state lottery twice in a row
than picking every game correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing the same feat at online sports book Intertops.com
will earn $2 million; Predictit.com and FansOnly.com have $1
million payouts. Not everyone likes the contests. ``We're adamant
about doing anything we can to get these things as far away as
possible from any appearance of gambling,'' Wally Renfro, an NCAA
spokesman, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker ban: Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker's diatribe in
Sports Illustrated cost him more than a 14-day suspension and $500
fine. Rocker paid dearly with an online fantasy league called
FantasySportsnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based site suspended Rocker for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell C. Lerner, the site's CEO, said they would review
Rocker's situation before the All-Star break, and ``if there have
been no further transgressions, and his ERA is below 3.00 and he's
accumulated 15 saves, he might be reinstated for selection by FSN
subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   Best fan: Here is a contest that Mavericks owner-in-waiting Mark
Cuban, or anyone willing to pay $250 million for a lower-rung NBA
team, might want to check. United Sports Fans of America
(UsFANS.com), a fan advocacy group, is on a two-month search for
``Basketball's Biggest Fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boca Raton, Fla.-based site, which tackles issues such 0as
escalating ticket prices, NFL TV blackouts, player and official
strikes, stadium funding and franchise moves, is accepting essays
of 150 words or less from fans vying for the title.
</P>
<P>
   The contest concludes April 18, the final weekend of the NBA
regular season. The grand-prize winner earns a trip to the 2000 NBA
Finals.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 0107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
