<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX     03-15 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAAS GETS PAST INITIAL AWE AT AUGUSTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rest assured, Hunter Haas is not the first person to suffer
momentary lockjaw upon his initial visit to Augusta National Golf
Club. Nor is he likely to be the last. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To a golfer, strolling down Magnolia Lane for the first time
must be akin to a follower of Islam getting his first glimpse of
Mecca. It's a time for silence and reflection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is what Haas, the U.S. Public Links champion from Fort
Worth, seemed to be doing at the guard booth to the main gate
before a recent practice round. His father, Jim, had to nudge him
back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked through the window at the guy and just froze. He
didn't know what to say,'' Jim Haas said. ``I finally told him,
`Say SOMETHING.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Haas stammered: ``I'm Hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   The attendant replied: ``Mr. Haas, we've been expecting you all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ice broken, the Southwest High School graduate and former
University of Oklahoma golfer relaxed and made the most of three
practice rounds in preparation for the biggest golfing week of his
career. Haas, 23, will compete April 6-9 at the Masters in Augusta,
Ga., and already has lined up a Tuesday practice round with Arnold
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But his initial exposure to the course came last weekend, when
Haas squeezed in as much golf as possible between three lightning
delays and pumped as much information as possible out of four
caddies, the course superintendent and a handful of members.
</P>
<P>
   First impressions?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's kind of an eerie feeling about the place. I'm not sure
that's the right word, but everywhere you go, you can sense the
history,'' Haas said. ``You definitely know where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas didn't bother keeping score during his rounds. He was more
interested in experiencing as many different shots from as many
different locations as possible. He lined up some U-shaped putts
and chips at the undulating 16th green. He felt the swirling winds
at Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he noticed his comfort zone expanding with each
shot during his Friday-Sunday stay.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Haas flew the green with his approach on No. 1
during his initial practice round. He opted to putt from the
fringe. Four strokes later, he had carded a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by Sunday, I knew where every putt was going and I was
actually making some long putts,'' Haas said. ``I really liked the
course. I felt comfortable. A lot more comfortable than if I went
in for the first time on Monday (of tournament week).''
</P>
<P>
   During the obligatory tour of club facilities, Haas made some
mental notes and adjusted some logistical plans. The tiny Crow's
Nest, a room in the clubhouse made available to amateurs during
tournament week, will not be a permanent resting place for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one or two nights will be fine, just for the
experience,'' Haas said. ``Definitely not for the whole
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of strategy, Haas got to experience the course in both
firm and wet conditions. A Friday rain limited his practice session
to seven holes but sunny conditions returned during weekend rounds.
Discussions with caddies convinced him that tee shots during
tournament week, when the course is firm and fast, would travel
30-40 yards farther than the shots he hit last weekend when the
course was tailored to members.
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddie told me a lot of pros play from the members' tees
this time of year because (approach shots) wind up where they'll be
hitting from in the tournament,'' Haas said. ``I hit from the back
tees, just for the visual image, then kicked it up 30 or 40 yards.
I think that will help me know how to shape shots and where I need
to be in the fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, where Haas would like to be _ on a permanent basis _
is in the room he enjoyed most during his tour: the champion's
locker room. Small and quaint, Haas noticed multiple names on each
door. Even Jack Nicklaus, a six-time champ, doesn't get his own
stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lets you know you have to earn your spot. They don't just
build a new locker every year,'' Haas said. ``I liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   While in the room, Haas said he envisioned his name on one of
those doors. But he didn't care if he shared with Nicklaus, Tiger
Woods or Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take whatever they can give me,'' Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Haas already may have taken his first steps in that
direction with last week's introduction to Augusta.
STRATEGY SESSION
</P>
<P>
   Members of the PGA Tour's policy board convene Wednesday to
decide what action, if any, the tour will take in pursuing its
ongoing legal battle with disabled golfer Casey Martin. A U.S.
appeals court in San Francisco ruled 3-0 last week to uphold a 1998
decision by an Oregon court that Martin, 27, should be allowed to
use a cart during competition under the Americans With Disabilities
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Martin suffers from Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber syndrome, a
circulatory disorder that has withered his right leg and makes
walking painful. In handing down the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruling, judge William Canby wrote: ``The central
competition in shot-making would be unaffected by Martin's
accommodation. ... All that the cart does is permit Martin access
to a type of competition in which he otherwise could not engage
because of his disability. That is precisely the purpose of the
ADA.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem issued a statement saying tour
officials ``will have further comment, if appropriate'' after
Wednesday's meeting. The final step in the appeals process for the
tour would be the U.S. Supreme Court, which could not hear the case
until 2001, at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Finchem &AMP; Co: You're already 0-3 when involving courts
on this issue (0-2 in actual legal venues, 0-1 in the court of
public opinion). It's time to do what should have happened
initially: Incorporate a tour bylaw saying players with permanent
disabilities that impair mobility, as attested by a doctor, can
ride a cart during competition. Over the next 100 years, the short
list of players who fit that description and break par regularly
will probably begin and end with Casey Martin. If not, there won't
be enough additions to make it worth the continuation of this
losing battle in the courts. UNLUCKY SEVEN
</P>
<P>
   Olin Browne, reigning MasterCard Colonial champion, was among
seven golfers who missed out on a Masters invitation because of a
new rule in place this year at Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials no longer automatically invite every winner
of a PGA Tour event in the previous calendar year. Instead,
invitations go to the top 50 players in the world golf rankings,
with the remaining spots filled by past Masters winners or by
competitors based upon finishes at other major championships
(professional and amateur).
</P>
<P>
   Joining Browne in the first wave of 1999-2000 tournament winners
to get the Augusta snub were Brad Faxon, Rich Beem, J.L. Lewis,
Brian Henninger, Jim Carter and Tom Pernice Jr. Two winners from
this season, Paul Azinger and Kirk Triplett, squeezed in based on
rankings (No. 49 and No. 27, respectively) as of the March 6
cutoff. Shigeki Maruyama, a career nonwinner on the PGA Tour,
vaulted into the field because he climbed to No. 48 in the world
rankings by the cutoff date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their tournament and they can do what they want. I'm
disappointed not to be invited,'' Browne said, choosing his words
carefully. ``I've played there twice already and think I've shown I
can compete in that setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, 40, finished 52nd at last year's Masters. O'MEARA
RETURNS TO COLONIAL
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, one of five high-profile players who skipped the
1999 MasterCard Colonial to accept a six-figure appearance fee and
compete in a European Tour event with conflicting dates, has made
plans to return to Fort Worth this season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, the 1998 PGA Tour Player of the Year, is among 62
players who have committed to compete in the May 18-21 event. It
will be O'Meara's first visit to Colonial since missing the cut at
the 1995 event.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable commitments released this week by Colonial
officials include four of O'Meara's teammates on the 1999 U.S.
Ryder Cup: Tom Lehman, Justin Leonard, Davis Love III and Steve
Pate. Also on the list are Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks and
two-time Colonial champs Corey Pavin, Bruce Lietzke and Ben
Crenshaw. Matt Gogel, an early contender for PGA Tour Rookie of the
Year honors, also has committed to make his Colonial debut.
</P>
<P>
   Commitments are not binding, but Colonial officials said all 62
players have arranged housing during tournament week and are
expected to compete. LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the
Star-Telegram will feature a significant moment in tour history
each week during the 2000 season. July 26, 1992
</P>
<P>
   Patty Sheehan, an LPGA Hall of Famer with three runner-up
finishes at the U.S. Women's Open, defeated Juli Inkster in an
18-hole playoff to win the event in her 13th attempt. Sheehan
needed birdies on the final two holes of regulation to force the
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was especially emotional for Sheehan, who
surrendered an 11-stroke lead to Betsy King over the final 33 holes
of the 1990 Open to finish second in heartbreaking fashion. To win
in come-from-behind fashion the same event two years, Sheehan said,
made the 1992 Open the most memorable of her 35 tour victories.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
