<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-PACERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS DOMINATE EAST'S NO. 1 TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Through the window, over the expressway, under the
tunnel, off the janitor's head.
</P>
<P>
   Had any of the Dallas Mavericks attempted one of those ludicrous
shots against Indiana, it probably would have dropped. It was that
kind of night.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Dirk Nowitzki's 28 points, the Mavs scored their
most-impressive victory of the season in a resounding 111-90 rout
of the Eastern Conference-leading Indiana Pacers before 15,761
Tuesday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, who led the entire game, shot 51 percent in the
first half and led by as many as 32 points in the third quarter
before the final 12 minutes became extended garbage time. It was
the Mavs' second-largest margin of victory, behind a 23-point
victory against Golden State in the third game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's contagious and perpetual,'' said guard Steve
Nash, who scored 21 points on 8-of-11 shooting, including 4-of-5
from 3-point range. ``It's not going to be that way every night,
but the good thing is that we played defense and when you do that
you give yourself a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense first, defense later.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs shot 60 percent (9-for-15) from 3-point range, scored a
season-high 36 first-quarter points and every player scored.
Highlighted by Nowitzki's 10-of-13 shooting, and 4-of-5 from
3-point range, and Michael Finley's 16-point, 11-assist
performance, the Mavericks' starters shot 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on fire tonight,'' said Pacers forward Austin
Croshere, who scored 10 points on 4-of-12 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Six Mavs finished in double-figures, punctuated by sub Greg
Buckner's first career double-double as he finished with 10 points
and 11 rebounds in 24 minutes. Even little-used reserve Bruno
Sundov jumped in on the fun with a hook shot that banked in with
less than one minute remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite clear we were hot and making shots,'' Mavs coach
Don Nelson said. ``But, that's just half of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense limited Indiana, which entered the game shooting 46
percent, to 33 percent shooting, and All-Star guard Reggie Miller
was held to seven points. This coming the day after the Mavericks
hired former Lakers coach Del Harris as their defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Del's wonderful isn't he? He makes a big difference in two
minutes,'' dead-panned Pacers coach Larry Bird. ``When you play
against a team that on the defensive end gets up into you and makes
a lot of shots on the other end, you're going to lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who were playing without injured All-Star forward
Dale Davis, suffered their second consecutive defeat and first loss
to a team with a losing record since Orlando defeated them Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson switched defensive assignments, putting the smaller Nash
on Miller and the taller Finley on point guard Mark Jackson.
Jackson and Miller were a combined 3- for-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we used it to our advantage,'' Nash said.''It can work
either way. It was a dilemma for them. You either let Finley go one
on one and I went to spot up, and by the time they got to me it was
too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also exacts a small degree of revenge for the
Mavericks, who lost at Indiana on Feb. 21 by one point on a
controversial late foul on Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there is extra satisfaction,'' forward Cedric Ceballos
said. ``We did the same thing in Indiana. We took over the game
(there), and then three other people (referees) started getting
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks jumped on Indiana so early that any interaction
from neutral parties was never going to be in question. The Mavs
led 17-6 in the first six minutes and stretched the margin to 18 by
the end of the first quarter. The inevitable NBA-run came in the
second quarter, when the lead was cut to 10 points with 59 seconds
remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Any thoughts of a comeback were buried by Nowitzki, who scored
10 consecutive points to begin the third quarter that were part of
a 25-3 run that pushed the lead to 80-48. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
