<SLUG> BC-BKN-ELLIOTT-RETURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' ELLIOTT RETURNS 7 MONTHS AFTER TRANSPLANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ With one thunderous dunk, Sean Elliott's big heart
overshadowed his new kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Almost seven months to the day after receiving a life-saving
kidney from his brother, Noel, the San Antonio Spurs forward
Tuesday night became the first professional athlete to return to
action after receiving an organ transplant. Showing no ill effects
other than fatigue and a hesitancy to shoot, Elliott otherwise
relieved the fears and calmed the nerves of teammates and a crowd
of 26,708 at the Alamodome by scoring a monumental two points in 12
minutes in a 94-79 Spurs victory against the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott missed his first two shots, but brought the crowd and
his teammates to their feet with a third-quarter drive-and-dunk
down the lane. Even before that _ by making a surprise start _
Elliott had already become a modern-medicine marvel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to approach it as just another game, but I think it's
pretty important because it affects so many people,'' said Elliott,
who received a hug from Hawks center Dikembe Mutombo and a standing
ovation before the opening tip. ``I couldn't feel my arms or legs
to start the game, my feet were heavy and my mouth was dry. And,
honestly, I was surprised I felt that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spurs team doctor Paul Saenz, ``Because Sean's venturing
into the unknown, I think we're all breathing a sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   While Noel downplayed his necessary role in Elliott's miracle,
his brother started slowly by driving twice on Mutombo but failing
to get off a shot in his first-half, five-minute stint. Elliott,
who showed signs of fatigue by bending over and grabbing his shorts
during timeouts, was more aggressive starting the third quarter. He
first launched a 3-pointer from the left wing and then left a
driving finger-roll layup on the front rim before making his
emphatic first basket of the season for a 56-53 Spurs lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dunk wasn't just two points,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich
said. ``It was the culmination of something very, very special. It
about brought tears to my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   As the clock dwindled under two minutes, the crowd chanted, ``We
want Sean!''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this over a kidney?'' Noel joked at the media attention.
``Seriously, seeing him on the court on a scale of 1-10, it's an
11.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott tried to shrug off his remarkable return, joking that
he'll eventually be ``the first transplant patient to be booed.''
But for the estimated 12,000 kidney-transplant patients around the
country, Tuesday night he became the first man to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great not just for us, but for all of basketball and even
all mankind,'' said teammate Avery Johnson, who pointed out that,
ironically, Elliott used to have the reputation as being ``soft.''
``He's beating the odds and giving hope to a lot of desperate
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott made his unlikely return in front of 40 friends and
family, including his surgeon, Dr. Francis Wright; his mother,
Odiemae; and older brother Noel, who asked only for two tickets to
little brother's first game back as payment for saving his life. As
the buzzer sounded, Elliott embraced Noel as they walked toward the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have prolonged his career,'' said Noel, who works for a
Tucson company that builds Learjets, ``but he's making me the
world's most famous organ donor.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA Hall of Famer Oscar Robertson recently donated a kidney to
his daughter, but Elliott became the first player to participate in
a game after receiving an organ from a donor.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 32, learned in 1993 he had a disease (focal
glomerulosclerosis) that slows kidney function and prevents them
from properly filtering waste from the blood system. With his
health deteriorating and his kidneys literally shriveling last
spring, Elliott informed only teammate Steve Kerr of his situation
so as not to interrupt the Spurs' successful run to their first NBA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Literally hours after the team's victory parade from atop floats
down San Antonio's Riverwalk in June, doctors considered putting
Elliott on emergency dialysis. On Aug. 16, a kidney was taken from
Noel and transplanted into Sean at the Methodist Specialty and
Transplant Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see Noel sitting over there smiling,'' Sean
Elliott said. ``The only way I can repay him is by playing the best
I can and taking advantage of my second chance. This is partly for
me, but also for Noel and other transplant patients that hopefully
can get some hope that their lives aren't over.''
</P>
<P>
   Working out on his own with no assurances of being allowed to
play again, Elliott almost gave up in December. He was having
trouble putting back on the 20 pounds he lost after surgery, and
his daily anti-rejection pills so weakened his immune system that
he was hospitalized with pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence was wrecked,'' Elliott said. ``What kept me
coming back was thinking about Noel, and my love for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's next hurdle: Using his new kidney to help regain his
old skills. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
