u p BC-ELN-RDP-ART-2TAKES(99     03-15 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-ART-2TAKES(990)-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUSPENSELESS TUESDAY MAKES GORE AND BUSH THE NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to delete delegate number in 20th graf, bgng Gore actually
reached...)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics
are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George Bush
of Texas claimed their parties' nominations Tuesday night, marking
the official if anticlimactic end to their primary campaigns and
the beginning of what promises to be one of the longest
general-election campaigns in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The two nominees effectively secured their nominations last week
when their only remaining serious rivals, former Sen. Bill Bradley
and Sen. John McCain, dropped out after defeats in nationwide
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night the voters in Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas gave Gore enough delegates to the
Democratic convention to lock up the nomination. Bush came within a
few dozen delegates, but his campaign's reckoning of the
complicated delegate calculus, including results from so-called
beauty contest primaries, put him over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I filed for president, I pledged I'd come home to Texas
with the nomination of my party,'' Bush said in remarks prepared
for a reception Tuesday night in Austin, Texas. ``Tonight we can
say: Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are halfway _ but only halfway _ to ending the Clinton-Gore
era in Washington, D.C. To get there, we must face one more
Clinton-Gore campaign. The last week has been a preview: The Gore
campaign will say anything to try to win at any cost. We will
confront their tactics one more time, and this time, we will
prevail and they will fail. They will fail because Americans have
caught on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticking off the states that put him over the top, Gore told a
rally at a high school here, ``We have now won enough delegates to
secure the Democratic nomination,'' adding: ``Tonight the South put
us over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has pulled even with Bush in the national polls, was
signaling that he would not concede the South or states like
Florida to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare for the eight months until the November
elections, the candidates are now the titular heads of their
respective parties. Gore takes over the Democrats after an
eight-year reign by Bill Clinton, and Bush the Republicans after a
turbulent era in which the party's loudest if not strongest voice
was that of the deposed speaker of the House, Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign feels it has the more palpable advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, as of tonight, we are the
presumed nominee, and under party rules, the party can pay for
travel and a lot of other things,'' said Tony Coelho, the Gore
campaign chairman. He added that, contrary to conventional wisdom,
Gore would not have to schedule ``official'' vice presidential
visits to make up for a lack of campaign funds, since the campaign
has about $13 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers also said he could now more freely raise money
for the party, and he has been taking advantage of that freedom. He
is attending three fund-raisers in the space of a week. Last
Saturday he raised about $100,000 in Houston. On Monday night, he
raised $200,000 from about 400 people attending a reception in
Belle Meade, a wealthy, generally Republican suburb of Nashville.
He has another fund-raiser scheduled for Washington on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Having the nomination in hand is also helping Gore organize his
campaign. Now that he is the nominee, he can start pulling together
the Democratic National Committee organizations in each state, one
Gore strategist said. On Monday night the vice president called
about 30 Democratic mayors to Nashville for a strategy session on
how to use their city machines as a counterweight to the state
organizations of the Republican governors supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors, Gore told them, are on the front lines. ``You give
me a swap out straight up between all the Republican governors and
the Democratic mayors, and I'm with you all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has already made wide use of the 31 Republican governors
who have supported him and Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman, said
there were no other advantages to clinching the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates now face the challenge of sustaining the
interest of voters without turning them off.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates are aggressively trying to define each other and
control the debate as they emerge from the primary process, and
they are both putting their opposition research operations into
high gear. Gore is casting Bush as a lightweight who lacks the
experience to run the country; Bush is chaining Gore to President
Clinton and raising doubts about the vice president's integrity and
his ability to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that both sides are already fully engaged, Bush
volunteers traveled to the small brick Forks River Elementary
School in Elmwood, Tenn., Tuesday morning, where Gore was voting in
the Tennessee primary, to hand out anti-Gore literature.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is already showing the same aggressiveness in the race
against Bush that he showed in the primaries toward Bradley. He
sought to take control Tuesday night, at least symbolically, by
sending an e-mail message to Bush, in which he reiterated his
challenge to eliminate all campaign commercials and debate twice a
week instead.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the earliest point in a campaign in modern times
that the parties have selected their nominees, when neither nominee
has been an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore actually reached and surpassed the magic number of
delegates Tuesday morning before the day's votes were tallied. This
was possible because over the last week, the party's superdelegates
_ its leaders and elected officials and others who will
automatically attend the convention in August _ pledged their
allegiance to him, by phone and by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans do not have superdelegates. Bush began the day
with 654 delegates and 341 were at stake Tuesday. That was 39 short
of the 1,034 need to claim the nomination. But under different
methods of calculation he had 227 more delegates from earlier
races.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the voting Tuesday, Bush received as much as 88 percent of
the vote, in Mississippi, to 74 percent in Florida. On the
Democratic side, Gore obtained 92 percent of the vote in Tennessee
to 69 percent in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his ability to win his party's nomination without losing
a single state, Gore, who first ran for president in 1988, remained
cautious about his achievement. ``It's still a little premature to
go, `Yahoo,''' Gore told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a fall-off of attention in the news media, that's
fine,'' he added. ``There's a natural rhythm and cycle to news
coverage. I don't worry about that. But in terms of my effort to
communicate directly with voters, there will be no let-up at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Making it clear that Gore will not be the only candidate dealing
with education issues, the Bush campaign released literature on
Bush's education proposals, plus a fact sheet on what the Bush
campaign said were measures of how schools have failed to improve
under the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   The references to education by the campaign and in Bush's speech
Tuesday night highlight one of the governor's greatest challenges,
jettisoning some of the perceptions, left by the dynamics of his
campaign against McCain, that his persona and positions are too far
to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was clearly sending signals to voters in the center with
the circumstances of his victory speech here Tuesday night. He held
it at a Jewish community center and was introduced by Mayor Carlos
Ramirez of El Paso, a Democrat who also happens to be Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's presence underscored the degree to which Bush has
cobbled together more political support from minorities in Texas
than Republicans traditionally command and spoke to Bush's hope of
establishing the same crossover appeal nationally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 0123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
