<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BELMONT-COUNCIL-2TAKE     03-15 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-COUNCIL-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SHARES BELMONT BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH AND BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The city of Los Angeles took jurisdiction over
environmental conditions at the Belmont Learning Center six years
ago but failed to ensure adequate safety systems were installed at
the now abandoned school, the Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   A little-known 1993 agreement between the city Planning
Commission and the Los Angeles Unified School District shows that
city officials _ who are now demanding a direct role in Belmont and
other school construction projects _ bear at least some
responsibility for the failure of the $175 million project.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between the city and school district made the city
``co-responsible'' for the mitigation of environmental problems at
the dangerously tainted property, as well as the installation and
monitoring of safety systems needed to protect the nation's
costliest school.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions of the 1993 agreement called for the city to get
involved before construction started.
</P>
<P>
   Work, however, was under way for nearly a year before the city
stepped up in 1998, documents show. And when it did, the city
Planning Commission accepted the LAUSD's assessment of the dangers
at the property and signed off on a proposed safety system to deal
with emissions of explosive and toxic gases rising from a former
oil field beneath the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no alarms or buzzers. Staff likely accepted what
the school district presented,'' said Bob Scott, a Woodland Hills
attorney who serves as one of five city planning commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   State toxic officials have since deemed the safety system
inadequate and have concluded that comprehensive environmental
tests were never conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The city Planning Commission approved the environmental report
for Belmont on July 9, 1998. While Scott voted in the majority, he
said, he doesn't remember details of the meeting and recently asked
the commission's staff to investigate why the school district
didn't have to submit to a rigorous environmental review for
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these matters come before us, and they appear more or
less routine,'' he explained. ``Nobody was there telling us it
doesn't look fine. We are volunteers and usually we have to take
what our staff tells us.''
</P>
<P>
   City Planning Director Con Howe recalled that the commissioners
had some concern because construction at Belmont had already
started. Nevertheless, he said, they decided to accept the school
district's environmental impact report and mitigation plans. The
approval was part of a larger conditional use permit for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Following the commission's recommendation, the permit was
submitted to the City Council for review and approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my firm recollection that the City Council has never
acted on it,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   The school board decided to abandon Belmont in January, citing
environmental and cost concerns. Five weeks later the City Council
belatedly intervened, demanding that the board reconsider its
action and give the city a role in future school construction
projects in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently unaware of the 1993 agreement with Los Angeles
Unified, as well as the city Planning Commission's action, the
council on March 3 criticized the school district's management of
the Belmont project and its decision to abandon construction.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from influential, well-paid lobbyists, the
council passed a motion calling on the school district to
re-evaluate the fate of the site and work with the city to find
alternative inner-city campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The motion, written by Councilman Mike Hernandez, included a
threat. If the city is not satisfied with the district's
cooperation, the council vowed to withhold building permits and
funding for public spaces at schools in the Belmont attendance
area, a dramatically overcrowded, low-income enclave.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez called the school district's decision to kill Belmont
a ``broken promise to the people of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez did not respond to requests for comment about the
city's ``co-responsibility'' for the environmental conditions at
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden referred to the city Planning
Commission's oversight of the Belmont project as ``just a
formality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely on the credibility of them (the people who submit the
environmental report),'' Holden said. ``We don't go out and
double-check ... If they say it's OK, it's their responsibility in
the end. If they misled the city, that's their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Joel Wachs, a mayoral candidate, disagreed. Wachs
argued that the City Council's new interest in Belmont stemmed not
from wanting to open a safe school for kids, but from interest in
doing a favor for lobbyists connected to one of the city's largest
law firms, O'Melveny &AMP; Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, the school board filed a malpractice lawsuit
against O'Melveny &AMP; Myers over legal advice related to Belmont. The
firm, which could be liable for millions of dollars in damages if
Belmont isn't built, has hired two lobbying firms to help
resuscitate the school and potentially minimize its damages in the
malpractice case. The lobbyists contacted several council members
before the March 3 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something really fishy going on,'' said Wachs, who
was the only member of the council to vote against Hernandez's
motion. ``There are a lot of people who have a lot of interest in
getting Belmont built and it doesn't have anything to do with
education. It's not about the kids. It's about money.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   School board member Valerie Fields, a former education adviser
to the late Mayor Tom Bradley, called on the City Council to take
its share of responsibility for Belmont. Fields urged the council
to start thinking about the city's children, not lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder whether the City Council was aware of their share of
responsibility for Belmont before they recommended that we consider
reopening the school,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the City Council feels so strongly about reopening Belmont,
they should take on all the responsibility and expense to mitigate
the environmental problems for the 30- to 50-year lifetime of the
school,'' she added. ``They should also take on all the liability
for every time a student or an employee at the school comes down
with an ailment.''
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD administrators, who recommended that the school board kill
Belmont, declined to comment on the district's 1993 agreement with
the city.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior official, who asked not be named, said: ``The city
and council missed a number of opportunities to be alarmed and
point out the dangers at Belmont. They didn't. They only got
involved on the advice of lobbyists. They got involved late, late
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the school district agreed to the added layer of city
oversight as a condition of the city Planning Commission's approval
of the purchase of the largest portion of the 35-acre downtown
site.
</P>
<P>
   The city insisted on the agreement to give it a means to review
the project's environmental conditions and safety, and prevent the
district from ``bulldozing'' through the project, documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the environmental oversight, the Planning Commission
insisted upon six other conditions to give the city more of a say
in various aspects of the school construction project. Without the
conditions, the school district would only have been required to
comply with state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions included requiring the district to complete a
traffic study and conduct public workshops during the design phase
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   State law would have permitted the district to exempt itself
from the city's conditions by a majority vote of the school board.
But the board never took any action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
