<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$50 MILLION FOR NOT BEING AWFUL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Tuesday was a big morale-lifting day for the
local BofA folks.
<P>
   First the employees picked up their Chronicles and learned that
their beloved leader, Hugh McColl, had been awarded a $50 million
bonus, even though the company nosedived last year.
</P>
<P>
   If Hugh had been moping, that should cheer him up.
</P>
<P>
   The execs in the home office in Charlotte, N.C., would have
phoned their San Francisco cousins to give them the good news, but
it's a toll call.
</P>
<P>
   Then the local employees, still giddy with excitement, found in
each of their mailboxes a genuine BofA lapel pin!
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was that the pin more than makes up for the fact
that much of the support staff didn't get Christmas bonuses last
December for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wear it with pride while busing your ATM,'' one staffer told
his fellow employees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND YET,  &LR; I sense in the general populace an undercurrent of
resentment that Hugh McColl is being obscenely rewarded for not
sucking too badly, while the bank's minions and the rest of us,
when it comes to merit raises and bonuses, seem to be judged by a
more stringent standard of performance.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh has a small PR problem. Maybe he should offer a $50 million
reward for the capture of the demon airport dogflinger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MINI BLACKOUT  &LR; Tuesday morning on the Embarcadero, as the Ferry
Building and 16 others lost power for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   When Carol Martin reported for work at the Agricultural Building
and found power out, she phoned PG&AMP;E with an SOS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your address?'' the PG&AMP;E woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the Port of San Francisco, the Ferry Building _ you
know, where the big clock tower is, at the foot of Market Street?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have an address.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Martin was connected to a Sacramento office.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to PG&AMP;E: If you do dispatch a crew to restore the power,
tell 'em San Francisco is the city right at the other end of the
big silver bridge, with the tall, pointy buildings, cute houses and
funny hills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT WOULD  &LR; Jesus drive? That question arose in a theological
discussion here. I guessed Triumph Spitfire, but others say no.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold S. Vorster, a Methodist pastor in Mill Valley, says he
has it on good authority that Jesus would drive an Austin Healy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toyota Corona, of course,'' says William Greene. ``Or maybe an
Infiniti Epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old Pizza Dude says it would be a Plymouth, Jesus' family
car. ``The Bible says God drove Adam and Eve out of the Garden of
Eden in a Fury.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a Plymouth. But more likely a Christler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``STOP MAKING  &LR; fun of student errors,'' scolds Bill Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Bill sat through 30 years of faculty meetings at California
junior colleges, mostly Santa Rosa and Merced, and jotted down
random statements of faculty and administration, including:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the statistics on the breakdown of our freshman
class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I normally speak to you ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Louise has some idea of how much down it could go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to launch a bandwagon or a panacea.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to get these figures in the budget so we can start
cutting them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, folks, what we're basically doing is working
with people, and I'm a living example of that, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope the word  &UR; immediate  &LR; has some flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a full-time person sitting in that chair because
that's only the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking as an average person, and I'd sometimes put myself in
that bag ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took off like Cape Canaveral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I failed to mention this because it is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Bill, ``Imagine what I might have heard had I stayed
awake.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEY,  &LR; Professor Bill: To launch a panacea, do you use a bottle
of champagne or Pepto-Bismol?
</P>
</TEXT>
