<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-1ST     03-15 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CITY LOSES 8 TO WAR, BUT NOT ITS FAITH IN THE CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS to add 4 grafs to end of 2nd take.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT8-11 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PSKOV, Russia _ Roman Sokolov led a group of Russian snipers in
Chechnya, and looked the part. He was solidly built, with regular
features, close-cropped soldier's hair and threatening V-shaped
brows set over eyes fixed in the flat, detached gaze of a career
warrior.
</P>
<P>
   His face, with its unlined and slightly menacing visage, could
easily be a poster in Russia's determined campaign to win Chechnya
at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday the image was in a frame that lay atop Captain
Sokolov's zinc coffin in Pskov's soaring Trinity Cathedral. It was
a coffin that, like the seven beside it, was covered in carnations
and tulips and lilies, bedecked in Russian Orthodox icons and wept
over by thousands of mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The eight men were among 84 members of a single Pskov-based
regiment who died in Chechnya early this month, trapped on a
hilltop by thousands of Islamic guerrillas who cut off
reinforcements and, in a gruesome all-night battle, virtually wiped
out a seasoned group of paratroopers. It was one of Russia's worst
defeats in its Chechen campaign, and it has left Pskov, a city of
200,000 on Russia's European border, in shock and bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   In other places, it might be the spark that ignited resentment
against a war that many outsiders see as needlessly brutal and,
ultimately, doomed. What Pskov's mourning Tuesday suggested,
instead, was that Russians, still adrift in their search for a
national identity, have seized on this war as a unifying force, and
wrapped themselves in its grief as in a comforting blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Few if any mourners talked Tuesday about the brutality of
Sokolov's war or the realization, dawning ever so slowly here, that
victory in Chechnya will not be quick or clean or cheap. Rather,
they talked about his heroism in the final hours of a lost cause,
and about his love of military life, and about the 3-year-old
daughter who is still asking her mother to bring daddy home.
</P>
<P>
   And when the service was over, they loaded his coffin on a
military flatbed, mounted his photograph on the back for
identification, and took him to a deserted cemetery for a burial
that was heartbreaking in its wintry sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are heroes,'' Yekaterina Zelinskaya, one of throngs
of women who jammed the cathedral, whispered above the sniffles of
the bereaved. ``They died in battle to defend us, to protect us
against new explosions like the ones last fall. We always knew we
could rely on them. If it is to be necessary, we will fight
terrorism ourselves to save our children.''
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious bombings of apartment blocks last fall, which
killed 300 and were attributed to Chechens but are still unproved,
sealed the Islamic revolt in Russians' minds as a threat to their
nation's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have since admitted to perhaps 1,500 combat
deaths in the conflict. Some outside experts contend that the true
number may be two or three times that. The military has been loath
to admit its losses, and refused to confirm the extent of the
disaster that befell the Pskov company until nearly a week after
local journalists had reported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go to the political officer of my division, and he
concealed the truth from me, even though everyone knew there was a
fierce battle,'' Sokolov's 24-year-old widow, Olga Sokolova, said
in an interview Tuesday. ``People in town knew more than we did in
the division.''
</P>
<P>
   But she and other Russians, almost genetically suspicious of
most government pronouncements, have largely accepted explanations
that the lag in reporting deaths stems from double-checking of
casualty lists.
</P>
<P>
   By design or otherwise, most of Pskov's dead remained Tuesday in
a military mortuary in Rostov, in southwestern Russia, where their
identifications and causes of death were being officially recorded.
Most will be shipped to other hometowns; Pskov, very much a
military city, was a stationing point for service men and women
from around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The eight who came home Tuesday were local boys, and were
mourned as such. Thousands lined the street outside Pskov's massive
1,100-year-old kremlin, in which the centuries-old cathedral
stands. More jammed the kremlin's cobblestone yard and strained
against police lines for a view.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the frigid cathedral, opposite a wall of ancient icons
perhaps 100 feet high, priests and a choir chanted an hourlong
dirge, their frosty breath merging with smoky puffs of incense;
their mantra the names of the dead: Mark, Aleksandr, Vladimir,
Roman, Sergei, Aleksei, Mikhail, Mikhail.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the service marked the start of a long procession to
the waiting military flatbeds, along a cobbled path strewn with red
carnations and lined by soldiers in camouflage, fur hats at their
waists.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heroes' welcome; an outpouring of reverence and grief
that made the familiar arrival of American military coffins at
Wilmington, Del., seem spartan by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
