<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-1ST     03-15 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CASUALTIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PSKOV, Russia: by comparison.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever one may think of the conduct of the Chechen war, it was
hard to fault Tuesday's proceedings. By any definition, these men
were military heroes, Sokolov first among them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small 2,500-foot-high ridge near the southern Chechnya
village of Urus-Kert that Company Six of Pskov's Regiment 104 took
Feb. 29, on orders to stop some 2,000 Chechen guerrillas from
escaping into neighboring Dagestan. By that afternoon they were
trapped in a fierce battle, with the nearest reinforcements more
than 5 miles away. Command of the force fell to Capt. Sokolov, who
had wanted to go to Chechnya last fall, during the bombings.
Instead, he shipped out from Pskov barely a month ago, just before
his 28th birthday on Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   At Urus-Kert, Sokolov organized the final defense of the
hilltop, aided by a few soldiers from a platoon that had broken
through rebel lines. At 11:30 p.m. that day, hundreds of guerrillas
began a nightlong attack against the defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Sokolov, by then wounded in the hand, rounded up six of his
company's newest members as the guerrillas drew close. He told them
to attempt a retreat, then radioed Russian forces and ordered
strikes on his own position in a last attempt to repel the
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Russians died that night, including Sokolov. The rest
were killed as the battle raged on. The six men Sokolov ordered to
flee were the only survivors.
</P>
<P>
   In a private ceremony on Monday, two able-bodied survivors came
to the yellow stucco gymnasium of the 104th Regiment, where the
caskets lay in state. There they kneeled before Sokolov's bier and
thanked him for his sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the funeral, a truck bearing his body arrived at a
small church in a run-down section of town, trailed by a bus
carrying family and friends. An honor guard unloaded the coffin. To
the beat of a snare drum and a trumpet, the soldiers carried
Sokolov past a broken iron gate and down a path of rutted frozen
mud strewn with spruce boughs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four soldiers followed the coffin, and perhaps 75
mourners. Sokolov's mother buried her face in her husband's
shoulder, sobbing as she walked. Mrs. Sokolova, her head shrouded
in black lace, was silent.
</P>
<P>
   As they reached the newly dug grave, the soldiers lifted the
rust-colored cover from the coffin, revealing the Russian tricolor
and a small window above Sokolov's face. His father, Vladimir
Timofeyevich, fell upon it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive me for remaining alive,'' he cried, before being
lifted from the coffin and into a relative's arms.
</P>
<P>
   A camouflage-clad officer spoke over the coffin. ``They did
everything for Russia to survive,'' he said. ``We will do
everything so that the cause you struggled for will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Sokolov and the others had to die, beyond the help of the
Russian army's vastly superior firepower, is a mystery. ``From a
professional standpoint, I can say that something wasn't followed
well,'' said a colleague, Aleksandr Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, who met survivors at the 104th
Regiment offices Tuesday afternoon, offered a remarkable admission
of responsibility for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear comrades, I address you as a person to whom you entrusted
the fates and lives of the people dearest to you,'' he told the
hundreds of mourners. ``I want to apologize before you that we
failed to save them in this, so grave an hour for Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for raising such wonderful sons and true patriots,''
he added. ``May soil be as soft as down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
