<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SASAKI IMMIGRATES TO M'S WITH HIGH MARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Not to put too much pressure on the new guy, but
Kazu Sasaki needs to virtually shut out the entire Valley of the
Sun for about 200 innings today in order to get the Mariners'
spring training ERA under a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But as a one-inning relief pitcher, and maybe the Mariners'
biggest off-season acquisition, such a deployment would be a bigger
squandering than the Tino Martinez trade.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, spring ERAs are like misdeeds of the Catholic church _
prone to handy revision. The Mariners can always put off such
gas-pump numbers on the season's infancy, or Arizona's light air,
or the other team's readiness, or any of the traditional excuses to
hide an absence of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Other than an adjustment time for American hitters, there should
be no excuses needed for Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   He has pitched only two spring innings, giving up a run on three
hits with three strikeouts. But a fellow who has watched him
throughout his 10-year career in Japan is persuaded that Sasaki has
what it takes to heal the ulcer of the Seattle bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy not to face him,'' said Kiyoshi Nakahata, a
former all-star first baseman for the Tokyo Giants and one of the
most popular figures in Japan's baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Nakahata retired about 10 years ago, just as Sasaki's pro career
began, and has been a baseball broadcaster for Japan's NTB Channel
4. The two met Tuesday for a long TV interview, sitting in the
outfield grass of a practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Nakahata explained through an interpreter what was
special about Sasaki's premier pitch, a forkball, or split-finger
fastball, the likes of which he suspects major league hitters have
not seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might not be known here is that he has three different
kinds of splitter,'' he said. ``One starts as a strike but drops so
low so quickly that it's a ball, and unhittable. A second splitter
starts lower and doesn't drop away so fast, so it's a strike at the
knees if the batter doesn't swing. A third one is actually
off-speed with some movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakahata knows Sasaki's Aug. 9 elbow surgery has slowed him a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``His curveball has improved, but his fastball is not there
yet,'' he said. ``When he's ready, it will (be) a 150-kph
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunnert-fifty? Oh, wait _ the conversion. That's about 93-95 mph
in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Nakahata said while Japanese hitters were thrilled to bid him
sayonara _ his ERAs the last three seasons were 0.90, 0.64 and 1.93
_ many fans did not share the excitement, much in the manner of
Seattle's reaction to the loss of Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best stopper and highest-paid pitcher in Japan,''
he said. ``They were very disappointed that they wouldn't see him
pitch anymore. But most understood the dream and the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the challenge has not been overwhelming, to hear Sasaki
tell it. Imposing physically at 6-foot-4 and 210 pounds, he
nevertheless is an amiable sort with an easy smile and a
worldliness when it comes to the media. At 32 with four previous
U.S. visits, including a 1988 stay in Seattle while pitching for a
touring college all-star team, he professes little trauma in
adjusting to American baseball or life.
</P>
<P>
   He already has an apartment in Seattle and loves cruising
Costco, so he's about one double-tall/low-fat/no-foam from having
moss appear on his north side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the food, and everyone has been nice _ no practical
jokes,'' he said through his interpreter, Alan Turner. ``Baseball
is the same language anywhere _ throw strikes, Lou says.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki thus has received the sum total of pitching help to be
supplied by the Mariners manager. But Sasaki is a self-starter who
has dictated his own regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Bryan Price has been working to correct a flaw in
his delivery that causes his left side to fly open upon release.
Sasaki has been sufficiently impressed with the greater power of
American hitters that he won't indulge himself mistakes that were
survivable in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change anything,'' he said, ``but I have to
be careful about high pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   After interest from both New York teams and Arizona, the free
agent signed Dec. 18 with the Mariners for about $8 million over
two years. The official plan is to have the right-hander set up in
the eighth inning for closer Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear is that there is not enough stomach lining in the
Northwest to endure another season of closes from Mesa, despite his
club record-tying 33 saves. Mesa last year was second in the
American League in most baserunners allowed per nine innings of
relief (16) and third-highest in batting average allowed (.305).
</P>
<P>
   He's been barely OK this spring, facing 13 batters and giving up
two hits and three walks. With Sasaki and Arthur Rhodes available
this season, Piniella is no longer forced to endure another night
like the opener at the new ballpark, when Mesa walked four of the
five batters he faced, forcing in the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is no issue for Sasaki, who has spent 10 years in the
ninth-inning crucible. He's even had the pleasure of facing
America's best, during the annual November exhibition tours of
Japan by U.S. stars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he recalled meeting up with Griffey. Whiffed him, in
fact, blowing by him a fastball up and in.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sasaki: ``He argued the call with the umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, Kazu. Wasn't his first complaint.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
