u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-JAVIER-S     03-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-JAVIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAVIER FINDS FIT WITH MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Stan Javier is near the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't run quite as well as he used to.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries take longer to heal.
</P>
<P>
   His bat speed has lost a tick.
</P>
<P>
   And he's no longer an everyday player.
</P>
<P>
   So why are the Mariners so happy to have signed Javier this
winter?
</P>
<P>
   Javier is built for Safeco Field. Consequently, he's built for
the 2000 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up around winners. He owns a World Series ring. He plays
the little game inside the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want me to do, I can do,'' Javier says quietly
without the swagger of a braggart. ``I can bunt, get on base,
hit-and-run, steal a base, play defense. That's the kind of game I
play.''
</P>
<P>
   But because he doesn't hit .300 every year or guarantee 30
homers and 90 RBIs, his skills aren't suited for a club still
trying to find itself. Put him in Minnesota, say, or Florida, and .
. . well, you just wouldn't find him playing for teams bereft of an
opportunity to win. Not at this stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help a team like that,'' Javier said. ``The kinds of
things they need, I can't do. I won't hit 40 homers or hit .340.
But if I'm on a team that's got a chance to win, I can help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do the little things _ bunting, running, playing
defense _ that fans may not always notice. But my teammates and the
opponents will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle manager Lou Piniella and Javier go back to 1984, when
Javier was just a kid trying to make it with the Yankees. But he
was a kid with a pedigree _ his father, Julian, played second base
for the St. Louis Cardinals in the Bob Gibson-fueled glory days in
the '60s _ and he was a kid with skills.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, then nearing the end of the line as an outfielder,
took one look at Javier that spring and told him that all he had to
do was hit .250-.270, and with his defensive skills, Javier could
play in the major leagues for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   This season will be Javier's 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never believed that when Lou said that,'' Javier said. ``I
never thought I'd play this long. But I've avoided big injuries,
and I've tried to keep my game at the same level.''
</P>
<P>
   Through all that, his family has kept him humble. His wife is a
doctor. Two brothers are doctors, as is one sister-in-law. Their
lives are not wound up in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at home, they're always talking about medicine and I
don't have anything to say,'' Javier said, breaking into a shy
smile. ``No one wants to talk about baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is spring training, and it's time to talk about
baseball again. One more time. The end is near for Javier as a
player. The end would already be here if a team like the Mariners
hadn't come calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that keeps me going is having the chance to win,''
Javier said. ``There's no better feeling than that. Preparing to
win, that's fun. If my only chance to play was to play for a team
that had no chance, I'd just stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than staying home, he spent the past four years with San
Francisco, generally a competitive team in the NL West. Back in
1989, Javier helped Oakland win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Jose Canseco went down for the first half of the
season with a wrist injury. Javier stepped in. When Canseco
returned, the A's had a five-game lead in the AL West, thanks in no
small part to Javier's ability as a fill-in, an ability the
Mariners want to tap in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said Javier, who stepped in and played for six weeks
when Barry Bonds of the Giants was injured last year, still has
what Piniella saw all those years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any winning team needs a player like Stanley,'' Piniella said.
``You need someone who can do all the little things and still step
up and fill in when necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Alex Rodriguez, a longtime friend of Javier's, takes
it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no value to a bad team. But he has unbelievable value
to a team like ours,'' Rodriguez said of the man he considers a
mentor. ``Getting Stan here was a great move by our front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anything he can't do in the outfield, playing
first base, hitting or running the bases. He's willing to do
whatever it takes for his team to win, and without guys like that,
you won't win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
