<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7189 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PATAKI-GUNS-2NDLD-WRI     03-15 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-GUNS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI PROPOSES BROAD PACKAGE OF GUN CONTROLS
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS to insert new 3rd-to-last graf.)   
(Eds: This story is an added starter to the front page.) 
(See also CLINTON-GUNS) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Swimming against the tide of his own party, Gov.
George Pataki on Tuesday proposed a sweeping package of gun
controls, including mandatory trigger locks with gun sales, a ban
on assault weapons and steps to make it easier for the police to
trace guns used in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates say the measures, if enacted, would give
New York among the strictest gun controls in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, if you think it's the right thing, you have to
pursue it,'' Pataki told ABC News in an interview Tuesday night.
``I'm hopeful we can get this through the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the measures would require so-called ballistics
fingerprinting, which would record the unique markings from all new
guns so that bullets and shell casings could later be traced to
them.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, the governor called for raising the legal age
for gun purchases to 21 from 18, and said he would seek to close a
loophole in the system of background checks for gun buyers by
requiring that those checks be done on buyers at gun shows and flea
markets, not just on those who buy in stores. Aides to Pataki said
he would unveil details of his proposals at a news conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are expected to pass in the Democratic-controlled
Assembly, though their fate in the Republican-dominated Senate is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proposals put Pataki, who harbors ambitions of
national office, at odds with the Republican leaders in Congress
and many of his fellow Republican governors. In fact, they put him
squarely in the camp of Democrats, including President Clinton, who
have been calling for many of the same measures for years. It is a
familiar position for Pataki, who favors abortion rights and gay
rights, and who recently signed into law an ambitious health care
program for the poor and a major increase in the state's cigarette
tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has called on Congress to require
background checks at gun shows and has proposed mandating
ballistics fingerprinting, and specific legislation is being
written by Democratic lawmakers, said Kristen Rand, the senior
counsel for the Violence Policy Center, a gun control group. The
gun control measure in the congressional conference committee
contains a trigger-lock provision, but gun control advocates say it
is too weak to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Morton, the spokesman for Handgun Control, said Pataki's
proposals go beyond what most other states are considering and are
important given that Pataki is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a Republican governor this is revolutionary,''
Morton said. ``This is an incredible, forward-looking step in law
enforcement and crime control. It shows that this is not a partisan
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's proposals are the first significant gun control
legislation he has called for in his five years in office. Various
elements of his plan have passed the Democratic-controlled Assembly
at one time or another. ``I welcome him aboard,'' the speaker of
the Assembly, Sheldon Silver, said Tuesday night. ``We've been
doing these things for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate, where Republicans hold the majority, has
resisted gun control measures in the past, but in this election
year, the majority leader, Joseph Bruno, has expressed a
willingness to consider some measures, though he has not given any
specifics. John McArdle, a spokesman for Bruno, would not comment
on the governor's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The most innovative part of the governor's plan would require
that any new gun sold in New York be fired first, to record its
ballistic fingerprint, the pattern of nicks and scratches left on a
bullet that is unique to each weapon. Such markings are often used
by the police and prosecutors to trace a crime to a particular gun,
but first the gun must be found. Under Pataki's plan, the
ballistics patterns of all new guns would go into a database that
could be used for comparison with bullets used in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a crime scene, people don't leave the gun very often,'' the
governor told ABC. ``But they do leave bullets or shell casings.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association has been opposed to the taking of
ballistics samples for the government, contending that it would be
a preliminary step toward national gun registration.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Michon, the vice president of the New York State Rifle
and Pistol association, the state affiliate of the NRA, said his
organization would likely oppose the legislation
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need any more legislation, they just need to
enforce the ones that are on the books,'' he said. ``They are
throwing up a smokescreen for their own inadequacies at enforcing
the laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Michon said the trigger lock legislation was inferior to a
measure Pataki vetoed last year that would have taught an NRA gun
education program in state schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trigger locks are unnecessary because it's proven they won't
work,'' Michon said. ``The state association has pushed to educate
kids that you should not touch a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control has become one of the most contentious issues in
Washington, and it promises to become a big part of the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have generally resisted gun control
measures, though some measures, like requiring trigger locks with
gun sales, enjoy broad support.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in the wake of the Columbine High School shooting in
Colorado, each house of Congress passed its own measure that would,
among other things, close the gun show loophole. But negotiators
have made no progress toward reconciling the differences between
the two bills, and some Republican leaders have made it clear that
they think both versions go too far, saying that what is needed is
better enforcement of existing laws. Clinton has accused
congressional Republicans of intentionally stalling.
</P>
<P>
   Each highly publicized school shooting like Columbine leads to a
new round of legislative proposals for gun control, and new heights
of popularity for those proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for requiring that trigger locks be included in all gun
sales have grown in the two weeks since a 6-year-old boy in
Michigan fatally shot a classmate with a pistol he found in his
home. Such a lock physically blocks the movement of the trigger,
making the gun impossible to fire without the key to the lock.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals to ban or restrict assault rifles gained momentum
after such a weapon was used in a schoolyard shooting in Stockton,
Calif., in 1989 that left five children dead.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office would not release details of the assault
weapons ban Tuesday night. There is a federal ban on assault
weapons, but it has so many loopholes that some states have passed
bans of their own to close them. A ban enacted in California last
year, for example, spells out the physical characterstics of banned
weapons, such as fixed magazines that carry more than 10 rounds and
features that allow rapid firing.
</P>
<P>
   Rand, of the Violence Policy Center, said that while the
measures proposed by Pataki were important to improve law
enforcement and gun safety, they might not do much to dent gun
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to decrease gun violence, you have to
regulate the gun industry in a more comprehensive way,'' Rand said.
``And that is difficult at the state level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
