<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN     03-15 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ NOT AFRAID OF BICEPS INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Pitcher Ramon Ortiz, who felt stiffness in his
right biceps while warming up Monday, returned to Los Angeles on
Tuesday to be examined by Dr. Lewis Yocum. Ortiz initially was
diagnosed with tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Before the examination, Ortiz, who has a 1.80 earned-run average
in two games this spring, said he wasn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the first time it's happened, that's why I know
it's nothing,'' he said. ``It happened to me before spring training
last year. They gave me some (medication). With that and massage, I
could pitch in three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia and pitching coach Bud
Black, however, will not send Ortiz out so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud's a little cautious, he wants Ramon to get in a good
bullpen before he goes out there again,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper improves: Brian Cooper, from USC, took a big step toward
winning a spot in the starting rotation with his performance
Tuesday against the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper gave up two runs (one earned) and five hits in four
innings of the Angels' 7-2 victory. Garret Anderson had the big
blow offensively, hitting a three-run homer, his second of the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   For Cooper, the outing was critical after giving up six runs in
two innings against the Brewers in his first start last Thursday.
Cooper needed to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would have been snow-bound if I had another tough
one here,'' Cooper said, referring to the weather in Edmonton, the
Angels' Triple-A affiliate. ``I haven't really been getting people
out or shown them how I can pitch. Even throwing bullpens
(workouts), I've been erratic the whole time we've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he needs to be consistent with his fastball, change
speeds and trust his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   He took a step in the right direction Tuesday, but it took a
while for him to get comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning I was trying to show them everything I've got
on the first day, and I overthrew,'' he said. ``Then it got to a
point where I was trying to fix everything and I lost my rhythm.
But after my last time out, I got off the mound for three days in a
row, and it helped me get back the fluidity of my windup and my arm
angle felt much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's emergence is important for the club considering the
injuries to Ortiz and Jarrod Washburn and the inconsistency of
Jason Dickson and Kent Mercker. But Scioscia said it's still too
early to win or lose a spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell a guy not to worry about results, but I knew Coop
needed it for his confidence,'' Scioscia said. ``He had much better
command and he's going to get better as he keeps pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman hot: In a split-squad game in Scottsdale, the Angels
got three hits from Justin Baughman, including a home run, to beat
the Giants, 8-6. The Angels now are 7-6 in the Cactus League.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ken Hill was roughed up for four runs and seven
hits in three innings. Among the seven hits was a home run by Barry
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad feels fine: Darin Erstad played his first spring game in
the outfield Tuesday and showed his left shoulder is fine. He made
a couple of throws from the warning track and hit the cutoff man
both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just trying to get his outfield legs right now,''
Scioscia said. ``It's going to take a little work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The minors The Angels sent seven players to minor-league camp.
Pitchers Elvin Nina, Scot Shields and Matt Wise, catcher Jason
Dewey and outfielder Elpidio Guzman were optioned, and pitcher
Steve Green and catcher Shawn Wooten were reassigned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
