A7214 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     03-15 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' HORRY LIKES RESERVE ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Robert Horry is playing like a starter. He's got the
minutes and often the stats to prove it. But he's told coach Phil
Jackson he wants to keep coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer it,'' said Horry, who plays behind A.C. Green but
these days plays more minutes and all fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it, warming up really hard and then getting that
little pause to get ready for the game,'' he said. ``I think A.C.,
his style of play is so different from mine, to watch him defend
the other guy, really lets me know how to defend the guy I have to
go out there and play. Plus, A.C. needs to be warmed up and come
straight on out. So I think I'm in a better situation to come off
the bench right now than he is....
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus you know how you get into a little groove, you don't want
to break the groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry's role has grown almost as quickly as the Los Angeles
Lakers' 19-game winning streak. And it's no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two players that have stepped up (during the
streak),'' Jackson said. ``Shaq (O'Neal)'s had some great games,
but two players that have stepped up and played at a level that's a
little better has been Robert and Kobe (Bryant).''
</P>
<P>
   Horry has scored in double figures just eight times this season,
but five of those have come in the last 11 games. He has raised his
shooting percentage to 44.8 percent, his 3-point shot is a threat
again and his defense against opposing power forwards has been at
times spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is consistently giving Horry starter's minutes, while
Green's playing time has plummeted to 18 minutes a game over the
past seven games. But Jackson has no plans to alter the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams have starters coming off the bench or players that
are equal to their starters,'' he said. ``That makes teams very
good and changes up what they do on the floor, gives them a little
more tenacity or speed or outside shooting or whatever, a lot of
things which Robert does do for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes two: Glen Rice now has ridden the bench for all but
three minutes of the last two fourth quarters combined, as Jackson
has gone to defensive-minded Rick Fox. Though Rice was upset by a
similar strategy in late January, he says he's fine with it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I was telling Rick before the game (Monday in Denver),
we're the two small forwards on this team, so we've got to go out
there and we've really got to do our part,'' he said. ``That's what
we're going to try to do from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was comfortable with the offense-defense switches
from Rice to Fox, Rice said, ``Yeah, it's comfortable, but don't
forget - I can play defense, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Breather: The Lakers will go for their 20th straight win, which
would tie the second-longest winning streak in NBA history, on
Thursday at Washington. They remained in Denver for light practices
Tuesday and today.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is receiving therapy for his strained right hamstring and
is expected to be fine for the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 0211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     03-15 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GALAXY OF QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ There are more questions than answers about
the Los Angeles Galaxy entering a new season, but the team's
history has taught the players to persevere.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's loss to D.C. United in the MLS championship game
last November was the team's second defeat in the final in four
years. Although the players are trying to remain optimistic as they
prepare to open the Major League Soccer season Saturday against
Colorado at the Rose Bowl, the Galaxy isn't exactly riding a wave
of favorable preseason reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preseason didn't deliver the results we expected,''
defender Paul Caligiuri said of the Galaxy's 2-3-1 exhibition
record, which included games against other MLS teams in Florida as
well as stops in Mexico and Argentina. ``I think the individual
efforts were there, but we could have done better in game
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems could be attributed in part to the fact Robin
Fraser, Cobi Jones and Greg Vanney spent more time with the U.S.
National team than the Galaxy. In addition, defender Ezra
Hendrickson was lost to St. Vincent &AMP; The Grenadines for World Cup
qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Galaxy's schedule includes four matches each with
powerhouses United, Colorado and Dallas. For the first time, the
MLS went with a weighted schedule, similar to that of the NFL -
meaning the best teams will play each other more often.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's task is even tougher because other MLS teams have
bolstered their foreign lineups while the Galaxy's requests to the
league for foreign help have been ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is lacking a foreign replacement for Carlos
Hermosillo, who decided to finish his career in Mexico. Meanwhile,
Iran's Khodadad Azizi was assigned to San Jose, German defender
Lothar Mattheus was assigned to New York/New Jersey, Henry Zambrano
was traded to Colorado and Kansas City picked up Miklos Molnar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of a victim of our own success,'' said coach Sigi
Schmid, explaining why the MLS has not assigned the team a marquee
foreigner to replace Hermosillo. ``If we had done bad, they would
have given us an allocation. That's just the way it is. We just
have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid remains optimistic. Last week, during an exhibition in
Argentina, he saw signs of the Galaxy coming together as a team for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they were getting after it a little more,'' Schmid said.
``Part of that is because we are getting close to the start of the
season, and part of that is guys realize that we can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he didn't have some of his starters, Schmid said the
preseason gave him an advantage he didn't have last year, when he
replaced Octavio Zambrano five games into the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big benefits of preseason was that we had a chance
to see everybody play in competition,'' Schmid said. ``We were able
to mix and match different lineups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a much better feel of what everybody needs to do and a
much better feel fitness-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri said the team is more match fit than it's ever been,
but that there are plenty of kinks to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sigi tended to focus a little more on fitness,'' said
Caligiuri. ``And because we were trying to lay a strong foundation,
there wasn't always the best results in (preseason) games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until our last game (in Argentina), I felt we hadn't played
well together as a team at all.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the camp's biggest surprises was first-round draft pick
Sasha Victorine, a midfield/striker from UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine, who stands 6-foot-2, gives the Galaxy a threat in the
air with his presence on crosses. He's the closest the Galaxy has
to a replacement for Hermosillo and he's worked well with midfield
playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we would like a striker to replace Carlos, but
Sasha has really stepped up,'' said Schmid. ``Sasha gives us more
of a target. He's a little stronger than anyone else we have up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   The backline that led the MLS in fewest goals allowed (29)
remains intact. Fraser, Caligiuri, Vanney and Hendrickson give the
Galaxy experience. Rookie Danny Califf as well as experienced
defenders Joe Franchino and Steve Jolley give L.A. depth.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, who amazes Schmid with his fitness and work ethic,
joins Roy Myers, Danny Pena and Clint Mathis in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, Jones will likely join Victorine.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, who has perhaps
more reason than anyone else to get this season started. More than
any player, he has bad memories of November's loss to United.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman botched a routine clearing pass that led to an easy
United goal. The mistake left a bitterness Hartman has tried to rid
himself of ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the healing begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me (this season) is personal,'' said Hartman, who recently
signed a new four-year contract. ``It's made me a lot more hungry.
For other people it maybe puts them into a daze before there is a
wake-up call, but I can't wait to get the season started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 0214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0058 </DOCNO>
