<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     03-15 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KINGS TO HAVE THRASHERS REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Ed Ward dropped off new Kings Kelly
Buchberger and Nelson Emerson at the Atlanta airport Tuesday
morning for their flight to Los Angeles, they wondered when they
might see each other again.
</P>
<P>
   How about tonight.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ward returned to his home, he had been traded from
Atlanta to the Mighty Ducks, who are hosting the Los Angeles Kings
at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he might want to stick around the airport,''
Emerson said, after arriving at the Kings practice facility in El
Segundo. ``There has been a lot of talk about who was going to be
traded. Now it has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, 23 players were swapped in 12 trades before Tuesday's
deadline. The biggest name was Vancouver's high-scoring forward
Alexander Mogilny, who had a goal in Monday's night's 3-2 overtime
loss to the Kings at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny is headed to the Eastern Conference-leading New Jersey
Devils, who many think have just secured their place in the Stanley
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings acquisitions aren't quite that dramatic. Emerson,
32,is joining his seventh franchise and missed nine games earlier
this season with a concussion. Buchberger, 33, will play on the
fourth line. But Emerson, the Kings new second-line right winger,
has five 20-goal seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than playing out the schedule for the expansion Atlanta
Thrashers, Emerson and Buchberger, a member of three Stanley Cups
champions in Edmonton, have been dropped in the middle of the tense
Western Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   By beating Vancouver, the Kings (34-27-8) jumped ahead of
Phoenix for the fifth spot in the West. That could mean an
unenviable matchup with Detroit rather than a showdown with
Colorado, one of the league's hottest teams.
</P>
<P>
   But by making the deal that sent disgruntled Donald Audette and
promising rookie defenseman Frantisek Kaberle to Atlanta, the Kings
showed they aren't happy just to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are missing pieces, no question,'' Kings captain Rob
Blake said after Monday's trade. ``This is a team that has a chance
to do some things in the playoffs. They bring great character and
leadership to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's post-season plans seem less certain since the Ducks are
five points behind San Jose for the eighth and final spot.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquired for a conditional pick in the 2001 draft and
will play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings are 10 points ahead of the Ducks in the
Pacific Division, they have not dominated their Southern California
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The teams tied 1-1 on Dec. 3 at the Pond and the Ducks won 5-3
on Feb. 8 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Buchberger, Emerson and Ward have had their numbers
blurred by playing on such a bad team.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger and Emerson seemed a little embarrassed that the
Kings acquired two players that totaled a minus-58 on the ice this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Buchberger's Stanley Cup background that makes him so
appealing. He was part of championship clubs in 1987,1988 and 1990
with Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Although those Oilers teams had superior talent, like Wayne
Gretzky and Mark Messier, Buchberger said the biggest lesson he
took from the experience was the concept of teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some of the all-time greats, but no one was bigger than
the team,'' Buchberger said. ``Those guys didn't care who scored
the goals, just as long as they won. That is not always easy.''
</P>
<P>
   About his role as a leader, Buchberger said, ``For right now,
the most important thing is to blend in. You get to know the guys
and they get to know you. They see that you work hard and want to
win badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitting in shouldn't be difficult. Emerson and Blake are old
friends from their college days Bowling Green. Both took quite a
bit of ribbing from Kings players after Emerson arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchberger's strongest connection for the Kings will be the
way he handles the other team's top forwards. Tonight's assignment:
Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so quick and fast, but you can take away their room
to operate on the ice. ``he said. ``That's what it's like in the
playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
