<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NUGGETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS BEAT NUGGETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Staples Center, which has become to Los Angeles
Clippers games as an off-duty church is to AA meetings, was the
site of a rare sobering experience for the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the distilled joy of a one-game winning streak, the home
team received another cold-blooded fourth-quarter performance from
rookie Lamar Odom to post a 110-104 victory Tuesday over the Denver
Nuggets before 10,706.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a lot better job of executing at the end of the
game,`` said Odom, whose team usually calls for the cigarettes and
blindfolds in the last 12 minutes. ``We were down, but I felt that
it was still anyone's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, anyone named Odom.
</P>
<P>
   With the Clips down, 99-90, he bagged a 3-point basket, then
followed with a runner in the lane to trim Denver's lead to 99-95.
After Derek Anderson (20) produced a three-point play that gave the
Clippers a 102-101 edge with 3:13 to play, Odom broke a 103 tie -
and the Nuggets' backs -- with a 3-pointer at 2:04.
</P>
<P>
   Denver never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many guys in the NBA can do what he can do,'' Clippers
guard Eric Piatkowski said of Odom, who scored 13 of his 25 points
in the final quarter. ``He's playing awesome right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Piatkowski isn't slouching these days, either. He followed
Sunday's 20-point effort at Oakland with a career-high 31 points on
11-of-15 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I can keep the feeling going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets (26-38), who led by as many as 14 points (92-78) in
the fourth, seemed to be feeling a bit gassed. After losing to the
Lakers on Monday in Denver, they didn't have enough residual
chutzpah to avoid a seven-game losing streak and overcome the
Clippers' Hyde-and-Jekyll routine, despite 31 points from Antonio
McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets trailed 27-24 after one quarter, achieved a tie at
55 by intermission and - thanks to 13 points from McDyess in that
period - led, 86-76, after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (14-50) were down by 14 midway through the fourth
quarter, before Odom went cuckoo with assorted moments of greatness
in the final stanza. His dynamic inclination keyed a closing run of
32-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew that for us to win, I would have to score,'' said
Odom, who also had 9 assists and 4 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Interim coach Jim Todd gave his blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells us we've been folding lately in situations like
that,'' said Todd, whose team made 53 percent of its field-goal
tries, but allowed Denver to snipe at a 57 percent rate. ``We don't
mind Lamar having the ball late in the game; he's getting better
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Point guard Jeff McInnis, a Y2K CBA evacuee and survivor
of two 10-day NBA contracts, was signed by the Clippers through the
2000-2001 season. The Nuggets' visit provided a reunion opportunity
for McInnis, who was chosen by Denver with the 37th pick in the
1996 Draft. ... Mario Bennett, who was signed to a 10-day contract
by the Clippers on March 7, did not suit up due to soreness in his
right knee. ... The status of power forward Brian Skinner remains
indefinite due to lingering pain in his left ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
