   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PLATT-STARTING-OVER (Santa Rosa, Calif.) _ In one of the more
unusual corporate job changes in years, Lewis E. Platt, 58, left
Hewlett-Packard last year after 33 years, including a seven-year
term as chief executive, and promptly took the top job at
Kendall-Jackson Wine Estates. While Platt's new job certainly seems
romantic, his switch has also brought a management problem that the
textbooks do not discuss: How does an executive who has already
climbed his way to the top, and grown used to the trappings that
come with one of corporate America's plum jobs, start anew? The
question is particularly relevant because both the average age and
the tenure of chief executives at large companies are dropping. By
David Leonhardt.
</P>
