<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX     03-15 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wally Pryor leaving job as UT `Voice'
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ His mellow voice is as much a part of
Royal-Memorial Stadium as Big Bertha, Bevo and bad nachos, but
Wally Pryor is through as ``the Voice of the Longhorns.''
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, who started as the public address announcer at University
of Texas football games in 1957, about the same time electricity
was discovered, and the same year Darrell Royal began coaching at
UT, says he's not upset about losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make a change, and I agreed,'' Wally said. But he
says UT brought it up, not him. ``It's disappointing, but it's not
the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the job isn't what it used to be anyway. It's gone from
calling out touchdowns to plugging Taco Bell. ``I'm reading
commercials the whole time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UT Associate Athletic Director Chris Plonsky says UT hasn't
decided who will take Wally's place.
</P>
<P>
   Wally's one of those chili cookoff kind of guys who doesn't fit
UT's stuffy image. Wally was born on Leap Day. ``I just had my 18th
birthday February 29th, so women can take advantage of me legally
now, but I can't drink yet,'' Wally joked.
</P>
<P>
   To add a little levity, Wally announced the Slippery Rock scores
over the stadium P.A. system. He was known for wisecracking in
front of 78,000 strangers. He was a friend of the late Hondo
Crouch, self-described ``imagineer'' and founder of Luckenbach, the
town near Fredericksburg that is really a beer joint with live
music.
</P>
<P>
   Wally says that at Scholz -- eer -- ar-- en before a game in the
1970s, Crouch asked him to mention his name over the P.A. system
during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I can't do that,''' Wally recalled. Yeah, right.
During the game, Wally announce-- : ``Hondo Crouch, Scholz -- eer
-- arden called. They want you to pick up your grandmother after
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterwards, Hondo came up and said, `Thank you; I'm going to
be at the Broken Spoke after the next game,''' Wally said. From one
game to the next, fans would wait to hear at which bar Crouch was
supposed to pick up his grandmother. One week Granny would
allegedly be at the Spoke, the next week at the Rusty Nail, the
next week at the Split Rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then T. Jones (a former assistant athletic director in the
early '80s) made me stop ad-libbing,'' Wally said. He says Jones
made him stick to the script because he made up names for the
members of the Longhorn Luvs, a female dance team that performed at
UT men's basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had given them all nicknames like Luscious Lil, Sexy Sal _
nothing bad,'' Wally said. ``He had gotten a letter from this gal,
and she complained about how I had introduced them.''
</P>
<P>
   So who will UT pick to replace Wally? One possibility would be
KVET radio executive Bob Cole, since KVET has the contract to
broadcast the UT football games. But Cole's not sure he's
interested. ``Following Wally Pryor would be like following Darrell
Royal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what about Matthew McConaughey?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso is a columnist for the Austin American-Statesman. He
can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
