<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-COX-     03-15 1806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-COX-FILE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was in Texas recently, I saw a billboard on I-20,
about 23 miles north of Big Springs, stating that the land was the
property of the Georgia Institute of Technology. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The property, which totals several hundred acres in Mitchell
County, was an endowed gift from the estate of Julius Brown in
1928, said Tech spokesman Bob Harty. Tech receives oil receipt
revenue from the land. The endowment income supports professorships
in electrical engineering and/or chemistry, Harty added, with the
chairs named in honor of Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When tracking the Dow Jones Industrial Average and Nasdaq
composite index, what do the numbers represent? How do changes
affect the individual investor?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Dow is an average obtained by adding the prices of 30
large blue-chip stocks and dividing by a divisor, which is chosen
to adjust for stock splits that have occurred over the years.
Because of the way it's computed, high-priced stocks have more
influence on the Dow than low-priced stocks, said Myron Greene,
retired Georgia State University business professor and publisher
of the Mutual Fund Timing Guide.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite is an index whose value is obtained by
dividing the current market value of all stocks traded on Nasdaq by
the market value of all stocks traded on Nasdaq on Feb. 5, 1971
(the Friday before Nasdaq's first day of trading), and multiplying
by 100. This technique gives more weight to stocks with higher
market valuations and is unaffected by relative price levels,
Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Point changes in any average or index aren't very significant,
Greene explained. Investors should focus on the percentage changes.
For example, when the Dow was at 1,000, a change of 100 points
amounted to 10 percent. With the Dow currently around 10,000, a
100-point change is a relatively insignificant 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow is dominated by large, well-established companies, while
Nasdaq is the home of many high-tech firms. So investors owning
equity-income or index funds should be more concerned with the Dow.
Those owning growth mutual funds should watch the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year, NASA recovered the Mercury 7 space capsule that
sank after Gus Grissom splashed down in it. Did the space agency
discover the reason for its sinking?
</P>
<P>
   A: NASA has known all along that the capsule's hatch blew open
prematurely, allowing the spacecraft to fill with water. But the
reason for the hatch's blowing open may never be known.
</P>
<P>
   The 7 1/2-foot aluminum and titanium capsule, Liberty Bell 7,
sank 3 miles to the bottom of the ocean floor after splashdown on
July 21, 1961. It was brought to the surface last July 20 by Curt
Newport, an underwater salvage expert who spent 14 years searching
for it. He finally located it about 300 miles southeast of Cape
Canaveral, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But Newport's team didn't find the hatch, which might have shed
more light on what happened. Grissom, who swam from the capsule
after the hatch flew off, insisted for the rest of his life that he
didn't cause it to blow. Along with two other astronauts, he died
in 1967 during an Apollo launch pad fire.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought I read that Herb Kelleher, of Southwest Airlines,
had died. Am I wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A: What you read was that Kelleher, Southwest's chairman,
president and CEO, was undergoing radiation treatment for prostate
cancer. It was reported in August that he would receive brief
radiation treatments each weekday for about eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest spokeswoman Linda Rutherford told Q&AMP;A that Kelleher's
doctors were ``very encouraged'' at his reponse to the radiation
treatment, which he finished in October.
</P>
<P>
   He's now back at work full time, she said, and will undergo
further testing this spring to monitor his status.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that there will not be another Feb. 29 in a year
ending in 00 until 2400. I've tried doing the math, but can't
figure out why 2100, 2200 and 2300 won't have one. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Only those century years (years ending in 00) that are
exactly divisible by 400 (such as 1600, 2000 and 2400) are leap
years. The century years you cited obviously don't meet that
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal. The calendar year and the solar year don't
quite coincide, so we add an extra day, Feb. 29, every four years
(leap year). But adding a day every fourth year then makes the
average calendar year 11 minutes, 14 seconds too long.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the 16th century, mathematicians decided to tweak the
system a bit more. They calculated that the correction amounted to
three days in 400 years, and saw that by dropping three leap years
in a cycle of 400 years, all would be well.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the extra day isn't added in the century years _ except
those divisible by 400.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard a radio interview with the U.S. ambassador-at-large
for war crimes issues. Who is he, and what exactly is his mission?
Is this something new?
</P>
<P>
   A: David Scheffer is the first-ever ambassador-at-large for war
crimes issues. The appointment carries an ambassadorial rank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Scheffer was nominated for the post by President
Clinton, confirmed by the Senate, and sworn in by Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson, who then was U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations. Scheffer has served in the Clinton administration since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department explains that this post addresses serious
violations of international humanitarian law anywhere in the world.
Scheffer coordinates support for the functions of the Yugoslav and
Rwandan War Crimes Tribunals, and coordinates and leads U.S.
participation in U.N. negotiations for the establishment of a
permanent International Criminal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Scheffer isn't the first, or the only, ambassador-at-large.
Among others: Stephen Sestanovich, for the new independent states
of the former U.S.S.R.; Robert Seiple, for international religious
freedom; and Michael Sheehan, for counterterrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With prices for gasoline continuing to rise, does the tax
also rise? Does the government make more money, in other words,
when gasoline costs more?
</P>
<P>
   A: The federal tax on a gallon of gasoline is 18.4 cents a
gallon; state taxes are extra. The total amount of tax revenue
going to the federal and state governments rises only if the total
amount of gasoline sold rises, unless some states impose a state
sales tax, which would apply to the retail price.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute posts tax information for all
states online at www.api.org/consumer/fueltax99.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Atlanta Braves pitcher Greg Maddux had laser eye surgery.
What's involved in the procedure?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Braves pitcher, who was nearsighted, underwent laser eye
surgery last July 9 at Emory Vision Correction Center in Atlanta.
Emory's Claire Schwall explained that in the LASIK procedure, which
is intended to correct near-sightedness and astigmatism, a portion
of the cornea is lifted and the bed of the cornea is reshaped. In
Maddux's case, the surgery enabled him to shed both the glasses he
often wore off the field, and the contacts he wore while pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said he had the procedure done for personal reasons, not
in hopes that it would improve his pitching. But he has told
reporters that he's now more comfortable on the mound. Before the
surgery, he wore contacts when pitching because they gave him
better peripheral vision than glasses. But they also were
constantly irritating his eyes, he said, so for him the surgery was
a better option.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported several weeks ago that a Navy helicopter
crashed and sank within sight of a ship off San Diego. Several
sailors and Marines were rescued. Did the Navy recover the bodies
of the others? I never saw a follow-up after an initial report that
the search had been called off.
</P>
<P>
   A: The bodies of six Marines and a Navy corpsman were pulled
from the wreckage at the bottom of the ocean nearly two weeks after
the Dec. 9 crash. The CH-46E Sea Knight helicopter had taken off
from the Bonhomme Richard, an amphibious assault ship, and was
approaching the Navy tanker Pecos when it apparently got caught in
a metal safety net and was pulled into the water. The men were
training for a mission to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Marines were rescued quickly after the accident, which
occurred about 15 miles off the San Diego shore. But the
23,000-pound copter filled with water and sank about 3,600 feet to
the ocean floor, making rescue of those trapped inside impossible.
Their bodies were recovered by a submersible robot that can dive to
5,000 feet and retrieve objects with mechanical arms.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service for the seven who died was held Dec. 20 at
Camp Pendleton in California.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed that on some TV crime shows, the police refer to
a criminal as a ``skel.'' Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: A dictionary of slang terms spells the word ``skell'' and
defines it as ``a street derelict who also may be a villain.'' The
Dutch ``schelm'' (meaning scoundrel or villain) appears to have
been the root word. According to the dictionary, the term found its
way into English as early as 1611, and was spelled ``skelum.'' It
was revived by New York police as ``skel'' or ``skell'' by the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, Q&AMP;A was settling a bet about the number of
counties in Georgia and Texas. In passing, you mentioned that
Delaware has only three counties. I'm a former Delaware resident,
and I believe the state actually has hundreds. Can you check?
</P>
<P>
   A: This may seem like a word game. Delaware has three counties _
Kent, New Castle and Sussex _ so that reference indeed was correct.
</P>
<P>
   But Delaware also has ``hundreds.'' In fact, it's the only state
with hundreds. But that doesn't refer to the number of counties;
hundreds is the term for the divisions within Delaware's three
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Newton of the Delaware Division of Libraries said the
state has a total of 33 hundreds, with 11 in New Castle, 9 in Kent
and 13 in Sussex.
</P>
<P>
   There are several theories about how the term originated in
Delaware, Newton told Q&AMP;A, but the two most widely accepted are
that it referred to an area of 10 families or 100 people, or to an
area that could supply 100 militiamen. It traces to centuries back
in England, Newton added.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online, check
http://dir.yahoo.com/Regional/USStates/Delaware/ for information or
look at the Delaware entry in World Book Encyclopedia, available at
any library.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
