</P>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A&AMP;E recently featured a program titled ``66 AD.'' Is it
possible to order a videotape of it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The complete title is ``66 AD: The Last Revolt.'' The
cost is $29.95. You can order it by calling 1-888-423-1212 (ask for
item number AAE-17772), or online at www.aetv.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the governor of Georgia, and what was the date, when
the state flag was changed to include the Confederate battle
symbol?
</P>
<P>
   A: On Feb. 13, 1956, Democratic Gov. Marvin Griffin signed into
law a bill changing the 1879 Georgia flag to the current one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What causes most accidental deaths in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Preliminary National Safety Council statistics for 1998 (the
latest available) show that 41,200 people died in motor vehicle
accidents. This compares to 16,600 from falls; 8,400 from solid or
liquid poison; 4,100 from drowning; 3,700 from fires/burns; 3,200
from ingestion of food/objects; 900 from firearms; and 600 from
poison gases.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Jim Henson Co. was sold recently to a German company. Why
would Henson's children want to sell their father's company?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a matter of economics, according to the principals
involved. In an interview with the Los Angeles Times, Brian Henson,
chairman and CEO of Jim Henson Co., explained that it's becoming
``harder and harder for independent companies like ours'' to face
the increasing difficulties as power in the entertainment industry
becomes more and more concentrated in the hands of a few global
conglomerates. ``The huge, vertically integrated companies want a
piece of our programs (in exchange for air time) and are paying
lower licensing fees,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Henson said combining with the German company EM.TV &AMP;
Merchandising, in a deal worth $680 million in cash and stock,
should enable Henson Co. to grow, without any change in leadership
and with its headquarters remaining in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Henson Co., which is controlled by the five
children of its founder, the late puppeteer Jim Henson, is
profitable on annual revenue of more than $200 million. But it has
struggled in recent years, despite the appeal of its Muppet
characters, to reinvent and grow the brand.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had agreed to buy Henson Co. in 1989 for $150 million,
but the deal fell apart after Jim Henson's sudden death in May
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the reporting about Sen. John McCain, we've seen and
heard very little about his first wife. Who was she? How long were
they married? Did they have children? Do you have any other
information about her?
</P>
<P>
   A: His first wife was Carol Shepp, who had been a model in
Philadelphia. They met when McCain was at the Naval Academy, began
a serious relationship while he was stationed in Pensacola, Fla.,
and married in 1965. They had a daughter, Sydney; and McCain
adopted Shepp's sons, Douglas and Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   As everyone knows, McCain was imprisoned in Hanoi during the
Vietnam War. During that time, his wife was severely injured in an
automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1980, McCain petitioned a Florida court to dissolve
the marriage, saying it was ``irretrievably broken.'' His wife
didn't contest the divorce. McCain agreed to pay her medical bills
for life and gave her the deeds to houses they owned in Virginia
and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Family friends blamed the breakup on McCain's 5 1/2-year absence
_ he was shot down in October 1967, and not released until March
1973 _ as well as affairs he later acknowledged. He married Cindy
Hensley in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Shepp, who remains loyal to her ex-husband, lives in northern
Virginia. She refuses to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When private individuals earn free airline tickets by
accumulating enough frequent-flier miles, are those tickets taxable
by the Internal Revenue Service?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you earn the miles (and tickets) with your own money, that
ordinarily isn't considered taxable income, said IRS spokesman Mark
Green.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that the IRS hasn't adopted an official
policy on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I have two homes, and we have received notices at
both that we will be receiving forms for Census 2000. Should we
complete both forms, since we split our time at both homes, or only
one for the home we consider our primary residence (where we are
registered to vote)?
</P>
<P>
   A: You should use the form delivered at your primary residence,
and discard the other one, said Mary Vetter of the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The forms, by the way, will have a telephone number to call if
you have any questions. And you'll be able to talk to a person and
not a machine, Vetter said.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, in case you won't be going back to your primary
residence in time to fill out and return the form by mail, you can
call the number and answer the questions by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you figure GMT?
</P>
<P>
   A: Greenwich Mean Time is based on the prime meridian, a
north-south line passing through Greenwich, a borough of London.
The site of Britain's Royal Greenwich Observatory, it was
designated as the world's prime meridian by an international
conference in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   There are 24 time zones, each with a width of 15 degrees
longitude. Moving west of Greenwich, the time becomes one hour
earlier with each time zone entered. In standard time, excluding
Alaska and Hawaii, the United States has four, GMT -5 (East Coast)
to -8 (West Coast). So, on standard time, if it's noon at
Greenwich, it's 7 a.m. in New York, 4 a.m. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were Girl Scout cookies ever made by hand?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes: the sale of cookies in 1917 when the Mistletoe Troop
baked and sold cookies in its high school cafeteria in Muskogee,
Okla., as a service project. Then, in the '20s and '30s, Girl
Scouts and their mothers in different parts of the country baked
their own simple sugar cookies, packaged them in wax paper bags,
and sold them door-to-door.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, Greater Philadelpia became the first council to sell
commercially baked cookies. Three bakeries _ down from 14 in 1961 _
are licensed to produce them now.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
