<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-BREAD-PHOTOS16-COX     03-15 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAD-PHOTOS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miracle of the loaves
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ave Bonar bakes autobiographical bread.
</P>
<P>
   Bonar is one of the most accomplished photographers in Texas,
specializing in striking black-and-white portraits and documentary
shots that capture whimsical and unguarded moments for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   But in her home in Austin, Bonar prefers to caress bread dough,
not a camera, to preserve her own family's history.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the rear corner of her refrigerator is a plastic box
where she stores a treasured family heirloom. Inside is 1 1/2 cups
of homemade liquid yeast that allows Bonar to keep her heritage
alive by continuing to bake the same bread her family has made for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Bonar's grandmother began baking with the yeast mixture nearly
80 years ago, and each bread loaf made since then carries her
imprint and that of all family members who baked after her. That's
because a portion of starter mixture is taken out of each batch of
dough and carried over to the next .
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother got it from a neighbor when my father was born
in Texico, New Mexico, and that was in December 1923,'' Bonar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandmother always called it the `everlasting yeast.' I never
heard her call it (bread) starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother, Amarillo homemaker Vonnie Peters Miller, handed
down the everlasting yeast to Bonar's father and mother in Lubbock.
When Bonar left home to attend art school at the University of
Texas in 1969, she packed the active ingredient for her family's
staff of life.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bonar has so cherished the family bread that she
has traveled cross country with the liquid yeast in an ice chest.
She has shipped a portion of the yeast by overnight mail to her
aunt in New Mexico. And she has given some away to close friends
who begged for it, including Austin photographer Steve Clark, who
owns the Stephen L. Clark Gallery for photography.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Bonar even wrapped some of the everlasting yeast in a
large plastic bag, packed it in a cardboard box and mailed it to a
friend. Unfortunately, the package arrived over a weekend and the
yeast grew, leaving the box lumpy and suspicious-looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``His secretary was terrified,'' Bonar said. ``She thought it
was a bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from UT in 1976 with a degree in journalism,
Bonar developed an unmistakable style of photography first inspired
by Russell Lee and others who documented the Depression in
compelling black-and-white photos. Bonar's photos often show the
wry side of life _ a dog tangled in a leash stretched almost to the
breaking point, a young man pushing a line of shopping carts, and
Ann Richards posing next to a tacky fish trophy in a small-town
chamber of commerce during her successful 1990 campaign for Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   As with her photographs, Bonar puts a signature touch on her
breadmaking. She turns the traditional white bread dough into whole
wheat or multigrain loaves.
</P>
<P>
   And, at a friend's suggestion, she installed a wood-burning oven
in her South Austin back yard last year to bake the bread. Since
then, she has discovered the joys of gathering wood, building and
stoking a fire, and guesstimating the oven's temperature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has put it in a different realm for me,'' Bonar said.
``It is so much better outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonar spent several hundred dollars for her oven made of natural
materials, which is called a cob oven. She and her friends mortared
recycled concrete chunks to form the base of the oven. An Austin
company called CobCrew helped build the baking chamber out of
layers of mixed clay, sand, and straw.
</P>
<P>
   Bonar hasn't had to buy firewood because she collects discarded
tree branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two station wagon loads of wood from (former Texas Lt.
Gov.) Bob Bullock's house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonar had been photographing a family that lived across the
street from Bullock. She stopped to talk to the tree-trimmers,
asked for the wood _ and they even cut it to lengths she needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a chain saw, but I've never had to use it,'' Bonar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bonar's friends, the everlasting bread is as popular as
her photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her she should be marketing it because it really is
fabulous bread,'' said Sherry Matthews, who runs her own marketing
and public relations company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her bread is a way of showing affection,'' Matthews said. ``If
I were sick or had a bad day or some stressful thing had happened
to me that I might have mentioned to her, then I would come home
and there would be this little round of bread on my doorstep. I
always thought it was wonderful. That would be her way of trying to
cheer me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonar's three siblings followed her example of carrying on the
family bread tradition. Her sister bakes the bread in Panama, a
brother bakes in Venezuela and another brother bakes in Austin. Her
mother still makes it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bonar's father baked bread, but he died of cancer in 1983. While
her father was ill, Bonar baked a lot of bread and brought loaves
to the hospital nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over there one day and we were standing over the bed,
and I told the nurse, `We bake bread,''' Bonar said. ``And he
looked at me and said, `No, you bake bread.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bonar knew her father, a psychiatrist who used to bring patients
home to knead bread, was handing off the everlasting bread for the
last time. Bonar, his eldest child, instantly understood that her
father was acknowledging that ``I'm carrying it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
