<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-HALIBUT16-COX     03-15 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALIBUT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresh halibut is on the line
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a signal that spring is really on its way, the
fishing season for fresh Alaskan halibut begins today. That means
the prized fish will be in stores by the weekend _ or no later than
Tuesday, the first day of spring. It depends on the weather those
first few days.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that under tightly controlled fishing, fresh
halibut was taken during brief openings and was available only
sporadically. The controls have worked and halibut fishing in
Alaska, which produces 90 percent of the Pacific halibut, is now
allowed from March 15 to Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Fish is always best enjoyed fresh and in season. During the
winter, what little fresh halibut is available arrives from the
East Coast. It is in short supply and commands a caviar price _ as
high as $15-$16 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific halibut is vastly more plentiful. While the opening
price may be high, it will drop dramatically as the season
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of halibut is that it is lean and pure white, with
appeal to those who avoid more assertively flavored fish such as
tuna and salmon. The flavor of halibut is delicate, and the big
flakes are firm. The only down side is that it dries out if even
slightly overcooked. That's why some experts avoid broiling or
grilling it, preferring to poach or braise it in liquids.
</P>
<P>
   But those aren't popular cooking methods. Roasting (or baking)
thick halibut steaks works if the fish is protected with butter. Of
course, it isn't so lean then, but in this case we're talking taste
and texture.
</P>
<P>
   It is crucial to cook the food on the bone to maximize the
flavor and retain moisture. The four sections of a halibut steak
separate from the bone easily when cooked.
</P>
<P>
   ROAST HALIBUT WITH BUTTER AND BREAD CRUMBS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, melted and seasoned with salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large or two medium halibut steaks, about 1 1/2 pounds or more
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup bread crumbs (fresh is best, but dried will work)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Pour half the seasoned butter in
the bottom of a baking dish and place the fish on top. Drizzle with
the rest of the butter and sprinkle bread crumbs over all. Place in
the oven. Bake about 8-10 minutes, then check for doneness by
peeking between the flesh and the bone with a thin-bladed knife.
</P>
<P>
   When there is just the tiniest bit of translucency remaining _
before the fish is totally opaque _ remove the fish from the oven.
It will finish cooking by the time you get it to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with some of the pan juices spooned over the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 416 calories, 22 g
fat, 100 mg cholesterol, 388 mg sodium. (Note: While the pan juices
are good, the fish is moist without them. Skip them and you'll
substantially reduce the calories and fat).
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe is adapted from Mark Bittman's ``Fish'' (Macmillan).
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite ways to cook fish is pan roasting. The fish
is seared on one side in an ovenproof skillet _ I use cast iron _
then turned and popped into a 450-degree oven to finish cooking.
The technique, a favorite of chefs, helps keep fish succulent but
provides a crisp exterior. Fish steaks or center-cut fillets should
be at least an inch thick for this technique.
</P>
<P>
   This is an everyday recipe that requires no special preparation.
Serve it with a a few spoonfuls of your favorite salsa.
</P>
<P>
   CUMIN-DUSTED HALIBUT
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds halibut steaks, at least an inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pat the fillets dry and sprinkle with cumin and salt and pepper
to taste on both sides. Heat oil in a large cast iron skillet. Sear
the fillets over high heat until brown, about 4 minutes. Use a
spatula to turn. Place the skillet in the middle of the oven and
roast for another 6 to 8 minutes. Check doneness by using a thin
knife to separate the flesh from the bone. It should separate
easily and be opaque throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 200 calories, 5.2
g fat, 54 mg cholesterol, 360 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
