<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-0316-     03-15 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photo and a sig/locator map are
available. The photo with this story is not of great quailty,
however, it can be used 2 cols.
 &HT;    LIFE-IN-AMERICA 0316: These ``gals'' love their vets
 &HT;    By Christine Evans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH. Fla. _ At Emma-N-Kay's Very Cheap and Wonderful
Volunteer Barber Shop in the Veterans Affairs Medical Center, two
special ladies keep the vets looking spiffy.
</P>
<P>
   And every penny in profit goes back to their 'fellas.'
</P>
<P>
   Barber shop profits used to help veterans in need
</P>
<P>
   C'mon in, hon! Take a load off! Doll face, you look adorable,
but what do we do about that mustache?
</P>
<P>
   It's open-up time at the veterans hospital, and the saints with
scissors, as their adoring customers call them, are busy snipping
and singing, and when they're finished, every single fella settled
into the cushiony chairs by the long mirror is gonna be a ``doll''
or a ``lady killer'' or a ``sure shot'' on that job interview.
Because, honey, this ain't just any old barber shop. This is
Emma-N-Kay's place.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can you dance to ``In the Mood'' while you get a
little taken off the sides?
</P>
<P>
   Where else do fellas in wheelchairs line up under an oldfangled
barber pole to book a date with their ``gals''?
</P>
<P>
   Where else do ``two old birds'' _ that's Emma talking, and she's
only 82 _ stand on their feet all day administering $5 haircuts,
then give away every penny of profit ($35,417.84, to be exact) to
the very vets who come in for a snip and an eyebrow clip?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, sure, as 73-year-old Kay might say in her spunky
Bostonese. Plenty of veterans hospitals have barber shops, don't
they? Yeah, yeah. But they don't have Emma-N-Kay, the saints with
the scissors (and matching blond bouffants), so really, there's no
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearts of gold, these ladies,'' a smitten customer says, after
Emma kisses his bald spot. ``Plus, they promised me hair on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello? You haven't been to Emma-N-Kay's Very Cheap and Wonderful
Volunteer Barber Shop on the first floor of the towering, pink
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in Riviera Beach? Your loss, doll.
Because there's a lot of good people in this world, and as Emma
puts it, ``most of 'em are right here, getting their sideburns
trimmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stand in the doorway a moment (the whole place looks as if some
set decorator got hold of it for an old black-and-white), and maybe
you'll get lucky. Maybe Emma will hit the button on the dancing
flowers she keeps on the counter right next to her 1934 operating
license from the Frances School of Beauty Culture, and the flower
pot will play ``In the Mood,'' and Kay will do a little dance as
she hot-curls the hair of a sergeant's wife, and the five-dollar
bills will land like B-17s in the cash register, only to fly out
again to help the vets.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Kay is in the middle of a color job, or Emma is busy
on a client's flat-top, and a doctor or nurse or social worker will
look in the door and say, ``Hey Emma, hey Kay, there's this fella
who needs ... ``
</P>
<P>
   And that's it. That's all it takes. They might do a little
research, put their heads together a bit, and then if the cause is
deemed worthy _ and it usually is, because these are America's vets
we're talking about _ they make a little withdrawal from their
significant reserves at the credit union. The other day, they
kicked in $200 to send veteran amputees on a Colorado ski trip. A
few winters ago, they bought 40 warm coats for homeless vets. And
when a fella needs a special mattress so he can, please God, sleep
one good night through, it's Emma-N-Kay who come up with the
$360-plus.
</P>
<P>
   And how about the vet who had cancer? His whole family got to go
to Disney World at Christmastime, thanks to Emma-N-Kay, and when
the thank-you note came in, on Mickey Mouse stationery, they pinned
it to the bulletin board and wept.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Preffer and Kay Douckas started up the Volunteer Barber
Shop not quite four years ago, after a hospital bigwig admired the
way they cut the hair of an ill veteran friend. They have worked
every Monday and Thursday since, giving $5 haircuts and $20 perms
to vets and spouses and sisters and best friends from Iowa _ some
5,000 heads in all _ pulling in $200 on a good day, and spitting it
right back out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our chance to do something,'' says Emma. Her husband,
Charles, drove a tank in World War II. Came home with heart
trouble. Kay's Frank was a foot soldier. Got two broken legs when a
tank plowed his foxhole. The husbands met after the war, through a
Disabled American Veterans chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The ladies are explaining all this when a gentleman with two
combat tours in Vietnam and two parachute jumps in Korea settles
into one of the comfy chairs and says he would like to put in a
word for the old days, back when patriotism was cool, not smirked
at or ignored. ``I'd like to see people in their 20s and 30s come
out and wave a flag once in a while,'' he says. ``Maybe show up for
a parade and shake a vet's hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite right, say Emma-N-Kay, and around the little shop there is
a collective nod, because there isn't a soul in here who doesn't
feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   Like old pros, which they are, having worked decades in the
beauty business, Emma-N-Kay remember everything _ who got the color
last time, who has the artificial knee, who does not want his
ponytail cut.
</P>
<P>
   They are accompanied in their meticulous pursuits by a
half-dozen volunteers who handle the cash and sweep the floors. And
then there's Jim Diana, a veteran himself who used to own a Chicago
hair salon. He has throat cancer, but even so he drives 38 miles
from Deerfield Beach to help the other vets, the ones without legs,
the ones without families, the ones who have job interviews and are
alight with hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take my picture,'' says Jim. And what he means is,
``Don't give me too much credit.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a sort of silent ``no self-aggrandizement'' rule in
force in the shop. Around here, you might have fought in the Battle
of the Bulge, but all the other guys fought in something, too, so
wouldn't do to brag about it. It's all for one, and one for all.
</P>
<P>
   And Emma-N-Kay for everybody. ``Oh, my, sweetheart, don't you
look grand!'' Emma says to a fellow who, really, does not look that
grand at all. But he will, when she's finished.
</P>
<P>
   A white-haired POW who was held in German camps during World War
II is wheeled in for a much-needed trim, and Emma gives him a red
blanket because he's cold, and takes up her scissors. The POW has a
son who is going to visit from Texas. He has not seen his boy in a
long, long time, and he has not said a word all afternoon, perhaps
because of nerves, but when Emma finishes him up and brushes the
white leavings from his shoulders, he gives her a little smile and
a $2 tip on the $5 haircut.
</P>
<P>
   A fella might not be able to lift a fork to his lips at
lunchtime, but he sure as hell will find a way to dig into his
pocket to hand the saints a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my, sweetie, thank you!''
</P>
<P>
   Now we know what you are thinking. Emma-N-Kay really ought to
charge more than five bucks a haircut. Yeah, yeah, says Kay. She
knows. They could.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't that be a little unpatriotic? Don't our fellas
deserve a break? And so, insists Emma, a glow in her cheeks, a
dance in her step, five dollars it is and always will be, at least
until the year 2010, at which point, they might reevaluate _ but
not retire.
</P>
<P>
   It's close-up time at the V.A. Barber Shop, but never mind,
sweetie pie, because Emma-N-Kay will be back on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   christineevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Hairstylist Kay Douckas (above, center),
</P>
<P>
   prepares to cut the hair of
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hurley, a resident of the extended care facility at the
veterans hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At right, Emma Preffer
</P>
<P>
   works with Herb Strelzik of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID SPENCER / Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0078 </DOCNO>
