son who is going to visit from Texas. He has not seen his boy in a
long, long time, and he has not said a word all afternoon, perhaps
because of nerves, but when Emma finishes him up and brushes the
white leavings from his shoulders, he gives her a little smile and
a $2 tip on the $5 haircut.
</P>
<P>
   A fella might not be able to lift a fork to his lips at
lunchtime, but he sure as hell will find a way to dig into his
pocket to hand the saints a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my, sweetie, thank you!''
</P>
<P>
   Now we know what you are thinking. Emma-N-Kay really ought to
charge more than five bucks a haircut. Yeah, yeah, says Kay. She
knows. They could.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't that be a little unpatriotic? Don't our fellas
deserve a break? And so, insists Emma, a glow in her cheeks, a
dance in her step, five dollars it is and always will be, at least
until the year 2010, at which point, they might reevaluate _ but
not retire.
</P>
<P>
   It's close-up time at the V.A. Barber Shop, but never mind,
sweetie pie, because Emma-N-Kay will be back on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   christineevans(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Hairstylist Kay Douckas (above, center),
</P>
<P>
   prepares to cut the hair of
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hurley, a resident of the extended care facility at the
veterans hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At right, Emma Preffer
</P>
<P>
   works with Herb Strelzik of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID SPENCER / Cox News Service
</P>
