<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   RAVES _ ATLANTA _ The face of the youth counterculture of 2000
can be seen at free-form parties called raves. Raves have been
around for awhile, but they've gone from spontaneous, semi-private
affairs to a full-fledged scene, promoted openly and held in venues
like the Tabernacle and the Atrium. Sometimes thousands attend, to
take in the thumping techno vibe, do drugs and interact
spontaneously, giving and taking massages from strangers, and
flailing on the ``dance'' floor. It's a turn-on, drop-out hippie
scene, minus the politics, plus technology (the techno music and
cyber networking). Another way to look at it: The anti-Buckhead
party scene, which draws 15- to 30-year-olds from all over the
area, and all over the South. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER NEWS
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ Shopping the World _ Without Leaving Town.
Atlanta's such an international city that you can find treaures
from around the globe right here. We tell folks where to find neat
stuff from the four corners. (Morrow, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
