<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GEORGIA-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      03-15 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER MOVES RAISE FEARS IN GEORGIA OF CHECHNYA CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND THOMAS W. HAINES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHATILI, Georgia _ The battered shells of a bus, two flatbed
trucks and a bullet-ridden Mercedes lie abandoned in this mile-high
gorge that snakes through the towering, snowcapped peaks of the
Caucasus mountains.
</P>
<P>
   This rugged landscape, on Georgia's border with the
scorched-earth combat zone that is Chechnya, is the battlefield of
another high-risk conflict, a war of nerves with potentially
explosive implications for a region where the United States and
Russia are maneuvering for influence and strategic strength.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Argun Gorge, Russian paratroopers have closed a
single-lane dirt road that connects Chechnya with Georgia. Russia
described the action as an effort to seal an escape route for
Chechen separatist militants while the army tries to wipe out
remaining rebel bands in the foothills to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is trying to strengthen a decade of independence from
Moscow by moving closer to the West. The Russian troops loom as a
threat that the war could spill over into Georgia. Such a
development would threaten this post-Soviet country's fragile
sovereignty, and cast doubt on lucrative, US-backed gas and oil
pipeline deals Georgia badly needs to revive its economy.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Georgian and Russian troops patrol high bluffs
separated by a neutral zone of a few hundred yards formed by the
sweeping canyon cut by the Argun River. They watch each other with
high-powered binoculars, and scan the area for rebel infiltrators.
Russian warplanes occasionally buzz through Georgian airspace,
dropping mines on suspected paths and firing on the Chechens
risking the snowy passage.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy fighting in the gorge and the harsh winter conditions in
the mountains have combined to trap tens of thousands of Chechens
on the Russian side of the border. Only several thousand refugees
have crossed into Georgia, a trickle compared to the 250,000 who
have sought refuge within Russia. The wrecked cars serve as a
warning that the Russians will shoot at anything that moves on the
gorge road.
</P>
<P>
   But in a few weeks, when spring comes, the snow will melt and
the trees will provide leafy, green cover for refugees to cross
from Chechnya into Georgia through dozens of footpaths. The Russian
troops cannot watch them all, and its air force cannot mine all the
paths.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia's capital, Tbilisi, there are two fears: That there
will be more refugees than this impoverished country, already
divided by two separatist conflicts of its own, can afford to take
in; and that rebel fighters will enter Georgia along with the
civilians, followed by the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions have tested the formidable diplomatic skills of
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze, known in the West as the
former Soviet foreign minister who helped bring down the Iron
Curtain in the late 1980s. Shevardnadze has ordered his country's
border with Russia closed, and negotiated the presence of an
unarmed, nine-person contingent from the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe to observe the border.
</P>
<P>
   Shevardnadze, 77, running for reelection on April 9, bluntly
rules out Chechens, or Russians, crossing into Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible that it will happen, because Georgia is an
independent state and it can control its own border,'' Shevardnadze
told reporters in Tbilisi on Monday. ``And whoever will violate it
will be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   In private, Shevardnadze supporters are not so confident. To
guard the mountainous, 50-mile stretch against rebel infiltration
would require a force much larger than the small detachment of
border guards in Shatili.
</P>
<P>
   And to prevent the Russians from crossing is ``impossible,''
according to Revaz Adamia, a senior member of the Georgian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Western observers doubt the OSCE presence would stop a Russian
advance to crush the rebels. And some Georgian observers suggested
that Russia is purposely pushing the rebels into Georgia to provide
an excuse to invade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's leader is someone capable of provoking and esclating
tensions,'' said Georgian lawmaker Irakly Batiashvili. He was
referring to Russia's acting president, Vladimir Putin, who has
parlayed his hard-line stand on the war into an almost certain
victory in the presidential vote March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and other Russian leaders have charged that Georgia is
aiding the rebels by providing them sanctuary and supply routes out
of their landlocked homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia seeks every opportunity to increase its influence over
Georgia,'' said Georgy Khutsishvili, director of the International
Center on Conflict and Negotiations in Tbilisi. ``It takes a very
delicate approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is negotiating a US-backed pipeline project that would
carry billions of dollars worth of Caspian Sea oil toward Europe
without passing through Russia. Shevardnadze has sought US and
European military and economic support, stating Georgia hopes to
apply for membership in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   But before this can happen, there is another problem: what to do
with the Russian military bases still in the country. Russia in
November agreed to remove them within the next few years, but
Georgians will believe that when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia still depends greatly on Russia, its largest trading
partner. Russian peacekeepers monitor the border with the
separatist Georgian province of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way is flexibility, and Shevardnadze understands that
quite well,'' said Gotcha Tskitishvili, who runs a political
polling firm in Tbilisi. ``It is a dangerous dance between two or
three superpowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Shevardnadze is skilled at the dance, but his government has
lost popular trust by failing to provide even heat and electricity.
A drive through the Georgian countryside outside Tbilisi reveals
entire regions that live by candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   In Tbilisi, the situation is only slightly better. Only
kindergartens, government buildings, hospitals and the five-star
hotel, where foreign visitors like to stay, have regular
electricity. So do residents who have found a way to bribe corrupt
energy officials. Each evening, diesel-fuel generators hum outside
the crumbling palaces that make up central Tbilisi, providing light
for the stores that occupy ground floors.
</P>
<P>
   Most people assume powerful crime groups are stealing
electricity, and that Shevardnadze is either too weak, or too
unwilling, to stop it, Khutsishvili says.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity is only the most tangible evidence of corruption
that spreads through all areas of daily life. Even border officials
were taking huge bribes from refugees from Chechnya who made it
into Georgia when the road in the Argun gorge was open. Other
Georgian officials have been accused by Russia of helping to arm
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Such charges are bound to increase when the spring comes.
Already, the tensions are evident in another icy gorge leading up
to the Chechen border, 40 miles east of Shatili. Here, in three
rough-hewn villages along the Alazania River long inhabited by
ethnic Chechens, 7,000 refugees jokingly refer to the area as ``the
only Chechnya we have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees here say more people will come as soon as the passes
open, rather than face detention, or worse, by Russian security
forces. Every day, someone up here receives news of the deaths of
family members in areas occupied by the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that rebels may try to infiltrate the region, Georgian
security forces have set up a roadblock, where officers search
anyone traveling the only highway to Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has frequently stated that as many as 1,500 rebels are
hiding out in the gorge. Last week, a Russian Su-25 attack bomber
appeared, making several low, threatening passes over the villages
before flying off across the Caucasus to the Chechen side of the
border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
