<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABE-EDUCATION-BOS     03-15 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABE-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE WOES ERODE IDEALS FOR EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe _ Twenty years ago, President Robert Mugabe
ushered in Zimbabwe's independence with a promise to make quality
education free and available to all the country's children. He
succeeded. Within five years, Zimbabwe's school system became the
envy of Africa. Literacy soared.
</P>
<P>
   But as this southern African state slides deeper into its worst
economic and political crisis, Mugabe's government is shedding its
dedication to universal education, and Zimbabwe's early gains in
the classroom are being lost. Education is no longer free. Schools
are crumbling. Teachers are leaving the country, lured to better
jobs in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Dropout rates, meanwhile, are climbing. Amid rising food prices
and rampant unemployment, poor parents are increasingly apt to send
their children to scrounge for work or food rather than to sit in
front of blackboards. Those who are rich enough are making
contingency plans to emigrate _ or at least to send their children
abroad to study.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got independence, the thrust was education. Throughout
the region, it was no secret that Zimbabwe offered by far the best
education, both in quality and quantity,'' said Peter Mabande, head
of the Zimbabwe Teachers' Association. ``Now people question why
the government did a turnaround on education. They were told it was
the passport to the good life. But in an economic crisis as we
have, parents might ask: `If my child is not doing well, why
continue?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe made two promises when he came to power: land reform and
universal education. The country's most arable lands were held by a
relatively small group of white commercial farmers. Schools were
grossly imbalanced according to race. The minority government of
Rhodesia, as Zimbabwe was known then, ensured white children
received excellent instruction, but neglected black schools.
</P>
<P>
   The two issues have followed different arcs since 1980, but both
now lie at the center of a political crisis as the country heads
toward parliamentary elections scheduled for April 29 and 30,
widely considered Zimbabwe's most important ballot since
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The war for liberation was fought over land. But agriculture is
the backbone of Zimbabwe's economy, and once in office, Mugabe
quietly made a deal with the white commercial farmers to leave them
alone if they helped keep the country afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Education reforms came fast on the heels of independence.
Schools were opened to all children, free of charge. Enrollment in
secondary schools nationwide rose by 700 percent between 1980 and
1985. Today, 90 percent of men are literate, according to
government figures, as are 82 percent of women.
</P>
<P>
   Despite early gains, however, several factors slowly eroded the
quality of education, as well as access to it. From the outset,
schools in high-density, low-income suburbs were forced to run two
half-day sessions to accommodate all students. In 1983, to further
ease overcrowding, the government decreed that all students must
advance whether or not they pass their classes. Standards slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first five years after independence, students strove
hard to pass,'' said Solomon Rusirevi, a high school geography
teacher who was a pupil at that time. Liberation motivated people,
he said. ``Now, the future looks bleak. The educated ones can't
find job and the young are losing interest. There is a high rise in
social vices: boys in gangs, girls on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The real difficulties, however, started in the 1990s. Facing
worsening economic conditions, the government accepted
belt-tightening measures under the International Monetary Fund. In
1992 southern Africa suffered its worst drought in a century. A
second drought followed in 1995. ``When agriculture sneezes, the
whole economy coughs,'' Mabande said.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the impact of economic structural adjustment,
drought, and an annual population growth of 3 percent, the
government was forced to abandon free universal education in 1996.
For the first time, parents were forced to pay school fees,
resulting, over time, in a serious discrepancy between the quality
of education in rural and urban schools.
</P>
<P>
   The past three years have been the worst. A worldwide tobacco
glut, economic mismanagement, corruption, and Mugabe's costly
participation in the war in Congo have created a foreign currency
crisis in Zimbabwe. Unemployment and inflation hover in the high
double-digits. The government cannot buy fuel or electricity, let
alone maintain school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are experiencing at the moment one of the hardest times
ever in terms of a projected future,'' said Matson Hlahlo,
president of the Affirmative Action Group, a promoter of small
black business. ``We expected the government to deliver
empowerment. But nothing is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators like Mabande and Rusirevi fear that Zimbabwe's
education system is crumbling beyond repair. Last year, Rusirevi
had no textbooks for his students and no maps to help in his
geography lessons. Schools rely on student fees and additional
levies, but dropout rates are climbing as the economy worsens and
more families cope with AIDS. While about 5,000 new qualified
teachers enter the job market each year, Mabande estimates, only 10
percent take jobs. Many are lured to other countries, leaving
Zimbabwean classrooms in the hands of unqualified or underqualified
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Ilan Elkaim is a parent trying to chart the best course of
education for his children. Late last year, his 16-year-old
daughter took a series of standardized exams determining whether
she could continue onward through the final years of pre-university
schooling. The first two months of this year were tense, but not
because Elkaim wasn't confident in his daughter's abilities.
Rather, the government failed to pay the the board that corrects
the exams, even though parents were required to pay for the testing
service before the exams.
</P>
<P>
   The government and the board reached an undisclosed agreement in
late February, allowing students in Zimbabwe to learn their
results. Elkaim's daughter passed, but now he faces a new worry.
Next year his daughter will take college admission exams. Given
Zimbabwe's current economic crisis, he fears the government will
fail to meet its obligations again, and she won't be able to
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Elkaim is fortunate. He owns a textile factory, so he has means,
and he is married to an American, so he can emigrate. He says
people in his position are putting aside funds to pay the board
directly if the government falters.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country that once served as a model in Africa, it
saddens Elkaim to see the dream of universal education dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is not so much what has happened up until now, but
what will happen in the future,'' he said. ``Parents would have to
source foreign exchange themselves to pay for the marking of their
children's exams. The rich will get recognition, the poor will not.
From the point of view of equality, which is what our schools are
supposed to offer, this is a huge problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
