<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-$ADV29-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV29 
 (FOR RELEASE WED., MARCH 29, 2000, AND THEREAFTER) 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: GRILLED FISH; ASPARAGUS AND PEARL PASTA 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years my friend Germaine Swanson, who used to own a
Vietnamese restaurant in Washington, has made contributions to this
column. Everyone loves her food. She has a light touch and sure
hand with seasonings, especially those from her native Vietnam. She
has lived in the United States for a long time and knows what
appeals to our palates.
</P>
<P>
   Today's recipe for grilled fish with greens is her take on
fusion cooking. In the original the fish is grilled outside, lots
of oil is poured over it after cooking and then it is topped with
lots of greens.
</P>
<P>
   The original recipe calls for much more oil than would ever fit
into the theme of this column, but after a few experiments I
discovered that a very reasonable facsimile could be concocted
without all the oil.
</P>
<P>
   For the recipe not only must you have the freshest fish but also
sprightly greens full of flavor because most of the flavor of the
dish comes from the greens.
</P>
<P>
   And since asparagus season is coming shortly _ California
asparagus is already on the market in abundance _ in keeping with
the spring green theme, asparagus has been combined with pasta for
the vegetable and starch dish.
</P>
<P>
   I have used a form of pasta _ pearl pasta _ that may not be
readily available. It looks a little like large whole tapioca.
Pearl pasta has a very appealing texture, but if you cannot find it
use some other small pasta like orzo.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAINE'S GRILLED FISH WITH DILL
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fillet of grouper
</P>
<P>
   Few sprigs fresh dill to yield 1/3 cup chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 large green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsalted, roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces mesclun
</P>
<P>
   Few sprigs mint to yield 2 tablespoons
</P>
<P>
   Few sprigs coriander to yield 2 tablespoons
</P>
<P>
   1. Turn on broiler, if using.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mix the turmeric with 2 teaspoons of oil, salt and pepper in
a bowl large enough to hold the fish. Wash and dry the fish and cut
into 1 inch cubes. Using your hands mix the fish with the turmeric
mixture until it is well coated. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash and chop the dill; wash, trim and chop the green onions;
place the peanuts in a plastic bag and coarsely crush with a
rolling pin or other heavy object.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare stove top grill, if using. Grill the fish, turning to
brown all sides. It should take 4 or 5 minutes. Or broil the fish.
</P>
<P>
   5. Meanwhile wash and dry mesclun, mint and coriander. Chop mint
and coriander.
</P>
<P>
   6. When fish is cooked, arrange mesclun on serving plate. Top
with fish; sprinkle with dill, onions, peanuts, mint and coriander.
Drizzle over remaining 1 teaspoon of oil and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ASPARAGUS AND PEARL PASTA
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup pearl pasta or other small pasta like orzo
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring water to boil for pasta.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash asparagus and trim off tough part of stem by breaking
asparagus where woody part meets tender part. Cut the asparagus
into 1-inch lengths and steam for 4 or 5 minutes until tender but
still firm.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook pasta according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   4. When cooked, drain and place asparagus in serving bowl with
orange juice and balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   5. When pasta is cooked, drain and stir into asparagus mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare asparagus through step 1.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare fish through step 3.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with asparagus through step 3.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with fish through step 5.
</P>
<P>
   Continue with asparagus through step 4.
</P>
<P>
   Finish fish.
</P>
<P>
   Finish asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Turmeric
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fillet of grouper
</P>
<P>
   Bunch dill
</P>
<P>
   Bunch green onions
</P>
<P>
   Small package unsalted roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces mesclun
</P>
<P>
   Bunch fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Bunch fresh coriander
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound asparagus
</P>
<P>
   Small box pearl pasta or other small pasta like orzo
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition information per serving: 690 calories, 19 grams fat,
60 milligrams cholesterol, 175 milligrams sodium, 50 grams protein,
80 grams carbohydrate.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Marian Burros by electronic mail. Her
address is: marbur(at)nytimes.com. The (at) represents the symbol
on your keyboard. Please include your name and daytime telephone
number. Questions of general interest will be answered in this
column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
