<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO BACK A BROWSER KEYWORD SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Microsoft Corp. is throwing its considerable
weight behind a keyword system that aims to enable Internet users
to navigate the Web without typing in the cumbersome addresses
known as URLs.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, developed by RealNames Corp. of Redwood City,
Calif., allows Web users to type in the name of a company or
product and go to the site of the entity that has paid RealNames to
lock up that keyword.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, company officials said Monday, Microsoft
will take a 20 percent equity stake in RealNames, which has filed
for an initial public offering of its stock. Microsoft's chief
executive, Steve Ballmer, is expected to make the announcement at
PC Forum, the annual technology conference here sponsored by
Edventure Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   RealNames charges large corporations $100,000 to $300,000 a year
to license a keyword, and 10 cents to $1 per visit generated. Small
businesses can buy a keyword for $100 a year.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, the system also refers users in many cases to
the most likely result, even if the keyword has not been purchased
_ for example, Apple Computer if the word ``apple'' alone is typed.
Typing in generic terms like ``pizza''generates a list of search
results.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Microsoft has incorporated the technology into
its Internet Explorer browser. It will now do so with its MSN
online service as well, enabling it to compete more effectively
with America Online, which has long used its own keyword system
within its proprietary network.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Navigator, the other popular Web browser, which is
owned by America Online, does not use the RealNames keyword system,
but the deal with Microsoft does not prevent AOL from adopting the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The RealNames system includes an elaborate tracking scheme that
the company says allows it to measure the effectiveness of offline
advertisements that mention the keyword, and to share that
information with its customers. RealNames hopes keywords will
replace domain name addresses and 800 numbers in print and
television advertising. AltaVista, Inktomi and the Go Network are
among the Internet companies using the system.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson, the host of the conference here, said that using
keywords would be a welcome new way to surf the Web. ``It's a very
nice concept,'' she said. ``There are lots of different ways to get
to URLs, and this is one of them. The world needs more creative
navigation interfaces. It needs point and click, it needs
pictorgrams.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that just as with the system of allocating domain
names, which is being opened up to competition, there is a
potential danger of a keyword monopoly. ( Dyson is the chairman of
the group that is overseeing the new domain name system, but she
did not speak in that capacity because the organization works by
consensus and only sets policies for the domain system.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they've done a deal with Microsoft, that obviously
puts them in a much stronger position,'' she said. ``Clearly, as
long as people have alternatives there are no issues, but when
people don't have alternatives, there are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-13-00 2239EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
