<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-BEYOND-COX     03-15 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-BEYOND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Documentary highlights wrestlers' struggles
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's already been a big year for multimedia in professional
wrestling. The industry's shows dominate the cable television
ratings, their books have topped the New York Times bestsellers
list, wrestling video games are among the hottest-selling items and
wrestling Web sites are getting millions and millions of hits each
month.
</P>
<P>
   Now, wrestling goes Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, the professional wrestling documentary, ``Beyond the
Mat,'' opened in limited release in New York, Los Angeles,
Charlotte, N.C., and Memphis, Tenn. On March 17, the movie opens
nationally with the backing of Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Although it failed to garner an Academy Award nomination in the
documentary category, word of mouth has been strong since director
Barry Blaustein gave the movie a screening in Los Angeles just
before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein's project was to follow the behind the scenes workings
of wrestlers in different organizations. As the movie's Web site
(beyondthemat.net) proclaims, ``(Beyond the Mat is) an honest,
intimate, revealing, highly entertaining, and critically acclaimed
documentary about wrestling. It takes viewers beyond the ring and
into the lives of the men and women who inhabit this colorful,
competitive, and surprisingly complex world.''
</P>
<P>
   While professional wrestling is complex, doing a documentary on
sports entertainment is just as complex. Blaustein, a former head
writer and supervising producer of Saturday Night Live, started his
project in 1995. It took him two years of hanging around and
informally meeting groups of wrestlers before he started to get
things down on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been a wrestling fan for a long time and I had met a lot
of these guys and it always struck me how they talked about their
families and I'd say, 'They're not very different than me,' but
they are,'' Blaustein said. ``I thought it would be interesting to
see the inner working of wrestlers' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein was amazed by the contrast of the control the
wrestlers appeared to have in the ring and the lack of control they
have in their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, getting the wrestlers to speak in front of the camera
as themselves and not their personas _ or to get ahold of them at
all was Blaustein's biggest obsticale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joked with Terry (Funk) and Mick (Foley) that the only
reason they are in the movie is because they called me back,''
Blaustein said. ``You get the cold shoulder by guys, guys don't
show up, it really makes you want to give up. But I would not give
up.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Blaustein created a movie that he hopes wrestling
fans and nonwrestling fans will enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with the wrestling beginnings of Darren Drozdov
of the WWF. Droz, who since the filming has suffered an in-ring
neck injury that has left him paralyzed, signs a deal with WWF
Chairman Vince McMahon to begin his professional wrestling career.
He earns such a deal on the strength of his professional football
career that is highlighted by his ability to vomit at will. As a
result, he becomes ``Puke'' in the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   And Drozdov calls home to tell of his good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, guess what? Your baby boy is now going to be called
Puke,'' he says excitedly into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to the minor leagues to visit with All-Pro
Wrestling, the film spotlights a wrestling legend _ Terry Funk. At
the time, Funk was 53 and looking for a role in a large U.S.
wrestling organization. After splitting time between his ranch, an
acting career that never amounted to much and some wrestling gigs
overseas, Funk signed on with the fledging Extreme Championship
Wrestling. Known for his brawling style, Funk went to the extreme
when he joined ECW, involving himself in matches that spilled his
blood all over the arena. Despite the pleas from doctors to give
his body a rest, Funk continued battling wrestlers half his age.
</P>
<P>
   We watch as the wrestlers of ECW join head honcho Paul Heyman
around television screens in the locker room area to watch the
legend work, while Funk's family watches in pain as he absorbs more
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Funk's push toward retirement is sprinkled throughout the movie.
Finally he announces his retirement at an ECW party and wrestles
his final match in his hometown of Amarillo, Texas. The wrestling
show has all of the top stars, including Bret Hart, wrestling in
the main event against Funk.
</P>
<P>
   While Funk was saying this was his retirement, Blaustein knew
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first announced it at the retirement party, he said he
might do a couple shows over in Japan,'' Blaustein said. ``Then,
the night of the retirement matches I asked him, 'Terry is this
really it?' And he said 'this was his final match ... in Amarillo.'
I don't think wrestling fans were shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just loves it too much. He's in terrible shape _ I mean for
the beating he has taken he's in great shape _ but he loves the
roar of the crowd and the fans' reactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk now works for WCW and is one of their main performers at
age 55.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also re-introduces wrestling fans to Jake ``The
Snake'' Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top heels for the WWF in the 1980s, Roberts fell on
hard times in the 1990s. When Blaustein catches up with Roberts, he
is traveling across the Midwest picking up shows wherever he can _
high school gymnasiums, converted livestock barns, etc.
</P>
<P>
   During one eight-hour trip, Roberts weaves a tale of his
horrific childhood and a wasted adult life complete with drug
addiction, crazed sexual escapades and children he hardly knows.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts attempts to reunite with his college-age daughter who he
hasn't seen in four years. But the meeting is too much for Roberts
to handle and he slinks away to buy crack.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Roberts has fallen, Mick Foley has risen from guy who
takes dangerous bumps in the ring to a wrestling superstar.
</P>
<P>
   His violent beginnings, the toll on his body and his family
along with the relationship between his family at home and his
family on the road are profiled. The movie picks up Foley as his
character is changed in the WWF and the real Mick Foley comes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Vince that if they just let Mick be Mick he would be a
star,'' said Blaustein of a conversation with WWF's top man Vince
McMahon. ``Mick Foley is a lot more interesting than the characters
he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein was right, and we watch as Foley is given the WWF
championship only to lose it in a brutal pay-per-view match. During
htat match his head is split open after taking 20-plus chair shots.
During the brutality, the Foley family (his wife and two small
children) watch in horror, until they can stand no more and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mick called me a couple weeks after and wanted to know how the
filming came out,'' Blaustein said. ``I told him, 'Mick it looked
truly horrendous.' The reason why I wanted to show him the footage
is because as a father I thought he needed to see the footage. It
was hard for me to show it to him. I didn't want people to think
that he's a bad father, because he's not. He just made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching his children screaming at the sight of their
father being beaten, Foley's eyes were opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like such a good father anymore,'' he says in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the scenes leading up to his viewing of the tape, Foley tried
to convince his children that it wasn't as bad as it looked. But as
they got older, the kids did not believe that the bloody mess their
father would become after a match was not without its pain.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the damage he had done to his body and because he
wants to be closer to his family, Foley wrestled his last match in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he might come back in a year or two and do a match,''
Blaustein said. ``But I called him and asked how he enjoys
retirement and he said, 'You know, I really do enjoy it', so I
think he'll stay retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to write another book and a children's
series and do some acting.'' With the success of books from Foley
and The Rock, Americans can't seem to get enough of the
behind-the-scenes workings of professional wrestling. Not everyone
likes the access. Vince McMahon did not like the movie and is not
getting a cut of the pie, so he has refused to run the movie
trailers during WWF shows and has censored WWF wrestlers from
talking about the movie since Foley's appearance on ``Good Morning
America'' with Blaustein in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has hurt the movie,'' said Blaustein of McMahon's
actions. ``Not being on (USA's Monday night) `Raw' and (UPN's
Thursday night) `Smackdown' has kept us from getting to the casual
wrestling fan.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, World Championship Wrestling _ which wouldn't
sign releases for wrestlers to be in the movie, although Diamond
Dallas Page talked to Blaustein at length _ has run the trailer and
is helping Terry Funk promote the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never did this movie for the money,'' Blaustein said.
``This is something along the line of a big home movie. I never
thought it would be up for some award or even have a threatrical
release. I just wanted to make it for people who could care less
about wrestling but are interested in people's stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
