<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEURIAL SIBLINGS; `PUSH TECHNOLOGY' RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTREPRENEURIAL SIBLINGS TAKE TO THE NET AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   These days, when an entrepreneur says he has a revolutionary
business plan that will forever change commerce using the Internet,
it's wise to raise an eyebrow, if not hit the mute button.
</P>
<P>
   But when the entrepreneurs in question are the brothers Jay and
Paul Shen, it may be worth listening in.
</P>
<P>
   The latest venture from the siblings Shen, each of whom already
has a hundred-million-dollar dot-com success to his credit, is
called myCustoms.com.
</P>
<P>
   The business, which is in a market test and set for a summer
rollout, is designed to enable e-commerce companies to expand their
overseas business by automating the import-export function.
</P>
<P>
   The Shens say they are seeking to solve what they describe as a
major kink in the international e-commerce pipeline. Most
e-commerce companies, they say, do not even entertain the idea of
overseas customers because they do not want to take the time and
energy to navigate myriad customs laws or calculate the duties and
value-added taxes of countless nations.
</P>
<P>
   Enter myCustoms.com, which the brothers say will calculate taxes
and inform buyers and sellers on import-export laws. ``Now the
entire process is very manual, very labor intensive, not applicable
to online,'' said Jay Shen, 27, the company's co-founder and
president. MyCustoms.com will enable people to ``trade globally as
they do locally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers say the site could also enable themselves to get
even richer _ even if the Shens could afford to retire already. In
1998, Jay founded Billpoint, a service that allows person-to-person
credit card transactions online, and sold it last year to eBay for
$125 million.
</P>
<P>
   His older brother Paul, 37, who is myCustoms.com's chief
executive, co-founded the iMedia Corp. in 1994. He sold iMedia,
which makes digital video software, to Terayon Communication
Systems last year for $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The third co-founder of the new venture is Manoj Karamchandani,
formerly vice president for international operations at eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Given their previous successes, why don't the brothers do what
so many other wealthy technology executives are doing these days _
sit back and invest their money in other people's entrepreneurial
efforts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just looking for a financial gain,'' Jay Shen said.
``This product will really help society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   `PUSH TECHNOLOGY' RETURNS IN A FORM THAT IS MORE POLITE
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago now that Pointcast's ``push''
technology was touted as the next big thing. But at the end of this
month the Pointcast news and information service will officially
become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Pointcast has been living on borrowed time since last May, when
Launchpad Technologies acquired the company for $7 million and
formed a new company, Entrypoint. Now, Entrypoint has informed the
some 400,000 remaining Pointcast users that the service is being
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Pointcast, introduced in February 1996, automatically delivers
news and other information from the Internet to users' screens. But
while push technology quickly gained fame and garnered numerous
industry awards, it consumed more than five megabytes of the user's
hard drive and was notorious for clogging corporate networks. And
many people complained that Pointcast was simply too obtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great idea in there,'' said Francis Costello,
president and chief operating officer of Entrypoint and former head
of Launchpad, which itself was a spinoff of the technology
incubator Idealab. ``They had not done some things that were fairly
obvious, like make it smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Entrypoint is hoping that it can avoid losing Pointcast's
customers altogether by converting them to its own information
delivery service. Called Entrypoint 2.0 (www.entrypoint.com), the
service displays information in an on-screen toolbar that has
various buttons linking users instantly to shopping, financial and
news sites of their own choice. Users can make purchases using
credit card information stored in an ``eWallet,'' _ technology that
Launchpad developed to simplify online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pointcast, which transmitted those megabytes worth of
data to an individual's hard drives whether the person wanted it or
not, Entrypoint sends only information the user has requested _
like updates on stock activity and the latest shopping deals.
</P>
<P>
   It is push technology, in other words, that is intended to be a
lot less pushy.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-12-00 1910EST &QL;
</P>
