<SLUG> BC-CPT-PATENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEAS INTO PRODUCTS, WITH THE WEB; WORKS IN PROGRESS BY YOUNG 
INVENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's say you own a widget company whose research and
development team has invented a machine grease that was a failure
on the factory floor but unexpectedly turns out to be a superior
formula for furniture polish.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, you might have made some informal phone calls
to your network of business associates, discreetly trying to
license the idea to a more appropriate company. Now, however, you
have the option of posting the invention on one of a growing number
of online intellectual property trading sites that promise to make
such technological matchmaking swifter, easier and more precise.
</P>
<P>
   The newest of these sites, run by a privately held company in
Cambridge, Mass., contends that it offers a fundamentally different
approach to the swapping and selling of intellectual property
online. The company, yet2.com (www.yet2.com _ and, yes, that is
pronounced ``yet to come''), says it offers a place to trade not
just patents but also trade secrets, unpatented inventions and
simple technological know-how.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old model was that nobody shared anything with anybody,''
said Ben du Pont, the president of yet2.com and an
eighth-generation descendant of E.I. du Pont, the founder of the
DuPont Co. ``The new model is that anybody can register for free
with yet2.com to hear about new technologies and to hear about them
right away. It's a fundamental shift.'' Du Pont said he got the
idea for the site when he was an employee at DuPont and grew
frustrated in trying to license a promising new polymer.
</P>
<P>
   Chris De Bleser, the chief executive of yet2.com, said the
site's approach was influenced by the practices of patent lawyers,
who typically pride themselves on being able to disclose enough
information about a new technology to get a patent, but not so much
that a competitor can build a workable prototype by simply reading
the patent.
</P>
<P>
   A certain patent might disclose the formula for a new polymer,
for example. But what the patent will not say, De Bleser said, ``is
that in order to get the goo to come out of the vat, you need to
kick it a couple of times and twist the nozzle to the left.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to patents, the site will trade in technology
packages that might include engineering expertise or advice on
regulatory compliance. Du Pont says companies and inventors can
also use yet2.com to sell inventions long before they receive
patents. ``Because we're not only about patents, it's possible to
post very recently discovered technologies,'' he said. ``DuPont
will be posting over 100 recently discovered technologies, all of
which are patent-pending.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would companies post their unprotected technology on a Web
site where any corporate spy could take a peek? What you see on the
site are simply marketing documents that contain no real
proprietary information and that do not identify the company that
owns the technology.
</P>
<P>
   If you want more information, you have to pony up $1,000 for an
initial one-on-one meeting. If a deal is struck, yet2.com gets a 10
percent cut, capped at the first $50,000 of the deal. ``We want
these people to post their billion-dollar technologies,'' du Pont
said.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont co. has a minority stake in the site, which thus far has
more than $20 million in financing that also comes from Venrock
Associates, 3i Group, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. and Honeywell
International. On Monday, the company is announcing a roster of 25
new recruits to the site, among them Arthur D. Little and British
Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical companies are heavily represented on the site, but
Boeing, TRW, Porsche, Ford Motor and others also hawk their
research and development on yet2.com. Collectively, yet2.com
contends, the companies on its site account for nearly 10 percent
of global spending on research and development.
</P>
<P>
   But the company expects to draw postings from small companies
and individual inventors as well. ``The most brilliant ideas,'' De
Bleser acknowledged, ``can come from the smallest research
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Works in Progress By Young Inventors
</P>
<P>
   College-age inventors descended upon Washington last week for a
convention sponsored by the Smithsonian's Lemelson Center and the
National Collegiate Inventors and Innovators Alliance. A dozen
teams displayed their works in progress. Among the inventions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bubble-imaging technology from the California Institute of
Technology that gives a lava-lamp quality to digital displays.
</P>
<P>
   _ A crescent-shaped pillow from Hampshire College that provides
needed arm support for women who have just had breast surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ A battery-powered cart from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology that will lower an aging gardener into a kneeling
position, then lift him back up again.
</P>
<P>
   _ A special swing from the University of Colorado at Boulder
that enables a person who is unable to pump her legs to swing
without assistance.
</P>
<P>
   _ A permeometer _ a device that measures how quickly a fluid
flows through a material _ from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute.
It enables the paper-making and fabric industries to measure
permeability 10 times more accurately than is now possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ A combination toilet seat and bathroom scale from the
University of Nevada at Reno. ``It was sort of a practical joke to
start with,'' explained Phil Weilerstein, program manager at the
collegiate inventors alliance. ``But then it became more serious
when the students realized it could be used in hospitals to monitor
the weight of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   NOMINEES SOUGHT FOR INVENTOR OF YEAR
</P>
<P>
   The nomination deadline for the 27th annual Inventor of the Year
Award, sponsored by the Intellectual Property Owners Association,
is April 12. A nominating form can be downloaded from the Web site
www.ipo.org. The award will be presented on June 28 on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-12-00 1847EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
