 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Let your talking do your dialing
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Innovation comes in waves.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of the printed book saved us the hassle of having
to listen to someone tell a story. Then the radio came along and
saved us from having to read. Now we could listen to someone while
in our bathrobes if we wanted. Television meant we didn't have to
picture what the storytellers looked like anymore, and phones meant
we could let our fingers do the walking.
</P>
<P>
   But we still had to dial the seven, or 10, digits.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently. A company called Digital Acoustics has software
that lets you pick up a phone and dial a number as simply as saying
``Mom'' or ``pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   The software, Tell A Phone, works on any phone; special phones
are not needed. A user just picks up the telephone, listens for a
dial tone and speaks the name associated with a number he or she
wants dialed. The software confirms the number before it dials. The
process takes less than three seconds, according to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, www.digitalacoustics.com/tellaph, offers some
basic information about the software:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I use voice-dial from all the phones in my home?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, Tell A Phone works with every phone connected to the
same line as your compatible modem or Voice Dial Manager.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What if I have two phone lines in my home or office?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tell A Phone voice-dials on one line. If your modem is
connected on a line that is normally not used for your telephone
calls, you would need to add a compatible modem devoted for
voice-dialing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do I need to leave my computer on all the time?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, to use the features of Tell A Phone, you need to have
your computer turned on. This should not be a major issue or
expense. Modern computer power management uses less power than a
single, low-wattage light bulb. In standby mode, it is even less.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I use my existing address book with the Tell A Phone
software?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tell A Phone uses its own phone book that imports from
personal information manager databases, including Lotus Organizer,
Microsoft Outlook, Symantec ACT and Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which family members can use Tell A Phone's voice-dialing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tell A Phone uses a speech-recognition engine that does not
require training. Once a name is typed into the phone directory, it
is available for voice-dialing. There is no age or gender
requirement, although our tests have shown that children under 6-7
years do not provide the speech patterns required for reliable
speech recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Tell A Phone language- or accent-dependent?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, Tell A Phone Version 2.3 works with ``American
English.'' Other accents and languages are available, such as
Canadian English, British English, French, Canadian French, Spanish
and 10 other languages.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I dial by speaking partial names, rather than full names,
in my phone list?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tell A Phone offers the option of speaking any part of a
two-word name or phrase. If the option ``Recognize Partial Names''
is enabled, you can say ``John,'' ``Smith'' or ``John Smith'' to
dial the same number entered for ``John Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Dial Logging?
</P>
<P>
   A: A feature available in Tell A Phone. Every time you dial,
Tell A Phone will record the digits you've dialed in your ``call
log.'' If you forget a number, Tell A Phone will have a record of
that number.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is a Caller ID announcement?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you subscribe to Caller ID through your local telephone
company, you can have Tell A Phone announce incoming calls from
your PC.
</P>
<P>
   To use Tell A Phone, you need a computer with a Pentium 90 or
greater processor, 32 megabytes of RAM, 20 megabytes of hard disk
space and a Windows 95 or newer operating system. You also would
need a Windows-compatible sound card and speakers, a serial or USB
port, and Caller ID for your telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
