 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Surfing for personal pages brings fond Web memories
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the World Wide Web was young, it was an
amateurish place, in a good way. It was not nearly as commercial as
it is today. Besides the academic and government pages, there were
personal Web pages that gave a true glimpse of the lives of
ordinary people from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The personal pages are still there _ in fact, like every other
part of the Web, the number of them has grown greatly. However, the
personal aspect of the Web has diminished as it has become more of
a tool for selling and providing information.
</P>
<P>
   Since personal pages are difficult to find compared with
commercial ones, our starting point will be at one of the largest
providers of free home pages on the Web: GeoCities. Go to
geocities.yahoo.com/home/ and you will see that the pages are
organized in neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Simply click on one of the neighborhoods _ say, Hollywood _ and
you'll find that these pages have been grouped by a topic that
suits the name Hollywood. You'll find personal pages and those
created by organizations devoted to fandom.
</P>
<P>
   If you hanker for something even more personal, select the
Heartland neighborhood instead, where you'll find family home pages
and pages devoted to personal topics.
</P>
<P>
   One warning _ and GeoCities is a relatively clean town by Web
standards, so this applies to all the personal pages you'll see:
Home pages are not generally censored. So, if you make this search
a family activity, make sure that you screen any of the pages
before your children see them.
</P>
<P>
   Our next stop is a fascinating collection of links to personal
home pages called Personal Homepages on the Web at
imc.iit.edu/internet.access/personalhomepages.html. Using the links
you find here, you'll be able to literally trace the history of
personal pages on the Web. For instance, click on the link for the
Well and you'll find a place (www.well.com:80/Community/) that, as
described on this page, was ``one of the earliest Internet service
providers ... a true community. Of course, it's in San Francisco,
so it's a different kind of community. ...'' It has all kinds of
pop culture represented, as well as San Francisco's (and other
cities') gay population.
</P>
<P>
   Other links on the compilation page will take you to personal
home pages selected for their novelty and interest by the Mining
Company, a professional Web search organization. You'll find those
Web pages at www.cs.ucla.edu/csd /people/undergrads.html.
</P>
<P>
   Still, from the compilation page, you'll be able to visit the
Web pages maintained by college students at schools such as UCLA
(www.cs.ucla.edu/csd/people/undergrads.html), Florida State
(www.cs.fsu.edu/people/undergrads.html), Carnegie-Mellon
(www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/usr) and Stanford
(www.stanford.edu/leland/dir.html).
</P>
<P>
   Soon you won't need any links or help, if you enjoy this type of
old-fashioned Web surfing (a term that is pretty much out of
fashion these days).
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting things about visiting the lives of
strangers is that _ on at least half the pages _ you'll find links
to other personal Web pages maintained by friends and relatives.
And, with any luck, you'll meet people from around the world and
experience some of the feeling of what things were like in the
earliest days, when the surf was up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-13-00 1038EST &QL;
</P>
