u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-ARTS-ART     03-15 1934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-ARTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALMOST HERE: A STREAM OF ARTS VIA YOUR COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or
888-603-1036.) 
 By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology is rapidly changing the way Americans consume
entertainment. Some day in the not-so-distant future, all forms of
recorded entertainment will be available, on demand or via
subscription services, over the Internet. Programming will become
more interactive, especially when it comes to e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of these changes are enormous, and they're
already shaking up the entertainment industry. The music business,
in particular, is facing a complete realignment; controversial
outsiders such as MP3.com and Napster.com have already launched
services that make digital distribution of music (and, by
extension, music piracy) easy for anyone with a basic working
knowledge of the Internet. So far, the recording industry has
mounted a two-pronged defense: It is suing Internet start-ups over
licensing fees and piracy issues, and it is also struggling to
develop a standard to secure digital music. To date, both efforts
have been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   But lawsuits and resistance aren't going to stop the technology
revolution, which has the potential to open up opportunities for
new artists and to provide consumers more entertainment options at
a lower cost. Admittedly, the technology is still in its infancy:
Quality is unreliable, and content is limited. But that isn't
holding back the early adapters. On college campuses and in church
halls, ordinary folks are already changing their viewing,
listening, and reading habits. Here's a look at people who are
doing what we'll all be doing within a few years. &QL; 
Internet radio
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Jasmine Francis had to scour the radio dial to
find programs that played reggae; she was limited to one or two
weekly programs on local stations. But now she listens to
radiojamaica.com on the Internet, and she can can have all reggae,
all day, at both work and play. ``It's a cultural thing,'' Francis,
33, explains.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, a computer technician in the Cambridge public schools,
moved here from Jamaica with her mother and brothers in 1974.
Internet radio keeps her connected with her native culture. Her
friends in Jamaica listen to some of the same radio programs;
sometimes, she sends in song requests via e-mail and asks the DJ to
send out a hello to her cousin at home.
</P>
<P>
   Radio, in fact, has made the transition to the Internet faster
than any other medium has. There are thousands of online radio
stations offering every possible genre, from Christian to classical
to cutting-edge music. Most traditional stations now simulcast
their programming online, while such startup operations as
www.gogaga.com and www.live365.com offer Internet-only programs.
Many Net-only stations post their playlists online and provide
links for listeners to purchase CDs from such e-commerce outfits as
amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream folks tune in for any number of reasons. Pamela
Fallon listens regularly to a radio station in Moscow; a publicist
for rock promoter Don Law, Fallon once did publicity for Mikhail
Gorbachev and is studying Russian. ``It helps me with my language
skills,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Another user, Northeastern University graduate student Mary
Churchill, tunes in to a station in New Orleans, where she spent
her honeymoon. ``It brings back memories,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Memories waft out of the computer at the Francis household,
where the machine is plugged into the Internet via a cable modem.
Francis has a passion for the Irie beat, even though her daughters,
Myasha, 10, and Nicqueta, 12, have a taste for American teen pop
and hip-hop. ``The Internet lets me introduce them to Jamaican
culture,'' Francis says. That's not to say the technology is
perfectly seamless; when Internet use is extremely high, audio
programs can stutter and spurt. But fine-tuning the machinery is a
family affair for the Francis clan. ``My 10-year-old daughter gets
around the problems by changing all the settings,'' Francis notes.
``She knows all the little tricks.'' &QL; 
Music
</P>
<P>
   Forget MTV. Today's youth are saying, ``I want my MP3.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Jacob Bouvrie, a 21-year-old electrical engineering student
at MIT. A music aficionado and a musician himself, he owns several
hundred CDs. Like most students, he moves frequently, and he is
tired of lugging around all that plastic. The solution? He
converted his CD collection to a digital file format called MP3, a
relatively simple process. He now stores his music on his computer.
``Every time I change dorm rooms, I just carry my hard drive with
me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 format, which allows high-quality music to be stored on
a computer and distributed over the Internet, is wildly popular on
college campuses, and it's spreading to the workplace as well. But
it is anathema to the music industry, since it makes piracy as
simple as clicking a mouse. The Recording Industry Association of
America is currently suing MP3.com and Napster.com, which
distribute digital music in controversial ways. And Napster uses a
program that eats up bandwidth, and as such, it has been banned on
many college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other students, Bouvrie is aware of the
establishment's wrath, but he still regularly downloads MP3 files.
He posts music recorded by his own band, called B Field, on the
MP3.com site; he doesn't expect to land a big contract, but he
appreciates the free exposure. And Napster allows him _ and other
remote users _ to share music files online. ``Legally speaking,
it's piracy,'' he says, ``but I don't have any qualms about it. My
musical tastes are obscure, and more often than not, MP3s have
prompted me to go out and buy the entire album.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, digital distribution is still in its infancy.
Portable MP3 players only store an hour's worth of songs; legal
content is still limited and the technology is feasible only for
users with high-speed Internet access such as broadband or DSL
(digital subscriber lines). But attitudes about the very concept of
music itself are changing. Todd Hiers, an MIT senior, has a new
definition for the MP3 generation. ``I tend to think of music as
information,'' he says. ``As data. Not as a physical object at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic books
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Billy Strayhorn isn't one of those ministers who
pontificates from the pulpit, looking down on his congregation. No,
the leader of the First United Methodist Church in Joshua, Texas,
gets down with the parishioners, moving among the people, pumping
flesh and patting backs as he quotes scripture from a handheld
text. But he's not lugging around the Bible; instead, he carries a
Rocket eBook, a $200 electronic reader that can store thousands of
pages of printed material. Strayhorn stores his sermons and prayer
list on the device, which he uses for daily devotionals, Sunday
services, even weddings and funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one wedding rehearsal, a bunch of folks were interested in
computers, and I got more questions about the Rocket than about the
ceremony,'' Strayhorn, 48, recalls.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described technogeek, Strayhorn bought his electronic
reader in April. The consumer device, which is about the size of a
paperback, hit the market in late 1998; users can download texts
free from a number of Web sites (including www.rocket-library.com
or http://promo.net/pg) or purchase trade books and textbooks from
such commercial vendors as Barnes &AMP; Noble. The electronic library
is limited to thousands of titles, ranging from esoteric technical
books to classic and contemporary fiction. But so far, Strayhorn
has been able to satisfy his eclectic taste, which runs from the
Bible to science fiction, murder mysteries, and ``good, ol' spy
thrillers'' by authors such as Stephen King. But he hasn't been
able to find an electronic copy of his favorite novel, ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' nor any of the Harry Potter books. He did acquire an
electronic version of a popular book called ``Experiencing God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife calls me Rocket Boy,'' confesses Strayhorn, a jolly
sort with a healthy laugh and a Texas twang.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket isn't the only way to read books electronically; some
avid readers are devouring novels on the tiny screen of the Palm
Pilot electronic organizer. Janice Karin of Malden, for instance,
reads about a dozen books a week on her portable organizer. The
27-year-old technical writer is legally blind, and the electronic
device allows her to adjust the size of the type to make reading
possible. ``It's certainly saved me from being bored out of my
skull on many occasions,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As for Strayhorn, he's not one to bore easily, but he carries
his reader with him all the time, just in case. And his newfangled
device has come in handy in one old-fashioned way: ``Sometimes some
of the men in the church think the preacher is way up there,
unapproachable,'' he says. ``But when they find out I'm into
computers, the quiet guys suddenly want to have a conversation.
It's an icebreaker, a point of contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   It all started with a movie series about a young man in a galaxy
far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the trailer for the prequel ``Star Wars: Episode I _
The Phantom Menace'' spread like a virus over the Internet, with
copies available for download on the official studio Web site as
well as on fan and bootleg sites. Steve Head, a 34-year-old
uberfan, watched the trailer online and in theaters. These days, he
and his friends watch trailers on the Internet all the time.
``We're all pretty fanatic about it,'' says Head, a computer
programmer from Weymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Head just launched a movie news site called filmforce.net, which
posts links to movie trailers online. The hottest trailer
circulating right now is the preview for ``The X-Men,'' a
futuristic comic-book thriller with the slogan ``Join the
Evolution.'' ``More people have seen the images from this trailer
via an online connection than have actually seen it in a theater,''
says Head. ``I know I have.''
</P>
<P>
   The trailer aired two weeks ago on ``Entertainment Tonight'' and
was posted on the Internet almost immediately. ``People get it on
tape and digitize it,'' explains Head. In fact, the sport of
watching trailers has become an entertainment form unto itself. So
why are people so nutty about short videos that are essentially
advertisements? ``There is a vicarious thrill of one-upmanship and
curiosity,'' says Scott Deering, a New Jersey computer consultant
who runs www.movie-trailers.com.
</P>
<P>
   Streaming video is still extremely limited because of bandwidth
and quality issues; even with a high-speed connection, the viewing
experience can be frustrating. But today's trailer addicts are
tomorrow's online entertainment audience. Some companies, like
www.den.net and www.atomfilms.com, are already producing shows made
for niche markets on the Internet, targeting Christian teens, dog
lovers, and break dancers alike. Many of these shows have a
built-in e-commerce mechanism; with the click of a mouse, viewers
can buy the items they see or the music they hear in any particular
program.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, early adapters such as Head are content with
the novelty of watching trailers. ``The downloading takes forever,
and the image is very small, but I have the opportunity to see it
online, any time I want,'' says Head. ``And that, I think, is
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-13-00 1335EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
