 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Webby Award Producers Catch Ecstatic Nominees by Surprise  
 By Carolyn Said   
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The contestants are off and running for this
year's Webby Awards, the digiteri's version of the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Technology publisher IDG, which produces the awards, on Monday
announced 135 Web site nominees in 27 categories ranging from
activism to weird. Nominees range from sites with
megabuck-corporate backing, like MarthaStewart.com, Amazon.com and
ESPN, to the cheeky irreverence of gwbush.com, a parody site that
has incensed the likely Republican presidential nominee.
Thirty-five of the nominees are from the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The awards _ a metallic spiral imprinted with zeros and ones _
will be handed out May 11 in a ceremony at the Nob Hill Masonic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my gosh, we're ecstatic,'' said Lianne Morgan, chief
executive of the Marketing Store, a 35-person Web design company in
Sacramento. The firm broke out the champagne to celebrate snagging
a nomination in the fashion category for ``Solemates: The Century
in Shoes'' (www.centuryinshoes.com), a multimedia ``Web-umentary''
about how footwear reflects ``the changing passions, perspectives
and ideals of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll help us help more folks out, and that ain't bad,'' said
Craig Newmark, founder of Craigslist.org, a San Francisco
classified-ads site nominated for Community. ``Maybe it will help
me launch other projects, like AskCraigsMom.com.''
</P>
<P>
   A 350-member panel of judges makes the nominations and picks the
winners. Celebrity judges include David Bowie judging in music,
actor Patrick Stewart in travel, cyber-guru Esther Dyson in
activism, Simpsons creator Matt Groening in humor, performance
artist Laurie Anderson in arts and commentator Arianna Huffington
in politics and law.
</P>
<P>
   Web surfers can also pick their favorites for the complementary
People's Voice Awards, casting ballots at www.webbyawards.com.
</P>
<P>
   Webby Award producers Tiffany Schlain and Maya Draisin were in
New York yesterday, along with a film crew, popping in unannounced
on nominees to tell them the glad tidings. ``I felt like Ed
McMahon,'' Schlain said. ``Usually we just call people and they're
crying, clapping, yelling _ we wanted to see it in person.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, a Webby staffer dressed as a bike messenger
delivered a cell phone to nominees and told them to press the call
button to hear the news.
</P>
<P>
   Schlain said soliciting entries from the whole Web community
helped ensure variety and diversity of the nominations. ``I worry
it's going to be like the Emmy's,'' with the same people and shows
up for awards year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Webby producers try hard to hammer home the
comparison to the Oscars, even hiring PricewaterhouseCoopers to
audit the voting, they differ in one important respect: Webby
winners can't ramble on ad infinitum; instead, they have exactly
five words to blurt their thanks.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Webby Awards' fourth year of existence. The ceremony
has grown from a nightclub event to a lavish fest expected to
attract 3,000 attendees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
(For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &LR;
</P>
