<HEADLINE>
INTEL, AMD GET NOSE TO NOSE AND LET THE CHIPS FLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX PHAM   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNNYVALE, Calif. _ There's nothing Silicon Valley loves more
than a good old-fashioned chip war.
</P>
<P>
   And riveting the Valley today is a dogfight between the
industry's two biggest players _ Intel Corp., the $30 billion
chipmaker, and its much smaller rival Advanced Micro Devices Inc.,
or AMD.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is nothing new to the Valley, where companies are
admonished to either eat someone's lunch or be someone's lunch.
What makes this contest interesting is the sheer audacity of AMD in
taking on Intel, one of the fiercest competitors in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, AMD, which hasn't had a profitable year since 1995,
seems to be scoring big. Last week, AMD made headlines by beating
Intel in introducing an ultrafast one-gigahertz chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a yappy little dog making a run at a pit bull,''
said Keith Diefendorff, editor in chief of the Microprocessor
Report, an industry newsletter. ``It's amazing that they've even
come close and have even beaten Intel. It's quite astonishing,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story in a nutshell: While both companies were
founded in the late 1960s at the dawn of Silicon Valley, Intel has
since buried its rivals with better talent, better designs, and
legendary drive, becoming the undisputed king-of-the-hill and
owning more than 80 percent of the $24 billion PC chip market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AMD has struggled to remain alive by focusing on less
expensive chips. In the mid-1990s, AMD's scrappy chief executive
and founder, Jerry Sanders, decided to bet his company on a new
chip design that he hoped would let AMD compete head to head with
Intel. The gamble was huge, involving expenditures in the billions
of dollars to develop the chips and build state-of-the-art
factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bet their entire company on this,'' said Diefendorff.
</P>
<P>
   What resulted was the Athlon line of chips, which began shipping
in June. For the first time, AMD had a viable answer to Intel's
high-end microprocessors, which are the brains in computers. ``We
had never before been in the high-performance space before the
Athlon,'' said Stephen A. Lapinski, AMD's director of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   AMD began to see its market share creep up, particularly at the
high end of the market. In January 1999, Intel commanded 97 percent
of the sales in the United States for chips used in personal
computers that sold for $1,500 to $2,000, while AMD had 3 percent,
according to Stephen Baker, director of hardware analysis at PC
Data in Reston, Va. By January 2000, Intel's share was down to 53.5
percent, while AMD claimed 46.5 percent, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, AMD was able to pull off its greatest coup by
introducing the fastest chip on the market _ the one-gigahertz
Athlon processor _ two days before Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something nobody has been able to challenge Intel on,''
said Baker. ``It's a great marketing coup.''
</P>
<P>
   But a marketing victory may be the only meaningful prize AMD
will get for its troubles, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMD won the race but only by the narrowest of margins,''
Diefendorff said. ``It's so narrow that in the big scheme of
things, it's not going to be very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Diefendorff points to weaknesses in the Athlon chip that slow
down its overall performance. The biggest problem, perhaps, is that
the chip's cache, or internal memory, sits slightly apart from the
processor, forcing information to travel to the processor and
slowing down the chip by slivers of a second. Intel's cache sits on
the processor itself, saving time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we put our processor on a racetrack, it will have higher
performance in total,'' said Ralph Bond, an Intel spokesman, of the
Intel Pentium gigahertz compared to the Athlon gigahertz. ``We
wound up with the fastest processor in the world, but we didn't
have the fastest news release in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, AMD has reason to crow. Just as Bill Bradley forced Vice
President Al Gore to fine-tune his campaign, AMD has made Intel
more fleetfooted. The result: Consumers have benefited because
products such as the gigahertz chip have come out months ahead of
schedule and prices have come down faster than if Intel were
unopposed, analysts say. Aside from that, the rivalry has made for
good theater in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Said Diefendorff: ``You can't deny AMD's got guts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-14-00 1537EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TECHNO-QUIXI-BOS &LR;      03-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNO-QUIXI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HUMAN RESOURCE FOR SURFING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PETER J. HOWE   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the next contestants in the dot-com derby will feature an
``intelligent agent'' for searching the Internet, combined with
state-of-the-art speech-recognition technology especially useful in
wireless Net access.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically: An actual human being who talks to you on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Five-month-old Quixi.com, a New York-based start-up going live
across the country in about 10 weeks, is cofounded by Newton, Mass.
native Robert Pines. It aims to cut through Internet hype and
technology overload by offering, for $20 a month, all the calls you
want to speed-dial to a personal assistant who will do your Net
surfing for you and also complete calls and e-mails for you.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hoopla over using your wireless phone to get onto
the Net, Quixi promises what many may find to be a satisfying
technological leap backward: Use the phone to call someone to go on
the Net and find or buy what you are looking for, rather than drive
off the road or walk into a mailbox while you try to scroll down a
tiny screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly lets you do e-commerce wherever you are,'' said
Pines, a 1986 Harvard graduate whose mother is former state Senator
Lois G. Pines.
</P>
<P>
   Pines likes to call Quixi the country's first ``personal
bandwidth'' company. ``We're definitely going against the trend on
the technology side, but we think the human being is the best
interface,'' said Pines. ``Other technologies don't necessarily
save you time. We get things done for you by providing a real
person to do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a lot to do _ offload some of it on us'' is a line
Pines and cofounder Evan Marwell, also a Harvard grad, use to
explain the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, for $19.95 a month, Quixi subscribers will get
unlimited access to three services: Find, Shop, and Connect. Find
and Shop are ways to get access to people who will search the Net
for information you need _ the closest steakhouse to your Houston
hotel, for example _ and buy the flowers you should have bought
your spouse for your anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Quixi Connect is like a flesh-and-blood version of Wildfire, the
phone-and-messaging virtual ``assistant'' offered by Wildfire
Communications of Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   By giving Quixi your Rolodex, you can call in and say, please
connect me to Alice and Lisa, or send this e-mail to John. Pines
envisions Quixi being especially popular for people driving home at
night or for some of the 5 million US personal digital assistant
owners who may be running through an airport and can't flip open
the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The great and perhaps unanswerable question until it hits the
market is how many people are willing to pay $240 a year to have an
Internet serf at their beck and call, plus an old-fashioned ``Get
me Watson on the phone'' secretary to whom you hand over your
entire address book.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many new-economy Americans say they would prefer
having more time than more money.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever used one of the new Internet-enabled wireless
phones to try to order a book from Amazon.com, for example, or get
directions to the Airport Sheraton in an unfamiliar city, you may
find it easy to imagine you could get the job done much faster by
using the phone like a phone and calling someone to do it _
especially using the keypad to write and send an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Quixi sees as one big customer base the 15 million of the 85
million US cell phone owners who use them more than 200 minutes a
week. But there is no reason you couldn't use it from any phone to
make exploiting the Net quicker and easier. Forrester Research has
estimated that nearly 40 percent of Net shoppers quit before
completing transactions they want to do because of the hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Pines has already made a fortune by founding a company called
InfonXX in Bethlehem, Pa. that provides directory assistance to
wireless telephone companies including Bell Atlantic Mobile,
AirTouch, AllTel, and some Cellular One franchises. To support
Quixi, an elite corps among the 2,000 InfonXX operators will be
trained as Internet Sherpas.
</P>
<P>
   Marwell and Pines already know a few things about the economics
of running a call center, where the 10 percent of pain-in-the-neck
customers may account for 50 percent of costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some big-name investors, including Flatiron Partners and
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, have shoveled $27.5 million into the
company. Much of the venture funding will go into a buzz-promoting
billboard campaign in New York and Los Angeles this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say we think we can make this work,'' Pines said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-14-00 1538EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
