<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's a whole lot of pew-shaking going on
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the follow-up to its million-selling ``Pages of Life Chapters
I &AMP; II,'' Fred Hammond and his accompanying vocal ensemble Radical
for Christ have come up with an all-purpose gospel record.
</P>
<P>
   For the younger fan who may want to blast ``Purpose by Destiny''
on the way to the mall, you can take ``I Want My Destiny,'' ``Let
Me Praise You Now'' and ``I Press'' to the higher decibels and _ if
no one's listening to the lyrics _ barely distinguish it from the
bass-heavy Brothers Johnson of the '70s or much of what slickly
produced R&AMP;B teen singer Brandy does today.
</P>
<P>
   In quieter places, like the side of your bed, one could offer up
the more meditative ``Give Me a Clean Heart,'' as Hammond seems to
be doing in his pinched, impassioned and muscular plea.
</P>
<P>
   And the tracks sure to shake the pews are the live recordings
``Jesus Be a Fence'' and ``Thank You Lord (For Being There),''
powerful throwbacks to the times when all it took to get the
worshippers out of the folding chairs was a drum set, a piano and a
hallelujah choir.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond and RFC wrench real spirit out of computer-driven
production, but they are smart enough to include what really
connects.
</P>
<P>
   'Purpose by Design'
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hammond / Verity / 13 tracks / Our critic's grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
