r e BC-AUDIO-G16-COX     03-15 0223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-G16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R&AMP;B baritone knows how to make you feel the pain
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Obviously Gerald Levert's patience with gold diggers has hit
rock bottom. The baritone starts his fourth solo album belting:
``When I didn't have money/ I didn't have you/ I didn't have
problems/ This much is true'' _ leading a listener to believe
(rightly so) that he's going to deal a lot with dollar-driven
women. But the smart songwriter sees unhealthy relationships from
varying sides of the coin. On the bluesy ``She Done Been'' he
empathizes with a woman in a situation where ``every guy you start
to dig comes with baggage and no (job).'' And ``Misery Loves
Company'' is a rare instance in music where a man tells another he
doesn't appreciate him taking advantage of his kindness.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't stay mired in dysfunction. But just when lithe
guitars ease you into such standard love songs as ``Heart Don't''
and ``It Hurts Too Much to Stay,'' ``Hurt'' ends with duet partner
Kelly Price saying she wants to kill his girlfriend to keep them
apart. Misery not only has company here, but a nicely crafted
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``G''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Levert. Elektra. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
