<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX     03-15 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reivews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate and Ryon Horne
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  FOLK-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying Saucer Blues''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Case. Vanguard. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Add Peter Case to the long list of singer-songwriters who've
never outgrown the '60s, despite coming of age after the Age of
Aquarius. With his raspy vocals, intricate acoustic fretwork and
clever lyrics, Case is often compared to Bob Dylan and Woody
Guthrie. He is neither, of course. His lyrics plumb more personal
than universal themes, and have more bark than bite. But like his
predecessors, he's at his best when spinning story songs _ funny
and serious _ that walk the line between folk and jangly rock.
Case's seventh solo CD covers familiar ground: lamenting lost
chances (``Coulda Shoulda Woulda''), romanticizing his roots
(``Black Dirt &AMP; Clay'') and facing down Y2K angst (``Paradise
Etc.''). Not everything works: Some songs suffer from similar
pacing and structure. But the total package is worthy of his
musical parentage, giving a new generation of folkies plenty to
ponder and savor.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``BTNHResurrection''
</P>
<P>
   Bone Thugs-N-Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthless/Epic Records. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Just when we thought one of the hard-core rap groups was calling
it quits, Bone Thugs-N-Harmony creatively splices together another
album that resurrects its authentic sound. Lyrically, the
Grammy-winning group has combined its most unapologetic poetry and
life experiences, rendering a list of tracks that negatively
influences (``Ecstasy''), positively inspires (``Change the
World'') and forcefully paints a vivid description of its world
(``Mind on Our Money''). Although the songs are contradictory at
times _ rapping about changing the world in one and then
glamorizing drugs in another _ the album is consistent musically,
with an appealing R&AMP;B sound.
</P>
<P>
   _Ryon Horne
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
