<HEADER>
A7457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-STPATS16-COX     03-15 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-STPATS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raise a toast to complex mix that is Ireland
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On St. Patrick's Day, everyone wants to be Irish. Not the
starving Irish of ``Angela's Ashes'' or the lamenting Irish of
``The Troubles.'' Just green-beer and leprechaun Irish. The two
best Irish movies ever made are John Ford's ``The Quiet Man'' and
John Huston's ``The Dead.'' They should not be missed. But here are
some other ideas, helpfully divided into light and dark, blarney
and bloody.
</P>
<P>
   BLOODY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In the Name of the Father'': Director Jim Sheridan reunites
with his Oscar-winning ``My Left Foot'' star Daniel Day-Lewis for
this true story of young Irishman Gerry Conlon, who was wrongly
convicted as an IRA terrorist in the early '70s. Worse, his
law-abiding father (Pete Postlethwaite) is also arrested as a
co-conspirator. The movie splits its attention between the
miscarriage of justice _ Emma Thompson is their steely-eyed lawyer
_ and the father-son jailbird bonding that takes place in prison.
Day-Lewis lost so much weight for the role that two fans stopped
him to ask, ``Are you all right? You were so handsome in `The Last
of the Mohicans.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Boxer'': Day-Lewis and Sheridan again. This time the
actor is a former IRA stalwart who, after 14 years in prison,
simply wants to resume his boxing career. But the suspicions of his
old IRA cronies and a rekindled romance with his old flame (Emily
Watson) make things difficult. In the best scene, a pointedly
apolitical bout between Day-Lewis and a Scottish champ erupts into
a full-scale riot. By this time, Day-Lewis was so identified with
Irish films that director Stephen Frears quipped, ``I knew Daniel
before he was Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Informer'': In 1935, John Ford made this film about
friendship and betrayal during the Irish Rebellion of 1922. It's
still powerful. The screenplay won an Oscar, as did the director
(it was his first; he would win three more directing trophies, and
two of his films won documentary Oscars). The star, Victor
McLaglen, who later punched John Wayne all over Ireland in the
brawling finale of ``The Quiet Man,'' told his son: ``Laddie, I
guarantee you that if I get that part in `The Informer' I will get
the Academy Award.'' He did and he did.
</P>
<P>
   BLARNEY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Into the West'': Pure enchantment. Directed by Mike Newell
(``Four Weddings and a Funeral'') and produced by Sheridan, the
movie follows the adventures of two young brothers as they flee the
appalling squalor of their Dublin tenement and ride west on the
broad back of a magical white horse. On their trail: their father
(Gabriel Byrne), an embittered ``traveler'' who's forsaken his
roots; a tracker (Ellen Barkin) in love with Byrne; a greedy
horseman who wants the animal for the show ring; and half the
police force of Ireland. Exquisitely balanced between gritty
realism and lyrical fantasy, the movie is funny, poignant, and, if
you know your Celtic lore and the legend of the Kelpie, a bit
chilling and not just for kids.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Matchmaker'': A shamelessly likable bit of Irish charm
about a senator's workaholic aide (Janeane Garofalo) who's sent to
find her boss' Irish roots for a photo op. She arrives in the
coastal town of Ballinagra, a place so quaint that it makes the
village in ``The Quiet Man'' look like Buckhead. She also happens
to arrive on the day of Ballinagra's annual matchmaking festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Darby O'Gill and the Little People'': Sort of the classic
faith-and-begorra movie. Disney wanted to make this tale of a wily
Irishman (Albert Sharpe) and the King of the Leprechauns (Jimmy
O'Dea) for almost 20 years. But don't mistake this for a kiddie
movie. Anyone who's seen it remembers with a decided shudder the
shrieking banshee and the mystical death coach.
</P>
<P>
   Note to readers: In last week's column, I wrote a joke that fell
flat. An item involving Max von Sydow mentioned how he played the
Grim Reaper in ``The Seventh Seal.'' Von Sydow was indeed the
knight who played Death in chess. Get it? Well, unfortunately some
people didn't. Next time, I'll be a better joke writer.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
