<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, March 15, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-GASOLINE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco topped the average
price for unleaded self-serve gas of any major U.S. city with a
record $1.90 per gallon, according to a survey released by the
California State Automobile Association. By JUSTINO AGUILA.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-EXECUTION (San Francisco) _ With a sacred white eagle
feather draped diagonally across his chest to signify his Indian
heritage, Darrell Keith Rich softly drew his last breath early
Wednesday and became the first Californian executed in the year
2000. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-LUCAS (San Francisco) _ A coalition of environmental
groups including the Sierra Club says the proposed George Lucas
digital arts center at the Presidio would produce serious water
problems, require far too much construction and violate the
development plan for the new national park. By GERALD D. ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO-EBAY (San Francisco) _ Going once, going twice, gone to
Yahoo? CNBC, the cable/Internet financial network, quoted unnamed
sources as saying that Yahoo Inc., the Internet's most popular
destination, is mulling over the purchase of eBay Inc., the wildly
successful online auction site. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (San Francisco) _ If you can't beat 'em, do a
deal with 'em. Seattle-based RealNetworks, which publishes popular
software that lets users listen to music over the Internet,
announced that it is licensing software from a bitter and
formidable foe: software giant Microsoft. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-ASIAN-MARRIAGE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Cultural rifts that
divide generations have been part and parcel of the American
immigrant experience. Indians from South Asia are no exception. For
many other second-generation Indian women in the United States,
issues of dating and marriage will plague them until they walk down
the aisle (or around the fire, if they choose a traditional Hindu
ceremony). By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-STEVE-YOUNG (San Francisco) _ Now some male chauvinists
might say, upon hearing that San Francisco 49ers quarterback and
perennial bachelor Steve Young got married, that his last konk on
the head loosened his marbles. But we prefer the opinion of
romantics: Young finally got some sense knocked into him. The knot
was officially tied Tuesday in a Mormon temple in Kailua-Kona,
Hawaii. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The average dream lasts about
six minutes, but for those who have sat on a Harley-Davidson, BMW
or other motorcycle, the dream lasts for as long as the motor is
rumbling. Now, you can rent a bike and go touring. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FISH-FAMINE (Monterey, Calif.) _ Scientists say that overfishing
has plundered the ocean. As of 1993 nearly 80 percent of the
commercially valuable fish were overfished or ``fished to their
full potential,'' according to the National Marine Fisheries
Service. To alert shoppers and restaurant patrons about what's
really hot and what's barely surviving in the ocean, the Monterey
Bay Aquarium has issued ``Seafood Watch: A Guide for Consumers.''
By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-IRISH-MOVIES (Undated) _ Movies about Ireland, elbowing
into America's theaters year after year after year, may have
finally elbowed themselves out the door. Over the past decade more
than a dozen movies have been filmed in Ireland, including box
office hits ``Waking Ned Devine'' and ``The Commitments.'' But the
three that debuted this year haven't made much of an impression. On
the eve of St. Patrick's Day, movies about the Emerald Isle may be
running out of audience. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The NRA doesn't shoot people, it
shoots itself in the foot. What in blazing six-guns was the
National Rifle Association's Wayne LaPierre thinking when he said
that President Clinton ``needs a certain level of violence in this
country.'' What Clinton needs is a certain level of the NRA talking
about violence. When it gets down to LaPierre's level it
embarrasses even Republicans and responsible gun owners. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
