<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW TALKING POINTS TO KEEP US BUSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK. Super Tuesday and Super Tuesday II are history.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining presidential primaries are like the final games of
the baseball season, those meaningless contests that must be played
even though playoff slots have been divvied up and fans are
counting the days until the World Series begins.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series of politics takes place this year on Nov. 7,
when citizens of the planet's lone remaining superpower elect a new
president. What do you suppose we'll talk about 'til then?
</P>
<P>
   Well, we could start by talking about the new poll that showed
Republican nominee-to-be George W. Bush leading Democrat Al Gore as
both candidates went about the business of adding to their delegate
totals in Tuesday's Southern primaries. The USA Today/CNN/Gallup
Poll put Bush's support at 49 percent among likely voters surveyed
with Gore grabbing 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the pollsters asked respondents their preference in a
three-way race that included Pat Buchanan as the Reform Party
candidate, Bush won again with the Texas governor racking up 47
percent to 43 for Gore and 6 percent for Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers add up to bad news for the tireless Bush-haters
who've been sending nasty e-mails and leaving insulting messages on
my voice mail: As Bush demonstrated in his second campaign for
governor and in his current campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination, he is a resolute and resourceful
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   What about other polls, you say, the ones that show Gore leading
Bush? Aren't those surveys good news for Bush's detractors?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. When he needs to be, Bush is a determined and
resilient underdog _ as he proved conclusively in his first
campaign for governor against highly favored incumbent Ann
Richards.
</P>
<P>
   These people who claim to be absolutely certain that the
American people will never choose Bush to occupy the nation's
highest elective office should prepare themselves for the shock of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Bush crowd is hereby invited, however, to go right on
underestimating the son of ex-president George Bush. George W. Bush
loves to be underestimated; surprising his critics makes his
victories all the more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Gore might want to check with Richards before he decides to take
Bush lightly. Richards' re-election strategy consisted entirely of
taking cheap shots at Bush _ deriding his background, ridiculing
his family, questioning his qualifications and even his right to
seek the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, ran a sharply focused campaign based on
his vision for the future of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Look for him to conduct a similar campaign against Gore _ or try
to. Bush would much rather discuss issues than trade insults with
opponents; but as John McCain learned in the primaries, Bush will
fight back if attacked.
</P>
<P>
   So if Gore plans to go after Bush the same way he went after
primary challenger Bill Bradley _ with misrepresentations,
half-truths and flat-out falsehoods _ the vice president should
understand that Bush will give as good as he gets.
</P>
<P>
   Even before voters went to the polls in Tuesday's last major
round of primaries, Gore had traveled to Texas to tell Bush's
elderly constituents that a Bush presidency would threaten Social
Security and Medicare. It was an outrageous lie, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore studied the ancient art of lying/fear-mongering at the
right hand of the master, Bill Clinton, and the president's prize
pupil obviously thought it was important to toss an early mudball
at his opponent on the opponent's home turf.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today, meanwhile, reported that the Bush campaign had
unveiled ``the Gore Detector,'' a periodic report on Gore's
``adventures with the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore seems determined to lie his way into the White House, just
as Clinton did when he and Gore ran against Bush the Elder in 1992
and against Bob Dole in '96. Bush the Younger is determined to make
sure Gore doesn't get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   And we were wondering what we'd talk about 'til Election Day?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
