<HEADLINE>
A TIP OF THE CAP TO THESE WORKS ABOUT THE IRISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; do not know US Representative Peter T. King, Republican of
New York, but I think I know the type. He seems to be an
against-the-tide type of politician. Last year he defied the
snarling House GOP leadership to vote against impeaching President
Clinton. Two weeks ago, he was point man in New York for the
insurgent candidacy of Senator John McCain, defying all the
Republican bosses crowded onto the bandwagon of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   King had some choice things to say about the Catholic-bashing of
the proprietors of Bob Jones University, and the Texan's timidity.
He denounced Bush for his tongue-tied and inelegant cameo at Bob
Jones U., a bastion of narrow nativism where no blacks or Roman
Catholics need apply, never mind more exotic breeds. King seems to
be one of those Irishmen to whom the joy of combat comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   But pugnacity in a politician can wear thin as quickly as
profanity from the lips of a woman. And King has put on exhibit in
a novel he has penned his softer side, except for the bloodthirsty
sentiments expressed about the British role in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   As co-chairman of the Congressional Ad Hoc Committee on Irish
Affairs, King knows a good deal about The Troubles in Ulster, and
his novel, ``Terrible Beauty,'' recounts the struggle of an Irish
Republican Army housewife in Belfast whose friends and relatives
are both victims and victimizers in the Balkans-style bloodletting
of that backward era.
</P>
<P>
   ``An extraordinary literary feat,'' testifies the book-jacket
blurb of Malachy McCourt, one of the brother act of Frank McCourt
et al., who have become the Flying Wallendas of Irish literature in
the United States. ``The work of a dead honest man,'' is the blurb
of Jimmy Breslin. And columnist Lars-Erik Nelson makes three,
saying King's ``role in the Irish peace accords helped to put an
end to the violence he so vividly depicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Unheralded roles of women and Protestant heroes of Irish
nationalism are themes of ``For the Cause of Liberty; A Thousand
Years of Ireland's Heroes'' by Terry Golway, New York Observer city
editor and columnist, who traces the millennium just past from
Brian Boru to John Hume.
</P>
<P>
   The eloquent embrace of death and the fear of dishonor recur
with remarkable frequency in Golway's retelling. After America's
Revolution, the Irish had another go at tossing off the Brits.
Wolfe Tone was captured and sentenced to be hanged, instead of
shot, as he preferred. He slashed his throat with a razor to cheat
the hangman, lingered for a week and died, aged 35. Sniffed Sir
George Hill, of the other persuasion: ``I would have sewed up his
neck and finished the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Army found soldiering on Irish soil easier than
here. ``In six months of fighting, 30,000 people had lost their
lives'' in Ireland's failed revolt, writes Golway. ``By comparison,
25,000 Americans had died in the six years it took for America to
win its liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   A century later, with Britain desperate for Irish recruits to
man its rifle battalions against the Boer rebellion in South
Africa, aged Queen Victoria was wheeled through Dublin as a
recruiting sergeant. William Butler Yeats, like Tone a Protestant,
penned a thunderous public letter of outrage: ``Whoever stands by
the roadway cheering for Queen Victoria cheers for the Empire,
dishonours Ireland, and condones a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Golway's thousand years ends with Gerry Adams and Martin
McGuinness taking their seats in Stormont, the castle symbolizing
British rule of the six counties of the North. The author credits
Bill Clinton with adroit moves in bringing Britain and the republic
to the peace table with the Ulster factions.
</P>
<P>
   He credits the economic boom of the '90s with reversing
Ireland's brain drain, as the young of Ireland ``eagerly embraced
the European Union, the global marketplace and secular politics . .
. Ireland in the 1990s also became post-Catholic, thanks in part to
a series of clerical sexual scandals that hastened the church's
weakening power and prestige in a country of well-educated young
people. Though still devout, Irish Catholics paid less attention to
church dictates than at any time since the days of Henry II and
Pope Adrian.'' The future, he concludes, ``has never looked
brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the past that mesmerizes the Irish, and historian
Lawrence J. McCaffrey has updated his original 1976 book. What was
``The Irish Diaspora in America'' has been retitled ``The Irish
Catholic Diaspora in America.'' Why the change? ``A majority of
people in the US who now define themselves as Irish or partly Irish
are not Catholic,'' which will be a rude shock to folks in South
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But they may find ample succor in the richly illustrated ``A
Journey Through Boston Irish History'' by Dennis P. Ryan, full of
rogues and rascals as well as politicians and prizefighters,
including bachelor William Stanislaus Murphy, Harvard 1885, who
bequeathed his $50,000 estate to Harvard ``to assist any qualified
student'' named Murphy. On my annual St. Patrick's Day pub crawl,
whether it be in Doyle's, the Eire, Amrhein's, or the Farragut, I
shall hoist a jar to Bachelor Billy Murphy, who knew, like the
Irish bartender eyeing change on the bar, that in the end, money is
``made round to go round.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
