<HEADLINE>
MY DAY WITH KOZMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 10:10 a.m.: Stagger in to work. Need stimulation. Gave up
coffee (for now). Gave up alcohol (on a trial basis). What's left?
Ah . . . a nice, fresh Poland Spring.
</P>
<P>
   I could walk 400 feet to the cafeteria, but who has the energy
for that? Instead, I log on to Kozmo.com and order the water
(itals)right from the computer where I'm working.(unitals) Delivery
is free even if I order the 60-cent Baby Ruth bar, and my order
arrives in less than an hour. In addition to the water, I tack on
an issue of Young &AMP; Modern magazine for girls, to check out their
hilarious ``Say Anything'' column, and a videocassette of Alfred
Hitchcock's ``Suspicion,'' which I can keep for three days. Total
order cost: $8.39.
</P>
<P>
   What's Kozmo? It's an instant gratification service for college
kids and the urban webocracy. It started in New York's grotty
Silicon Alley, where two entrepreneurs had the idea of delivering
essential life supplies _ food, video games, and toiletries (read:
condoms) _ to twentysomething Web slaves who worked more or less
around the clock. Free delivery, in under an hour. They've got a
ton of . . .
</P>
<P>
   10:45: It's here! That was quick. A full liter of Poland Spring,
plus I notice that my beloved ``Say Anything'' column has been
supplemented by a new, equally engaging feature, ``Ask Anything.''
(Sample question: ``There are squiggly lines on my chest! How did
they get there?'') And the video.
</P>
<P>
   Where was I? Oh, yes. Kozmo has a ton of venture capital and now
operates in San Francisco, Washington, and Seattle as well as in
Boston and New York. Just two years ago, the founders were
delivering videos themselves, on bicycles, in lower Manhattan to
help their messengers keep up with soaring demand. Now they're
planning to go public.
</P>
<P>
   How do you make money delivering stuff for free at
non-extortionate prices, e.g. a three-night video rental for $3.50?
First answer: Making money isn't always Goal Number One for dot.com
companies; building market share is. (In New York, Kozmo already
has a competitor, Urbanfetch.com.) Second answer: If you deliver a
whole lot of stuff, you'll make the same profit margins as the
bricks-and-mortar video shops and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   12:25 p.m.: Hydrated and half-Hitchcocked _ I'm at the part
where Joan Fontaine is indeed entertaining ``suspicions'' _ I
depart for my lunchtime run. More of a slog, really.
</P>
<P>
   2:05: Famished. What's for lunch, Kozmo? Not much, alas. They'll
be adding sandwiches in the future, but the future isn't now. Now
is snack foods galore, microwaveable pizzas, milk, and ice cream
treats. I settle for some real grok: Cool Blue Raspberry Gatorade,
a stack can of Pringles BBQ Potato Crisps, and a peanut butter
Power Bar. Bon appetit!
</P>
<P>
   2:55: Kozmo man Aaron arrives in his van 10 minutes short of the
60-minute deadline. He's wearing the funny Kozmo jacket people talk
about and explains that he ran into some traffic tie-ups on the way
from Allston. Everything you see on the Web site _ the 20,000
videos, the 2,000 DVD titles, etc. _ is stored in a warehouse
across the street from the Harvard Stadium. From 10 a.m. until 1 in
the morning, space-age logistical software sends Kozmo's 125
carriers, about half of them on bikes, to their appointed rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Kozmo makes several thousand deliveries a week to
much of Boston, and all of Cambridge, Brookline, Somerville,
Belmont, and Watertown. Local manager Will Weddleton plans to add
ZIP codes as time goes on.
</P>
<P>
   What goes wrong with Kozmo? Not much. I had some browser
problems that may have had more to do with my medieval (1998)
computer than their system. At one point, they failed to process my
credit card but a customer service call cleared that up instantly.
And no, they didn't know I was writing about them.
</P>
<P>
   The newsmagazines on display at the Web site are a week old. The
book selection is pretty thin. But the video selection is, well,
awesome. They even had my latest candidate for Worst Movie Ever
Made, Bernardo Bertolucci's ``The Sheltering Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   3:20: This final order is more or less random, as the designer
and I try to call up objects of different shapes and sizes that
will photograph well. Combining our photographic and epicurean
urges, we order a pint of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Coffee Heath Bar Crunch,
Nirvana's ``In Utero'' CD, and a stick of Right Guard deodorant. By
now, I assume the goods will arrive in less than an hour, and they
do, 40 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   4:15: I go back to watching ``Suspicion.'' Good work if you can
get it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT PEOPLE WANT . . . NOW!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Top sellers at Kozmo in Boston this week: &QL; 
Movie rental: ``Eyes Wide Shut'' &QL; 
Music CD: ``Machina,'' Smashing Pumpkins &QL; 
Game rental: Fear Effect for PlayStation &QL; 
Ice cream: Ben &AMP; Jerry's Chocolate Chip Cookie Dough &QL; 
Juice: Fresh Samantha Banana Strawberry Smoothie &QL; 
Magazine: Sports Illustrated &QL; 
Book: ``The Cider House Rules'' &QL; 
Household product: Huggies Newborn Diapers &QL; 
SOURCE: KOZMO.COM &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
