<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HITECH-GYM-BOS &LR;      03-15 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-GYM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYMS UPGRADE WITH HIGH-TECH GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For years, Nick Tranquillo was ``just another guy on a
treadmill.'' He had his daily workout at the YMCA's Central Branch
just the way he liked it. In fact, the 67-year-old retired teacher
has a long record as a gym rat, going back to his boyhood in
Boston's North End.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to his routine, he saw little reason to pay attention
to the computer-linked fitness system that has become the hot trend
in the nation's workout culture and which his own branch of the Y
installed almost two years ago. ``Who wants to bother?'' Tranquillo
remembers asking himself when the gym went high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what it was, this thing they put in,'' he says
about the central computer, called the kiosk, and the hand-touch
computer screens, called ``training partners,'' that are attached
to most of the training equipment and which, together, are the
backbone of the Y's computer-aided workout. Tranquillo kept to his
own format, mixing aerobics and weight lifting, while eschewing the
new new thing in exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year he tried it, and Tranquillo became a convert to
techno-exercise. ``It's like having a trainer at your side,'' he
says. Working out on the hip abduction machine, the small screen
attached to the training equipment notifies Tranquillo when he's
moving his legs too quickly, how many repetitions he has left, and
then, when he slams the weights together too hard, the computer
beeps and a mock-trainer message flashes: ``Don't let the weights
touch.'' Tranquillo laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a basic premise for the interactive workout is to extend
the reach of a gym's trainers. The computer hook-ups provide a
virtual hands-on experience, so that even if Tranquillo rarely sees
face-to-face the trainer the Y has assigned to him he might get
e-mail when he logs on and he knows the trainer is reviewing his
workout periodically from the computer terminal set up in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the trend in interactive workouts is a great
equalizer in a fitness world where personal trainers have
traditionally been an option only the affluent could afford.
</P>
<P>
   To go high-tech, the Y went with FitLinxx Inc., of Stamford,
Conn., one of a handful of techno-exercise firms that have appeared
in the past few years. Netpulse, for example, features monitors
attached to the workout equipment so a user can watch TV, listen to
music, surf Web pages, read e-mail, or simply track a workout. The
company Schwinn Cycling and Fitness Inc. of Boulder, Colo., offers
a setup not unlike FitLinxx. For those who prefer home fitness to
the Y or private gym, there's iFit.com, where users hook up their
treadmills and stationary bikes at home to the company's Web site
and then interact in real time with a trainer via video camera.
Users can also watch training programs or tap into other online
workout services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old golf pencil and the workout card _ we've moved way
past that,'' says Melanie P. Adams, fitness director at the Boston
YMCA. The Y, like most gyms, is always looking for ways to attract
new members and retain those who start working out full of energy
but then lose interest, tail off, and even disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The fitness industry estimates that half of new exercisers drop
out within six months of beginning a fitness program. The
interactive workout, however, seems to be making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   At the central branch, says Adams, about 1,500 of the Y's nearly
5,000 members have become FitLinxx users. Overall, the Y has a
yearly membership drop-out rate of about 38 percent. But, notes
Adams, the dropout rate among those members who are
techno-exercisers has fallen to 27 percent. This is good news, says
Adams, meaning the Y is retaining the exercisers who are
interacting with a virtual trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about communication,'' says Adams. The Y has eight
trainers, she says, and ``it's impossible to keep track personally
of the all the members.'' Even if it's through e-mail, the gym's
computer network allows trainers to accomplish some ``one-on-one
hand holding'' that in the past was found only in expensive,
exclusive clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``FitLinxx enables the trainers to track members: Have they been
in recently? How often? How many miles have they run? How much have
they lifted?'' From home, or if out of town on business, members
can e-mail their trainers as well as gain access to their workout
regimen and data through the company's Web site, www.fitlinxx.com.
</P>
<P>
   At the Y, each FitLinxx member is assigned a trainer and
together they set up a workout regimen. Each visit, the member logs
on at the kiosk, the central computer that looks like an ATM. Many
of the weight-training and aerobic machines are hooked directly
into the FitLinxx system, which means the workout is not only
interactive but its results go directly into a member's file.
Members log their own workout data after using machines that are
not yet hooked up or after completing exercises _ like swimming
laps _ that cannot be connected to the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm visual, so it's great for me,'' says Liz Lender, a
32-year-old photographer. The screen attached to the leg curl
machine she's working out on reports that on her last visit she
lifted 50 pounds 13 times. The screen counts her repetitions and,
when she hits her target, she's rewarded with a round of beeping
sounds. Linder rolls her eyes. ``The salute,'' she says, ``is a
little bit much for my taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranquillo is standing at the kiosk. His ``workout notebook''
saves data for all his workouts, so he can review the past week,
month, or year and see totals for how much he has run or lifted.
Over time, the exercisers accumulate ``fitpoints'' _ one point for
every 10 pounds lifted, 10 points for every strength-training
station used, five points for every minute of cardiovascular
exercise _ and then the Y posts the monthly top point-getters by
age category and gender. Tranquillo's name often appears in the
monthly list of top 10 for his age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you an edge, motivates you,'' says the Y regular, who
estimates he spends about four hours a day at the gym, between the
``workout, the socializing, showering, and watching some handball
matches.''
</P>
<P>
   When a young man enters the weight room, Tranquillo greets him
with a ``There's the man!'' Then he finishes punching in his
treadmill results. How long? Sixty minutes. How far? Three and
one-third miles. (``A fast walk,'' he nods. ``That's my pace.'')
Estimated calories burned? Six hundred and ninety-two. Never mind
that the estimate is inflated because he entered a high
``exertion'' level when he stepped onto the machine. He smiles,
nonetheless. ``That's great,'' he says. ``Breakfast gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
