<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-TEENS-BOS &LR;      03-15 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-TEENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS GUIDE PARENTS THROUGH THE CRINGE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 16-year-old Zack Elias told his mother he ought to write a
book about all the ways parents embarrass their teenagers, her
response was surprisingly un-embarrassing. She actually encouraged
him.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Elias, vice president of Ballantine Publishing Group, had
a hunch such a book might find a sympathetic audience among other
clueless parents _ who seem to do nothing right while raising
teenage children. So, with his friend Travis Goldman, Zack Elias
spent the summer of 1997 working on a comprehensive guide to the
things parents should never do, say, wear, buy, eat, snicker at, or
comment on in or near their teenager's presence, to avoid utterly
humiliating them.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``How Not to Embarrass Your Kids,'' an 80-page
manual that spells out 250 ``don'ts'' for adults raising teenage
sons or daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The authors' premise is that parents not only mortify their
teenagers on a daily basis, but ``are actually oblivious to our
steady discomfort,'' they write in their introduction.
</P>
<P>
   The book leaves no source of humiliation undocumented. There are
prohibitions for eating in restaurants (``don't tell your life
story to the waiter''); attending movies (``don't yell out the
answers to the pre-movie trivia quiz show''); for driving (``don't
use the steering wheel as a drum or the dashboard as a keyboard'');
for fashion (``don't wear pants that stop above the ankle'').
</P>
<P>
   Some don'ts would probably seem reasonable enough to parents.
``Don't walk around in a bathrobe or your underwear'' and ``don't
call us by your pet nicknames in front of our friends'' might fall
into this category. Other no-no's are much less obvious (``don't
ask us to walk the dog when we are with a friend'' and ``don't ever
buy Jujubees or Jujyfruits'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know all these things were embarrassing,''
acknowledges Betsy Elias, citing the chapter on watching TV, with
such advice as ``don't use your index finger to work the remote _
always use your thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I walk into the room and sit down and watch TV, all I've
done is watch TV,'' she says, in a telephone interview. ``It's not
like I've walked in and burped, or said something risque.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias and Goldman are 19 now and college freshmen _ Elias at
UMass-Amherst, and Goldman at Boston University. They had low hopes
for their book's publishing prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted a nice letter of rejection from a good company
that we could put in our college applications saying we'd tried to
publish a book but failed,'' says Elias.
</P>
<P>
   But Betsy Elias asked a friend to recommend an agent, who
shopped the manuscript around. As though Elias' mother wasn't
embarrassing enough already for Zack, her own company, Ballantine,
rejected it. But Warner Books jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too far away from being a teenager myself, and I found
myself laughing out loud when I read it,'' says John Aherne, an
associate editor for Warner Books in his early 20s who acquired and
edited the book, now in its second printing with 17,000 books in
print. ``Everything they described was something my parents did to
me and my friends' parents did to them. They knew exactly what it
was that parents did to drive their kids up the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is one conclusion that can be reached from the book,
it's that the infractions cited by the authors are eerily familiar.
Is there a parent on the continent who has not violated the
following rules from ``How Not to Embarrass Your Kids'':
</P>
<P>
   --Don't ever say, when we are using the (television) remote,
``you're going too fast; I can't see what's on.''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't point to another kid whose shirt is tucked in and say
how nice he/she looks.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't make a whole big thing when you ask us what we did at
school all day and we answer ``nothing.'' For example, don't ever
say, ``OK, so you just sat and looked at the wall all day?''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't sing out loud to the golden oldies.
</P>
<P>
   Parents' ``general presence is embarrassing,'' says Elias,
interviewed in his unkempt UMass dorm room, the walls covered with
Led Zeppelin and movie posters, the floor with books and laundry.
He freely owns up to liking his parents a lot, but that doesn't
diminish his urge to crawl under a rock when, for example, his
father cheers too loudly for his ball team or quips to the man in
the turnpike booth, ``this is highway robbery.'' Goldman describes
the same urge to hide, but for different reasons _ his father's
tendency to wear sleeveless shirts, for instance, or his mother's
habit of ``dragging me by the arm into a clothes store and saying
to the clerk, `What would be cool for a person like my son here?'
''
</P>
<P>
   The boys argue no venue is safe for teens when they are
accompanied by their parents, not even when they're out of town.
Elias thought the coast was clear the time he went to Paris with
his mother, until he bumped into a friend from school while at the
Louvre. (The embarrassment was mitigated slightly by the fact that
the other boy was with his parents. ``We just gave each other a
look and went our separate ways,'' he recalls.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, family vacations bring a whole set of risks _ such as
being in one's parents' presence when they wear dorky hats, affect
local customs, such as kissing everyone on both cheeks while in
France, or attempt in vain to speak a foreign language. (Goldman
says his mother once mortified him in Spain by asking, ``Donde esta
the little girl's room?'')
</P>
<P>
   Elias maintains that the rule of thumb for parents when a
teenager is with friends is to keep a low profile. Very low. ``The
preferred distance is 3.5 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   One expert on teenagers thinks there is a better approach to
handling the embarrassment issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the solution is not to try not to embarrass your kid
because it's not possible,'' says psychologist Anthony E. Wolf of
Longmeadow, author of ``Get Out of My Life But First Can You Drive
Me and Cheryl to the Mall?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not work to walk on eggshells lest you mortify them,
and simply breathing mortifies them. If you talk, you run the risk
of enraging them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wolf says in an interview, ``When you say, `Good
morning my darling,' and they go, `Oh God,' just give them a big
hug, as though to say, `You can't stand me but I love you so much
anyway and I don't take it personally.' It absolutely works and
(deflects) their grumpiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he agrees that, for almost all teenagers,
commingling between parents and friends is ``embarrassment beyond
belief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once kids get into their teens, they develop an allergy to
their parents,'' Wolf says. ``It's a 100 percent normal thing.''
The hallmark of adolescence, as he writes in his book, is the
mandate to ``turn away from childhood and childish feelings.'' And,
since childhood is marked by domination by parents, it follows that
teenagers must experience themselves as independent. Reminders of
their parents' hold on them are simply, well, embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   There is good news, though. ``The nice thing is, it passes, as
they become more independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Zack Elias. ``Now when I come back from college, the
chances of being seen by my friends is a lot smaller,'' he says.
``The risk factor is much less.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE FIVE MOST EMBARRASSING OFFENSES BY PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1) Don't be seen in your underwear when your teenager's friends
are over.
</P>
<P>
   2) Don't tell the salesperson your life story or your kid's life
story.
</P>
<P>
   3) When your kid is shopping for clothes, don't ever say the
word ``crotch.''
</P>
<P>
   4) Don't cheer loudly for your kids when they are playing
sports, and if they get injured, don't rush up to them and say,
``Suck it up and deal.''
</P>
<P>
   5) Never go to the movies with your kids, and if you have to,
sit far away from them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
