A7550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CRUCIBLE-BOS &LR;      03-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CRUCIBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE FRENCH AND INDIAN WAR SOWED REVOLUTION'S SEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CRUCIBLE OF WAR 
The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North
America, 1754-1766 
By Fred Anderson 
Knopf, 862 pp., illustrated, $40 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historians now recognize the French and Indian War as not merely
some isolated frontier conflict, memorable as the background for
the historical novels of James Fenimore Cooper, but as the event
that created the conditions for the American Revolution. In its
guise as the North American component of the Seven Years' War _ the
first global conflict, waged also in Europe, in India, and at sea _
that frontier war also weakened the power of the European
empire-states. The argument is that defeat of the French in Canada
freed the English-speaking colonies from dependence on Britain for
military security and released the pent-up expansionist pressures
felt by the colonists.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Fred Anderson underscores that argument by bracketing
his account of the conflict between two set pieces involving George
Washington. Washington, it turns out, was in at the beginning _ a
frontier skirmish (a year before the better-known Braddock's
Defeat) in which a French emissary was hacked to death before his
eyes by Washington's Indian guides. (This is a brilliantly written
scene-setter which for Anderson is ``a clear example of a
historical moment when events . . . run out of control.'') As a
postwar planter and land speculator, Washington symbolizes the
aspirations of the colonists for economic freedom from British
control and for land in areas formerly under French or Indian
control. But these aspirations were blocked, in the first case by
taxation and trade-control measures, and in the second by Britain's
promises to its Indian war allies.
</P>
<P>
   Between these two events, Anderson has laid out the course of
the conflict as it moves from the North American frontier to Europe
and the Far East, and then back to the frontier. Anderson pays
particular attention to the important role the various Indian
tribes played in enabling the French to win a string of victories
in the early years of the war, including Braddock's Defeat, and
then their contribution to the final British victory after their
allegience had dramatically shifted.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came in July 1759, when Iroquois warriors
joined the British forces at the siege of Fort Niagara _ to the
complete surprise of the French defenders. As Anderson carefully
notes, they were acting not out of some whim, but after
considerable deliberation in the preceding winter months by the
chiefs of the six Iroquois nations meeting at Onondaga. ``For the
first time in its history,'' Anderson writes, ``New France would
face its enemies alone.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also significant that much of the second half of the
750-page text is devoted to the political fallout of the war in the
North American colonies. Anderson's account of the 1766 campaign
for the Massachusetts House between ``the court party'' and ``the
country party'' is as lively as that of any contemporary
legislative campaign. It was, he writes, ``the first time in the
history of the Bay Colony (that) an attempt to to organize a
province-wide political campaign actually worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a Harvard-trained historian now at the University of
Colorado, is also the author of ``A People's Army,'' a
well-regarded study of Massachusetts soldiers during the French and
Indian War. His ``Crucible of War,'' which expands on that work, is
likely to stand as the standard account of the French and Indian
War, if not of the global Seven Years' War as well. Its bulk
includes nine superbly executed maps and 63 illustrations from
historical sources, which Anderson uses as opportunities to treat
matters of geography and the characters of leading players.
</P>
<P>
   Readers for whom the French and Indian War has long held a
romantic fascination will want to pull out their copies of Francis
Parkman's ``Montcalm and Wolfe'' and compare his classic accounts
of Braddock's Defeat, the Battle of Quebec, and other events with
Anderson's. They will find that as a story-teller, Anderson
compares more than favorably _ that opening scene-setter at
Jumonville's Glen sets a vivid standard for the rest of the book _
and gets the edge with the benefit of the scholarship available to
a modern historian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
