<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-ALEX-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      03-15 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ALEX-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JULIA CHILD'S OLD KITCHEN, KATHIE ALEX HOLDS FORTH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATEAUNEUF DE GRASSE, France _ There was a moment during Kathie
Alex's apprenticeship on the Cote d'Azur two decades ago, in the
then three-star Moulin de Mougins restaurant, when she wondered
what she was doing. Forty years old and trying to keep up with a
very young all-male staff, she was too exhausted to do anything but
sleep on the beach during the afternoon break. In her real
``bedroom'' _ a friend's living-room floor _ she wasn't much better
off. ``I had a big house in California and a Mercedes in the
garage,'' Alex recalls. ``Sometimes it didn't make much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But sunny California came with marriage problems. Sunny Provence
promised something else. She was the first woman ever to work in
Roger Verge's famous Mougins kitchen. If she stuck with it, who
knew what would come her way?
</P>
<P>
   Something quite wonderful, as it turned out. Alex now owns La
Pitchoune (The Little One), the light-filled stucco cottage that
Julia and Paul Child built on a former potato patch 35 years ago in
this small town on the eastern edge of Provence, near the French
Riviera. In the same kitchen where Julia Child tested recipes for
the second volume of ``Mastering the Art of French Cooking,'' Alex
runs a school she calls Cooking With Friends in France. The
students are mostly Americans. Probably the same Americans who
learned to cook from ``Mastering'' in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Child is pleased that Alex got her house. ``She's a darling
person,'' Child says on the telephone from her winter residence in
Santa Barbara, Calif. ``She's just charming. She knows the whole
area, and she's so friendly with everyone. What a nice way to learn
French cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   When Alex first began teaching in the house in the early '90s,
Child wrote to her. ``I hear everything's going well,'' she wrote.
``I'm counting on you to teach Americans about butter and cream.''
</P>
<P>
   The two met 20 years ago, when Alex came here to take a class
from Simone ``Simca'' Beck, Child's friend and ``Mastering''
coauthor, who died in 1991. La Pitchoune is located within Domaine
de Bramafam, a 62-acre compound owned by a cousin of Jean
Fishbacher, Beck's husband.
</P>
<P>
   Built with royalties from the first volume of ``Mastering,'' the
single-level house is surrounded by olive trees and a sun-drenched
patio. Like all French houses, it has a small and unadorned
kitchen. This one contains a simple four-burner stove, a
dishwasher, a work table that seats six, and pegboard to hang pans
and implements. Paul Child, Julia's husband, installed the board
and drew lines around each pot, a system he also used to organize
the Childs' Cambridge kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It's not what students expect. To reach Bramafam, they have to
fly into Nice, rent a car, and drive the half-hour to Grasse, near
the famous perfume factories. They pass groves of olive trees, rows
of cypresses, and field after field of roses and grapevines. Once
they're inside the back door, Alex says, it's not uncommon to hear
someone say, ``Wow, this is small.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' she usually answers. ``This is the way it was.
You don't need a professional kitchen.'' But Child did cook on a La
Cornue range, which was gone by the time Alex arrived.
</P>
<P>
   And then the students settle in. They sleep in the Child cottage
or in a neighboring house that belongs to the Beck heirs, and they
spend a week cooking Provence's aromatic ingredients, sampling
local cheeses, visiting the street markets and Alex's own
purveyors, touring a two-star kitchen, and eating meals under a
mulberry tree on the patio, where lavender hangs over the wall and
the air smells of rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Alex's guest book is filled with her students' enthusiasm. Early
in the week, everyone seems to overcome the small-kitchen worry.
``Some segments of `The French Chef' were done in this kitchen,''
says Alex. She has painted the little room and meticulously redrawn
Paul Child's outlines on the pegboard _ even though she doesn't own
the pots that were once there. ``If I can put out a meal in three
hours from this basic stove,'' she tells her students, ``you can
too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julia and Paul Child had spent many years in France when Paul
worked for the United States Information Service. Once they went
back to the United States, they liked the idea of returning to
France for vacations. They decided they wanted a house in the
south, Julia Child recalls, ``and Simca said, `We'll lend you some
property.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't more official than that. ``It was understood through a
handshake that we would leave it one day,'' says Child.
</P>
<P>
   They had a simple house built, with three bedrooms. Julia and
Paul each had one, and there was a third for guests. While the
Childs were in the States, Simone Beck furnished the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simca also put in all the lawn and so forth.'' Child says she
wouldn't have landscaped it as well: ``I would have had pots of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fishbachers took care of the house. When the Childs would
arrive for their winter stay, ``the heat was on and the fridge was
full,'' says Child. ``Simca was very, very generous _ rather
un-French. They were just lovely to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Child tested recipes in the kitchen and could walk between the
olive trees to confer with Beck. Since the 1950s, Beck and her
husband had lived in the ``mas,'' the property's 300-year-old
farmhouse, which once housed both the landowners and their animals.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Child used a tiny two-room house next to La Pitchoune,
called the ``cabanon,'' as his painting studio. Alex now uses it as
her office and its basement as the wine cellar (the Childs did
too). When students are at La Pitchoune, Alex sleeps in the
cabanon.
</P>
<P>
   There are several similar little houses all over the property,
once used by workers. ``Italians walked down here from the Piedmont
to pick olives,'' says Alex.
</P>
<P>
   She began renting La Pitchoune when Julia Child stopped coming,
the year after Beck died. Child went for the last time in 1992,
just before her 80th birthday. Jean Fishbacher had died, Paul Child
was in a nursing home in Lexington, Mass., and the place held too
many memories for her, she told an interviewer after returning that
last time.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Fishbacher's sister, France Thibault, inherited the
property. She sold La Pitchoune to Alex a year ago _ and if she
hadn't, Alex might not have gotten it. Thibault died last month,
and her sons made the transaction difficult, Alex says. Alex now
owns 1 1/4 acres of land, which, according to local law, is the
minimum lot for a house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windows, shutters, and wiring all need attention, so Alex is
renovating slowly. Some things she won't touch. ``Julia is a note
person,'' says Alex. The bedroom that she used still has a packing
list tacked inside the closet door, pinned high so the 6-foot-2
cook didn't have to stoop to read it. ``Stockings &AMP; u/wear'' are on
the list, as are ``passport &AMP; dollars,'' ``eve purse,'' and
``make-up (all).'' Paul's list includes ``razor, t-brush, etc,''
``pills (all),'' and ``handk &AMP; underwear &AMP; ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Some notes were addressed to housekeepers, and those, of course,
were in French. Over the dishwasher, one reads: ``Ne pas ouvrir et
ne pas stopper en cours de route'' (``Don't open or stop during the
cycle''). Another lists what equipment should never go into the
washer: kitchen knives, iron frying pan, things made of wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love it,'' says Alex. ``I want to keep it the way it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex takes nothing for granted. She is grateful to be living
here, and when students come, she puts on the dog. Weeklong classes
cost $1,950, and the groups don't exceed eight people, just the
right number to fit into the kitchen. The rate includes six nights'
lodging, breakfast and lunch, five lessons, and excursions. Alex
arranges for a local chef to come in and teach one of the days,
often Christian Morisset of La Terrasse in Juan-les-Pins, a
Michelin two-star restaurant. The chef cooks while Alex translates.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are held only during May, June, September, October, and
November, since winters are chilly in Provence and summers hot and
crowded. Alex does take students outside her regular months when
she can.
</P>
<P>
   She is a confident but unpretentious cook. One day recently, she
hadn't had time to prepare anything for lunch guests, and she
opened the refrigerator to see what was there. Students had just
finished a special weeklong winter truffle program. She found some
roasted peppers, fresh tomato sauce, a few eggs, and big slabs of
butter, and turned them into the classic piperade. Along with salad
greens tossed with a mustardy vinaigrette and some local goat
cheese, she presented a fine lunch, served on traditional Provencal
pottery in deep olive and mustard, on a colorful yellow cloth
typical of the region, on the table under the mulberry tree.
</P>
<P>
   The winter sun was warming, and the setting was just about
perfect. ``Look,'' Alex says, pointing to some chips around the
edges of the plates. The thrifty French Chef had ``painted'' them
with marker pens to cover the chips; the colors weren't quite the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Alex wouldn't dream of buying new ones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
