<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN FINDS HIS OFFSEASON DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was ready to hit the road Tuesday, 12 hours nonstop from
Columbus, Ohio, to Boston, so he would be in Foxborough in time for
this morning's team meeting, the first of the Bill Belichick era.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn said he has made a commitment to the new Patriots
coach to take part in the team's strength and conditioning program.
He's also making the commitment to himself and to the fans to be
the go-to guy, especially with Bruce Armstrong, Ben Coates, and
Shawn Jefferson no longer with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want that,'' said the Pro Bowl wide receiver, who will be
entering his fifth year with the Patriots. ``I want to be the guy.
I'm ready for that. I have been ready for that. I thought I did
well when I was thrown the ball last year. I think everyone knows I
can make things happen when I get the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be strange not seeing Ben and Bruce and Shawn
around here, but I know Ben and Bruce will hook on someplace else
and I know Shawn, who came into this league as a ninth-round draft
pick, finally has a chance to make his money and take care of his
family. I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ben and Bruce can't find a place to play, it would great
for both of them to come back here. That would make our team that
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   With two pass catchers gone, the pressure on Glenn almost
certainly will increase.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Brown, who is now the highest-paid receiver on the team,
will be the No. 2 and maybe even the No. 3 guy if Tony Simmons is
able to move up. And between now and September, the Patriots may
add another veteran.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, Glenn knows the focus will be squarely on
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with a new offense that will mix things up and keep
the defense off-balance _ which is what I think Charlie (Weis) is
going to have here _ the sky's the limit for us,'' said Glenn. ``We
know we have an excellent defense, and with Bill running that, you
know we're going to be a top team offensively. If we can plug in a
few holes between now and the start of the season, we're going to
be a very productive offense. When you have Drew (Bledsoe) out
there, good things are going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn just bought a new house in a Columbus suburb, and except
for spending a few days in Honolulu for the Pro Bowl, he has been
taking courses at Ohio State this offseason. He was scheduled to do
his workouts with Ohio State conditioning coach Dave Kennedy, but
Belichick wants Glenn in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   After the team meeting, Glenn will return to Columbus to take
exams, then make it back for the official start of the strength
program Monday. The program runs through the first week of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Bill wants and that's what I'm going to do,'' said
Glenn. ``Bill has called me a couple of times and explained the
importance of all of us being around for the program since this is
the first year, so I understand that and I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   While Glenn concedes ``it's not my first preference,'' he said
he's aware that star players need to set an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about this season,'' said Glenn, who played
in the first 15 games last season before coach Pete Carroll
suspended him, allegedly for breaking team rules when he had the
flu. Glenn still has a grievance pending on the suspension; it
could be heard by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn doesn't have to worry about playing for Carroll
anymore, and Belichick, who had a close relationship with Glenn in
1996 in New England, has said he will not look to deal Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers coach Ivan Fears was one of the few assistants
retained from the Carroll regime, and Glenn also looks forward to
teaming up with Weis again. Weis was New England's receivers coach
in Glenn's rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to his house and having hamburgers,'' said
Glenn. ``Charlie took me in and made me feel welcome. When I got
here in '96, we had key people in place like Drew and Curtis
(Martin), and I think having the big receiver was the key piece
that was missing and I was able to fill that. Now, Drew and I are
in place and we're trying to find the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who thought some of his teammates had turned on him when
he wasn't able to play in the final game of '99, thinks the air is
clear and there are no more issues surrounding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win,'' said Glenn. ``It was frustrating at
times last year. There's no reason the players on this team can't
rally together and produce an excellent team. I'm going to try hard
to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
