r d BC-FISH-FAMINE-HNS &LR;      03-15 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-FAMINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AQUARIUM PUBLISHES EATERS' GUIDE OF FISH NOT TO EAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ It is a hot item on the restaurant menu, but
the Patagonian toothfish is quickly disappearing from southern
ocean waters off the United States, along with orange roughy,
redfish, Atlantic swordfish, Georges Bank cod and other fading
stars.
</P>
<P>
   To alert eaters about what is really hot and what is barely
surviving in the ocean, the Monterey Bay Aquarium has issued
``Seafood Watch: A Guide for Consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the size of the fish populations and how well they are
managed by government regulators and fishermen, the aquarium is
providing three lists: ``best choices,'' ``proceed with caution''
and ``avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Monterey Bay Aquarium Executive Director Julie
Packard, is to use market pressure to conserve ocean species and
healthy diets.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say that overfishing has plundered the ocean. As of
1993 nearly 80 percent of the commercially valuable fish _ those
whose status is known _ were overfished or ``fished to their full
potential,'' according to the National Marine Fisheries Service, a
branch of the U.S. Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   A report to Congress by 40 scientists said that almost all of
the important fish stocks off the northeastern, southeastern and
Gulf of Mexico coasts of the United States are either overfished or
nearing that status.
</P>
<P>
   Through its new guidebook, the aquarium, backed by information
from a panel of scientists and the Audubon Living Oceans Program,
warns restaurant-goers and cooks away from those fish whose
populations have been dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood is placed on the ``avoid'' list if the numbers are
depleted or the method of fishing them also kills turtles or
incidentally takes tons of other fish, called the by-catch.
</P>
<P>
   American lobster, bluefin tuna, lingcod, rockfish, monkfish,
shark, trawl-caught spot prawns and farmed salmon, among others,
are on that list.
</P>
<P>
   Farmed salmon and shrimp also are on the ``avoid'' list because
they sometimes create waste, disease and, in the case of salmon,
occasionally escape into a wild population.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``best choice'' list are albacore tuna, squid, Dungeness
crab, California and Alaska wild salmon and Alaska halibut. The
eat-up list also includes the following farmed animals: oysters,
clams, rainbow trout, catfish and striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   Some fish that make the ``proceed with caution'' list are
petrale and English sole, snow crab, Bay scallops and shrimp, and
wild Washington and Oregon salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The Packard Foundation, which founded the Monterey Bay Aquarium
in 1984, is spending $3 million this year to support consumer
education, eco-labeling and certification programs for well-managed
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   A well-managed fishery signifies that its operation is
environmentally friendly, that it is not taking more fish than can
be replenished naturally or not killing other species through
harmful fishing practices. A certified fishery can earn a ``Forever
Fish'' logo on its products, telling customers that the fish has
been taken in an environmentally sound way.
</P>
<P>
   One certification group being supported by the Packard
Foundation is the Marine Stewardship Council, a London-based
nonprofit organization set up in 1996 by World Wildlife Fund and
Unilever, a major food supplier in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, the council opened its first U.S. office in
Seattle. At a seafood show in Boston last week, the council
certified its first two fish _ the Western Australian rock lobster
and the Thames River herring _ because the industry that brings
them to the market has sound fishing operations. They now bear a
``Forever Fish'' logo.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Alaska Fish and Game Department requested a
``Forever Fish'' certification from the council, which is
evaluating the state's five runs of salmon: Chinook, coho, sockeye,
pink and chum.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the California fishing industry is talking to
the Sierra Club and other environmental organizations about
starting labeling that would appear on packages denoting which fish
are in season, which are particularly healthful and which come from
sustainable fisheries, said Zeke Grader, executive director of the
Pacific Coast Federation of Fishermen's Association.
</P>
<P>
   Grader consulted with the Monterey Bay Aquarium on its guidebook
list, which was revised in February based on comments from
fishermen in his group.
</P>
<P>
   One fish that didn't make it on the ``best choice'' list but
should have was the sardine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one fish we should be promoting because it's being
managed on a sustainable basis,'' Grader said. ``It's taken us 50
years to rebuild the stocks, and I think we've learned from our
mistakes of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Other populations of fish that aren't doing as well are rockfish
and groundfish, including lingcod, pacific red snapper, sablefish
and butterfish. But new regulations put in place recently by the
Pacific Fishery Management Council, a regional regulatory agency,
should improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
   In Islip, N.Y., Carl Safina, Audubon's vice president for marine
conservation, said it was worth saving the endangered species of
fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have those fish to eat in the future, and the
quality of peoples' lives depends on these things we like so much
maintaining a presence in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of power to protect sea life lies with consumers and
restaurateurs, he said. The Audubon Living Oceans program next
month will publish a 120-page full-color ``Seafood Lover's
Almanac.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
