<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-SOUTH-ASIAN-MARRIAGE-     03-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-ASIAN-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR MANY SOUTH ASIAN IMMIGRANTS, PARENTS STILL PLAY THE DATING
GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIE CHAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Cultural rifts that divide generations have
been part and parcel of the American immigrant experience. The
Indians from South Asia _ 1.2 million strong in the United States _
are no exception.
</P>
<P>
   For many other second-generation Indian women in the United
States, issues of dating and marriage will plague them until they
walk down the aisle (or around the fire, if they choose a
traditional Hindu ceremony).
</P>
<P>
   ``For a girl to grow up and have a successful marriage and
children is fulfilling some part of her duty,'' said Ketu H.
Katrak, director of Asian-American Studies at the University of
California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   In India, marriage is traditionally more a union based on social
and economic interests rather than romantic love between
individuals, a decidedly more Western notion. While some immigrants
from India do allow their daughters to love American style, others
insist they maintain as many Old World customs and beliefs as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents become even more traditional after arriving in the
United States because they fear their children will get too
``Americanized,'' said Katrak, who left India in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, the kind of patriarchal control that exists within the
Indian context certainly continues within the diaspora and often
gets more pronounced,'' she said. Some parents believe that ``if
you don't assert those cultural values, you might lose that
culture, or lose your children to Americanization, quote unquote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bina, a vivacious, attractive doctoral student in Palo Alto, is
33 and under intense parental pressure to find a husband. Not just
any husband will do. He must be Indian, and he must be Hindu.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're extremely worried,'' said Bina, who preferred not to
give her last name. ``It's a daily talk: `You're getting older. You
need to start thinking about marriage. If you don't start now, you
won't find any Indian boys.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents and friends are forever introducing her to potential
mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a job search,'' she said. ``It's much more
systematic as I get older because I don't have as much time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to generalize about the Indian subcontinent, an
immensely diverse region, with several major religions, dozens of
languages and subcultures, and vast class divisions. And, to be
sure, cultural and generational conflicts abound in every immigrant
family.
</P>
<P>
   But for Indian daughters, the question of when they marry is one
they will all have to answer. The pressure comes in numerous forms,
from an occasional inquiry, to a ``daily talk,'' as with Bina's
parents, to set-ups, to matrimonial ads placed in Indian newspapers
or on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   How daughters deal with parents' concerns is just as varied. The
dozen or so women interviewed for this article, many of whom would
give only their first name for fear of embarrassing their families
with details of their personal lives, rejected or subscribed to
their parents' beliefs to differing degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Some try to do what their parents want. Some date on the sly.
Some try to urge their parents to accept new ways. Some refuse to
do set-ups, while others reluctantly agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a huge sense of responsibility for making my family
happy,'' Bina said. ``I think Indian women get the party line told
to them, which is, `We've done so much for you to make you happy,
this is the least you can do to make us happy.' I think that level
of guilt is something I haven't been able to work through.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonima Khan, a sophomore at the University of California at
Berkeley, said her parents, who are Muslims from Bangladesh, had
forbidden her to date but expected her to marry when she was 24 or
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like, why are they even sending me to school
if they're just going to marry me off?'' she said. ``I feel like my
whole life has been a scam. They've raised me to be this perfect
eligible bachelorette.''
</P>
<P>
   Khan, 19, said she wanted to travel, establish her career and
become financially independent after graduating, but would probably
marry by the time she was 25 ``because anytime after that, my mom
would seriously go into depression.''
</P>
<P>
   Khan, who left Bangladesh _ formerly a province of Pakistan _
when she was 2, would prefer a South Asian spouse for cultural
reasons, but her parents insist that he be Muslim as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is, we're all pretty much the same _ Pakistan,
India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka,'' she said. ``I don't see why we
should all divide. Our culture and beliefs are a lot alike. I don't
differentiate between Bengalis and Hindus and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents place more emphasis on character than ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (my two children) a long time ago, they can marry
anybody they want to, but a nice person,'' said Aruna Reddi of
Fremont, whose son, 31, and daughter, 24, are both single. ``I just
want them to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For some parents from India or its South Asian nations, playing
matchmaker for their children _ as well as those of friends,
relatives and neighbors _ is viewed as a pleasure if not a duty.
But unlike traditional arranged marriages where the whole family
meets the other family, arranged dates these days are usually
little more than a phone number or e-mail address passed on to the
daughter to use if she chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude has definitely changed,'' said Jasmin Patel, a
30-year-old legal research and writing instructor at the University
of California at Berkeley law school. ``In high school or college,
my parents setting me up with someone? No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Patel said, she'll meet the guy ``as long as we're clear
with expectations. ... If we don't get along, I'm not obligated to
see him again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
