<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SCHOOL-CHEF-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SCHOOL CHEF'S MENU IS TOPS IN ITS CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His lunch customers would be happy with a bag of chips and a
slice of pizza. But, he wants them to have the pasta e fagioli soup
and fettucini in tomato-alfredo sauce.
</P>
<P>
   They might be fine with chicken patties and tater tots. But, he
feels better if they have sweet and sour chicken, fried rice, and
garlic and chili green beans.
</P>
<P>
   They are students.
</P>
<P>
   He is Garth Petracca, food service director.
</P>
<P>
   Everyday he heads into a school cafeteria kitchen to wage a
culinary war to conquer young stomachs - and he's winning, it
seems.
</P>
<P>
   The April issue of Restaurant Hospitality magazine recently
recognized Petracca's efforts at Bristol-Plymouth (Mass.) Regional
Technical High School with the Best Kids Menu in America award.
Petracca was chosen from among 200 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Now designing menus for the Duxbury, Mass. school system, he won
for his five-week rotating menus featuring theme days and ethnic
dishes like Honduran tomato soup, soy and ginger cabbage, broccoli
fra diavolo and Teriyaki chicken stir-fry.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity and the concepts made Petracca the winner, said
Katie Smith, who helped coordinate the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to good menus is to treat students like real diners,
says Petracca. ``I really don't think of it as food service,'' said
34-year-old Mashpee, Mass. resident. ``I think of it as my little
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Petracca's passion for preparing meals has paid off. One of the
most unusual items he got students to eat was hot and sour soup.
``Once they tried it, they got a big kick out of it because it was
unlike anything they had eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   But Petracca knows the battle to win students' tastebuds isn't
over: he left out the tofu in the hot and sour soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my limits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1331EST &QL; 
