<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dandy weed wields incredible nutritional power
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had to spend some time on a desert island and could
choose just one plant to sustain you, which would you choose?
Spinach, cabbage, turnips, beans and corn probably come to mind.
But would you think of dandelions? Probably not. In most Americans'
minds, dandelions are pesky, unsightly, lawn-destroying weeds that
we pull or poison at every opportunity. You should know, however,
that nutritionally, the humble dandelion is nothing short of
amazing. Scientific studies in Europe and the United States,
including one from the University of California, suggest that
dandelions are one of the most, if not the most, nutritionally
potent plants nature has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Take beta carotene, the substance the body converts into vitamin
A and that's generally thought to lower the risk of cancer and
heart disease: Carrots are considered to be loaded with beta
carotene, with 6.1 milligrams per 10 grams. Dandelions contain 8.4
milligrams for the same amount, according to USDA figures.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do dandelions contain more beta carotene than carrots,
but they have more potassium than bananas, more lecithin than
soybeans and more iron than spinach. In addition, they are
particularly rich in fiber, calcium, magnesium, phosphorus, the B
vitamins thiamin and riboflavin and a veritable alphabet of other
vitamins and minerals. They also are rich in rare micronutrients
such as copper, cobalt, zinc and boron.
</P>
<P>
   So why do Americans, who are seemingly so diet- and
health-conscious, do all they can to eradicate dandelions every
chance they get?
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gail, a botanist and author who has spent the past 37
years studying how various cultures use weeds as food and medicine
and a major figure in the dandelion underground, says it's a
generational thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dandelions were a staple up to and throughout the Depression
and World War II. They were not only used for food but for medicine
and in some cases kept people alive. Then came the GI Bill,
suburbs, lawns, pesticides and supermarkets that stocked iceberg
lettuce and it was goodbye dandelions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Europeans are a lot more appreciative of
dandelions, regarding them highly on their tables and in their
medicine cabinets. For centuries dandelions have been used as a
restorative for the entire system, especially for the blood, liver,
stomach, spleen and pancreas.
</P>
<P>
   If you are craving a true spring tonic and a time-honored way to
capture a surge of spring energy, you need only go as far as the
nearest dandelion patch. To reacquaint yourself with the remarkable
dandelion, here are some tips about gathering them, some
informative Web sites and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TIPS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gather dandelion leaves when they are young, before flowers
appear. After they finish flowering, cut them back to the top of
the roots and continue to harvest the young greens as they keep
coming back until November.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pick plants growing in the shade. They will be bigger and less
bitter than those growing in full sun. If you want to add
dandelions to your garden, plant them under pole beans, tomatoes or
other tall crops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dandelion roots are efficient but nondiscriminating miners of
all the minerals in soil. They will take up lead, mercury and
pesticides along with the good stuff. As far as auto pollutants,
studies have shown that it is safe to collect dandelions 75 feet or
more from the roadside. Also look for those growing behind a
structure, like a house or barn, that protects them from airborne
pollution. And certainly avoid picking any that are on chemically
treated lawns, parks or fields.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You may have sampled dandelions way back when, recoiled at the
bitter taste and never tried them again. Yes, mature dandelion
greens eaten straight up can be bitter, but not any more so than
some other greens eaten that way. There are growing and harvesting
techniques and imaginative recipes that will reduce the bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't forget, you can enhance the nutritional value of soups,
stews, salads and just about any dish by adding a few dandelion
greens. Dressing them with a simple raspberry vinaigrette works
nicely, too.
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start by visiting Botanical.com's
www.botanical.com/botanical/mgmh/d/dandel08.htmlhis for an overview
of the history, cultivation, chemical makeup and medicinal uses of
dandelions. See www.dandelions
</P>
<P>
   .com/why.html for another informative overview.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For detailed health and nutritional information, see Peter
Gail's essay at www.herbal-alternatives.com/dandelio.htm; ``The
Incredible Edible Dandelion'' at
www.lincolnnet.net/users/lmpkfrst/fmarket/dandel.htm and
``Dandelions'' at www.sbherbals
</P>
<P>
   .com/0497HotM.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check out www.tomifobia.com/dndylion.html, a thoughtful essay
that begins: ``Dandelions are not only survivors, they are
prevailers. Dinosaurs had their day, mankind is currently enjoying
its fifteen minutes. But dandelions shall inherit the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   DANDY RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About.com has a wonderful collection of dandelion recipes and
related sites at
//homecooking.tqn.com/food/homecooking/library/weekly/aa052598.htm.
There are some great salads and dressings that soften the sometimes
bitter taste of the leaves. Salads and dressings also can be found
at www.wcco.com/partners/radio/suez/dandelion.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At //home.flash.net/(tilde)tinyt/otdandy.html, find recipes
that use the flowers, buds, roots and leaves to make coffee, tea,
several versions of dandelion wine, syrup, jam and fritters.
Dandelion greens get paired with potatoes, pasta, eggs and cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recipes at //memberpage.women.com/food/
</P>
<P>
   kanawa/wild.html include one that combines the greens with
bacon, hard-boiled eggs, honey and rice wine vinegar. If you are
feeling adventurous, there are some fascinating recipes that use
other wild plants and weeds, including cattails and one for jelly
made with Queen Anne's lace.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Several recipes for dandelion flowers, including one for wine,
can be found at www.herbal-alternatives
</P>
<P>
   .com/dandelio.htm.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of Peter Gail's book ``The Dandelion Celebration: A
Guide to Unexpected Cuisine'' or for more information about the
National Dandelion Cookoff in May near Cleveland, call
1-800-697-4858 or visit www.edibleweeds.bigstep.com.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Dandelion Chicken Quiche
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's the winner of last year's National Dandelion Cookoff,
held in Dover, Ohio. If you can't find dandelion at your store and
don't want to pick any, you can substitute arugula. Just don't cook
it as long.
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts dandelion greens (available at farmers' markets)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   6 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-inch) deep-dish pastry shell, pricked and uncooked
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked and diced chicken breast
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, well-beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   Hot sauce to taste, up to 1 tablespoon
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Clean dandelion greens. Add greens
and salt to boiling water. Boil 10 minutes, drain, cool and
coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   Line pastry shell with foil, then fill with dried beans or
uncooked rice. Bake shell 8 minutes, then remove from oven. Reduce
oven temperature to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, toss cheese with flour. Add chicken, milk,
eggs, onion, pepper and hot sauce; mix well. Pour into prepared
shell. Bake 40-45 minutes or until set. Let stand 10 minutes before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 419 calories, 27 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 27 grams carbohydrates, 212
milligrams cholesterol, 444 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
