<HEADER>
A7566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-ALEX-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     03-15 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ALEX-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CHATEAUNEUF DE GRASSE, FRANCE: ... new ones.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Alex jumped on a plane in California in 1979 to come here
for Beck's classes, it was on a whim. Beck undoubtedly took to
Alex. In the photographs that rest on tables at La Pitchoune, the
resemblance between the regal, blond, bespectacled Beck and the
young, blond, bespectacled Alex are striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simca was my first mentor,'' she says. Alex returned in 1981.
``I'd gone back home to study French.'' In 1983, Beck arranged an
expensive weeklong ``stagiaire'' (apprenticeship) at Mougins for
Alex. ``You had to pay almost $1,000, but Simca got the week for
free,'' says Alex.
</P>
<P>
   After seven days, Verge asked Alex if she wanted to stay on for
three months. She mulled it over. Things at home weren't great, and
her only son was grown. When she got right down to it, there was no
reason not to stay. Then Simca, to whom she went for advice,
weighed in. `` `Do you think it's going to change anything if you
go home now?' '' Simca asked.
</P>
<P>
   So she joined Verge's staff. ``It changed my life.'' There were
no women in the kitchen, and the young men _ many of whom had been
cooking since they were teenagers _ had much more energy than she
did. ``I worked just like anyone else, which means a double
shift.'' In France, most of the top restaurants serve both lunch
and dinner. All employees are expected to work both meals.
Afternoons, while Alex napped on the Riviera, the rest of the
kitchen went outside for an impromptu game of soccer (what the
French call ``football'').
</P>
<P>
   ``It was grueling,'' says Alex. ``I weighed the least I had
weighed since I was 16. It melts off you.''
</P>
<P>
   After her apprenticeship, Verge wanted her to open a cooking
school in San Francisco. ``I was an accountant,'' says Alex. ``He
thought I would certainly have lots of money.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't, but Verge opened other doors. Alex returned to
California and became a regular assistant to other top chefs who
taught at Mondavi Winery's ``Great Chefs of France'' cooking
program.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 years ago, she moved back to France to live in Antibes;
she cooked on yachts and in private villas, and assisted Beck. Then
the opportunity came to move to La Pitchoune.
</P>
<P>
   Alex is at home now, very friendly with several top chefs and
their wives. She seems to know everyone. At the local pizza house,
she greets the proprietor, then goes over to say hello to the cook
before sitting down. She points out four people in the middle of
the restaurant. ``Chefs on their night off,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   They start laughing. At first it's just the loud, throaty laughs
of heavy smokers, and then they get going and they can't stop.
They're howling with laughter, and it just keeps erupting every
time it seems to be dying out. The whole restaurant joins in, not
really knowing what was funny in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Alex starts laughing too. She's enjoying the spectacle. When the
place finally settles down, she sits back in her chair, slightly
flushed. The table is littered with an empty pitcher of red wine
she and her guests have polished off, remnants of several small,
smoky, wood-baked pizzas, and Provencal salads. She looks enviably
relaxed and happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How wonderful life turns out,'' she says, ``when you least
expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kathie Alex's Cooking with Friends in France, located in
Chateauneuf de Grasse, costs $1,950 per person, which includes five
classes, accommodation for six nights, and all breakfasts and
lunches. Classes are held May, June, September, October, and
November. For more information, call Jackson &AMP; Co., 617-350-3837.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
OEUFS A LA PIPERADE
</P>
<P>
   (Eggs with red peppers and tomatoes)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded, and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound red peppers, roasted, peeled, seeded, and chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   8 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Fresh basil leaves, chopped (for garnish)
</P>
<P>
   In a large nonstick frying pan over medium-high heat, heat the
olive oil. Add the onion and saute it until limp. Add the garlic
and continue cooking until the onion is a light golden color. Add
the tomatoes, salt, and pepper. Reduce the heat to low, and simmer
for 20 minutes or until tomatoes are softened. Add the peppers and
continue cooking for 10 minutes or until all the liquid has
evaporated from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the mixture from the pan and wipe out the pan. Melt 2
tablespoons of the butter and, before it browns, add the eggs. Cook
them over low heat, stirring with a spoon. After 1 minute, add 1/4
cup of the pepper-tomato mixture. Continue stirring 1 minute more.
Add the remaining 3 tablespoons butter and cook until the eggs are
scrambled but soft. (Save the remaining tomato mixture to use as a
sauce for pasta.) Sprinkle with basil and serve at once. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CROSTINI DE PAIN PERDU AVEC FRUITS DE SAISON
</P>
<P>
   (Crusty brioche with sauteed fruits)
</P>
<P>
   This is a typical cooking-class recipe. The brioche is made into
what we call French toast, known in France as ``pain perdu''
(``lost bread,'' because the bread, generally stale, is useless for
anything else).
</P>
<P>
   For the fruits:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark rum
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 Golden Delicious apples, peeled, cored, and quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 Bartlett pears, peeled, quartered, and cored
</P>
<P>
   1 cup strawberries, halved
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 orange
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   For the bread:
</P>
<P>
   4 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   8 3/4-inch slices of brioche or other egg bread, such as challah
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 stick unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 pint vanilla ice cream, or 1/2 pint heavy cream, whipped
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   For the fruits: In a bowl, soak the currants in the rum for 10
minutes. In a large skillet over medium heat, melt the 4
tablespoons of butter, stir in the 1/2 cup sugar, and cook,
stirring, until the sugar dissolves. Add the apples and pears and
cook them for 15 minutes or until they are soft and golden. Stir in
the currants with the rum, the strawberries, and the orange and
lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Simmer until the liquid reduces by half. Remove the pan from the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   For the bread: In a bowl, beat together the eggs, extra yolks,
and 1 1/2 cups sugar. With a sharp knife, scrape the vanilla seeds
from the bean into the bowl. Add the milk and stir until blended.
Soak each slice of bread for 2 minutes in the egg mixture, then
remove with a slotted spatula and place on a rimmed baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Using a strainer, sift some of the confectioners' sugar over
each slice to cover them evenly.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, melt 4 tablespoons of the butter over medium
heat. Add enough brioche slices, sugared side down, to fill the
pan. Cook them until browned on the bottom. Sift more
confectioners' sugar over the tops, turn, and brown the other side.
Add more butter to the pan if necessary. Remove the slices from the
pan and transfer to a baking sheet. Keep them warm in a low oven.
Repeat with more butter and the remaining slices.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Cut the toast in triangular pieces. Place them on
heated plates and spoon over the warm fruit. Add vanilla ice cream
or whipped cream if you like. Serve at once. Serves 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
