<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POTPIE-RECIPES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potpie perfection? Got it covered
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diane Phillips tested dozens of recipes over a year's time for
her cookbook ``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover, '' (Doubleday,
$24.95). In that same year, her husband gained 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. You won't gain that much, because you probably
won't try 85 different kinds of potpie. But from the recipes below,
we hope you'll add one or two to your dinner rotation.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't made a potpie in a while _ or ever _ start with
the chicken potpie. Don't let the length of the recipe scare you.
It has the kind of details a novice will appreciate, but they are
guidance, not dire warnings.
</P>
<P>
   And if you try these recipes but are just not happy because you
are a double-crust person, then check out the directions for double
crusts on the flaky pie dough recipe. You can even have a pastry
crust on the bottom and one of the more innovative crusts on the
top.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Simple Chicken Potpie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We found this classic, well-tested recipe in a 1996 Cook's
Illustrated. You can make the filling ahead of time and chill it
overnight, then reheat before topping with the crust and baking.
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe Rich Flaky Pie Dough (see below)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds boneless, skinless chicken breasts and/or thighs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups homemade chicken broth or 1 (15-ounce) can low-sodium
chicken broth with water added to equal 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-large onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 medium carrots, peeled and cut crosswise 1/4 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 small celery ribs, cut crosswise 1/4 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup frozen green peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Make pie dough (directions below) and refrigerate until ready to
use. Adjust oven rack to low-center position; preheat oven to 400
degrees. Put chicken and broth in small Dutch oven or soup kettle
over medium heat. Cover and bring to a simmer; simmer until chicken
is just done, 15 to 20 minutes. Transfer meat to large bowl,
reserving broth in measuring cup.
</P>
<P>
   Increase heat to medium-high; heat oil in the empty pan. Add
onion, carrots and celery; saute until just tender, about 5
minutes. Season to taste with salt and pepper. While vegetables are
cooking, shred meat into bite-size pieces. Transfer cooked
vegetables to bowl with chicken; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter over medium-high heat in the empty pan. When foaming
subsides, add flour; cook about 1 minute. Whisk in chicken broth,
milk, any accumulated chicken juices and thyme. Bring to simmer,
then continue to simmer until sauce fully thickens, about 1 minute.
Season to taste with salt and pepper; stir in sherry.
</P>
<P>
   Pour sauce over chicken mixture; stir to combine. Stir in peas
and parsley. Adjust seasonings. (Can be covered and refrigerated
overnight; reheat before topping with pastry.) Pour mixture into
13-by-9-inch pan or any shallow baking dish of similar size. Top
with pie crust (follow directions in pie crust recipe below); bake
until pastry is golden brown and filling is bubbly, about 30
minutes. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 548 calories, 33 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 32 grams carbohydrates, 125
milligrams cholesterol, 339 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   PASTRY
</P>
<P>
   Rich Flaky Pie Dough
</P>
<P>
   Makes one 9-by-13-inch crust
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 30 minutes or more
</P>
<P>
   The crust is the key to a good potpie, and this one can work
well on any recipe. If you like a double crust, then double the
recipe, halve and make two crusts. For the bottom crust, press the
dough into the bottom of a pan and pre-bake for at least 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, chilled and cut into 1/4-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chilled all-vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   Ice water
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour and salt in workbowl of food processor fitted with the
steel blade. Scatter butter pieces over the flour mixture, tossing
to coat butter with a little of the flour. Cut butter into flour
with five one-second pulses. Add shortening; continue cutting in
until flour is pale yellow and resembles coarse cornmeal, keeping
some butter bits the size of small peas, about four more one-second
pulses. Turn mixture into medium bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle 3 tablespoons ice-cold water over the mixture. Using
rubber spatula, fold water into flour mixture. Then press down on
dough mixture with broad side of spatula until dough sticks
together, adding up to 1 tablespoon more cold water if dough will
not come together. Shape dough into ball, then shape into a
rectangle and flatten to about 3/4 inch thick. Wrap in plastic and
refrigerate 30 minutes while preparing pie filling.
</P>
<P>
   Roll dough on floured surface to approximate 15-by-11-inch
rectangle, about 1/8 inch thick. Lay dough over potpie filling.
Tuck edges down into the pan side. Cut at least four 1-inch vent
holes. Proceed with potpie recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 238 calories, 2 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 69), 16 grams carbohydrates, 31
milligrams cholesterol, 150 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mom's Beef Stew
</P>
<P>
   Topped With
</P>
<P>
   Sage Parmesan Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour, 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rich and satisfying, this recipe drew raves from tasters. It
also makes a pretty presentation. It's easy to prepare, and the
stew can be refrigerated overnight.
</P>
<P>
   For the beef stew:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds beef stew meat, cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh sage, or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   3 carrots, cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   2 cups 1-inch potato cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh, or frozen and defrosted, corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh, or frozen and defrosted, petite peas
</P>
<P>
   For the Sage Parmesan Biscuits:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried sage
</P>
<P>
   For the stew: Sprinkle beef with salt, pepper and garlic. In a
3-quart ovenproof casserole or Dutch oven, heat the oil. Add meat,
browning it on all sides for 6 to 8 minutes. When the meat is
browned, add broth, stirring to scrape up any bits that have stuck
to the bottom of the pan. Add sage, carrots and potato cubes. Cover
and simmer 35 minutes. Add corn and peas and continue to cook for
another 10 to 15 minutes. The sauce will appear thin, but it will
thicken when the biscuits bake. (The stew can be refrigerated at
this point for 2 to 3 days, or frozen for up to 2 months. Allow to
come to room temperature before baking.)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the biscuits: In a large mixing bowl, combine Bisquick and
Parmesan cheese. Add milk and sage, stirring with a fork to
combine. Turn the dough out onto a floured board and knead 5 times.
Roll the dough out to 1/2 inch thickness, cut out individual
biscuits with a 2-inch cutter and place on top of stew. Or transfer
the entire crust to the top of the stew, cutting it to fit. Bake
the stew in the preheated oven for 17 to 20 minutes, or until the
biscuits are browned and the stew is bubbling. _ From: ``Pot Pies:
Comfort Food Under Cover,'' Diane Phillips (Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 561 calories, 44 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 30), 52 grams carbohydrates, 96
milligrams cholesterol, 1555 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Seafood Potpie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Because the crusts are baked separately, this is really a faux
potpie. But the end result is the same _ delicious. While the sauce
is stewing, bake the pastry tops. If you want to make this richer,
add a touch of cream to the tomato sauce. If you don't like the
selection of seafood added at the end of the recipe, then add your
preference. You'll need about 1 3/4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt, plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   12 small mussels (8 ounces), debearded and scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 anchovy fillets, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can Italian plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet frozen puff pastry, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow bell pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces wild striped bass, skin removed, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces calamari, cut into rings
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces shrimp, tail on, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces bay scallops
</P>
<P>
   Combine the shallot, wine, salt and water in a medium saucepan
and bring to a simmer. Add the mussels and cook, covered, until the
shells are open, about 2 minutes. Remove the mussels from the shell
and set aside, loosely covered. Discard the shells. Strain the
cooking liquid through double layers of damp cheesecloth, and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a medium straight-sided saute pan over medium
heat. Add the garlic and onion and cook until soft, stirring
occasionally, about 5 minutes. Add anchovies; cook another 2
minutes, stirring. Raise heat to medium-high; add the tomatoes,
breaking them up slightly with the back of a spoon. Add reserved
mussel liquid and red pepper flakes, and cook until the sauce has
thickened, about 25 minutes. Transfer the sauce to a bowl of a food
processor or blender and puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 425 degrees. Place six 6-ounce ramekins on a baking
sheet and set aside. In a small bowl, combine the egg and milk and
set aside. Lay the puff pastry on a clean surface. Using a round
cookie cutter or the rim of a glass, cut out six pastry rounds a
bit larger than the rims of the ramekins. Place pastry on
parchment-lined baking sheet; brush with egg wash. Bake until
golden brown and puffed, 9 to 12 minutes. Set aside in a warm
place.
</P>
<P>
   Return sauce to saute pan; stir in yellow peppers, thyme and
parsley. Season with salt and pepper. Stir in all seafood;
distribute mixture evenly among ramekins. Place on a baking sheet;
bake until juicy and bubbling, 15 to 20 minutes. Place a round of
puff pastry on top of each cup and serve immediately. _ From:
``Favorite Comfort Foods: The Best of Martha Stewart Living''
(Clarkson Potter, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 404 calories, 33 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 19 grams carbohydrates, 263
milligrams cholesterol, 1,465 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Lamb Pie
</P>
<P>
   With Goat Cheese
</P>
<P>
   Mashed Potato Crust
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd's pie, with its mashed potato crust, is in the potpie
family. Here, goat cheese gives the mashed potatoes an edge.
Cooking time is based on potatoes that are mashed and ready to go
(deli mashed potatoes could be a timesaver).
</P>
<P>
   For the lamb filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boneless lamb, cut in 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup 1/2-inch-thick onion slices
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   For the mashed potato crust:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 to 4 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   To finish:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: In 5-quart Dutch oven, heat oil. In small bowl,
combine flour, salt and pepper. Toss lamb cubes in mixture, then
brown meat in hot oil, a few pieces at a time, about 6 to 8 minutes
per batch. (You can use two pans at a time to speed browning, then
combine in the Dutch oven.) When the lamb is browned, add the onion
and garlic and saute until the vegetables are soft, about 3 to 4
minutes. Pour in the wine and scrape up any browned bits that may
be stuck to the bottom of the pan. Add the broth, thyme and bay
leaf, stirring the sauce. Cover the pan and bake in the preheated
oven for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the crust: Place the potatoes in a mixing bowl and beat in
the goat cheese, thinning the mixture with the milk. Keep a fairly
stiff consistency. Remove the lamb stew from the oven and remove
the bay leaf. Remove the lamb and onions from the pot and put in
small bowl and set aside. Put pan on stove over medium-high heat
and boil the mixture to reduce it by one-third. Return the lamb and
onions to the pan. Spread the potatoes over the stew and dot the
top with butter. Bake uncovered for an additional 20 minutes. _
From: ``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover,'' Diane Phillips
(Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 526 calories, 38 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 33 grams carbohydrates, 124
milligrams cholesterol, 1,021 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Easy Taco Potpie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Easy is the operative word here. Quick comes in a close second.
You can make this on any busy weeknight and your family will thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped (about 1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 (16-ounce) jar taco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (4 ounces) shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Bisquick baking mix
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cook beef and onion in ovenproof 10-inch skillet over medium
heat, stirring occasionally, until beef is brown; drain. Stir in
taco sauce. Sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, stir together the Bisquick baking mix, milk
and egg until blended. Pour over beef mixture. Bake about 30
minutes or until golden brown. _ From: www.bettycrocker.com
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 379 calories, 25 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 22 grams carbohydrates, 115
milligrams cholesterol, 783 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Turkey Squash Pie
</P>
<P>
   With White Cheddar
</P>
<P>
   and Bacon Crust
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ideal for leftover turkey and corn bread, this potpie gets an
extra flavor punch from bacon, sage and white cheddar. You can add
a touch of cream for a thicker, richer sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For the turkey squash filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 small zucchini, cut into 1/2-inch-thick rounds
</P>
<P>
   3 small yellow squash, cut into 1/2-inch-thick chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped carrot
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked turkey or chicken meat, cut into bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped fresh sage, or 1/2 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   For the white cheddar and bacon crust:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped green onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cups crumbled corn bread
</P>
<P>
   8 slices bacon, cooked, drained and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly grated white cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken broth, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: In a 4-quart saucepan, melt the butter and add
the zucchini, squash and carrot. Saute the vegetables for 2
minutes, then sprinkle with the flour. Stir the mixture until the
flour begins to bubble. Whisk in the broth and stir until the sauce
is thick and smooth, about 4 to 6 minutes. Stir in the turkey or
chicken, salt, pepper and sage. Transfer the mixture to a 3-quart
ovenproof baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the crust: In a saute pan, heat the butter and add the green
onion. Saute for 2 minutes, until the onion begins to soften. Place
the corn bread in a large mixing bowl. Transfer the onion-butter
mixture to the bowl along with the bacon and cheddar cheese.
Drizzle some of the broth over the corn bread to moisten it. When
the mixture is crumbly, sprinkle it over the turkey in the baking
dish.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the pie for 30 minutes, until it is browned and bubbling.
Remove from oven and allow to sit for 10 minutes, and then serve. _
From: ``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover,'' Diane Phillips
(Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 537 calories, 38 grams protein, 31 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 24 grams carbohydrates, 150
milligrams cholesterol, 1,154 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini Pie With
</P>
<P>
   Parmesan Rice Crust
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   OK. This one stretches the definition of potpie. Some might
argue it's more like a casserole. But it was so delicious, we had
to run the recipe no matter what it's called. You can substitute
brown rice for white for a nuttier flavor. Just increase the
cooking time by 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups (about 2 1/2 pounds) grated zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 shakes Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Spray a 13-by-9-inch ovenproof
baking dish with nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   In a saute pan, melt the butter; add onion and garlic and cook,
stirring, until the onion is softened, about 2 to 3 minutes. Add
zucchini and cook until it is no longer giving off moisture, about
4 to 6 minutes. Season with salt, pepper and Tabasco. Sprinkle with
flour and cook, whisking for 2 minutes. Gradually stir in the
broth, whisking until smooth. Add the cream and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the zucchini mixture into the casserole dish. Sprinkle with
the rice, then the cheese. Bake for 25 to 35 minutes, until the
rice is tender and the cheese is golden. _ From: ``Pot Pies:
Comfort Food Under Cover,'' Diane Phillips (Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 211 calories, 6 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 19 grams carbohydrates, 38
milligrams cholesterol, 827 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
