<HEADER>
A7572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      03-15 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH RISK ISN'T ANSWER FOR NONPERFORMING BANK FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I enjoyed your rant about buying mutual funds at banks. Even
though I had been warned not to, I bought mutual funds through two
local banks. Each sold me the worst fund from the fund family
involved. Neither one said a word about what happens if the fund
turns out to be a dog, let alone a super dog. They just collected
fees for services not rendered _ a total of $430. I don't know if
they are irresponsible nitwits or just enjoy cheating old people.
Most inexperienced investors have no idea they can transfer money
from a bad fund to a good one. Shouldn't people receive some kind
of information for the fees they pay? A friend bought $30,000 worth
of mutual funds at a bank after he had lost $9,000 at a different
one. Needless to say, he won't be making many trips to Cancun with
the profits.
</P>
<P>
   My money is now in the funds listed above. I hope you are wrong
about the days of double-digit returns being numbered. I'd like to
get back some of the money I've lost in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   J.C., Umatilla, Ore. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I agree, it's risky to buy funds at banks, where the adviser
sometimes appears to know little more about investing than the
customer. But it's also a risky to scan the offerings within any
fund family and put your money into the fund or funds that show up
at the top of the recent performance list. Following that approach,
you usually end up buying funds that invest in the riskier sectors
of the market, and those whose risks have been rewarded by hot
current markets.
</P>
<P>
   It's dizzying to look at a record such as the 146.2 percent 1999
advance of Invesco Technology I (and the 47.76 percent gain so far
this year). But figures such as those can also be interpreted to
mean that the prices are pretty overblown by now. Note, for
example, the 56.6 percent portfolio average price-to-earnings ratio
for the same fund, 150 percent of that of the Standard and Poor's
500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to have some funds like that _ they supply the spice,
the potential for big wins. But such funds also bring the potential
for big losses.
</P>
<P>
   Your portfolio is like a meal that begins with a brownie,
progresses to a slice of chocolate layer cake, and finishes with
cherries jubilee. You're taking on a lot of risk _ a very great
deal of risk.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the bank's sales people didn't do all that
horribly by you. You don't specify your age. So they probably
pushed the traditional button, choosing bond funds that would
supply you with a good income stream. Alas, with rising interest
rates and the prospect for more ahead, the last couple of years
have been terrible ones for bond and bond fund owners, and when you
look at the offerings of various fund families, the recent returns
almost invariably show the long bond funds at the bottom of the
list. That doesn't make them the worst funds in a family. It simply
means they are, by charter, obligated to invest the owners' money
in a market category that has been taking a pasting.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock side, you can say the same for value-oriented
funds. I'll bet bucks to bananas that if you look at the 10-year
results of these funds, they are quite respectable. Bond funds do
work for retired people, but you must have the stamina to ride out
the inevitable slumps in the bond market and take a decade-long
perspective on your investment.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is that you abandon your attempt to make up your
losses with the very aggressive portfolio you have chosen. At the
very minimum, I suggest you put at least half of your money in
traditional and proven funds, such as Janus fund and Fidelity
Puritan fund. And I'd be happy if you moved another quarter of your
portfolio into a solid fixed-income fund such as Fidelity GNMA. You
could then spread the final quarter among your favorites of the
high-fliers that you now hold. Such a portfolio might not take you
to the luxury suites at Cancun all that quickly, but it would bode
fair to keep you off Skid Row.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband is taking early retirement; I expect to work until
age 67. My 401(k) plan at work will be our major supplement to our
retirement income. With 13 more years to contribute and with
additions of about $6,000 a year, how much can I reasonably expect
to have when I retire? We have 25 years to go on a 30-year mortgage
at 9 percent, with a balance of about $146,000. If we pay an extra
$100 a month against the principal, how much sooner can I expect to
pay off the mortgage? What computer program would I need to make
similar calculations myself?
</P>
<P>
   A.K., Buena Park, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you add $500 a month to your 401(k) program for 13 years,
and if you achieve average market returns of 10 percent, you would
amass $357,480 at the end of the period. Given your current
holdings and allocations, I think that's a reasonable expectation.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mortgage, I estimate your current payment is $1,189 _
a figure unlikely to be precise but probably pretty close. If you
added $100 to each monthly payment, you would cut five years and
five months from the payment schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those calculations were made with a computer program
called Interest Vision Special Edition, which I got free from
Parsons Technology Inc. many years ago. I subsequently purchased
Interest Vision Professional from the same company but found the
enhancements so insubstantial that I rarely use it. Parsons' Web
address is www.parsonstech.com, but I had a terrible time locating
the product, and found it only after doing a Google search under
Interest Vision, where it popped right up. Interest Vision 2.0
(which is newer than the Interest Vision Professional version that
underwhelmed me) costs $24.95. I haven't tried the 2.0 version, but
it should do the job my software does plus a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: While we're in this vein, does anybody know of a
program for calculating the effects of projected inflation at
various rates and over various time periods? I use one at the
Merrill Lynch Web site, but would love to find a similar product I
could download and use offline. The Merill Lynch calculator can be
found at: www.ml.com/family/inflation-calc.html
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
