A7569 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-POTPIE16-COX     03-15 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POTPIE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potpie, the ultimate comfort food
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a cold, everyone knows chicken soup with noodles and a
clear, soothing broth restores.
</P>
<P>
   But for pure comfort, creamy chicken and vegetables under a
blanket of flaky pie crust is what the soul really desires.
</P>
<P>
   Potpies are popular again. There they are on the April cover of
Food &AMP; Wine magazine and in Martha Stewart's ``Favorite Comfort
Foods,'' (Clarkson Potter, $22.) Potpies also are featured on the
new menu for Northwest Airlines _ first class, no less.
</P>
<P>
   And cookbook author Diane Phillips has written a whole book
devoted to them _ ``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover''
(Doubleday, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to beg my parents to go out so we could have a
babysitter, because she always gave us Swanson's potpies,'' said
Phillips. Such nostalgia is behind the comfort food craze in
general and the return of potpies in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with all the fears about Y2K and a new age, many of us
wanted to go back to what's comfortable,'' Phillips said. ``We want
to make our homes a center for our family. And there's nothing that
makes you feel better than coming home after a long day to the
aroma of a potpie.''
</P>
<P>
   To create that comfy scene on a weeknight, get a head start. The
night before, roast the meat and prepare the crust. You can get two
meals for one if you serve roasted chicken and vegetables with
biscuits one night, then convert the leftovers into a potpie the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a great vehicle to stretch your food dollar,'' said
Phillips. ``If you have two cups of chicken leftovers and some
biscuits or chive mashed potatoes, you've got a meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Or while you are eating dinner the first night, pop a turkey or
chicken breast in the oven along with a batch of corn bread.
They'll be ready for assembly on the second night, and you'll have
a potpie in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   There are even shorter cuts _ precooked chicken, turkey or ham
and frozen puff pastry or phyllo dough or refrigerated biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   It's that versatility that makes potpies a good family meal.
``If you don't have all the ingredients a recipe calls for, don't
let that stop you,'' Phillips said. ``Go ahead and make a potpie
with what you have in the pantry or freezer.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips prefers to put a crust on the top only for ease and
because bottom crusts get soggy. And while a pastry crust is the
classic, crusts of bread crumbs, corn bread, mashed potatoes or
biscuits all work beautifully. Seasonings like chives, pesto and
rosemary can really fancy up a crust. To stretch the concept even
further, Phillips experimented with vegetable toppings such as
pureed beans.
</P>
<P>
   Fillings can be innovative, too. Everything from steak to
monkfish can be sauced and blanketed. Inside we offer a classic
chicken potpie, a hearty beef stew pie, spicy seafood topped with
puff pastry and an easy taco pie that's a busy weeknight delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a meal you can put on the table in under an hour,''
said Phillips. ``And you can have a good time doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKE IT UP AS YOU GO WITH CREATIVE COMBOS
</P>
<P>
   All it takes to create a potpie is imagination. After trying the
recipes inside, consider mixing and matching these options. Combine
meat and vegetables with thickened stock or sauce. Then top with
your choice of blankets.
</P>
<P>
   FILLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Turkey or chicken and gravy
</P>
<P>
   Chili
</P>
<P>
   Beef or lamb stew
</P>
<P>
   Pot roast
</P>
<P>
   Gumbo
</P>
<P>
   Bouillabaisse
</P>
<P>
   Ham in cheese sauce
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue
</P>
<P>
   Ratatouille
</P>
<P>
   TOPPINGS
</P>
<P>
   Pie crust
</P>
<P>
   Crumbled corn bread
</P>
<P>
   Herbed bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   (plain or with cheese
</P>
<P>
   or herbs)
</P>
<P>
   Mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Polenta
</P>
<P>
   Pureed beans
</P>
<P>
   Puff pastry
</P>
<P>
   Phyllo dough
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
