<HEADER>
A7576 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-15 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON 5, CONTINUED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Not everyone wants to be an ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, I wrote about how James Daley, the former owner of
the Copley Plaza hotel, had bought himself a nomination as
ambassador to the Eastern Caribbean. The price: $271,000 in
campaign donations to President Clinton and the Democrats since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is part of the Boston Five, Clinton's own Boston bank of
five deep-pocketed contributors he has turned to time and again,
most recently to write big checks to fund his legacy and
presidential library. Which got me wondering: If Daley gets to cash
out as Ambassador Deluxe, what about the rest of the Boston Five?
</P>
<P>
   At 52, Jack Manning, chief executive of Boston Capital Corp., is
too young to cash out. But he and his fabulously successful
investment firm may be in line to cash in. The immediate goal: an
exclusive contract to build housing for the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story.
</P>
<P>
   The military, at the prodding of Congress, has turned to
privatization _ hasn't everyone? _ as the answer to rebuilding the
decrepit housing on bases around the country. With the military in
need of more than 200,000 new or renovated units, the initative
could be a gold mine for private developers while saving the
government billions by getting it out of the housing business. But
five years after it was authorized, virtually nothing has been
done; a congressional hearing this week is asking why.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Capital wants a piece of the action. The firm is one of
the biggest owners of affordable housing, with 110,000 apartments
nationwide. With money for affordable housing slowing down, the
chance to rebuild the nation's military housing is just too good to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Capital is starting with the Air Force. In particular,
the firm is going after a pilot program to build 550 houses and
town houses on Florida's Patrick Air Force Base near Cape
Canaveral. But that could only be the beginning: Manning estimates
the Air Force alone needs 60,000 units of housing, costing maybe
$10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The base had been proceeding on a traditional competitive
bidding process until recently, when Boston Capital made what
Manning calls ``an unsolicited proposal.'' The Air Force listened
and has deferred the bidding process to allow Boston Capital to
make an exclusive proposal. Why? ``That decision was made at the
Pentagon level,'' says Ken Warren, a spokesman for the base.
</P>
<P>
   Manning says this is far from a done deal. If the Air Force does
not like Boston Capital's proposal it can still put the contract
out for bid. He says Boston Capital must pick up all expenses. ``We
are doing this without a net,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not doing it without friends. Manning is one of the
most prominent FOBs in Boston, holding a $25,000-a-pop reception
for the president at his Back Bay home and golfing with Clinton and
John Kerry in Edgartown. When Clinton summoned his most faithful
contributors to his Park Plaza suite in January, Manning was there
with the rest of the Boston Five.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Capital, in fact, is well wired on both sides of the
aisle. Since 1991, Boston Capital and its top executives (and
Manning's wife's own firm) have given nearly $1 million to the
Democrats, according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
Meanwhile, Boston Capital chairman Herbert F. Collins and other
executives have contributed about $465,000 to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no politics involved at all,'' Manning says.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Jim Daley would say, too. And they may be right, of
course. Maybe the only return on their investment these businessmen
were expecting was a good government, a good economy, and a good
round of golf with the president. But when the numbers get so huge
who is going to believe it _ and isn't that just the problem with
our current campaign finance system?
</P>
<P>
   If Alan Solomont, Howard Kessler, or Fred Seigel _ the rest of
the Boston Five _ turn up with another ambassadorship or another
exclusive contract, let's just say we will not be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can reach me at (617) 929-2902 or bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
