<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX     03-15 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-first lady's strawberry dish takes the cake
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Several readers came to Charles Spraggins' aid when he
asked for Rosalynn Carter's ``strawberry poundcake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While not a true poundcake, this may be the recipe,'' wrote
Martha Pierce of Jasper, Ga. ``Moist and delicious, it is
wonderfully easy to assemble for all of us busy bakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipe from the former first lady has been widely published
in community newspapers and cookbooks, including ``Plains
Pot-Pourri,'' ``Something Southern'' and ``Enotah Edibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the strawberry flavor and pink color are intense.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 package (18 1/4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   yellow or white cake mix
</P>
<P>
   1 (3-ounce) package
</P>
<P>
   strawberry gelatin
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package frozen strawberries or 1 pint fresh
strawberries mashed with
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Coat the inside of a 10-inch tube
pan with cooking spray and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine all ingredients except nuts,
then stir in nuts. Mix all ingredients and beat well; pour into
prepared pan. Bake about 45 minutes or until a tester inserted near
center of cake comes out clean. Serve plain or with whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 476 calories, 8 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 51 grams carbohydrates, 107
milligrams cholesterol, 327 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Request
</P>
<P>
   Ken Taddeo of Marietta, Ga., wants a recipe for the Italian
bread ciabatta, his family's weekend favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Published recipes
</P>
<P>
   To request copies of recipes published in the newspaper, call
The Stacks at 404-526-5668.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
