<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-YALE-STARTUPS-BOS &LR;      03-15 1818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YALE-STARTUPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE START-UPS BOOST NEW HAVEN AS MAJOR BIOMEDICAL CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Alfred ``Buz'' Brown is every bit the tour
guide.
</P>
<P>
   To persuade the founder of a biotechnology start-up to locate
his company in this city, home of Yale University, Brown drove him
around some tony nearby suburbs where the entrepreneur's family
might live. He told him that more than 90 percent of local students
go to good public schools and that property values are high and
taxes reasonable. In the town of Madison, Brown crowed, residents
pay only $30 a year to use the Surf Club, the posh town-owned beach
on Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot: William Rice decided to start his company, Achillion
Pharmaceuticals Inc., in downtown New Haven, just a block from Yale
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buz did a sales job on me and said so up front,'' Rice
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Brown isn't a salesman, real estate agent, or even a
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   He is director of Yale's Office of Cooperative Research, which
besides licensing technology developed at the school has recently
gotten into the start-up game. That includes finding entrepreneurs,
helping to write business plans, and arranging financing _ services
Ivy League universities rarely provide to industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``MIT and Stanford would never do this,'' chuckled Brown. ``But
then they don't need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Stanford
University, which have spawned bicoastal high-technology meccas
over the past 30 years, Yale is a late bloomer in fostering
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   But now, New Haven, long known for its declining economic base,
is getting a shot in the arm with the blossoming of a biotechnology
industry spurred by Yale's research and fed by close ties to the
299-year-old university, the nation's third-oldest.
</P>
<P>
   In the emergence of biotech in New Haven, Yale serves as a
catalyst, in much the same way that universities have always spun
off technology and ideas through ties with private industry and the
commercialization of university research.
</P>
<P>
   Only within the last 4 1/2 years has Yale, the Ivy League
university that dominates New Haven, begun to come down from its
ivory tower and recognize the importance of economic development
near the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Yale has gone from an insular focus on basic research to
``acknowledging in the early 1990s that there are exciting
commercial opportunities'' in biotechnology and information
technology, said Leonard Bell, a former Yale professor who is
founder and chief executive of Alexion Pharmaceuticals Inc., one of
the oldest and largest New Haven-based biopharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic change began under longtime faculty member Richard
C. Levin, who has been Yale's president since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Levin announced plans to spend $500 million on
university biomedical programs aimed at turning New Haven into a
major biomedical center over the next 10 years. He also committed
another $500 million to promote basic science, engineering, and
clinical research programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those funds will be used to build laboratory facilities
near New Haven's Science Park, an aging industrial park with a
troubled history that is home to a handful of companies started
with technology developed at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Greater New Haven is home to 15 biotech- and
bioscience-related companies employing about 800 people in
high-paying, skilled jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That's equivalent to just a small office park in Massachusetts,
where the Cambridge-to-Worcester corridor is home to more than 120
biotechnology companies that employ more than 13,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this first wave of New Haven companies in biotech and
genomics _ the study of genes for targeting the cause of diseases _
represents a nascent industry that could help New Haven stem a
brain drain of technical and professional workers.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven's bioscience growth, however, could pose problems for
some Massachusetts companies in the competition to hire young,
educated employees. With its college-town amenities, lower housing
costs, and promixity to New York City (a 90-minute drive), New
Haven can be alluring to young professionals, the city's boosters
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really not competing with Cambridge, but for young
researchers looking for jobs, this area now offers an
alternative,'' said E. Jonathan Soderstrom, managing director of
Yale's Office of Cooperative Research.
</P>
<P>
   To promote economic development, Yale has been stepping up its
activity with business start-ups since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, Soderstrom's office has launched
technology transfer practices aimed at bringing the university's
discoveries to private industry, particularly near the campus.
</P>
<P>
   And while the strategy fosters economic development and job
creation, it's also designed to attract and retain Yale faculty
members who are looking for commercial outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Yale receives stock for helping to launch start-ups
and cash for multiyear licensing of university-developed
technology. Last year, Yale received $40.7 million in license
revenue, an eightfold increase over the $5 million it reported in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Soderstrom said his office launches three to four companies per
year.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is PhytoCeutica Inc., a company involved in herbal
drug discovery and founded with research from Yung-Chi Cheng, a
Yale professor.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng is also the faculty founder of Achillion, which is
developing a drug to treat the AIDS virus and hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
   Yale's bioscience efforts are getting a boost from several other
sources. These include venture capitalists from New York and
Boston, who routinely visit New Haven, and Connecticut Innovations,
a quasipublic agency that provides equity financing and manages the
state's $30 million in facility improvement loans to young
companies. Ten-year-old Connecticut Innovations has been providing
financing for biotech and genomics companies for several years.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Connecticut Innovations has spent nearly $16 million on
developing laboratory space for eight companies and nearly $7.6
million has been invested in six New Haven-area biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   The largest investment, $4.8 million, went to Genaissance
Pharmaceuticals Inc., which helps drug makers tailor medications to
an individual's genetic makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is to achieve a critical mass of 30 or so companies
in the greater New Haven area within the next five years,'' said
Victor R. Budnick, president and executive director of Connecticut
Innovations. The agency's mission is similar to that of the
Boston-based Massachusetts Technology Development Corp., which has
helped back a burgeoning group of Route 128 companies over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Originally started from the proceeds of state bond funds,
Connecticut Innovations is now self-sustaining, thanks in part to a
wildly successul bet on CuraGen Corp., New Haven's most successful
publicly traded biotech firm, which was formed with technology
licensed by Yale. Connecticut Innovations' $600,000 investment in
CuraGen is worth more than $20 million following a recent 2-1 stock
split.
</P>
<P>
   CuraGen, a genomics company founded in the basement of Yale
scientist Jonathan Rothberg in 1993, is using biology and
information technology for drug discovery. In its posh headquarters
overlooking Long Island Sound, where the quiet is broken only by
the humming of machines that analyze DNA, CuraGen is developing
technology to predict which drugs will cause toxic side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-employee company, which competes with Millennium
Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Cambridge, tracks how drugs affect genes in
human tissue, particularly cells from the liver, kidney, and heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the right place at the right time, and we are seeing
a lot of interest by the state, Yale, and investors that was just
not there when I first started CuraGen,'' said Rothberg, who grew
up in New Haven and holds a doctorate in molecular biology from
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   The largest concentration of biotech and genomics companies is
in Science Park, in a bleak industrial area bounded on one side by
Yale Divinity School and on another by some of the poorest sections
of New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies in the park occupy buildings that once
turned out Winchester rifles and ammunition for U.S. Repeating Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to make shell casings here,'' said Richard S.
Judson, vice president of informatics for Genaissance
Pharmaceuticals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In an airy, brightly lit converted factory, Genaissance uses
rows of high-speed machines to decode human and chimpanzee DNA in
order to help drug makers design more effective medicines tailored
to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The science park was started 17 years ago as something of a
social experiment _ to provide the community with jobs in high-tech
fields. But over the years, the park deteriorated, getting a cold
shoulder from businesses and little attention from civic leaders.
It was also beset by vandals. In the last five years, the park has
begun a turnaround, attracting bioscience companies.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the industrial park will depend on whether it can
continue to attract biotech start-ups and build new facilities,
including a cafeteria and health club, said Alan Kessman. He is
president of Vion Pharmaceuticals Inc., a Science Park tenant
that's developing anticancer drugs, using technology licensed by
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science Park may thrive if it becomes more employee
friendly,'' he added. ``There also has to be more laboratory
space,'' he said, referring to a shortage of such facilities in New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Carter J. Winstanley hopes to alleviate the shortage. He is
managing partner in a family-owned business in Concord, Mass., that
last month acquired a 550,000-square-foot building in downtown New
Haven. A block from the medical school, this former phone company
building will house Achillion and three other companies this year.
The nine-story facility, with paint peeling from the exterior, is
already outfitted with fiber-optic communication systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning a combination of laboratory space for biotech
start-ups and offices for information technology and
telecommunications start-ups,'' Winstanley said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are few critics of New Haven's growth, not everyone
is convinced that Yale's betting on entrepreneurs is the best
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university has realized that good ideas come from the
young start-ups, but we are reaching a transition point where Yale
must appeal to more experienced business-savvy companies rather
than rely on small players,'' said Gualberto Ruano, the founder and
chief executive of Genaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love New Haven and Science Park, and bioscience is here to
stay. But we are reaching the point where Yale needs to go beyond a
dependence on small start-ups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
