<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 DESPITE GOOD TIMES, JOBS STILL ELUDE SOME
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The letter was short and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, a middle-aged Massachusetts man who had obtained a
master's degree in criminal justice but had yet to find a
professional position in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite talk that a booming economy and a labor shortage have
created more job vacancies than employers can fill, the letter
writer felt he had been left out of the equation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Diane, I continuously read in The Boston Globe and trade
magazines how tight the labor market is throughout the United
States; how employers are offering free training and hiring bonuses
for new applicants. Am I missing something?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last May, I graduated from Suffolk University with a master's
of science degree in criminal justice. Since that time, I have
actively pursued job opportunities in that profession. I have
attended career counseling seminars, searched the Internet, spoken
with politicians, and networked at seminars sponsored by criminal
justice organizations. Unfortunately, my job search has not been
successful . . . sometimes I think I'm overqualified. Any
suggestions?'' (K.H.)
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, K.H. described himself as a
blue-collar worker who had delayed going to college for several
years after graduating high school. After obtaining a bachelor's
degree, he worked as a security guard while pursuing a master's. He
had assumed an advanced degree in criminal justice would help him
secure a position as a probation or parole officer.
</P>
<P>
   K.H. felt deceived. In the past, an uncle or father or brother
could get you a position, he said. But what happens when you don't
have those contacts?
</P>
<P>
   Because people move around so much, many of those old networks
or ties have been severed. As a result, colleges and universities
are expected to reach out to prospective employers. Certainly, they
cannot guarantee a job.
</P>
<P>
   I contacted Suffolk University's career placement office. Paul
Tanklefsky, director of career services and cooperative education,
said the university offers lifetime career assistance at not cost
to alumni, and suggested that K.H. come in. ``We are more than
willing to work with students and graduates to help them get to
where they want to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior employment specialist George Zeller said K.H. should look
more closely at his job search strategies and ``attack'' the hidden
job market. ``He should try speaking directly to people who
graduated from that program five to 10 years ago,'' he said.
``These people can keep their eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, he should look at organizations that have hired
graduates from the program in the past. Call those firms; bypass
the human resources person, and go directly to a manager or
supervisor in charge of hiring.'' The names of hiring managers
should be available at Suffolk's career center.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, K.H. may be competing against people in their 20s
and 30s with more experience. How to get around that? ``He should
say straight out that he is looking for an opportunity, an
entry-level position that permits advancement,'' noted Zeller, of
Jewish Vocational Services, which offers counseling and job search
assistance. ``He may need two resumes: one for a higher position
and one for situations where the employer is likely to assume that
the advanced degree makes him too qualified or too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reader wrote: ``I am one of those legions of people on
the outside looking in. I see that you mentioned (in another
column) a team that helps the Commonwealth's pink-slipped legions
regain their footing, remake their lives, and find new work. How
can I contact them? Do they help writers, like myself, find new
work? A phone number or a contact would be extremely helpful.
Freelancing . . . doesn't pay the bills.'' _ N.B.
</P>
<P>
   These readers are hardly the first to question whether an
ongoing labor shortage is benefiting all members of the nation's
work force. Such cynicism, though based solely on personal
experience, is justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the economy is operating at full employment levels and,
among college graduates, the rate of unemployment is extremely
low,'' noted Paul Harrington, an economist at Northeastern
University's Center for Labor Market Studies.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not true for all graduates, he added. The highest
rate of demand continues to be for graduates with business degrees
or science and technical backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   So what does this mean for all the other college graduates?
Often, it means underemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 10 years, the fastest-growing sector of the work
force is expected to be the service industry. So there is a paradox
here, since demand will continue to be concentrated in the two
opposite poles of the employment line _ the sciences and high-tech
sector at the top, and low-wage retail jobs at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   So pronounced is this growth that of the 20.3 million jobs to be
added to the US work force between 1998 and 2008, 19.1 million of
them will be service producing, according to the federal
government. By 2008, service sector jobs will account for three out
of every four US jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said even though the overall unemployment rate for
all college graduates is below 2 percent and will probably remain
low, underemployment continues to be a problem for these workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still substantial numbers of college graduates who
are employed outside their fields of study or in jobs that do not
require a college education, or low-paying jobs,'' he said. ``In
any given year, 10 to 15 percent of all college graduates are in
positions that typically do not require a college degree.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Get trained in an area where demand is high.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, a number of universities have targeted
new programs to such employees. Boston University, Worcester
Polytechnic Institute, and Northeastern each have programs that
help people in nontechnical fields find work in information
technology-related fields, where jobs are plentiful, wages are
good, and demand is expected to increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there is a huge shortage of skilled people to
work in the IT world, and so we got together with people in the
industry and asked how we could design a program that would suit
both their needs and a college graduate's needs,'' said Susan K.
Moulton, director of corporate outreach at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Information Networks Professional Program, this
training is being offered during the day. The 25-week program
begins May 22, three days a week at the Burlington campus, from 9
a.m. to 1 p.m. The cost: $10,000. However, financial aid is
available. There is also an evening program for people in the
industry who wish to keep their skills up to date.
</P>
<P>
   The networks program also offers a seven-week primer for those
who know nothing about computers but wish to break into the field.
Moulton calls it a ``jump-start primer.'' This training begins
March 27 in Burlington. Moulton said last week that upon completion
of the training, participants will be placed in internships and
will receive help with the job search. ``We have an advisory
committee made up of companies that will be eager to find out who
these folks are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One new training program, Aquent SpringBoard (www
</P>
<P>
   .aquent.com), is being offered free by Aquent, a Boston IT and
computer graphics and design staffing firm with offices around the
country. Like many other US firms, Aquent is facing increased
demand for information technology professionals but is finding few
qualified takers in a field where unemployment is a scant 1.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aquent screens applicants and then it picks 24 people for two
separate monthly training sessions,'' said Mariela Azcuy, a company
spokeswoman. ``The company will fly them to Boston if they are from
out of town and will house and feed them. During the training
period, they receive intensive instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they graduate, Aquent places them in a job and they are
required to stay with Aquent for at least six months,'' she
continued. ``After that, they can continue to work through Aquent
or they can go out on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Azcuy says pay varies from $25,000 to $50,000 or more for those
with the right skills. Will such training help reader number two
land a permament job? I can't say. It might help him get his foot
in the door. But once there, it will probably take more training to
advance.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis can be reached at 617-929-2069 or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
