</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MAGAZINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS MAGAZINES TAP A NEW MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March is a big month for women's sports, and a good time to find
out whether women's sports magazines will finally take off.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA women's basketball tournament and high school
tournaments are played this month, and women's hockey teams compete
for championships. March also marks the start of six other sports
played in college and by some high schools _ softball, crew,
lacrosse, track, golf, and tennis. And women, much like men, are
gearing up for the warmer months of the year, concerned about
shaping up for a more active existence.
</P>
<P>
   After testing the market for two years and being placed on hold
temporarily, Time Inc. chose to begin publishing Sports Illustrated
for Women on a bi-monthly basis beginning with the March/April
edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout 1998 we did a lot of focus groups, a lot of
research and we studied a lot of e-mail that came in after our two
test issues were published in 1997,'' said the editor, Sandy
Bailey. ``The common denominator for the women who read us most was
that they played sports, they weren't just spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just, `I want to read a great big story about a
star athlete. It was, `I'd read it if it was inspirational to me,
and motivated me to do my sport.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the results in circulation and advertising, Sports
Illustrated for Women eventually might be published monthly or 10
times per year.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the bi-monthly launch, now on the newsstands,
features Anna Kournikova, in a photographic expression of what
Sports Illustrated for Women strives to be about: providing
information on training for athletes, equipment, nutrition, health,
fashion, and beauty.
</P>
<P>
   So do not expect to read about Kournikova's trials and
tribulations as one of the Top 10 money winners on the WTA tour
last year, and certainly nothing about her engagement to the NHL
star Pavel Bure. Instead, Kournikova joins four other prominent
women athletes _ the LPGA's Kelli Kuehne, Olympic sprinter Inger
Miller, cyclist Alison Dunlap and Olympic swimmer Jenny Thompson _
in offering tips about workouts geared specifically for
participants in their sports.
</P>
<P>
   Although the issue features a report on figure-skating gold
medalist Tara Lipinski's fledgling career as an actress, the piece
deals largely with the motivational and emotional aspects of her
twin pursuits and how they compare, while discounting some of the
more gossipy angles of a prominent life in sports and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our target is the 18- to 34-year-old woman, even younger, say
a 16- or 17-year-old preparing for college, who is interested in
sports as a participant,'' Bailey said. ``As we did all of the
testing and research, what we realized is that no one else was
really doing a book like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The planning for Sports Illustrated for Women actually began in
1996. The two test issues were published in 1997. But then the
concept was then shelved throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of SI changed. Don Elliman moved on and Mike
Klingensmith came in from Entertainment Weekly,'' said Bailey,
explaining the delay. ``But perhaps the biggest factor was the
startup of ESPN The Magazine, and the need for us at SI to really
concentrate on the core SI.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, the wait was probably a good thing. We were not
nearly as focused on what Sports Illustrated for Women was, and how
we are different from the men's magazine, as we are now,
certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the success of the WNBA and the breakthrough of women's
team sports spurred last summer by the Women's World Cup, the
concept for the magazine was pulled off the shelf for four
``special editions'' published in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers that are indicators of success for us are all
strongly positive, and even stronger since 1999,'' Bailey said.
``Now, one out of every two and a half women played a varsity sport
in high school. When we started the planning in 1996, it was one
out of three. That compares to back in 1971 when it was one out of
27.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Sports Illustrated for Women taken the bi-monthly
plunge, the circulation of a competitor, Conde Nast's Women's
Sports &AMP; Fitness, has jumped from 475,000 in January 1999 to
650,000 this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the largest percentage increase of any Conde Nast
publication in the past eight years,'' said Mistrella Egan, its
director of public relations. ``Women's sports are getting more
attention than ever, and we reap the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we changed our title in June 1998 and added the word
fitness, it really helped us take off. Women really identify with
fitness and they see fitness and sport as one in the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, smaller publication, Amy Love's Real Sports circulates
bimonthly to about 150,000 readers nationwide. Based in San Jose,
Calif., it is part of the ADL, Inc. publishing group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically just the three of us, nationally,'' Love said.
``And we all have different approaches to women's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the magazines can survive is an open question,
considering that they still need to firmly establish themselves in
the market. But people at both magazines say they ultimately see
more that is complimentary than in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their demographics are a bit lower, both younger and less
prosperous,'' Egan said. ``We celebrate the active lifestyle,
including travel and fitness and features on athletes who are
women. They are more sport- and participant-oriented, with a heavy
emphasis on the high school or college athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers will play a major role in the magazines' success or
failure. A Massachusetts athletic shoe manufacturer, New Balance,
advertises in both.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, the thing that attracted us was the equity
of the SI name,'' said John Donovan, New Balance's manager of
marketing services. ``Second, it's targeting the kind of audience
we want to target, very active women, 18 to 35. She runs. She plays
sports. She's into fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is a good investment for what we are hoping the
payoff eventually will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
