u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      03-15 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE REVOLUTION, A NEW SEASON, OLD QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution are going where no area
first-division professional soccer team has gone before. They will
begin their fifth season when they trek to Fort Lauderdale to meet
the Miami Fusion Saturday, surpassing the modern-day staying power
of the Boston Rovers (1967), Minutemen ('74-76), and New England
Tea Men ('78-80).
</P>
<P>
   But despite the stability provided by strong local ownership,
persistent fan interest, and Major League Soccer's foundation, the
Revolution's prospects for this season are nearly as mysterious as
they were in their first campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Fernando Clavijo and director of soccer operations Sunil
Gulati have taken strong steps to place their stamp on the team,
and the Revolution have prospered in the preseason, compiling a
5-2-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many questions remain. Clavijo is seeking to present a style
of play that will blend the flair of Leonel Alvarez, Wolde Harris,
Eduardo Hurtado, and Mauricio Ramos with the directness of John
Harkes and Ivan McKinley. He also hopes to rejuvenate the team with
youngsters such as Shaker Asad, Adam Eyre, Rusty Pierce, William
Sunsing, and Fabio Zuniga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see a change in style,'' Clavijo said Tuesday. ``It
will be a very attractive way of playing. I don't like to lose the
ball because it takes a lot of hard work to get it back. So you
will see the team keep possession of the ball most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous Revolution coaches have announced similar intentions,
then were unable to produce the proper chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you will see the team win a lot of games,'' Clavijo
said. ``I want them to go out and work hard and give everything
they have. Every game they play has to be like the last game they
are ever going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Hurtado are capable of matching the departed strike
force of Joe-Max Moore (Everton, England) and Giovanni Savarese
(Viterbese, Italy), though Harris will likely start as a lone
striker in a 4-5-1 alignment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The midfield will revolve around the creative instincts of
Ramos, who is expected to provide a spark the way countryman Marco
Etcheverry does for D.C. United. Ramos is an uninhibited marksman
from distance and likes to combine a short passing game in midfield
with long-range distribution to the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive midfield support will be provided by Alvarez and
Harkes, the strongest leaders on the team. The Alvarez-Harkes-Ramos
midfield triangle will set the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest questions, though, are in outside midfield positions
and in central defense.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielders Imad Baba and Johnny Torres have been inconsistent,
but Clavijo has faith in them and they responded during the
preseason. The outside backs will be Ted Chronopoulos, who has
played 100 games for the Revolution, and Pierce, at least until
Mike Burns (groin injury) recovers. Burns has captained the team in
102 of its 130 MLS games.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo used seven central defenders before settling on Brian
Dunseth and McKinley, who were paired briefly during the
Revolution's most disastrous season, 1998. Clavijo is not
comfortable with the situation, and he is pursuing Juan Samuel
Caballero, a 25-year-old Honduran who made a strong impression in
the CONCACAF Champions Cup and Gold Cup tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution also must overcome the stigma of past failures.
They won only 16 games in regulation time in the last two seasons,
and many of those wins resulted from the scoring of Moore and the
goalkeeping of Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   Keeper Jeff Causey will not come close to Zenga's level but will
provide consistency. Jurgen Sommer, acquired from Columbus for a
third-round draft pick Tuesday, is expected to become the starter
once he recovers from injury. Sommer, who has played in England for
the US national team, has had cruciate ligament surgery on both
knees in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a risk but it's a good risk to take,'' Clavijo said.
``He is one of the best goalkeepers in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the Revolution have players with national team
experience: Alvarez (Colombia), Baba, Burns, Dan Calichman,
Chronopoulos, Harkes, Harris (Jamaica), Hurtado (Ecuador), McKinley
(South Africa), Ramos (Bolivia), Sunsing (Costa Rica). Dunseth is a
US Olympic team candidate and Jamar Beasley, Carlos Parra, Pierce,
and Torres have played for US junior national teams. The Revolution
have always had sufficient talent but never a winning combination.
</P>
<P>
   And, as in the past, the team is setting its sights high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to say anything about winning the
championship,'' Clavijo said. ``Attitude is the key and the
attitude of the players who aren't playing is the key. It will take
20-22 guys to win the championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
