<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-VOTERS-0316-CO     03-15 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-VOTERS-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS DIVISIONS BECOME CLEARER IN TAIWAN PREZ RACE, NEGATIVE
RHETORIC CRANKS UP
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Chao.
 &HT;    With box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI _ Unfortunately for the ruling Nationalist Party,
23-year-old Iris Liu speaks for a lot of people in Taiwan in
explaining why she supports the opposition party candidate in the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nationalist Party has been in power too long,'' she said.
``We need a new party, with new views.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years of political domination by the Nationalists,
also known as the Kuomingtang, or KMT, could come to an end
Saturday as Taiwanese go to the polls to elect a president in what
has been a highly-charged and extremely close three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   As the opposition candidate gains momentum in the final days of
the campaign, with fresh endorsements from prominent academics and
business people, the Nationalists have ratcheted up the rhetoric,
warning voters that economic and political instability could result
if anyone other than Vice President Lien Chan is elected.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Taiwan's stock market suffered the largest single-day
decline in its history, falling 6.6 percent in what some analysts
said was a reflection of fears of a victory by the Democratic
Progressive Party's Chen Shui-bian. The Nationalists have portrayed
Chen, a former Taipei mayor, as someone who would provoke China
into war and destabilize Taiwan's economy if he were president.
</P>
<P>
   For people under 40, who make up the bulk of Chen's supporters,
such talk does not ring true. To them, Chen will solve what they
see as the biggest problem in Taiwan: corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Nationalist party is completely rotten,'' said
Patty Lai, 30. ``They have money. They have power. They don't care
about the people. We need reform, even if that means instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainland China's repeated recent threats to use force if a
pro-independence candidate wins also do not scare supporters of the
Democratic Progressive Party, even though its party platform
advocates independence for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China is going to take military action, they'll do it no
matter who is elected,'' said Liu, who finished a degree in
international relations last year and hopes to go to the United
States for graduate studies.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nationalist's message has sunk in for some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the election to make Taiwan more chaotic,'' said
Shu Lin Hsieh, 32, who supports Lien. ``I'm quite scared. Taiwan is
prosperous. We have everything we need. I want stability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists have been working hard to get the youth vote,
holding break-dancing rallies in the streets of Taipei and
distributing pamphlets saying it's not shameful to vote for the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Although corruption is one of the top issues for Taiwanese
voters according to polls, relations with mainland China overshadow
just about everything on this island of 22 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalist Party, once the ruling party of China, fled to
Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to the communists. It ruled
Taiwan with an iron fist for decades, jailing political dissidents
_ including members of the Democratic Progressive Party _ and using
martial law for almost 40 years to curb free expression.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing still regards Taiwan as a wayward province to be
reunified with the motherland. But as Taiwan's economy flourishes
and its democracy becomes one of the most vibrant in Asia, native
Taiwanese feel more and more distant from their communist brethren
across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
   For people like Fred Chiou, who support eventual peaceful
unification with China, Lien is the candidate who will most likely
maintain harmonious relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan's safety is the most important issue. There's a lot of
pressure from China. We need a president who can negotiate with
China. For Asia and the rest of the world, it would also be
beneficial,'' said Chiou, who headed the Chinese Community
Federation of Atlanta, an umbrella group of 14 organizations, until
earlier this month when he left Atlanta to join an Internet
start-up company in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen has pledged he will not declare independence and
even hopes to visit the mainland as a trust-building measure, many
voters doubt his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid of Chen Shui-bian, but we don't believe Lien
Chan,'' said Chuen Huei Wang, who teaches economics at a college in
Taipei. ``He (Lien) is old government, old politics, with many
money scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 40, joined the Nationalist Party when he was just 15
because his father was a long-time member, but he said he quit 15
years ago because he was disgusted with it. His vote is going to
James Soong, a longtime Nationalist insider and former Taiwan
governor who broke away from the party last year to run an
independent campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   David Yu, chairman of Summit National Bank in Atlanta, said he
assumed most of his business and professional acquaintances in
Taipei would be Lien Chan supporters but was surprised to find they
are going for Soong. Like many Taiwanese living overseas, Yu holds
dual citizenship and returned to Taipei this week to vote. He
declined to say which candidate he supports.
</P>
<P>
   With just days remaining, all three candidates are holding
massive rallies with tens of thousands of people throughout Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Negative campaigning has also climbed to new heights, with no
insult too low to sling. Lien recently called Soong a person with a
``wolve's heart and dog's lung,'' meaning a person of no integrity.
Both Soong and Chen camps blamed Monday's stock tumble on
manipulation by the Nationalist party, which controls many of the
country's financial institutions. Some of Chen's relatives held a
press conference Tuesday calling him a liar and cheat.
</P>
<P>
   The level of negative campaigning is far beyond that in the
United States, said Yu.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not really debating the issues facing the country,''
he said. ``They try to dig up dirt on each other, which is not very
healthy. Unfortunately, the voters pay a lot of attention to the
negative campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   KEY DATES IN TAIWAN'S DEVELOPMENT
</P>
<P>
   -1945: Taiwan, which had been ruled by the Japanese for half a
century, is returned to China's
</P>
<P>
   control.
</P>
<P>
   -1949: Republic of China government relocates from mainland to
Taiwan as a result of civil war on mainland. Government enacts
decrees limiting personal freedoms and restricting formation of
opposition political parties.
</P>
<P>
   -1971: China's seat in the United Nations is taken away from the
ROC and given to the mainland People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   -1979: United States withdraws its diplomatic recognition of the
ROC. Political opposition forms a coalition and begins publication
of Formosa magazine, mouthpiece for Taiwan's democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   -1986: Policy of liberalization begins.
</P>
<P>
   -1987: Martial law is abolished, and new freedoms are granted to
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   -1996: First popular election of president and vice-president is
held.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN'S PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   -Lien Chan, candidate of the long dominant Nationalist Party,
also known as the Kuomingtang or KMT. Lien is currently Taiwan's
vice president. He has spoken of moving relations between Taiwan
and the mainland to greater mutual confidence and contact.
</P>
<P>
   -James Soong, popular independent candidate, former Nationalist
Party superstar and former Taiwan provincial governor. He says
China-Taiwan relations should be ``quasi-international'' rather
than ``state to state'' and envisages signing a 30-year non-
aggression treaty with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   -Chen Shui-bian, candidate of the Democratic Progressive Party.
Chen has moderated his views on China by pledging not to declare
independence unilaterally, but his party includes many independence
supporters. The former mayor of Taipei has offered to journey to
Beijing to talk face-to-face with China's leaders on any issue.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
