<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Flight of the Lama &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sondheim On the Musical Theater He Has Outlived &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Generation Rx &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package ... this week's New
York Times Magazine articles are for release as indicated below.
</P>
<P>
   .....................
 &UR; FLIGHT of the LAMA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By ISABEL HILTON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: March 12 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dodging spies and Chinese army checkpoints, scaling mountains in
the cold, dark night, without provisions, traveling via a
Mitsubishi SUV, helicopter and horseback, Ugyen Trinley Dorje _ the
17th Karmapa _ an appealing 14-year-old child, escaped into India.
Arriving half-starved at Dharamsala, the exile home of the Dalai
Lama, he touched off a worldwide sensation and speculation by many
that he will be the future leader of the 100,000 exiled Tibetans,
the potential temporal successor to the exiled ruler of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Isabel Hilton, a London-based writer and broadcaster, is the
author of ``The Search for the Panchen Lama,'' to be published in
May by Norton. slugged: BC-LAMA-CENTERPIECE, priority code s,
category code c) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENERATION RX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By AMY BLOOM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: March 12 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Prescribing psychotropic medications for school-age children is
a booming business these days. Ritalin's production alone is up 700
percent since 1990. A battle has arisen between the pro-medication
and anti-medication camps: heated, public and utterly spurious.
Some children need medication; others don't. The real trouble lies
in how the assessment is made. The person with the cash, the power
and even the transportation usually gets to identify the patient,
setting the stage for all subsequent decisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Amy Bloom, a psychotherapist, is the author of the novel
``Love Invents Us.'' slugged: BC-RITALIN-CENTERPIECE, priority code
s, category code c) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SONDHEIM ON THE MUSICAL THEATER HE HAS OUTLIVED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK RICH &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: March 12 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sondheim, who turns 70 on March 22, was so obscure in
1957 that he wasn't even mentioned in The New York Times review of
``West Side Story.'' He is now the greatest and perhaps best-known
artist in the American musical theater. But that is a somewhat
empty distinction. Sondheim may be the last major creator of
Broadway musicals. He may have even outlived the genre, which was
long ago exiled by rock music from center stage to niche status in
American culture and is now barely a going concern.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Frank Rich was the chief drama critic of The New York Times
from 1980 to 1993. He is now an op-ed columnist and senior writer
for The New York Times Magazine. slugged: BC-SONDHEIM-CENTERPIECE,
priority code s, category code c)
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much,
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------- &QC;
</P>
