<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SWEENEY-BO     03-15 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY PONDERS UPCOMING FREE AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's 33 years old, a terrific skater, and one of the
few Bruins who has had a season about which he can be happy. He's
also a mobile, physical defenseman who is due to become an
unrestricted free agent on July 1, so it was no surprise that Don
Sweeney's name was being bandied about as the trade deadline
approached.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 3 p.m. threshold came and went and Sweeney remained
a Bruin. After the departures of icon Ray Bourque and veteran wing
Rob DiMaio, it wasn't a shock that the Bruins held onto one of
their few veterans, one who has played his entire 12-year NHL
career in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens on July 1, when Sweeney can walk away? Sweeney
said his agent, Mark Witkin, and Bruins president/general manager
Harry Sinden had lunch Monday but it was more to quell trade rumors
than to hammer out a new deal. Assistant GM Mike O'Connell said the
Bruins very much want to keep Sweeney, but with his first chance at
unrestricted free agency, the defenseman is in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have asked me about contracts and trades,'' said
Sweeney. ``I've said the same thing since Day One of training camp:
I only want to focus on this year. Obviously, we've had a lot of
things go on. We're not out of a playoff race. We've got the
excitement of winning a couple of games and we could've probably
won all three (of the last three), and that is all I'm focused
on.''
</P>
<P>
   With two more teams set to join the league, enlarging it to a
whopping 30, Sweeney's services could be in very high demand. As
the father of twin sons, he said, part of his decision will be
based around his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed the time away from the rink moreso than ever with
my kids and my wife,'' he said. ``I'd have to reevaluate with her
what her preference would be. I don't have anything else to go on.
I haven't been presented with anything so I'll have to take things
as they come. If they present me a contract, I'm obviously going to
get a chance to evaluate that. If they don't and somebody else
does, then I'll have to evaluate that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been in a free agent situation. I don't know what
comes next, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls Boston home year-round, he likes the lifestyle here,
the city, the fans, the team. He hasn't spent a lot of time on
possible scenarios down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys would rate that as a financial decision, some guys
would rate that as an opportunity to go to a warm city, there are
all kinds of things to evaluate,'' he said. ``I've been very
comfortable here. It's not like I haven't understood my role or
position or enjoyed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're going through a playoff stretch here but we've got
an evaluation period going on here as well. I think that's been
openly admitted. I read (owner Jeremy Jacobs's quotes) and they're
going through an evaluation in terms of anyone involved in this
organization. So there is going to be some sorting out.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you look at it, it appears to be a win-win
situation for Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly an interesting time,'' he said. ``I'd be the
first to admit that because I've never been in the position before.
I'm going to have to take time when all that stuff sorts itself
out. During the course of the year, it just hasn't been that time.
The Bruins have implied they would like to try to sign me but I
have no comment on the contract side of things because I haven't
heard or done anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd like to go to a contender _ as his mentor and
friend Bourque did _ Sweeney said of course he wants to win,
everyone wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the excitement of just winning a couple of
games,'' he said. ``It does a lot for the psyche of everybody. But
I like things that are in front of me that I can analyze and
process. My options are what they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
