<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-CCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKENMAN MAKES A DIFFERENCE FOR CENTRAL CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. _ Stand-up comedians of the world, breathe
easy. Central Connecticut State fourth-year coach Howie Dickenman
has a flair for one-liners, but guiding the program from a
laughingstock 4-22 finish two seasons ago to this year's NCAA
tournament is proof he's too exceptional a basketball mind to
consider another line of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who we used to recruit against? Nobody,'' said
Dickenman with a raspy, low-toned delivery that is vintage
Dangerfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask my assistant, `Who's involved with this kid?' He'd
say, `Us and nobody.' I'd say, `How are we doing?' He'd say, `We're
like 50-50.' We think we lost a couple of kids to nobody. They're
at Stop &AMP; Shop now, packing bags or something. People say, `How do
you lose a kid to nobody?' I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Central standout player and University of Connecticut
assistant coach is now getting the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   After posting the second-best turnaround in Division 1 last
season (19-13), CCSU captured the Northeast Conference title and
its first NCAA tournament bid this season, culminating a 25-5
campaign that included a school record-tying 15-game winning streak
and a 54-50 triumph over Providence for the school's first win over
a Big East opponent in 17 tries.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th-seeded Blue Devils meet second-seeded Iowa State (29-4)
in the first round of the Midwest Regional Friday in Minneapolis at
approximately 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, many feel this year's campaign is the
start of something big at Central, a program filled with players
overlooked by most other schools who have come together to carve a
niche in a state that is UConn crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this season, the last time Central had sold out a game
at 3,200-seat Detrick Gymnasium was during the 1984-85 campaign,
when the University of Bridgeport came to town with Manute Bol.
This season, the team not only had an overflow crowd of 3,275 for
its regular-season finale against Quinnipiac but led the NEC in
home attendance (2,249 average).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got people calling in advance for tickets. The school's
on a high, and now the state's been following us,'' said Dickenman.
``We're the new kid on the block, going to the NCAA. UConn's an
automatic every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Dickenman, an intense, emotional mentor, for turning
around the program in its 14th season in Division 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils are ninth in the nation in rebounding margin
(plus 6.3 per game) and fifth in field-goal percentage defense
(37.6 percent). While averaging 45 percent shooting from the floor,
Central has four players in its rotation averaging at least 10
points a game and five averaging at least five boards a game.
</P>
<P>
   Central is led by senior point guard and NEC player of the year
Rick Mickens (17.7 ppg, 2.8 assists), who grew up in nearby
Newington a UConn fan. He didn't receive any other scholarship
offers and opted for Central Connecticut rather than a walk-on role
at Storrs.
</P>
<P>
   He became one of Dickenman's first recruits, along with Victor
Payne, a senior forward who is the first player from Barbados to
receive a Division 1 scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Those two, now cocaptains, helped provide the nucleus for a
program Dickenman was brought in to help turn around after it had
endured 11 straight losing seasons _ including two four-win
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   His hiring came less than two months after Central endured one
of its lowest points as a Division 1 team _ a 116-46 loss to
Connecticut at Hartford. ``I was one of the first ones out of the
UConn locker room that day,'' said Dickenman, embarrassed by his
alma mater's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet turning the program around was anything but easy. There was
a 9-13 first season, then the 4-22 debacle. The latter season,
Central was the youngest team in Division 1. Attendance averaged
less than 500 a game, and the team failed to qualify for a
Northeast Conference tournament the school hosted.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest point, said Dickenman, came during the second year,
when he had to put a 117-75 loss to Long Island University behind
him to speak at a social engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 31 turnovers; I remember 31 because people in the
second and third row were ducking all day because of balls we were
throwing out of bounds,'' said Dickenman.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lady got hit in the fourth row, broke her glasses. Two
guys had to go to the hospital . . . I'm kidding a little bit
there, but you got to be careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started three or four freshmen that day. They pressed us
baseline to baseline. It was like hot potato: `I don't want it; you
take it. No, I don't want it; you take it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You really cherish wins when you don't win much,'' added
Dickenman. ``I remember when we were at UConn, we won about 30
games a number of times. You don't cherish 30. But when you win
four, whoa boy, you love every one of those four. They're
priceless.''
</P>
<P>
   The team turned things around last season when it won its first
four games, a first for the school at the Division 1 level. It lost
in the NEC final to Mount St. Mary's but had a taste of things to
come.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of Fairfield transfer John Tice, a blue-collar
point guard who had helped the Stags to an NEC title and near upset
of North Carolina in the NCAA tournament in 1998, many figured
Central _ the closest Division 1 program to ESPN's headquarters
(less than 15 minutes) _ had the toughness and experience to
achieve a breakthrough season and gain notice.
</P>
<P>
   Then the setbacks struck.
</P>
<P>
   First, the team could not use the gym for two weeks during
preseason because the floor had been resurfaced poorly and had to
be redone. Then the bleachers, which were supposed to be redone in
August, weren't taken care of until the latter part of October,
forcing Central to move an exhibition game to a local high school.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest blow came when the season began: Payne and
Mickens were suspended five games by the NCAA for reportedly
misusing their scholarship funds to purchase books for five
nonscholarship athletes and one nonathlete. John Tice and Harvey
Van Stein were also involved and received three-game bans.
</P>
<P>
   The school initially took steps to handle the situation
internally; the students were given books, and the players had to
do community service before returning to the team. None had tried
to gain monetarily from the venture, but rather had been trying to
help fellow student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the NCAA upheld its sanctions. ``After the suspensions
were upheld, it felt as if everything was going wrong,'' said
Payne. ``But we looked at the positives: A lot of people played
while were were out, and they got experience in the long run. We
knew we could count on them when we came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Central spread the suspensions over the first six games. The
only contest that all the players missed was at La Salle, a 70-60
loss.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blue Devils returned to full strength, they were a more
determined bunch, as evidenced by their win at Providence. It was a
major boost to the program and to the league, which ended a 36-game
losing streak against Big East competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when people identified us as being a good basketball
team,'' said Dickenman.
</P>
<P>
   That was the second of 15 consecutive victories, a streak that
at the time tied Central with Long Beach State for the longest in
Division 1. The streak was snapped by Fairleigh Dickinson in
mid-February and a loss to Robert Morris followed, but Central
regrouped to win three tournament games by an average of 11.6
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of the year,'' said Mickens, ``we knew that
as long as we played up to our potential, I had the utmost
confidence'' the team would reach such heights.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils returned home from the NEC final at 4:30 a.m.
and received a police escort from Interstate 84, where they were
greeted on campus by more than 200 fans, who braved the cold to
welcome the winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This basketball team, we are humble and appreciative,'' said
Payne. ``We know where we came from. We still hug people we don't
even know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Central has any illusions about what this team has
accomplished in comparison with the defending national champions.
Connecticut is, and alway will be, UConn territory. But people at
Central are happy with the spotlight they're basking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connecticut basketball is the team to follow,'' said Mickens.
``They're big-time college basketball. We're just trying to play
hard and we have our fans, too. We have a lot of pride, and we just
go out and win basketball games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
