</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IRISH-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE END IS NIGH FOR AMERICA'S LOVEFEST WITH IRISH FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies about Ireland, elbowing into America's theaters year
after year after year, may have finally elbowed themselves out the
door.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade more than a dozen movies have been filmed
in Ireland, including box office hits ``Waking Ned Devine'' and
``The Commitments.'' But the three that debuted this year haven't
made much of an impression. Movies about the Emerald Isle may be
running out of audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes,'' at the top of the New York Times bestseller
list for 40 weeks, did not last long in the theaters. Neither did
``Agnes Browne,'' the story of an Irish widow juggling a big
family. And ``The Closer You Get,'' a tale of Donegal men
advertising for American wives, may not last long _ it was slapped
by critics for presenting yet another stereotypical view of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than enough stereotypes of Ireland floating
around. For a country of 3.7 million people, it has claimed an
inordinate amount of attention from Hollywood and London. A casual
glance through a film encyclopedia finds more than 60 movies about
Ireland since the 1935 version of ``The Informer,'' which won four
Oscars for its portrayal of Dublin as home to intrigue, betrayal,
zealots, misfits, thick drinking and cosmic sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Movieland's image of the Irish hasn't changed much since 1935.
Dublin is seen as odd, from ``Ulysses'' in 1967 and ``Portrait of
the Artist as a Young Man'' in 1979 to John Huston's honestly
affecting ``The Dead'' in 1987. In the British-produced Barrytown
Trilogy from author Roddy Doyle in the 1990s _ ``The Commitments,''
``The Snapper'' and ``The Van'' _ the view of Dublin is best
described in ``Commitments'' as ``the Irish are the blacks of
Europe, Dubliners are the blacks of Ireland and Northside Dubliners
are the blacks of Dublin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commitments'' also philosophizes that ``the Irish wouldn't
be shooting the arse off each other if they had soul,'' and ``We're
a Third World country, what can you do?'' Other thoughts on the
Irish come from ``Ryan's Daughter'' (``Talk _ this whole cursed
country will capsize with talk''), ``The Informer'' (``Why must we
be killing one another? What good will it do?'') and ``Cal''
(``There are bad bastards on both sides'').
</P>
<P>
   Movie views of Irish life, particularly rural life, careen
between the bleak and giddy. Giddiness dominates John Ford's
classic 1953 movie about Inisfree, ``The Quiet Man,'' and Disney's
1959 hit, ``Darby O'Gill and the Little People'' _ their
unrelenting images of feisty, lovable villagers make Brigadoon seem
like Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   Ford rolled out the biggest Irish American names for ``The Quiet
Man,'' including Maureen O'Hara and Barry Fitzgerald, whose
one-liners have never been topped (``Impetuous,'' he says, looking
at the broken remains of a honeymoon bed). In the wake of ``Quiet
Man,'' the Irish villager has gone from feisty and lovable to dumb
and hateful (``Ryan's Daughter,'' 1970) to dumb and lovable
(``Waking Ned Devine,'' ``The Closer You Get''). While offering its
own variations on those themes, the 1997 U.S.-Irish production,
``The Butcher Boy'' goes one step further, suggesting villagers are
so crazy that a whacked-out, throat-cutting, red-haired youngster
can walk among them as easy as you please, carrying the guilt of
betrayal, zealots, misfits and cosmic sadness on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Butcher Boy,'' filmed in County Monaghan, centers on a
snow-thick village in 1962, its craziness played to a background of
``Mack the Knife'' on Hawaiian guitar. John F. Kennedy shares wall
space with the Virgin Mary, just as Elvis would share wall space
with the Pope in ``The Commitments'' 30 years later. ``Butcher
Boy'' also made good use of the current generation of Irish-movie
actors, including Ian Hart, the lead in ``The Closer You Get.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Closer You Get'' is in the best carpetbagging tradition of
Irish movies. Produced, directed and written by an Italian, Scot
and Englishman, it follows in the steps of ``Waking Ned Devine,''
``Dancing at Lughnasa'' and ``The Matchmaker,'' wallowing in a
down-to-earth Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Locations manager Stephen Killen says he was looking for a
village that recalled the Scottish fishing town in ``Local Hero.''
He settled on Kincaslough, a coastal village in Donegal, but it was
altogether too clean and modern-looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the houses were very bright and just didn't fit in
with the feel that we were after,'' said production designer Tom
McCullagh. ``The whole village had to have a kind of weariness, a
tiredness to it, like nothing ever changed there that much.''
McCullagh's crew ``painted everything down a few shades,'' covered
the center line of the town's road with gravel and changed the
church interior because ``it was a bit too extravagant for the feel
that we were after.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking liberties with the look of Ireland is nothing new to
filmmakers, who have also taken liberties with their ``Irish''
leads. Britain's James Mason is an IRA kingpin in the ``Odd Man
Out'' (1947), a surprisingly even-handed British look at the Irish
Republican Army. Scottish poster boy Sean Connery is an Irish
farmer in ``Darby O'Gill,'' Helen Mirren, the Briton later to star
in the crime series ``Prime Suspect,'' is an Irish Catholic in
``Cal.'' American Chris O'Donnell is all Irish in ``Circle of
Friends,'' a variation on ``The Group'' set in the postcard
villages of County Kilkenny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan's Daughter'' is the prime example of pseudo-Irish actors
moving through an Irish landscape _ in this case the Dingle
peninsula. Trevor Howard, the ranking officer in every other
British war film, plays a hardscrabble Catholic priest. Britain's
Sarah Miles is Ryan's daughter, while John Mills, Sir John Mills,
plays the village idiot. Leo McKern of ``Rumpole of the Bailey''
fame is the town barkeep _ yet another guilt-ridden betrayer of the
Irish dream.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Darby O'Gill,'' the standard for Irish pap and twaddle,
Albert Sharpe plays Darby as a kind of Gabby Hayes from
Knocknasheega. The movie is full of stereotypes _ dancing
leprechauns, shrieking banshees, lies told over a glassful of
Guinness, Connery singing about pretty colleens while Janet Munro
smiles hard enough to break her face _ but it is also a pleasant,
optimistic look at the Auld Sod, the flip side of all the IRA
movies made in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Cal'' in 1984 to ``In the Name of the Father'' in 1993 to
``Michael Collins'' in 1996 and ``The Boxer'' a year later, each
IRA film has had an ax to grind. There's agreement the killing
should stop, but once that's said there's no agreement at all _
much like the on-again, off-again negotiations over the future of
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   To balance the long run of bombs-and-blood films about the
North, movieland turned to a more innocent Ireland, cashing in with
the giddy ``Waking Ned Devine.'' ``The Closer You Get'' is trying
to follow up with much the same formula, but it could be too late.
</P>
<P>
   The American capacity for Irish movies may, at long last, be
filled to the brim. Wobbling between the ever-bleak and the
always-giddy, between ``Angela's Ashes'' and ``The Closer You
Get,'' Americans may have had enough of cinematic Ireland for a
while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
