<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7650 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     03-15 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS SPILL THE BEANS ABOUT DESSERTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many readers sent in the requested recipe for pinto bean cake.
The first one we're running was sent by Joan P. Roberts. Judy Hall
of Burleson, Texas, sent the bundt-cake version, and Cherish Young
sent the pinto bean pie recipe. Ann Strawser of Arlington, Texas,
sendt the recipe for a cake made with pork and beans.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PINTO BEAN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12-16
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked pinto beans, mashed and whipped until fluffy
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Cream sugar and margarine or butter until light and fluffy. Add
eggs and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Add beans and dry ingredients that have been sifted together.
Mix well. Stir in pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into lightly greased and floured 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan.
Bake at 350 degrees for 50 to 60 minutes or until cake tests done.
Cool before frosting with following icing. Butter icing:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soft butter
</P>
<P>
   3 cups powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and sugar; stir in vanilla and milk. Beat until
smooth and of spreading consistency. Spread on cake evenly;
sprinkle top with coarsely chopped nuts, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 276 calories, 12 grams fat, 39
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 36 milligrams cholesterol,
174 milligrams sodium, 40 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PINTO BEAN CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 20
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg (beaten)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked pinto beans, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced raw apples
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease a 9- or 10-inch tube pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter or margarine and sugar together. Add the beaten egg
and mix well. Stir in the mashed cooked beans and the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour, baking soda, salt, ground cinnamon, cloves and
allspice together. Add the chopped pecans, golden raisins and diced
apples to the flour mixture. Stir to coat. Pour flour mixture into
the creamed mixture and stir until just combined. Pour batter into
the prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 45 minutes. Dribble with a simple confectioners' sugar
icing and garnish with candied cherries and pecan halves, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 355 calories, 13 grams fat, 55
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 42 milligrams cholesterol,
160 milligrams sodium, 34 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PINTO PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cooked beans, drained and mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 sticks melted margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 8-inch unbaked pie shells
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs until frothy. Add sugar. Beat until well blended. Add
beans, margarine and vanilla. Beat until smooth. Pour into pie
shells and bake 10 minutes at 450 degrees. Reduce heat to 350 and
bake 30 to 35 minutes or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 447 calories, 24 grams fat, 54
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 71 milligrams cholesterol,
339 milligrams sodium, 48 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PORK-n-BEANS CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 20 slices
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can drained pork and beans
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour five 16-ounce cans OR two 8-by-4-inch loaf
pans. In a large bowl, mix sugar, oil, eggs and beans until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, combine flour, cinnamon, baking powder and
baking soda. Add to bean mixture, stirring just until combined.
Stir in raisins and vanilla. Fill cans 2/3 full with batter, or
divide batter into prepared loaf pans. Place cans or pans on a
baking sheet. Bake for 45 to 50 minutes, or until a tester inserted
in the center of the cake comes out clean. Cool completely on wire
racks before removing bread from cans or pans.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per slice: 256 calories, 12 grams fat, 34
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 33 milligrams cholesterol,
142 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
