<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX     03-15 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP CALLS FOR SHARP INCREASE IN VISAS FOR SKILLED WORKERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers representing several high-tech hot spots
Wednesday joined forces to push for a sharp increase in visas for
highly skilled foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortage of skilled workers is a threat to our strong
economy,'' said House Rules Committee Chairman David Dreier,
R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier led a group of 18 House members from both parties
sponsoring legislation that would raise the limit on H-1B visas to
200,000 in each of the next three fiscal years. The visas allow
well-educated foreigners, such as engineers and computer
programmers, to work in this country for up to six years.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, co-chair of the House Information
Technology Working Group, said the fast-growing tech companies in
central Texas need more H-1B visas because they must attract ``the
best and brightest, not only from all over the country but from all
over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill contains a provision to boost the fee employers pay for
each visa from the current $500 to $1,000. The money is used for
worker training and high-tech education. The bill also has
provisions aimed at improving administration of the visa program.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier's legislation is similar to a Senate bill that cleared
the Senate Judiciary Committee last week.
</P>
<P>
   But in the House, it must compete with a bill recently
introduced by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the
immigration subcommittee, which has jurisdiction over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's bill would boost the number of H-1B visas from the
current 115,000 to 160,000 in this fiscal year. But that relief
would be only temporary. The number of visas would fall to 107,500
in fiscal 2001 and 65,000 the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's far from clear which bill will gain momentum in the
House, backers of Dreier's legislation say they have the support of
members of the Republican leadership and key Democrats. Doggett
said he believed President Clinton, who has backed the idea of
increasing visas, would support the Dreier bill.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups that have been cool to the Smith bill rushed to
praise Dreier's package. Calling it ``a well-balanced bill,''
Sandra Boyd, chair of American Business for Legal Immigration,
cheered the bipartisan effort. ``There is an immediate need for
educated professionals who possess math, science and engineering
skills to fill the technology jobs that are being created,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-immigration groups and lobbyists for engineers and other
U.S. workers oppose increases in H-1B visas, saying labor shortages
are vastly overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsors of the Dreier bill include Reps. Zoe Lofgren,
D-Calif.; Tom Davis, R-Va.; Adam Smith, D-Wash.; Anna Eshoo,
R-Calif., and John Linder, R-Ga. The sponsors represent such
high-tech meccas as Atlanta; Austin, Texas; the Silicon Valley;
Northern Virginia, and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
