<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-IRISHCUISINE-1100(2Ta     03-15 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISHCUISINE-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN WITH ENVY: IRISH FOOD LEAPS BEYOND CORNED BEEF AND CABBAGE,
B'GOSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People don't go to Ireland for the food.
</P>
<P>
   But they would, if they knew more about it.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland, where lamb stew and Guinness stout come to mind. Where
salmon reign in the cold, fast-flowing rivers and the icy Atlantic
beyond. Salmon that end up poached or delicately smoked.
</P>
<P>
   Where cream _ whipped alongside your wedge of chocolate cake or
gently piled atop your Irish coffee _ is tinted slightly yellow,
butterlike. Where rainfall averages up to 100 inches a year and the
term ``Emerald Isle'' is no misnomer _ it's an understatement. The
cows are fat and their cream is rich.
</P>
<P>
   Even oatmeal tastes better here. With a texture so chewy that it
sometimes resembles barley, it's more filling, too. Of course, it's
cooked in whole milk and drowned in _ you guessed it _ cream. No
wonder it tastes so good.
</P>
<P>
   So when you're asked, ``Would you like cream with that?'' say
yes. This is not the time or place to worry about your cholesterol
level or your calorie intake. This is the time, and the place, to
enjoy fine cuisine or simple, hearty fare, prepared with care from
high-quality ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   'Tis true that Ireland doesn't immediately come to mind when the
subject is haute cuisine. And yet, a culinary renaissance has been
quietly taking place for 10 or 15 years. Chefs train on the
Continent or in England, or they undergo a two-year training
program sponsored by the Irish government. Local farmers and
producers supply hotels and restaurants with top-notch meats,
cheeses, herbs and vegetables. Thanks to a booming economy and a
youthful, well-traveled and sophisticated population, Ireland's
demand for fine food is growing. And it is being met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a time of renaissance for Irish food,'' says Declan
Ryan, owner of the Arbutus Lodge in Cork. ``It's the most exciting
time ever.'' Ten or 12 years ago, ``There were only six or eight
serious restaurants in the country _ like little lighthouses in the
fog.'' Now, he can't count all the fine-dining establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Curran, general manager of the Aghadoe Heights Hotel in
Killarney, credits the economy. Instead of relying primarily on
agriculture, the economic base has diversified, fueled by a strong
high-tech industry. ``The Irish have a lot more money to spend, and
it's socially acceptable to eat out and talk about food,'' Curran
says. ``People are prepared to pay good money for good food.'' As a
result, restaurants have improved, along with the scope and quality
of locally available ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's culinary history goes way back, Ryan says.
``Unfortunately, ours was interrupted by the famine,'' he said,
referring to the Great Potato Famine of the 1840s. ``Everything
ceased and started all over again.'' Before that catastrophe, the
island was blessed with fine cheeses, among other delicacies.
``Now, nobody even knows what the cheese tasted like.''
</P>
<P>
   He used to import cheese from France. ``Now I have nothing but
local cheeses on the board _ all farmhouse cheeses, nothing from
the factory,'' he says. In the past, he had to grow fresh herbs on
the premises. ``Now I have a choice of three different herb
growers.''
</P>
<P>
   As a tourist destination, Ireland is becoming increasingly
accessible, thanks to more direct flights. ``We're seeing a growth
in hotels and restaurants,'' Curran says. ``It's possible to make
money out of a restaurant.'' Or out of supplying a restaurant, he
adds, mentioning ``the local person that makes the bread or makes
the marmalade for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Irish may not (yet) be known for their cuisine,
their friendliness and warmth are renowned. Kenneth Broderick, a
bartender at Shannon International Airport, where Irish coffee is
said to have originated, was asked whether he could make a decaf
version of that concoction. ``Well, it wouldn't exactly be an Irish
coffee,'' he replied. But he was quick to amend, ``If you want, I
can do it that way, no problem.'' And to share the recipe, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the Twelve Pins Lodge in Barna, County Galway, disappointment
at the unavailability of mussels sent the waitress scurrying back
to the kitchen to dispatch a boy to the pub across the road to see
if it had any of the tasty bivalves. Alas, the pub didn't, but her
effort exemplifies the eager-to-please charm of the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   So forget the corned beef and cabbage. Why bother, when you can
feast on roasted rack of lamb on a bed of creamed spinach served
with gratin potatoes, followed by Baileys souffle in a chocolate
cup at the Beaufort Bar and Restaurant near Killarney? Or
whole-meal bread (a version of Ireland's ubiquitous brown soda
bread) or rich, intensely flavored chicken-liver terrine at The
Purple Heather in Kenmare? Lightly fried Galway Bay oysters; lean,
salty bacon; silken foie gras; artfully arranged seafood cassoulet
in phyllo pastry; heady cream of tomato soup _ the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   So the remark of a satisfied diner, upon completion of an
elaborate meal at the Arbutus Lodge, seems apropos:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really in Ireland; we're in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-LIVER TERRINE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces bacon, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces butter
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds chicken livers
</P>
<P>
   Salt and cracked black pepper, to taste (salt may be omitted
unless low-sodium bacon is used)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons port
</P>
<P>
   Fry bacon until crisp. Remove and drain on paper towel. Pour off
bacon grease.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in same skillet. Saute onion until soft, about 10
minutes, adding garlic for last 1 to 2 minutes. Add chicken livers
and cook, stirring, until done, but still slightly pink inside,
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place bacon and chicken-liver mixture in food processor and
puree. Add salt and pepper, thyme and cream.
</P>
<P>
   Deglaze skillet with brandy and port over high heat, cooking
until liquid has been reduced by approximately half. Add to mixture
in food processor and puree until smooth. Pack mixture into a crock
or mold and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 418 calories, 30 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 29 grams protein, 534 milligrams cholesterol,
648 milligrams sodium, 66 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Purple Heather, Kenmare
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ROAST RACK OF LAMB ON A BED OF CREAMED SPINACH
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 racks of lamb, French-trimmed, 4 pounds total
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Savory bread crumbs, see below, OR packaged herb-flavored bread
crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   Sprig of fresh thyme, chopped, OR pinch of dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces spinach
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cream
</P>
<P>
   Season lamb with salt and pepper. Place excess bones and
trimmings (which should be included when you purchase
French-trimmed rack) on bottom of a roasting pan. Spread mustard on
lamb. Spread bread crumbs on meaty side of rack. Place lamb on top
of trimmings and roast at 450 degrees for 20 minutes, or until
cooked to desired doneness. Remove from pan and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Pour fat out of pan and deglaze with red wine. Add thyme and
check seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Cook spinach until tender in a little water. Strain and chop
coarsely. Add cream and season with salt and pepper. Place a
spoonful in center of each serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange chops on top of spinach. Serve with wine sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAVORY BREAD CRUMBS
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1 2/3 cups) dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce (approximately 1/2 head) garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients, using just enough olive oil to moisten.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 430 calories, 21 grams fat, 12
grams carbohydrates, 45 grams protein, 141 milligrams cholesterol,
284 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beaufort Bar &AMP; Restaurant, Killarney
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GRATIN POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds potatoes, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cream (or more)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pureed garlic OR bottled ground garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Arrange potato slices attractively in an ovenproof dish.
</P>
<P>
   Mix cream, milk, garlic, salt and pepper and pour over potatoes.
Cover and cook in a 350-degree oven for 1 1/4 hours or until
completely tender. If necessary, baste exposed edges of potato
slices with additional cream to keep them from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 267 calories, 7 grams fat, 47
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 25 milligrams cholesterol, 32
milligrams sodium, 23 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beaufort Bar &AMP; Restaurant, Killarney
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHOLE-MEAL BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 slices
</P>
<P>
   3 cups stone-ground, whole-meal Irish flour, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 pint (2 cups) buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Sesame seeds, optional
</P>
<P>
   Combine dry ingredients. Add egg, butter and buttermilk and mix.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into a greased loaf pan. Sprinkle top with sesame seeds.
Bake approximately 1 hour in a 350-degree oven, until top is brown
and springs back when pressed with a finger.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If Irish whole-meal flour is unavailable, substitute 2 1/2
cups whole-wheat flour and 1/2 cup wheat bran.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 216 calories, 4 grams fat, 38
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 29 milligrams cholesterol,
226 milligrams sodium, 17 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Purple Heather''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BAILEYS SOUFFLE IN A CHOCOLATE CUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Baileys Irish cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon gelatin, softened in 3 tablespoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate cups, see Note
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries and mint leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Separate eggs. Whisk yolks, sugar and Baileys over low heat or
in a double boiler to a light, creamy consistency. Remove from
heat, add softened gelatin and whisk in thoroughly. Allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Whip cream to soft peaks and fold into Baileys mixture. Whip egg
whites until stiff and fold in. Pour mixture into chocolate cups.
Refrigerate for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with whipped cream, strawberries and mint leaves. Dust
with powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you can't find chocolate cups, make your own by melting
12 ounces semisweet chocolate and spreading it in paper muffin-cup
liners. Allow to harden. Remove paper very carefully, as chocolate
is fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 215 calories, 14 grams fat, 22
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 78 milligrams cholesterol, 24
milligrams sodium, 57 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beaufort Bar &AMP; Restaurant, Killarney
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IRISH COFFEE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 shot (1 1/4 ounces) Power's whiskey (or other Irish whiskey)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup hot coffee
</P>
<P>
   Whip cream until soft peaks form (NOT stiff peaks).
</P>
<P>
   Heat an Irish-coffee cup with hot water. Pour out hot water and
fill with boiling water. Pour out water.
</P>
<P>
   Place sugar in bottom of glass. Pour in whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Fill glass with coffee to within 1/2 inch of rim. Pile whipped
cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 162 calories, 3 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 10 milligrams cholesterol, 7
milligrams sodium, 16 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shannon International Airport bar
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
