<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAH     03-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BUSH DOESN'T NEED McCAIN  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) 
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    In politics, the ``W'' word is the kiss of death.
 &HT;    Just ask former President George Bush. His standing as a former
star athlete and bomber pilot didn't keep him from being labeled a
wimp, a tag which hurt him among the electorate.
 &HT;    The same hazard lies in wait for his son, who has the double
handicap of being nicknamed ``W'' after his middle initial. If
George W. Bush listens to the olive-branch crowd now urging him to
make nice with defeated rival John McCain, he'll find it impossible
to dodge that word.
 &HT;    Imagine the bumper stickers: ``W   W.''
 &HT;    The moment it was obvious that Bush had locked up the nomination
on Super Tuesday, television's conventional-wisdom crowd rushed to
advise him that he needed to move quickly to court McCain's
supporters.
 &HT;    McCain's advisers, anxious to keep their man in play, lost no
time in intimating to the press that McCain's enthusiastic
endorsement of Bush would not be forthcoming unless Bush moved
toward the Arizona senator's position on campaign-finance reform.
 &HT;    Last week, as Bill Bradley took his medicine and rallied behind
Gore, McCain went on vacation, merely wishing Bush well. Meanwhile,
angry McCain backers began buzzing about a possible third-party
run.
 &HT;    Suddenly Bush found himself facing the first major leadership
test of the post-primaries campaign season. A defeated John McCain
seemed even more difficult to deal with than a surging John McCain.
 &HT;    ``Seemed,'' I say, because things weren't quite the way they
looked.
 &HT;    Karen Hughes, communications director for Bush, had it right
last week when reporters asked her about the status of Bush-McCain
negotiations.
 &HT;    ``Negotiations?'' she said. ``Gov. Bush won. We hope that Sen.
McCain would help enact the campaign-finance reforms that Gov. Bush
laid out.''
 &HT;    A collective gasp swept the airwaves. Pro-McCain forces seized
on Hughes' response as evidence that Bush isn't a real reformer or
that he's back to his old, cocky self again. A Bush snub of McCain,
the media mavens howled, would drop all those independents and
moderates into Gore's lap.
 &HT;    But all this pressure to ``make peace'' is total nonsense. Sure,
Bush should act respectfully and cordially toward McCain, but
anything more than that will backfire.
 &HT;    During the next few months, Bush needs to convince America that
he believes in his political philosophy so strongly that he's
willing to lose John McCain completely. A strong leader doesn't
kowtow to his political rivals _ the more time Bush spends
extending olive branches in McCain's direction, the weaker he will
appear.
 &HT;    Bush's views _ including, presumably, those on campaign finance
_ helped him to coast-to-coast primary victories. Changing those
views now to accommodate a defeated rival would only alienate his
core supporters, while reinforcing the doubts swing voters have
about Bush.
 &HT;    McCain's appeal was due largely to his past heroism and his
plain-spoken approach, not to his views on particular issues.
Contrary to what media coverage would have you believe, exit polls
indicate that campaign finance is not a burning issue among the
electorate.
 &HT;    So far, the Bush team seems to be hanging tough. But the longer
the speculation about a McCain third-party run lingers, the more
the brain trust in Austin will be tempted to arrange a tete-a-tete,
one that would culminate in some sort of compromise on campaign
finance.
 &HT;    The pressure isn't coming solely from McCain boosters. Bush
backer Jack Kemp, who is an expert on losing to Al Gore, is
promoting a Bush-McCain kiss-and-make-up, going so far as to urge
Bush to pick McCain as his running mate. So is Bob Dole, whose
vaunted political savvy wasn't enough to keep him from losing even
to a scandal-tarred Bill Clinton in 1996.
 &HT;    Instead of pandering to McCain, Bush must continue his strategy
of taking his message directly to McCain's voters. He has to call
upon them to help him put an end to the hodgepodge foreign policy
of the past eight years, to Gore's allegiance to the hard left, to
the Clinton-Gore history of fund-raising abuses, to the missteps
with OPEC that led to today's high gas prices and to Gore's
politics of racial division a la Al Sharpton.
 &HT;    It isn't as if Bush were doomed without a McCain rapprochement _
a new USA Today poll shows the Texas governor 6 points ahead of
Gore.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, though, the beat goes on. McCain co-chair Warren
Rudman predicted disaster if Bush refuses to take up the McCain
campaign-finance mantle.
 &HT;    ``I don't think he'll do anything to hurt the ticket,'' Rudman
said disingenuously, ``but I'm not sure how much enthusiasm he'll
have for the ticket.''
 &HT;    This is the sort of low-grade political extortion that Bush
should spurn.
 &HT;    John McCain's voters were attracted to his straight talk,
honesty and toughness under pressure. It is foolhardy for Bush to
think that the way to attract those same voters is by scraping and
bowing to a man whom he handily defeated. 
 c.2000 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and a special election correspondent
for MSNBC. She is the author of the upcoming book, ``The Hillary
Trap: Looking for Power in All the Wrong Places,'' due from
Hyperion in June 2000.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.)
</P>
