<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, March 16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ In a pre-election warning to the people
of Taiwan, Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Ronghi reiterated China's
standard posture toward Taiwan: ``We must make it crystal clear. No
matter who comes to power in Taiwan, Taiwan will never be allowed
to be independent. This is our bottom line. This is also the will
of the 1.25 billion Chinese people.'' By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ The flavor of the Taiwanese
election including reaction to the Chinese prime minister's remarks
Wednesday in Beijing. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AFRICA-DIAMONDS (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security
Council on Wednesday debates the Fowler Commission report on
diamond trading and insurgency in Africa. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Days before Pope John Paul II's
arrival in Israel, the leading Muslim cleric pulls out of a
ecumenical meeting, hurting the chances that the pontiff's visit
will be a mission of reconciliation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WITHDRAWAL (Jerusalem) _ Israel's security Cabinet on
Wednesday narrowly approved a long-overdue Israeli troop withdrawal
from 6.1 percent of the West Bank, clearing the way for a
resumption of peace talks with the Palestinians in Washington next
week. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-BUDGET (Washington) _ Republicans on the House Budget
Committee push for their version of the federal budget. The White
House and congressional Democrats object that the measure paves the
way for tax and spending cuts that are far too deep. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ After three years, an
investigation clears the IRS of allegation that the agency ran
politically motivated audits of conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   DUAL-LANGUAGE-EDUC (Washington) _ Education Secretary Riley
talks about the state of education for Hispanics and challenges for
the next century. By Irvin Mototsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-PORN (Undated) _ The governor of Utah is expected to sign
legislation on Friday creating a ``porn czar'' for the state. The
position, an ombudsman in the state attorney general's office,
would help communities develop laws and standards for regulating
pornography and obscenity. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-UNIVERSITY (Undated) _ High-tech billionaire Michael
Saylor is donating $100 million to start an online university he
says will include videotaped lectures from the world's ``geniuses
and leaders,'' offering an ``Ivy Leage-quality'' education to
anyone _ free. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Story list to come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRIMATE-FOSSIL (Undated) _ Fossil bones of an animal no
bigger than a shrew and weighing less than an ounce have been
identified as belonging to the earliest known relative of the
primate lineage that led to monkeys, apes and eventually humans.
The wee animal lived 45 million years ago in a humid rainforest in
what is now China. It was probably a nocturnal and solitary
creature and fed on insects and fruit. The paleontologists who
announced the discovery Wednesday said the fossil animal, named
Eosimias for ``dawn monkey,'' was the best evidence yet for fixing
the time and place of one of the more fateful branchings in
evolution. By John Noble Wilford (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-DRUG (Undated) _ The FDA is investigating reports
that manufacturers of a controversial diabetes drug covered up
liver failure problems during the approval process. By Denise
Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER-FTC (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission
suspended its antitrust case to block BP Amoco's acquisition of
ARCO in light of a deal to sell all of ARCO's Alaskan assets to
Phillips Petroleum for more than $6 billion. Talks between the
government and BP Amoco appear close to reaching a settlement. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-STRATEGY (Undated) _ Looking at how the AOL-Time Warner
deal and other recent developments may have affected the strategies
of eBay and Yahoo. By Laura Holson and Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in afternoon trading. At
2:20 p.m. the Dow industrials were up 270 points, but the Nasdaq
index was down 50 points. Treasury prices were slightly higher.
European stock markets were lower: London was down 0.85 percent and
Frankfurt down 2.57 percent. Tokyo's Nikkei closed down 0.33
percent and Hong Kong ended down 1.07 percent. Crude oil was at
$30.80 a barrel in early New York trading. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   THAI-BANKRUPTCY (Singapore) _ Thai Petrochemical Industry has
been declared insolvent, paving the way for creditors to take
control of Thailand's largest delinquent debtor. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ London Stock Exchange members voted to
make the exchange a publicly traded company. The vote came as talks
for a broad European alliance of markets _ including London _
appeared to be dead, and the smaller Paris, Dutch and Belgium stock
exchanges said they are holding talks on a possible merger of their
three exchanges. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Jeff
Madrick, the editor of Challenge Magazine and adjunct professor of
social sciences at Cooper Union.
</P>
