</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MONEY _ You got it. George W. needs it. He's down below $10
million and out rattling the tin cup again, starting off tonight at
a war college (?) in a Chicago suburb. A look at the depleted Bush
finances as the guv hits the trail again. (Heath, Austin
American-Statesman). 20.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-VOTERS _ TAIPEI _ We've heard what diplomats and
academics and security experts have to say about the presidential
election in Taiwan. How do the people who live there feel about
their island's future and who will guide them through the next few
crucial years of dealings with China and the United States. A
short, colorful advance on the upcoming Taiwan presidential
election. Developing. (Chao, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: With box attached at end of story.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DALEY _ WASHINGTON _ U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley
addresses a National Press Club luncheon on ``China's Trade
Status.'' Developing. (Schultz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EST in (i) International and
(w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DIESEL _ WASHINGTON _ As the Environmental Protection Agency and
the petroleum industry gear up for a fight over whether diesel fuel
should be cleaned of sulfur and other pollutants, the national
association of clean air officials and an environmental group, the
Clean Air Trust, release data purporting to show how many cases of
cancer in numerous U.S. cities, including Atlanta, West Palm Beach
and Austin, are caused by diesel exhaust. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CONTENT _ WASHINGTON _ Americans with low incomes or
poor reading skills are being stranded on the information
superhighway because online information aimed at them is either
hard to find or nonexistent, according to a study released
Wednesday. (Turay, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COUPLE _ WASHINGTON _ Their kids miss the food of Austin:
Amy's ice cream. Thundercloud subs. Mangia's pizza. And the Tex-Mex
restaurants in the nation's capital can't compare to their hometown
jalapeno haunts, say Texas expatriates Cecile Richards and Kirk
Adams. But the politically attuned daughter of former Gov. Ann
Richards, her labor organizer husband, and their three children
apparently aren't following their appetites and calling the moving
vans any time soon. (Dart, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-HISPANICS _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard
Riley called Wednesday for Latinos to lead the way in helping
schools develop ``bi-literacy'' in English and one other language
for as many students as possible. Riley made what was billed as his
``first ever'' address on the state of Hispanic education.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers representing several
high-tech hot spots Wednesday joined forces to push for a sharp
increase in visas for highly skilled foreign workers. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 15 WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-COLLEGES _ WASHINGTON _ Students at the 13 historically
black colleges and universities with the highest default rates on
student loans will keep their eligibility for federal student
loans, the Education Department announced Wednesday. Some adopted
remediation programs and others managed to lower the percentage of
former students who fail to repay loans below the cutoff threshhold
of 25 percent. The schools include Central State University,
Wilberforce, Ohio; Huston-Tillotson, Austin, Texas, and Wiley
College, Marshall, Texas. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-BEACH _ OAK ISLAND, N.C. - Just weeks from the start of
vacation season, southeastern North Carolina beaches have yet to
recover from chronic erosion, worsened by Hurricane Floyd six
months ago. Some coastal experts predict that the state could lose
some of its hardest-hit beaches in the next generation, unless the
government pays for the pumping of sand to replenish the ocean
floor scrapped clean by five major hurricanes since 1996. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-FAME _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Princeville's unique history and
recent catastrophe have brought it fame in the wake of Hurricane
Floyd. But many other small towns and communities in eastern North
Carolina have been hit hard. Grifton, population 3,000, lost 300
homes, or one-quarter of its residences, in the flood. The Belvoir
community (unincorporated) was nearly completely under water. Has
Princeville's compelling story benefited it in the scramble for
flood relief dollars? (Moscoso, Greenville, Daily Reflector). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Second of six installments by the Greenville Daily
Reflector looking at Eastern North Carolina's recovery from
Hurricane Floyd on the six-month anniversary of the storm.
</P>
