<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-HNS &LR;      03-15 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INTERNET COMPANY LICENSES COMPETITOR'S MEDIA PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ RealNetworks, which publishes the popular
software that lets users listen to music over the Internet, has
announced that it is licensing software from a formidable foe: the
Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It is the result of a strategy that harks back to the Microsoft
behavior that embroiled the company in a historic antitrust battle
with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, called Windows Media Player, allows Microsoft to
gain a grip on an emerging Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows Media is poised to become an audio standard,'' Will
Poole, the general manager of Microsoft's digital media division,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Microsoft also announced
Tuesday that Yahoo, the world's most visited Web site, is licensing
the Microsoft technology.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes against a backdrop of fierce feuding
between Microsoft and RealNetworks. Rob Glaser, the RealNetworks
chief executive, has appeared as a witness in the federal antitrust
trial against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Glaser told the Senate Judiciary Committee
investigating Microsoft business practices that the company had
sabotaged a new version of Glaser's Real Audio audio player.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denied the charge and blamed Glaser's software for the
glitch. It also dismissed Glaser's complaints as the carping of a
disgruntled former employee. Glaser had worked at Microsoft in
Redmond, Wash., for 10 years before launching RealNetworks in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives bragged during Tuesday's announcement that
the Windows Media Player had gained an 80 percent share of the
Internet audio player market, according to New York-based Media
Metrix, an online ratings service.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight months ago, RealNetworks controlled 85 percent of the
Internet streaming market, according to Media Metrix, but that lead
was eaten away by Microsoft when the software titan included a free
copy of a full-featured Media Player with its Windows 98 and
Windows 2000 operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   RealPlayer has to be downloaded from the Internet. The company
charges $30 for a full version of its software.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks had no comment on Tuesday's announcements.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario, said Zona Research chief Internet analyst Clay
Ryder, recalls another bruising Internet battle: Microsoft's
death-cage match with Netscape Communications Corp. of Mountain
View.
</P>
<P>
   In that battle, Microsoft began distributing a free version of
its Web browsing software with its Windows operating system after
Netscape had captured a majority of the market with its Navigator
browser software. A browser lets a user view information on the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape withered and was acquired by America Online. Microsoft
emerged from that battle holding a lion's share of the browser
market _ and a federal judge's opinion that the company had engaged
in illegal corporate arm-twisting to gain that foothold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does have that flavor of a Netscape scenario,'' Ryder said.
``By including a free media player in their operating system, it
pushed out the company that charges for the software. It was
inevitable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
