<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7716 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-YAHOO-EBAY-HNS &LR;      03-15 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-EBAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YAHOO, EBAY WON'T COMMENT ON MERGER SPECULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yahoo Inc., the Internet's most popular
destination, and the on-line auction house eBay Inc. are not
commenting on reports that they are getting ready for a
cyber-marriage.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, the cable and Internet financial network, quoted unnamed
sources Tuesday as saying that Yahoo Inc. is considering buying
eBay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   EBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove said it is a company policy not
to comment on ``speculations, gossip, rumors or the like.''
Similarly, a Yahoo spokesman said, ``Yahoo doesn't comment on rumor
and speculation, and this is clearly what this all is.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Jerry Yang, the co-founder of Yahoo, said recently
that ``everyone wants to talk deals with us.''
</P>
<P>
   According to CNBC, ongoing delicate discussions between the two
companies range from a ``deep partnership'' to an outright eBay
buyout by Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Such a merger would create a company with a combined market
capitalization of some $116 billion, smaller than the $140
billion-plus market cap of Internet giant America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation is being fueled by the ongoing merger frenzy in
the media and Internet worlds, including the giant Time Warner/AOL
deal in January and this week's announcement that the parent
company of the Chicago Tribune will buy the Los Angeles Times and
other properties.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, according to CNBC, has been feeling pressures from these
acquisitions, which could end up creating entities that would
dilute its market lead.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has also been in reported talks with Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp., which has been actively seeking corporate alliances with
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   An eBay/Yahoo deal would make the on-line auction market a major
sales channel, said Munjal Shah, president and chief executive of
Andale Inc. in Mountain View. Andale publishes software to help
sellers track their Internet auction sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make the business world see this as a legitimate
e-commerce venue,'' he said. However, a merger could close Yahoo's
own auction sites, which don't charge for listings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
