<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STPATRICK-PRIMER-TEX     03-15 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STPATRICK-PRIMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ST. PATRICK'S DAY PRIMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHO WAS ST. PATRICK?
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick was the man responsible for converting most of the
Irish to Christianity. His life remains shrouded in mystery, with
most facts coming from the ``Confessions,'' written near his death.
He was born to a wealthy family in what is now Scotland near the
end of the fourth century. At 16, he was kidnapped by pirates and
sold into slavery. During his six-year captivity, he turned to
Christianity for strength.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he escaped and headed to Britain. According to his
writings, God had come to him in a dream and told him to leave
Ireland. While in Britain, Patrick wrote that an angel told him to
return to Ireland as a missionary. Most Irish people practiced a
nature-based religion at the time; however, there was a small
number of Christians on the island.
</P>
<P>
   For about 40 years Patrick was a missionary in Ireland,
baptizing, preaching, establishing churches and schools. He mingled
native Irish religion with Christianity in order to win converts.
It's believed that he died on March 17, around 460.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHEN DID ST. PATRICK'S DAY PARADES BEGIN?
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's Day has been observed as a religious holiday for
more than a thousand years in Ireland. On St. Patrick's Day, which
occurs during the Christian season of Lent, Irish families
traditionally attended church in the morning and celebrated in the
afternoon. Prohibitions against the consumption of meat were lifted
on St. Patrick's Day, and families ate, drank and danced in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The first St. Patrick's Day parade took place on March 17, 1762
in New York City. Irish soldiers serving in the English army
marched through the streets of New York City in an effort to
reconnect with their Irish heritage and meet fellow Irishmen
serving in the army.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAS ST. PATRICK'S DAY ALWAYS BEEN POPULAR IN AMERICA?
</P>
<P>
   Most Irish immigrants, until the mid-19th century, were part of
Ireland's Protestant middle class. In 1845, the Great Potato Famine
swept through Ireland, bringing almost a million poor, uneducated
Catholic Irish to America. They were greatly discriminated against
because of their religion and accents. When Irish-Americans filled
city streets to celebrate St. Patrick's Day, newspapers portrayed
them in cartoons as drunken, brawling monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Irish soon realized that their great numbers
afforded them strong political power. They organized a voting
block, known as the green machine, and became highly influential in
politics. In a snap, St. Patrick's Day parades, once a spectacle
subject to scorn, became a show of pride for Irish-Americans and a
must-attend event for political hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Today, St. Patrick's Day is celebrated in a number of countries,
including Canada and Australia. It has been celebrated even in
Japan, Russia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHY IS THE SHAMROCK ASSOCIATED WITH ST. PATRICK'S DAY?
</P>
<P>
   It's thought that St. Patrick used the shamrock, or three-leaf
clover, to convey the Christian doctrine of the Trinity. The
shamrock was also called a seamroy by the Celts. It was held sacred
in ancient Ireland because it symbolized the coming of spring.
After the English began to seize Irish land and prohibit the use of
Irish language and the practice of Catholicism, many Irish wore
shamrocks to symbolize pride in their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHY ARE LEPRECHAUNS ASSOCIATED WITH ST. PATRICK'S DAY?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lobaircin,'' meaning ``small-bodied fellow,'' is the Irish
name for leprechauns. In Celtic folk tales, leprechauns were cranky
little men who mended shoes and were known to use trickery to
protect their fabled treasure. Originally, they were not a part of
St. Patrick's Day. Walt Disney's 1959 movie ``Darby O'Gill and the
Little People,'' introduced Americans to a friendly, upbeat
leprechaun, totally different from the moody little guy of Irish
folklore. The cheerful leprechaun is an American invention that
quickly came to be associated with St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Javonna May-Mons
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
