<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7739 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GEORGE-LUCAS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-LUCAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENRIVORNMENTAL GROUPS ATTACK PRESIDIO PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GERALD D. ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sierra Club and eight other environmental
groups say the proposed George Lucas digital arts center at the
Presidio would produce serious water problems, require far too much
construction and violate the development plan for the new national
park.
</P>
<P>
   The charges, among the fiercest criticisms of the proposed Lucas
complex in a public document to date, are part of the Presidio
Trust's 423-page environmental appraisal that gauges how the
project may affect San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The critiques are directed at what would be the Presidio's
largest alteration contemplated by the trust, which runs the former
Army base. The Lucas project at the old Letterman Hospital site is
seen as the trust's principal cash cow, estimated to rake in $3.8
million to $5.7 million in revenue toward satisfying a
congressional demand that the Presidio raise its own $40 million
operating cost by 2013.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is the creator of the ``Star Wars'' films.
</P>
<P>
   With neighborhood support, Lucasfilm was chosen by the Presidio
Trust board of directors from among 17 rivals last June to develop
the 23-acre Letterman site with a research and film production
center, including a seven-acre green for public use.
</P>
<P>
   The nine environmental groups complain of ``significant flaws''
in the trust's draft environmental impact statement on the Lucas
center scheduled to be published Friday by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency. The groups charge that the proposal:
</P>
<P>
   _ Foresees more new construction of greater magnitude and
sensitivity than was contemplated in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fails to evaluate the effect on the Presidio's views, trees,
wildlife and visitor experiences.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lacks housing for the employees who would work there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Would cause ``serious water quality problems'' resulting from
a combination of sewer overflows from storm water and runoff,
problems that have led to ``numerous beach closures.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust, in its responses contained in the environmental
report, disputes the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest in a series of controversial issues to beset
the 200-year-old military installation since the Sixth Army pulled
out in 1995. In its wake, the National Park Service and, later, the
presidential-appointed Presidio Trust has taken over most of its
real estate, leaving the National Park Service to govern its
waterfront and beach areas under supervision of the Golden Gate
National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   One critic whose comments carry more than casual weight is
Hilary Gitelman, San Francisco's chief environmental review
officer, whose comments were similar to those of the Sierra Club
and allied conservation groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gitelman said that during wet weather, ``there is substantial
public concern about partially treated sewage'' from a city
sewage-treatment plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
