<P>
   HARLEM-RENEWAL (New York) _ The predominant language in
south-central Harlem these days is the language of renewal. This is
not the retail turnaround of 125th Street, the Main Street of
Harlem, with its glossy mall, its new Old Navy and corner
Starbuck's. This is a modest renaissance that encompasses renovated
brownstones, storefront restaurants and new church- and
mosque-sponsored condominiums. Once nearly destroyed by drugs,
crime and debilitation, the square mile area is on the way up. By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-DEVELOP (Wuensdorf, Germany) _ The train from Berlin to
Dresden makes a local stop at Wuensdorf, a dot on the map 25 miles
south of the German capital. For most of the past century,
Wuensdorf led a secret double life: a sleepy Prussian village
twinned with a forbidden city of soldiers. Now it is a city of
civilians _ the site of the biggest settlement project in Germany
whose success may inspire similar projects throughout eastern
Europe. By Jan Otakar Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-COLOR-PENS (Undated) _ A pen is a pen, you'd think.
Especially a ballpoint. You lose it, you buy another for $2.99.
They stop making your kind, you switch. No biggie. Except, the pen
is my life. Literally. Bic's four-color ballpoint is the organizing
principle of my Week At-A-Glance diary: blue for work-related
entries; red for personal; black for illness, public appearances
and acts of God; green for extra-curricular projects. Much more
than just a pen, it's my personal Palm Pilot. You know the pen I'm
talking about: fat plastic barrel with four plungers _ blue, red,
black and green. Maybe you had a BIC 4C in school and thought
they'd stopped making them. They haven't. What they have done is
changed them. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   GE-RECALL (Undated) _ Should consumers with defective GE
dishwashers rewire them or buy new ones? And how much of the cost
should GE pick up? From April 1983 to January 1989, General
Electric produced 3.1 million dishwashers with a defective slide
switch (Heated Dry/Energy Saver) that has the potential to melt or
ignite, creating a fire hazard. Although there have been no
injuries from the switch, there have been about 50 incidents, three
of which damaged homes. About 900,000 of the dishwashers were still
being used by consumers and property managers when the recall began
last year. By Rosalie Radomsky.
</P>
<P>
   NIKKO-FIRS (New York) _ The Nikko firs rose 70 feet over our
heads, their soft needles and elegant branching more suggestive of
a mountain on the coast of Japan than the rivers of traffic around
their home at the New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. But this
rare stand of 30 trees, which includes a few American and
Mediterranean firs, is in trouble. By Ann Raver.
</P>
