<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TRACKING-KIDS-ART     03-15 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRACKING-KIDS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HI, MOM. AT THE BEEP, LEAVE A MESSAGE. 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif., N.Y., Del.)   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
By KATIE HAFNER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since the time of chaperones and high-button shoes has there
been such a direct means of keeping tabs on children.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many parents have bought pagers and cell phones
to help them keep track of their teen-agers, although it is
impossible to say just how many. A result is a new balance in the
perennial struggle between parents' desire to know what their
teen-agers are doing (and where, and when, and with whom) and the
teen-agers' desire to have their parents back off.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may be happier with the electronic ties than their
teen-agers are. True, many teen-agers consider their pagers and
cell phones instruments of liberation, but others view them as yet
another means by which their parents can exert control. Annoyed at
constantly being summoned, they either insist that their parents do
so less often or they find ways to beat the system.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-year-old Zan Morris, a ninth grader in San Anselmo,
Calif., an affluent community north of San Francisco, has owned a
pager for six months. Originally, Zan said, she wanted a pager so
her friends could get in touch with her. But now most of the pages
seem to come not so much from her friends as from her mother, she
said, and she is having second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just complicates matters, really,'' Zan said. ``Now it's
like I have kind of a dog chain on. If she pages me, I have to call
her back. She always has some kind of access to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she got her pager, Zan said, ``it felt almost as if I had
a little more freedom.'' She added that life with a pager made her
``feel kind of overwhelmed and cramped, like my personal space is
being invaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Fontaine, 16, a high school junior who lives in Brooklyn,
N.Y., has had her pager for four months. Although her mother does
not page her too much, sometimes Brooke has trouble figuring out
why her mother pages her at certain times and not at others, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, if she calls home and can't get through
because I'm online or something, she'll page me,'' Brooke said.
``Other times, if I'm out with my friends and she doesn't know
where I am, she won't beep me.''
</P>
<P>
   Educating one's parents in the ways of appropriate pager and
cell phone use is important, those teen-agers with more experience
say.
</P>
<P>
   Maura Tuohy, 18, a high school senior in San Francisco, has had
her pager for two years and has reached a happy medium with her
mother. ``My mom doesn't page me on whims, like to ask me where I
put the cereal,'' Maura said. ``She just pages me if she wants to
know where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   At Maura's school, Lowell High School in San Francisco, Ray
Cordoba, a dean of students, estimates that about half of the
school's nearly 2,700 students carry pagers or cell phones, even
though that is against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Maura and her mother also have codes to convey the urgency of
the page. Including 911 in the numeric message means that Maura
should call right away; 811 is less important, and 711 is ``call
whenever,'' Maura said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, pager codes are usually reserved for
friends. Maura and her friends use a set of codes popular among
teen-agers for conveying particular messages. Each number stands
for a letter or combination of letters. Some number sequences have
a meaning, too, like ``143'' for ``I love you,'' or ``411'' for
``What's going on?''
</P>
<P>
   Robi Tse, a classmate of Maura's, said she had listed the codes
for her mother. ``But she only knows `call home' or `call Mom,'''
Robi said. ``And that's all I want her to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teen-agers have gone to more extreme lengths to keep their
parents out of their social lives. Many of the teen-agers
interviewed said they kept their parents at arm's reach by doing
things like turning off their cell phones or telling white lies
about dead batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Broude, 17, has had a pager for four years but has
tried to keep it a secret from her parents. That frees her to use
it to communicate with her friends _ and only with her friends.
``If my parents knew I had a pager, I don't think I'd keep it,''
said Danielle, who subscribes to the pager-as-leash school of
thought, at least if parents are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, however, Danielle's pager shows up around the
house. ``They've found it five or six times,'' she said, which has
led her to believe that her parents are on to her secret. What does
she tell her parents? ``I think up lies,'' she replied, ``like,
`Oh, it's Kathleen's, but she's out of town, so she let me borrow
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are increasingly common among teen-agers, as
prepayment options give parents control over the volume of calls
and family plans reduce the cost of calls between parents and
children. A survey of 1,502 American households conducted last June
found that children had cell phones in 7 percent of families with
children, said Ken Hyers, an industry analyst with Cahners In-Stat
Group, the market research firm that conducted the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, however, not all teen-agers want to move from
pagers to cell phones, even given the higher level of status that a
cell phone offers.
</P>
<P>
   Some who were interviewed for this article said that if they had
a cell phone, they would not have enough time to think up a
plausible alibi before speaking with a parent. Receiving a page, on
the other hand, gives them ample time to fine-tune a story before
calling back.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Gonzalez, a high school senior in San Francisco, explained
why a teen-ager with a pager might encourage his or her parents to
stick to pager communications instead of calling the place where
the parents expect the teen-ager to be. ``If kids are spending the
night at places where their parents don't want them to be,'' she
explained, ``they can manipulate things by saying, `Just page
me.''' That, in effect, prevents the parent from knowing where the
child actually is. ``Lots of kids get away with it,'' Elena added.
</P>
<P>
   That may prove to be a short-lived ploy, however, as wireless
devices with built-in Global Positioning System trackers start to
come on the market. That represents a teen-ager's nightmare: being
in a position where parents can track every move.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Elena said her parents generally paged her only if they needed
her _ or, she added, if they found a hole in her account of where
she was or what she was doing. ``If your parents page you, it's `uh
oh, I'm in trouble,''' she said. ``So you find a quiet room and
call them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Endress, a high school senior in Greenbrae, Calif., north of
San Francisco, said she was glad that her parents had a way to
reach her. ``It has actually helped my parents loosen up a lot,''
she said. ``I think they like the fact that if I'm out late or if
I'm going to the city or far away, they can always get ahold of me.
It's definitely given me more freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   But that freedom is closely managed, from both sides. Some
months ago, Ali lost her pager. ``It just disappeared,'' she said.
``My parents didn't believe me at first because I quote lost it so
many times before, so it took a while for them to understand that I
had actually lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she now had a cell phone with one especially attractive
feature: ``When it rings, it has built-in Caller ID. And if it says
Home is calling, I can hit a button and it sends it to the voice
mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teen-agers are unwilling to carry around any kind of
in-loco-parentis technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Evan Losow, 16, a high school junior in Queens,
N.Y., who uses neither a cell phone nor a pager. `It's a leash at
this age,'' he said. ``When I'm out of the house, I'm out for a
reason. I really don't want people to contact me. If I'm in school,
the only people who need to contact me are my friends, and they're
there with me.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents trust him, Evan said. ``When I say I'm going to a
movie or wherever, they trust me,'' he said. ``If something
happens, I have quarters with me, and I just use a pay phone.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still early for many academic studies of pager and cell
phone use, but for some who study families, the technology offers a
new twist on an old theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have always felt kind of tethered _ that's part of being
a teen-ager,'' said Laurence Steinberg, a psychology professor at
Temple University.
</P>
<P>
   Pagers and cell phones can be a good thing for teen-agers, he
said. ``They probably end up giving them more freedom, not less,
but in a good way,'' Steinberg said, ``because one of the
challenges that faces parents and teens today that didn't face them
25 years ago was the challenge of having two parents out working,
with different schedules and travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said that in research on latchkey children, employers
reported that the quality of their employees' work began to slip
after 3 p.m. every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't get any good work out of them because they were
so worried about where their kids were,'' Steinberg said. ``But now
if this technology has made it easier for working parents to stay
in touch with their kids, that's a win-win-win situation. Good for
parents, good for kids and good for employers.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, that is, if you can keep tabs on the pager itself. Pagers
are small, and teen-agers are famously absent-minded. Pagers are
routinely swept under beds, left on hot dashboards, dropped on hard
pavement and put through the wash.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty of the pager's whereabouts raises the anxiety
level a notch or two, not necessarily for the teen-agers but for
the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's not wearing the pager and I page her several times, I
get more uptight or anxious,'' said Zan Morris' mother, Gail,
``because I think, `Wait a minute, she's got a pager.'''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Tse, Robi's mother, has similar frustrations. ``Sometimes
she leaves it at home and it's buzzing like crazy,'' Tse said.
``One night I was paging her and I could hear it in the other
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamara Hareven, a professor of family studies and history at the
University of Delaware, said that apart from the chaperones who
went along on many dates at the beginning of the 20th century, she
saw few precedents for the kind of supervision a parent gets with a
pager or cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Hareven said, the principle of parental supervision
of teen-agers' behavior has been in place since the age of the
Puritans, who were so concerned about disciplining their teen-age
children properly that they sent them to live in other people's
homes. ``Parents did not trust themselves to sufficiently
discipline their own teen-age children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always an anxiety about raising them properly, and
about their conforming to basic rules,'' Hareven said. But the
numerous attempts on the part of parents to supervise the behavior
of young adults were not necessarily effective even during the
Puritans' time, she added, because even the Puritans were
confronted by premarital pregnancies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
