<HEADLINE>
DO FLOPPIES WEAR OUT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Can floppy disks go bad over time? Are recordable CDs a more
permanent solution for long-term data archiving?
</P>
<P>
   A. A year seems to be the expected life span of floppies, but
your mileage may vary with frequency of use and how you store them.
Conditions like heat, humidity, dust and dirt can affect the
magnetic surface of the disk, causing erosion that takes your
stored files with it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the data is stored magnetically, exposure to nearby
magnetic fields (including other floppies) can cause problems as
well. To preserve the lives of your floppy disks for as long as
possible, keep them in a cool, dry place, away from dust, and try
not to stack them on top of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Recordable CDs, or CD-Rs, do have a much longer life span when
stored properly and are better for long-term storage. CDs, which
record data optically when a laser etches the data into dye on the
reflective surface of the disc, are not affected my magnetic
fields, although heat, dirt and dust can alter the reflective
surface and cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   CD-Rs made with cyanine, a dye that gives them a greenish color,
are thought to last between 70 and 100 years, while gold-colored
discs made with phthalocyanine dye have a life expectancy of 200
years, based on accelerated-age testing.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to humidity, sunlight or harsh cleaning solutions can
gradually break down the dye on the disc's surface, rendering the
data on it unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   CD-RWs, rewritable CDs that let you copy and recopy data to the
disc, have a shorter life expectancy than CD-Rs _ an estimated 30
years. CD-ROMs, which are not recordable, are sturdier and thought
to last about 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   To safely store your CDs, keep them out of the sun and wipe off
smudges and fingerprints with a soft, lint-free cloth. Ballpoint
pens can scratch the surface, so use a felt-tip marker to write on
the disc if you need to label it. Handle your CDs by the edge and
keep them in their cases in a cool place with low humidity for the
best care.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
