<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MORALS-EDUC-ART-NYT &LR;      03-15 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORALS-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORAL ISSUES GINGERLY FIND A PLACE IN CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NINA SIEGAL  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In Kiersten L. Johnson's 10th-grade humanities class,
students have been asked to consider the nature of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pops a tape into the VCR, and the 15 students, seated in
two facing banks of metal desks, watch a news report by Bill Moyers
on South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission. They become
somber as a black victim of police torture tells how he was dangled
from a window of the room where Steve Biko, the anti-apartheid
leader, was fatally beaten. The tape rolls on and the moral issues
become more complex. A white South African faces three young black
militants who killed his wife in a fusillade of bullets and
grenades during a 1993 attack on a church in a Cape Town suburb.
</P>
<P>
   As they shift edgily in their seats, the students grapple with a
thorny question: Is it morally easier to pardon the actions of the
militants than the white police torturers?
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have whipped him and let him off,'' says Diaby
Moyabi Mohammad, 16, referring to the black militant who apologized
for the attack on the church. ``Some people just wanted to hear the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay Dawson, 15, disagrees. ``I think you should take
responsibility, but there should also be punishment,'' he says,
arguing that the man should face the death penalty. ``Because
without punishment there are no consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's class, at the East Side Community High School on the
Lower East Side, is nearing the end of the kind of course that once
would have been confined to explicitly religious schools or private
institutions like the Ethical Culture School. Her students are not
only learning world history and politics, but how to make hard
moral choices in a world of both apartheid and terrorists fighting
its injustice, a world of Holocausts and of bystanders who never
protested its horrors.
</P>
<P>
   This particular program is called Facing History and Ourselves
and is one of a number being taught in the New York City region as
moral education has found a growing place in American schools.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the upsurge reflects a growing concern about school
violence. ``Every time you hear of a school shooting, there's a
renewed cry for this,'' said Joan F. Goodman, a professor at the
Graduate School of Education at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   But the push for lessons in ethics also comes from educators,
who perceive an unsettling shift in students' attitudes and
behavior, said Karen E. Bohlin, director for the Center for the
Advancement of Ethics and Character at Boston University,
</P>
<P>
   ``Many teachers testify that there is a growing lack of respect
for other human beings in terms of language, basic courtesy and
bullying, just a real breakdown in healthy relationships,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, New York State received a $1 million federal grant for
``character education,'' to support pilot programs in four school
districts to teach ``caring, self-reliance, trustworthiness, and
open-mindedness,'' among other virtues.
</P>
<P>
   When the programs begin in September, said Vito J. Borello,
president of Every Person Influences Children, the nonprofit group
that is managing the funds, it will be the first time the state has
specifically focused on teaching morality. Yet New York is
certainly not the first state to enter the game. Character-building
classes are now officially mandated in 10 states _ up from five
just two years ago _ and such classes are encouraged in seven other
states, said Esther F. Schaeffer, executive director of the
Character Education Partnership, a national nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the Facing History curriculum, which usually
centers on the Holocaust but also has classes on the apartheid and
civil rights eras, is being taught in about 200 of the city's
public and private schools, including the Center School and the
Dual Language Middle School, both in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Such lessons are not without their critics. Some feel the
promotion of virtue in the classroom can easily border on religious
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right is worried it's going to be excessively liberal and
permissive humanism,'' Goodman said. ``The political left is
concerned that schools are going to start preaching to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Others criticize some of the programs for having a prefabricated
curriculum, which may produce orderly behavior but does not build
character. ``Many of those commercial programs even have
multiple-choice questions to measure kids' absorption of the
correct virtues,'' said Alfie Kohn, an author who writes about
moral education. ``Some contain simplistic little stories, at the
end of which the lead character says, ``I will never be selfish
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took a weeklong course with Facing History, a nonprofit
organization created in 1976 by Margo Stern Strong, a middle school
teacher in Brookline, Mass. Its programs now reach about a million
students each year. Johnson said she wanted to incorporate moral
lessons into her curriculum not for fear of gunfire in her
classroom, but because these particular teaching methods would
strengthen her humanities course work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in 10th grade and all they care about is their
existence,'' she said. ``We're using that natural curiosity about
the self and the identity and layering it on the curriculum to get
them interested.''
</P>
<P>
   The students grapple with material that is tough for many
adults, like the degradation of European Jews that eventually led
to the Holocaust, or attacks on black children who integrated
schools in the South.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the students are asked to turn history's lessons
on themselves. One of Johnson's students, Ila K. McCall, 15, said
her teacher asked her whether she viewed the homeless any
differently after learning that the white South African government
once regularly seized property from blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at people on the street and saying `Yuck,''' she
said. ``But now I know that just because you live on the street
doesn't mean you're not a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's students did not go home with a featherweight load. As
she concluded her section on the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, Jason A. Pizarro, 16, remarked that some black
militants were probably responding to the conditions in which they
were reared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you grow up in violence, is that an excuse for violence?''
Johnson asked as the class came to an end. ``Most of us have
witnessed violence in our own lives. If we think that's the case,
how do we ever achieve peace?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
