<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WITHDRAWAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND THE PALESTINIANS AGREE ON LATEST WEST BANK HANDOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Overcoming a dispute that had frozen peace efforts
for weeks, Israel and the Palestinians agreed Wednesday on the area
of a further handover of West Bank territory to Palestinian
control, and the transfer was approved by the Israeli security
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement removed a persistent stumbling block to the
resumption of negotiations on a permanent peace. The talks are
scheduled to resume on March 20 in Washington before moving back to
the Middle East, with the aim of reaching a framework agreement in
May and a final peace accord by September 13.
</P>
<P>
   The latest handover, which is supposed to be ratified at a
meeting of the full Israeli Cabinet on Sunday, will put another 6.1
percent of the West Bank under full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators agreed on maps delineating
the areas to be handed over, and the transfer is expected to take
place as early as Sunday, leaving the Palestinians in full or
partial control of 42.9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The areas to be ceded by Israel include several Palestinian
villages and towns around the cities of Ramallah, Bethlehem and
Hebron. Palestinian officials said they chose the areas from a map
of 10 percent of the West Bank submitted by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians had suspended negotiations last month,
complaining that the Israelis were trying to dictate the terms of
the land transfer without prior consultation.
</P>
<P>
   However, demands by the Palestinians to receive villages
adjacent to East Jerusalem, which they view as their future
capital, were not met, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel decided against a proposed
handover of the village of Anata, abutting Jerusalem's city limits,
after members of his fractious coalition, including right-leaning
ministers in his Cabinet, raised strong objections. The decision
highlighted Barak's political vulnerability as he tries to forge a
peace agreement while keeping his coalition together.
</P>
<P>
   Education Minister Yossi Sarid of the leftist Meretz party, who
abstained in Wednesday's security Cabinet vote, said that the map
of areas to be handed to the Palestinians had ``been drawn with a
coalition pencil,'' raising questions about Barak's freedom to
maneuver in the more weighty negotiations that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, the leader of the opposition Likud party, said
that in consulting with the Palestinians about the areas of
withdrawal, Barak had ``folded,'' and a Likud statement accused the
prime minister of ``surrendering to the dictates'' of the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials said that they expected to receive areas
near East Jerusalem in a third and final Israeli pullback under the
terms of interim self-rule accords. That withdrawal, still to be
negotiated, is supposed to leave Israel in control of only
settlements and military locations, but the interpretation of those
terms remains in sharp dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on a permanent peace will focus on the most profoundly
divisive issues separating the two sides: the future of Jerusalem,
settlements, Palestinian refugees, and the delineation of borders.
</P>
<P>
   The security Cabinet also approved the release of an undisclosed
number of Palestinian prisoners on the forthcoming Muslim holiday
of Eid al-Adha, the Feast of the Sacrifice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
