<HEADER>
A7796 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WOMEN-ELECTRONICS     03-15 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WOMEN-ELECTRONICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING WOOFERS AND TWEETERS TO THE SANER SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(lh) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My husband and I see eye to eye on a lot of life's important
issues, including the wisdom of sleeping in, traveling without
children and dark rum over light. But when it comes to buying
stereo speakers, there is some mild disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``What are those huge, huge, ugly brown tower things sitting
in the middle of the living room? And where did you put the
couch?''
</P>
<P>
   Him: ``I moved it to the kitchen so it wouldn't distort the
sound. Listen to that bass.''
</P>
<P>
   Me (screaming to be heard over blaring stereo): ``Why do I see
seven separate cords running across the floor?''
</P>
<P>
   Him (playing air guitar): ``Eight. I'll tape them down.''
</P>
<P>
   I always thought the reason we had such conflicting attitudes
was obvious. I have taste and he, well, is insane. But now, some
people who sell those big, loud, blaring stereo things online tell
me that I have been wrong. It turns out that my husband and I are
cliches in the battle of the sexes. In other words, the old
stereotype is true: Men love electronics. Women don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical marketing words like `room-shaking bass' and `big
black box' just do not appeal to women,'' said Maria Cataldo, a
spokeswoman for Hifi.com, which has been selling consumer
electronics online since 1994. ``Last year we surveyed 1,000 women
and found that more than 50 percent said they were intimidated
about buying consumer electronics. But at the same time, women
account for 22 percent of consumer electronics sales, so it was
crazy that their needs have not been met.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding that women were an untapped market, Hifi.com last month
introduced a sort of sister site, called Herhifi.com
(www.herhifi.com).
</P>
<P>
   Herhifi.com sells the same 900 stereos, televisions, DVD
players, speakers and radios as Hifi.com but in a very different
way. For instance, in addition to listing products in traditional
categories like home theater, multimedia or video, Herhifi.com
sells things by room. So if you want to buy a stereo, you can click
on Living Room.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard about the strategy, my first reaction was negative.
I figured that sort of approach must be bad, because it would
perpetuate stereotypes about male and female roles. I also thought
it sounded condescending toward women; I don't see anyone rushing
to put up Web sites like Hiswallpaper.com aimed at
shopping-impaired men. And worst, I thought it might give my
husband (who just last week bought a new roll of wide black duct
tape) the mistaken impression that he was sane, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But then I tested both Herhifi.com and Hifi.com, and I have to
say, I liked Herhifi.com a lot more than Hifi.com, which gave me a
headache with its screaming orange and blue type, its animated DVD
players and a headline that announced a ``Surround Sound Sale.'' In
contrast, Herhifi.com offered tasteful backgrounds of pale yellow,
deep purple and leaf green, an uncluttered design and a picture of
a woman with hair like me washing her face in a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   After I clicked on Shop by Room, the screen filled with the
sorts of soothing, gentle images _ including a sun-filled dining
room and a bunch of purple grapes drying beside a kitchen sink _
that I would expect to see in a home decorating magazine (yes, I
indulge) but not a consumer electronics catalog.
</P>
<P>
   I clicked on the grapes and arrived at a carefully edited
selection of items in four categories _ phones, shelf stereo
systems, televisions and radios _ appropriate for use in the
kitchen. The $49.99 Sony Kitchen Clock Radio, for example, can be
mounted under a kitchen cabinet. It comes in a nice, clean shade of
white.
</P>
<P>
   But I was a little concerned when I read the description: ``Its
clock doubles as a kitchen timer.'' Had I found evidence of sexism?
Did this language imply that I, as a woman, would be more likely to
need a kitchen timer than a man?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, I gritted my teeth against the orange blare and
used Hifi.com's Shop by Product search feature. I clicked on Home
Audio and then on the Radios subcategory and arrived at a long list
that included the Sony clock radio. The description was the same;
Hifi.com acknowledged the fact that men, too, need kitchen timers.
</P>
<P>
   During another 20 minutes of searching, I realized I could not
find one thing on the Herhifi.com site that offended me. In fact, I
actually appreciated the Knowledge Builder feature, which answered
some of the questions that have been bugging me, like: ``What size
TV do I need? Is there such a thing as too big or too small?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was because the site's color scheme mimicked my dining
room's, but after a while, I realized that for the first time in my
life, I felt like buying electronics items. Shaken, I logged off
and sought advice from Tina Pieraccini, a communications studies
professor at the State University of New York at Oswego, whose
research focuses on the effects of media on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is going to be very much like magazines have been
since the 1700s, targeting very specific audiences in different
ways,'' she said. ``I would be concerned if these sites were very
sexist, but it doesn't sound as if they are; they're just appealing
in different ways. I think there are going to be a lot more of
these sites popping up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Autobytel.com, which sells cars online, is another
example, having recently introduced a For Her informational section
for female car buyers. For Her offers articles on topics like how
to keep your tires in top condition and tips on remaining calm when
there is a teen-age driver in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that women are not necessarily as interested in
the same things men are when they are shopping for cars,'' said
Tracey McCarter, who directs Autobytel's women's programs. ``But
that doesn't mean we're coddling women. We have information both
about safety and about horsepower.''
</P>
<P>
   This online trend of selling to the sexes will continue.
Considering the cost of doing business in a physical space in the
real world, the Internet is a cheap laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Web, you have the opportunity to present people with an
almost infinite variety of approaches,'' said Roland T. Rust, a
management professor at Vanderbilt University whose research
focuses on advertising and customer satisfaction. ``What these
sites are trying to do in their initial halting, crude way is to
create a personal experience that's unique to the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   So we can expect even more of this _ shopping sites aimed at
teen-agers who like a certain band or dog lovers who own two or
more Border collies. People who like the song ``American Pie.'' The
far larger group of (sane) people who hate the song. I know I was
disappointed to learn that the domain name DarkRum.com is no longer
available.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail address: Slatalla(at)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
