r a BC-CIVILWAR-SLAVERY-TEX     03-15 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-SLAVERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH FOUGHT TO PRESERVE SLAVERY, HISTORIANS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Texas _ It's not only South Carolina. The Confederate
battle flag remains a potent symbol, angering some, pleasing
others, right here in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the current debate is research into what Southern
soldiers actually thought they were fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding of the relationship between slavery and the
Civil War changed before the war, during the war and every decade
since the war,'' said Ed Ayers, a University of Virginia historian.
``The trick is to realize that slavery was absolutely fundamental
to the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the South went to war, a powerful wave of Confederate
patriotism swept the region, and many whites marched off to war to
defend their home and hearth, many scholars say. Although few
Confederates discussed slavery in their letters and diaries,
significantly, none wrote in favor of abolition.
</P>
<P>
   Buster Wayne Desselles Jr., 41, a colorful fringe candidate in
Tuesday's Democratic primary for a Texas Legislature seat, is so
convinced that the Confederate icon is a positive symbol that he
used its design for dozens of campaign yard signs.
</P>
<P>
   Running in Navarro, Henderson and Freestone counties, which make
up District 12, he printed 2,500 fliers with a photo of himself
dressed as a rebel general leaning against a draped battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   The East Texas freight-line pilot, who describes himself as
``hanging off the right side'' of the Democratic party, said he
used the flag ``as an attention getter,'' noting ``all of the
recent hoopla'' about it in South Carolina, Texas and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People has called for the removal of Confederate plaques
from the Texas Supreme Court building, the end to the practice of
flying the battle flag at schools and the scrapping of a planned
Confederate monument outside the Grimes County Courthouse in
Anderson, north of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. George W. Bush said he would look into the issue
of the Supreme Court plaque. Before the Republican Primary in South
Carolina, Bush said the state's residents should decide whether the
battle flag should continue flying over the state Capitol. This
presents a clear point of difference with Democratic presidential
contender Al Gore, who has urged South Carolinians to take down the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   To many Southern whites, the plaques and battle flag recall a
noble but lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   Most African-Americans contend that that cause was the
preservation of slavery, which many whites in the region dispute,
saying that the war was fought over states' rights and inequitable
tariffs. Complicating the issue has been the wholesale adoption of
the flag as an emblem by the Ku Klux Klan and other white racist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   But what did Johnny Reb himself think he was fighting for?
</P>
<P>
   The answer that slavery was a fundamental cause for the
secession won't please descendants of Confederate soldiers.
Although it hasn't filtered down to much of the Southern public,
much research has been done in recent years on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers has launched an ambitious Web site _
http:/valley.vcdh.virginia.edu _ that chronicles the wartime views
of two Shenandoah Valley communities, one Northern, the other
Southern. It taps letters, diaries, military records and 30,000
pages from local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Virginia community, they are always determined to keep
slavery,'' said Ayers, a native Tennessean. ``That's a constant.
But the strategies they used to keep slavery varied widely. The
answer is not going to fit on a bumper sticker.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 book, ``For Cause &AMP; Comrades'' by Pulitzer Prize winner
James M. McPherson of Princeton University, is based on 25,000
letters and 249 diaries of Civil War soldiers from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   A far higher percentage of Northern soldiers cited in the book
debated slavery in their writings than their Southern foes. Only 20
percent of 429 Rebels mentioned slavery, while more than twice that
percentage of Yankees did.
</P>
<P>
   Although slavery and emancipation were contentious issues in the
North, the South just didn't have a need to rehash the arguments,
McPherson said.
</P>
<P>
   Confederate enlisted men and officers, he found, ``took slavery
for granted as one of the Southern `rights' and institutions for
which they fought and did not feel compelled to discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   McPherson noted that although just ``20 percent of the soldiers
avowed explicit pro-slavery purposes in their letters and diaries,
none at all dissented from that view.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's asked the war's causes, McPherson gives a two-part
answer:
</P>
<P>
   After Abraham Lincoln was elected president without a single
Southern electoral vote, the South seceded because it could no
longer control the political situation for the long-term survival
of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Once the war started, Confederate soldiers fought to defend
their homes, their country, their constitution. And that's what
many contemporary white Southerners dwelt on, although virtually
all university-based, professional historians accept the view that
slavery was the underpinning cause of the war, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Historians said most Confederate letter writers used euphemisms
for ``preserving slavery,'' saying they fought to protect
``Southern liberties and institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But some were blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country without slave labor would be completely
worthless,'' William Nugent, a lieutenant with a Mississippi
regiment, wrote to his wife in 1863. ``We can only live &AMP; exist by
that species of labor: and hence I am willing to fight to the
last.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vandals of the North ... are determined to destroy
slavery,'' a young Kentucky physician, Lunsford Yandell Jr., wrote
his slave-owning relatives. ``We must all fight, and I choose to
fight for Southern rights and Southern liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that a sense of honor, patriotism and a
desire to defend one's home from ``rapacious Yankees'' were not
important motivating factors in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go to war for all sorts of reasons,'' said Joseph T.
Glatthaar, a military historian at the University of Houston and
author of three Civil War books. ``But the reality is that the
Southerners knew they were fighting for the institution of
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   When Southerners marched off to war, they clearly knew what
their leaders had decreed, Glatthaar said.
</P>
<P>
   The first reason Mississippi cited in its declaration of
secession was the ``institution of slavery, the greatest material
interest of the world.'' When Texas seceded, it cited ``the
servitude of the African to the white race'' as justification and
simultaneously outlawed the freeing of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Confederate Vice President Alexander Stephens declared that the
new nation's ``cornerstone rests upon the great truth that the
Negro is not equal to the white man; that slavery ... is his
natural and normal condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Southerners argue that the war couldn't have been fought
over slavery because only 25 percent of Confederate soldiers owned
slaves. But slaveholding represented wealth and status in the South
and many of those not in the slave-owning class strove to join it,
said Steven Woodworth, a historian at Texas Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a universal human characteristic that everyone wants to
believe their heritage contains noble elements,'' Ayers said.
``Just being defensive and refusing to acknowledge the full
complexity of the situation faced by our ancestors doesn't honor
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice isn't Simon Legree and Robert E. Lee,'' Ayers said,
referring to the evil slave driver of ``Uncle Tom's Cabin'' and
Lee, the respected Confederate commander. ``Many Southerners
balanced a love for Union and belief that slavery was God's plan
for America but were tortured by it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Barry Shlachter is a staff writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7718, or e-mail:
bshlachter(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
