<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FOUR-COLOR-PENS-NYT &LR;      03-15 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUR-COLOR-PENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIC MAN LAMENTS:   IT'S MY PEN! DON'T CHANGE IT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pen is a pen, you'd think. Especially a ballpoint. You lose
it, you buy another for $2.99. They stop making your kind, you
switch. No biggie.
</P>
<P>
   No. Biggie.
</P>
<P>
   My pen is my life. Literally. Bic's four-color ballpoint is the
organizing principle of my day-planner diary: blue for work-related
entries; red for personal; black for illness, public appearances
and acts of God; green for miscellaneous ``creative projects.''
Much more than just a pen, it's my Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   You know the pen I'm talking about: fat plastic barrel with four
plungers _ blue, red, black and green _ at the top. Maybe you had
one in school and thought they stopped making them. They haven't.
What they have done is changed them in a small but unsettling way.
</P>
<P>
   The change that threw my system out of whack is not even a
functional one, but an aesthetic issue. The blue plunger at the top
of the medium-point pen was always the same color as the bottom
half of the barrel: light blue. They matched. Then, suddenly, they
didn't. The plunger is now navy.
</P>
<P>
   A person would have to be both a design fetishist and obsessive
about this particular pen even to notice a detail like this. I am
that person.
</P>
<P>
   Like my writer friend who says magazine redesigns give him
anxiety attacks, or the legions of M&AMP;M traditionalists who freaked
out when they brought in blue, I realized that the god of small
things is vengeful indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Switching to keyboard control, I e-mailed the Bic Corp. in
Milford, Conn. Although Bic 4Cs are still stamped ``Made in
France'' (by Bic's French parent company), they are packaged here.
I asked what the deal was with the new color and got an explanation
from Linda K. Kwong in corporate communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change you noted was made to be closer to the actual blue
ink color,'' she e-mailed back.
</P>
<P>
   Such literalism! After all these years, consumers are actually
going to think that a light-blue plunger means light-blue ink? Is
this really a concern worthy of the attentions of a global
conglomerate that sells 21 million stationery products a day?
</P>
<P>
   I pummeled Kwong with more questions.
</P>
<P>
   _ When was the 4C introduced?
</P>
<P>
   _ When was the color of the plunger changed to navy?
</P>
<P>
   _ When would I be able to speak to Bruno Bich, who has run the
company since his father, Baron Marcel Bich, died in 1994?
</P>
<P>
   She politely obliged:
</P>
<P>
   _ The baron (pronounced  &UR; beek)  &LR; introduced the pen in France in
April 1970, a year later in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ The covert color change occurred in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monsieur Bich was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   No sales figures on the 4C would be released. ``Fun factoids''
were offered instead. The pen is a favorite among students and
nurses, who use different colors on medical charts for each shift.
The first advertisement in France boasted ``3 francs for 4
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a fine-point version, with a bright orange barrel,
but I prefer the medium-point.
</P>
<P>
   Kwong noted that the 4C ``has a unique little white ball at the
top (representing the famous `Bic boy' head _ from the Bic
trademark) that was used to dial a number on the old rotary
phones.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``old rotary phones'' line made me feel as much like a
kooky '70s relic as the pen. I do remember my mother using a
two-color blue-and-red version back then so she could do double
crossword puzzles. But I wasn't using the 4C for nostalgic reasons.
I didn't seek it out until about five years ago when I started this
obsessive-compulsive rainbow diary thing. Also because it looks
cool and no one else I know uses one. The only other person I've
ever seen brandish a 4C was a young city reporter. ``You never run
out of ink,'' he said flatly, pointing to an attribute that never
would have occurred to me.
</P>
<P>
   Fixated on the pen as industrial design object, I tried to find
out who invented it. The Bic people were no help here. They cited
only an ``internal team.'' Many of the 20th century's most
innovative product designers were fated to corporate anonymity,
said Donald Albrecht, a guest curator at the National Design
Triennial at the Cooper-Hewitt museum. ``Trying to reclaim the
history of these things is really hard,'' he said. ``The brand
becomes the designer, and the company forgets after a while who
designed its products.''
</P>
<P>
   I then e-mailed Steven Skov Holt, another curator of the
Triennial. Holt calls himself a ``visionary and vice president of
creative culture'' at Frog Design, a product and graphic design
firm based in San Francisco. He relayed the following thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   ``On the positive side, the Bic 4C represented one of the early
triumphs of democracy-in-design action. The pen was made to be
popular, accessible and inexpensive. The consumer was given a
semblance of choice, with each of the pen's cardinal directions
representing a particular color ink. Arguably, it was part of a
small group of products that combined over a period of time to
create the `expectation of color choice' that today's iMac has so
compellingly capitalized on.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued:
</P>
<P>
   ``On the negative side, the Bic 4C came out at a time when pens
were made to be disposable. It represented the apotheosis of
disposable writing instruments _ the frankly terrible notion that
not only could resources be tossed aside once even a portion of
them was used up, but the idea that entire mechanisms could be
disposed of wholesale as well. Ecologically speaking, the Bic 4C
was a couple of cartridges short of a six-pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Not being a visionary, I'm not troubled by the eco-wastefulness.
If anything, the pen's disposable '70s decadence makes me like it
even more.
</P>
<P>
   I've always hated change, and this whole pen business has
reminded me of that bad character trait. Forced to adapt, I will
press on somehow, as long as they don't mess with my Week
At-a-Glance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
