<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-HNS &LR;      03-15 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA EXECUTES KILLER, RAPIST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With a sacred white eagle feather draped
diagonally across his chest to signify his American Indian
heritage, Darrell Keith Rich softly drew his last breath early
Wednesday and became the first Californian executed this year.
</P>
<P>
   A confessed serial killer and rapist who terrorized Shasta
County for a two months in 1978, Rich was pronounced dead at 12:13
a.m. Wednesday, seven minutes after state prison employees began
pumping a deadly mixture of fluids into his vein.
</P>
<P>
   His final statement to the world: ``Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   That same word was on the mind of a woman Rich raped 22 years
ago. She watched impassively as her tormenter twitched and died
from the lethal cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can finally live in peace,'' the woman, whose full name has
never been made public, said in a statement. ``He won't be there to
haunt me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who said earlier she suffered two decades of
nightmares after Rich snatched her off a rural road and raped her,
silently held hands with the relatives of five other victims during
the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too easy for Darrell Keith Rich after what he put us
through for 22 years,'' said another witness to the execution,
Peggy Eastwood. Rich killed her sister, Annette Edwards, by
crushing her skull with a rock after he raped her on July 4, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen victims and relatives traveled to the San Quentin
Prison for the execution, but the authorities had room for just six
of them in the viewing area adjacent to the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Rich, 45, was convicted of killing four women and sexually
assaulting five others.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted all the crimes, including the rape of a neighbor,
11-year-old Annette Selix. After he raped her, he threw her off a
105-foot bridge near Lake Shasta. Clad only in her underpants, she
lived long enough to inhale her own blood and crawl into the fetal
position.
</P>
<P>
   Rich was given the death penalty for the Selix killing and the
murder of 28-year-old Linda Slavik. The other convictions resulted
in prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gov. Gray Davis denied Rich's request for clemency,
saying ``There is absolutely nothing about Mr. Rich's brutal
behavior that warrants clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat who ran on a pro-capital punishment and
tough-on-crime platform, now has denied three clemency pleas since
January 1999. Neither Davis nor his predecessor, Republican Gov.
Pete Wilson, accepted a clemency plea in the eight years since
executions have resumed in California.
</P>
<P>
   Rich spent his last hours praying with his two spiritual
advisers and meeting with lawyer James Thomson. His last meal
consisted of beef broth, papaya juice and Gatorade. ``It was a
rather Spartan meal at his request,'' said Department of
Corrections spokesman Bob Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Strapped into a gurney with wide leather bindings, the doomed
man looked straight ahead and showed no emotion when the curtain to
the small death chamber was opened to the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   As the lethal chemicals were pumped into his body, his jaw
clenched but his breathing continued, then slowed. Several minutes
later, his chest convulsed a couple of times. Then he stopped
moving.
</P>
<P>
   The foot-long Indian ceremonial feather quivered with each
breath. It became still as Rich's chest stopped moving.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a guard in the witness room received a
small slip of paper passed through a portal in the door. The guard
read it, then announced that Rich had served his death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Rich was injected with sodium pentothal to put him to sleep,
pancuronium bromide to arrest his breathing and potassium chloride
to stop his heart.
</P>
<P>
   He became the eighth murderer executed in California since the
state resumed capital punishment in 1992, following a hiatus of
more than a quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
   Rich, one-quarter Cherokee, was the first American Indian
executed by the state in that period.
</P>
<P>
   The last Californian to be executed was Vietnam veteran Manuel
Babbitt, killed by injection last May for murdering a 78-year-old
Sacramento woman during a robbery and attempted rape in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
