<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7804 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MARCH-MADNESS-NYT     03-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MARCH-MADNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITE SEES A SURE THING IN BASKETBALL CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like an audacious gamble for a small dot-com that lost
more than $6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sandbox.com, one of the several thousand Internet start-ups in
the Washington area scrabbling for attention and wealth, is putting
on a rich sweepstakes based on the men's college basketball
tournament that begins on Thursday, promising to pay $10 million to
anyone who correctly chooses the winners of all 63 games.
</P>
<P>
   So far about 600,000 contestants have filled out the brackets
online, and Sandbox's 30-year-old president, Lawrence M. Cotter,
said he expected the total to approach 1 million contestants before
the contest, called It's Madness, closes at noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But as with so many things in the new online economy, the risks
for Cotter and his company are illusory. First, it is highly
unlikely that anyone will win. Statisticians put the odds of
selecting all 63 winners at something in the neighborhood of eight
or nine quintillion (a quintillion has 18 zeros).
</P>
<P>
   But then, most basketball fans think that they bring some
knowledge and skill to the selections. ``So I think the odds are
really in the neighborhood of one in 5 billion,'' Cotter said,
``meaning that the chances are about 1 in 600 that a Sandbox member
will win.''
</P>
<P>
   But a single upset in the tournament can cause turmoil. Last
year, when Sandbox offered a mere $1 million prize, every one of
the 160,000 contestants was shut out in the very first round, after
the highly ranked University of North Carolina lost to Weber State,
a Cinderella team, by 1 point in the first game _ which almost
nobody predicted. This year, another Web site, Predict It
(sports.predictit.com), is offering a similar contest with a $1
million prize.
</P>
<P>
   Cotter said he hoped that his contest would last longer this
year. After all, the game for Sandbox.com is to gain national
attention as well as new members for its online gaming business.
And at this point he has nothing to lose, because if someone does
win, Sandbox.com doesn't have to come up with the $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company bought ``hole in one'' insurance, so named for the
country-club practice of parking a Cadillac Coupe DeVille on the
golf course, next to the 18th hole, and promising to give it to the
member who can sink a hole in one.
</P>
<P>
   An insurance examiner figured the odds for Sandbox.com's contest
and assessed a fee of about 25 cents per player, or just $250,000
if 1 million people play.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the contest and resulting attention will shut down
quickly again this year, Sandbox is also giving away other prizes,
like a car and entertainment centers, for people who pick lots of
game winners, if not all of them. The top scorer wins a Pontiac,
donated by another Web site, AutoMall.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sandbox also recruited several paying ``sponsors,'' or
advertisers, for the contest. The lead sponsor, whose banner
advertisement appears at the top of the contest Web page, is
another Internet start-up, PhoneFree.com. Jan Horsfall, the
company's president, said, ``We are extremely stoked to be part of
such great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Sandbox is earning money from the entrants.
Registration is free, but Sandbox presents about a dozen special
offers _ trial magazine subscriptions, memberships at other Web
sites _ on the registration page.
</P>
<P>
   So many people are taking them up on the offers that on average,
Sandbox is getting $3.50 in commissions and other fees as a result
of each registration, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, ``everyone's a winner,'' Cotter said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   The contest almost did not get off the ground. The company
ordered new server capacity to handle the surge in visitors to the
site, but after weeks of promising, the contractor had not
delivered by last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association was to post the
game brackets on Sunday evening, and that is when Sandbox needed to
have its contest up and running. ``We called all around the area,
desparately looking for bandwidth,'' Cotter said. Finally a local
company stepped in to help, and the higher-capacity servers were in
place just in time on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to have someone win so we could march him around the
country with a big $10 million check,'' Cotter said. After a moment
of thought, he added with a grin: ``That's the second-best thing
that could happen. The first-best thing would be for a hacker to
shut down our site for two hours in the middle of the contest, and
we'd be on the front pages of all the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, a windfall like that has not arrived. So the company is
already thinking about next year's contest. Bill Carey, Sandbox's
executive vice president, has said the company is thinking of
offering $64 million in 2001. After all, what's to lose?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
