<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-CONTENT16-CO     03-15 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CONTENT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET NOT SERVING POOR, LOW-LITERACY AMERICANS, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    410&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Information geared toward Americans with low
incomes or poor reading skills is scarce and difficult to find on
the Internet, according to a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long study by the Children's Partnership, a
Washington-based organization, was billed as the first to look at
what low-income internet users want and need online.
</P>
<P>
   The organization identified nearly 50 million Americans _ 20
percent of the population _ who are ``on the other side of the
content gap because the Internet does not have the information and
services they could use,'' said Wendy Lazarus, co-director and
co-founder of the Children's Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Authors of the study interviewed low-income Internet users,
community leaders and literacy experts, and analyzed 1,000 Web
sites. Only 6 percent of the sites contained local information that
low-income users said they needed, and 1 percent contained
information about local jobs and housing.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that only 1 percent of the sites were
easily readable by the 44 million Americans who read below the
average literacy level. Only 2 percent were geared toward the 32
million non-English speaking Americans, and only 1 percent catered
to the 26 million foreigners living in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to wait another day to tackle the content
gap,'' said Laurie Lipper, the group's other co-director and
co-founder. ``We have a compelling need, examples of what works,
many of the technical tools we need and now, with this report, a
clear road map for action.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization's recommendations include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Working with low-income communities and using their input to
design information portals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Developing search tools that help low-income users find
information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Training members of low-income communities to develop their
own local content and providing them with investment capital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Conducting more research.
</P>
<P>
   ``By releasing this report, we are placing a flag in the sand,''
Lazarus said. ``If we want all Americans to reach their full
potential, we must close the digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Online Content for Low-Income and Underserved
Americans: The Digital Divide's New Frontier,'' is available at the
group's Internet site (www.childrenspartnership.org/indextop.html).
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Others have taken steps to make it easier for low-income
Americans to gain access to the Internet. Days after noting the
digital divide in his State of the Union address in January,
President Clinton launched Click Start, a federally funded program
to subsidize computers and Internet connections for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson recently opened an office in East Palo
Alto, Calif., a predominately black city 30 miles south of San
Francisco, intended to serve as the Silicon Valley headquarters of
Jackson's effort to close the digital divide.
</P>
<P>
   And more recently, billionaire Michael Saylor donated a $100
million to start developing an online university that he says will
offer an Ivy League-quality education to anyone in the world free
of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
