u f BC-OIL-MERGER-FTC-NYT &LR;      03-15 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MERGER-FTC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC SIGNALS THAT BP AMOCO-ARCO MERGER IS LIKELY BE APPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, West Coast)   (bl)  
 By DAVID STOUT and STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission on Wednesday put a
hold on its attempt to block a merger of BP Amoco and Atlantic
Richfield Co., signaling that the $30 billion deal is very likely
to win government approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the substantial and constructive proposals made by
the defendants, all parties have agreed to seek adjournment of the
federal court proceedings in FTC vs. BP Amoco and Atlantic
Richfield Co. in order to conduct negotiations,'' said Richard G.
Parker, director of the agency's Bureau of Competition, in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Parker did not elaborate, but there was no doubt he was
referring to BP Amoco's just-announced intention to sell the
Alaskan assets it would get from Atlantic Richfield (or Arco) if
the merger went through. Together, BP Amoco and Arco now control
about 70 percent of oil production in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC had expressed concerns that the merger would lead to
substantially higher prices for Alaskan crude oil at refineries on
the West Coast, where gasoline prices are already among the highest
in the country. But BP Amoco has just reached a deal to sell its
Alaskan assets to Phillips Petroleum in a deal valued at $6 billion
to $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With that arrangement, BP Amoco appears to have eliminated the
highest hurdle standing in the way of its acquisition of Arco.
While Parker's terse statement referred to further negotiations,
its mention of ``substantial and constructive proposals'' seemed to
indicate that federal court hearings might not be necessary. The
hearings, which were to have begun next week in San Francisco,
would have been on the FTC's motion to block the merger on grounds
it would violate antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   The BP Amoco-Arco merger is the largest proposed deal ever to be
opposed by the federal government. Assuming that the FTC does drop
its opposition, the merger would create a company second in size
only to Exxon Mobil. The merger of Exxon and Mobil, a deal worth
some $80 billion, was approved only last November.
</P>
<P>
   Both BP Amoco and Arco executives had argued that the government
misinterpreted antitrust law, and that notwithstanding the
regulators' concerns, their merger would not drive prices in
California even higher. Gasoline prices across the country _ near
historic lows not many months ago _ have skyrocketed recently and
threaten to become a major political issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
