u l BC-HOME-GE-RECALL-NYT &LR;      03-15 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-GE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SEEKS OPTIONS   IN DISHWASHER RECALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROSALIE R. RADOMSKY  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should consumers with defective GE dishwashers rewire them or
buy new ones? And how much of the cost should GE pick up?
</P>
<P>
   From April 1983 to January 1989, General Electric produced 3.1
million G.E. and Hotpoint dishwashers with a defective air-drying
switch that has the potential to melt or ignite, creating a fire
hazard. The switch has caused no injuries, but there have been 50
hazardous incidents, three of which damaged houses. About 900,000
of the dishwashers were in use nationwide by consumers and property
managers when GE began a recall last year.
</P>
<P>
   Affected dishwashers are all among the Hotpoint and GE model
numbers GSD500D, GSD500G, GSD540, HDA467, HDA477 and HDA487.
Specific serial numbers of the affected machines are available on
the General Electric Web site at www.geappliancerecall.com or from
(800) 599-2929. The numbers appear on a rectangular label to the
right or left front rim of the tub.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer of New York filed a federal
lawsuit earlier this month over what the state described as a
difference in treatment between commercial customers and
individuals. ``We want General Electric to offer all consumers the
same opportunity,'' he said. He said he was also dissatisfied with
GE's current rebate offers.
</P>
<P>
   GE has offered a temporary measure to property managers and
corporate customers: a set of instructions for rewiring the
dishwashers, along with a plastic connector for tying off the ends
of cut wire, and in some cases, a small payment toward rewiring.
Individual consumers, meanwhile, are not getting the rewiring
option. Instead they are being offered a $25 rebate toward a new
Hotpoint or non-GE brand and $75 to $125 toward GE dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   About 45,000 rebate checks were mailed and more than 166,000
claim packages were sent out by the end of January, Terry Dunn, a
GE spokesman, said. He added that property managers, who are
dealing with numerous recalled dishwashers, had rewired more than
100,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   One 26-unit condominium Soundview Terrace, in New Rochelle,
N.Y., was entirely equipped with the GE dishwashers, said Joseph
Poggioli Jr., who lives there with his wife and two children. His
GE Model GSD500D was in the apartment when he moved there in 1990.
He has not replaced it. ``I'm going to wait for the outcome of the
lawsuit, or until my wife gets tired and bugs me for a new
dishwasher,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GE has made additional arrangements with some bulk purchasers of
its dishwashers. For instance, GE is offering the National
Association of Housing Cooperatives, based in Washington, either
new GE dishwashers for $150, or $15 for a 15-minute rewiring for
those of its 1,000 member buildings that own the recalled machines.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, responding to consumer complaints, would
like General Electric to finance the entire cost of the rewiring,
about $75 for a qualified service call, and to provide more money
for rebates.
</P>
<P>
   But, Dunn said, rewiring the dishwashers is an unsatisfactory
option for consumers. ``The rewiring option permanently disables
the function'' _ a choice between hot- or cool-air drying _ ``and
degrades the performance of the dishwasher,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, the average life span of a dishwasher is
assumed by the industry to be 9 to 11 years, and the models being
recalled are near the end of that period.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, rewiring is not required under the program approved
by the federal Consumer Product Safety Commission, which oversees
such matters.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows GE to choose how to resolve the recall. ``We also
wanted GE to do a full repair program to all consumers free of
charge, and they refused, which is their right,'' said Russ Rader,
a commission spokesman. ``The law says a company can select a
repair, refund or a replacement. It's their right to select the
refund program. Whirlpool had a similar fire problem with
dishwashers in 1996 and did a full repair free of charge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
