<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, March 16. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-CHOCOLATE (Paris) _ Years of sticky debate ended on a
bittersweet note Wednesday as the European Parliament finally
allowed British chocolate to invade the Continent. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ In a pre-election warning to the people
of Taiwan, Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Ronghi reiterated China's
standard posture toward Taiwan: ``We must make it crystal clear. No
matter who comes to power in Taiwan, Taiwan will never be allowed
to be independent. This is our bottom line. This is also the will
of the 1.25 billion Chinese people.'' By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-UNIVERSITY (Undated) _ A 35-year-old software billionaire
says he will spend $100 million to realize his vision of 21st
century higher education: a giant free Web site that would provide
access to what he calls the 1,000 greatest minds of our time, in
lectures and interviews recorded for the site. By Jacques
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-PORN (Salt Lake City) _ Taking aim at the easy access of
sexually explicit material in his state, Gov. Michael O. Leavitt of
Utah is planning to sign into law on Friday a measure that will
give Utah the nation's first pornography czar. Leavitt conceded
that the new ombudsman, a deputy state attorney general, would have
no powers over the biggest sources of sexual content, the Internet
and cable television. But in a state where the Morman church and
its socially conservative views influence almost all aspects of
life, Leavitt said the new law would `'codify our highest moral
aspirations'' by adding state powers to community efforts in
fighting what some residents may regard as offensive. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER-FTC (Washington) _ BP Amoco cleared a major hurdle in
its proposed acquisition of Atlantic Richfield Co. on Wednesday as
the U.S. government moved for an adjournment of its antitrust case
against the oil companies, citing ``constructive action'' to meet
its competition concerns. BP Amoco Plc was poised to announce later
in the day in Anchorage that it had agreed that Arco would sell all
of its Alaska assets to Phillips Petroleum Co. for nearly $7
billion _ a big chunk of the overall deal, which was worth $27
billion. (Summary from wires) By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRIMATE-FOSSIL (Undated) _ Fossil bones of an animal no
bigger than a shrew and weighing less than an ounce have been
identified as belonging to the earliest known relative of the
primate lineage that led to monkeys, apes and eventually humans.
The wee animal lived 45 million years ago in a humid rain forest in
what is now China. The paleontologists who announced the discovery
Wednesday said the fossil animal, named Eosimias for ``dawn
monkey,'' was the best evidence yet for fixing the time and place
of one of the more fateful branchings in evolution. Eosimias
appeared to be a transitional figure when lower primates, known as
prosimians, went their way, developing into today's lemurs,
lorises, bush babies and tarsiers, while the diverging higher
primates, the anthropoids, evolved into more prepossessing
creatures, including human beings. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-BOOKS (Undated) _ In what could be a critical moment in the
evolving electronic book market, Stephen's King's novella about a
Mustang-driving ghost has proven so popular in two days of literary
life that several online booksellers could not meet orders that
topped 400,000. In the first 24-hour after posting ``Riding the
Bullet'' on various Internet Web sites, readers overwhelmed leading
online booksellers with purchases or orders to download the 66-page
digital horror story into their computers, electronic readers or
Palm Pilots. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DNA-INDICT (New York) _ Manhattan prosecutors announced the
indictment Wednesday of a man known not by name but by a genetic
sequence, one of the first times in the nation a DNA signature
alone has been used to charge a crime. The man referred to in the
indictment by the name John Doe and a series of genetic makers is
wanted for a series of 16 rapes on the East Side of Manhattan
between 1994 and 1998. The indictment charges the man with 15
charges related to three of those rapes.
</P>
</TEXT>
