<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERIENCE-MUSIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE MUSIC FINALLY GETTING READY TO ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After months of primping, Paul Allen's curvaceous and
colorful interactive music museum finally has set a date for her
debutante ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Frank Gehry-designed, 140,000-square-foot Experience Music
Project at Seattle Center will open June 23, kicking off a multiday
celebration of live performances throughout the center grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Though EMP hasn't confirmed the lineup, it will include artists
of many genres _ rock, funk, soul, gospel, hip-hop, jazz and blues.
The Northwest will be well-represented.
</P>
<P>
   Additional details will be announced this spring. Offerings may
include some unusual live collaborations; there is a rumor James
Brown's original band may be reunited.
</P>
<P>
   Some concerts will be ticketed events, while others will be
free. Charter members will have first pick of the tickets to the
grand-opening concerts when they go on sale sometime this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Membership fees range from $35 for the ``acoustic student''
package (for full-time students 21 and under with ID) to $5,000 for
the ``superstar'' package. For more information, call 877-396-8742
or visit the Web site at www.emplive.com.
</P>
<P>
   Construction still is under way at the site along Fifth Avenue
North, where the Monorail slices through the roof of the
eye-popping structure before rolling into its terminal at Seattle
Center. A sign greeting visitors at the site reads: ``When You Feel
You Have No Rhythm, Place Your Hand Upon Your Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Seattleites think of EMP's exterior design, the
building's interior and its spectacular soaring spaces surely will
awe them.
</P>
<P>
   The star attractions at the 18-room museum will include Sky
Church _ a grand hall inspired by Jimi Hendrix's concept of a place
where people of all ages, interests and backgrounds could come
together to experience music _ and a ridelike multimedia experience
called Artist's Journey. The latter opens in June with ``Funk
Blast,'' which explores the origins and sounds of funk music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Disney-esque without the thrill-ride aspect,'' Paul
Zumwalt, EMP's design and construction manager, said during a tour
of the museum this week. ``It's more about music.''
</P>
<P>
   For Zumwalt, the project has been the highlight of a career that
has included the design of museums, resorts and golf courses from
Ohio to the Caribbean. One of his most notable projects was the
Museum of Anthropology in Veracruz, Mexico. Zumwalt previously
worked for Allen as project manager of Portland's Rose Garden Arena
from 1990 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   During months of construction at the EMP site, Zumwalt has
watched iron workers sign their names, poetry and song lyrics to
the museum's giant beams. Many of those working on the museum are
caught up in the excitement of the unusual project.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who really loves music, this is as good as it gets,
as wild as it gets,'' Zumwalt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Experience Music Project was founded by Microsoft co-founder
Allen and his sister, Jody Patton. Inspired by Allen's fascination
with Hendrix, the interactive museum has been designed to be far
more than a repository for EMP's more than 80,000 artifacts,
including what is reportedly the world's largest collection of
Hendrix memorabilia. Once envisioned as a Hendrix museum, EMP has
expanded its scope to encompass thousands of artists and all styles
of popular music. Amenities will include a cafe and nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   After slogging through mud at the construction site, Zumwalt and
a reporter entered the museum through a plywood construction door.
Indoors, the museum is a labyrinth of soaring spaces cluttered with
plastic tarps, rolls of wiring, construction debris and stacks of
building materials. High above, wildly curved beams accentuate the
building's rebellious geometry.
</P>
<P>
   The main lobby features a giant ``snake wall'' that wriggles to
the ceiling like a shapely dancer dressed in exotic, brightly
colored garb. The wall is covered with the same painted metal
shingles that decorate the exterior.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the main lobby, the space that houses the
Demo Theater juts downward like a UFO that has crashed through the
roof of a building. The hanging appendage is covered with polished
silver shingles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it Frank Jr.,'' Zumwalt quipped. ``It's like a little
bit of Frank Gehry hanging out in the lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sky Church is a cathedral-like space with a 65-foot-high
ceiling. The grand hall was designed by The Floating Co., a San
Francisco company that created stage designs for U2's ``PopMart''
tour and the Rolling Stones' ``Bridges to Babylon'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   When it is finished, Sky Church will function as an audio-visual
space by day and dance club or performance space by night, with a
state-of-the-art sound system.
</P>
<P>
   A steel scrim will encircle the Sky Church like a curtain,
hiding video screens and lights until they are activated. A frieze
of electronic images will play continuously along one wall.
Illuminated time capsules filled with donated objects will be
installed in the translucent flooring.
</P>
<P>
   Graceful curved trusses soar to the ceiling like giant steel
ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a museum of natural history, this is is where the
dinosaurs would be,'' Zumwalt said.
</P>
<P>
   A wide staircase leads to the second-floor galleries, including
the Hendrix Gallery (which will feature the Fender Stratocaster
Hendrix played at the '69 Woodstock festival), the Guitar Gallery
(where the 1934 Rickenbacker ``frying pan'' electric lap steel
guitar will be among more than a dozen instruments displayed) and
Northwest Passage, offering a look at local music history (Quincy
Jones' trumpet from the 1940s is one of the Northwest treasures).
</P>
<P>
   Other galleries are dedicated to the Roots of Rock 'n' Roll (EMP
plans to exhibit Elvis Presley's black leather jacket from the
early '60s), Rock's Next Generation (would you believe Janis
Joplin's bell-bottom pants from 1970?) and Hip-Hop (which will
offer a peek at handwritten lyrics by Kurtis Blow).
</P>
<P>
   Nine designers worked on the various spaces at EMP. Gehry
himself designed the cozy but high-tech JBL Theater, a
200-capacity, fixed-seat room for film and video screenings, master
classes and intimate live performances.
</P>
<P>
   The multisegment building has been compared to pieces of a
broken guitar, a human heart and parts of the human inner ear. But
Gehry has claimed that electric guitars, with their bright colors
and curved shapes, were the inspiration for EMP's exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry used CATIA, the three-dimensional computer program
employed in the design of France's Mirage fighter jets. The program
also has been used by Boeing and Daimler-Chrysler. Gehry is the
first architect to use it to create shaped-metal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intended for designing aircraft and anything that
requires the shaping of metal,'' Zumwalt said. ``This is the first
time it's really been put to the test.''
</P>
<P>
   The second floor includes Sound Lab, a futuristic studio where
visitors can create music, regardless of their level of skill,
using guitars, drums or keyboards. Visitors can learn basic skills
or work on improving their existing ones. Toys include sound pods
and the Jam-o-Drum, a high-tech version of the ancient drum circle
that features psychedelic graphics projected onto the ceiling,
conjuring images of early humans playing around a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tested it with 8-year-olds and 80-year-olds,'' Zumwalt
said. ``Regardless of age, they were caught up in the joys of
creating music from scratch. We couldn't pull them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the interactive exhibits will be hundreds of oral histories
_ original audio and video footage of artists talking about their
memories, contributions and inspirations. Among those recorded so
far are Ann and Nancy Wilson, Bonnie Guitar, Buck Owens, Bo
Diddley, Noel Redding, Ice-T, Taj Mahal, the Dust Brothers and
Ernestine Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibit titled ``The First Rock 'n' Roll Record,'' music
veterans talk about the origins of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We was tired of all that slow music,'' Little Richard says of
early rock. ``We wanted to boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
