<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RILEY TELLS HISPANICS AMERICANS MUST SPEAK TWO LANGUAGES
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley told Hispanic
leaders Wednesday that American schools must produce more students
with ``bi-literacy'' in English and one other language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation can only grow stronger if all our children grow up
learning two languages,'' Riley said in an hourlong speech billed
as his ``first ever'' address on the state of Hispanic education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, too many teachers and administrators today
treat a child's native language as a weakness if it is not
English,'' Riley said. ``It is high time we begin to treat language
skills as the asset they are, particularly in this global
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley noted that a poll of teachers showed that half of them
have some students with limited English proficiency in their
classrooms, but only one-fifth feel ``very'' prepared to educate
them.
</P>
<P>
   Between 70 and 75 percent of the 3 million U.S. students with
limited English skills speak Spanish, according to the Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to calling for a ``more diverse and more adaptable''
teaching force, Riley said that he would like to see the number of
``dual-language'' schools created by federal, state and local
cooperation rise to 1,000 within five years.
</P>
<P>
   He said there now are about 260, including Grant Elementary
School in Salem, Ore, where all English-speaking and
Spanish-speaking students must develop their skills in both
languages.
</P>
<P>
   Riley also praised Bell Multicultural High School, where he was
speaking. Its 700 students come from more than 40 different
countries and speak at least 20 languages, said its principal,
Maria Tukeva.
</P>
<P>
   Each student at Bell studies grammar, vocabulary and literature
in English and one other language, usually Spanish. Though 98
percent of Bell's students are poor enough to qualify for
subsidized school lunches, 70 percent go on to higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his proposal for 1,000 dual-language schools is really
exciting,'' Tukeva said. But Riley's contention that starting out
with a non-English language is an asset, rather than a weakness, is
only correct ``sometimes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really varies,'' she said. ``If the students have a
strong background in their native language and strong academic
skills, it's actually an asset. But some of them don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dual-language schools aren't the only useful approach, Riley
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many different and effective strategies for teaching
English, from bilingual to sheltered English to English as a second
language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But whatever the approach to teaching English, it cannot be
simply a defensive or reactive one,'' Riley said. ``If we see to it
that immigrants and their children can speak only English and
nothing more, then we will have missed one of the greatest
opportunities of this new century.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Riley outlined $8 billion in federal education programs that he
described as elements of President Clinton's ``Hispanic Education
Action Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon the president will host a White House meeting to further
discuss these issues and commit the nation to action,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's speech and the financial commitment grew out of years of
quiet lobbying by Latino leaders, said Guillermo Linares, a New
York City council member who chairs the President's Advisory
Commission on Educational Excellence for Hispanic Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential year in which Clinton cannot run to succeed
himself ``is an opportune time for us to highlight the potential
that we have and the challenges that we hope will be faced by the
changed leadership, regardless of what happens,'' Linares said.
</P>
<P>
   In political terms, his polite words translate into cheerful
anticipation of a bidding war between the presidential candidates
for Hispanic votes.
</P>
<P>
   A text of Riley's speech will be available at
http://www.ed.gov/Speeches/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
