<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GAS PRICES IN SAN FRANCISCO TOP OTHER URBAN AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fuel costs in San Francisco topped the nation's
other cities, with motorists paying an average $1.90 per gallon for
self-serve gasoline, according to a survey released by the
California State Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   The price is being driven up by higher crude oil prices and
lower production of gasoline at area refineries, said Paul Moreno,
spokesman for AAA of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't hold your breath for gas prices to come crashing down
anytime soon,'' Moreno said. ``Most analysts expect OPEC will
increase production, but there's little agreement as to how much.''
</P>
<P>
   In one month in Northern California, the average price per
gallon of regular unleaded gas rose 25 percent to $1.83, according
to the AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Prices hit record highs across the rest of the United States as
well, with a gallon of regular gasoline averaging $1.54 at the
self-service pumps in the AAA March survey released Tuesday, up
17.6 cents since mid-February and 57.3 cents from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline is typically more expensive in California because of
environmental laws that make crude oil costlier to refine.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, gasoline was a relative bargain at $1.65 per
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Schlichting, a spokesman for the California Energy
Commission, which monitors gasoline in the state, said San
Francisco tends to be more expensive because there are fewer gas
stations.
</P>
<P>
   In AAA's report on Tuesday, the average price for a gallon of
gas in the nine-county San Francisco Bay Area was $1.84 per gallon,
a 34-cent increase since February.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Rosa, the lowest average gas price was $1.78 per
gallon, according to AAA.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has announced that the
Clinton administration is looking at ways to reduce fuel costs,
especially since driving will increase in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddly enough,'' Moreno said, ``last year there was a much
stronger reaction when gasoline prices went up.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, a series of refinery fires in Northern California
caused the production of gasoline to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable why people are angry,'' Moreno said.
``People will be driving more soon, and the upward pressure on
retail will increase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
