<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uncover colorful treasures and trinkets from around the world at
Atlanta's ethnic shops
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put your passport away. People with a penchant for that
well-traveled look can fill their homes with exotica from around
the globe without the hassle of jet lag _ not to mention without
leaving Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Within the metro area, there are a wealth of shops and galleries
chock-full of treasures from faraway places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the trend in decorating with imported pieces
escalate over the past five-ten years. Right now the market is
flooding with items from the Pacific Rim,'' says Randall Cobb, vice
president of David Incorporated in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of furniture and accessories from China, Malaysia
and Thailand. In fact, 90 percent of the accessories in my shop are
from the Pacific Rim,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are buying individual imported pieces that stand on
their own _ not like their parents who bought living room and
bedroom suites.''
</P>
<P>
   Those partial to African goods _ from textiles to jewelry _ need
merely to head for Little Five Points, home of African Connections,
or consider Underground Atlanta's African Pride as a sampling of
shopping possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Thousand Villages in Virginia-Highland is a nonprofit gift
store run by volunteers that sells merchandise from around the
globe. The shop helps provide income to Third World craftspeople by
marketing their handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
   And that's one of the drawing cards for local television
producer Conne Ward-Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I shop there is because I like the idea of
fairly traded goods. But who wouldn't? Also, it's relatively
inexpensive. I gravitate to the hand work quality of it _ you get a
sense of the maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people come in all the time who say they just didn't
buy enough souvenirs on their trip, so they stop here to get
more,'' says manager Marg Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   You can select from soapstone carved in India, South American
pottery, dishware from Vietnam and beautiful handmade paper from
Bangladesh. And that's just the short list.
</P>
<P>
   On Zonolite Road in East Atlanta, Mingei World Arts offers a
view into an exotic realm. This little space is crammed with the
bizarre and stunning. Consider a collection of exquisite silk
slippers made and worn by Chinese women whose feet were bound. Note
that 3-inch feet were thought to be the ideal. Think of it as a
case of beauty and art emerging from excruciating pain.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you'll also come across old Cambodian temple paintings,
Javanese puppets and flying dragons from Bali, which are placed
over children's beds to keep evil spirits away.
</P>
<P>
   For Indonesian furniture _ old and new _ as well as Balinese
carvings and batiks, Manorism's 30,000-square-foot warehouse in the
Westside area near the Atlanta Water Works is worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   And those who crave European flair will find many shopping
venues in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Along with tartan ties and English bone china, Taste of Britain
in Norcross offers all of the accouterment needed for the perfect
English tea.
</P>
<P>
   Francophiles can soak up their fill of country French at Pierre
Deux in Phipps Plaza. The boutique stocks fabrics from Provence,
glazed Quimper faience from Brittany and even a line of foods from
Le Cordon Bleu.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of our favorite finds from a whirlwind tour of
some of Atlanta's international shopping venues.
</P>
<P>
   Sources
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  African Connections, 1107 Euclid Avenue, Atlanta.
404-589-1834.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  African Pride, 88 Lower Alabama St., Underground Atlanta.
404-523-6520.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buford Highway Farmers Market, 5600 Buford Highway, Doraville,
Ga. 770-455-0625.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Classic Linens, Inc., 3168 Peachtree Road, N.E., Atlanta.
404-266-3783.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Irish Crystal Co., 3168 Peachtree Road, N.E., Atlanta.
404-266-3783.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kilim Collection, 22 Bennet St., Atlanta. 404-351-1110.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Manorism Inc., 1494 Ellsworth Industrial Blvd. N.W., Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mingei World Arts, 1123 Zonolite Road 20-A, Atlanta.
404-815-5055.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Out of the Woods Gallery, 22-B Bennett St., Atlanta.
404-351-0446.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pierre Deux, Phipps Plaza, Atlanta. 404-869-7790.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taste of Britain, 73 S. Peachtree St., Norcross, Ga.
770-242-8585.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ten Thousand Villages, 1056 St. Charles Avenue, N.E., Atlanta.
404-892-5307.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Bengal Store, 4897 Buford Highway, Chamblee, Ga.
770-986-4111.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
