<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Merchants bring Adamson Square back to life
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARROLLTON, Ga. _ At Horton's Bookstore, owner Dorothy Pittman
rings up sales on the shop's original 1892 cash register. But don't
expect a receipt.
</P>
<P>
   She can't find paper to fit the machine anymore.
</P>
<P>
   That might be a small drawback, but it's also a drawing card for
the customers _ many who know Pittman personally _ who like to shop
at Carrollton's oldest downtown business. ``We have been affected
by Amazon.com,'' said Pittman, referring to the online bookstore,
``but we still offer personalized service. For example, we send
Bibles away to be re-bound and will wrap all your purchases free.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, as Pittman points out, if you shop online, you won't be
able to pet Chloe. She's the tabby cat that has taken up residence
on a chair in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Personal service and a mix of businesses. That's what merchants
are banking on to attract residents and visitors to this west
Georgia town of 18,000, about 45 miles from downtown Atlanta.
Incorporated in 1829, Carrollton was named in honor of Charles
Carroll, one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Today, shops, galleries and restaurants revolve around
picturesque Adamson Square and its adjacent streets. Buildings date
from the late 1800s on the square, which was named for William
Charles Adamson, a 1900s state representative and local judge. Here
you can find the old and the new, from an Indian skirt at the Gypsy
Peddler, a 4-month-old shop on Rome Street, to home accesssories
and antique furniture at Groover-Smith Co., a 68-year-old fixture
on the square.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a gardener, you should head to Burson Feed and Seed, a
business on Rome Street that's been selling yard tools, plants and
fertilizer for 50 years. For a change of pace, drop by Linda
Cagle's Design Associates shop on the square, where she will work
with you from the blueprint stage to selecting the right wallpaper
for your home. Cagle also stocks plenty of gift accessories and
does custom flower arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Although the downtown is humming today, with students from the
nearby State University of West Georgia and with visitors, this
wasn't always the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a number of years, the square was dead,'' said Oak
Mountain school counselor Lucy Gay, who moved to Carrollton with
her husband, Jim, in 1971. ``But in the last five years, it has
come back to life. Now you can find anything you need, including
restaurants like Pearl's Cafe and Tea Thyme and two of my favorite
shops, Victoria &AMP; Ivy and Clayworks. I like to support the local
merchants, who are also my neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Such merchants are weaver Carol McWhorter and her husband, Don,
a potter. They own McWhorter Clayworks Fine Craft Gallery, a
4-year-old business on the square. ``We have lots of repeat
business from the county and from out-of-towners staying in condos
at Fairfield Plantation,'' said McWhorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visitors want to find a piece of the Old South off I-20,'' she
added. ``Last week, we had a couple from Chicago who read about our
shop in Southern Accents magazine and went out of their way to find
us.'' Clayworks sells one-of-a-kind items from 100 artists around
the country who specialize in clay, fiber, glass, metal and wood.
</P>
<P>
   Since its 1985 designation as a Main Street city, which
encourages economic improvement and renovation of a downtown
commercial district, Carrollton has been the beneficiary of several
programs. One has been the renovation of the Lawler Hosiery Mill
into loft apartments. Situated just off the square, the lofts offer
a built-in clientele for shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   To further stimulate business, Main Street director Tammy
Calhoun is planning Mayfest 2000 on May 6. Arts, crafts,
entertainment and food will be featured around the square. And
Friday at noon, during the summer, free concerts are held on the
square.
</P>
<P>
   However, the best day to shop in Carrolls
</P>
<P>
   Books
</P>
<P>
   Horton's Bookstore, 410 Adamson Square
</P>
<P>
   Galleries
</P>
<P>
   McWhorter Clayworks Fine Craft Gallery, 307 Adamson Square
</P>
<P>
   Furniture/Gifts
</P>
<P>
   The Hope Chest, 119 Bradley St.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelery
</P>
<P>
   Cole's Jewelry, 104 Adamson Square
</P>
<P>
   Miscelleaneous
</P>
<P>
   Burson Feed and Seed Inc., 124 Rome St.
</P>
<P>
   Design Associates/Linda Cagle, 404 Adamson Square
</P>
<P>
   Green Lantern Frame Shop, 302 Adamson Square
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsy Peddler, 116 1/2 Rome St.
</P>
<P>
   Imaginations Unlimited, 108 Alabama St.
</P>
<P>
   Ink Rush Tattoo, 108 Rome St.
</P>
<P>
   L.K. Rich &AMP; Son Army Store and Pawn Shop, 118 Rome St.
</P>
<P>
   McEver's Awards, 213 Bradley St.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Norman Cosmetics, 103 Newnan St.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
