<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I buy the orange peeler that Andy Rooney recently
demonstrated on ``60 Minutes''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Doxey, Carrollton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: For those of you who hate to peel an orange (or any other
citrus fruit), Wilbur Blank's Qwik Orange Peel is for you. Using
the side cutter, insert the gizmo into the fruit's center, rotating
it round and round. Then insert blade between fruit and rind.
Slowly turn fruit while working blade up to the top. Repeat on
other half. Then twist and remove the rind.
</P>
<P>
   Available through Wil-Le Products, three peelers are $5 plus $2
for shipping; six peelers are $10 plus $3.50 for shipping. Send
checks only to: Wil-Le Products, R.R. 1, Box 65, Toulon, IL 61483.
</P>
<P>
   Like reader Doxey said, Andy Rooney demonstrated, and listed,
this orange peeler as No. 10 on a list of what he considers the 10
best unimportant inventions of the 20th century on ``60 Minutes.''
Incidentally, the other nine Rooney choices in ascending order: the
thermos, zipper, remote-control garage door opener, remote-control
channel changer, paper clip, paper bag with handle, pop-top can,
refrigerator door light and the elastic band.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Help! Bugs are in my pasta. I am looking for clear glass
canisters with rubber seals and metal buckle latches. I've checked
the discount department stores to no avail. Any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jean Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   A: Those little crittettle represents Lavin and her daughter
dressed for a ball. Like many fine fragrances, this one dropped out
of favor in the 1970s and '80s but was relaunched in '94.
</P>
<P>
   The original formula has not been copied note for note. ``This
could not be done today because the quality of oils and flowers has
improved and the harvesting and processing methods refined,'' said
Catherine Holmes of Cosmair. ``But the new Arpege has the same
richness, the same diversity and quality of the natural flowers as
the original. Longtime wearers will recognize their fragrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent issue of In Style magazine, singer Marc Anthony
swore by a hair product called dirt. What is it, who makes it and
where can I get it? I've called around to local hair salons, but no
one knows a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   _ James S. Meisenzahl,
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: We hit pay dirt. California hair stylist Jonathan Antin
developed dirt, a nongreasy, nonsticky moulding pomade, ``to take
hair from its cleanest state to a more moldable, pliable one.'' The
pleasant-smelling styling aid can also be used ``to achieve that
day after, messy look.'' The 4-ounce jar ($20) is available in
Atlanta at Carter-Barnes Hair Artisans at Phipps Plaza
(404-233-0047). You can also order this Jonathan product at
1-877-673-3734. Other celebs who use the stuff: Ricky Martin,
Jewel, Jay Leno, Tiger Woods and Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been trying to find dip-it cleaner, which is marketed
as a cleaner for coffeepots, but in reality will clean any
burned-in mess out of any pot, with no scrubbing. The powder form
is most effective and is found in small green boxes. I'm desperate
for a supply of this!
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan Andrews, Lilburn, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's always a pleasure to help a desperate woman. We found
dip-it destainer (5-ounce box of powder, $2.49) or dip-it 2
(7-ounce liquid bottle, $2.49) at Publix, 6300 Powers Ferry Road
N.E. (770-612-5140). In addition to cleaning automatic and drip
coffeemakers, the manufacturer also recommends dip-it for removing
food and beverage stains on porcelain, plasticware, glass and
countertops.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
