<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-DALEY-0316-COX     03-15 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DALEY-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DALEY URGES CONGRESS TO PASS BILL BOOSTING TRADE STATUS FOR
CHINA
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ALEC SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling the decision an ``economic no-brainer,''
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley urged Congress Wednesday
to pass legislation that would grant China permanent most favored
nation trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economics of this deal are very good for America,'' said
Daley, speaking at a National Press Club luncheon, adding that the
Clinton Administration will push for approval of the proposed
legislation by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Administration has made quick approval of permanent MFN for
China a primary goal of the president's foreign policy in this, his
final year in office. The White House argues that American
companies will have better access to a Chinese market of more than
1.2 billion people, and American consumers will benefit from
cheaper goods.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the deal is also expected to facilitate Chinese
entry into the World Trade Organization, another issue at the top
of the president's foreign policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the anticipated fullcourt press by administration
lobbyists, however, certain members of Congress _ most notably,
Democrats _ seem in no hurry to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., has said that ``if the Senate
schedules a vote in April or May, there will not be nearly enough
time for public scrutiny of this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone, and other Democrats continue to cite Communist
China's lack of human and workers' rights as reasons to vote down
any attempt to give the country better trade status with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said he is convinced the trade deal will pass. But with
such criticisms being voiced in Congress, he admitted that the
administration does not yet have the number of congressional votes
required for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, House Democratic Whip David Bonior of Michigan said that
``there is nothing on worker rights, nothing on the environment,
nothing on human rights or democratization and no strong
enforcement'' in the legislation offered up by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in here to convince anyone that the U.S.
should permanently give up our leverage with China,'' Bonior said,
adding that the current system of annual review gives the United
States an advantage in dealing with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley countered Wednesday that there has been no great
advance in Chinese human rights under that current system of annual
review either.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic legislators also worry about offending organized
labor, some of the trade legislation's harshest critics. Labor
leaders do not want to see American jobs lost as a result of
Chinese competition.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that there will be winners and losers in the
deal, Daley said the benefits to the United States will far
outweigh the losses. He said U.S. economy has nothing to fear from
its Chinese counterpart, which is only only 1/10 its size.
</P>
<P>
   The United States should seize this opportunity to open China to
American products and industry, the secretary argued.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has stated that he does not want the United
States to have to come late to the Chinese markets and lose out to
other nations. The Chinese government has entered into trade talks
with numerous other partners, including the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to sway the vote, Daley will lead a group of
congressmen to China. The group will consist largely of legislators
who are either opposed to, or undecided on the legislation. They
will visit Beijing, Shanghai, and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
