<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abundant moisture will stream north from the Gulf of Mexico to
the Northeastern states ahead of a slow-moving cold front. An area
of rain with imbedded thunderstorms will move from the lower
Mississippi Valley early Thursday morning to the Ohio Valley during
the midday and afternoon as a jet stream disturbance lifts the
moisture-laden air. One to 3 inches of rain will be common in much
of the Ohio Valley by Thursday evening. Meanwhile, clouds and
broken areas of showers and thundershowers will cover much of the
Southeast. Heavier showers will be favored near the southern
Appalachians where moist winds ascend the sloping terrain. Farther
south, humid weather and some sunshine will linger in central and
southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will quickly fade near the Northeast Coast as a strong
cold front gradually approaches. Showers will arrive in the
interior Northeast during the midday hour and will spread to the
coast at night. Behind the cold front, temperatures will fall
quickly causing rain to change to snow in a narrow band across
extreme northern New York and New England later Thursday. Colder,
drier air will spread from the Midwest throughout the Northeast
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered rain and a few strong thunderstorms will develop near
low pressure in northern Texas and Oklahoma. Some patches of snow
will fall in the higher elevations of the panhandles and into
southeastern Colorado. Farther west, generally dry and seasonable
conditions will prevail in the interior west. The Northwest will
stay unsettled while sunshine continues to bathe the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow Season
</P>
<P>
   Winter is often very slow to end near the Front Range of the
Rockies. Indeed, the two snowiest months in Denver, Colo., are
March and April, with average snowfalls of 12.8 and 9.0 inches.
Most of the spring snow falls in a few, big spurts. With the
northward retreat of the jet stream in spring, the availability of
moisture from the Gulf of Mexico increases. When passing
disturbances draw cold air from Canada southward and moist air from
the Gulf of Mexico northward, big snows can result. Thursday a
fast-moving snowstorm will come to an end across eastern Colorado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WORLD-BOOKREVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-15 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BOOK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN UNDER THE INFLUENCE, TWICE 
</HEADLINE>
 REVIEW-NYT  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 29, 1976, Kim Barnes attended her high school graduation
in Lewiston, Idaho, vainly searching the audience for her family.
As she recounts in her beautifully written if harrowing new memoir,
``Hungry for the World,'' that evening there was to be ``a
supervised senior party given by the family of a classmate at their
cabin 150 miles north on Coeur d'Alene Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, she had asked her devoutly religious father for
permission to go, and he had said no. ```I'm 18,' I'd said,
shivering with the courage it took to question. `What if I go
anyway?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me from the brown recliner, looked at me with his
cool-blue eyes, looked at me until I began to understand and not
care. `Then you would have to take your things and never come
back.'''
</P>
<P>
   What had happened to Barnes up to this point in her life was
told in her first book, ``In the Wilderness,'' which won the
PEN/Jerard Fund Award and was a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The same story is retold in the first 75 pages of ``Hungry for
the World'': how her parents moved to Idaho from Oklahoma so her
father could work as a logger and enjoy the solitude of the
woodsman; how the voice of God told him he must give up that life
and join the Pentecostal Church of God in Lewiston, and how his
daughter, whom he both dominated and encouraged to think for
herself, alternated between subservience to family and church and
rebellion against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years away from that child sleeping in her mother's arms, I
would enter into my young woman's life knowing these two things: by
my gender I was cursed, and my mind would destroy me.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, her life would be the same
only more so. As she writes in another context, it was about
``being raised to believe that women want to be, must be,
dominated.'' It was about ``rejecting those beliefs and still being
unable to escape them _ so wide a river, so many currents to swim
through.''
</P>
<P>
   She did attend that senior party at the lake, taking her
belongings with her and moving into her own apartment in Lewiston.
At first she enjoyed her new-found freedom and solitude but soon,
beginning to feel alone, she found her sexual fantasies taking a
dark turn. ``I came to the deepening belief that there was
something freakish in my nature, something dangerous and
destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   These anxieties would soon be realized. Working as a drive-in
bank teller, one day she served a shaggy young man, David W.
Jenkins, a Vietnam veteran and long-haul truck driver. He asked her
out to dinner, seemed to like her, asked her out again, took her
hunting even, reminding her of her father in his knowledge of the
woods, but refused to do anything more than kiss her goodnight.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, she liked the sensation this gave her, the
sense that they were companions and she was an equal. But soon his
aloofness grew frustrating, and when she asked him for more, he
introduced her to his collection of sex toys, encouraged her to be
with other men and gradually revealed his sadistic side.
</P>
<P>
   She found this behavior enthralling: ``I had succeeded in
remaking myself into that hybrid I believed might grant me the
greatest access into the world of men: a masculine spirit and
intellect; a feminine body and libido. With my mind, I challenged
and prevailed; with my sex, I appeased and confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   But in time, of course, the relationship grew worse than
sterile. ``Even our once lively conversations had become stilted,
as though we had emptied ourselves into each other and now must
face the limits of our ken.''
</P>
<P>
   When an intruder tried to break into her apartment and she told
David about it, he said, ``Maybe next time it will be me.'' He had
done that to old girlfriends. ``Wait a few years, then hide behind
the door, find a closet. They always fight at first, but they want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally escapes David, forms ``an uneasy truce'' with her
parents, works her way through college, marries, has children, and
at last begins to write, tapping into her childhood love of
language, and publish her stories, poems and memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her triumph in finding herself and describing her
experience so powerfully, what sticks in the reader's mind is her
final evocation of her ordeal:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of the Inuit way: a wolf bone whittled to a point at
both ends, coiled and frozen in blubber, left along the path of
bears. The bear eats it and weakens slowly, over miles, over days,
the bone twisting and slashing, killing from the inside out. Shame
feels this way, swallowed and sharp, working its way deeper with
each move to dislodge the pain, so that finally, we lie still,
dying with blood in our mouths. We eat our stories and starve.''
</P>
<P>
   We read her story and bleed for her.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `HUNGRY FOR THE WORLD: A Memoir'
</P>
<P>
   By Kim Barnes
</P>
<P>
   241 pages. Villard. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
