<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GERMANY-DEVELOP-2TAKE     03-15 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-DEVELOP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING SWORDS INTO SUBURBS   IN EAST GERMANY'S BUNKER CAPITAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAN OTAKAR FISCHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The train to Dresden makes a stop at Wuensdorf, a dot on the map
25 miles south of Berlin, now once again the German capital. When
Werner Reisinger comes home from work each evening, he can see
blocky Cyrillic letters on the derelict station. They read:
``Wuensdorf-Moscow.'' Reisinger is again reminded that he lives on
hard-won ground.
</P>
<P>
   For most of a century, Wuensdorf led a secret double life: a
sleepy Prussian village twinned with a forbidden city of soldiers.
Now it is a city of civilians _ the site of the biggest settlement
project in Germany, whose success may inspire similar projects
throughout Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Wilhelm II cleared the land adjoining Wuensdorf for a
firing range and infantry school. By 1914, the site was the biggest
military base in Europe. In the chaotic years after World War I,
the barracks were occupied by the right-wing Freikorps troops.
After the Nazis took power in 1933, Hitler built a network of
concrete bunkers, code-named Maybach and Zeppelin, where the
invasion of Poland was coordinated in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   The bunkers were the German Army's World War II nerve center,
but to the end, the Allies did not know of their existence. In
March 1945, American planes destroyed barracks but did not hit the
bunker complex. A month later, as the Soviets drew nearer, the
bunkers were evacuated in hours. Cups of coffee were left warm on
the desks.
</P>
<P>
   The 60,000-acre military sector was transformed into the inner
sanctum of the Soviet forces in East Germany. The Zeppelin bunker
became their secret communications center, from which they were
prepared to direct a nuclear war against the West. Berlin was the
front line of the Cold War, and Wuensdorf was its field office,
with perhaps 30,000 to 70,000 Russians soldiers and their families
living in the military enclave. By September 1994, they were all
gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Brandenburg government established the Waldstadt Development
Agency, under the direction of a young Berlin official, Juergen
Baumann, charged with nothing less than building a new city in a
ghost town, where no one had ever lived without a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   To the west of the train tracks, in the old town of Wuensdorf,
little seems to have changed since the Berlin Wall came down.
Almost 3,000 people live in traditional detached houses. The signs
of prosperity are few: an occasional satellite dish, a rare new
car.
</P>
<P>
   East of the tracks, however, things are moving fast. The
military zone has been integrated with the old municipality and
rechristened Waldstadt, or town in the woods. Long three- and
four-story dormitorylike buildings stand in formation. Most of them
sport pastel-tone plaster facades and shiny red ceramic roof tiles.
Interspersed are brand-new-looking prefabricated concrete apartment
buildings, ringed by shady lawns.
</P>
<P>
   From zero in 1996, the population of Waldstadt has grown to
2,500, and projections allow for 10,000 by 2005. If the growth rate
is sustained, it will be one of Europe's highest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is not a typical planned community. A tank tread
sits on a restaurant terrace. A flaking statue of an unknown jet
pilot and a corroded figure of Lenin emerge from the trees, and so
do huge rocket-shape concrete towers, their noses well above the
neighboring buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a new community is an exciting and rare opportunity,
and this site is more interesting than most,'' said Wolfgang Metz,
an urban planner and a guiding force behind the efforts of the town
to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   The inheritor of the Wuensdorf garrison, the Brandenburg state
government, called on Metz to help coordinate the Russian
evacuation of Wuensdorf. A deal was struck: Germany paid Russian
troops a salary to decommission, and in return the material
infrastructure was left mostly intact. The arrangement hastened the
withdrawal, but left the Germans with more than they bargained for:
45,000 cubic yards of trash, 250 tons of toxic chemicals, 30 tons
of spent munitions, 2,800 bombs and 98,000 rounds of ammunition.
The cleanup took two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Waldstadt Development Agency hired Baumann. What
did he have to work with? More than 1,000 buildings of every
description _ barracks, administration buildings, factories, sports
facilities, warehouses, villas, stables _ 700 of which were deemed
fit for reuse. A territory of considerable charm, including dense
forests and a wide lakefront, which had not been environmentally
wasted. A fortunate site on a rail line and highway linked to
Berlin. And history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, we are turning a place of war into a place of peace,''
Baumann likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   The 1916 officers' headquarters building, imperial stables and
bunkers became protected monuments. Investors bolstered the
infrastructure with gas stations, banks and bakeries. The state
government moved 1,000 government officials into offices in the old
barracks, a crucial step in creating the core of an employment base
in the town. The first grammar school was built before there were
enough pupils to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   Petra Dittmer, 29, is a resettled employee of the state
ministry, and on weekends she takes people down into the Zeppelin
bunker. She grew up in the shadow of the Soviet base. ``We had no
idea about the bunkers or other things, but we sometimes saw the
soldiers in town,'' Dittmer said. ``Our shoemaker got a lot of
business.'' The promise of a low-cost, sanitized apartment, and of
a government job to which she did not have to commute, persuaded
her to join Baumann's roster.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new residents of Waldstadt are like those who fill
suburbs everywhere in Germany: young, middle-class couples with
children who want affordable, modern amenities in the embrace of
nature. Eighty percent are eastern Germans who may be seeking to
escape their still crumbling hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   Rental apartments in converted barracks range from studios to
five rooms, from $250 for 390 square feet to $660 for 1,240 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Converting barracks in this case was not the problem you might
expect, since at Wuensdorf they had always been used by officers
and their families,'' Baumann said.
</P>
<P>
   The old barracks were laid out with three-room apartments. These
buildings were gutted and then refitted with apartments of varying
sizes, along with new bathrooms, linoleum floors, parking spaces,
balconies and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The result is housing that to a large extent conceals its
martial origins. Bright honey-color plaster walls and hanging
plants, playgrounds, birches and private garages serve to disguise
what are still unmistakably large and regimented structures. But
they end up looking solid and conservative.
</P>
<P>
   This is part of their appeal, if you can ignore history, because
across from your bedroom window may be a 70-foot concrete air raid
bunker or a hero of the Soviet Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Waldstadt was perhaps more of a challenge for two of
its most recent arrivals, Werner and Hannelore Reisinger. Like
thousands of their colleagues, they spent last summer moving all
their belongings from Bonn, where Reisinger worked as chief
librarian of the Labor Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not want to live in the big city,'' Reisinger said.
</P>
<P>
   They bought the first available lot for a three-bedroom detached
house and then ordered wood-frame components from a builder. They
paid about $175,000 for more than 1,160 square feet of living
space. Nearly 700 one- or two-family houses are planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Berlin or even Bonn, we could only afford to rent in a
two-family house, but here we could build our own,'' Reisinger
said. ``And nature is at our doorstep. At night, we can hear the
wild boar snorting around below our window.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reisingers have not yet been to see the bunkers, though they
are visible less than 100 yards away. Reisinger's father was killed
fighting in Yugoslavia in 1943 _ she cannot bring herself to enter
the chambers where his last orders were dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Not far below the surface lies another concern, common to most
settlers from western Germany: fitting in to the east. There is
still a suspicion among westerners that only the youngest people in
the former East Germany show the motivation to make something of
themselves (like turning a military base into a soldierless town);
and that an urge to buy now dominates the ``Ossie'' (eastern)
mentality, something the west got over decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   From the other side, western Germans, or Wessies, are still
thought of by many in eastern Germany as patronizing opportunists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit worried at first about being the new rich
Wessies on the block, with an instant house and stay-at-home wife
and all that,'' Reisinger said. ``But we have had no problems.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.0
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Metz has been busy luring transient visitors. One weekend, four
years ago, he was traveling in Britain and stopped at Hay-on-Wye,
the village near the Welsh border that has become a pilgrimage site
for rare book collectors. There are 20 such towns worldwide,
including Nevada City, Calif., and Metz immediately set about
adding Waldstadt to the list. The former army bathhouse and post
office were renovated to showcase the wares of a dozen German
antiquarians.
</P>
<P>
   The monolithic concrete and moldering relics of failed regimes
exert a fascination for war tourists, several hundred strong each
week. Hourly weekend tours take people into the chilly
107,000-square-foot recesses of the Zeppelin bunker, whose
reinforced walls the Russians discovered were too thick to
detonate.
</P>
<P>
   Metz, the first civilian to become a resident of Waldstadt, is
busy plotting the future from his office in the Book Town building
(now the unofficial town hall). In 1998, he gave up his civil
service job to form his own Book Town tourism company. The state of
Brandenburg has pumped in $130 million worth of investment, while
private investment stands around $160 million. Apartment rental
prices are averaging 65 cents a square foot compared with $1 a
square foot elsewhere in the region, so the space is rapidly
filling.
</P>
<P>
   Baumann is finding new distractions: a steady stream of
government officials from countries like the Czech Republic and
Ukraine have been arriving, seeking conversion advice for their own
tattered and abandoned infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The Book Town is opening a fourth building this summer. One way
Baumann wishes to foster community is to build up the cultural
base. An artists' colony has been proposed for the old troop
exercise yards, and the row of empty imperial stables is to become
a military museum extension, art galleries, a printing plant and
space for publishers. A couple of miles away, the officers'
headquarters complex is waiting for the right investor to revivify
the grand old Prussian spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kind of institution would be right, or a high-tech
company campus,'' Metz said. Then he paused with a smile, ``You
don't happen to know Bill Gates, do you, or maybe Steven
Spielberg?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER16-COX     03-15 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Are you ready for eight more months of this?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With eight months left until November, Al Gore and George W.
Bush locked up their nominations with primary wins in the South.
Bush said he was braced for Gore's ``politics of personal
destruction and distortions,'' while Gore argued that Bush's
``risky tax scheme'' would hurt the economy. And Bush brushed off
as a stunt Gore's latest challenge: a promise to hold off on TV ads
funded by ``soft money'' as long as Bush does, too.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AHEAD IN PARTY LOYALTY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has his work cut out for him in the South. Exit surveys
by Voter News Service for several news media organizations
suggested that George W. Bush ran stronger among Democratic voters
than Gore did among Republicans. Just 6 percent of voters in
Republican primaries said they would vote for Gore in November;
twice as many Democrats said they would defect to Bush. And more
than 20 percent of Democrats said they had a favorable view of
Bush; half as many Republicans had a favorable view of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   THAT WOULD BE A NO-NO, GEORGE
</P>
<P>
   As the primary returns were coming in from Texas and five other
states, George W. Bush celebrated with supporters in Austin. His
campaign decided to feed the traveling press pork barbecue. The
only problem was that the victory party was held at the Dell Jewish
Community Center and they refused to allow pork on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   OVER ALMOST AS SOON AS IT BEGAN
</P>
<P>
   The front-loaded primary and caucus schedule enabled the vice
president and the Texas governor to win nominating majorities
earlier in the election year than any prior candidate who wasn't
already president. ``I think change is badly needed,'' said Jim
Nicholson, the Republican Party's national chairman. ``If we don't
change it, we're headed inexorably to a national primary day, and I
think that would be bad.'' Said Joe Andrew, Democratic national
chairman: ``The goal has got to be voter participation, not just a
rigid system that tries to spread things out.'' So far, however,
there's no consensus in either party on the problem or the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS OPEN, REALLY OPEN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's advisers are preparing to establish a political
action committee that would allow him to campaign for other
candidates this year and lay the groundwork for his own future,
which could include another White House race. McCain is expected to
give the final go-ahead on the project when he returns to work in
the Senate next week, the advisers told The Associated Press on
Wednesday. They also said McCain is still in no hurry to endorse
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   FEC LOOKING FOR A LITTLE HELP
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission is urging Congress to pass a law
saying foreigners cannot give any money to federal campaigns _ a
subject at the heart of the scandals involving President Clinton's
1996 re-election effort. The FEC wants Congress to enact such a
measure during its current session and make it a top priority. An
existing law specifically bans foreign contributions to candidates,
and the FEC has ruled that the statute also applies to unregulated
soft money given to political parties. But some courts have ruled
otherwise. Most of the foreign donations to the 1996 Democratic
presidential campaign were soft money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK OWNERSHIP NO OCCIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore defended his family's ownership of stock in Occidental
Petroleum Corp., which plans to drill on land near a Colombian
Indian reserve, saying ``there certainly is not'' anything wrong
with the arrangement. Gore inherited the stock from his father, the
late former Sen. Albert Gore Sr., who had served on the board and
served as chief executive of a subsidiary. The stock, valued at up
to $500,000, is in a trust fund to benefit his mother. ``If you can
find anything wrong with that, please tell me,'' Gore said. The
U'wa Indians believe oil exploration will bring violence and
destroy their culture.
</P>
<P>
   CULT-IVATING RELIGIOUS HARMONY?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones University has dropped from its Web site statements
calling Catholicism and Mormonism cults. A new message on the site
has president Bob Jones III recounting how he contemplated on
Christmas Eve ``the growing worldwide hostility toward the
evangelizing efforts of Bible-believing Christians.'' But gone is
the message in which Jones said, ``The diminution of evangelistic
enterprise to cults which call themselves Christian, including
Catholicism and Mormonism, is frightening.'' The language was cited
repeatedly after George W. Bush was criticized for speaking on the
South Carolina campus Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY DEFENDS FUND-RAISING . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton denied that a campaign event held last month in
New York by Pakistani-Americans influenced her husband's decision
to visit Pakistan during an upcoming trip. ``If anybody thinks they
can influence the president by making a contribution to me, they
are dead wrong, and I think there is no evidence of that,'' she
said. The Senate candidate said it was well known that her husband
wanted to include Pakistan in his visit to neighboring India. The
fund-raiser reportedly netted her $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND GIULIANI FORMS SOFT MONEY OPERATION
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani has set up a political action committee to collect
largely unregulated donations known as soft money. ``We have to
remain competitive. ... We're going to fight fire with fire,'' said
Stuart Roy, a spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial
Committee. An earlier decision by Clinton to set up soft-money
accounts for the New York Senate race had been roundly criticized
by Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN `SUSPENDED' FROM BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   Oregon officials have decided to remove John McCain's name from
the primary ballot in May, a move that has irked some McCain
supporters, who noted that he has not formally withdrawn from the
presidential race. McCain said last week that he was ``suspending''
his campaign. Oregon Secretary of State Bill Bradbury said voters
would be presented with ``a false choice'' if McCain's name
remained on the ballot, and that any of his die-hard supporters
could still write-in his name. The move leaves two Republicans on
the ballot, George W. Bush and Alan Keyes, and two Democrats, Al
Gore and Lyndon LaRouche.
</P>
<P>
   EASIER FOR TED THIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   The last time Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.) sought re-election, he
faced one of the stiffest challenges of his long political career.
That was against Republican Mitt Romney in 1994. This time around,
the six-termer may not even break a sweat. Kennedy's likely
Republican challenger is Michael Sullivan, district attorney in
Plymouth County. He has little money or name recognition despite a
solid political background that includes three terms in the
Massachusetts House and two terms as district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA DEMOCRAT LOOKS GOOD IN POLL
</P>
<P>
   A poll of registered voters in the Florida Senate race offered
some encouragement to state Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson, the
lone Democrat, and Republican Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher.
It was less kind to Republican Rep. Bill McCollum, one of the House
managers who prosecuted President Clinton's impeachment trial. A
survey by Mason-Dixon Polling and Research Inc. (4 percentage point
margin of error) found that Nelson would win a hypothetical general
election over McCollum by 43 percent to 33 percent, and would nudge
Gallagher by 39 percent to 38 percent. Republican Sen. Connie Mack
is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   HATCH GETS A CHALLENGER
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from an unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential
nomination, Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) will not even have clear
sailing toward a fifth term. Democratic state Sen. Scott Howell,
Senate minority leader since 1995, said he'll oppose Hatch in
November. For Democrats, Howell is a lifesaver: Until now, Hatch
was unopposed by both parties.
</P>
<P>
   RUNOFF FOR RIGHT TO FACE ARCHER
</P>
<P>
   Texans head back to the polls April 11 for runoffs to decide
which Republican will be the favorite to replace retiring House
Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer this fall. Rep. John Culberson
and businessman Peter Wareing were the top vote-getters among eight
GOP candidates. The winner will be considered a shoo-in against
lone Democrat Jeff Sell. Archer, who went to Congress in 1970, was
the only incumbent in Texas' 30-member House delegation not to seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   RUNOFF FOR RIGHT TO FACE HUTCHINSON
</P>
<P>
   Five little-known Democrats sought to oppose Texas Republican
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson. Gene Kelly, a retired Air Force lawyer
who has lost six previous statewide bids, snared the top berth.
Party favorite Charles Gandy, who served one term in the
Legislature in the early 1980s, was locked in a tight race for
second place with computer systems analyst Don Clark. In East
Texas, actor Noble Willingham of ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' fame
snagged the GOP nomination to take on Democratic Rep. Max Sandlin.
</P>
<P>
   RUNOFF IN MISSISSIPPI, BUT NOT FOR LOTT
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, seeking his
third term, escaped a primary challenge. Troy Brown Sr., an
unsuccessful candidate for lieutenant governor last year, will face
national party representative Rickey Cole in the April 4 Democratic
runoff. In the 4th Congressional District, District Attorney Dunn
Lampton beat a primary challenger to face freshman Democratic Rep.
Ronnie Shows.
</P>
<P>
   GAY MAJORITY ON TOWN COUNCIL
</P>
<P>
   An openly gay city council member, John Fiore, was elected mayor
of Wilton Manor, Fla., a feat believed to have made the
municipality north of Fort Lauderdale one of only two in the nation
with a gay majority. Fiore, 46, has been on the council since 1988
and was the vice mayor. The town has two other gay members of the
council. West Hollywood, Calif., is the only other U.S. city with a
gay majority on its council, according to the Gay and Lesbian
Victory Fund.
</P>
<P>
   CLOGGED STREETS, UNCLOGGED RE-ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, two-term Orlando Mayor Glenda Hood easily won
re-election in a hotly contested race where the city's clogged
streets had become the central issue. In tiny Briny Breezes, an
oceanside mobile home park near Boca Raton, voters re-elected
77-year-old Mayor Robert Conkey, who spent $11 in his campaign. His
83-year-old opponent didn't spend a cent.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
