computer services company, agreed to buy Atlanta-based LHS Group
Inc. for $4.7 billion in stock to become the largest seller of
customer-service software to wireless phone ompanies. Sema's shares
fell as much as 20 percent. London-based Sema offered 2.6 shares
for each LHS share, which values LHS stock at $69.70, or 76 percent
more yesterday's closing price on the Nasdaq Stock Market. LHS
hareholders would own about 27 percent of a combined company.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
