<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-BUILDING-WEBPAGES     03-15 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BUILDING-WEBPAGES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WANT TO BE IN PICTURES? WILL YOU SETTLE FOR A WEB PAGE?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Calif., Va.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While just a few years ago it might have been akin to owning a
Lear jet, having your own Web page these days is about as exciting
as, well, having your own e-mail address. But if you really want
one, whether to show off family photos or to plug a new business,
there is plenty of room still available in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Internet service providers like America Online, Earthlink, AT&AMP;T
WorldNet Service and Juno Web offer the easiest and fastest way to
create and publish Web pages. Most offer five to 15 megabytes of
storage space for the pages they hold on their servers. That is
more than enough to accommodate several pages with images and text.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the space, these services offer simple
page-creation programs that let you type in text, choose background
colors and transmit digital photographs from your system to the
server. Most offer the page-making program free when you sign up
for the monthly Internet service (ranging from about $10 to $20 per
month, depending on the provider and amount of time spent online).
</P>
<P>
   America Online's 1-2-3 Publish feature, for example, lets AOL
subscribers set up a free home page in a few steps. Pick a
background color and a logo for the top of the page, type in a
title and some text, add a few favorite Web pages for links, and
you're done.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet portals like Yahoo, Mindspring and About.com now
offer the ability to create Web pages at no charge, in exchange for
registering and agreeing to allow the portal to run an advertising
banner somewhere on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The megaportals are in many cases offering free Web building
as another enticement to get you to come to their site,'' said Gene
Phifer, vice president and research director of Internet strategic
services at the Gartner Group, an Internet research firm based in
Stamford, Conn. ``It's appealing to people's egos, having the
ability to say, `I've got a Web site.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site programs available at ISPs and portals are an easy
way to display family photos and keep relatives up to date on the
latest family activities. Some people might find posting a Web page
to be a more palatable alternative to sending out the newsy ``Dear
everyone'' holiday notes, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can usually create a page in a couple of hours with
these types of programs, they do not give you a lot of flexibility
in terms of how your pages look. Most of these programs offer a
limited number of page templates, fonts, colors and borders. Other
elements that are common on more sophisticated Web pages, like
streams of moving text, clocks or flashing buttons or images are
hard to come by, although some portals and ISPs are starting to
make them available.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to be more creative with their pages and
incorporate some flashy features can choose from a variety of
software, like Microsoft FrontPage 2000 ($149, before a $40
rebate), Sausage Software's HotDog PageWiz 1.02 ($70) and
NetObjects Fusion 5.0 ($299).
</P>
<P>
   Like the programs used by the ISPs and portals, these
what-you-see-is-what-you-get, or Wysiwyg (pronounced WIZZY-wig),
programs let you lay out a page without having to know HTML, the
computer code used for writing Web pages. Instead, you can focus on
how the page looks while the program translates your work into
HTML.
</P>
<P>
   After you insert a photo, write a paragraph of text or insert a
page link, the program immediately displays the result on a working
sample, letting you click Save or Undo after each step.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the ISPs that sell Net access for a fee let
people create pages within a Wysiwyg editor and then send the file
to the host site, not every ISP will accept all Wysiwyg programs.
</P>
<P>
   These off-the-shelf programs offer both adventurous novices and
experienced Webmasters the chance to create original and complex
sites. ``I'm absolutely amazed that two weeks ago I said to myself,
`I'm going to create a site,' and that I was able to without the
slightest knowledge of how to do it,'' said Jason Orans, a film
producer in New York who is developing an entertainment-related
site using FrontPage 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Orans said it had taken him about a day to learn the basics of
FrontPage 2000 and about three days to put up a page. ``I'm pretty
happy with the site, but I still don't have the knowledge or skills
to do exactly what I want,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the programs also let the Web purist write and edit in
HTML, allowing complete control of the page's design.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who are building pages will view the source codes of
pages they like and cut and paste them into their own work to use
as a model. All Internet browsers have the ability to display the
HTML source code of a Web site. In Microsoft Internet Explorer, for
example, clicking on the View button on the upper-right part of the
screen and selecting the Source option will display the code.
Although copying whole pages of work from other sites is frowned on
by Web designers, it is generally acceptable to borrow font styles
and colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK to mimic code, as long as you use your own graphics
and text,'' said Will Harris of Point Reyes, Calif., who is the
editor of efuse.com, a site for beginning and intermediate-level
Web page designers.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for people who want to build a more sophisticated
site than those found at the free portals is available at
Homestead.com. A free Web publishing service that began operating
last June, Homestead.com offers hundreds of templates for specific
uses, like promoting a business, an event, a club or a hobby. There
are also personal-page templates geared to different age groups.
Homestead.com has a large bag of tricks to choose from, including
novelty cursors, shopping carts, guest books and chat rooms.
Although the service is free, features like stock quotes and chat
display the names of the companies that have provided them. You
will also have to indicate whether you want to participate in the
optional user surveys, which Homestead.com uses to deliver
advertising.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter what method you use to create a Web site, it is a good
idea to test your page on different computers. Factors like
Internet connection speed, processor speed and system memory can
affect how quickly the pages load, and monitor size can determine
how much of each page is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people make the mistake of putting a 200-kilobyte
image of their dog on their opening page, thinking that it only
takes a minute or so to load when they test it at work,'' said
Jeffrey Veen, a designer at Wired Digital in San Francisco. ``Then
they see that it actually takes five minutes to load on their
computer at home.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a good idea to see how your pages run on both
Netscape and Microsoft Internet Explorer because they sometimes
read certain lines of HTML differently.
</P>
<P>
   If you are building Web pages to promote yourself or your
business, you might want to register your own domain name. Getting
your own domain name at one of the dozens of registrars, like
Networksolutions.com or Register.com, requires that you check that
the name you want is not already taken and that you pay a fee
(usually $70 for two years). You then have to find an ISP to serve
as host for the site with your domain name, which costs an average
of $50 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Some services will post a site at no cost. Angelfire.com, for
example, will do it free, but your domain name will appear as
www.angelfire.com with two more names, or directories, after .com
that you select from a pull-down menu. You choose the first
directory based on your state or interest, like ``NY'' or
``Pokemon,'' then enter the text you want for the second directory.
(You could, for example, end up with
www.angelfire.com/pokemon/lover.) Although the result is a domain
name that may not necessarily reflect your business or interests,
your site is online free.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where your site is located, most page-creation
programs provide password protection options, which allow you to
control who sees it. ``No matter how confined you think your group
of visitors is going to be, you never know who's going to come in
and look at it,'' said Chuck Green, president of Logic Arts, a Web
design firm in Glen Ellen, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Although a sense of place adds to the overall feeling of a site,
Green said, site creators should never include information that
they would not post on a sign in the backyard. And when you include
those family photos, he added, never reveal children's names or the
exact location of your residence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
