<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   PROS
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS_ELLIOT_ One day after his return to the Spurs, San
Antonio forward Sean Elliott says he's feeling fine and wants to
continue to be in the starting lineup. Elliott said he could have
played back-to-back games if necessary. (Rosner, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NCAA PLAYOFFS
</P>
<P>
   BKC-CINDERELLA-TEAMS _ Every year, the NCAA basketball
tournament produces one, sometimes two, Cinderella teams, who pull
stunning upsets through the first two rounds. History suggests the
No. 12 seeds are dangerous. Here's some unknowns who just might
surprise beginning today, when the march to the Final Four begins.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION. 30.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-LANDERS _ Is this the year that Georgia women's coach Andy
Landers finally wins the big one? He's one of the winningest
coaches in women's college basketball history, and his Georgia Lady
Bulldogs are among the top teams in the nation year after year.
This year, Georgia is the top seed in the West Regional and hopes
to return to the Final Four, where it has been three times in the
last five years. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-DIVERSITY _ The Atlanta Braves have hired Maryland
consultant Cook Ross to conduct diversity trainining sessions for
the baseball team in the wake of the John Rocker incident. The
sessions are now under way. It may be the first sports team to take
a corporate approach to handling such a sensitive matter. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-SELECTION _ So many are complaining about the
Masters new selection process that you wonder if the officials
there might go back to the way things were. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
