<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7860 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-OPPOSING-GAME-NYT     03-15 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OPPOSING-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VARIATION ON THE SEQUEL FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES HEROLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as Hollywood does, the computer game industry loves to turn
out sequels. Myst begat Riven, and Final Fantasy begat Final
Fantasy 2 through 8. But computer games have another kind of sequel
_ called the mission pack _ that Hollywood can only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   When an action game is successful, the manufacturer puts out a
mission pack as soon as possible. Mission packs let companies add
new levels without building a whole new game engine and make more
money without actually coming up with a new product. And mission
packs, created with more speed and less inspiration than the
original games, are almost never as good.
</P>
<P>
   Valve Software, the creator of Half-Life, has teamed with
Gearbox Software for a mission pack called Half-Life: Opposing
Force. Just as Half-Life changed the first-person shooter genre by
providing a fully developed story, Opposing Force, by rethinking
that story, could do the same for mission packs.
</P>
<P>
   In Half-Life, the player was a scientist named Gordon Freeman
who had witnessed an accident that ripped a hole in space, allowing
horrific monsters to invade Earth. Freeman, making his way to the
planet's surface to find help, discovered that the government had
tried to cover up the botched experiment by sending in the Marines,
who proved as deadly as the aliens.
</P>
<P>
   As a story line, this might not seem very complex, but since
previous shooters had story lines like ``aliens have destroyed the
earth: kill them all,'' Half-Life became the ``Citizen Kane'' of
the genre.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical mission pack, you would play a few more levels of
Half-Life as Freeman. But Opposing Force puts you inside the skin
of one of Half-Life's villains, a marine who has been sent to cover
up the disaster. In Hollywood terms, it is like watching one of
those sports movies in which the coach has to redeem his violent
past and the quarterback needs a scholarship to get out of the
slums, then watching a version of the same movie, this time about
the opposing team's coach who wants to win one more time before he
dies of cancer and the team misfit who finally has a chance to
prove himself to his abusive father.
</P>
<P>
   The mission pack begins with boot camp, where you are impolitely
told that you are a maggot before being shipped out to the Black
Mesa Research Project for what your buddies are afraid will be a
``baby-sitting mission.'' You play the game in the same time frame
as Half-Life; you hear some of the same radio reports and even
catch sight of Freeman boarding an alien transporter.
</P>
<P>
   As with Half-Life, the plot gives you a sense of being part of
an ongoing crisis. When a dying soldier wheezes, ``You've got to
kill that thing,'' you have a sense of purpose unknown in a game
like Quake. If the soldier had not told you to kill the monster,
you would have done it anyway because it is the only way to
continue, but the narrative structure makes the player's objectives
more palpable. All good shooters are fueled by adrenaline, but
Opposing Force makes you wonder not only whom to shoot next but
also what may happen next.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot does happen. In a series of imaginative levels you are
challenged by intelligent puzzles of the
get-into-that-unreachable-place or fix-the-monster-killing-machine
kind, along with heart-stopping action and graphic violence. If
bloody skulls landing at your feet disturb you, the game's
content-control option allows you to turn off the gore. (The
control is protected by a password so that parents can shield their
children from the sight of aliens spurting blood.)
</P>
<P>
   As with any mission pack, there are new aliens to encounter.
That is Opposing Force's concession to the mission pack tradition:
Logically, if you are in the same place at the same time as you
were in the original game, it is unlikely that you will meet any
new monsters. You can also team up with other marines _ a medic, an
engineer and a grunt _ lead them into a dangerous area and then run
back and hide while they battle it out with the alien hordes. Hey,
war isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a mission pack, a lowly add-on that will not even
run without the original game, Opposing Force is the best new
shooter since Half-Life a year earlier, almost matching the
original. Kingpin may be edgier, Mortyr more visually seductive,
but you can stop playing either game without ever wondering how it
all turned out.
</P>
<P>
   It is too bad Opposing Force does not go a bit further. In the
original, the marines were out to kill the scientists, including
Freeman. In the mission pack, your helicopter is shot down before
you are given the order to murder the scientists. The mission pack
would have been meatier had you been ordered to shoot unarmed
civilians and had become disturbed by the government conspiracy of
which you were now a part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Opposing Force makes the marines the good guys. The bad
guys are ``black ops'' who are as interested in killing marines as
they are in killing aliens. Maybe it would have been too much to
ask that a game primarily concerned with blasting aliens have a
conflicted anti-hero, but playing off the original story would have
been an awfully entertaining counterpoint. Of course, if you wanted
to stay in the spirit of the first game, you could shoot scientists
and security guards on your own, but they are not much of a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer dramatic value, it might be better to play Opposing
Force before Half-Life. You could start with the marine grunt's
view of battle, not knowing the circumstances or the overall
objectives, and then find some answers by playing as Freeman. It
would be a little offbeat to play a mission pack before the game
itself, but Half-Life broke some rules, so why shouldn't you?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-TITUS-NYT &LR;      03-15 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TITUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYSFUNCTION   AT A JUNCTION   OF CONFESSION   AND COMEDY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ His mother was a manic-depressive schizophrenic who
killed one of her husbands, wound up in a mental hospital and
committed suicide. His father drank too much and married five
times. Their son was _ as you can imagine _ an unhappy and
dysfunctional child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've driven your drunk father to your mom's parole
hearing, what else is there?'' said the son, Christopher Titus, 35,
the star and co-creator of ``Titus,'' an autobiographical Fox
sitcom that essentially turns tragedy on its head. The half-hour
show has its premiere on Monday night at 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   Titus, who grew up in small towns in Northern California, has
been a stand-up comedian since he was 17. But in 1994, at the
Montreal Comedy Festival, he finally got tired of being what he
called ``a happy comic, making observational jokes, being physical
and high energy.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled: ``I wanted to quit. I got tired of talking about
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   His agent and friend, Bruce Smith, pulled him aside. ``He said:
`What are you doing? You're talking like Seinfeld. You're not
Seinfeld. You're talking like a happy guy. You're intense and
driven. Talk about your life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Titus said the audience would never get it. But he went ahead
and nervously tried a two-and-a-half-minute act about his troubled
family, about growing up in a world where his mother was mostly in
mental hospitals and his father drank and caroused.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of it the audience went nuts,'' said Titus. ``I
instantly changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Network already has one dysfunctional family in its
lineup, in ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' the most successful new
sitcom on television. But that show _ with its genius son and
funny, wacky parents _ hardly has the edge or the potentially
tragic undertone of ``Titus.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, chairman of the Fox Television Entertainment
Group, acknowledged that ``Titus'' was hardly a traditional sitcom.
``That's a good thing because it's been proven time and time again
that the conventional half-hour format doesn't work any longer,''
said Grushow. ``At Fox we're accustomed to doing things that are a
little bit outside the box. That's where `Titus' fits in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has been a haven for dysfunctional families ranging from the
Bundys in ``Married . . . With Children'' to the animated
characters in shows like ``The Simpsons'' and ``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Grushow acknowledged that he was a little concerned about the
reaction to ``Titus.'' ``Unlike `Malcolm,' I believe `Titus' will
be a show that's polarizing,'' he said. ``There'll be people who
love it, and people who won't have a taste for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Titus' partners in creating the series are Jack Kenny and Brian
Hargrove, two former New York stage actors who have been writers on
shows like ``Dave's World'' and producers on ``Caroline in the
City.'' Partly because of their theatrical training and Titus'
stand-up comedy experience, the series is taped in front of an
audience without interruption to give it a sense of live theater.
Usually studio audiences sit for three or four hours or even longer
during the taping of a 22-minute sitcom while scenes are reshaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts a lot more pressure on the actors,'' said Kenny.
``It is like theater.'' Hargrove said, ``But there's an energy and
immediacy and focus that the actors and the audience bring to it
that, we hope, is translated onto film.''
</P>
<P>
   The pivot of the show is, of course, Titus. The other major
character, Ken Titus, his father, is played by Stacy Keach.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Titus said with a laugh that at first his father was
a little disturbed by the way he was depicted on the show but that
he now enjoyed it. ``My dad got a little angry, but he signed the
release,'' said Titus. ``What's he going to do? My brother, Dave,
is fine with it. He's like an extreme sports guy. He surfs all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the show's blurring of the line between fiction and reality
takes some odd turns. At a recent Friday-night taping, Titus
proudly introduced his father, who stood and waved to the audience.
The taping that night depicted a real-life event: His father once
faked a heart attack because he smashed up a car while he was
engaged in sex with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is wickedly close to my life,'' said Titus. ``My dad
never missed a drink, never missed a joint, never missed a party.
He also never missed a day of work, a house payment or a car
payment. He was a single parent, and he did his best.''
</P>
<P>
   One or two episodes will depict Titus' mother returning home for
a visit from a mental hospital. His mother, Juanita, killed herself
in 1994. She had earlier shot and killed an abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know her well,'' said Titus. ``She was a concert
pianist. She spoke four languages. She was brilliant. But she
wouldn't take her medicine. She loved the ride of schizophrenia.''
Titus himself grew up with two half-sisters and a half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   Titus said that as a 5-year-old he wanted to make people laugh
and to become a comedian. He would sneak behind the sofa every
night so he could stay up late to watch Johnny Carson, and he
listened to and imitated the records of Bill Cosby. He began
performing in clubs as a teen-ager in San Francisco and in recent
years has won a following on the club circuit. A one-man show at
the Hudson Theater in Los Angeles in 1998 called ``Norman Rockwell
Is Bleeding'' led Michael Hanel, senior vice president of comedy at
20th Century Fox Television, to team Titus with Kenny and Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   Titus is married to his high school sweetheart, Erin, who is
also depicted on the show.
</P>
<P>
   The ever candid Titus said: ``My wife and I once cheated on each
other. I said the most cruel things in the world to her. We fought
through it. Now no one can ever get between us.'' The incident will
of course be used on the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HIGH-TECH-VISAS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-VISAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSE SEEKS DRAMATIC RISE IN VISAS FOR HIGH-TECH WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in the ``f'' and ``w'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A coalition of House members introduced legislation
Wednesday that would dramatically raise the ceiling on visas for
foreigners with high-tech skills from 115,000 to 200,000 over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the second increase in the cap in two years and is
similar to legislation moving through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of raising the limits under the H-1B visa program say
that if companies can hire skilled workers from overseas, they will
not bother to train older American workers or strive to improve the
teaching of computers and technology in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, backed by Democrats and Republicans, attempts to
deflect such criticism by boosting to $1,000 from $500 the visa fee
paid by employers of foreign workers. The money would be used for
scholarships and training for students in computer and
technology-related fields.
</P>
<P>
   The bill gives current H-1B workers the right to remain in the
United States while they await green cards. It also sets aside
10,000 of the visas for universities that have difficulty
attracting foreign workers in high-tech areas such as engineering
and computer programming.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., the sponsor of the bill, said an
unprecedented shortage of skilled workers is threatening the
technology industry that he said has created 4.8 million jobs in
six years and has created the highest standard of living in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let the technology labor shortage undermine our
economic boom,'' Dreier told a news conference. ``Prosperity in the
information age is fueled by brainpower and people, not steel and
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies in the Silicon Valley of California and other regions
flush with technology-related jobs predict they will hit this
year's limit of 115,000 foreign workers this spring. Under existing
law, they would have to wait until new visas become available on
Oct. 1, when the H-1B visa cap will drop to 107,500. In 2002, they
would be further squeezed as the cap is scheduled to drop to
65,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., said a key part of the bill would
allow workers on H-1B visas to stay in this country while
immigration officials process their applications for permanent
visas.
</P>
<P>
   The H-1B program, created in 1990 with a cap of 65,000 visas per
year, grants visas for up to six years to noncitizens with college
degrees. The maximum period of admission in the United States is
three years, but it can be extended for three more.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren said backlogs at the Immigration and Naturalization
Service are forcing highly skilled workers to wait years for
permanent visas, which often means their employers must to send
them back to their native countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be hundreds of thousands of people sent home in the
next few years'' unless the law is changed, Lofgren said.
</P>
<P>
   The co-sponsors of Dreier's Helping to Improve Technology
Education and Achievement Act are Adam Smith, D-Wash., Thomas M.
Davis, R-Va., Calvin Dooley, D-Calif., Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash.,
James P. Moran, D-Va., Pete Sessions, R-Texas and Anna Eshoo,
D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said the legislation would ``import the best trained
people in the world while providing the resources and programs to
train and educate our own citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who heads the House immigration
subcommittee, has a competing bill that would raise the visa cap to
160,000 only for this year, then retain the current levels for the
two succeeding years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Senate Judiciary Committee approved legislation
that would boost the number of H-1B visas to 195,000 this fiscal
year, which ends Sept. 30, and during the next two fiscal years. It
would exempt those who come to the United States to work at
universities and those who have recently received advanced degrees
at a U.S. college.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, led an effort to raise
the annual ceiling on high-tech visas from 65,000 to 115,000 for
the 1999 and 2000 budget years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
Judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
