<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK REVIEWS,   STILL A SECRET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It matters that few people in book publishing seem
aware of the existence of an ambitious, glossy bimonthly magazine
devoted entirely to black literary culture, to books by or about
blacks and to news about the few black people who work in
publishing. The magazine, Black Issues Book Review, is a secret
that doesn't want to be kept, and it matters that it is largely
unknown in the industry because more books written by black authors
are being published than ever before. Black Issues is trying, with
some success, to reach African-Americans, particularly but not
exclusively those on the high end socially and economically. In
short, regular book customers.
</P>
<P>
   To mainstream publishing, blacks are somewhat like a very
welcome weekend guest that the host doesn't quite know how to
entertain. Thus, for instance, Susan McHenry, editor of Black
Issues, said that although the magazine is filled with book
reviews, it still has difficulty getting on publishers' lists to
receive galleys of new black books. It's not that publishers want
to withhold them; it's just that they don't think black. Without
such galleys, there can be no reviews, and without reviews no
influence for the publication and no sales for the book.
</P>
<P>
   Among other examples: in some book stores, the works of Toni
Morrison are found on the racks identified as African-American
literature, not general literature, where one would expect to find
a Nobel laureate. (Sometimes, but not always, they are
cross-indexed.) There remains that old question: Where are the
black editors? The answer is not that publishers don't want them
but rather that they don't know how to attract them. This is not
about prejudice as much as it is about a meandering lack of
urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the growing number of books by and about blacks, in
recent years black readers' groups have popped up all over.
Publishers, with some exceptions, have been slow to respond to this
expanding constituency. Doubleday Direct, the book club division of
Bertelsmann, has Black Expressions, a club devoted to books by and
about blacks, with its own online version, and Ballantine has its
One World imprint, which publishes black writers. HarperCollins
owns Amistad Press, devoted to work by and about African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a divide between what's being published and
what's being publicized about black literature; to cross that
divide there are black literary magazines, the newest among them
Black Issues. Its latest issue, March-April 2000, celebrates the
magazine's first anniversary. There are other magazines, like The
Quarterly Black Review, founded in 1993, and Mosaic Literary
Magazine, a quarterly founded two years ago as a showcase for new
black literary writers.
</P>
<P>
   Black Issues is a slick magazine, ambitious in scope, with crisp
writing and quality production values. Its format is slightly
larger than a news weekly, and it is divided into sections about
literary subjects (the latest issue features poetry and the cover
line is ``Rap Is Poetry: Hip-Hop's Poet Ambassadors'') and the
business of book publishing. Between them are scattered eight
fiction reviews, 11 nonfiction reviews, six reviews of books of
poetry and the usual magazine tchotchkes: shorts about deals,
today's top 10 poetry CD's, a feature called Bookbytes etc.
</P>
<P>
   Rone Shavers, the managing editor, said the magazine hoped to
attract bookstores, libraries, agents, book publicists and art
designers, ``but the main mission is reaching regular book
readers.''
</P>
<P>
   McHenry said: ``There's no one place where someone can go and
find out what's in the bookstores and libraries about people of
African descent. A major national review may review a handful of
black books a year. We do more than that in our latest issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a national forum for the growing black book
audience,'' she continued. ``There's a community of lovers of black
literature who are interested in contemporary black writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Black Issues was founded by a cultural entrepreneur, William E.
Cox, who had started two other publications, Black Issues in Higher
Education and Community College Week, a newspaper. Both are
bimonthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran book reviews in the higher education magazine,'' he
said, ``and we started to receive so many unsolicited book reviews
back from readers there was no way we could publish them. First we
did a special report twice a year. But there was this tremendous
interest in books, we found, based on our feedback. Why starve an
audience out there?''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of the book review was sent to colleges and
universities. ``But I wanted to cut across all areas, whether high
school graduate or not, whether college graduate or not,'' Cox
said. ``I wanted a broad-based audience, yet I wanted to attack the
high end economically and socially.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine sells 40,000 copies of each issue, through
subscriptions and newsstands, which includes bookstores, most but
not all of which are black. The Borders chain is its largest
advertiser and major supporter, and has been from the start. The
magazine is advertising-driven, and Cox hopes to start making money
on it in two years. Black Issues in Education also sells 40,000
copies each issue, but it has much more advertising and is a
moneymaker, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest issue of the book review has 74 pages, about its
average size. Borders has its usual full-page ad inside the front
cover and a second one for its Web site. Absolut vodka has the back
cover. In between are but a few book publishing ads. Of the
mainstream publishers, Doubleday has a full-page ad, and Penguin
Putnam has an ad. There are also ads from Arabesque, Warner Aspect
and the University of Indiana Press.
</P>
<P>
   Book publishers, who often moan about their sales, should
certainly be out there supporting anything that moves the product,
which makes the ghostly absence of major publishing house ads all
that more surprising.
</P>
</TEXT>
