<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK COLLEGES WIN APPROVAL FOR STUDENT LOANS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Students at the 13 black colleges with the highest
default rates on their student loans can continue to get federal
loans and grants, the Education Department announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   All the schools had received warnings after an average of 25
percent or more of their former students, as measured over a
three-year period, weren't making payments on their student loans.
A legal exemption from the rules for ``historically black colleges
and universities'' expired last June.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Woods, chief operating officer of the department's office
of student financial assistance, said that all 13 have since taken
one of the two steps needed to avoid the loss of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some reduced their loan default rate below 25 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most devised a default management plan acceptable to Woods's
office, and hired an experienced contractor to help implement the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plans ``help them lower their default rates while raising
their financial accountability,'' Woods said. ``It's best for the
students, it's best for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13 schools and their 1997 default rates, reported last
October, are:
</P>
<P>
   Miles College, Birmingham, Ala., 25.2 percent; Arkansas Baptist
College, Little Rock, Ark., 21.5; Mary Holmes College, West Point,
Miss., 26.3; Barber-Scotia College, Concord, N.C., 33.3; Central
State University, Wilberforce, Ohio, 22.5; Allen University,
Columbia, S.C., 42.1; Lane College, Jackson, Tenn., 18.2;
Huston-Tillotson, Austin, Texas, 26.7; Paul Quinn College, Dallas,
36.8; Texas Southern University, Houston, 21.4; Wiley College,
Marshall, Texas, 10.9; Southwestern Christian College, Terrell,
Texas, 31.1, and Texas College, Tyler, Texas, 53.8.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
