<HEADLINE>
GEEK NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microphones for People Who Hate Headset Hair  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If headsets introduced the era of hands-free telephones, then a
couple of new products may usher in the era of head-free headsets.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are offering PC microphones that allow users
to use voice-recognition programs, even Internet telephony, without
the bother of being wired to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Labtec's Clearvoice LVA-7280 Digital Microphone and the Desktop
Array microphone from Andrea Electronics both use four microphones
and digital signal processors to capture the voice of the speaker
and to block out other voices and ambient sound. In the case of
Labtec's products, users can move within about a 30-degree radius
of the microphone and within a distance of about two feet and be
clearly understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering you don't have these things strapped to your head,
they offer performance on par with close-track microphones,'' said
Jeff Anderson, an electrical and acoustical engineering manager
with Labtec Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Labtec ran tests in conversation-filled office settings and
found that its microphone still recognized only the speaker's
voice, Anderson said. The Clearvoice retails for $129.95 and is
available this week through the company Web site. Andrea sells the
Desktop Array for $149.95 and also sells the Autoarray, a version
designed for auto PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Can't Get to Broadway? Get a Glimpse Online
</P>
<P>
   Theater lovers who can't bask in the footlights can turn to
TheaterMania.com, a new Web site devoted primarily to Broadway and
off-Broadway theater productions (www.theatermania.com). There are
streaming video clips of interviews with actors and promotional
previews of several shows, including ``Phantom of the Opera,''
``Rent'' and ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Theatergoers can find the stories, schedules and prices for
dozens of shows, feature articles and information about what's on
stage in Boston, London, Los Angeles, Chicago and more than a dozen
other cities. And of course, fans can shop for show posters,
recordings, T-shirts and programs and Big Apple souvenirs. There's
no business like e-business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe Faces Lawsuit Over Delayed Rebate Checks
</P>
<P>
   In the latest legal skirmish over rebate programs in the
computer industry, a Florida law firm has filed a class-action suit
against CompuServe Interactive Services, accusing CompuServe of not
giving rebates to customers in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed this month on behalf of two Florida customers
who were each promised a $400 rebate when they purchased a Compaq
Presario and signed up for three years of CompuServe's 2000 Premier
Service in August 1999. The suit says the rebate checks were not
received until last month and seeks to have CompuServe pay
interest.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe began its rebate program with computer manufacturers
like Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and IBM in July 1999. Ann Bentley, a
spokeswoman for CompuServe, said the company advises customers in
the rebate agreement that checks take 8 to 10 weeks to arrive. The
rebate program was similar to those offered by other Internet
service providers as a way to get more people to sign up for their
services. CompuServe has mailed more than 700,000 rebate checks,
Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Byron Petersen, a lawyer at Petersen &AMP; Hawthorne in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., who is handling the suit, said the firm had
received more than 100 e-mail messages from CompuServe customers
who were awaiting rebate checks.
</P>
<P>
   Trish Primrose, a spokeswoman for America Online (CompuServe is
a wholly owned subsidiary of AOL), said CompuServe has a Rebate
button on its site that allows customers to check the progress of
their rebates. ``Some of the problems in issuing rebate checks stem
from CompuServe customers not filling out the rebate forms
correctly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission recently reached agreements with
Memtek Products and Umax Technologies, stating that the two
computer products companies would provide checks to their customers
within the time specified on the rebate agreements. Mitchell Katz,
a spokesman for the FTC, said that it has not filed a complaint
against CompuServe in relation to rebate offers.
</P>
<P>
   OED Finds Meaning For the Word `Internet'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perspicacious or precipitous? Heuristic or hermeneutic? The
ongoing battle to sound smarter than you really are just got a
little easier and a lot more expensive. On Tuesday, the Oxford
English Dictionary made all the entries from its 20-volume second
edition available on its Web site (www.oed.com).
</P>
<P>
   There are other dictionaries online, most notably
Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary (10th edition) at
www.m-w.com, and The American Heritage Dictionary of the English
Language (third edition) at www.dictionary.com, which are free to
users. But neither has the authority or the cachet of the OED.
</P>
<P>
   The online version of the OED comes in the middle of the
dictionary's current revision, only the second in its 116-year
history, which is expected to more than double the number of
entries from 640,000 to 1.3 million. Lexicographers and editors
began the project in 1990 and expect to finish in 2010 ``with every
word and every meaning fully reviewed and updated, and new words
and meanings added,'' according to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers to the online edition will be able to search for any
word in the dictionary's database and receive the full Oxford
entry, including pronunciation, etymology, variant spellings and
illustrative quotations. The online edition will be updated
quarterly. But the price of knowledge isn't cheap. Subscriptions to
the OED online edition run $550 for individuals and $795 for
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Money Is Pledged to Close `Digital Divide' on Campuses
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, IBM and AT&AMP;T last week pledged more than $101 million
worth of materials, software, services, training and financial
support for a newly announced program of the United Negro College
Fund. The program is designed to improve computer access for
students and faculty at the fund's 39 member institutions, which
are all historically black colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the $130 million program, said William H. Gray III,
the fund's president, is to help increase computer access among
black college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a 45 percent gap between American households and
African-American households that own computers,'' he said, ``and a
72 percent gap between UNCF students and students nationally who
own computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 percent of the 420,000 students attending United Negro
College Fund schools have computers, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft pledged $50 million in software, reference and
training materials to the program, called the Technology
Enhancement Capital Campaign. IBM promised to provide equipment and
services worth more than $50 million, which includes a two-thirds
discount on IBM personal computers for students, faculty and
administrators at UNCF schools. AT&AMP;T donated $1 million to help
train faculty to use information technology in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he was confident that the remaining $29 million the
program calls for could be raised.
</P>
</TEXT>
