<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAGRANT FRANGIPANI  
 BETTER RED THAN NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAGRANT FRANGIPANI
</P>
<P>
   Q. Twice I've brought back plumeria cuttings from Hawaii for a
friend who spent her teen years there and would love to recapture
plumeria's lovely scent. A nursery potted up the first, which died,
and I am trying to start the second. I let them dry first, but one
cutting rotted, and the other barely survives. After nine months it
had grown only two tiny leaves and no roots. Last month I put it
under fluorescent lights, and now it has two new leaves. Any
suggestions about how I can grow this stubborn stub into something
that approximates the lush shrubs we see and smell in tropical
climes?
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if the artificial longer days have awakened
them. Richard Criley, a professor of horticulture at the University
of Hawaii in Manoa, said that Plumeria rubra, or frangipani, the
classic flower of the Hawaiian lei, needs at least 14 to 15 hours
of light each day and temperatures above 50 degrees or it will go
dormant. He said that tip cuttings, commonly available in tourist
shops in Hawaii, should have the cut end dipped in rooting hormone
before being planted in a well-aerated medium, like peat and
perlite, kept moist but not wet, in a warm, brightly lit spot. It's
not too late to apply the hormone to yours, but don't make a new
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Under the best conditions it takes four to six weeks for roots
to grow, maybe longer. But the wait has just begun. Assuming the
cutting is large enough, at least three-quarters of an inch in
diameter, and gets all those hours of light, it will set flower
buds this summer and bloom next spring.
</P>
<P>
   As a houseplant, plumeria tends to be tall and gawky, with few
branches and the leaves mainly at the top, so its attraction is
strictly in the flowers. The waxy, simple pinwheel flowers range
from white to dark red, rose-pink, yellow and orange and
multicolored, while the fragrance is unique but reminiscent of
jasmine. One sniff and it's clear why people love them, even though
when shorter days lead to dormancy and all the leaves fall off,
they look exactly like an old walking stick jammed in a pot.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for plumeria include Stokes Tropicals, P.O. Box 9868,
New Iberia, LA 70562, (800) 624-9706, catalog $5; and the Exotic
Plumeria, 500 Grove Ave., Seffner, FL 33584, (813) 653-2496,
catalog $10.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER RED THAN NOT
</P>
<P>
   Q. This past spring I planted two red twig dogwoods. One had
some new growth, so we have had a few brilliant crimson branches to
enjoy during the winter months. Next winter I would like more of
the red color and have heard that you should trim the shrub down
quite a bit. But when? I don't want to lose the flowers in the
spring or the berries in the summer and fall.  &QL; 
A. The subtle whites, browns and grays of the winter landscape have
a quiet beauty, but some days you just need something that shouts.
Whether they are in your garden or just off the side of a road, the
bright red stems of Cornus alba or C. sericea and their cultivars,
or the yellow-green stems of C. sericea Flaviramea, can jolt you
right out of your winter blues.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with people, the young are the most colorful. As the
stems get older, they turn duller and darker, so late-winter
pruning is necessary to keep the display bright red. Go on out
today. By cutting the 3-year-old stems every year right down to 6
inches above the ground you always have two-thirds of the shrub _
the one- and two-year-old stems _ to provide showy winter color.
</P>
<P>
   Late-winter pruning does have one risk: you are likely to step
on the tender hints of your spring bulbs, so tread lightly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd
St., New York, NY 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(at)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
