<HEADLINE>
A MODEL FOR ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The GI Bill _ or contemporary versions of it _ is becoming
popular again. In 1944, President Franklin Roosevelt signed the
bill, which gave World War II veterans a basket of benefits
including money for education, housing loans, and employment
assistance. Seen today as a huge success that helped educate a
generation, the bill in its time was thought by some to be too
generous. But the American Legion _ chartered by Congress in 1919
as a wartime veterans' organization _ lobbied hard and is credited
with getting the bill passed.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard sociologist Theda Skocpol sees the bill as a template
for other programs, calling it one of ``America's finest social
policy achievements,'' in her book, ``The Missing Middle: Working
Families and American Social Policy.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the GI Bill's best features is that it attracts broad
support. Instead of being seen as a handout to idlers, it has been
nobly elevated to payment of a national debt of gratitude to
service members who defended the country and its values.
</P>
<P>
   The pressing question: How can the spirit of the GI Bill
flourish when the country is not at war?
</P>
<P>
   One promising example is the new Teacher Next Door program,
announced this week by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development. HUD will help public and private school teachers buy
single-family homes at a 50 percent discount and a downpayment of
as little as $100 if they live in ``revitalization areas,''
typically low- and moderate-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The program insightfully identifies teachers as a group whose
service can be honored by helping them buy homes. The program also
extends teachers' service by making them part of communities that
need stable, active homeowners. Because teachers are seen as
hard-working but undervalued, the program should stir little public
resentment. It ought to set an innovative example.
</P>
<P>
   Creative political thinking needs a national forum. Al Gore and
George W. Bush can lead by using the presidential race to spotlight
more GI Bill-style thinking. The country is hungry for public
policies that are effective and popular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
