<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILITY IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration appears to have learned a belated
lesson about ethnic conflicts in the Balkans. State Department
spokesman James Rubin and National Security Council official Chris
Hill have been visiting a liberated but unpacified Kosovo this
week, asking Albanian Kosovars to cease vengeful violence against
Serbs and warning the Kosovo Liberation Army not to provoke a new
pogrom across the border in southern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In the territories of the former Yugoslavia, an ounce of
prevention is worth a pound of cure. Albanians in Kosovo have been
killing and attacking Serbs since last spring, when NATO ended its
bombing campaign against the regime of Slobodan Milosevic.
Recently, the divided town of Kosovska Mitrovica has been wracked
by intercommunal violence, suggesting that Albanian and Serb
Kosovars are no more willing to live together now than they were
before the NATO intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we hear another story about ethnic minorities who
are abused by Kosovar Albanians, our determination to help Kosovo
weakens,'' said Rubin. ``We're in this for the long term, but if
the Kosovar Albanians want that commitment to be upheld, they have
to act responsibly.'' This was the message Rubin was tasked to
deliver in Kosovo by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's aim is to get the attention of leaders in
the Kosovo Liberation Army, in the hope that they will be so
fearful of losing Washington's backing that they will clamp down on
acts of vengeance or intimidation against Serbs and gypsies within
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   This is a proper message to send, and the administration's
attempt to take preemptive measures against another eruption of
ethnic cleansing in Kosovo or southern Serbia is commendable. It
would also help if a properly trained and funded international
police force were provided to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the spectacle of American envoys trying to cajole
the hotheads and thugs of the KLA into imposing order in Kosovo may
be a sign that the United States and its NATO allies have gotten
themselves entrammeled in a Balkan tarbaby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
