vacation season, southeastern North Carolina beaches have yet to
recover from chronic erosion, worsened by Hurricane Floyd six
months ago. Some coastal experts predict that the state could lose
some of its hardest-hit beaches in the next generation, unless the
government pays for the pumping of sand to replenish the ocean
floor scrapped clean by five major hurricanes since 1996. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/FLOYD-FAME _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Princeville's unique history
and recent catastrophe have brought it fame in the wake of
Hurricane Floyd. But many other small towns and communities in
eastern North Carolina have been hit hard. Grifton, population
3,000, lost 300 homes, or one-quarter of its residences, in the
flood. The Belvoir community (unincorporated) was nearly completely
under water. Has Princeville's compelling story benefited it in the
scramble for flood relief dollars? (Moscoso, Greenville, Daily
Reflector). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
