<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-XRAY-VISION-710(2     03-15 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-XRAY-VISION-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING THE SKULL BENEATH THE SKIN, ON THE SKIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif.)  (rk) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   X-Ray vision would be so handy around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Need some rewiring? Nothing to it _ just stare through the wall,
as Superman would do, and then snake conduit through the wooden
framing with nary a snag.
</P>
<P>
   Superman's magic eyes would help doctors, too. They could borrow
them to see through breast tissue to a lump lying deep below _ not
by looking at an X-ray, but as they are doing examinations.
</P>
<P>
   Soon feats like those will not be solely for superheroes.
Proponents say a computer technology called augmented reality
promises to make transparent the solid walls of flesh or plaster
within a decade, or even sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Augmented reality is the general term for electronic technology
that lets people see not only the surface of the world but also,
superimposed on it, things like bones or wiring hidden deep below
the surface. Augmented reality is already available in the Cadillac
DeVille DTS or DHS, which uses infrared technology to generate
images of obstacles on a dark road, like deer frozen in the
headlights, and projects those images onto the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is not the familiar virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``With virtual reality, you put on the goggles and plunge into a
completely synthetic world,'' explained Henry Fuchs, a computer
science professor at the University of North Carolina and a pioneer
in the high-performance graphics hardware used in augmented reality
systems. ``With augmented reality, you see the real world, plus an
overlay of synthetic information that enriches the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, systems like the varied ones being developed by
Fuchs, his colleagues and other researchers will, for instance, let
surgeons perform precise biopsies of the breast by looking through
head-mounted displays that let them see both the breast and virtual
images of its interior. That would enable a doctor to relate
information from touch or sight with a view beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physician needs to see her hands and instruments,'' Fuchs
said. ``The augmented reality _ the visualization _ is just for the
few square inches inside the breast the physician also needs to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs and his colleagues have developed what they call a video
see-through system. In one version, video cameras are mounted just
in front of the eyes. The computer running the show adds the
virtual imagery of the breast, based on ultrasound data, to the
camera image, aligning the synthetic graphics and the real. The
final, layered image is presented through stereoscopic liquid
crystal displays.
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs said he had first been drawn to work in augmented reality
in 1970, when he was in graduate school and saw the groundbreaking
see-through displays developed by Ivan Sutherland, widely regarded
as the father of modern computer graphics. This head-mounted
display overlaid stick-figure graphical objects onto a normal view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken with wanting to add to the real world what a
computer could create, and I've been doing it ever since,'' Fuchs
said. ``I'm interested in medical applications principally because
it's honorable and compelling. Playing even a small part in helping
to save lives is wonderfully fulfilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs and others see many practical applications for augmented
reality in the future. ``There will be so many jobs in which people
need to see what they can't with their naked eye,'' he said. ``I
thought about this every time I pulled out my manual to work on my
BMW. It's a wonderful manual, but what I really need to do is look
at the car and see inside.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the emerging applications of augmented reality is in the
repair not of engines but of people _ patients undergoing
reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Biocomputation Center of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration at Stanford University, Kevin
Montgomery, the technical director, is working toward that goal
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does you no good to live until 150 if you look like 150,''
said Montgomery, who believes that while humans are not going to
live to 150 just yet, the discovery of many cellular mechanisms
raises the real possibility of eventually extending human life by
decades. ``We're going to need to replace a lot of body parts as
they break or wear out,'' Montgomery said. ``And they'll have to
fit well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
