<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7894 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-XRAY-VISION-2NDTA     03-15 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-XRAY-VISION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: fit well.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Montgomery, whose background is in computer engineering, said
his interest in augmented reality began at the NASA Ames Research
Center, where he worked on space-related research. Body parts came
later, when he came to Stanford and was drawn to medical and
surgical applications.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery and his colleagues have developed a series of
three-dimensional visualization techniques for surgical planning,
which they hope to extend into the operating room through augmented
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, for instance, the team used 3-D visualization
techniques to design a new jaw for a patient whose own had been
devastated by cancer. First the team took the patient's CAT-scan
data and built a computer model, making detailed measurements of
the patient's jaw, including the angles between the various parts.
</P>
<P>
   Then team members created a virtual replacement jaw, traced its
template onto film that could be sterilized and took the pattern
into the operating room for the surgery, placing the pattern
directly on the bone they were cutting up to make the new jaw.
``It's like making a dress,'' Montgomery said. ``Slide Tab A into
Slot B.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his team want to take these surgical planning and
replacement strategies a step further. They want to put the 3-D
visualizations, like the CAT-scan data, into the direct view of the
surgeons while they are performing surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working on an augmented reality system designed to give
surgeons virtual windows hanging in front of them that show
CAT-scan and other data,'' he said. ``In essence this will give
surgeons X-ray vision because they can see the computer model of
this woman's skull, generated by the computer from her CAT-scan
data, superimposed on her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Many problems lie ahead before augmented reality like the kinds
being tested at the University of North Carolina and at NASA's
center at Stanford are realized.
</P>
<P>
   But Fuchs is confident that augmented reality systems will soon
become part of our everyday lives. ``We'll have our computer with
us all the time and have it display helpful information
superimposed on what we are looking at,'' he said. ``The same way
we carry a wallet or watch, we'll have a display and be able to add
to it information that is of interest to us, whether to identify a
mountain we are looking at or whether to turn right at the next
intersection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
