<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORDLABEL-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST WORD AT A LITTLE LABEL CALLED LAST BEAT: HONESTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It started with a simple enough idea: A friend is
making a record. We've got some extra cash. Let's help him out.
</P>
<P>
   That act of kindness has, seven years later, evolved into one of
the most popular and well-respected independent record labels in
North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last Beat Records, dreamed up and run by president/owner Caron
Barrett and label manager Tami Thomsen, formed when the women, then
in their mid-20s, forked over a few bucks to help their buddy,
longtime Dallas musician Jeff Liles, put out a disc by his band
Decadent Dub Team.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the label, headquartered in a swank office on Commerce
Street in Deep Ellum, has a solid roster of a half-dozen acts (some
of which are playing the label's showcase this week at the South by
Southwest music festival in Austin), the range of distribution that
only a handful of indie labels attains and, perhaps most important,
a reputation for treating bands well _ both as people and as
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we just always try to be real honest, fair and nice.
That doesn't always play to our advantage, but we're not gonna
change,'' says Barrett, who's also a member of a band called
Astrogin. ``We had a guy who worked here for a while and he said,
`Why don't we just lie to the bands?' We would never dream of that.
That guy didn't last long.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this frame of mind that has attracted some of the area's
heaviest-hitting bands. Alumni include Arlington, Texas, pop-rock
outfit Slowpoke, which released an EP on Last Beat before it signed
to major label Geffen, Dallas pop-rock band Tomorrow People (also a
onetime Geffen signee), longtime Dallas prog-rock unit Vibrolux,
noise-rock icons rubberbullet and popular pop-punk trio Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   That's just scratching the surface. As the label's reputation
has solidified over the past year, its release schedule has become
astonishing. Captain Audio, Pinkston and Pleasant Grove, all
on-their-way-up bands from this area, have recently put out Last
Beat efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But the label's largest score: Baboon, a Denton, Texas-based
punk-rock band that's easily one of Texas' biggest draws, is set to
release a live disc on the label later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Several things explain why Last Beat Records is so hot: It's a
small operation (six people work in the office), the distribution
is strong (you can pick up Last Beat efforts in record shops from
Fort Worth to New York), a recording studio is built into the
office (Last Beat bands get a discount on usage) and every band,
Thomsen says, gets treated with hands-on, specialized care.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the record-deal strategies of groundbreaking indie
labels such as Touch &AMP; Go out of Chicago and Amphetamine Reptile in
Minneapolis, band contracts differ from group to group. Unlike
major labels, Last Beat doesn't require each act to sign a
multi-record deal _ a sigh of relief for bands that want to take
their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our contracts are really individualized to the band,'' says
Thomsen. ``Vibrolux has had big deals in the past, but they don't
even have a record out. We signed them for a one-off deal. Had we
insisted on signing them for anything more, it would not have
happened. They just need to get one out. Whereas Pinkston is a
younger band that is looking at things a little differently, so we
did a multiple record deal with them. Every band's a little
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Last Beat's roster keeps growing: The recording
studio is a state-of-the-art room where local superheroes such as
the Toadies, Reverend Horton Heat and Edie Brickell &AMP; the New
Bohemians have banged out material. Recently it was renovated and
redesigned by Nick Griffiths, a producer/sound wizard who has
worked with artists including Pink Floyd, Joy Division, Squeeze and
Killing Joke.
</P>
<P>
   Thomsen says the label found Griffiths while looking for a
producer for Astrogin's record. ``We sent out a bunch of tapes to
people and Nick was one of the ones that replied back,'' she said.
``As they began talking about the record, Nick had some suggestions
for the studio. One thing led to another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Last Beat phenomenon grew, partially at least, out of a
failure. In 1991, Barrett and Thomsen opened Last Beat Records as
an underground/punk-rock record shop on Elm Street in Deep Ellum.
Thanks to Deep Ellum's constant foot traffic, the store thrived for
a few years before chain record stores such as Best Buy and
Blockbuster Music started carrying _ and selling for less _ punk
records, helping kill Last Beat's business. In 1997, the store
closed.
</P>
<P>
   By that point, though, the label had established itself as
competition for other local labels by releasing a string of
well-received efforts, and they'd already set up shop on Henry
Street in Deep Ellum. The bigger and better space soon came along
on Commerce Street, where the Last Beat camp has been ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the label has had its share of struggles _
with money, with ornery bands, with employees who didn't subscribe
to the Last Beat mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music industry is like a big whirlwind and you have to
stand there and jump at just the right time, and who the hell knows
when that is,'' says Barrett. ``Then when something does happen,
operating in the political realms of the industry is yet another
hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Not making it any easier for Last Beat is that Thomsen and
Barrett are competing in a male-dominated field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't always been easy, but we realize it's a Republican
world. At least it seems that's the way things operate,'' says
Barrett. ``But some people find it intriguing, too, a little bit
out of the norm. Thing is, we're not dormant. We're very
aggressive. We're not just a coupla bimbos sitting around with CDs
stuffed in our high heels.''
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
