   CIVIL WAR-SLAVERY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Texas _ It's not only South Carolina. The Confederate
battle flag remains a potent symbol, angering some, pleasing
others, right here in Texas. Lost in the current debate is research
into what Southern soldiers actually thought they were fighting
for. ``Our understanding of the relationship between slavery and
the Civil War changed before the war, during the war and every
decade since the war,'' said Ed Ayers, a University of Virginia
historian. ``The trick is to realize that slavery was absolutely
fundamental to the war.'' By BARRY SHLACHTER. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
