<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-KADOSH-REVIEW-LA     03-15 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KADOSH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KADOSH' LOSES ITS RELIGION AMID GRATUITOUS SEX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Israeli film ``Kadosh'' lands somewhere between an astute
examination of how religious fundamentalism is used by insecure men
to dominate women and an overwrought excuse to watch Hasidic girls
get naughty.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly more intelligent and persuasive than the melodramatic
``A Price Above Rubies'' from a few years back, ``Kadosh''
nevertheless falls into the same trap the earlier film did: It
reduces a critique of the ultra-observant lifestyle to narrow
sexual parameters. Which is a shame, since hints of the wider
political conflict between Israel's secular and religious Jews are
tantalizingly dropped during the earlier stages of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Jerusalem's Orthodox Mea Shearim neighborhood, the
claustrophobic piece initially finds some humor in the Hasidim's
frustrated efforts to convince their disinterested countrymen _ and
even, in brief moments, themselves _ that theirs is the only true
religion. But neither these brief encounters, nor the siege
mentality the believers sporadically express toward the outside
world, do much in the way of addressing the real struggles of faith
and power that are increasingly defining the traditionalists'
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what we mainly get is a sometimes touching, sometimes
shrill study of two tragic marriages. Meir (Yoram Hattab) and Rivka
(Yael Abecassis) have been happily together for 10 years and even
have a pretty hot love life, considering the cultural strictures
(Meir's morning prayers thanking God for not making him a woman
being an emblematic indicator). Trouble is, no babies yet, which
the sect considers the only real measure of marital success.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rivka's younger sister Malka (Meital Barda) is slated
to marry Meir's most devoutly loony fellow Talmud scholar, Yossef
(Uri Ran Klausner). Predictably, she's really in love with the
hunky Yaakov (Sami Hori), who's been rejected by the congregation
for joining the Israeli army and now makes his way as a nightclub
singer.
</P>
<P>
   Meir's rabbi father pressures him into leaving guilt-ridden
Rivka for a younger, presumably more fertile wife. Spunky Malka,
meanwhile, gets to experience what is surely the worst sex ever
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Can any of this possibly be what God intended?
</P>
<P>
   Director Amos Gitai clearly does not think so, and his general
distaste for the perceivably sexist subculture permeates
``Kadosh.'' He takes every opportunity to present the Hasidim as
backward, paranoid and coercive.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Gitai's own family was involved in founding
Israel's Labor party. The prejudices the director brings to the
material might be more forgivable if he hadn't presented them with
such glacial solemnity. Most shots are twice as long as they need
to be, and if this is meant to evoke the kind of suspended-in-time
lives the characters lead, it does so to a fault. What is of
interest in ``Kadosh'' just takes too much time to get at, and film
audiences cannot be expected to have the patience of lifelong
biblical scholars. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Kadosh'' (NR; sex, violence). &QL; 
The stars: Yael Abecassis, Yoram Hattab, Meital Barda, Uri Ran
Klausner, Sami Hori. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Amos Gitai. Written by Gitai,
Eliette Abecassis and Jacky Cukier. Produced by Laurent Truchot.
Released by Truchot. Released by Kino International. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 50 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
