<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DEAF-THEATER-REVIEW-L     03-15 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAF-THEATER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SIGN OF THE TIMES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blanche can hear. Stanley cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes things more interesting, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   Ed Waterstreet did, which is why he set about reconceiving ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' for his Deaf West Theatre Company in North
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In Deaf West's new production, which is running through April 9,
the protagonists' failure to communicate takes on an even deeper
metaphoric layering than is usual for Tennessee Williams' hothouse
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   As played by actors Suanne Spoke and Troy Kotsur, Blanche
DuBois, the faded Southern belle, and Stanley Kowalski, her earthy
brother-in-law, are estranged not only by cultural and
temperamental differences. Quite literally, they talk in different
tongues. Blanche speaks in English while falteringly translating
her words into an old-fashioned form of sign language. Stanley uses
American Sign Language, a far more visceral lexicon of hand thrusts
and finger jabs, to convey the emotions roiling within him.
</P>
<P>
   Waterstreet, Deaf West's founder and artistic director, hopes
this unusual approach will give hearing and non-hearing audiences
alike a new perspective on ``Streetcar'' and the tragic
misunderstandings that can result when cultures collide.
</P>
<P>
   That's a theme Waterstreet, 56, deaf since acquiring childhood
pneumonia, understands well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's all hearing,'' he explains through an interpreter,
``and they would take me to the theater. And not knowing what was
going on, I would always be poking my family, `What's going on?' I
would feel so empty and isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Using theater as its medium, the non-profit Deaf West has spent
its nine-year existence uniting the often isolated realms of
hearing and non-hearing people. Its mainstage productions of shows
ranging from ``Equus'' to ``Shirley Valentine'' have won bushels of
awards, and the company gradually has added a children's theater
program and professional training workshops for deaf and
hearing-impaired artists.
</P>
<P>
   By casting deaf and hearing actors in its shows, Deaf West also
has frequently been able to tap into emotional and poetic nuances
that might elude traditional productions of the same texts. In most
Deaf West productions, deaf actors perform in American Sign
Language alongside hearing actors who speak the words aloud,
creating a multilevel interpretive strata not unlike the effect of
a Greek chorus.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty sometimes comes in making sure the dueling
dialogues and performances don't crowd each other out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing actors need to learn when they come on board that the
acting choices are the deaf actors','' Waterstreet says. ``They
can't make different choices. They have to mold into one. It's a
very big challenge for the hearing actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Deaf West productions also use projected subtitles, an
acknowledgement that roughly three-quarters of the 7,000 people who
attend its shows are not hearing-impaired.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Deaf West became the latest theater to relocate to
North Hollywood's NoHo Arts District after several years of
temporary residence at the Fountain and Heliotrope theaters. The
company occupies a two-story storefront on the same block as the
Lankershim Arts Center, a location it hopes will be more
recognizable and accessible to the community it serves
(approximately 750,000 deaf and hard-of-hearing people reside in
Los Angeles County).
</P>
<P>
   Deaf West eventually hopes to add a coffee shop that would serve
as an informal social center, and also to acquire the
2,500-square-foot building next door. That would allow the company
to double its space, expand from 60 to 99 seats, and offer more
workshops and acting classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally have a real home,'' Waterstreet enthuses. ``I don't
mean to brag, but I can't help myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A recently awarded five-year, $4 million grant from the U.S.
Department of Education will allow the company to continue
producing three mainstage shows a year and to develop a national
tour each year for one of its shows.
</P>
<P>
   Since its opening production of ``The Gin Game'' in May 1991,
starring Phyllis Frelich _ a 1980 Tony winner for ``Children of a
Lesser God'' _ Deaf West has consistently sought out plays that can
be explored and even enhanced through the use of deaf performers,
without requiring any changes in the script.
</P>
<P>
   Waterstreet says he got the idea of doing ``Streetcar'' four or
five years after watching a captioned version of the 1951 film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee Williams' language is very poetic, and it sort of
matches the style of visual sign language,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Deaf West's production, Stanley's wife, Stella, also is
represented as deaf and is portrayed by the hearing-impaired
actress who goes by the single name Terrylene.
</P>
<P>
   Making Stanley and Stella deaf emphasizes the bond between them,
and sharpens the threat that Blanche represents to their shared,
insular reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Blanche) is putting cracks into their relationship,''
Terrylene explains. ``We have to find a way to solve all the
problems. Because I'm trying to save our marriage. That's my goal,
is to get into a regular life.''
</P>
<P>
   When Terrylene and Kotsur engage each other on stage, their
colleague Spoke finds the sight to be, well, beyond words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch the two of them, they look like dancers to me,'' Spoke
says. ``It's beautiful. The individual becomes like a living
portrait. It amazes me.'' &QL; 
________ &QL; 
What: ``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' &QL; 
Where: Deaf West Theatre, 5112 Lankershim Blvd., North Hollywood. &QL; 
When: Performances at 8 p.m. Thursdays and Fridays, 2 and 8 p.m.
Saturdays, 3 p.m. Sundays; through April 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
