<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BEYOND-THE-MAT-R     03-15 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEYOND-THE-MAT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK BEHIND THE WWF CURTAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use FRIDAY, March 17 or later. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might think that a documentary about pro wrestling, written
and directed by the former head writer of ``Saturday Night Live,''
would be a satire.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen the outrageous costumes, listened to the subhuman
bellowing on pay-per-view, maybe even bought a T-shirt or a beer
stein. Can you imagine anything more in need of a cinematic
smackdown than ``Smackdown!''?
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Barry Blaustein has a different agenda. In
``Beyond the Mat,'' Blaustein isn't out to skewer, or even
necessarily to expose the foibles. A self-confessed wrestling
junkie since the age of 8, Blaustein spent five years on the road
watching and interviewing the folks who make their living stomping,
crunching, mangling and setting fire to their ``opponents.'' His
conclusion that the wrestlers are people ``just like you and me ...
only very different'' won't win any points for profundity, but the
journey he takes to arrive at this conclusion is often revealing
and occasionally fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein's stars are the stars of the World Wrestling
Federation: people like Terry Funk and Mick ``Mankind'' Foley.
Popping in for cameos are The Rock, Chyna, Stone Cold Steve Austin,
and even wrestler-turned- politico Jesse Ventura. We also meet the
hopefuls, no-names waiting like starlets for a call from the World
Wrestling Federation. One hopeful with a talent for projectile
vomiting even gets an audition with WWF head Vince McMahon. ``It
seems pretty logical that you should be Puke,'' McMahon tells him
tongue not in cheek. ``Puke is good, Puke is nice, and it fits with
the WWF attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   After proposing that pro wrestling is a form of theater and
spectacle, Blaustein shuts the curtain, getting into the brains
(and living rooms) of three wrestlers of various stages of
celebrity and disrepute. There's Funk, a 53-year-old ``living
legend,'' whose arthritic knees are degenerating with every tumble.
There's Funk's frequent opponent Mankind, the devoted family man
with an unusually high threshold for pain, and finally there's
``Jake the Snake'' Roberts, the disgraced cerebral wrestler who
flings serpents onto his opponents in the ring, but who has spent
too much time battling personaldemons (read drugs), frequently
coming out the loser.
</P>
<P>
   When not crashing through cages or braying into a microphone
through a mask of blood, these men are seen walking their daughters
down the aisle, having a heart-to-heart with an estranged child and
frolicking with their adorable kids. Cross-cutting between match
footage and Funk _ looking like five miles of bad Texas roadway _
dragging himself out of bed isn't exactly subtle. Ditto, playing
Rosemary Clooney crooning ``I'll Be Seeing You'' during a
wrestler's farewell bout. These are people who don't invite
mawkishness or sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   But as respectful of these wrestlers as Blaustein obviously is,
he isn't afraid either to show his subjects' warts or to use harsh
tactics to get a point across. In a particularly stomach-turning
sequence, he keeps the camera on Foley's wife and children cringing
and crying out from the front row of an Anaheim match as they watch
an opponent repeatedly pulverizing Daddy with a folding chair.
Blaustein then goes one better, filming himself taking that footage
to the Foley Florida home and watching it with Mr. and Mrs.
Mankind. Mankind's reaction: ``I don't feel like such a good dad
anymore.'' Well, duh! Although Mom should share some of the
culpability.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons not entirely clear, the WWF _ after participating in
its creation _ has now disavowed ``Beyond the Mat'' and refuses to
take advertisements for the film on its television shows. This
seems a little surprising, since the organization and its
controversial leader come across largely as astute business
entities who have figured out a rather unusual way to put on a
show. If McMahon and company are exploiters, they're reeling in
people who seem more than willing _ and even eager _ to be
exploited.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: McMahon and the WWF are treated as background to a
story about people, and for obvious reasons. Who after all is more
interesting _ the individual who sells his soul, or the person who
purchases it? See ``Beyond the Mat'' and draw your own
conclusions. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Beyond the Mat'' (R, violence, language). &QL; 
The stars: Terry Funk, Mick ``Mankind'' Fole, Jake the Snake
Roberts. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Barry Blaustein.
Released by Lions Gate Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 42 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TEXAS-FILM-FESTIVAL-2     03-15 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FILM-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL ON THE EDGE OF FAME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In ``One Soldier,'' a very funny short film
written and directed by its star, the comedian Steven Wright _ he
of the cadaverous deadpan and hair that hangs from both sides of
his head like tumbleweed _ he asks, ``Why are we here?'' And then
he answers, ``I think we're here because it was too crowded where
we were supposed to go.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a motif for Austin's South by Southwest Film
Festival, which began seven years ago as an offshoot of the SXSW
music festival. It has become one of the best known film festivals
in the country, and it is poised to be the next Sundance. A hit on
the order of ``The Blair Witch Project'' or even ``Sex, Lies and
Videotape'' would do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks an increase in visibility would be a
good thing for the festival, which began on Friday and ends this
weekend. Speaking on a panel about the future of independent film,
John Pierson, president of Grainy Pictures, compared SXSW and other
smaller festivals to the regional music labels that dotted the
country in the 1950s and '60s. Those labels championed acts that
not only became successes but also influenced the pop music
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Because SXSW is a magnet for indie filmmakers _ in the hallways
of the Austin Convention Center, ``What is independent film,
exactly?'' has been the constant topic of heated conversations _
the event has the jazzed pulse of a music show. (More pure high
spirits than the music portion of SXSW, when record industry types
descend on the shaggy calm of Austin and suddenly so many people
hit the streets wearing black in daylight that the city looks like
the Dance Club of the Living Dead.) With eager young filmmakers
everywhere here, scrambling to get their films seen or to get them
made, SXSW crackles with excitement.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the SXSW panels tend to be just as big a deal as the
screenings, though this year attendance at them has seemed down,
with a few exceptions. (That the SXSW crowd is filling the theaters
this year rather than going to the panels is, of course, a very
good sign for filmmakers with movies playing here.) The panels
offer a chance to hear directors, producers and actors speak on the
vagaries of how pictures are made.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a panel on the state of independent film featured
Bingham Ray, former head of the indie house October Films, and
Pierson, an indie film hero who has helped nurture the movement
through his involvement as an investor and producer with projects
like Spike Lee's ``She's Gotta Have It'' and the Independent Film
Channel program ``Split Screen,'' where ``Blair Witch'' first
appeared as a short.
</P>
<P>
   Another well-attended panel set up by Harry Knowles of the Ain't
It Cool News Web site featured the first meeting of John Carpenter,
the director known for low-budget genre pictures like
``Halloween,'' and Robert Rodriguez, the Austin filmmaker, whose
aesthetic _ his movies include ``El Mariachi'' and ``From Dusk Till
Dawn'' _ was influenced by Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter asked Rodriguez the film festival equivalent of ``Did
you inhale?'': How much did ``El Mariachi'' really cost? Rodriguez
legendarily made it for only $7,000, which has made him both a hero
and the disbelieved envy of the indie scene.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez sighed and said the figure was accurate. Carpenter
then made a statement that won him the hearts of those in
attendance: ``Until you confront catastrophic failure, you're not a
filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the movies that most people came to SXSW to see.
Among the ones that made an impact was Chris Wilcha's ``The Target
Shoots First,'' a documentary about his time as an employee of
Columbia House, the record club whose ``12 records for a dollar''
pitch was the siren song for an entire generation. It sounds like
an unlikely subject for a film, but Wilcha used the material to
comment on the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Target,'' which traces the parallels between Wilcha's life,
the music scene, Columbia House and Kurt Cobain (Cobain was turned
onto music by listening to records his father bought through the
club), is sharp, self-deprecating and ultimately troubling. The
film recounts how Wilcha accurately tagged punk itself as an
institution after he used the punk sensibility _ anarchy from an
aerosol can _ to successfully repackage Columbia House for a new
audience. ``Target'' won both the judges' and the audience
documentary awards.
</P>
<P>
   Documentaries are the best reasons to go to a film festival,
both for the audience members _ who rarely get to see them outside
of festival settings _ and for the filmmakers, who get to see them
projected on the big screen on their way to television. Paul
Stekler, a film professor at the University of Texas here and
co-director of ``George Wallace: Settin' the House on Fire,'' a
stunning and probing documentary that exposes largely unknown facts
about the race-baiting former Alabama governor, said, ``The thrill
of seeing your work 70 feet tall in front of an audience that loves
it, a work that won't be seen like that too many times _ there's
nothing else like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The director Steven Kessler offered ``The Independent,'' a
hilariously pointed mock documentary about Morty Fineman, a
little-known _ and nonexistent _ exploitation filmmaker with a
social conscience (played by Jerry Stiller, who seems to have gone
prematurely blond). It was worth seeing if only for the brief clips
of the films from Fineman's supposed 437-film career, a filmography
that included ``Twelve Angry Men and a Baby.'' The co-star is the
actress-comedian Janeane Garofalo, who spends as much time doing
independent films as she does mainstream work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones you do for next to nothing are the good jobs,''
Garofalo said in a panel discussion. ``I've done 24 films, and no
one knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Comedy was the high point of this year's SXSW. Even the Dogme
'95 film on the bill, ``Enigma (Love Is a Four-Letter Word),'' was
a minor achievement. It was the first film with a sense of humor by
Dogma '95, the Dutch collective committed to naturalism. ``Enigma''
chases after its star, Max, who is filming his audition for a
script so good ``Al Pacino would kill Nick Nolte [or Nol-ta, as Max
pronounces the name) for it.'' As ``Enigma'' moves around the
streets, sending up the self-absorption of actors and directors, it
feels like MTV's Tom Green's take on ``Inside the Actor's Studio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rollercoaster,'' a bleak and stylish blend of comedy and drama
about a group of disaffected teen-agers, was a winner of this
year's judges' narrative prize. One of the more intriguing films
was ``Loving Jezebel,'' a romantic comedy whose hero (Hill Harper)
is in love with love and, throughout his life, with the wrong
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jezebel,'' which won the audience narrative award, deserved
notice because race isn't an issue, though its protagonist has an
African-American mother and a white father and falls for girls of
varied ethnic backgrounds. Maybe it is a sign of the future in
film, one well worth keeping an eye on.
</P>
<P>
   The shorts included ``Soldier,'' essentially a Civil War
black-and-white version of Woody Allen's ``Love and Death,'' and a
great short on the cult filmmaker Kenneth Anger's ``Scorpio
Rising'' in which Anger relates how, in ``Mean Streets,'' Martin
Scorsese picked up on his use of pop music to advance the story, a
practice the rest of the filmmaking world has adopted.
</P>
<P>
   This year SXSW had a retrospective of Monte Hellman's brooding,
laconic films (``The Shooting,'' ``Two-Lane Blacktop''), and at a
modestly attended Saturday morning panel he mused on his devotion
to his craft, saying that although he hadn't made a film in 11
years, he works every day on projects that end up falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   He summarized the indie life by quoting his wife: ``There is not
a day in my life when I don't wake up and hear my wife say, `Why
don't you get a job?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
