<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-BIOTERROR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NATIONAL SECURITY BECOMES A MEDICAL ISSUE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    America has been reminded once again that it is woefully
ill-prepared to deal with the threat of biological terrorism. The
General Accounting Office, an investigative branch of Congress, has
charged that the government has failed to properly manage the
medical stockpiles developed to protect the public from the scourge
of potentially devastating biological weapons.
 &HT;    In a scathing report, the GAO criticized multiple government
agencies for managing the stockpiles so poorly that they might be
unavailable in the event of an attack. It found shortages of vital
drugs as well as deficiencies in the amount of emergency supplies
that were supposed to be on hand.
 &HT;    The Chemical Biological Incident Response Force, a Marine Corps
unit created in 1996 to help treat civilian victims of a biological
attack, was cited for glaring shortcomings: the GAO discovered that
more than a quarter of the Corps' stockpile was plagued by
inventory discrepancies and record-keeping errors. The Department
of Veterans Affairs was also cited for its failure to competently
manage emergency supplies.
 &HT;    This government ineptitude is no idle matter. If deadly microbes
like anthrax or smallpox were released into the general population
_ a prospect that experts say is quite plausible _ federal
stockpiles of medical supplies would be critical to saving lives.
State and local authorities could be overwhelmed by mounting
casualties, and federal intervention would be urgently needed. No
city in the country has the resources to handle a major attack on
its own.
 &HT;    Yet Washington has been dragging its heels in preparing for a
potential crisis. The recent GAO report is only the latest evidence
to emerge that the government's effort to prepare for a biological
attack is alarmingly ineffective.
 &HT;    The problem, quite simply, is that the nation has yet to take
the steps that could ultimately save thousands, or even tens of
thousands, of lives. Such steps include everything from enhancing
our disease surveillance system to ensuring an adequate supply of
lifesaving vaccines and antibiotics.
 &HT;    The government's failure to take these steps raises inevitable
questions. With the stakes so high, why isn't Washington taking
more aggressive action? If national security and health officials
agree that the threat is real, why aren't they working harder to
mitigate the threat?
 &HT;    The answer may lie in the unique challenges posed by the specter
of bioterrorism.
 &HT;    Unlike a chemical or explosive attack, a biological attack will
require the close collaboration of groups that are not accustomed
to working together: the national security and public health
establishments. It's an odd mix _ doctors and intelligence agents _
but for biological counterterrorism to work, they must join forces.
Unfortunately, the National Security Council and other federal
agencies have yet to fully integrate the medical community into
their plans.
 &HT;    In order to succeed, they will have to correct this flaw,
because the first responders to any bioweapons attack are likely to
be doctors and local public health authorities _ not firemen,
police or SWAT teams. If terrorists should ever unleash infectious
agents on a city, the first evidence of the attack will almost
certainly appear in hospital emergency rooms. At this point, a
rapid response will be critical: if diagnosis and treatment is
delayed, it could mean huge numbers of casualties. The very
survival of healthcare providers could be at stake.
 &HT;    But how well prepared are we to handle such a crisis? Few
doctors have ever seen a case of smallpox, plague or anthrax. Few,
if any, medical laboratories are equipped to diagnose such
conditions. And as the GAO just noted, our stockpiles of drugs and
supplies are far from ideal.
 &HT;    There are other problems as well. The national counterterrorism
effort, for example, has thus far focused mainly on chemical and
explosive weapons rather than on infectious agents. Perhaps this
reflects the security establishment's familiarity with such
weapons, since its efforts in this area have largely involved the
enhancement of existing hazardous material protocols. But what
about the biological threat?
 &HT;    Medical experts point out that biological weapons are far more
dangerous than either chemicals or explosives, since the
devastation from this kind of attack can persist and even get worse
over time, as new cases of disease continue to arise. In contrast,
stabilization and recovery from a chemical or explosive attack can
begin almost immediately. Yet despite this reality, preparations
for a bioweapons attack have lagged far behind efforts to prepare
for more traditional kinds of threats like explosives.
 &HT;    The problem is not just one of priorities. It's also a matter of
expertise. Our national security apparatus _ accustomed to dealing
with military (rather than medical) issues _ hasn't brought enough
health experts into the nation's emergency preparedness program. In
fact, according to the Center for Civilian Biodefense Studies at
Johns Hopkins University, the medical community has so far received
little funding or targeted attention from any preparedness program,
and few hospitals have participated in the bioterrorism response
exercises sponsored by federal authorities.
 &HT;    This is a particularly illogical strategy, since planning for a
possible ``man-made'' epidemic is best handled by the people who
are specially trained for this kind of occurrence: epidemiologists
and infectious disease specialists. Preparing for bioterrorism
without their active involvement is a bit like preparing for war
without the Department of Defense. It's time to correct this
oversight.
 &HT;    We also need to improve the communication between the medical
and law enforcement communities. National security efforts in the
biological arena simply will not work without the combined
participation of both communities. By planning ahead, we can not
only avoid unnecessary problems like drug shortages but we can also
minimize the chance that cultural differences between the national
security and health establishments will hamper the nation's
response to a terrorist attack.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Stephen L. Cohen
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stephen L. Cohen, M.D., is a medical journalist based in New
York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
