<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ESCAPING REALITY ON A ROAD HOG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The average dream lasts about six minutes, but
for those who have sat on a Harley-Davidson, BMW or other
motorcycle, the dream lasts for as long as the motor is rumbling.
</P>
<P>
   If I have to explain, as the saying goes, you won't understand.
</P>
<P>
   But the one reality that shocks a lot of would-be riders is the
sticker price of the new bikes _ $15,000 to $22,000 is typical for
the new high-end Harleys and Beamers, with even the Honda, Yamaha
and Kawasaki touring lines getting way up there in price.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is an answer for that.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a renting a motorcycle for a vacation is growing
quickly and now popular enough to support a minitour industry. For
a package price, you can set up a vacation that includes a rental
bike (often a high-end Harley-Davidson), insurance, a proposed
itinerary, lodging, food and support.
</P>
<P>
   I don't own a bike at the moment, but I've driven about 75,000
miles around the western United States at various times on old
Triumphs, Harleys and BMWs, and can say the sensation of freedom
from a road trip on a bike is right up there with the best of any
California adventures and getaways. My preference is to throw my
camping book in a saddlebag and see where I end up, but there are
many more formal options _ as well as several wild cards.
</P>
<P>
   The price of rentals can be as low as $40 per day (offseason,
weekday, no insurance, no food, no nothin'), and go as high as
$3,500 a week for the all-included, everything-goes deals. Now is
the time when most reservations for planned vacations take place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are three of the major rental/tour companies in the San
Francisco Bay Area, as well as a selection of best elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Dubbelju Motorcycle Rentals: Instead of fitting your vacation
time into somebody else's plan, you instead set your destinations
and pace, and Wolfgang will create a tour based on that. His rental
fleet includes BMWs, Harley-Davidsons and Triumphs, and to keep
your mind free and easy, he includes a 24-hour roadside assistance
program. Wolfgang is known in Europe and across North America and
draws a cult-like following; it is common for someone to call him
from points around the world and say, ``I'm coming into San
Francisco in July. Set up a loop trip through Yosemite and Lake
Tahoe,'' and thus a dramatic vacation is born. Prices range from
$79 to $139 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Write Dubbelju Motorcycle Rentals, LLC, 271 Clara
Street, San Francisco, CA 94107, or call (415) 495-2774. On the Web
at www.dubbelju.com.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Rider of San Francisco: Starting from San Francisco, trips
feature the rental of near-new Harley-Davidsons, with your choice
of heading south via two-laners to Carmel or north on Highway 1
with a loop back through the wine country. They call it the
``California Dreaming Tour,'' featuring the best of the Pacific
Coast Highway. The five-day tour adds routes into the Sierra
foothills on the curvy two-laners. A three-day tour costs $995 and
a five-day trip goes for $1,595.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Write Eagle Rider, 1060 Bryant Street, San
Francisco, CA 94103, or call (415) 503-1900. On the Web at
www.eaglerider.com.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Cruise America, Oakland: This is a do-it-yourself-style rental
service, located adjacent to the Oakland Coliseum, where you select
either a Harley-Davidson, Honda or BMW, rent it by the day,
unlimited mileage, then head off for yonder. I strongly suggest
carrying a certain large, red camping book with you so you never
get stuck for the night. For a top-of-the-line Harley Road King or
Soft-tail, the price is $129 per day, with insurance available. You
supply your helmet and all gear. During summer, they suggest
reservations at least a month in advance; otherwise, a week advance
is plenty. In case of rain, renters are provided the ability to
reschedule.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Write Cruise America, 796 66th Ave., Oakland, CA
94621, or phone (510) 639-7125. Web site: cq
CQwww.cruiseamerica.com.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   State of Jefferson Motorcycle Tours: This is the only tour of
its kind, featuring custom back-country fishing, camping and riding
on BMW and Honda GS bikes in the ``State of Jefferson,'' that is,
in Northern California from Dunsmuir across Siskiyou, Modoc and Del
Norte counties. Three-day trip: $750. Phone (530) 235-0081, or
write at P.O. Box 70, Castella, CA 96017.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   American Dream Motorcycle Rental: Based in San Diego,
specializing in tours heading up Highway 1 as well as south into
Baja, with rates as low as $39.95 daily. Phone (888) 235-7190. Web
site: www.mltechs.com/harley/.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   America Frontier Tours: Based in Santa Fe, N.M., features tours
through the high mountains and deep canyons of northern New Mexico
on Harley-Davidsons. $275 per day and up. Write P.O. Box 29241,
Santa Fe, NM 87592, or phone (888) TOURS-HD. Web site:
www.americanfrontiermc.com/.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Arctic Motorcycle: This the wildest trip I could find, where for
$5,000 Canadian (about $3,500 U.S. dollars), you ride from the
Yukon on through Dawson on the Dempster Highway up to the Arctic
Circle. Write at P.O. Box 5621, Whitehorse, Yukon, Canada Y1A 5H4,
or phone at (867) 633-3344. Web site: www.arcticmoto.yk.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
