u i BC-MEXICO-SUICIDE-NYT &LR;      03-15 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO INVESTIGATES OFFICIAL'S SUICIDE AND SOURCE OF CONCEALED
CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Authorities investigating the suicide of a senior
official in the attorney general's office are trying to find out
where he obtained the small fortune that he kept in a safe deposit
box.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Juan Manuel Izabal, denied in one of at least
three notes that he wrote before he killed himself last Wednesday
that he had received the money from narcotics traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Jorge Madrazo said drug ties had not been
ruled out. Authorities are also investigating whether the money may
have come from selling senior law-enforcement jobs, shaking down
contractors who have sold equipment to the attorney general's
office or other corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide is the latest in a series of scandals to hit the
country's top law-enforcement agency, which Mexican and U.S.
officials say has been thoroughly corrupted by traffickers and
other criminals despite purges aimed at eliminating dishonest
officials. A former deputy attorney general also committed suicide
_ in New Jersey last year _ after having been charged with
laundering $9 million in traffickers' bribes. His aide had carried
the money to Houston in suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have reported finding at least $700,000 in one safe
deposit box registered to Izabal. The newspaper Universal reported
Sunday that investigators had found $500,000 in two additional safe
deposit boxes and had obtained warrants to search others.
</P>
<P>
   Izabal was the top administrative officer at the attorney
general's office, an agency with thousands of employees and offices
in all 32 states. He managed the agency payrolls, hiring and
purchases and the thousands of buildings, planes and vehicles
seized from traffickers. He had worked closely with Madrazo for
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Izabal's notes, he said he had received the money
before going to work for Madrazo. But several Mexican newspapers,
citing unidentified government officials, suggested that the
unfolding scandal had brought pressures from within President
Ernesto Zedillo's government for Madrazo's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Izabal's body, with a gunshot wound to the head, was found last
Wednesday morning, seated at the wheel of his Chevrolet Suburban,
parked a few blocks from his Mexico City residence. A .38-caliber
Beretta pistol was in his hand, and investigators ruled his death a
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The contents of the first of the safe deposit boxes, in a Mexico
City branch of Citibank, seem to have been discovered by accident.
Bank executives, preparing to close the branch, had sent three
notices to Izabal urging him to retrieve the contents. But Izabal,
for reasons that are been clear, did not respond, Madrazo said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the bank opened the box and found the $700,000 and
``personal documents,'' Madrazo said. The documents have not been
described.
</P>
<P>
   The day before his death, Izabal appeared at the branch, Madrazo
continued, but the bankers refused to give him access to his box.
Instead, they reported finding the money and documents to Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   Izabal killed himself before dawn the next day. At the morgue,
investigators found two handwritten notes in Izabal's suit.
Handwriting experts said they Izabal had written them, although his
brother disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To whom it may concern,'' the first began. ``Do not blame
anyone for my death. It is my decision, and I take responsibility.
May God forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   The second note was addressed to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive me for what I am going to do,'' it began. ``You are
going to learn of things you don't know about, and they will
disappoint you. The safe deposit boxes do not only contain
documents, as I told you. There is also money that is difficult to
explain. It is the product of business deals that I have done, but
that in my position as public servant would not be understood. It
is not from narcos, but I did not declare it, and the circumstances
have me up against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   City detectives who searched Izabal's office found a third note,
addressed to Madrazo, in which he said he had not received the
money in the three years that he worked for the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake before working in the attorney general's
office,'' the note said. ``The money is from before. It was my
protection, and I've had it for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Izabal said in the note that he had told his wife when he
acquired the safe deposit box that he had put ``important documents
from a job'' in it and that ``if something happens to me, take them
out and use them to help me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
