<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYING OUT THOSE WET BASEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water in the basement can be a year-round problem, but it seems
particularly acute during the spring and summer. In the early
spring, melting snow turns into ground water that seeps through the
soil. Pressure in the soil forces it through the foundation walls
into the basement. Spring rains can trigger a deluge of water that
dumps thousands of gallons of water around the house. This will
percolate into the ground, where hydrostatic pressure will force
the water through basement walls. In the summer, the humidity in
the air condenses on the basement walls and drips down to form
puddles on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of techniques you can employ to dry a wet
basement and avoid it getting wet in the first place. For the
first, you must determine where the water is coming from, and then
you can plan an effective strategy to end the problem. There are
three major sources of basement water: condensation, runoff and
subsurface penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Condensation comes from the ambient moisture in the basement
air. Unlike runoff water and subsurface water penetration that
comes from outside the house, condensation is an interior problem.
But how can you tell if the water droplets collecting on the walls
come from ambient humidity or are the result of ground water
seeping through the walls?
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple test you can perform to tell where the water
on the walls is coming from. Tape pieces of aluminum foil (about 6
by 6 inches) over damp spots on the walls. Check the foil patches
after a few days. If moisture has formed on the outside of the
foil, then condensation is the cause of the water. If, on the other
hand, the moisture is on the wall side, the water is seeping
through the wall from the ground outside.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you have a condensation problem, what can you do about
it? Start by airing out the basement. Open as many windows as
possible and set up fans to pull the air outside. Remove any items
that add to the humidity in the air. These include newly cut
firewood and wet clothes hanging on an indoor clothesline. If you
have a basement clothes dryer, make sure that it is vented to the
outside and that there are no leaks in the vent ducts. Wrap
cold-water pipes with foam insulation to isolate them from the
warm, moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, install a dehumidifier in the basement. A good
heavy-duty unit can pull more than 50 pints of water out of the air
each 24 hours. It is best to place the unit near a drain. This will
make it more convenient to empty the reservoir. In the fall and
winter, make sure the basement is heated so moisture evaporates
quickly
</P>
<P>
   Some question the merits of a basement dehumidifier. They point
out that the dry basement atmosphere will actually pull water in
from the surrounding soil because water naturally flows from a wet
environment to a dry one. There is some truth to this, but experts
point out that an efficient dehumidifier can easily evacuate the
small amount of water drawn in through the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Runoff water is another significant cause of basement water.
Runoff comes from rain or melting snow. The way to control runoff
and keep it from entering the basement is to channel it away from
the house before it has a chance to seep into the ground. Start by
inspecting the gutters around the roof. They should be clear of
leaves and debris with tight seams and no holes.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the downspouts to make sure they are clear, and place
splash blocks under the downspout elbow. These will divert the
water pouring out of the downspout away from the foundation.
Ideally, the gutters should drain four feet away from the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The ground surrounding the house should slope down, at least one
inch per foot, so water will run away from the house. Some houses
at the base of a hill may have an additional drainage system in the
form of a U-shaped channel that wraps around the house. Coarse
gravel in the channel captures runoff from the hill and diverts it
around and away from the house. This system is effective at first,
but over time the runoff will deposit silt in the channel and clog
the spaces in the gravel bed. The remedy is to dig up and replace
the gravel after sifting out the silt.
</P>
<P>
   Water can enter the basement by coming up from below. Called
subsurface penetration, the excessive moisture is a result of
underground springs or a rising water table. It is best to consult
with a professional to find the ideal solution for your home. He
may suggest installing a sump pump and perhaps digging around the
foundation walls to apply a waterproof membrane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
