u e BC-SUBURBS-FILM-REVIEW-N     03-15 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBURBS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LIFESTYLE': A DISQUIETING LOOK AT MIDDLE-AGED `SWINGERS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That old Freudian maxim about the mind being the most important
sexual organ certain applies to ``The Lifestyle: Group Sex in the
Suburbs,'' David Schisgall's disquieting documentary study of
middle-aged ``swingers.'' Although some may be stimulated by the
movie's fleeting glimpses of gray-haired, pot-bellied,
cellulite-jiggling, over-60 orgiasts lustily going at it in their
suburban living rooms after an evening of barbecue and California
dip, many more will probably be repulsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lifestyle'' includes one brief hard-core scene, but it is
not an exploitation film. In its blunt deglamorization of sexual
license, it is more like the antidote to Stanley Kubrick's elegant,
fearful erotic dream, ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' In Kubrick's
Freud-drenched vision of sexual transgression, group sex within the
upper class was portrayed as the ultimate taboo, a secretive
nightmarish dance with the Devil. Here it is an indoor sport played
by married middle-class couples on Saturday night in living rooms
decked out with disco balls and Japanese lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   The movie devotes much of its time to interviews with devoted
longtime swingers attending Lifestyles '97, a national convention.
We learn that most swingers meet at clubs that advertise in
publications in every state except North Dakota. Bisexuality is
encouraged among the women but not among the men. (Not so much as a
homosexual glance is exchanged in the movie.) Nobody seems to worry
about sexually transmitted diseases, since the use of condoms is
taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   What lends the movie a comic undertone is how everyday many of
these swingers are. There is absolutely nothing to distinguish
these polyester-clad, politically conservative suburbanites from
the crowds in any Middle American shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes bluntly clear the reasons for the popularity of
swinging. Our society uses sex to sell everything and places such a
premium on sexual attractiveness and fulfillment that thousands of
frustrated people are bound to respond to the eroticizing of the
climate. Many of those interviewed have been married for decades,
and they attest that swinging is a solution to sexual boredom in a
relationship that has lost its zest. It's also a way to deal with
the loneliness of empty-nest syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the couples interviewed cheerfully stand up for
their lifestyle, there are exceptions. John and Gina, the youngest
and by far the most attractive couple interviewed, are naysayers.
After trying the swinging life (at John's instigation), they
withdrew because of Gina's reluctance to play, and the damage their
experimentation has done to their marriage is painfully visible.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has its share of oddballs and fanatics. We meet an
enthusiastic but dumpy-looking 73-year-old man who claims to have a
marathon sexual appetite. There is Dr. Robert McGinley, president
of the Lifestyles Organization, who estimates the number of
swingers in North America to be 3 million and daydreams about their
being organized into a political bloc.
</P>
<P>
   One devoted swinger enthusiastically points to the promiscuous
habits of chimpanzees as a model for an emerging orgy-porgy sexual
utopia. We even visit a swingers' church, the Earth Church of the
Pacific, to witness a wedding whose ceremony invokes the blessings
of ``angels and wizards'' instead of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lifestyle'' leaves you with strong contradictory feelings.
The sex shown in the movie is so routine and passionless that the
couplings look more like collaborative stretching exercises than
soul-stirring erotic encounters. Might this indiscriminate,
unromantic bumping and grinding be the outcome of ultimate sexual
liberation? If so, who wants it?
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, you have to admire these swingers for standing
up for pleasure in a society that, despite its obsession with sex,
views sex negatively. There's something courageous and healthy in
their demonstration that you don't have to be young and beautiful
to find sexual pleasure and celebrate the erotic.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE LIFESTYLE'
</P>
<P>
   Group Sex in the Suburbs
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Schisgall; director of photography, Peter
Hawkins; edited by Andrew Hafitz; music by Byron Estep and Edward
Sperry; produced by Dan Cogan; released by Seventh Art Releasing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Sarah and Orin, Carmen and John, Pat and Ric, Gina and
John, Wild Bill Goodwin, Dr. Robert McGinley, Jim and Shery, Hugh
and Karen, C.J. and George, Jeanne and Bright and Dante Amore.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 78 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
