<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FINE ART OF ART CRITICISM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the fine-art collection of  &UR; Steven Wynn &LR;  at the
Bellagio hotel in Las Vegas last weekend, Personals received a
press kit extolling the glories of the paintings, which include
works by Rembrandt, Van Gogh, Picasso, Miro, Manet, Monet, De
Kooning and other masters.
</P>
<P>
   The press kit for the exhibit included an essay by  &UR; Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Schjeldahl &LR; , apparently written as a free-lance assignment before
he became an esteemed art critic for the New Yorker. The following
bon mots from Schjeldahl describe the wonders of the collection:
</P>
<P>
   - This ``remarkable American collection comes together suddenly
in a place that seems ever less unlikely the more one thinks about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``All pleasures are pleasurable, but not all are equal.''
</P>
<P>
   - Describing  &UR; Claude Monet &LR; 's ``Water-Lily Pond With Bridge,''
the critic writes, ``The picture is a moisturizer of the soul.
Monet's painting also observes a high holy day of the human hand.''
</P>
<P>
   - As to  &UR; Joan Miro &LR; 's ``Dialogue of Insects,'' ``Nagging at the
mind like sandy grit caught in your eye, the apparitions clamor to
be identified, but none is anything you have seen before.
Gradually, as you look, you sink into the condition of those
winsome critters, sharing a perspective by which, say, a grain
stalk towers like a redwood tree. In the universe, aren't we all
odd, dwarfed critters, too?''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Looking (at  &UR; Willem De Kooning &LR; 's `Police Gazette') we seek
eyeholds like sailors grasping for survival in a storm at sea.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Come to close quarters with all of the works here
assembled,'' the critic implores. ``Think of the hands that made
them _ because those hands are thinking of you!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLOBAL NIBBLES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Scottish chef who introduced deep-fried Mars Bars at a Paris
restaurant has caused international consternation, says a report in
the Times of London, forwarded to Personals by  &UR; Dennis &LR; 
 &UR; Cavagnaro &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The dish _ made by dipping a cold Mars Bar into batter, frying
it in oil, then serving it with whipped cream and strawberry sauce
_ was first prepared at Le Chipper in Paris by a Glaswegian chef
who has since departed. The left-wing French newspaper Liberation
proclaimed the treat ``not bad at all,'' an opinion not shared by
many Parisians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried one of their deep-fried Mars Bars and found it
disgusting,'' said Marie-Ange Renaud, owner of Le Petit Bonheur, a
traditional French restaurant next door to Le Chipper. ``That sort
of thing will never work in France.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberation has responded to French indignation by adding fuel to
the fire. Last week it printed a recipe for ham roasted in cola
with sugar, mustard and breadcrumbs.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``Is your hair making your face look fat?'' asks the latest
issue of Glamour magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - At a downtown Manhattan bar so new it doesn't yet have a name,
 &UR; Keanu Reeves  &LR; was upset when the bartender told him that he
doesn't sell cigarettes. According to New York magazine, the owner
of the place sent the bartender two blocks to the nearest deli to
make the purchase. Reeves tipped him $150.
</P>
<P>
   - The Ebonite Skull Ball, a clear bowling ball with a replica
human skull inside, costs $150, reports Men's Fitness. This item is
on view at www.ebonite.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Martha Stewart &LR; , who's been fighting with her neighbors in
Connecticut, is departing for Clintonland, Westchester County, N.Y.
She's bought a $50 million estate in Bedford Hills, next door to
 &UR; Ralph Lauren &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  ``Is it more prestigious to be a tenured professor or a
famous actor?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  ``Actors tell stories that serve a function, we go through
things for people. Historically, that's what plays do. You go to
the theater and you have that catharsis because there's a heroic or
non-heroic figure going through these things that speak to you in
some way, and you are involved and feel vital, and maybe you learn,
but at least you have an experience because we all can't go through
these heroic things. ... That's a great service. ... If I were a
teacher at Yale, I'd be teaching people who are already really
well-educated. You're not really saving anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - David Duchnovny &LR;  of ``The X-Files'' in a Movieline interview
that notes he ``almost ended up an academic instead of an actor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
