<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER PATROL DETAINS STRAY MEXICAN SOLDIERS AFTER SHOTS FIRED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal lawmen detained nine Mexican soldiers for
several hours Tuesday night after they fired two shots in the
direction of U.S. Border Patrol agents, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, part of an anti-drug patrol, apparently fired the
shots after inadvertently crossing the U.S. border into a remote
area south of Santa Teresa, N.M., just west of El Paso. No one was
injured, and the Border Patrol did not return fire, INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol is investigating whether the shots were fired
at the agents, a drug suspect or by accident, said Tomas Zuniga, a
spokesman for the patrol's central regional office in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at all possibilities at this time,'' Zuniga said
of the patrol's investigation. ``We are trying to come up with ways
to prevent this from happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. diplomats are meeting with their Mexican
counterparts over the incident, reported INS, the Border Patrol's
parent agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Consulate in El Paso confirmed that soldiers
accidentally crossed into the United States. But consulate
spokesman Marco Antonio Fraire told The Associated Press that he
had no information about any shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The shots were the most harrowing part of a night in which two
Mexican anti-drug patrols in Humvees apparently crossed into the
United States inadvertently at 11:30 p.m. CST. In both cases,
Border Patrol agents identified themselves and informed the
Mexicans that they were in the United States, INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident, shots were fired from a Humvee that later
crossed back into Mexico. It was not clear when the shots were
fired, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents detained the nine occupants of the other
Humvee. They were questioned for several hours at the Santa Teresa
Border Patrol Station.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were then released, and they returned to Mexico in
their Humvee and with their weapons and their drug-detection dog.
The Mexican colonel in charge of the soldiers later met with Luis
Barker, the Border Patrol's chief agent in El Paso, INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colonel explained that the Mexican vehicles and officers
were part of a counter-narcotics unit that had been working
primarily in the interior of Mexico and were unfamiliar with the
border region,'' INS said in a prepared statement. The agency did
not disclose the colonel's name.
</P>
<P>
   Zuniga, of the Border Patrol, said it is not unusual for Mexican
and U.S. agents to cross the border inadvertently, especially
during night operations. But gunfire has never occurred during
these incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go into Mexico by accident and they come here by
accident,'' Zuniga said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We communicate with each other whenever one of these incidents
occurs,'' he said. ``We are two friendly nations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
