A7934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DIESEL16-COX     03-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIESEL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DIESEL FUMES SAID TO PUT 125,000 AMERICANS AT CANCER RISK
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 125,000 Americans are at risk of getting
cancer during their lifetimes from breathing exhaust from trucks,
buses and other users of diesel engines, state and local air
pollution regulators said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Associations representing the state and local regulators called
on the Environmental Protection Agency to adopt stringent standards
limiting the amount of sulfur allowed in diesel fuel, and the
emissions of soot and smog-forming nitrogen oxide from new trucks
and buses that burn it.
</P>
<P>
   The two closely related organizations, the State and Territorial
Air Pollution Program Administrators and the Association of Local
Air Pollution Control Officials, said they based the cancer
estimate on a study released last year by California's South Coast
Air Quality Management District.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on analysis of air samples collected at
various locations in the Los Angeles metropolitan area during a
one-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The state and local air pollution groups assumed that the
per-capita cancer risk from diesel exhaust was twice as great in
Los Angeles as in the rest of the country. To estimate the risk in
other locations, they halved the risk found in the Los Angeles and
multiplied it by local population estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the national cancer estimate was the second shot in a
budding debate over whether EPA should also cut the allowable
concentration of sulfur in diesel fuel by more than 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's request for permission to develop the new sulfur
rules is being reviewed by the White House Office of Management and
Budget. The proposal is opposed by oil companies, truckers and
other interests.
</P>
<P>
   Air quality control scientists say sulfur must be removed from
fuel in order for pollution control devices to work properly.
</P>
<P>
   The California study concluded that more than 70 percent of
cancers attributable to air pollution in southern California could
be traced to soot and other components of exhaust from diesel
trucks, buses, construction equipment and other machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no pollution more disgusting than the thick, noxious,
suffocating smoke that billows from trucks and buses,'' said S.
William Becker, executive director of both the state and local air
pollution associations. ``But even worse, these fumes are putting
us at risk of cancer, a risk that can be almost completely
eliminated with modern pollution controls.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA allows the diesel fuel to contain a maximum sulfur
concentration of 500 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this analysis is another strong argument why EPA needs
to clean up diesel fuel and set very stringent emission standards
for trucks, buses and other big engines that use it,'' said Frank
O'Donnell, director of the Clean Air Trust, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from either petroleum or
trucking industries.
</P>
<P>
   However, earlier this week, a coalition of groups dominated by
the two industries called on EPA Administrator Carol Browner to
withdraw a proposal to reduce the permissible fuel sulfur
concentration to 15 parts per million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA's proposal for diesel sulfur is likely to reduce the
supply of diesel fuel as well as heating oil and even gasoline,''
the associations said in a letter to Browner. ``We consider it a
blueprint for future shortages of diesel and home heating oil.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter stated that the proposed cap and the six-year time
frame for implementing it ``are in excess of what is feasible or
advisable,'' and said EPA had not conducted a satisfactory analysis
of the rule's impact.
</P>
<P>
   The groups said they were ``committed to dramatically reducing
diesel engine emissions'' but asked that EPA ``perform the
necessary analysis before proposing a rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by the Petroleum Marketers Association of
America, the Society of Independent Gasoline Marketers of America,
the Independent Fuel Terminal Operators Association, the National
Association of Convenience Stores, the American Petroleum
Institute, the Service Station Dealers of America and Allied
Traders, the National Association of Truck Stop Operators, the
National Petrochemical and Refiners Association and the National
Council of Farm Cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
