<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PENNSYLVANIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE COURTS VOTERS IN PIVOTAL PENNSYLVANIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pennsylvania voters have almost always picked the
winning presidential candidate for the last four decades, and with
that in mind, Democrat Al Gore wasted no time Wednesday heading
there to stake his claim to the key battleground.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, Gore courted union workers, raised money,
picked up the endorsement of Mayor John Street and visited a
vocational school.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded a cheering state AFL-CIO conference of the
anti-union practices of past Republican administrations and warned
of a rough general election campaign ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win, the other side is going to throw everything
but the kitchen sink. They're manning the barricades. They're
throwing unprecedented amounts of money at the campaign. They will
stop at nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pennsylvania holds its primary April 4, Gore is
spending his time here and in a half-dozen other swing states with
an eye on the November election against Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A manufacturing powerhouse earlier in the century, Pennsylvania
has gradually and painfully made a transition to a more high-tech
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The state's population is aging and heavily Catholic. Its voters
are often socially conservative but also supportive of government
programs such as Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent times neither political party has dominated the
state. Even as President Clinton won the state in 1992 and 1996,
Republicans have dominated the statehouse. While the mayors of
Philadelphia and Pittsburgh are Democrats, both U.S. senators are
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty much a centrist electorate,'' said Terry Madonna,
a professor at Millersville University.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Keystone poll, which Madonna directs, has Gore and
Bush in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released 10 days ago, shows dramatic improvement for
the vice president, who had trailed Bush by 20 points last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is Gore is doing much better among
blue-collar working Democrats,'' Madonna said.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster said Gore was also beating Bush in the Philadelphia
suburbs, the home of many moderate Republicans who were critical to
Clinton's two victories.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the survey shows the vice president is not
doing as well as he should in the traditionally Democratic
strongholds of Pittsburgh and the old industrial belt in the
southwestern corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem for Gore is senior citizens. The poll
showed Bush even with Gore among those older than 65, an important
voting block in a state with the second-highest percentage of
senior citizens in the nation, following only Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But among Catholics, another pivotal group of voters, the vice
president leads Bush, who spent the last part of the primary season
defending his decision to speak at Bob Jones University, whose
leaders have made anti-Catholic comments.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns claim they have advantages in the state. Bush
advisers are counting on the state's popular Republican Gov. Tom
Ridge, a Catholic who favors abortion rights, to put his political
machine to work to energize voters. Ridge has frequently been
mentioned as potential running mate for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a state where I think I can win,'' Bush said Wednesday.
``That's a state we intend to compete in. It's a state where it's
going to be helpful to have my friend Tom Ridge by my side. He's
been a good governor. But it's a tough state. It's going to be very
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Republicans will hold their national
presidential convention in Philadelphia this summer, which GOP
officials anticipate will shower their candidate with even more
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted the significance of the convention site, telling the
AFL-CIO workers: ``I want you to make sure that's as close as he
gets to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is relying on organized labor and the
Democratic mayors to provide the ground troops to get voters to the
polls for him in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor is gong to pull out all the stops for Gore,'' Madonna
said.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna also said that another factor helping Gore is that
traditional Democratic issues such as health care, education and
prescription drug coverage for the elderly rank high among
Pennsylvanian's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   However, tax cuts, the centerpiece of Bush's economic plans,
were mentioned by only one out of 10 voters polled as a top
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna said he expected Gore and Bush to lavish attention on
the state. A major reason, he said, is that Pennsylvania has failed
to vote for the White House winner only once since 1960. That was
in 1968 when voters went with Democrat Hubert Humphrey over Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to this report from
Austin, Texas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
