<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7952 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-CLERKS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CLERKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER QUESTIONS JUSTICES ABOUT LACK OF MINORITY CLERKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Supreme Court justices Wednesday defended their
choices of law clerks amid a congressman's repeated pleas that they
and their colleagues do a better job of hiring minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before a House panel, Justices David H. Souter and
Clarence Thomas acknowledged that federal judges in general should
strive to hire more minorities to be law clerks. The justices,
under persistent questioning from Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif.,
added that an applicant's race is irrelevant when they choose their
clerks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That simply is not the criteria on which we hire,'' Souter
said, referring to a candidate's ethnic background. He added that
he scours federal appeals courts with a ``broad'' eye in search of
the most qualified clerks, regardless of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, echoing Souter, said he and his high-court colleagues
``keep our eyes and ears open'' for clerks with strong academic
records and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the nine justices hires up to four clerks annually. The
clerks are recently licensed attorneys who help the justices
research and write their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Souter and Thomas declined to say if any of their current clerks
are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make the clerks public figures,'' Souter said.
He added that his clerks are free to disclose their ethnic
backgrounds but that he would not.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court during the past two years has come under
attack from the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People for what it has called a distressing paucity of minority law
clerks. This year, in marked improvement from past years, five of
the court's 35 clerks are members of minority groups _ two blacks
and three Asian-Americans, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent improvement, Dixon told the justices that he
will continue to press them and their colleagues to hire even more
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to go away,'' Dixon said of the
hiring issue.
</P>
<P>
   Souter and Thomas appeared before the House Appropriations
subcommittee on behalf of their colleagues to urge Congress to
appropriate $45.2 million for the high court in fiscal year 2001,
which begins Oct. 1. The justices' annual appearance before the
panel is the only chance Congress members get to question
high-court jurists, and Dixon made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Souter and Thomas, who also testified last March, were called
upon for the second time in as many years to respond to Dixon's
criticism that they and their colleagues have not hired enough
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, as they did last year, held fast to the position
that law schools and lower court judges have failed to move
qualified applicants up the judicial employment pipeline to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Justices generally hire clerks who graduated near the top of
their law school classes and have clerked for a federal appeals
court judge, prerequisites not too many minority lawyers have
satisfied, Souter said. That prior experience is necessary because
Supreme Court clerks must be ready from their first day on the job
to assist the justices, Souter told the Subcommittee on Commerce,
Justice, State and Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas added that justices and lower federal court judges have
no formal guidelines on the hiring of law clerks, leaving it up to
the jurists to decide for themselves whom to hire as assistants.
But, based on informal discussions with fellow justices and judges,
Thomas said he senses a ``heightened awareness'' of the need to
hire more minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Under continued questioning from Dixon, Thomas said the court's
record of hiring women is stronger than its record of hiring
minorities. Thomas attributed the disparity to the greater number
of female law clerks at the federal appeals court level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that difficult to find women law clerks,'' Thomas
said. ``They're fairly well represented there'' on the appellate
courts, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But Dixon interjected, ``It's not difficult to find white women
law clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparking the law-clerk controversy was a March 1998 USA Today
study that found only seven of the then-most recent 394 clerks were
black, four were Hispanic and 18 were Asian. In October 1998, NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume was arrested and held briefly for protesting
on the steps of the Supreme Court the justices' lack of minority
clerks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
