<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PARIS-MAYOR-NYT &LR;      03-15 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SETBACKS FOR EMBATTLED MAYOR OF PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Not long ago, Mayor Jean Tiberi invited the foreign
press to lunch. Under the coffered ceilings and the crystal
chandeliers of Paris' magnificent City Hall, he laid out a spread
that began with foie gras accompanied by a 30-year-old sauterne and
ended, many bottles later, with a 1985 Dom Perignon.
</P>
<P>
   Between sips, Tiberi described his political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good record,'' he said. ``And I am standing on my
record. Someone will have to explain to me why I should not run
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiberi made it sound like a simple equation. It is not. In fact,
Tiberi's attempt to hold on to his job is one of France's most
entertaining political stories these days. The post is coveted for
the comforts of the City Hall building and its wine cellar. But it
is also considered a jumping-off point for bigger things. Before
becoming president of France, Jacques Chirac as mayor of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiberi has problems, and they seem to mount by the day.
There is the matter of his wife, Xaviere, and her brush with the
law. Last year, before her conviction was put aside on a
technicality, Mrs. Tiberi was found guilty of accepting $36,000 for
a 36-page report on a subject she knew nothing about.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the flimsy report on France's relations with
French-speaking nations, with childish spelling and grammar
mistakes, showed up in the press. One of Mrs. Tiberi's
co-defendants testified that it was her husband who had arranged
the fake job as a pretext for a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor blew right by that one, meeting the press the next
day to tell them that he had been convicted of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, Tiberi's fortunes seemed to dim further as
his honesty was questioned once more. Looking to keep the Gaullist
party's nomination, despite polls that found that only 5 percent of
Parisians believed him honest, Tiberi turned to party members for
support.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the leader of his party, Michele Alliot-Marie, to put
his candidacy to a vote by party members. (Usually, the party
leader simply decides who will have the nomination.)
</P>
<P>
   But while he was waiting for an answer, the party's national
headquarters unveiled a little problem: The list of local members
supplied by Tiberi contained 1,500 phantom members _ Parisians who
had moved away, stopped paying their dues or died. One party
employee found seven strangers listed as living in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Tiberi quickly withdrew the list, blaming the celebrated Year
2000 malfunction for what he termed ``computer errors.'' This
caused a great deal of mirth among French journalists, as Year 2000
problems have barely appeared in France.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason that Parisians are on the edge of their seats
waiting to see what happens to Tiberi is his long association with
Chirac, who handpicked him for the job. Tiberi, 65, was Chirac's
deputy for most of Chirac's time as mayor from 1977 to 1995.
Political analysts often speculate that Tiberi has been untouchable
because he knows too much about scandals at City Hall through the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Many scandals are still being investigated. One inquiry is
looking at the mayor's role in awarding public housing contracts to
supporters of Rally for the Republic, including those given out
when Tiberi was Chirac's right-hand man. The mayor is also being
investigated for inflated voter rolls and he has been questioned
about evidence that political cronies hold city jobs but are not
required to do any work.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiberi's lifeline to Chirac may be fraying. At lunch with
the foreign press, he boasted that he expected Chirac's continued
support. ``I have supported him when he was down,'' he said. ``Why
should he not support me?''
</P>
<P>
   This week he thundered that it was ``unimaginable that anyone
should try to eliminate a friend of Chirac's.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few days, Chirac has been conspicuously silent.
Even when Tiberi was admitted to a hospital with an infection,
Chirac apparently did not call. Such an oversight, said the
satirical weekly Le Canard Enchaine, was hard to imagine, when
``most provincial Rally for the Republic members suffering from
corns'' got calls from the president wishing them well.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Tiberi took another blow. Rally for the Republic,
worried it would lose the mayor's race in March 2001 if Tiberi ran,
moved to suspend him as party leader in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to take measures to show our nomination will be decided
in a totally open manner,'' Alliot-Marie said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiberi indignantly declared at an afternoon news conference
that the action came as a complete surprise to him. ``This
method,'' he said, ``was authoritarian, dictatorial, fascist and
Stalinist.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed not to let go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
