<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FAVORS REQUIRING USE OF `SMART GUN' TECHNOLOGY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Under fire from Democrats as weak on gun
control, presumed Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush
said Wednesday he could favor a law requiring every new firearm to
include technology that would allow the weapons to be fired only
when matched to the owner's fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the technology changes it will be good,'' Bush said. ``I
want to make sure I understand fully how the technology works
before I would embrace something like that, but it's not a bad
option. I will consider that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush for weeks has been promoting such ``smart gun'' technology
as a means of keeping unauthorized individuals and children from
shooting a firearm. But his statement Wednesday is the first time
he has indicated he might require gun makers to use such
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The technology uses a computer chip and a sensor on a gun to
match a fingerprint or palm print to the weapon's owner, allowing
only that person to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has embraced the ``smart gun'' technology in defending
Democratic criticism over his opposition to requiring all gun
owners to keep a trigger lock on their firearms when not in use.
Bush says such a law would be unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments in a wide-ranging interview with the
Houston Chronicle as he sat in the front parlor of the Texas
Governor's Mansion, a day after clinching the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared riled by an e-mail he had received Tuesday from
the presumed Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore,
challenging Bush to begin a series of debates and to forgo using
unrestricted soft money raised by the political parties to campaign
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sent an e-mail reply to Gore on Wednesday, saying Gore
should encourage the White House and the Department of Justice to
release all records related to alleged fund-raising abuses
committed by the vice president during his 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your e-mail. This Internet of yours is a
wonderful invention,'' Bush's note said, poking fun at Gore's
exaggerated claim to have been responsible for creating the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will be willing to debate Gore later this year when
more voters are paying attention. The governor also refused Gore's
challenge to reject soft money _ unregulated contributions to
political parties for use in general election campaigns _ because
he does not trust Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said let's ban soft money, and President Clinton is raising
it hand over fist,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is just an attempt to obscure or to try to divert
people's attention from what's going on in this administration,
including his trips to Buddhist temples and his calls out of the
White House. I don't trust him,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Gore limited soft money expenditures through the
Democratic Party, Bush said the vice president's allies in
organized labor would still be free to run television ads attacking
him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush favors banning soft money from corporations and labor
unions, but not from individuals. Bush said he does not believe
large sums of money in U.S. politics corrupts the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it necessarily corrupts. I think honest people
are not corruptible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the New Hampshire Republican primary to Arizona
Sen. John McCain in a surprise upset that led to six more weeks of
campaigning, Bush said he is satisfied that his campaign staff did
a good job in winning the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Bush's Washington backers had been privately calling on
him to replace strategist Karl Rove, manager Joe Allbaugh,
Communications Director Karen Hughes and advertising consultant
Mark McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of nattering. The team is intact. Everybody
performed well,'' Bush said. ``I've got great confidence in Joe,
Karl, Karen, Mark, as well as everybody else. We may be broadening
our reach. These decisions will be made in the next couple of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said any decision on a vice president will likely be put
off until just before the Republican National Convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a list yet for potential running mates. I'm going
to take my time before putting one together,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main criterion is whether the person can be the president,
whether or not we agree on issues and whether or not we can get
along,'' Bush said. ``Whether a person brings something from a
region or a state, or whether the person is of a gender or a race,
all of those will be factors in making the determination as to who
ought to be vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   On one current issue of the campaign, Bush said it is not his
role as Texas governor to use the relations he has built with
Mexican officials during this decade to get them to increase crude
oil production in the government-owned oil company to help bring
down the rising price of gasoline in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the president ought to be doing _ not only Mexico,
but other friendly nations in OPEC,'' Bush said. ``I don't think
governor's ought to be interfering with the job that the president
ought to be doing. It's the president's job to be conducting
foreign policy.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
