<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH16-COX     03-15 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three sure signs that Gov. George W. Bush has
clinched the GOP presidential nomination:
</P>
<P>
   Official letter from Republican National Committee Chairman Jim
Nicholson declaring Bush the ``presumptive nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents, taking over from Texas Department of
Public Safety, spending first day on the job at the Governor's
Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Snippy e-mail response from Bush to Democratic opponent Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your e-mail,'' Bush said in a Wednesday response
to a Tuesday e-mail from the vice president. ``This Internet of
yours is a wonderful invention.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after he became the GOP's presumptive nominee by
sweeping six southern primaries, Bush sat through a rapid-fire
series of interviews at the Governor's Mansion and geared up for
the fall battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of time to celebrate,'' Bush told the Austin
American-Statesman. ``We're on to the next phase of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The next phase includes a lot of behind-the-scenes machinations,
including raising more money, patching things up with vanquished
foe John McCain, getting Bush people in place at the Republican
National Committee and trying to persuade Americans that Gore is
the kind of guy who will ``say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   On hold for now is the effort to work things out with McCain,
who dropped out of the race after Bush won most of the Super
Tuesday contests on March 7. Bush wrapped up the nomination Tuesday
by winning six primaries, including Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is vacationing out of the country. Bush, who has had one
brief phone chat with McCain recently, views reunification as
inevitable, though terms have not been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can work together on a lot of reform issues,'' said
Bush. ``We're pleased that many of his supporters are coming
around. ... There is plenty of room for common ground.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush searches for common ground with a former foe, don't
look for the same kind of effort with his current foe. Gore and
Bush have wasted no time in going after each other.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president moved quickly Wednesday to point out exit
polls from Tuesday's Texas primary showing that 40 percent of the
GOP voters said there have not been ``significant reforms'' in
Texas schools under Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Education is the issue Bush believes can propel him to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush talked a lot about reform, but Texans are not seeing
results,'' said Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway. ``On education, as
on so many issues, George W. Bush is all hat and no cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was unaware of the exit poll results on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics say different. I don't know what the polls
said, but the test scores showed different. I haven't seen the
polls, but I will tell you we are making great progress, better
than any other state,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will mount a campaign aimed at ``elevating the
spirit of America,'' but he will not shy from a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to defend myself,'' said Bush, launching into what
has become a familiar refrain about Gore, ``and this is a man who I
believe will say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Gore battle became a certainty on Tuesday when each
candidate swept primaries in Texas, Tennessee, Florida, Louisiana,
Mississippi and Oklahoma. Both candidates lost their top foes last
week when McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley gave up.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to differing interpretations of when a delegate
officially becomes bound to Bush, there are varying numbers
floating around on exactly how many delegates are now in Bush's
corner. It takes 1,034 to clinch the nomination. The Associated
Press count has Bush with 1,093 so far.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson on
Wednesday declared Bush ``has secured the requisite number of
delegates to win the Republican nomination.''Nicholson said his
count was based on ``convention delegates elected or selected to
date and the voting history of delegations from caucus states.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, however, is not offering a specific number on how
many delegates are in the Bush corner. The RNC will not go beyond
saying the number is ``over 1,034.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, as of today, the Republican National Committee
officially recognizes Governor Bush as the party's presumptive
nominee,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said Wednesday he is not sure he will be taking any
international trips prior to the nominating convention, though he
would like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be the right forum. I'm not sure we're going to do
one,'' he said. ``If we did one I'd like to start in our own
neighborhood. I'd like to go down to South America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said a trip to Mexico is problematic because it would
get him wrapped up in the country's July 2 presidential election
``and I certainly don't want to get involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
