s e BC-WAGNER-MUSIC-ART-2TAK     03-15 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGNER-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTING A STELLAR `RING' OF DIVERSE PARTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Matthew Gurewitsch's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the filming of ``Leporello'' in Toronto.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recordings of Wagner's tetralogy, ``Der Ring des Nibelungen,''
are no longer the cultural milestones they were at midcentury. The
first studio recording _ Decca's _ took shape in stages from 1958
to 1966, with the as yet unknighted Georg Solti leading the Vienna
Philharmonic and a cast headed by Birgit Nilsson, Hans Hotter and
Wolfgang Windgassen.
</P>
<P>
   More than three decades on, remastered and reissued on at least
two occasions, it remains the best-selling ``Ring'' in the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   A rival take from Deutsche Grammophon, produced by Herbert von
Karajan between 1968 and 1970, features the Berlin Philharmonic and
artists including Thomas Stewart, Jon Vickers, Regine Crespin and
Helga Dernesch. It, too, makes the cut as a classic, though too
rarefied and idiosyncratic a one for universal acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the CD, several digital contenders followed.
Artistic merits aside, the market could not absorb them all, as the
more prescient in the industry realized from the start. Privately,
a highly placed recording executive from Deutsche Grammophon (then
embarked on James Levine's ``Ring'' with the Metropolitan Opera)
told me he had made a bet with a counterpart at EMI (simultaneously
occupied with Bernard Haitink's ``Ring'' with the Bavarian Radio
Symphony) as to whose set would sell (italics)less.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   But corporate image was at stake; neither label backed off. To
compound the folly, Deutsche Grammophon and EMI had to share a
single artist in the central role of Wotan. Commercially speaking,
James Morris had no competition.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling the expectations of the cynical, both sets marched
straight to the white-elephant graveyard. Decca later gave
Christoph von Dohnanyi approval for yet another new studio
``Ring,'' this one with the Cleveland Orchestra. But in the lean,
mean '90s, the old rules no longer applied. After two installments,
the project went south. At least Dohnanyi was spared the
embarrassment of forging ahead without a viable Siegfried, the hero
of the third and fourth operas.
</P>
<P>
   The time for such Ozymandian projects is past, maybe forever.
Yet thanks to microphones in the opera house and concert hall,
recordings of the ``Ring'' continue to proliferate. In this context
one thinks first of the long-established cottage industry in
historic cycles (Toscanini at La Scala, Clemens Krauss at
Bayreuth).
</P>
<P>
   But as I discovered last year, taking refuge from a midsummer
downpour, some new bottles actually contain new wine. The source
was the record store Die Schallplatte, the audiophile's Wagner
Central in the Bavarian town of Bayreuth, home to the festival the
master founded in 1876 in honor of his own genius.
</P>
<P>
   There, amid the reissues, lay stacks of two genuine collector's
items. A ``Rheingold'' (Arte Nova 74321 63650 2; two CDs) documents
Gustav Kuhn's performances at the Tirol Festival in Erl, Austria,
and in Naples in 1998. The orchestra is that of the Teatro di San
Carlo, Naples; the singers are members and guests of Kuhn's
international training institute, the Accademia di Montegral. Of
the same vintage and similarly unexpected provenance is a
``Siegfried'' from a production at the Kassel State Theater (Ars
Produktion FCD 368377/80; four CDs), conducted by Roberto
Paternostro, for several years an assistant to Karajan.
</P>
<P>
   And now the historic label Testament has released Hans
Knappertsbusch's legendary, previously unpublished Decca
``Gotterdammerung'' from the first post-Hitler Bayreuth Festival,
in 1951 (SBT 4175; four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   The usual way to approach the ``Ring'' is via the more or less
unified conception of a single team of interpreters. Thus, the
Metropolitan Opera preserves a well-worn ``Ring,'' always conducted
by James Levine. The production _ originally directed by Otto
Schenk in decor by Gunther Schneider-Siemssen and Rolf Langenfass
in a literal-minded, reactionary conception _ is unified to a
fault. But breaking the cycle up may not be such a terrible idea,
if only for the greater imaginative flexibility the experience
demands from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for three cycles this spring, beginning next
Saturday with the matinee broadcast of ``Das Rheingold,'' the Met
has already presented ``Die Walkure'' out of sequence. Much more
radically, the Stuttgart Opera has been mounting the four music
dramas as a single project with a different director and designer
in charge of each, though a single conductor, Lothar Zagrosek,
presides throughout.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of creative fragmentation, why not take advantage
of the chance alignment of unrelated recordings to traverse the
``Ring'' (three-fourths of it, anyway) in contrasting readings, all
live, all unfamiliar? (Anyone holding a bootleg ``Walkure,'' kindly
speak up.)
</P>
<P>
   The glimpse into the state of Wagnerism in the outback struck me
as particularly appealing, for reasons touched on by Ioan Holender,
director of the Vienna State Opera, in an introductory note to the
Kassel ``Siegfried.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget,'' writes Holender, who had attended the
show, ``that decisive innovations in the arts have always come from
the so-called `provinces.' The important singers and conductors who
have laid their artistic foundations in such places are legion. The
new generations of weighty Wagner voices, in particular, almost
never emerge from the metropolis but require the care and slow
development characteristic of smaller houses.''
</P>
<P>
   If weighty voices are in short supply in these recordings, there
are compensations, especially in ``Das Rheingold.'' Kuhn is hardly
the first to discover the glinting threads of melody that weave
through this score, but the flow of melody he sustains virtually
from start to finish is quite out of the ordinary. Even the
prelude, that astonishing fantasia in pure E flat suspended in
primordial timelessness, does not just hang there on this occasion
but sings.
</P>
<P>
   Instrumental gestures give off a pointillist brilliance, and the
scene painting is remarkable. Passages of violence and fury, often
played as if to crush the bones, unfold here as episodes in a
fast-paced thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the revolutionary nature of ``Das Rheingold'' lies in
the aggressive alliteration of its extensive dialogue. The
``talky,'' self-conscious quality of the language often leads
singers to adopt a style that foreshadows the harshness of German
Expressionism and even Sprechgesang. Unusually, Kuhn seems to
espouse a vocal ideal harking back to the cantabile of Italian
song.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese trio of Rhinemaidens (Hi-roko Kouda, Junko Saito
and Taeka Hino), dulcet almost beyond belief, and the Chinese giant
Fasolt (Xiaoliang Li) set the standard. As the dwarf Alberich, the
forger of the ring, Andrea Martin does not prejudice a listener
against him by snarling or growling, yet he never fails to put
across his character's malevolence at the proper moments.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
