<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TO FORM PAC TO CONTINUE `STRAIGHT TALK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was hardly in doubt, but it was confirmed Wednesday that
Senator John McCain will not recede from the national stage as
Texas Gov. George W. Bush campaigns for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign workers said the Arizona senator's ``crusade'' for
campaign finance reform, an issue that helped to define his
candidacy for the Republican nomination until he suspended his
campaign on March 9, will continue.
</P>
<P>
   It will continue, not in a third-party run, as some have
speculated, but via a far more conventional route: a political
action committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, the Senator, who returns from vacation at the end
of the week, will announce the formation of a PAC called Straight
Talk America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a vehicle which will allow Senator McCain to
continue his crusade for reform,'' said spokesperson Todd Harris.
``He will actively campaign in support of reform-minded Republican
candidates across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But the PAC will be mostly a vehicle for McCain himself, said
spokesperson Howard Opinsky, a way for the senator to ``continue
promoting his cause of reform, and to speak for the millions of
Americans who want something different out of their government.''
</P>
<P>
   The PAC will fund a speaking tour by the senator some time in
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC will also serve as a clearinghouse for reform ideas, and
a way of fulfilling McCain's frequent stump pledge to make
beneficiaries of pork-barrel expenditures ``famous'' by exposing
them to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until last week, our campaign was our vehicle to push
Senator McCain's reform agenda,'' Harris said. ``His support of
that agenda has not gone away. The vehicle he'll be using to
advance the cause of reform has simply changed names.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain will retain his delegates, Opinsky said, in the hopes of
bringing a campaign finance reform amendment to the floor at the
Republican National Convention, if nominee George W. Bush hasn't
already introduced the principle into the platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in making sure the reform agenda is a part of
Republican party, and we've heard a lot of rhetoric about it thus
far,'' Opinsky said. ``But with seven states won and a large number
of delegates to his name, Senator McCain wants to reserve the right
to utilize those delegates if necessary, which it may not be.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has not yet endorsed Bush, and is not expected to do so
in the immediate future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WAGNER-MUSIC-ART-2NDT     03-15 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGNER-MUSIC-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: proper moments.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rest of the ensemble ranges from highly acceptable to much
less so. Sad to say, the Wotan of Albert Dohmen _ to be heard also
in ``Ring'' cycles in Trieste and Catania, Italy, Geneva and Madrid
_ is at the wrong end of this spectrum: wobbly, lacking in
projection, fussy of phrase. Still, here is a prologue to a
``Ring'' it should be fascinating to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The best news from the Kassel ``Siegfried'' concerns individual
instrumentalists. Given the opportunity, they brighten the
proceedings with lovingly shaped comments and interjections. Where
the effect depends on more complex movement or interplay within the
orchestra, Paternostro coaxes forth the occasional magical
pianissimo, eerie chill or tidal swell. But too often the music
fails to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   Among the singers, the most familiar is the veteran Manfred
Jung, whose Siegfried did yeoman's service two decades ago at the
Bayreuth Festival in the centennial production directed by Patrice
Chereau and conducted by Pierre Boulez. Kassel now has him in the
demanding, unglamorous role of the dwarf Mime, who raises the
orphaned hero for nefarious purposes of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Jung's frayed instrument can still summon the volume the role
requires, and the grotesque accents in his final scene bespeak a
wicked theatricality formerly held in check.
</P>
<P>
   Time may tell otherwise, but the representatives of the younger
generation show less promise for the future than they give cause
for present alarm. Christian Franz has a pleasing way with
Siegfried's lyric and meditative passages, but even at only
slightly higher volume, the sound turns pinched.
</P>
<P>
   As the Valkyrie Brunnhilde, stirred from her magic sleep, Susan
Owen gets by as best she can on sweetness and clarity of tone but
fades at the climaxes. Claudio Otelli's Wanderer (Wotan's alias in
this opera) hits his stride only in the third act. Even here,
though, he staggers, helpless against a wide vibrato.
</P>
<P>
   Turning from these contemporary accounts to the Knappertsbusch
``Gotterdammerung,'' we are overwhelmed by the sheer richness of
the voices. At the very start, the Norns of Ruth Siewert, Ira
Malaniuk and Martha Modl lend their gloomy nocturne an ample-toned,
ravishing solemnity.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is Astrid Varnay's majestic Brunnhilde, sensuous yet
serene, flinging bright high notes like the spears of an Amazon. At
her side is Bernd Aldenhoff, a robust yet romantic Siegfried,
emotionally complex and fascinating. In the thrilling voice of
Hermann Uhde, even the weakling Gunther comes off as a personage of
quasi-mythic stature, elevating the tragedy remarkably.
</P>
<P>
   The Bayreuth bark? You will hear none of that here. Heinrich
Pflanzl's Alberich and Ludwig Weber's Hagen conspire in
sleep-haunted, subliminal tones. If the jet-black, savage timbre
and grizzly attack we associate with Hagen's music are not Weber's
to command, he conquers by other means: among them, the wild,
frightening parlando he applies sparingly but to tremendous
consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the sets of ``Rheingold'' and ``Siegfried,'' each spliced
together from a run of performances (and possibly a patch session
or two), this ``Gotterdammerung'' is presumably all one take.
Knappertsbusch, legend that he was, had human players to contend
with, and the account of Siegfried's Funeral March goes grimly
awry.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the coherence and intensity of the whole are
extraordinary, and the placement of tragic accents is masterly.
Varnay, gripping throughout, delivers Brunnhilde's Immolation Scene
as if to stake her claim on immortality, encompassing the passions
and the wisdom of a lifetime. Perhaps spurred on by this
achievement, Knappertsbusch and the orchestra, a pickup crew
gathered from orchestras all over Germany, surge into the
instrumental peroration with a force nothing short of apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   With material of such caliber at hand, should we grieve if the
``Ring'' never gets recorded in the studio again? No _ and yes.
Records cannot replace live performance, as we are often told. But
neither can live performances replace studio recordings, in which
the accidents of live performance can be held at bay.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, a studio recording may convert a performance into an
artifact, in which, at least, all the material is present and
accounted for. No doubt this pedantic Platonic notion is more
congenial to some listeners than to others, but it would be hard to
deny that ``reference performances,'' like reference books, have
their uses.
</P>
<P>
   Live recordings can rarely fill that function. But for some who
were there, or others who for reasons of their own wish they had
been, examples like the new ``Ring'' fragments from the Tirol
Festival and Kassel must make cherished keepsakes: items of
personal history.
</P>
<P>
   In our brave new world of potentially boundless electronic
connectedness, institutions should soon be able, at affordable
prices, to self-produce such memorabilia to their constituencies'
hearts' content.
</P>
<P>
   Some such documents, like the Knappertsbusch ``Gotterdammerung''
of 1951, are historic in a broader sense. But only some dream
``Ring'' of the future could ever challenge Solti's. At the right
time, with the right cast, such a challenge will always be worth
mounting. Artistically speaking, that is. What happens in the
marketplace is another question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
