<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOST-DOG-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GHOST DOG' MISSES THE GRAVY TRAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2{ stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his latest film, ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,''
formalist wiseacre Jim Jarmusch (``Stranger Than Paradise,'' ``Dead
Man'') attempts to blend gangster, hip-hop, cartoon and Japanese
action-movie elements into one poker-faced satiric hybrid. It's a
fundamentally fun idea that doesn't mesh very well with the
filmmaker's detached, cooler-than-thou aesthetic attitude. As a
result, the film's pleasures are more theoretical than actual.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch's signature cross-wiring of cultural references gets a
real workout in this story of a decrepit Mafia family's run-in with
an African-American hit man who fancies himself a latter-day
Samurai warrior. Basically, the film is about the clash of two
different, violent ethics, but it's also about all things running
their course. Set in a generic, post-industrial urban blightscape,
the movie unfolds at the speed _ and, even at its funniest, with
the tone _ of a funeral procession.
</P>
<P>
   Which is appropriate, since the upshot of all this has less to
do with contrasting themes and imagery than with making a lot of
dead bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Portly, putty-faced Forest Whitaker is the unlikely title
assassin. An ascetic, silent type who lives in a shack atop a
tenement next to his pigeon coop, Ghost Dog's life, like any good
Samurai's, is devoted to serving his master.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, said lord is an aging mob underling named Louie
(John Tormey), who saved Dog from an awful beating many years
earlier. Though he doesn't quite know what to make of this strange
guy who so willingly and effectively carries out requested hits,
Louie is happy to use him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   However, when a small glitch mars an otherwise perfect contract
killing, Louie's bosses order the Dog killed. This, of course,
proves easier said than done; after huffing and puffing their way
up flights of stairs, the family's gray-haired mooks barely have
enough energy left to pull triggers on the various pigeon-keepers
they mistake for their elusive prey.
</P>
<P>
   Dog, meanwhile, combines his ancient fighting skills and
high-tech arsenal in a war of attrition against the new set of
enemies, while all the time trying to stay loyal to Louie. As any
soldier will tell you, there's a lot of downtime between battles,
which Dog spends bonding with a little girl in the park and having
conversations he doesn't understand with a French-speaking ice
cream vendor.
</P>
<P>
   The mobsters, meanwhile, indulge the usual movie made-guy
eccentricities: Sonny (Cliff Gorman) digs that funky rap music the
most; godfather Ray (Henry Silva) makes fun of people's names and
tries to get his face to work; the jokers can't make the rent on
their headquarters; and they all watch cartoons too much.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is funny, some of it just fills space, all of it
takes too long. To remind us that we're looking at a movie instead
of a still life, Jarmusch keeps throwing triple exposures,
superimpositions, editing stutters and other cinematic
attention-getters into the mix. In the plus column, he also comes
up with a good half-dozen inventive visuals (the great Robby Muller
shot the film). And the syncopated soundtrack by Wu-Tang Clan
leader THE RZA is the movie's most reliably lively element.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ghost Dog'' isn't about life, however obsessed its
principles may be with the codes they live by. Practically
everybody we meet here is dead on first contact; it just takes a
long time for the realization to become final. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai'' (R; violence,
language). &QL; 
The stars: Forest Whitaker, John Tormey, Cliff Gorman, Henry Silva,
Isaach de Bankole. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Jim Jarmusch. Produced
by Jarmusch and Richard Guay. Released by Artisan Entertainment. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 56 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: !star!!star!1/2!wrapoff! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
