<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CRUDUP-FILMS-ART-2TAK     03-15 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUDUP-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING ONE STEP AHEAD OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (Eds: Sylviane Gold, who reviews dance for Newsday, has been a
theater critic for The Wall Street Journal and writes frequently
about the arts.)  
(af)  
By SYLVIANE GOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So far, most of the articles about Billy Crudup _ and
there have been a bunch since his 1995 Broadway debut as the
heart-piercing tutor in ``Arcadia'' _ have noted the pronunciation
of his name. CREW-dup. CRU-dup. KROO-dup.
</P>
<P>
   And they have predicted that any time now, any time at all, the
name would become as familiar as DiCaprio or Damon or Affleck: that
the bitter college ladykiller he played in ``Inventing the
Abbotts'' (1997) or the star-crossed runner he played in ``Without
Limits'' (1998) or the pining cowboy he played in ``The Hi-Lo
Country'' (1998) would make him a star.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here they come again. This time, the movie is ``Waking the
Dead,'' based on Scott Spencer's novel about an up-and-coming
politician haunted by intertwined memories of lost love and
abandoned ideals. The 31-year-old actor is in just about every
scene in the film, which flips back and forth between Fielding
Pierce's passionate affair in the '70s with Sarah (Jennifer
Connolly), a committed political activist, and his pragmatic '80s
campaign for a freshly vacated congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship ends when Sarah is killed in a car bombing, but
Fielding's career continues on the smooth track he had laid out for
it. As his long-held dream is about to come true, visions of the
martyred Sarah begin to obsess him and the film's director, Keith
Gordon, lets Crudup's chiseled but increasingly distraught face
tell the story, in close-up after close-up.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup has transformed that face for each of his roles: coolly
handsome in ``Inventing the Abbotts,'' cocksure and determined in
``Without Limits,'' naive and stubborn in the 1996 Broadway
production of ``Bus Stop,'' broodingly romantic in ``The Hi-Lo
Country.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Waking the Dead,'' which opens Friday, the large brown eyes
are keen and intelligent, the cheekbones commanding. So it's no
surprise that Crudup looks like someone else again when he shows up
on a blustery day for an interview in Manhattan _ finer-featured
than he appears on stage and screen but somehow less defined, less
finished. The long hair is a leftover from the movie he has
recently completed, about a '70s rock star; the sweatshirt looks
like a leftover from his days as a graduate acting student at
nearby New York University; and the earnestness with which he talks
about why he did ``Waking the Dead'' seems a throwback, too, to the
days before irony became the lingua franca of the young and the
talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the idea of life's complications being unsolvable, and
that we persist anyway,'' he says. ``I identified with Fielding a
lot, with his confusion, and with his need for some point of view
that would lead him through life. He gets the opportunity to have
what he's always wanted, and all of a sudden he doesn't know why he
wants it anymore. It's a beautiful sentiment to examine: how we are
in part who we are, and in part what we're told we are, and in part
what we do well, whether we want to do it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting is something Crudup has always done well, but that has
not kept him from reflecting on why it's worth doing. ``You
gravitate toward the things that people give you the most positive
feedback for,'' Crudup says. ``And I was, for whatever reason, good
at being a sort of class clown and mimicking different
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   His fate may have been sealed at Hillcrest High School in
Dallas, when a teacher assigned the class to recite an excerpt from
Shakespeare. Crudup chose Hamlet's ``To be or not to be''
soliloquy, and found he had been able to memorize far more than
anyone else. (This is a skill he has not lost. Ask anyone who saw
his marathon performance as Oedipus in Dare Clubb's four-hour Off
Broadway reworking of the classic tale.) ``I remember the look of
awe on some of my classmates' faces as I went on and on and on and
on. That felt really good, to be special at something.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he pursued acting in college and then in graduate school,
he fretted over whether he was performing for the right reasons. At
the University of North Carolina, studying Western civilization was
hard, studying a performance piece was easy. ``Am I just into it
because it's the easiest route for me?'' he asked himself. ``Am I
doing this to keep regaining the attention that I needed at some
point in my life?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he says, he concluded that acting ``was a way for me to
be expressive about life and also to make a living, and to feel
like I'm adding something to the community experience of life.''
</P>
<P>
   That last part was important to him. A friend since
fourth-grade, Rafe Bemporad, recalls Crudup as ``always incredibly
outgoing and clever and fun to be with.'' But Bemporad, whose
father is a rabbi, also recalls his friend at the Bemporad dinner
table, taking part in discussions of ``political issues or current
events or just ideas and expectations for our own lives, and how to
be human beings in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bemporad continued: ``It was an upbringing where we were talking
about community life as much as about the latest movie. I remember
one discussion about why you go to school: Was it to make a living
or to make a life? Billy chose his profession as a way of making a
life for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Van Lieu, who has taught acting at NYU since 1975, says that
the school encourages that kind of outlook. ``We train actors with
the idea that they belong to a larger community, that the artistic
choices they make make a statement,'' he says. Crudup's social
concerns and natural empathy, he says, helped him fit easily into
the NYU culture. ``He was truly, deeply concerned about being the
most responsible actor he could be,'' Van Lieu says.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Crudup recalls his three years at NYU as heaven:
``You took classes from 10 to 5, you rehearsed in the evenings from
7 to 10, you did performances on the weekend, all the time,'' he
says. ``I didn't want to leave.'' Indeed, his conversation leads
you to believe that if it were possible, he would think about
acting, talk about acting, work on his acting, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   He would talk about why plays, which he has been regularly
squeezing into his film schedule, are more fun than movies: ``The
feeling you get from theater work is much more palpable _ you have
that to go home with each night. There's the cathartic effect of
starting and completing something each night. When you do film, at
the end of the day there's always a sort of emptiness, because your
performance hasn't ended. It's lingering, and everything you did
today you won't do again, so you can't learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He would talk about the pitfalls of being in demand as an actor:
``When you get to a certain point, you get offered things that
you're not right for. And you have to be careful. You may want to
do it because it's a great exercise for you. But I don't think
taking jobs as exercises is such a great thing. Take a class. Don't
subject everybody to your exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   He would talk about the difference between spontaneity and
technique: ``The artistry of spontaneity is sort of lost on me _
people who just come in and do it once and it's brilliant, but ask
them to do it again and you don't know if they will. Creating a
truly rich layered moment that appears as though it happened just
once, and would never happen again _ that's what I'm most
interested in. Especially when you do it again. I'm much better at
learning than I am at spontaneously erupting with brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   And even when you asked about his personal life, he would talk
about acting: ``If you're primarily interested in convincing
somebody for a short period of time that you're somebody else, the
more they know about you, the harder it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reticence, there are a few facts on the record:
childhood moves from Long Island to Texas to Florida, and the
wrench of watching his parents' marriage fall apart not once but
twice. An older brother, a younger brother and a long-term
relationship with Mary-Louise Parker, whom he met when they were
both cast in ``Bus Stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Josephine R. Abady, who directed the play, says she was taken by
the combination of danger and sweetness in Crudup's acting. ``Part
of his skill is inhabiting the character to the point where you
don't realize it's a performance,'' she says. ``It's not
pyrotechnics: You notice the performance, you forget about the
actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also remarks on Crudup's ability to submerge himself in
the roles he plays. ``In everything he does, he moves differently,
he talks differently, he holds his body differently,'' he says.
``And it's so casual, it looks as if they just found this guy and
he's really right for this part.''
</P>
<P>
   To Crudup, that's what the job entails. ``I don't want my own
personality to become the role,'' he says. And he relates an
anecdote about his preparation for the role of Steve Prefontaine,
the University of Oregon track star who died in a 1975 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working with the dialect coach,'' Crudup recalls, ``and
after a little while, he said, `You're not planning on doing an
impersonation of him, are you?' And I thought, `Well, that's kind
of exactly what I'm planning: I'm planning on being him _ speaking
like him and moving like him and thinking like him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So accurately did Crudup approximate Prefontaine's physical
characteristics that the film's director, Robert Towne, intercut
documentary footage of Prefontaine running at the 1972 Munich
Olympics with footage of Crudup pretending to do the same. And the
smile you get when you tell Crudup that the trick was undetectable
tells you everything you need to know about what makes him happy.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings him back to the fame thing. He describes with wry
detachment his reaction to an interviewer who ``was lamenting for
me the fact that nobody had seen a lot of my movies.'' But, Crudup
said, ``I was very proud and pleased with these movies. And the
idea that I could see them as successful was sort of ludicrous to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he does recognize that part of his job is
connecting with a public. And he relishes that as much as he enjoys
the analysis of a script and the building of a character. ``It's
not fun to be gawked at, or to be appreciated for being famous,''
he says. ``But it is a thrill to be appreciated for your work.'' He
motions outside the window of the restaurant. ``Not a lot of people
go up to the Con Ed guy out there, no matter how good a job he does
giving you electricity, to say, `Listen, what you're doing is
really helping me with my life, and I want to tell you that I
appreciate it.' As an actor, you get told that. Frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   As he leaves, the Con Ed worker Crudup had taken notice of takes
no notice of him. Will ``Waking the Dead'' change that, finally?
Will his next movie, ``Jesus' Son,'' which opens this summer? Or
will he remain, in Gordon's phrase, ``a character actor in a
leading man's body''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I want him to become a big star more than he does,''
Gordon says. ``There's a Zen quality about him. You get the sense
that he's not walking through life wanting things he can't get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
