<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-AUDREY-HEPBURN-2TA     03-15 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AUDREY-HEPBURN-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH ONE'S AUDREY, AND WHY IT MATTERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TV-HEWITT-HEPBURN) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ For an actress who epitomized American cool, Audrey
Hepburn is inspiring a lot of nervous sweat. In life, her fragile
beauty and elegantly pared-down fashion sense made her one of the
most distinctive, most admired stars on the Hollywood screen. And
that is precisely the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very protective of Audrey Hepburn,'' said Susan
Lyne, executive vice president for movies and mini-series at ABC,
which will broadcast ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' this month.
``They worry that someone will come along and try to besmirch her
reputation. It's not like doing the Marilyn Monroe story where
people are salaciously interested in every misstep she took.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama, starring Jennifer Love Hewitt, will be shown on
Monday, March 27, one day after the Academy Awards. The timing is
no coincidence. Executives hope that the annual love affair with
Hollywood glamour will create an audience keen to relive the
Hepburn story, and starry-eyed enough to accept Hewitt, a former
television teen queen, as a reasonable fascimile of the poised and
sophisticated Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   For the 21-year-old Hewitt _ beloved of teen-agers in the Fox
drama ``Party of Five'' and now the star of a spinoff, ``Time of
Your Life'' _ the decision to star in the film is a risky one, and
the network is plainly concerned that critics will be merciless.
</P>
<P>
   The last time anyone tried to step into Audrey Hepburn's famous
Ferragamo flats, the result was the disastrous 1995 remake of
``Sabrina,'' from which Julia Ormond's career has still not
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   From another perspective, though, the decision by ABC to proceed
with the movie and accept potentially stinging criticism is a
measure of the desperation at the networks for something _
(italics)anything(end italics) _ to halt the hemorrhaging of
audiences to cable and the Internet. They are increasingly willing
to risk crass and shallow programming, the recent vow by the Fox
chairman to swear off ``exploitative material'' notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for instance, CBS presented ``Perfect Murder,
Perfect Town,'' a drama based on the JonBenet Ramsey murder case,
and late last year NBC offered up an embarrassing ``Mary and
Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans need not worry that ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' will
detract from their memories of the star. The movie, which
chronicles the actress' childhood and career up to the age of 32,
is in fact gentle. And it has a surprisingly strong pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was written by the Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright
Marsha Norman. An executive producer, Robert Greenwald, is one of
the most respected producers in television, with a track record
that includes Emmy Award-winning dramas like ``The Burning Bed''
and ``A Woman of Independent Means.'' The director, Steve Robman,
came to television from Yale Drama School and New York and regional
theater.
</P>
<P>
   But the force behind the project was the determined Hewitt _
everyone calls her ``Love'' _ who has been obsessed with Hepburn
ever since she saw a video of ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' when she
was 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother showed me `Breakfast at Tiffany's' and told me to
take some pointers from Audrey Hepburn,'' Hewitt said, ``and I've
never been the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt spoke candidly. ``I'm absolutely scared to death about
playing her,'' she said. ``Two weeks before filming, I was in
tears. I told my mom I didn't know if I could do it. I knew the
press would not say kind things about me. I thought I wasn't pretty
enough. I thought I wasn't talented enough. My mom looked at me and
said, `If that's your decision, OK But think of the three things
Audrey Hepburn was most afraid of: that she wasn't pretty enough,
wasn't talented enough and what people would say about her.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I did it. I'm proud of it, and I'm proud of the fact that
it was something I was terrified of doing but did anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The project was the result of a serendipitous meeting between
Hewitt and Kimberly Rubin, who had worked with Greenwald. ``At the
end of the meeting we were kind of chatting,'' Hewitt recalled,
``and I said that my dream project was to play Audrey Hepburn one
day. She just stared at me. She said that for the last few years
her dream project was Audrey Hepburn.'' ABC quickly approved the
project because of Hewitt's commitment to it. ( Rubin is an
executive producer of the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald said that Hewitt's adoration for Hepburn informed the
film. The actress worked with a dialogue coach for months to
perfect the Hepburn accent, and she watched Hepburn films over and
over. ``There's an innocence that she brings to it,'' Greenwald
said. ``There's no cynicism, no wink of the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is, if not a valentine, then certainly an homage to an
actress who was, in the words of the critic David Thomson, a
``fairy queen'' in Hollywood in the 1950s and 1960s. The story
traces Hepburn's life from her difficult childhood in Holland
during the German occupation of World War II through her days as a
dancer on the London stage to her success on Broadway in ``Gigi''
and stardom in ``Roman Holiday,'' ``Sabrina'' and in her signature
role as Holly Golightly in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a life that had a lot of inherent conflict,''
Norman said. ``How do you make a story out of that? I think we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The story ends in 1961. ``Once she got to `Breakfast at
Tiffany's,' her transformation from ugly duckling, which she felt
she was, to this kind of princess was complete,'' Norman explained.
``I didn't feel we needed to see the rest of it. The question of
how she became Audrey Hepburn was the thing to see, not how do you
go on being Audrey Hepburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Hepburn was no saint, but her life was not bedeviled
by the demons that afflicted, say, Monroe or Ava Gardner. The film
dwells on some painful chapters but skirts others.
</P>
<P>
   Her father (played by Keir Dullea), who was estranged from her
mother (Frances Fisher), was a Nazi lobbyist in England. As an
adult, Hepburn had two unhappy marriages, the first to the actor
Mel Ferrer, the second to Dr. Andrea Dotti, an Italian psychiatrist
and socialite. (She had a son from each marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   She had affairs with several actors, including a difficult one
with William Holden, who was married and an alcoholic. There are
intimations that she may have had an eating disorder. In short, her
life was, for a movie star, perfectly normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried hard to show the adversity this woman lived through,
especially during the war when she nearly died of malnutrition,''
Robman said. ``One has to assume her father was a great source of
turmoil. But there was no terrible dark secret or hidden tragic
mystery here that will rip the image of Audrey Hepburn to shreds.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress died of cancer in 1963 at the age of 64, having
spent the last years of her life working for the United Nations
Children's Fund, often visiting refugee camps in Africa and Asia.
``The fact that she ended up giving back to children, trying to
rescue children the way she was rescued as a child, seemed very
natural to her,'' Norman said. ``It was totally in character.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the aura of her good works, Hepburn is defined for many
fans by her sense of style. Renee April, who designed the costumes
for the movie, said she was not allowed to directly copy the
outfits that Hubert de Givenchy created for Hepburn and for films
like ``Sabrina'' and ``Breakfast at Tiffany's,'' but she tried to
imitate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audrey knew her flaws and her good features,'' April said.
``Her body did not change. She had the same measurements at 60 that
she had at 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt shares some physical similarities with Hepburn. ``She has
that same swan neck,'' April said, ``and she carries herself with a
lot of grace.'' In other respects, the resemblance is more of a
stretch. ``She's shorter, she's bustier,'' April said, laughing.
``She has a tiny waist, but she comes more in curves.''
</P>
<P>
   April, too, was intimidated by Hepburn. ``Who wouldn't be
intimidated?'' she said. ``We were dealing with Audrey Hepburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the pitfalls of taking on the film are never far from
the filmmakers' minds. ``To Jennifer Love Hewitt's credit,'' Robman
said, ``when we talked about the fact that it was a dangerous road
to tread, she said that no matter what kind of performance she
gives, there'll be criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Audrey Hepburn was such an important part of her growing up
that she wanted to pay homage to her as best she could,'' he said.
``I thought, if this young woman is as brave as that, I have to be
at least as brave.''
</P>
<P>
   The intrepid Hewitt said: ``I tried not to think of career.
You've got to do some things from the heart. You've got to do
things that challenge you to be better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
