<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-MONEY-COX     03-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush needs more money for White House bid
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He vanquished his chief Republican rival after
transforming into a ``Reformer with Results.'' Now, Gov. George W.
Bush could use some cash.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly down to $6 million from a dizzying $70 million in
contributions, Bush kicks off a series of fund-raisers tonight in
the Republican stronghold of DuPage County, Ill. He is scheduled to
attend a $1,000-a-person reception at the Cantigny War Museum, in
Wheaton.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is also planning at least a dozen upcoming events
in, among other places, Florida, Arkansas, New Jersey, New York
City and Baltimore. Michael Dell, chief executive officer of Dell
Computers, will host a New York event on April 6, part of the Bush
team's plan to go after high-tech money. Four days later, former
President Bush is set to attend a fund-raising event in Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Scott McClellan wouldn't say how much cash
Bush has on hand. Through Jan. 31st, McClellan said the campaign
spent $13.1 million on television and radio advertising, including
in South Carolina where Bush's protracted primary fight with
Arizona Sen. John McCain reached its crescendo in an intense and
bitter ad blitz. The next legally required finance disclosure
report, due Monday, will reflect media spending in major states
such as New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll release the numbers Monday when the report is filed,''
McClellan said. ``The goal is to raise $5 million to $10 million by
the end of April ... We're going to have plenty of resources to
continue spreading the governor's compassionate conservative agenda
... Our supporters are energized and enthusiastic and we are
building upon our broad-based support.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Austin American-Statesman Bush declined
to confirm reports that campaign finance chairman Donald Evans will
soon move to the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be. Could be,'' Bush said. ``There are ways to work
together and I want to make sure it's in a way that doesn't disrupt
the RNC and, at the same time, allows us to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush wrapped up the Republican nomination fight Tuesday with a
string of primary victories, including Texas and Florida. Now, Bush
and Vice President Al Gore are rattling tin cups even as they
tussle over who should inherit McCain's reformer mantle. Gore held
campaign fund-raising events Tuesday in Tennessee and Wednesday in
Philadelphia. And the two camps continued trading shots over
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he accepted the challenge to ban soft money he could take a
little break,'' Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway said of Bush's
fundraising schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bush campaign released an e-mail that Bush wrote
to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I challenge you to clear the air on some serious
charges,'' Bush wrote, referring to a 1996 Democratic fund-raising
scandal. ``I hope you will encourage the White House and the
Department of Justice to release all records and photographs
relating to fundraising abuses by you and your administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The note was written in response to an e-mail Gore sent to Bush.
In his note, Gore pledged to ask the Democratic National Committee
to run issue ads bankrolled with soft money only if the Republican
Party chooses to.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has called for banning lobbyist contributions to members of
Congress while Congress is in session, raising the limit on
individual contributions and preventing unions from using members'
dues for political contributions without members' permission.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gore, Bush is not calling for a ban on soft money _ the
funds that flow from corporations and labor unions to political
parties and are not subject to federal contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign on Wednesday also released a list of overnight
guests at the Texas Governor's Mansion in response to a report by
the nonpartisan Center for Public Integrity. The analysis of
overnight guests from January1995 to February 2000 shows that 60
have given and raised more than $2.2 million for Bush. At least 15
are members of Bush's fundraising team of ``Pioneers'' _ the
campaign's name for people who have raised $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
