<HEADER>
A7986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HOSPITAL-OVERDOSES-BO     03-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-OVERDOSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVE PROBE OF FATAL CANCER OVERDOSE CASE ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts board that regulates nurses has
dropped controversial charges against two Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute nurses involved in a notorious 1994 chemotherapy overdose
episode in late 1994, while reprimanding one other nurse for her
role in the affair.
</P>
<P>
   The action, announced Wednesday, the day public hearings on the
charges were to begin, brings to 16 the number of Dana-Farber
nurses who have accepted state reprimands or probation for their
role in the chemotherapy mistake. The board's decision closes the
books on disciplinary proceedings that have sparked considerable
criticism among nurses nationally.
</P>
<P>
   However, a nursing board official said there are still pending
complaints on seven additional Dana-Farber nurses who did not
directly administer or monitor the erroneous chemotherapy but
allegedly played some unspecified role in the affair. The board
will investigate those cases and decide whether to proceed or drop
them in the next weeks, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing board's actions grew out of a medical error in a
Dana-Farber chemotherapy experiment that killed one breast cancer
patient, 39-year-old Boston Globe health columnist Betsy A. Lehman,
and severely injured another, a 53-year-old North Andover
schoolteacher, Maureen Bateman.
</P>
<P>
   The Dana-Farber overdoses are widely cited as a seminal event in
the nation's newfound recognition of preventable medical errors,
which a federal panel last December said kill from 44,000 to 98,000
Americans annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a sea change in ideas about medical error since
Betsy's death, and it was her death and subsequent events that
triggered it,'' said Robert Distel, a Dana-Farber scientist who was
Betsy Lehman's husband. ``I want Betsy to be remembered, because it
was Betsy's bravery and who she was that was a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana-Farber and many institutions have made changes designed to
catch medication errors. But there is still considerable debate
about the degree that individual professionals should be held
accountable when preventable errors occur.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David G. Nathan, Dana-Farber's president, and Susan Grant,
the institution's chief of nursing, said in a statement that the
board's charges were ``inappropriate and unwarranted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been easy for these nurses to have walked away
from their profession, and their patients, in frustration under the
pressure of the board's unnecessary action,'' they said. ``But they
didn't, and we are proud that more than five years later most are
still part of our service.''
</P>
<P>
   The two exonerated nurses, Ilene Galinsky and Susan
Coggeshall-Aikey, said in a statement that the accusations against
them were unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be accused as we were by the board hurts deeply and sends
an incorrect message to nurses everywhere,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Maura A. Murray agreed to a formal reprimand and extra
training in chemotherapy administration, as 13 other Dana-Farber
nurses have also done. Two Dana-Farber nurses accepted a year's
probation in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between Galinsky and Coggeshall-Aikey and the
other 16 nurses, a nursing board official said, is that the two
exonerated nurses monitored the chemotherapy infusion rather than
administered it, and had each been involved with only one of the
patients on the initial day of the overdose, which occurred over a
four-day period for each patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expert witnesses lined up for the hearing said this
initial dose was very large, but it was a dose known to have been
administered as one-time dose in other protocols,'' said Theresa M.
Bonanno, the nursing board's executive director. ``So their index
of suspicion that this was a problematic dose was lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The nursing board charged that the Dana-Farber nurses should
have checked to be sure the high chemotherapy dose, incorrectly
written by a trainee physician, was correct. But the nurses
maintained that they had followed the board's own standard, which
their attorney Wednesday said required them to follow a ``valid
doctor's prescription.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``valid prescription,'' said attorney Frank Reardon, is ``an
appropriate order in compliance with what other patients in similar
situations might receive.'' Reardon said the nurses had lined up
two expert witnesses to testify in the hearing that had been
scheduled for Thursday. Dana-Farber medical personnel were also set
to defend the nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Sara T. Fry, a professor of nursing ethics at Boston College,
said the Dana-Farber case has underscored a problem many nurses
face these days _ how to render safe care when they feel that they
lack support services from the institutions in which they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all nurses should be held accountable for what they
give to the patient _ what they do and do not do,'' Fry said.
``That's part of their legal and moral responsibility. But the
institution has responsibility to make sure support systems are in
place. In this case, it looked like the nurses were the last ones
in the chain and everything else failed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
