<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-HEWITT-HEPBURN-ART     03-15 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HEWITT-HEPBURN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPYING COPIES: THE SAD SLIDE FROM STARDOM TO CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (Eds: Jeff MacGregor worked in the television industry for 20
years, as writer, producer and network correspondent.)  
(af) 
 By JEFF MacGREGOR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In those ancient days long before the earth had cooled, when the
mighty pterodactyl still ruled the darkling skies, I took my first
job in television news. This was 1975, the early Polyester Period
of the Cenozoic Era, and the only thing wider than the bright
horizon on which I projected my youthful ambitions was the tie I
wore to work.
</P>
<P>
   It was an age of great social and technological upheaval:
American women abandoned the spiritual impoverishment of the home
for the spiritual impoverishment of the workplace, and, in
response, men began using hair dryers and wearing platform saddle
shoes. Microwave ovens delivered bad popcorn in only half the time.
Back in Minnesota, we recorded and reported these events with all
due dispatch and the appropriate gravity.
</P>
<P>
   That year, technology also brought the widespread use of
videotape to television news gathering. Film was laborious and
expensive, so we welcomed the convenience and speed of videotape.
We were warned by factory representatives, however, of a serious
concern with the new medium. ``Generational deterioration,'' they
would solemnly intone, speaking directly into the tabletop, bent
double by the weight of neckwear the size of lobster bibs, ``is a
real problem.'' Unable to nod, we could only murmur our agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Generational deterioration describes what happens when you make
copies of copies of copies, an effect common in videotape (and the
genealogy of Europe's royal families). By the fourth or fifth
generation the loss of quality is obvious, and one is left with
only a dim facsimile, a blurred and colorless rendering of the
original.
</P>
<P>
   A similar phenomenon can be observed in its proper laboratory
setting on March 27 when the ubiquitous ingenue Jennifer Love
Hewitt essays the title role in the television biopic ``The Audrey
Hepburn Story.'' While Hewitt's charms are considerable, and her
various talents have been corroborated by an astonishing number of
teen-zine cover stories, the portrayal by a popular young actress
of a show business original like a Hepburn, any Hepburn, can only
result in lopsided comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that the outcome of viewing something like this
will be to increase our longing for the genuine article at the
expense of our regard for the woman playing her.
</P>
<P>
   That fans of ``Roman Holiday'' and ``Breakfast at Tiffany's''
greeted the news of this project with barnyard snorts and
eye-rolling of a magnitude unseen since the heyday of Snub Pollard
is not a direct attack on Hewitt. Miscast or not, she will do her
best, I am sure, and the movie, like most movies, will be promptly
forgotten in any case. What seems to gall people is the potential
damage that might be done to their memories, however imprecise, of
Audrey Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something else at work here, too. Fueling that
upset is perhaps the broader exasperation we feel at the explosive
growth of ``celebrity'' and the proportional shrinkage of old
school ``stardom'' that accompanies it; at the casual and
unapologetic devaluation of originality; and at the melancholy
xerography of most current entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Hepburn vs. Jennifer Love Hewitt competing for America's
affections is a fixed fight, certainly, but may be emblematic of a
much bigger problem. In trying so hard to earn a buck on the cusp
of the Intertainment Age, Hollywood seems to specialize now in
nothing so much as its own diminishment.
</P>
<P>
   Before it gave way to new technologies and economies in the
1950s, the old studio system thrived on the gradual assembly of
film legends. It could take years to build a John Wayne or a James
Stewart or an Audrey Hepburn. The Hollywood bosses of that feudal
era understood that what they manufactured was not movies but movie
stars.
</P>
<P>
   The time and money it took to make one was well spent, because
that kind of marquee appeal was a guarantee of moviegoing fannies
in the seats. It was a long-term investment, one in which both
parties benefited. The studios got their stars, at a price, and the
stars, while constrained by their ironclad contracts, usually
learned their craft with a schoolhouse rigor unimaginable today.
</P>
<P>
   If one looks at the kind of roles assumed by Errol Flynn or Joan
Crawford or Spencer Tracy, the breadth and variety of the material
they tried (or were forced to try) is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, Hollywood is engaged in the bulk manufacture of
celebrities _ interchangeable entertainment widgets. The face on
that magazine cover seems vaguely familiar and may belong to that
guy we saw in that movie that time but, then again, may belong to
that other guy in that other movie. That the company that owns the
movie also owns the magazine  &UR; and  &LR; the magazine show covering them
both makes for a closed economy wherein the importance of the
individual is superseded by the impersonal necessities of a
business done in volume.
</P>
<P>
   Hence a generation of actors like Ben Affleck or Jennifer Lopez
who are on magazine covers because they are in the movies and seem
to be in the movies only because they are on so many magazine
covers. Ben Affleck is, I am sure, a nice young man, and somebody
somewhere is determined to make him a celebrity if it kills him.
Who and why I cannot say. Happily, the likelihood of seeing him in
something like ``The Jimmy Stewart Story'' remains remote, at least
for the moment. The part may go to Vince Vaughn. Or that other guy.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of strangely anonymous celebrity, with its high-speed
turnover and confusing sub-identities, is not limited to film. In
the space of about a month last year, we witnessed the emergence of
Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, Jessica Simpson and Mandy
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The music business has obviously perfected the genetic
engineering of blonde, sexpot teen-pop singers, and these are the
results. In the old days Madonna had to invent herself piecemeal by
invoking the ghost of Marilyn Monroe. These four sprang full grown
from the MTV laboratories and are virtually identical, right down
to the bare midriff and semisuggestive lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   I would challenge the scientists who created them to
differentiate them (or their songs) in a police lineup. Can't be
done.
</P>
<P>
   What is most awe-inspiring about the new age of show business
devolution, though, is its copy-to-copy-to-copy rapidity. More
channels than ever, with more time to fill with more ``content,''
means more derivative performers in more derivative formats than at
any time in history. Digital technology aside, a copy is a copy is
a copy, especially if there are more of them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Witness the current state of television, the great devolver. Who
among us can honestly keep the casts of ``Felicity,'' ``Popular''
and ``Dawson's Creek'' straight? And why, after all, should we
bother? Maybe because we've been booked to appear on ``Greed''!
</P>
<P>
   The big story of the last six months has been the triumphant
return of the quiz show. ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
breathed life into a form long thought dead by the experts. Based
on a British show of the same format, it has made an unlikely
prime-time colossus of Regis Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a manner befitting a stylish Cosa Nostra funeral
director, Philbin sits on the bridge of the starship Free
Enterprise, firing questions at chatty contestants and signing
their souvenir checks. In its Americanized production, the
questions are not very tough (if you got through junior high earth
science and have a subscription to People magazine, you can make
some real dough), and the appeal of the thing seems to lie in its
ready accessibility. It is now on the air 128 nights a week and
seems to muscle its way onto the schedule whenever it damn well
feels like it.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of waning generations, however, kicked in with the
subsequent rollout of NBC's counterweapon, ``Twenty One.'' Not only
is this a show trying to capitalize on the first-generation success
of ``Millionaire,'' it is likewise a pale descendant of one of
television's most (in)famous early hits.
</P>
<P>
   Dumbed down as though the whole thing had been poleaxed with the
stupid stick, it betrays the initial appeal of the original, which
was hard questions asked of sweating contestants in giant
soundproof saltshakers. Now the Q&AMP;A is remedial multiple choice,
the booths look air-conditioned and the only tension arises when
the M.C., Maury Povich, tries to crack a joke. He has all the comic
timing of a death row chaplain and is far better suited to his
talk-show day job supervising teen prostitute makeovers and
mouthing pieties about our failing family values.
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Twenty One'' may have been rigged, but at least
it was worth watching. NBC is learning this the hard way as the new
show's ratings travel quickly south.
</P>
<P>
   In the seat just ahead of it on that downbound bus is the
aforementioned ``Greed.'' A Fox show from top to bottom, it has
failed to catch fire, maybe because it stole only the elements from
``Millionaire'' that nobody liked: the music and the set. Or
perhaps the audience doesn't think that knowing the five most
popular sandwich spreads is worth a million bucks. If Fox knows how
to make lemons into chicken salad, though, next month we will all
be glued to the set watching ``Who Wants to Marry Chuck Woolery?''
</P>
<P>
   The CBS entry in the quiz show sweepstakes, ``Winning Lines,''
was dead on arrival. More complicated than the New York state tax
code, the entire show was taken up by Dick Clark's dogged
explanation of the rules. Thus ended, in a matter of weeks, the
explosive success cycle of prime-time game shows. Only Regis seems
destined to endure.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable about all this is not that network television
resorts to ripping off successful ideas from its competition or its
own past but that it can do it so quickly. It has long been
axiomatic that imitation is the sincerest form of television, but
this season we have witnessed a new achievement in the turnaround
time necessary to beat the life out of a defenseless idea.
</P>
<P>
   Television is history's most insistently derivative medium. Our
other major pop-cult industries, like film and music, depend on it
for the promotion and cross-pollination of their own derivatives.
The lookalike morning show books the lookalike actors who are on
the lookalike magazine covers plumping the lookalike movies that
start this Friday. The next day another actor another magazine
another movie. And the next. And the next.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidity with which these pale copies track past us
diminishes the value of each, including the ones that preceded
them, blurring and obscuring even the most authentic. In this way
we spiral into ever faster, more meaningless cycles of spin, sales
figures and cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   Thus diminished and inured to sensation, we can easily forget
why we loved that generation of originals from long ago, from the
time before the world grew cold. But if in remembering, or trying
to remember, you decide to rent ``Roman Holiday'' or ``Breakfast at
Tiffany's'' as an act of defiance or absolution or faith, don't
forget to thank young Jennifer Love Hewitt for the inspiration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
