<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLOYD-FAME-COX     03-15 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HURRICANE FLOYD: SIX MONTHS LATER
 &HT;    ALL SIGNS POINT TO PRINCEVILLE
 &HT;    EDS. Second in a seven-part series
 &HT;    By Chad Eric Watt
 &HT;    and Eunice Moscoso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCEVILLE, N.C. _ In a strange fusion of history and
devastation, Princeville has become the most famous casualty of
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Edgecombe County town, which was submerged in 23 feet of
water for two weeks, has inspired Congressional press conferences,
high-profile celebrity donations, hundreds of news stories, and an
executive order from President Clinton mandating a group of D.C.'s
most powerful officials to help rebuild the flood-ravaged
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hardly knew Princeville was there,'' said Rep. Eva
Clayton, D-N.C. ``Now, it's something the nation wants to preserve
because they see it as a part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and other lawmakers say all the attention on Princeville
has helped the entire state secure emergency aid. But flood victims
in other areas, including the Grifton and Belvoir communities in
Pitt County, say that their plight has been overshadowed by
Princeville's.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment surfaced in Belvoir last November when more than
500 volunteers from Washington came to help flood victims in
eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Two buses of volunteers, organized by the Congressional Black
Caucus, mustered at the Belvoir Volunteer Fire Department to start
a day of cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought they were interested in helping us,''said Wendy
Brady, a Belvoir resident who has helped coordinate recovery
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But flood victims in Belvoir were upset that only a few
volunteers came to help, Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Smith, a spokesman for Clayton, said the resentment is
``unfortunate'' and that lawmakers are working to help every
community hurt by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the damage in Princeville was far more severe
than other towns and that it holds a unique place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was Plymouth Rock or an area of rich cultural
identification of another group maybe others would be more
understanding of the attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Princeville, the oldest town in the country incorporated by
freed slaves and still populated mostly by their descendants,
became the focal point of media attention after last year's brutal
flood.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures and stories were compelling _ an entire community
swallowed by the Tar River, senior citizens reported missing,
caskets unearthed from Wilson Cemetery, where town founder Turner
Prince had rested in peace for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors placed casualties in the dozens.
</P>
<P>
   As waters receded, however, the real numbers emerged : no
deaths, except for the town itself, which barely had a pulse.
Nearly all of its 1,143 homes, 37 businesses and three churches
were heavily damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Political attention shortly followed as the Rev. Jesse Jackson
stood on the steps of the old town hall, clutched the town's
muddied flag and declared that Princeville would live again.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, the Congressional Black Caucus _ citing the
rich history of Princeville _ demanded a recovery strategy for
eastern North Carolina similar to the Marshall Plan, which provided
extensive aid for post-war reconstruction of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The pop musician formerly known as Prince donated $37,000 to the
town for building materials, citing the association of his own name
to Princeville.
</P>
<P>
   Other thought to be overlooked
</P>
<P>
   ``People do feel like they've gotten more publicity, help and
attention,'' said Billy Tarlton, a coordinator for church volunteer
efforts in Grifton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything big still happens, it happens there, even though
the devastation was just as big and bad here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady said that echoed sentiments expressed by Belvoir flood
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like that (Princeville) shouldn't have been the
focal point,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   The Belvoir community, which parallels the Tar River north and
west of Greenville, saw more than 100 homes hit by floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got plenty of people still trying to get back in
their homes,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. and Faye Bullock returned to their Belvoir-area home in
early March. They fled to a nephew's home when more than 20 inches
of water filled their house.
</P>
<P>
   Church groups from Hillsboro and Virginia helped the couple in
their 60s dry out and rebuild their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this part of the road, we've got neighbors on both sides
who got help (from church groups),'' Mrs. Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Grove United Methodist Church near Hillsboro has been the
conduit for much of the recovery work in Belvoir, Brady said.
Volunteers from that church arrived during the flooding to cook
meals. Now they are still helping with labor and providing money
for rebuilding supplies.
</P>
<P>
   In Grifton, a town of 2,307 people and 900 houses, about 400
houses were damaged in the flood. Churches and public buildings,
including the police station and fire department, were also gutted.
</P>
<P>
   But Grifton Town Manager Paul Spruill said that ``the town is
getting the resources it needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene James, a Pitt County commissioner who was evacuated by
helicopter from his Belvoir home during the flooding, said relief
money could have been more evenly distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other areas were hit bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James added that many people in Belvoir have received help, and
more is promised on the way from the U.S. Department of Agriculture
and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a lot of help and we're so grateful,'' he said.
``But you can't count on it until you've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said the battle for emergency aid has been ``complicated
by the fact that we have so much red tape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been frustrating in terms of seeing some progress, but
it has been reassuring that at least there are people willing to
work on the issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton also said that she has come to the difficult realization
that ``at best we don't have enough money ... that the loss and the
devastation is greater than the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeville, like other communities, is hoping for more aid.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Princeville Housing Authority received
$2.5 million in grants to rebuild public housing. The town has
applied for another $2.5 million to replace the Montessori School
there.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Princeville, a town of 2,152, has hired a recovery
manager and the Federal Emergency Management Agency has contracted
with a private, nonprofit redevelopment team to help the historic
town recover.
</P>
<P>
   The latest emergency aid package moving through Congress
includes a $1.5 million federal study on raising the dike that
protects Princeville from the Tar River. The money had been dropped
from a Republican plan, angering many people, including Clayton,
who called the omission ``unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   In further evidence of Princeville's increasing importance, the
motion to reinstate the money was not brought by a North Carolina
lawmaker but by the powerful chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big time around here,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive political intervention for
Princeville came from the highest political office. President
Clinton _ by executive order _ created a task force earlier this
year to preserve and protect the historictown.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive group includes officials from 12 federal agencies
and members of the Cabinet including the secretaries of defense,
agriculture, commerce, labor, health and human services, housing
and urban development and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   While the president has shed light on Princeville's predicament,
flooded areas have also relied on lower-profile assistance from
church volunteers to help rebuild communities.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Bell and a group of students from the Baptist Student Union
at Carson-Newman College made their second trip to Grifton during
their spring break this week.
</P>
<P>
   The group came from Jefferson City, Tenn., to Grifton last fall
after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see the need _ you look around and see total
devastation,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennesse group was helping Shelton Grady and his grandson
tear out carpets and walls from his flooded Water Street home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as much help as I've got,'' he said. ``Thank God
they're helping me take this apart.''
</P>
<P>
   He was approved for a federal disaster loan but hasn't taken it.
He and his family have been living in a nearby apartment complex
while waiting for a chance to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Blocks away from Grady's home, Mary and Walter Artis' house on
East Main Street in Grifton resembles a partially built new house,
with bare floors and dusty white drywall.
</P>
<P>
   Those walls and floors were put in by church volunteers as well.
The Artises said they received a small grant from the federal
government. They had to pay for the building materials to restore
their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people around here have been volunteers,'' Mrs. Artis
said. ``We've come a long way, and we've still got a long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
