<SLUG> BC-BHUTTO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bhutto: Set `big agenda' in Pakistan
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It wasn't an easy decision for the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   And former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto could
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   As a believer in democracy, Bhutto was not surprised that the
American president would hesitate to include a visit to Pakistan in
his tour of South Asia next week. Since October, Pakistan has been
ruled by a military regime that has so far set no time table for
restoring democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a Pakistani, I thought it was important'' that Clinton
visit, Bhutto said Tuesday. ``And as a South Asian I thought it was
important, and that is why I am glad the president is going to
Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to her country won't be long _ a mere five hours
after five days in India and one more in Bangladesh. But Bhutto,
46, said during a visit to Atlanta for a speech at Agnes Scott
College that she would like to suggest a ``heavy agenda'' for the
president during his stay.
</P>
<P>
   She hoped Clinton would engage in ``behind-the-doors diplomacy''
to help both India and Pakistan _ the newest members of the nuclear
weapons club _ manage their long, bitter dispute over the Himalayan
territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also hope that he would take the opportunity to persuade
Pakistan's military leadership to promote the democratization
process,'' said Bhutto, who twice served her country as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutto, who in 1988 became the first woman to head the
government of an Islamic state, said she had spoken with Clinton
last month about her views and had also written him a letter.
</P>
<P>
   She will not be accompanying the president during his travels,
however. Bhutto currently faces arrest on corruption charges if she
returns home, and her husband, Asif Ali Zardari, is currently
jailed there.
</P>
<P>
   But Bhutto, daughter of the late Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, continues to play a key role as leader of the opposition
Pakistan People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before speaking at Agnes Scott, she offered a
detailed rebuttal of charges against her and said she had been
``convicted by a kangaroo court'' for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   She said her country badly needs ``an independent mechanism''
for handling corruption cases and that she would not hesitate to
have the facts of her case examined in that way.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in her political career, Bhutto spent nearly six years
either in prison or under detention for her democratic activism.
</P>
<P>
   Her current legal fight began during the regime of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, who was overthrown in last year's military
coup. But Bhutto said Gen. Pervez Musharraf, Pakistan's new
military ruler, had missed an opportunity for reforming
anti-corruption laws that are often politically applied. She said
she had hoped Musharraf would call all political parties together
and have them jointly create a process for prosecuting corruption
that would be applied with an even hand, ``so that tomorrow if you
are tried you don't turn around and say that it's persecution.''
Her own case aside, she took the current government to task for
failing to address many other issues that plague her nation,
including the need for restructuring the economy, defusing
terrorism and bringing the military budget into line with reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a great expectation when (Musharraf) took over that
he would move on a reformist agenda,'' Bhutto said, ``and there
were voices which said that popular government could not take
difficult decisions which a military dictator could.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf often ``says the right things,'' she said, but the
perception has grown that other military leaders limit his ability
to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan is a country which in the last 3 1/2 years has really
gone downwards in social indicators, economic indicators,'' Bhutto
said. ``And what makes it far more explosive is the fact that there
are important international issues like terrorism and
proliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   Removing the military from civilian institutions is key to
Pakistan's future, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vast defense machinery was subsidized by the West,''
Bhutto said. ``The West wanted us to fight communism, and we wanted
to fight India. And so we allowed the West to subsidize our
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   But the world has changed since the end of the Cold War. ``And
we in Pakistan need to realize that the old ways won't do,'' Bhutto
said.
</P>
<P>
   She called for more steps to build confidence between the
nations in South Asia and to open up borders, both physically and
economically. She also said good behavior should be rewarded by
Marshall Plan-style programs to alleviate poverty in the region.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing evidence that the people of Pakistan are not
happy with the present government, Bhutto said. And that public
opinion _ along with the kind of pressure she hopes President
Clinton and other world leaders apply _ will be critical toward
bringing about a return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at history, governments that are democratic don't
go to war,'' she said. ``It's the governments that are not
democratic that too often end up in conflicts. And I think there's
far too much at stake for the West to turn its back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
