<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ARMS-BOS &LR;      03-15 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ARMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABER RATTLING CLOUDS TAIWAIN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINMEN ISLAND, Taiwan _ Through the narrow maw of a concrete
bunker at the tip of this Nantucket-sized island it is easy to see
communist soldiers exercising on the beaches of mainland China a
mile away. Through a telescope, Chinese machine gun nests behind
rocks come into focus, as do mainland tourists waving back from
lookout stations on the far side.
</P>
<P>
   This heavily fortified patch of the Taiwan strait is the
equivalent of Korea's Demilitarized Zone and what was once the
Berlin Wall. Here more than anywhere the proximity of Taiwan to its
giant neighbor, and the potential for eventual reunification _ or
disastrous conflict _ is impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   As Taiwan prepares to choose a new president this weekend,
voters on this Taiwan-controlled isle are resisting a final-days
surge toward Chen Shui-bian, the opposition candidate who until
recently openly advocated independence from the mainland. With
Beijing warning darkly of the consequences that such a vote would
bring, residents here do not want to once again become pawns in a
cross-straits game of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   China considers Taiwan a breakaway province, and has always
demanded that it resubmit to mainland rule and vowed to attack
Taiwan if it declared itself independent. In recent weeks, Beijing
has upped the drumbeat by showing off newly &UR;  &LR; purchased Russian
destroyers and threatening to invade if Taiwan as much as drags its
feet over reunification talks.
</P>
<P>
   With just two days left before the vote, China's military
menace, and the perceptibly growing arms race on both sides of the
Taiwan strait, have become the looming issues in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the China threat will be the
deciding factor at the polls Saturday. Many voters resent China's
leaders' telling them how to vote and ordering them to surrender to
negotiations or face attack.
</P>
<P>
   And _ except perhaps on Kinmen _ many are skeptical that China
can back up its military bluster. Although China's forces outnumber
Taiwan's 6-1, many strategic analysts question whether Beijing's
war machine is capable of conquering, or even rapidly neutralizing,
its well-equipped neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an open question whether a military assault would be
worth the cost to China. Any attack would forever alienate
Beijing's avowed ``brothers'' across the strait and make voluntary
reunification impossible. It would also spark global condemnation,
economic sanctions, and a possible confrontation with the United
States, which is pledged to defend Taiwan against assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of an attack would be very high'' for China's
leaders, said Maj. Gen. Tyson Fu, director of strategic studies at
Taiwan's Armed Forces University, and a former member of the
intelligence bureau of the joint chiefs of staff. China's
``decision-makers are not idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji Wednesday issued a new
warning that those who doubt China's capacities should not
underestimate its determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``People making such calculations don't know about Chinese
history,'' he told reporters. ``The Chinese people are ready to
shed blood and scarifice their lives to defend the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
   Kinmen, once known as Quemoy, was long the staging ground for a
50-year hot-and-cold battle between Chinese nationalists on Taiwan
and communists on the mainland following the end of their civil war
in 1949. That year, nationalist troops repulsed a Red Army force
that attempted to invade the island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Mao Zedong's forces tried again, raining 57,000
artillery shells in two hours on this fragile outpost. Over 44
days, Beijing's forces fired half a million shells onto its 59
square miles of sand dunes, scrubby pines, and farmland in a
conflict that pushed the United States to send aircraft carriers
into the area, and China and the United States to the brink of war.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre deal that followed, China offered to shell on odd
days, while Taiwan shelled on even ones. Sunday was everyone's day
off. The surreal alternate-day battle continued through 20 years
and 970,000 shells, with artillery eventually replaced by
cannisters of propaganda leaflets and queer forms of Taiwanese
psychological warfare, including _ inexplicably _ see-through
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has given up on such tactics. The enormous speakers that
once blasted nationalist propaganda across the waters have been
replaced with smaller ones that jingle with Taiwan pop songs and
fishing reports. And even those play at volumes too low to reach
China; deafening decibels have been abandoned to avoid disturbing
Kinmen's own residents.
</P>
<P>
   Modern weaponry means that Kinmen is no longer the obvious
target of a Chinese assault, nor an important focus of Taiwan's
defense effort. Military forces here have shrunk to one-fifth of
the high of 100,000 troops. Today, China could eschew sending
frogmen and artillery to Kinmen in favor of launching missiles
directly at cities 100 miles away on the main island of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when China test fired missiles as a intimidation tactic
during Taiwan's last presidential election, the mainland was
thought to have fewer than 75 short- to medium-range missiles, said
Parris Chang, former chairman of the national defense committee.
Today, Beijing is believed to have about 300 such missiles, and the
Pentagon predicts it could have 800 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing announced last week a 13 percent increase in military
spending to a record $14.5 billion this year _ capping a decade of
a double-digit growth aimed at modernizing the 2.5 million-member
army. Actual spending is probably two to five times higher. China
has bought electronics, ships, and state-of-the-art equipment,
including missile-firing destroyers capable of evading the defenses
of US carrier fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's strategists boast that China could force Taiwan to
heel by launching a coordinated airstrike to cripple air defenses,
airfields, and command, control, and communications centers within
45 minutes. Most of Taiwan's major targets _ cities, harbors and
airfields; economic targets such as oil refineries and steel mills;
political targets such as the presidential palace and legislature _
are on the west coast facing the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts here are skeptical, saying China is five to 10
years from being able to mount such a surgical strike. China's
missiles are not accurate, said Chang; they could aim for the
presidential palace and hit a nearby girls' school instead.
</P>
<P>
   And though China's air force greatly outnumbers Taiwan's,
Taipei's is considered far superior, with an edge in technology and
pilots that the mainland might not be able to match or surpass for
one to two decades. Taiwan's radar systems are also superior.
Beijing also lacks a transport fleet large enough to ferry a major
invasion force across the strait, even though Taiwan's own ships
and submarines are woefully outdated. But China probably could
impose a naval blockade.
</P>
<P>
   Key to maintaining Taiwan's current air superiority is US
willingness to supply it with advanced defense systems, such as
forthcoming third-generation Patriot anti-missile batteries and
warships fitted with Aegis anti-missile radar systems _ sales the
United States is debating because of Beijing's vehement opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Pentagon authorized Raytheon Corp. to sell 162
Hawk anti-aircraft missiles and upgraded air surveillance radar to
Taiwan, in a deal estimated to be worth $106 million. But in the
end, said Lin Yu-fang, a strategic analyst at Tamkang University,
the only thing that could save Taiwan from an all-out Chinese
assault would be direct US intervention, and few believe that
Taiwan can count on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people here do not believe the US would fight
face-to-face against (Beijing) to save Taiwan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 Taiwan Relations Act, a pledge by the United States to
defend Taiwan, is ``a very vague promise,'' said Lin, military
affairs' adviser to James Soong, the candidate seen as most in
favor of eventual reunification with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, strategic adviser to opposition candidate Chen,
acknowledged Wednesday that Kinmen, Matsu, and other front-line
islands ``are not defendable.'' But he said China could have long
ago seized those islands and chose not to, to maintain the
proximity and psychological link between Taiwan and China.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the 51,000 civilian residents and 20,000 soldiers on
Kinmen seem oddly blase about living within virtual spitting
distance of China, perhaps inured after decades of bombardment.
This isle of winding paths through tile-rooved farming villages has
a sleepy, holiday-camp feel to it. But the apparent thick-skinned
nonchalance of the residents hides their true feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an attack (on Kinmen), it would be very difficult
for Taiwan alone to protect us,'' a 48-year-old who identified
himself as Mr. Hsu said sadly. ``Only if America protects us would
we have a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
