<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Company offering health care info to Web sites to add 30 workers
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Adam.com, which supplies health care information to
several popular Web sites, said it will add 30 jobs at its Atlanta
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The people hired likely will be writers, medical illustrators,
producers and product managers, said Bob Cramer, Adam.com's
39-year-old chief executive and co-founder. Adam.com employs 45
people in it's Atlanta location. A San Francisco office employs
about 8 people, down from 35 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Adam.com creates and licenses the information found in
illustrated medical encyclopedias and on health care Web sites. Its
information is used by more than 20 sites, including Yahoo,
Healtheon/WebMD and Excite. The mission of the San Francisco office
was to place the behind-the-scenes company in the forefront _ to
design a Web site people would visit to research health issues,
such as breast cancer and knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt to get taken seriously in the early days of e-health,
you had to have a portal,'' Cramer said. ``We felt our strength was
to be a content syndicator. We sort of pulled back from being a
destination and will focus on being more of a business to business
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer said the company plans to invest more than $30 million to
develop more products. Adam.com's illustrated medical encyclopedia
costs about $250,000 per year to use. The company plans to
introduce between 15 and 20 more products over the 18 months,
Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
