<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta apartment construction due for surge, consultant says
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta apartment construction will surge this
year, surpassing 1999's performance by 33 percent. The area will
see the addition of 15,470 apartments this year, up from 11,567 in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction comes from M/PF Research, a Dallas-based
apartment market data collector and consultant. The company
introduced itself to the Atlanta market Wednesday morning with an
extensive briefing session for the executives it hopes will be
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders, owners and developers heard company President Ron
Witten report that 1999 was a better year here than in many other
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter occupancy in Atlanta was at 96 percent, up 1
percentage point from the same period in 1998. Employment growth
pushed the increase. Atlanta created 116,000 jobs in 1999, placing
the metro area second among the nation's top job generators. New
York ranked first.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for apartments continued apace, Witten said, even though
Atlanta remains one of the hottest single-family-house markets in
the country. The metro area absorbed nearly 14,000 new apartments
in 1999, a 68 percent jump over previous-year volume.Absorption is
a measure of new units occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Among the submarkets, the northeastern suburbs _ Gwinnett
County, Roswell/Alpharetta and east Cobb _ accounted for the
greatest growth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Midtown held its own with 810 new units coming over 1999.
In 2000, seven apartment communities with 1,100 units will be ready
by year-end. Chamblee, Brookhaven and northwest Atlanta also have
apartments in the pipeline. The largest of these will be the
478-unit monolith going in at the Preserve at Deerfield, by
Fairfield Property.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 surprise was that Decatur, increasingly popular and
pricey as a residential area, saw only one completion. That was the
380-unit Jefferson Square in Decatur, Witten said. But this year,
there will be an ``impressive surge,'' Witten said, because more
than 2,000 units are targeted for completion.
</P>
<P>
   In south Atlanta/south Fulton, only one new community of 248
units opened, in College Park.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
