<SLUG> BC-CRAB-LIMITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUBUDON HITS SMALL SIZE OF HORSESHOE CRAB LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commission decision
last month to impose a 25 percent reduction on catches of the East
Coast horseshoe crab amounts to no cut at all, the National Audubon
Society contends. The group claims that Massachusetts, Connecticut,
New York, and other states inflated their catch numbers prior to
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Audubon this week informed Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci
in a letter that his state not only raised its numbers in advance
of the decision by the Commission's horseshoe crab management
board, but voted against a minimally protective 50 percent cut
proposed by the US Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission acknowledged the states raised their numbers, but
not because they were trying to avoid the reduction in catches. The
increases were based on new data the states collected and filed
last year, it said. And Massachusetts stands by its new catch
number as accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the books cooked? No, that's not the case,'' said Bruce
Freeman, chairman of the horseshoe crab management board. ``It may
appear that way, but it certainly wasn't something contrived to
increase the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the peak of the crab season just weeks away, the
creature that has scoured the ocean floor of New England for 350
million years remains imperiled by rampant fishing, Audubon says.
The crabs are used as bait for eel and conch, which have become
popular in Europe and Asia. And a substance in crab blood is used
to detect bacteria in surgical implants and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew a cut was coming, and so they tried to manipulate
the numbers so that a cut would have no real effect on the status
of the fishery,'' said Perry Plumart, senior policy adviser at
Audubon. The group has sought cuts as high as 60 to 80 percent to
save the crabs. As is, the crabs ``are poised for a major
collapse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Pizzi, a spokesman for the Massachusetts state
Executive Office of Environmental Affairs, said the state's revised
number reflects solid reporting that was then reviewed by
scientists and fishery managers for accuracy. ``It's the best data
we have, and we stand behind it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Horseshoe crabs thrived for hundreds of millions of years on the
East Coast, but a century of catches for fertilizer and livestock
virtually wiped them out by 1960. They rebounded, thanks to
conservation efforts. Red knots and other migratory birds gorge on
them in Delaware Bay for a few days in the spring, stopping en
route from their wintering grounds in South America to their
breeding grounds in the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   But with the recent, soaring value of eel and conch, boatloads
of crabs are being caught off the New England coast and elsewhere,
at a time when the commission itself says it has no idea how large
the crab population is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TEXAS-WYLY-ART-2NDTAK     03-15 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WYLY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: traded company.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In particular, Calpers pointed to decisions by directors of the
company's board, which it described as ``dominated by Wyly family''
interests, to award themselves and corporate executives overly
lucrative compensation packages and generous golden parachutes.
</P>
<P>
   Those directors also repriced their stock options to benefit
themselves during years when the company's stock was low, Calpers
found.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it difficult to accept that these actions are
representative of an independent board,'' said Charles P. Valdes,
chairman of Calpers' investment committee in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said that in response to Calpers' concerns, Michaels Stores
had since appointed two independent directors. ``We have met with
Calpers,'' he said, ``and I think they are happy today with what we
are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Calpers, Brad Pacheco, said the pension fund was
pleased with the changes but still had questions about the
company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wyly, his son, Evan, and his daughter, Lisa, as well as offshore
trusts whose beneficiaries are Wyly family members, also hold
stakes in GreenMountain.com, SEC filings show. Those documents also
show that Maverick Capital invested $15 million in
Greenmountain.com immediately before last year's planned stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing barred such an investment. But the move is striking,
given previous comments by Lee S. Ainslie III, a Maverick managing
partner, that it would not invest in a Wyly-controlled company.
Evan Wyly is the fund's other managing partner, said Sam Wyly, and
Wyly family investments make up about $400 million, or 10 percent,
of the fund's assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work very hard to maintain a degree of separation between
the entities,'' Ainslie told Barron's in 1996. ``For instance, we
never have and we never will be able to have any stake _ we being
Maverick _ in Sterling Software or Michaels Stores, just because
there's too much potential for conflict of interest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ainslie said Maverick's investment in GreenMountain.com, which
first took place in 1997, was not at odds with his previous
comments because the energy concern is a private company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no change to our policy of not making an
investment in public companies where we believe there is potential
for a conflict of interest that would result from nonpublic
information,'' said Ainslie, who added that he was in charge of the
fund's investments.
</P>
<P>
   SEC documents show that if the planned stock offering by
GreenMountain.com had gone forward, Maverick Capital would have
retained an 11 percent stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Maverick Capital also holds a 9 percent stake in Scottish
Annuity &AMP; Life Holdings, a publicly traded insurer based in the
Cayman Islands. Until last month, Wyly was chairman of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ainslie said that at the time Maverick's investment was made,
Scottish Annuity was also a private company. SEC filings show that
a major investment by the fund was made one month before the
insurer's initial public stock offering in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said he did not see any conflicts with Maverick Capital's
investment in GreenMountain.com. David Russ, managing director of
public markets for the University of Texas Management Investment
Co., said the group's guidelines did not bar Maverick from
investing in the energy company.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said he had no immediate plans to pay for ads against Vice
President Al Gore during the general election, but Wyly he added
that he and another son, Andrew, a Dennison University student whom
he credits with the promotions against McCain, have kicked around
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   They would be built around the theme that Gore, whose
environmental record might appeal to some voters, was a
regulation-happy Democrat who would not be good for business or the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be green without being red,'' said Wyly, testing out a slogan
on a listener. ``Al Gore is an heir to the old czars and
commissars. He never saw a regulation he didn't like.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
