<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-SALARIES     03-15 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-SALARIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ENVY OF BASEBALL WITH EFFECTIVE PAYROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ As the Baltimore Orioles venture about
Florida this spring, they travel with a large stigma. And no, that
doesn't necessarily mean Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   When the O's team bus rolls into a ballyard parking lot, the
reaction among baseball people will include some snickers and
whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, I wasn't a personal witness to any of that yesterday as
the Rangers played host to Baltimore, but what goes without saying,
snickering or whispering is Doug Melvin would never want to be in
the Orioles shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The third-highest 1999 payroll in baseball ($84 million)
produced a grand total of 78 victories to finish 20 games behind
the Yankees in the American League East. And if you think not
keeping up with the $88 million invested by the Yankees isn't
exactly a disgrace, the Orioles were 16 games back of Boston for
the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore provides a handy excuse for 29 other owners and 29
other general managers. If those parties are being grilled about a
lack of spending for talent, ``see,'' they will say, pointing to
the Orioles, ``it's not always about how high the payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not always, but ...
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, of course, have had a hammerlock on the World
Series, one reason being money is no hindrance. But high-dollar
payrolls for Baltimore and the LA Dodgers (77 wins last season)
couldn't prevent sub-.500 seasons, and frankly, this kind of
malfunction has become, in today's game, the worst of front-office
blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that play better than their payrolls would suggest _ the
Reds and Athletics were examples in 1999 _ have general managers
and managers hailed for their shrewdness in knowing payroll value.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, on the other hand, present a strange payroll
paradox this spring.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Melvin has what a vast majority of his
counterparts would gladly kill for _ a $66 million budget, which is
down from $75 million last season, but a generous owner who is
willing to take it back to 75 mil via any trade that might come
along.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Melvin's payroll structure is the envy of one and all. The
team's three best players are all signed for two years or beyond at
below-market value. Rafael Palmeiro is the highest at $9 million
this season, then comes Pudge Rodriguez at $8 million. The
third-best player on the team, Rusty Greer, is baseball's best
bargain at $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three at those salaries _ that's incredible,'' Toronto
manager Jim Fregosi was saying this week during a Charlotte County
Stadium stop. ``\RThe Rangers\S got that done only because all
three wanted to be in Texas. That kind of loyalty from that kind of
talent is also almost unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the payroll to do so, Melvin has thus far avoided one
fear _ having a player hit the $10 million or beyond mark in yearly
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that day is coming,'' Melvin said yesterday, ``but
for 10 million, I've got to have a very special player, someone who
gives the numbers, of course, but also someone who brings
leadership and a community presence.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a Palmeiro-type, as opposed to the departed Juan
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, a year ago, the Rangers offered salaries beyond
the $10 million mark to free-agent pitchers Randy Johnson and Roger
Clemens. Both went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two qualified as special cases,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the payroll situation is very nicely proportioned,
most of the national preseason guesswork on the 2000 season has the
Rangers being a team in sharp decline. In general, they are mostly
being picked to drop to third in the AL West behind Seattle and
Oakland. ``USA Today'' had this club this week at a massive 50-to-1
to win the World Series. Those 95 victories from last season have
been quickly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, no baseball-type in this camp believes a word of the
team-in-decline predictions. But should that stuff be correct, then
Melvin's butt quickly goes on the line, no matter his neat bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total balancing act that in the end must lead to
winning,'' Melvin said. ``We have been fortunate with players who
did want to be here, and they didn't put money over happiness. But
others have left or didn't come because more money was offered
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the game today. But I think we've come out ahead
in all areas with those who did choose to be with us at what is
probably now below their market value.''
</P>
<P>
   If Melvin wins with this plan, he'll be next winter's general
manager genius. If not? Well, it's still far too early to be
discussing such unpleasantries. \Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports
at Six'' can be heard weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
