<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IRS-AUDITS16-COX     03-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-AUDITS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS FINDS NO IRS BIAS AGAINST AUDITED CONSERVATIVE GROUPS
 &HT;    660&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A long-awaited congressional study rejects
allegations by some conservative groups that they have been audited
by the Internal Revenue Service because they criticize President
Clinton or his policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the three-year investigation by the Joint Tax Committee
finds evidence that the White House may have improperly sought
information from the IRS about some tax-exempt groups.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``no credible evidence'' the tax-collecting agency was
biased against anti-Clinton groups, the report stated. The IRS had
also audited organizations that ``would be considered supportive of
the Clinton administration,'' said the 170-page report, a copy of
which was obtained by Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional probe was a bipartisan response to allegations
of bias raised by several groups in 1996 after they were audited.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations include the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative research center, and the private watchdog group
Citizens Against Government Waste, both based in Washington, as
well as the Western Journalism Center in Fair Oaks, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Christian Coalition has sued the IRS, charging
it with unfairly rejecting its application for tax-exempt status
after a review process that took almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the report did not substantiate allegations that tax
audits were used as political weapons, it nonetheless faulted the
Clinton administration for evidence of two ``nonroutine'' contacts
made with IRS employees.
</P>
<P>
   Because of tight secrecy laws involving taxpayer information,
the Joint Tax Committee report avoids mentioning any group by name
but states that it reviewed the records of 83 non-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, White House aides ``appear to have attempted to
obtain taxpayer return information'' that is protected by privacy
law. And in a second example, a Treasury Department official ``was
alleged to have made a 1995 inquiry to IRS employees'' about the
tax-exempt status of an organization under examination by the tax
agency, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These types of contacts lend credence to the allegations that
the administration does intervene in IRS matters pertaining to
specific taxpayers,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the study found that the Treasury Department inspector
general's office took no action on the 1995 incident until the
subject was raised two years later by the congressional staff
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Among other conclusions, the Joint Committee:
</P>
<P>
   _ Disclosed that tracing behavior at the IRS was difficult
because, prior to the middle of 1998, the agency had a practice of
destroying audit information once a decision was made not to pursue
an organization for back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Calculated that members of Congress made nearly 500 inquiries
to the IRS between 1994 and the middle of 1997. But as with the
White House, the report said that the lawmakers' contacts had
apparently not altered the way the IRS handled audits of tax-exempt
groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Listed eight instances of ``alleged IRS employee misconduct''
relating to tax-exempt groups. Few details were offered, although
one case involved an allegation that an employee in the IRS chief
counsel's office improperly sought taxpayer information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Found no signs of political discrimination in granting
tax-exempt status, but it said that the IRS was ``unacceptably
slow'' in ruling on applications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Confirmed that some high-profile tax-exempt organizations and
individuals ``received intense internal review and scrutiny by the
IRS,'' but the staff again found no ``credible'' evidence that this
scrutiny was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the IRS said the agency would have no response
until the report is formally released, possibly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy referred a reporter to Vice
President Al Gore's office, which did not immediately return a
phone call Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levin, whose conservative Landmark Legal Foundation has
sued the IRS in this controversy, said he was shocked at some of
the findings, especially the information about documents being
routinely destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's group has sought to force the IRS to disclose which
lawmakers and which administration officials have sent inquiries to
the IRS. He has told the court that a witness alleges that that IRS
officials spoke of shredding documents he sought.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Justice Department ``explained this rather
elaborate procedure that they followed to gather information,''
Levin said. ``At no point did they say that they were destroying
documents.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal district court in Washington last week rejected
Levin's attempts to force the IRS to disclose more information or
answer questions about documents. Levin said he is considering
further legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
