<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-COST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG DIG' BILL COULD RISE EVEN HIGHER, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Acknowledging remaining construction contracts may cost
more than expected, ``Big Dig'' officials revealed Wednesday the
price tag of the highway project may climb to $12.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Federal Highway Administration, the state
said a recently discovered $1.4 billion shortfall may actually
range between $1.3 and $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, concerned that construction bids
continue to exceed estimates, said he instructed project managers
to build in a funding cushion just in case there are unforseen
problems in submerging Boston's Central Artery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a range in there at my request,'' Cellucci said. ``I
don't want to get into the same problems we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   The project cost, which was originally supposed to be $2.6
billion, has risen steadily since ground was broken in 1991 and may
now exceed $12.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The hot economy, with high demand for construction materials and
workers, continues to boost prices. Last month, every bid submitted
for one of the project's final contracts came in more than $22
million over budget, discouraging officials who are trying to hold
the line on spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig's report on the cost overrun -- and Cellucci's plan
to use borrowing and cash reserves to cover it -- were delivered to
the Federal Highway Administration's district office Wednesday to
meet a deadline imposed by US Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater.
</P>
<P>
   A federal task force, which includes a Washington auditing team,
will evaluate both documents from the state, along with their own
findings, and issue a report expected to be made public early
April.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Washington, including Bay State Congressman J. Joseph
Moakley, believed the governor should have submitted a more
complete financing report, one that had won the backing of
legislative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan has already been roundly panned by the
Legislature, and the final financing strategy is likely to be
dramatically different from what Cellucci proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate are likely to take up the issue next month.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Crockford, the massive project's chief of staff, played
down the revelation that the Central Artery price tag could reach
$12.5 billion. Crockford said the report -- validated by an outside
consulting firm -- was not meant to suggest that costs are sure to
climb. The state wants to err on the side of caution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maintainted all along that $1.4 billion is a best
estimate and there should be a range,'' Crockford said. ``The point
is not to draw a line in the sand here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig document, an in-house financial outline that was
supposed to be submitted to federal highway officials in October,
was delayed because Massachusetts Turnpike Chairman James J.
Kerasiotes was in the midst of a ``top to bottom'' review of the
budget and put the report on hold.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Kerasiotes admitted the $1.4 billion budget gap
last month, triggering the audit and Wednesday's deadline to
explain the overrun.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his faith in Kerasiotes' budget numbers was flagging
and that is why he requested an overrun range be included in the
report, Cellucci hinted that may be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have (Administration and Finance) Secretary (Andrew)
Natsios working with the Big Dig, double checking, triple checking
all the numbers,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also said the overrun should come in at $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it doesn't, he has called for paying down
high-interest debt using surplus funds, a move that could save $600
million over 5 years, which could be enough to cover an additonal
budget gap. Those funds are in addition to his plan to use cash and
borrowing to pay for the $1.4 billion overrun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to think that's what we're guaranteeing,''
he said of the $1.4 billion figure. ``When you're building
something under a 350-year-old city, we've already run into
construction problems. ... What I do know is that we're almost
two-thirds the way done and that's less exposure we have.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are two final construction contracts that remain
to be bid this summer which could come in higher than budgeted due
to the hot economy and high fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   One is a $348 million job involving the Interstate 93 southbound
tunnel through Dewey Square and demolition of some of the elevated
artery.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a $144 million contract to finish the South Bay
interchange between I-93 and the Massachusetts Turnpike, along with
the restoration of Albany Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
