<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EUROPE-CHOCOLATE-NYT &LR;      03-15 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-CHOCOLATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S CHOCOLATE-COATED VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After years of The Great Chocolate Debate, Europeans may
soon get to eat their British chocolate _ and its fat, too.
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament lifted a ban on British chocolate
Wednesday, saying it can now be officially sold on the Continent
after more than a quarter of a century of arguments about its
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, those rare Continentals who craved Creme Eggs,
Maltesers and Cadbury's Flake Bars had been able to buy them _ but
not legally as ``chocolate.'' The typical British candy bar is made
with some vegetable fat in place of the expensive cocoa butter.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since the British joined the European Union in 1973,
chocolate purists, notably the Belgians, Dutch and Luxemburgers,
have insisted that European law recognize only chocolate made with
100 percent cocoa butter. What the British made, they sniffed,
could call itself ``vegelate.''
</P>
<P>
   What became known as the Two Chocolates Policy had corollaries,
including the Two Milk Chocolates Policy, based on the British and
Irish taste for as much as 25 percent milk in their milk chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   With the $15 billion European chocolate market at stake, the
British lobbied hard, and Wednesday the opposition finally gave in.
Bars made with up to 5 percent vegetable fats can legally be called
chocolate, as long as the substitute is from a short list: illipe,
shea, sal, kokum gurgi, mango kernel or palm oil.
</P>
<P>
   The British fared less well on the second issue _ their milkier
bars must be marked ``family milk chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote needs final approval at next week's meeting of European
heads of state in Lisbon, but that is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Paris, Robert Linxe, founder of the famous Maison du
Chocolat, called the decision ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks the quality,'' he said. ``It's money, always money.
I will never employ anything but pure cocoa butter, but others will
make it with fat and not mark it as fat, which is very bad. You
must not fool the client.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
