<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SEMA-LHS16-COX     03-15 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMA-LHS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $4 billion deal aims to capture wireless billing market
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A British software company has agreed to pay more than
$4 billion to buy LHS Group, a low-profile, but high-growth
Atlanta-based company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which sent LHS Group stock soaring Wednesday, calls
for London-based Sema Group to give 2.6 of its shares in exchange
for each one held by an LHS shareholder. The agreement is meant to
create a powerhouse in the market for software used to calculate
bills for using wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies would be the largest provider of wireless
billing software with nearly 40 percent of the market. Buying LHS
would let Sema leap-frog past Cap Gemini, currently the leading
European company in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market share is key,'' said Pierre Bonelli, chief executive of
Sema. ``If you are looking for one motivation, that's the one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonelli said there would be ``relatively minimal'' job cuts
after the merger. ``Good people are hard to come by and what we
need is brains.''
</P>
<P>
   LHS officials in Atlanta were unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Cuccio, chief executive of LHS Group, told Bloomberg
News that the company now lacks the muscle to sell systems to the
biggest mobile phone companies. ``Sema gives us the power to
address the largest carriers.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is a relative newcomer to Atlanta, with its roots in
Europe. LHS was established in 1990 as a three-person operation in
Dietzenbach, Germany. The company started a subsidiary, LHS
Communications Systems, basing it in Atlanta to target service
providers in this hemisphere. Later that year, the company shifted
its corporate headquarters to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Company revenues were $200,000 in 1990. Last year's sales were
$263 million. The company has about 1,700 employees, but most are
in other offices throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   LHS customers include Bell Atlantic and Nextel. Sema clients
include Vodafone AirTouch. Chief competitors for LHS Group and Sema
are Amdocs of Missouri and Cincinnati-based Convergys Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement as announced would have been worth $4.7 billion,
providing a stunning 75 percent premium over the price of LHS Group
shares. But then Sema shares fell by about 15 percent,
substantially trimming value from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   When announced, the accord would have valued LHS at $69.70 per
share. By the end of trading Wednesday, the deal would provide $59
a share to LHS shareholders _ still a healthy premium over the
price before the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   LHS stock rose $12.37 1/2 to close Wednesday at $52 a share, a
52-week high. Shares in the company were as low as $22 in November.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jason Bell of the Robinson-Humphrey Co. said the
companies are attacking a rapidly growing market. Revenues from
wireless services are expanding at a rate of more than 20 percent a
year. Even more robust is the demand for wireless data services,
which is growing at a 50 percent-a-year clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a really explosive market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey now rates the stock as neutral, although the
deal has clear benefits for those who were already LHS
shareholders, Bell said. ``We view this transaction as very
positive for shareholders of the LHS Group. The real question is,
long-term, what can the new combined entity deliver?''
</P>
<P>
   As much as demand for wireless is growing, the industry also is
in flux. The ``bundling'' of wireless bills along with those for
other telecommunications services helps to make for uncertain
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Moore, a money manager at Gartmore Capital Management, told
Bloomberg News that he is uncertain about the prognosis for the
merged company. ``What investors need to look at is the return on
investment and the long-term strategic rationale for the deal,
which right now remains a slightly shrouded mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
