<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-CINDERELLA-TEAMS-     03-15 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CINDERELLA-TEAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time to crown a new Cinderella
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, in the film ``Caddyshack,'' Bill Murray
actually spoke with perfect clarity. ''It's a Cinderella story!''
he cried, meaning golf. But Murray easily could have been talking
hoops of the most heavenly kind.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Cinderella has become a frayed and overused cliche. No
matter. At least not in the grandest sporting event of all, the
NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament, where Cinderella imagery is most
apt. So if the glass slipper fits, wear it. And every March it
does, and they do. Every March, some small school from a mid-major
conference springs a first-round, even a second-round, upset in the
NCAAs and turns a high-seed big-school stepsister ugly. You could
look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gonzaga and Miami of Ohio, each seeded 10th, along
with Southwest Missouri State (12th) and Oklahoma (13th), all
reached the Sweet 16. Gonzaga advanced to the Elite Eight before
the clock struck midnight PST for the Zags in the West Regional
final.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 14th-seeded Richmond stunned No. 3 South Carolina,
while Valparaiso, a 13, won twice before heading home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 15th-seeded Coppin State and its coach named ''Fang''
made one-and-done out of second-seed South Carolina.
Tennessee-Chattanooga, a 14, upset Georgia and Illinois before
falling.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1996, 13th-seeded Princeton showed Jim Harrick's
defending national champion UCLA the back door in the first round,
43-41.
</P>
<P>
   And this year? Hey, it'll happen again. Always does. Probably
starting today, when the Midwest and West regions begin.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith, some Cinderella possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure. Fairy tales can come true, they can happen to
you, especially if you're a 12th seed. Since the NCAA field
expanded to 64 teams in 1985, a 12th seed has beaten a No. 5 18
times in 15 years, and at least once every year except '88. So why
not St. Bonaventure, even against mighty Kentucky tonight in
Cleveland?
</P>
<P>
   ''St. Bonaventure is going to beat them,'' said John Chaney,
whose Temple Owls split with the Bonnies during the regular season
before blowing them out in the Atlantic-10 final. ''There ain't no
way they're going to contain that little boy Winn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Winn, a splendid senior point guard, could make life
miserable for Kentucky's Saul Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But Winn's not alone. ''Those guys on the front line, they're
really going to surprise them,'' Chaney said, referring to
6-foot-11 Peter Van Paassen and 6-foot-9 Caswell Cyrus, who have
the size to battle UK's Jamaal Magloire.
</P>
<P>
   Even given Tubby Smith's traditional tournament tenacity, the
Wildcats were humbled by Arkansas in the SEC Tournament, then lost
starting forward Desmond Allison to suspension Sunday. Factor in
Kentucky's dismal shooting, its worst in 37 years, and St.
Bonaventure's tough zone defense, and Chaney might be right.
</P>
<P>
   Utah State. It might sound odd calling a school with an
enrollment of 20,808 a sleeper, but the 12th-seeded Aggies are
relatively sleepy. Utah State has won its last 19 games, the
nation's longest winning streak, which included taking the Big West
tournament. Even against defending national champ Connecticut, the
Aggies have hope.
</P>
<P>
   They play tenacious defense, allowing 61.1 points a game; have
balanced scoring, with four starters averaging in double figures);
and shoot well from the outside, with guard Tony Brown hitting 45.3
percent on 3-pointers, forward Troy Rolle 41.1).
</P>
<P>
   But at 6-foot-8, coach Stew Morrill is taller than all but one
of his players, 6-foot-11 center Dimitri Jorssen. And UConn is
bigger, physical and experienced. Still, the Aggies could surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra. Six years ago, when Jay Wright walked out for his first
game as Hofstra's head coach, he carried T-shirts to give to
students in the stands. One problem: No students were in the
stands. Not now. The Flying Dutchmen won the last two Holiday
Festivals and on Saturday captured their first America East title
and first NCAA bid in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Laden with New York talent, Wright has an NCAA essential: senior
guard Craig ''Speedy'' Claxton, the two-time America East player of
the year. Claxton was eighth in the nation in scoring at 22.9
points a game and, even at 5-foot-11, has legitimate NBA potential.
Forward Norman Richardson (15.8) can fill it. In Oklahoma State,
however, the 14th-seeded Dutchmen face a more physical, experienced
team that plays tough defense. But can the Cowboys slow down
Speedy?
</P>
<P>
   Penn. The Quakers have Michael Jordan. Not that Jordan, but the
6-foot guard who averaged 16.3 points and 4.9 assists a game to
become the Ivy League's player of the year. The 13th-seeded Quakers
by four to Temple on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Owens, the 6-foot-11 center, and freshman forward Ugonna
Onyekwe combined for 100 blocks, and Penn held opponents to 39.7
shooting. Yes, it's the Ivies and yes, Penn's playing Illinois. But
the Quakers are NCAA savvy and have a terrific coach in Fran
Dunphy.
</P>
<P>
   Samford. A year ago, the Bulldogs were a tournament curiousity
before a 22-point first-round loss to St. John's. The Trans America
champs return with familiar strengths; the Bulldogs were second in
the country in field-goal percentage (50.3) and hit 38.7 percent of
its 3-pointers. With coach Jimmy Tillette an acolyte of
ex-Princeton coach Pete Carrill, 13th-seeded Samford ran its
back-door offense well enough to upset St. John's in the
season-opener and to win at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   A dearth of size and depth could hurt against Syracuse, which is
stinging from an upset loss to Georgetown in the Big East
tournament and whose 3-2 zone could close the back door for
Samford. But the Orangemen, who won their first 19 games, lost five
of their last 10 and have a history of struggling with _ and
sometimes stumbling over _ Cinderellas of all shapes and sizes.
</P>
<P>
   For now, this year's crop is living happily ever after. At least
until the b-ball's over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
