<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-DIVERSITY-     03-15 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-DIVERSITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves make a pitch with diversity training
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the Braves' new world of baseball, curbing foul
mouths has become as important as catching foul balls.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from corporate America's playbook, the Braves'
front office has hired a diversity expert to help coach the team
through the difficult time following John Rocker's infamous
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Picture, if you will, a kinder, gentler baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Along with stretching exercises, the team has spent a portion of
spring training in some soul-searching with the help of Cook Ross,
a Silver Spring, Md., consulting firm. Cook Ross also has worked
with the likes of the American Red Cross, the Bureau of National
Affairs and Geico, an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' sessions, which started in late February, are
mandatory for everyone from farm team rookies to Braves President
Stan Kasten. They've included one-on-one sessions with team
leaders, and group discussions. The topics have ranged from the
O.J. Simpson trial to dealing with stereotypes about athletes, to
how life in America differs dramatically for minorities from what
whites experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased at what we've seen so far. We had a lot of
dialogue. They were very engaging. They asked a lot of questions,''
said Kasten who found the experience eye-opening. Kasten said the
Braves are considering more sensitivity training sessions in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the off-season we had and the attention we have had on
this (Rocker) matter, we thought it would be useful for the entire
organization to go through it. We take the business of our
community relations and our image in the community very
seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been beneficial to everybody,'' said general
manager John Schuerholz, whose brother recommended Cook Ross ``Out
of adversity grows the opportunity to be a better organization and
show leadership in the industry, coming to grips with the
situation, embracing it more and becoming a stronger team because
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Braves players, the sessions were as much about
forgiveness as about rebuilding relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody got something out of it,'' said third
baseman Chipper Jones. ``We could heed the advice of a person who's
been through an experience like this before. The gist of it was to
face it. Sweeping it under a rug is not going to solve the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, who was critical of Rocker early on, said players
were encouraged not to be judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all make the mistake of, instead of getting to know
someone, you judge them first, then get to know them later when
it's too late,'' the right fielder said. ``It's a shame it had to
come down this way, but it's all part of the learning process.''
</P>
<P>
   While big business has had to face head-on a changing workforce
and ensuing racial and gender conflicts for some time, it's a
relatively new issue for baseball. The National Basketball
Association and Major League soccer are ahead of the sports pack on
this issue, according to one sports industry expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much on point for the audience in the business of
sports today,'' said Jose Masso, chief operating officer at
Northeastern University's Center for the Study of Sport in Society,
in Boston. ``They realize the business of sports has changed
drastically over the last 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And that change has meant challenges for diversity experts like
Howard Ross, who makes a living helping others cope with change.
Ross conducted the Braves session with former Chicago Bears
linebacker Mike Singletary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have a mistaken view of diversity training,''
said Ross, a 15-year veteran of the field and president of Cook
Ross. ``They either think it's Mr. Rogers touchy-feely where you
sit around in a circle and sing 'Kumbaya' or it's about beating up
on white guys and telling them they're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume that most people want to do the right thing and that
many are pretty ignorant about how to go about doing that,'' Ross
said Wednesday from a cell phone while watching the Braves play
Kansas City. ``They don't know that they don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that baseball is a team sport, and disharmony
in the locker room could hurt the Braves on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, said Ross, ``have epitomized team work. This is
potentially disruptive to them, so this is why the management of
the team wanted to use it (the diversity program) as an opportunity
to move forward in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
