r s BC-BKC-LANDERS-COX     03-15 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LANDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldog hoping to rid monkey from his back
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keep asking if the albatross around his neck feels heavier, and
he'll deny one exists. Bring up the obvious Buffalo Bills
reference, and Andy Landers shrugs his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Five times the Georgia Lady Bulldogs have reached the Final
Four. Five times they have failed to stand in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Landers is well aware of the goose egg beside his name. No other
women's coach has taken a team to the Final Four as many times and
not brought home a championship trophy. He insists that he never
has dwelled on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely never have. Why should I?'' he asked. ``I'm proud
that we've been there five times. There are probably 310 schools
out there that would like to get there once.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Georgia, which earned its fifth Final Four appearance in a
surprise last season, has every expectation of making it six before
the month is out. The Lady Dogs (29-3) begin their quest Saturday
night against Montana in a first round West Regional game in
Stegeman Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Only Pat Summitt of Tennessee (64) and Louisiana Tech's Leon
Barmore (50) have won more NCAA games than the 28 by Georgia teams
under Landers. They also have national championships to their
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a certain amount of luck to win a national
championship, and Georgia just hasn't gotten that break when they
needed it,'' former Mississippi coach Van Chancellor said.
Chancellor is a friend who never got to the Final Four but who has
won three consecutive WNBA titles with the Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Georgia's first NCAA title game, Teresa Edwards fouled
out for the only time that season with 10 minutes left in the game,
clearing the way for an upset by Old Dominion.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia was favored over Tennessee in the 1996 finals. Right
before tipoff, the Tennessee mascot was taunting a stuffed bulldog
toy when the toy exploded, spewed debris on the court and delayed
the start of the game by 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Landers said the incident did not affect the outcome of the
game, but the Lady Dogs came out tight, and Tennessee coasted to
the first of three NCAA titles in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's up to another generation of Georgia players to get
title for the program, and for Landers. Instead of feeling
pressure, however, he is heartened by suggestions from well-wishers
that just maybe it's his team's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more people pulling for us to win it than
questioning why we haven't done it,'' he said. ``I don't think
there's a lot to feel bad about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
