A8038 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-SPURS-ELLIOT-COX     03-15 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ELLIOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's play two: Elliott says he's in shape
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sean Elliott not only survived his return to the San Antonio
Spurs lineup with a transplanted kidney Tuesday, he felt able to
pass one of the NBA's tests of stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott could have played again Wednesday, had the schedule, and
Coach Gregg Popovich, beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop asked me 'if today was a back-to-back, how would you
feel?''' Elliott said Wednesday. ``I said `fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who underwent the transplant last Aug. 16, said he went
through one of his most grueling workouts Wednesday since returning
to practice on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott played 12 minutes against Atlanta on Tuesday, starting
the game at small forward. He expects to be in the starting lineup
tonight against Dallas. Many expected Popovich to move Elliott back
in as a reserve. But Popovich preferred to start Elliott as a
tribute to him, to avoid disrupting the game by sending him in
during the first quarter, and to reunite the lineup that won the
Spurs' first NBA title last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop doesn't want me coming off bench for bunch of games and
then changing during the playoffs,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who underwent surgery to both knees in recent seasons
and lost strength in his legs while he was away from basketball,
said he felt strong on Tuesday. He was particularly pleased with
the driving dunk he made during the third quarter for his only
basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really explosive,'' Elliott said. ``I don't have any
pain in my knees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs (41-23) have the fourth-best record in the Western
Conference. Despite the dominance of the Lakers, and to a lesser
degree, Portland, Elliott thinks the Spurs can repeat as champions.
Every NBA champion since the Lakers won in 1987 and '88 has
successfully defended its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, I think we have a chance,'' Elliott said. ``I
felt a good chemistry on the court last night. A lot of guys are
quietly confident we can put something together.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who received a kidney from his brother Noel, said he is
not entirely comfortable with all the accolades he has received for
his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are calling me courageous,'' Elliott said. ``But I took
something from my brother. He's the one who made the sacrifice. My
brother was the one who laid himself on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner may be reached at mrosner(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
