<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S WRONGED: THERE ARE NO SAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It has gone from an eight-team NIT undercard to a
64-team pure-American extravaganza commanding attention from
Ketchikan to Key West.
</P>
<P>
   Its championship weekend has acquired a universally accepted,
and widely copied, nickname. That climax has gone from a Thursday
night/Saturday afternoon format in which only the latter was
televised to the point where its key games are shown in prime time
and every game is available on television to someone.
</P>
<P>
   The show that reveals the participants is a big deal. Every
office in the land has a pool. In a society in which special
interest entertainment is the rule, it may be one of the few
remaining avenues of binding national communal discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The latest television contract was worth $6 billion (Yup, that's
a ``b'').
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA men's basketball tournament is now a certified American
ritual. Mention ``March Madness'' and all but the most obtuse
cultural snobs will understand the reference. All this being the
case, one would think there couldn't possibly be anything new to
say about the NCAA tournament. If persistent in that belief, one
would, of course, be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite safe to say there has never been a circumstance
quite like the one facing St. John's University as the Red Storm _
sorry, but that coerced nickname still grates on the ear _ prepare
for their first-round game Thursday night with Northern Arizona at
the University of Arizona's McKale Center. For almost right up to
the moment the referee throws up the ball, coach Mike Jarvis and
the rest of the St. John's party will be looking to see if a fellow
in a suit is standing behind the bench waving some legal document.
</P>
<P>
   How did Erick Barkley get that car? Who helped pay for his
tuition at Maine Central Institute? Were his SAT scores on the
up-and-up? Does he secretly advocate the violent overthrow of the
American government? The St. John's point guard has been
investigated more than Jerry Tarkanian.
</P>
<P>
   And why now? Isn't the time to ask all the questions before the
season starts? Perhaps L'Affaire Barkley is shady, perhaps not. But
who's dropping the dimes to the NCAA, anyway? And if Erick Barkley
is guilty of something, what about half the starters on just about
every team in the top 40? If any player accepted just one extra
T-shirt or said yes to an offer for one ride across campus from an
assistant coach to avoid walking in the rain he has, strictly
speaking, broken an NCAA regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't you outraged?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, someone is out to get St. John's, and you know what
that means, don't you? It means St. John's, a quite legitimate No.
2 seed, has adopted a definite Us vs. The World mentality, and that
means the Red Storm will be highly motivated. Adding spice to the
plot is the fact that recently there has also been within the St.
John's family a curious Us vs. Us corollary _ a strange fistic
encounter last week at the Big East tournament featuring the
aforementioned Mr. Barkley and a very skilled teammate, Bootsie
Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to make sense, therefore, for Coach Jarvis to make
sure noted St. John's alumnus Mario Cuomo is present for the game.
For in addition to his famed legal skills, the ex-governor is known
to be a very spiritual man, a healer of sorts. He might come in
handy, at many levels.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's. the Big East champion, can handle itself on the
court, as can Duke, Stanford, Michigan State, Ohio State, Temple,
Iowa State, Connecticut and, yes, Cincinnati. Do not dismiss
Cincinnati simply because Kenyon Martin, the Player of the Year,
broke his leg in the first round of the Conference USA tournament.
You want to talk Us vs. The World? That's Cincinnati's unofficial
motto, every year. They don't ever care what anyone thinks of its
modus operandi. Coach Bob Huggins still has a variety of weapons,
and no team ever out-toughs Cincinnati. A trip to the Sweet 16
would certainly not be out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Are the above all pure? Define pure. Not getting caught; that's
pure. The competition for, and the care and feeding of, America's
finest young basketball players is a bizarre story that far exceeds
the average American's imaginative capacity. It's the sausage
factory, folks. Don't ask, and we won't tell.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has engaged us all in a giant fairy tale. For example,
the athletes are never, ever, referred to as ``players'' by those
running the tournament. No, no, no. They are the _ are you ready? _
``student-athletes.'' Perhaps. It sounds good, anyway. But if
you're determined to root only for student-athletes, you'd be
better advised to focus the attention on Salem, Va. That's where
the Division 3 tournament is wrapping up. And you can be sure there
are a requisite number of ``eligibility majors'' even at that
relatively innocent level.
</P>
<P>
   That's simply the way it is. Is it exciting? Is the competition
often absolutely top drawer? Are many of the participants exemplary
people, even some of the coaches? Oh, yes, absolutely. But is it
also cutthroat and deadly serious business for those who really
have a chance to win this thing, as well as for the next level of
wannabes who would engage the services of Beelzebub in a heartbeat,
if guaranteed a trip to the Final Four? Affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other American industries, it is what it is. If you
take it, you take it, warts and all. Whoever's after St. John's is
just a sore loser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
