<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD-BEACH16-COX     03-15 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-BEACH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. beach still wading through Floyd damage
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK ISLAND, N.C. _ Mayor Joan Altman walks along the glistening
beach at low tide. It is under water at high, severely eroded by
Hurricane Floyd six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you going to put your towel when you come here?''
said Altman, 47, showing how the surf washes underneath battered
beachfront cottages still awaiting repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Island is the latest of North Carolina's hurricane-wrecked
beaches scrambling to prepare for the return of vacationers who,
along the state's coast, spend an estimated $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   When Floyd roared ashore Sept. 16, it unleashed a 6-foot tidal
surge that washed away four miles of this barrier island's nine
miles of oceanfront dunes. Officials on Oak Island fear damage to
private and public property and losses of property taxes and rental
income will reach $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floyd just whacked us,'' said Dara Royal, 43, who heads the
Oak Island Beach Preservation Society.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Hurricane Hazel in 1954 has Oak Island been so badly
raked. A popular family beach between Wilmington and Myrtle Beach,
this town of 7,000 permanent residents now claims coastal North
Carolina's highest concentration of erosion-threatened structures.
Floyd damaged 430 of the 500 oceanfront buildings, undermining
foundations and unearthing concrete septic tanks. Along North
Carolina's 150 miles of developed shoreline, from this beach town
near the South Carolina line to the Outer Banks bumping against
Virginia, 968 oceanfront buildings are now threatened by erosion,
according to a new survey by the North Carolina Sea Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the destroyed cottages are on Oak Island, along the four
miles of beach that had eroded badly in recent years, before Floyd.
The narrow breadth of sand couldn't stop Floyd's tidal surge. It
washed away the dunes as it surged underneath cottages on the
second row. Altman figures that 60 percent of the damaged beach
houses will be repaired for summer tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Island spent $2 million to push sand into a temporary dune
running just behind the oceanfront cottages. Littered by broken
concrete and shards of metal and wood, the heaped sand is Oak
Island's primary defense against another storm damaging second-row
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very vulnerable,'' said Altman, Oak Island's
mayor for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   She is now president of a new organization that lobbies for
state and federal funds for beach renourishment, the pumping of
sand to rebuild depleted beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is expensive and open to criticism that it does not
stop erosion, making oceanfront development too risky to warrant
spending tax dollars. Altman's group, the North Carolina Shore &AMP;
Beach Preservation Association, argues that it's reasonable to
spend tax dollars to preserve beaches, protecting homes and the
public's access to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either preserve it, or lose it,'' Altman said. ``Oak
Island is the best example I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
