<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HARLEM-RENEWAL-ART-2T     03-15 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-RENEWAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIT AND GLORY IN SOUTH HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT 33-35, are being sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On West 116th Street between Lenox and Seventh
Avenues, a window in the Gabaron Barber Shop advertises services in
French. A few doors away, a young man in the burgundy-colored robes
of West Africa calls home from a long-distance phone center,
speaking in a gentle French patois.
</P>
<P>
   On the brick and brownstone plain of south-central Harlem,
thousands of new arrivals are putting down roots: black and white,
richer and poorer. In their robes and headdresses, especially on
holy days, West African Muslims may be the most recognizable. The
word has gone out: This neighborhood has cheap rents and many
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you have the Chinese in Chinatown,'' said Maimouna
Ndiaye, a Mali immigrant who saved the money she earned cooking
African food in her apartment for homesick compatriots and bought a
coffee shop on West 116th Street. ``We would like to make this
Africatown.''
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks away, Tony Morgan, an Australian-born graphic
designer, is savoring his version of the American Dream. Morgan,
28, sold his Greenwich Village co-op and bought a four-story
brownstone on West 118th Street for $237,000. ``My friends couldn't
believe it when I moved to Harlem,'' he said, laughing. ``But then
they came here, and saw what I had!''
</P>
<P>
   He restored the wainscoting, pocket doors and built-in cabinets
_ and loves to hear that his house might be worth more than
$600,000. But Morgan, who moved in last November, said he is not
selling. From the elegant window in his back parlor, he can see a
town house development rising, and beyond that, the dome of a
mosque, the Masjid Malcolm Shabazz. His favorite sound is the bells
that ring five times a day, calling Muslims to worship.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the retail turnaround of 125th Street, the Main
Street of Harlem, with its glossy mall, its new Old Navy and corner
Starbucks. This is a modest renaissance that encompasses renovated
brownstones, storefront restaurants and new church- and
mosque-sponsored condominiums. Once nearly destroyed by drugs,
crime and debilitation, the square mile bordered by West 110th
Street and West 124th Street, Morningside and Lenox Avenues, is on
the way up.
</P>
<P>
   People like Morgan are helping to make the area a residential
neighborhood again. But many community leaders credit the West
Africans who have settled around West 116th Street with making it a
community once more.
</P>
<P>
   At Joe Pep Dry Cleaners on 116th Street, where West Africans
take their ceremonial robes before Friday services at the mosque,
the owners are jubilant. Four years ago, they closed for the
summer. ``We just weren't making it,'' Errol Joseph, an owner,
said, sitting at a sewing machine with a tape measure around his
neck. ``Now, we're doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Kathryn Suggs, a real estate agent on West 145th Street,
said she was afraid to go to the area five years ago; now she sells
brownstones there for as much as half a million dollars. There are
people waiting for any house, no matter how much of a wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe now,'' Suggs said. ``People wouldn't buy in this
part of Harlem until it was safe.'' She said would-be buyers _ who,
increasingly, are of all nationalities and races _ worry that they
have missed the market. Prices of restored brownstones rose an
average of 25 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The houses are going to men and women who have moved from
neighborhoods like TriBeCa and the Upper West Side. Many are
African-Americans (and a substantial number of mixed-race couples)
who say they seek to discover their roots _ or simply feel
comfortable uptown.
</P>
<P>
   There are also hundreds of lower-income applicants lined up to
rent or buy apartments in fixed-up brownstones and in apartment
complexes just rising, many sponsored by the area's religious
institutions. Renaissance Plaza, a 240-unit subsidized co-op on
Lenox Avenue at 116th Street, has an occupancy date of January 2001
_ and a waiting list of 500, among them Timothy Hopewell, a
newlywed who now lives in the Bronx. Hopewell grew up on West 118th
Street. ``It's kind of nostalgic,'' he said. ``It's kind of a dream
to go back there and live.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramona Smith, whose rental management company controls 600
apartments and 18 storefronts in this area, said West Africans
constituted 60 percent of her tenants. In New York City, the number
of sub-Saharan immigrants, most of them West African, almost
doubled from 1990 to 1996, from 44,000 to 84,000, said Andrew
Beveridge, a professor at Queens College who specializes in
demographics. The exact figure is unclear, and city officials say
new immigrants are reluctant to participate in the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are illegal or do not have their green cards, so
they are afraid,'' said Councilman Bill Perkins, who represents the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from interviews with dozens of West Africans and their
landlords, most of the men and women who have come here have
bettered their living conditions in the last five years. Many
newcomers from Senegal, Guinea, Gambia, Mauritania, Nigeria, Ghana,
Mali and the Ivory Coast have left single room occupancy hotels for
studio apartments that rent for $500 to $600 (sometimes with a
bathroom down the hall). The prosperous have moved to one- or
two-bedroom rentals.
</P>
<P>
   West Africans say the language barrier is their greatest
drawback. Fofana Souleymane, a livery driver and aspiring musician
known as King Up Tereby, complained that the social services
agencies do not regularly employ French-speaking translators. On a
morning last week, one French-speaking woman, distressed at the
prospect of hailing a cab, sought someone who spoke her language.
She went into Ndiaye's coffee shop, Farafina's, which car service
drivers frequent for cafe au lait and goat stew. She was quickly
promised a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Ndiaye, who speaks English, came to the United States eight
years ago. ``A lot of African men could not find African food to
eat, so I stayed here,'' she said. ``At first, I cooked for them in
my apartment and they gave me money to cook.''
</P>
<P>
   After six years, she started Farafina's with $5,000. Like many
other African immigrants, she lives with relatives: a cousin and
his wife, on West 112th Street. She pays $1,300 a month rent for
her small coffee shop. She pays another $250 a month for the
espresso and cafe au lait machine. Someday, she wants to move the
kitchen to the back room and put in proper tables and chairs. ``But
no matter how hard I try to save, all my money goes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The West Africans in Harlem are praised by city officials and
local religious leaders for their industriousness and their piety,
but they have been criticized by some older black residents for
what immigrants have always been criticized for: a perceived
unwillingness to adapt to American ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all group together and you don't know what they're
talking about,'' said Charlie Saunders, 52, a construction union
official who has lived in this area all his life and is perplexed
by some of the newcomers' habits. ``That makes a division. I'm not
saying it's wrong, but it segregates them.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Alfonse Jean, 40, a taxi driver, is still puzzling
over New York standard baksheesh. ``Sometimes before you get the
apartment, you are supposed to give a `tip' for the super _ like
$2,000,'' he explained. ``That is everywhere here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Perkins, the councilman, contends there is ``no
significant amount of misunderstanding or bad blood'' between the
longtime African-American residents and the newcomers. But he does
acknowledge some tensions. ``These differences require
sensitivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Some West Africans have dumped used cooking oil in the street; a
few have tossed trash from commercial buildings and have
double-parked livery cars. In turn, African children are taunted
for their differences.
</P>
<P>
   But things are changing. One example: the Canaan Baptist Church
is sponsoring French classes to help members of the congregation
converse with their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors east, at a mosque, the Masjid Malcolm Shabazz, its
leader, Imam Izak-el M. Pasha, is also looking for solutions. His
mosque will soon buy a garbage truck and start charging merchants a
fee to pick up their trash.``It's probably just clashing
cultures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   South-central Harlem has always been a neighborhood full of
contradictions _ and nationalities struggling to coexist.
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War, horses of millionaires raced along what is
now St. Nicholas Avenue and august visitors _ including Ulysses S.
Grant _ cheered. By the turn of the century, most of the
brownstones had been built, along with Graham Court, one of the
grandest rental buildings in New York, an Italian Renaissance
palazzo commissioned by William Waldorf Astor in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say that a 1900 West Side melee between blacks and
police, and the completion of the Lenox Avenue portion of the IRT
in 1904, inspired a black real estate agent, Philip A. Payton, to
urge blacks to move uptown from Hell's Kitchen. Payton formed the
African-American Realty Co.; a rival, the Anglo-Saxon Realty Co.,
quickly formed to combat the trend, Sorin said. To no avail: white
flight increased.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1910, rural blacks from the South streamed into central
Harlem just as the famous Harlem Renaissance started to soar.
Experts agree that the Great Depression killed the renaissance.
Black World War II veterans returned to find bias, along with a
dearth of jobs and services.
</P>
<P>
   But West 116th Street kept going. ``In the '50s, we had three or
four movie theaters on 116th Street alone,'' said Saunders, the
construction official, who lives on Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
Boulevard at West 117th Street. ``We had shoe stores, restaurants,
supermarkets, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came drugs. And Vietnam, which Saunders said took away the
best of the neighborhood's youth. Many landlords left their
buildings to rot; rent strikes followed. In 1968, a headline in The
Amsterdam News warned, ``Thugs, Addicts Take Over: Terror Reigns on
116th Street.'' By the 1980s, New York City was the area's biggest
landlord.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wyatt Tee Walker arrived at the Canaan Baptist Church
33 years ago. ``The federal government had just declared that this
area had the lowest level of services of any in the country,'' said
Walker, former chief of staff to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, 62 percent of his congregation lived in the
surrounding neighborhood. In five years, that number had dropped to
32 percent. Soon, the churches of Harlem were taking on the job of
building apartment houses and rehabilitating old ones. When the
current imam arrived at the Masjid Malcolm Shabazz arrived in 1993,
the mosque, too, got into the construction business.
</P>
<P>
   June Broxton, a secretary, is buying a new $300,000 three-family
house in Shabazz Gardens, a 41 town-house development co-sponsored
by the mosque. She will use the rents to pay her subsidized
mortgage. ``When I first heard about the area, it was stereotyped
as a bad place,'' Broxton, 36, said. ``But when I visited there, I
realized it was nice, the kind of place where people on the street
said, `Good morning' and `Good afternoon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Councilman Perkins worries that some of the wealthier people
are buying brownstones for speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Suggs agrees, recounting a recent case of one man who made
$150,000 in a year by ``flipping'' an unrenovated brownstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not poor,'' Perkins said. ``They're not
coming to Harlem to live the American Dream.'' He paused. ``They're
just moving uptown.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the new homeowners will have less of an impact than
the West Africans. ``The West Africans come here not only to live
but to run their businesses and build their churches,'' he said.
``That usually suggests they'll be here for a while, as opposed to
the interloper or the transient or the speculator.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. John P. Quinn of the 28th Precinct, whose territory
encompasses south-central Harlem, is optimistic. The crime rate has
dropped 50 percent in five years, according to police statistics,
which is significantly better than the city average. ``Things
aren't perfect,'' he said, ``but it's looking real good right
now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Fridays, Fadel Gueye, a butcher, and his wife, Dieynaba Agne
Gueye, exchange their jeans for the traditional long robes of
Senegal to attend services at the mosque near their apartment on
West 116th Street. Gueye moved to Harlem 15 years ago, a single man
living in one of the SROs. He said he was ``the first African on
116th Street'' and he may be right. ``When I came here, there were
maybe two stores _ nothing _ the rest were boarded up,'' he said.
``We built this community.''
</P>
<P>
   They rent a spacious sixth-floor walk-up that bears the traces
of an 1980s renovation: the walls are of Sheetrock and the window
trim is plain, but the living room windows are covered with
glittering cerise draperies. During the day, Gueye, who now owns a
butcher shop on 116th Street, is often found at the slaughterhouse.
When he meets suppliers, he dresses like a film director, with a
camel-color coat and slim-wrap sunglasses. He sometimes dreams of
Senegal but he has not been back, even to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must give my children an opportunity here,'' he said. ``Not
only me, but the West Africans who live here are very hard working.
They are making it from zero.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
