<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-ELECT-NY     03-15 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN CANDIDATES FIND CAMPAIGN FODDER IN BEIJING THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CHINA-TAIWAN and CHINA-TAIWAN-BUSINESS)  
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Presidential candidates here tried Wednesday to
gain a political advantage from China's belligerent warnings
against talk of the island's independence.
</P>
<P>
   And President Lee Teng-hui spent Wednesday trying to dispel
rumors that he secretly supports the opposition candidate over his
chosen successor in a campaign that has been filled with planted
rumors and unsubstantiated charges from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   The election, on Saturday, is essentially a tight contest among
the three leading candidates: Vice President Lien Chan, the
candidate of the ruling Nationalists, or Kuomintang; Chen
Shui-bian, whose Democratic Progressive Party is closely associated
with the cause of independence; and James Soong, a popular
politician whose breakaway candidacy has split the Nationalist
majority.
</P>
<P>
   In danger of losing their power, the Nationalists have resorted
to scare tactics. Lee, although reviled in China for his own
assertion of Taiwan's statehood, has joined Lien in warning that
Chen's election could provoke China to war.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night a spokeswoman for Chen's campaign tried to turn
the tables on the Nationalists for what Chen calls ``terror
tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We find it regrettable that the mainland is using such threats
to try and influence our election,'' said Bikhim Hsiao, director of
international affairs for the Democratic Progressive Party. ``And I
think it hurts the feelings of the Taiwanese people to have the KMT
echoing the statements from Beijing,'' she added, using the
initials for the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a former mayor of Taipei, has made some far-fetched
accusations of his own. When Taiwan's stock market plummeted
Monday, supposedly on fears of a Nationalist loss, he immediately
charged that the government had manipulated the market. While no
evidence has been offered, many voters here are prepared to believe
it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chen found few takers for his charge, made at a rally
Tuesday night, that the Nationalists had sent an emissary to
Beijing to ask it to hold military exercises near Taiwan to scare
voters away from him.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, several prominent scholars and businessmen who
are supposedly friends of Lee said they were supporting Chen. In
that atmosphere, the perennial rumor that Lee is a closet supporter
of the independence-leaning opposition gained new currency.
</P>
<P>
   For different reasons, both the Chen and Soong camps find this
to be a helpful rumor, and they miss few opportunities to spread
it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two days, Lee has urged voters to stick by Lien.
But Lien is widely regarded as the most lackluster of the three
contenders and is struggling to get out from Lee's shadow while
holding on to his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more votes Lien gets, the more secure our country will
be,'' Lee said Wednesday, wearing the white golf jacket of the Lien
campaign at an unusual news briefing just before the weekly meeting
of the all-powerful Nationalist Party standing committee.
</P>
<P>
   Published polls are banned in the 10 days before the election.
In earlier surveys, the three top candidates were virtually tied,
but at least a quarter of the electorate said it was undecided, and
no one is sure where trends are headed, although the campaigns
selectively leak secret surveys. All sides are making the most of
the polling vacuum, with each claiming a groundswell.
</P>
<P>
   Soong has urged Nationalist supporters to reject Lien, who he
says is losing ground, to prevent a victory by Chen. Lien has urged
just the opposite, a movement to dump the supposedly faltering
Soong.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to counter Chen's impressive
endorsements, the Nationalists have released a list of 100
prominent citizens who would form an advisory group to Lien if he
is elected _ not mentioning that a few of those listed have
publicly endorsed the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, the Nationalists released a statement in support
of Lien signed in New York by the 103-year-old widow of Chiang
Kai-shek, Soong Mayling, better known as Madame Chiang. Many of the
mainland-born Nationalists who fled to Taiwan in 1949 with Chiang
have never been happy with Lee, who was born on the island and
ended the mainlanders' grip on the party. They are switching from
his candidate, Lien, in favor of Soong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could such an old lady really sign her name so clearly?''
asked 83-year-old Chu Zhichung, a onetime resident of Yunnan in
southwest China who fought with the Nationalist army against the
Japanese and the Communists, as he waited for a prescription at the
huge Veterans General Hospital in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   But these old soldiers dislike Chen and his party almost
universally and are appalled at their appeal among the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people don't understand the danger of seeking
independence,'' Chu said. ``They've never known the horrors of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen Shui-bian is a liar without any credibility when he says
he has changed his mind on this,'' he added. Chen has said that if
elected, he would not push for formal independence because Taiwan
already enjoys it in practice, and he says he could make piece with
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, a senior senator and campaign official of
the Democratic Progressives tried to play down the threat of a
Chinese attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chen wins, China will accept it and slowly adapt to the
situation,'' said the legislator, Shen Fu-hsiung. ``They'll learn
that he is not as rigid as they thought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
