<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW REGISTERS BIGGEST GAIN IN 17 MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a reversal of fortune, blue-chip stocks recorded
their biggest gain in 17 months Wednesday, while the
technology-dominated Nasdaq market slumped.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stocks that have been so beloved by investors as the
engines of the new economy have in three days lost a stunning 9.2
percent, just short of what Wall Street considers a correction.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, investors piled instead into financial, drug and
other high-quality stocks that have been old economy laggards. They
drove the Dow Jones industrial average up 320.17 points, or 3.3
percent, to 10,131.41, paring its loss so far this year to 11.9
percent. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 33 points,
or 2.4 percent, to 1,392.15, narrowing its loss for the year to
5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money, stock analysts said, came from sales of
Nasdaq stocks. The Nasdaq composite index skidded 124.01 points, or
2.6 percent, to 4,582.62 just three days after hitting a record
5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things are going on,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief
market strategist at A.G. Edwards in St. Louis. ``You're getting
some bottom-fishing for the really strong values that had developed
and some long overdue profit-taking in the new economy stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping to lead Wednesday's heavy stock trading was a report on
industrial output last month that some took as a sign the economy's
breakneck expansion might finally be slowing. If the members of the
Federal Reserve board believe this is happening _ and the
production figures are compiled by the central bank _ it reduces
the chance of several increases in interest rates and could rule
out a jump of more than one-quarter point at next Tuesday's policy
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the slide in Nasdaq stocks is viewed as a force for
economic restraint since rapid gains in them have contributed to
consumers' feelings of wealth and their willingness to spend. ``I
think it's the healthiest type of action you could hope for,'' said
Charles J. Pradilla, chief strategist at SG Cowen Securities,
referring to the realignment of values. ``It's the sort of stuff
Greenspan loves to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has often observed in recent
months how expensive some stocks have become in relation to their
demonstrated earning power and how stock-market profits have helped
sustain the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is starting to flow into companies with improving
earnings and more compelling valuations,'' added Robert M.
Balentine, an investment counselor in Atlanta. ``You can't have
such a bifurcated market continue to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's 3.3 percent gain in the Dow while the Nasdaq fell
2.6 percent was the biggest divergence Balentine, a market veteran,
said he could remember. The only other session in which the Nasdaq
dropped more than 2 percent while the blue-chip average jumped more
than 3 percent was the day after the Oct. 19, 1987, crash. And
never before this week has the Nasdaq lost triple-digit points for
three consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goldman said that while the market was becoming less
unbalanced, high-tech would continue to shine. ``I don't think this
is a sea change,'' he said. ``People aren't selling the Internet
and buying a bank.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jeff Rubin, research director at Birinyi Associates, agreed,
calling the recent action ``your standard, run-of-the-mill Nasdaq
correction, which we have every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology stocks, slammed on Tuesday after President Clinton
and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain said genome research
should be made freely available to all, recovered part of their
losses after investors realized that this did not mean that gene
sequences could not be patented. But the speed with which billions
of dollars of value had evaporated on this development kept a pall
over the sector and spread into other Nasdaq sectors as well,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen, which lost 5 3/4 Tuesday, jumped 6\ Wednesday, to 58{,
but Millennium Pharmaceuticals shed another 4 3/16, to 171 13/16,
after plunging 59{ Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric and J.P. Morgan each soared more than 6 points
to pace the Dow industrials, 27 of whose 30 components advanced, 23
of them by at least a point. Hewlett-Packard was a big loser for a
second straight day, sliding 9[ to 130~.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly all pharmaceutical stocks were huge gainers _
Warner-Lambert, Eli Lilly and American Home Products were up more
than 5 points each. Schering-Plough and Merck were up 3 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Among the financials, Chase Manhattan, SunTrust Banks, Wells
Fargo, State Street and American Express all gained more than 4
points and First Union, which has been down sharply, jumped 2~, to
35~.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 1.3 billion shares changed
hands, making it the third busiest day on record, with 1,909 issues
advancing compared with 1,130 that declined, much better breadth
than has prevailed in most recent sessions. New 52-week lows
outnumbered new highs by 140 to 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
