<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8072 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VIRGIL-THOMSON-MUSIC-     03-15 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIL-THOMSON-MUSIC-ART-3TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT OPERA, DISCOMBOBULATING IN ITS SIMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCHH 19)  
 (af)  
 (Eds: Anthony Tommasini, a music critic of The New York Times, is
the author of ``Virgil Thomson: Composer on the Aisle.'')  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1947, the composer Virgil Thomson, then the
powerful chief music critic of The New York Herald Tribune,
received an inquiry from a young man, a fledgling culture critic,
that really ticked him off. The writer, seeking feedback, had sent
Thomson an excerpt from a feature piece he was preparing for
Harper's Bazaar on ``The Mother of Us All,'' Thomson's opera to a
text of Gertrude Stein, which was about to receive its premiere at
Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not too happy at seeing my score called whimsical,''
Thomson wrote back. ``Also, I think the idea that Stein and I are
primarily wits is, if you will permit me, both antiquated and
inaccurate. I should appreciate it if you could refer to `The
Mother of Us All' _ both the words and the music _ as a serious
work on a serious theme.'' That theme, of course, is women's
suffrage, and the title character is Susan B. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to sabotage the article, Thomson ended his letter
tactfully: ``I am sorry to be so critical, because I know you spent
a great deal of thought on the paragraph which you sent me. But
since you have asked for my cooperation, I should be most grateful,
and so would Stein if she were living, for some word that would not
place us quite so definitely with the amusers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Thomson, who died in 1989 at 92, many who have
enjoyed the opera would agree with the young writer that it is
whimsical. How could they not? On first impression, Stein's text is
delightfully wacky, and Thomson's score seems a crazy quilt of hymn
tunes, parlor songs, bugle calls, ditties and stretches of what
Thomson called his Missouri plainchant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to a devoted core of admirers, including this critic, ``The
Mother of Us All,'' which comes to the New York City Opera this
Sunday afternoon in a new production by Christopher Alden first
unveiled at the Glimmerglass Opera in 1998, is the most original
and arguably the greatest of American operas.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1984 article in The New Yorker, Andrew Porter, an
infuential critic and opera scholar not known for a casual use of
superlatives, stated that every time he heard ``The Mother of Us
All'' he was ``tempted to consider it the best of all American
operas'' and, on calm reflection, would ``hardly modify that beyond
`one of the three best.'''
</P>
<P>
   True, other critics over the years have dismissed, even reviled
Thomson's two operas on Stein texts. (``Four Saints in Three Acts''
was the first, in 1928.) At worst, one would think, the operas are
harmless novelties. How can they elicit such vehemently negative
reactions?
</P>
<P>
   What typically arouses critics is the unabashed simplicity of
Thomson's style. The 20th century, especially in its early decades,
was characterized by radical innovation in music. Tonal harmony had
been explored, expanded and chromatically thickened, many composers
felt, to the point of inertia. Daring new atonal and 12-tone
musical languages emerged, along with complex rhythmic writing that
shattered regular meter and multilayered musical textures.
</P>
<P>
   Intellectual opinion during the 20th century, driven by
composers themselves, placed a premium on complexity and
methodological rigor in contemporary music. Even works thought to
be excessively complex failures were at least granted intellectual
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Decades before it became fashionable to do so, Thomson bucked
the trend by writing simply, with tonal harmonies, sometimes spiked
with polychords or dissonance, and lucid textures; a master of
prosody, he set words to music so that they were vividly clear. Yet
he tried to write simply in a way that was radical: a kind of
discombobulating simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it doesn't work, a Thomson piece just sounds
simplistic. When it works, though, Thomson's simplicities seem
fresh and startling. And in none of his compositions did this
radical simplicity work more successfully than in ``The Mother of
Us All.''
</P>
<P>
   While a student of Nadia Boulanger in Paris during the
mid-1920s, Thomson kept abreast of emerging modernist techniques.
In 1926, he composed his raucous ``Sonata da Chiesa,'' impishly
scored for five disparate instruments: clarinet in E flat, trumpet,
viola, horn and trombone. He called it his ``bang-up graduation
piece in the dissonant neo-Baroque style of the period.''
</P>
<P>
   But he felt that the penchant for complexity and ``100 percent
dissonance saturation,'' as he put it, was quickly becoming stale.
So, taking inspiration from his idol Erik Satie, the champion of
inconsequence, he boldly started to compose as things came into his
head.
</P>
<P>
   He simplified his style and drew freely from the music of his
youth in Kansas City, Mo.: Baptist hymns, parlor songs, the band
concerts he attended in the park, his older cousin Cecil's banjo
playing. He also tapped the well of medieval and Renaissance vocal
music he sang as a member of the Harvard Glee Club, which was
directed for years by the pioneering early-music scholar Archibald
T. Davidson. Kansas City and Harvard met stylistically in Thomson's
landmark ``Symphony on a Hymn Tune'' of 1928, a work that
emboldened Aaron Copland to simplify his own style.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's true declaration of independence from dissonant
complexity came just two months after his ``Sonata da Chiesa'' in
1926 with his first setting of a text by Stein. Thomson had
devoured Stein's works in college and longed to meet her. He
finally did, in Paris in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Gratified by his appreciation of her work, the imposing American
expatriate writer welcomed Thomson into her circle. Even Stein's
jealously protective companion, Alice B. Toklas, was eventually won
over. The bond was sealed one day when the women found, left at
their door, the score to Thomson's setting of Stein's poem ``Susie
Asado.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The hermetic text would seem to be a portrait of a gracious
hostess, Susie Asado. The first lines read as follows. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet sweet sweet sweet sweet tea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susie Asado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet sweet sweet sweet sweet tea.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Asado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susie Asado which is a told tray sure. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once one gets immersed in Stein, it is possible to find hints of
meaning in the words and the wordplay. Asado apparently serves very
sweet tea at her gatherings, but she is also a ``sweet tea''
(sweetie) and a ``tray sure'' (treasure). Moreover, she is a
``told'' treasure, meaning, perhaps, that everyone speaks of her
graciousness and sweet tea.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson was fascinated not by the possible meaning in the text
but by the lack of it. In vocal works, clear expression mattered
intensely to him, but not clear meaning. ``My theory was that if a
text was set correctly for the sound of it, the meaning will take
care of itself,'' he wrote in his autobiography in 1966. ``And the
Stein texts, for prosodizing in this way, were manna.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson treats Stein's words here with utter seriousness. The
vocal line carefully mimics the natural rhythm and flow of the
language; the piano part is spare: just eerie ascending scales in
parallel sevenths and ninths, and plain chords of open fifths. It's
simple yet stunning. This two-minute work was published by Cos Cob
Press in 1935 in a volume of 10 songs by a roster of emerging
American composers, among them Copland, Roger Sessions, Paul
Bowles, Israel Citkowitz and Marc Blitzstein. Today nothing in that
collection seems more radical than ``Susie Asado.''
</P>
<P>
   The libretto for ``Four Saints in Three Acts'' was the first
text Stein wrote specifically for Thomson to set. Finished in 1928,
the opera was not produced until 1934, by which time the creators
had weathered more than three years of a bitter breakup in their
friendship. The necessity of cooperating so that the premiere
production at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford could go forward
forced them to patch up the rift.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is hard to tell from Stein's obscure yet somehow
incantatory text, the opera is a community portrait of 16th-century
Spanish saints, some based on historical figures (Teresa of Avila
and Ignatius of Loyola) but most of them made up. Thomson set the
text despite having no idea what was supposed to be happening in
the opera.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, the painter Maurice Grosser, the closest Thomson had
in his life to a longtime companion, played a critical role by
devising a workable scenario for the dramatically abstract work:
the action would depict the daily rituals of worship, work and
pleasantry among the saints.
</P>
<P>
   The opera made history for its landmark premiere production,
which moved from Hartford to Broadway, where it ran for six weeks.
Thomson daringly cast the work entirely with black singers
recruited in Harlem. Florine Stettheimer created her famous sets
and costumes of cellophane and tulle. Frederick Ashton served as
choreographer and director; John Houseman was the creative
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Many aficionados consider ``Four Saints'' the purer of the two
Thomson-Stein operas. Porter has written lovingly of its
``simplicity, directness, candor, seriousness of utterance.'' A
sensitive production, he added, should leave an audience ``rapt in
a wonderful vision of holiness, rendered _ not without jokes, not
without wit _ in transfigured American speech and transfigured
American song.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the reaction to the work among nonmusicians (poets,
painters, dancers) was ecstatic, the opinions of musicians varied
wildly. The brainy, formidable Sessions hated it. During the New
York run, when the composer Theodore Chanler, who was writing about
the opera for the journal Modern Music, expressed enthusiasm after
a performance, Sessions blew up at him.
</P>
<P>
   He ``pulverized me with scorn and indignation at having dared to
like it,'' Chanler later wrote to Thomson. The young composer was
so intimidated that he reviewed the opera quite negatively, turning
Thomson against him until the truth came out, years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Saints,'' innocent though it may seem, can still arouse
Sessions-like vitriol. ``The Mother of Us All'' has never been as
controversial and has thrived for years in smaller companies and
colleges. The City Opera production, the company's first, features
the dynamic soprano Lauren Flanigan in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   Though the opera's theme is women's suffrage, in a larger sense
it is a homage to 19th-century American political rhetoric. During
that era the lifeblood of the nation was captured in grandiloquent
orations rich with metaphors, classical allusions and quotes from
Shakespeare. Ordinary citizens routinely traveled great distances
to hear politicians speak and debate. Today, when ``I'm a uniter,
not a divider'' and similar banalities pass for presidential
campaign discourse, it is hard to understand how exciting political
oratory once was.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An early scene in the opera presents a great debate between two
historical figures who of course never actually met: Susan B.
Anthony and Daniel Webster. Stein weaves bits of speeches from the
era into this exchange of non sequiturs. ``Youth is young, I am not
old,'' Susan B. sings in stately, calm music; to which the
imperious Webster replies with grandiose lyricism, ``When the
mariner has been tossed for many days in thick weather, and on an
unknown sea, he naturally avails himself of the first pause in the
storm.'' Certainly, it's funny; but as set by Thomson, with verbal
crispness and mock grandeur, this nonsensical debate seems
genuinely stirring.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is filled with historical figures from different times
who confide in and bicker with each other, like President Andrew
Johnson, the actress Lillian Russell and a gruff, impatient Ulysses
S. Grant, who sings of himself, to a sort of bugle-call motif, ``He
knew that his name was not Eisenhower.''
</P>
<P>
   Two characters called Gertrude S. and Virgil T. serve as
narrators and comment on the opera as it goes along. Several of
Stein's real friends are characters in it, like Constance Fletcher,
a writer of novels, here portrayed as the romantic interest of John
Adams (presumably John Quincy Adams).
</P>
<P>
   Their slightly daffy love scenes are inexplicably touching.
Adams is constrained by his high position from actually doing
anything. ``Dear Constance Fletcher,'' he sings in his first,
gently melodic entreaty, ``it is a great pleasure that I kneel at
your feet.'' In the next breath, he sputters several phrases with
clipped rhythmic insistence: ``But I am an Adams, I kneel at the
feet of none, not anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he returns to his former sweetly lyrical vein. Soon, the
perplexed chorus, singing in emphatic, grim block chords, repeats
the sad facts of the scene just witnessed: ``If he had not been an
Adams, he would have kneeled at her feet.'' And so on. Thomson's
music pokes gentle fun at the heritage of tenor and soprano
operatic love duets yet rescues it from hackneyed sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   The constant verbal and musical interplay makes every moment of
the score, however simple on the surface, surprising. ``The Mother
of Us All'' invites you to listen to words for ``sound and syntax
only,'' as Thomson wrote. For once, you may disengage the part of
your brain that craves cogency and meaning.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the opera does have meaning. Through most of it, we are
exhilarated by Stein's jumbled history lesson and disorienting
language, and by Thomson's patchwork score. Then, in the final
scene, the spirit of the deceased Susan B. appears to sing what is
in effect her own elegy, ``All my long life.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally the music is not radically simple but straightforwardly
simple: a wistful melody, hymn-tune harmonies, the strains of a
church harmonium. Is even Wotan's sublime final scene in ``Die
Walkure'' more profound?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mother of Us All'' was Stein's last completed text. She
died during an operation for cancer on July 27, 1946, before
Thomson had written a note of the score. The premiere at Columbia
University, conducted by the composer Otto Luening, attracted many
major musicians of the day and was critically hailed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson lived to see the day when an emerging generation of
postmodern composers saw him as a prophet before his time, who had
made straight the paths for a return to simplicity, accessibility
and the use of vernacular sources. Though such acknowledgment was
gratifying, to the end of his life Thomson yearned for respect as a
serious innovator.
</P>
<P>
   He was not against complexity as rendered by the master
composers of the day, just the puffed-up kind of complexity so
often produced by their imitators. A vibrant musical culture should
be able to celebrate Messiaen's ``St. Francois d'Assise'' as well
as Thomson's ``Four Saints in Three Acts.''
</P>
<P>
   In words that could be applied to himself, Thomson once
described Satie's aesthetic as having valued ``consequence,
quietude, precision, acuteness of auditory observation, gentleness,
sincerity and directness of statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The words apply especially to ``The Mother of Us All.'' Just
don't call it whimsical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
