<HEADER>
A8075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-15 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OUT WEST, A TOUGH ACT TO FOLLOW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only one play, one highlight, but did you happen to catch
the dunk Tuesday night? Did you see Sean Elliott come down the lane
and finish with a flourish?
</P>
<P>
   That didn't look much look like the so-called soft player that
too many people, yours truly included, for so long believed Elliott
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before Elliott left the championship stage for a
hospital bed, before he accepted his brother's kidney and vowed to
play again for San Antonio, there was a day at a Knicks' practice
last June when the subject of Elliott's ``toughness'' was broached
with Don Chaney.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' assistant coach had presided over the
post-championship Detroit Pistons, the Bad Boys turned plain bad,
and was asked if he thought the Knicks might have a bully's edge
for the coming NBA finals over Elliott at small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had physical problems when he was with us in Detroit,''
Chaney said. ``But then there was the question about whether he was
more of a West Coast player.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Chaney smiled knowingly and said, ``We'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Elliott's one season in Detroit, 1993-94, was about the
time he learned that he had focal segmental glomerular sclerosis, a
disease that prevents the kidneys from properly filtering waste
from the blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team doctors were saying that he had five years before
kidney failure,'' Matt Dobek, the Pistons' longtime vice president
of public relations, said Wednesday. ``They were alarmed, worried
about the guy's life. He wanted to play. We tried to trade him to
Houston but they looked at our reports and backed out. No one
wanted him, only San Antonio, and eventually we sent him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Laimbeer played in 11 games that season, and went home.
Isiah Thomas played in 58 games, tore his Achilles' tendon, and
retired. Allan Houston was a rookie. Acquired in a criticized trade
with the Spurs for Dennis Rodman, Elliott was said to be everything
the Bad Boys were not. He was, in the minds of the holdovers,
another Western Conference wimp, a symbol of a dynasty turned sour,
gone soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact was, we weren't any good,'' Dobek said. ``We had no
big men, no help defense. Sean was heavily medicated, and he had
the worst year of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been an All-Star the previous season, and always an
earnest, quick defender. The shallow labels we pin on individual
players in team situations are never easy to shake, though. Dan
Marino, who never had a running game to support his throwing,
retired this week and most testimonials ended with ``but he never
won the Super Bowl.'' By contrast, John Elway, who at the end of
his career lucked into Terrell Davis, is in the dot.com legends'
business with Gretzky and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott didn't have a great series against the Knicks, but it
looked a lot better when we found out that he had averaged 36
minutes and eight points with failing kidneys. Not without some
shame, I can recall Elliott getting a step on the defender in the
dying seconds of Game 5, the Spurs down a point. Soft player, I
thought. He will not take it hard to the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, of course, didn't have to, finding Avery Johnson on the
left baseline for what became the title-clinching jumper. More than
eight months and the kidney transplant later, he was challenging
Dikembe Mutombo and landing on his backside. But in the second half
came another chance to beat his man off the dribble. This time, he
took it to the rim and made his point with a power slam.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he said Wednesday, he was playing for something
greater, ``for people who are going through what I went through or
are just going through adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA managed to undersell the best story it had in this
season of the viewers' discontent. Greg Hughes of Turner Network
Television said the national telecast, Houston at Knicks, featured
cutaways to San Antonio and a pregame feature, but, as far as he
knew, the NBA did not ask the network to switch games.
</P>
<P>
   Here it had a returning member of the defending champions and
the first player to ever to play with a kidney transplant. It had
the donor, Noel Elliott, walking out in the Alamodome to a standing
ovation. The country settled for Jeff Van Gundy allowing the boom
mike into the Knicks' team huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is fine. Humanity is grand. Sean Elliott, a modern
medical miracle, said he was a ``bundle of nerves'' warming up
Tuesday night. But he went, as they say, strong to the hole, and
proved, once and for all, he is as East Coast as they come.
</P>
</TEXT>
