<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-SUBPRIME-LENDING-A     03-15 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBPRIME-LENDING-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE TO CRACK DOWN ON UNSCRUPULOUS LENDING TO HOMEOWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Calif., Ill., Md., Minn., Mo., S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Regulators in New York state, the nation's largest
banking center and an industry pace setter, are devising new rules
to crack down on predatory lenders who impose exorbitant fees that
force countless homeowners into foreclosure and bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The abuses at issue are the underbelly of the lucrative $280
billion national market in so-called subprime loans that serve
borrowers with limited credit ratings. Although such loans charge
higher interest rates, they have been a godsend to many people who
otherwise might not get financing.
</P>
<P>
   But some unscrupulous operators seek out unsophisticated
clients, typically elderly or minority homeowners or first-time
buyers in poor areas. They talk the victims into refinancing or
applying for other loans saddled with excessive interest and fees.
The lenders and brokers collect their fees up front. If the
borrower falls in arrears, the mortgage holder seizes the house.
</P>
<P>
   With action on the issue apparently stalled in Congress, the New
York State Banking Board is flexing its powers to license and
oversee mortgage bankers and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who appoints the board, ordered it to take
up the issue last year after an investigation of a major lender,
Delta Funding, by Attorney General Eliot Spitzer. Pataki was stung
by Spitzer's suggestion that his regulators had gone easy on Delta.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The final regulations, which would apply to so-called high-cost
home loans, are expected to win the board's unanimous support in
the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will become a model for similar regulation and
legislation in other states and on a nationwide basis,'' said
Elizabeth McCaul, the acting superintendent of banks and the
board's chairwoman. ``We want to end abusive practices, but we
don't want to inadvertently cut off access to credit in those
communities where we are trying to create more access.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulations would make impose several new standards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defining high-cost loans as those that charge interest more
than eight percentage points above the comparable U.S. Treasury
rate, or up-front fees greater than five points on a loan (a point
is 1 percent of the total loan amount). For second mortgages and
other home loans, the threshold would be nine percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring lenders to consider borrowers' ability to repay and
notify them that impartial credit counseling is available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning negative amortization (in which the principal grows),
balloon payments before seven years and higher-interest penalties
after a default.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting certain fees and points to 5 percent of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting the ``packing'' of certain insurance and other
costs into the loan, the ``flipping'' of loans by refinancing at
excessively higher costs, the charging of bogus fees for services
not rendered and unfair mandatory arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   While McCaul said the proposals had broad support from the
public and the lending industry, consumer groups say the plan does
not go far enough. A joint statement from 70 groups and 12 elected
officials last month said the proposal ``leaves serious and glaring
loopholes what would allow creative lenders and brokers, in too
many instances, to continue their predatory practices as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Those endorsing the statement included the American Association
of Retired Persons; New York Public Interest Research Group;
Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now, known as
Acorn; Harlem Consumer Education Council; and Greater Rochester
Community Reinvestment Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``All eyes are on the New York State Banking Department,'' said
Sarah Ludwig, a leader of a statewide coalition of groups against
predatory lending. ``The whole country is watching. It's a huge
problem, and they've got to get this right. What's clear is they're
not really serious about putting the screws to this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Lending-industry leaders, worried that that a few disreputable
lenders are tainting the rest, say they want the abuses stopped.
But they caution that overly stringent rules would hamper
legitimate lenders and curtail access to loans for people who need
them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one bad actor, it puts a black eye on the entire
industry,'' said Robert S. Lotstein, counsel to the National
Association of Mortgage Brokers, which has 12,000 members. ``We are
certainly against predatory lending, but if we need any additional
safeguards, they should be narrowly tailored so that we don't throw
the baby out with the bath water.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stephen A. O'Connor, director for residential financing for
the Mortgage Bankers Association of America, which has 3,000
members, said: ``New York is a bellwether state. Whatever they do
is often copied or emulated.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other states are also considering action: bills have been filed
this year in the legislatures of California, Illinois, Maryland,
Minnesota, Missouri and South Carolina. The industry warns that a
state-by-state hodgepodge of 50 systems would hinder lenders and
drive up costs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We would much prefer uniformity to a patchwork,'' Lotstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   The subprime lending market exploded after Congress changed the
banking laws in the 1980s in an effort to help the battered savings
and loan industry. The pressure for new regulations stems from a
surge of complaints about loan abuses by a number of lenders. One
high-profile company, First Alliance, a national company with four
offices in New York state, has been under investigation by the
federal Justice Department and regulators in seven states,
including New York.
</P>
<P>
   The only state that has enacted rules against predatory lending
so far is North Carolina, under a law passed last year in a
compromise reached by consumer groups, some industry groups and
government officials. Consumer advocates in New York say that North
Carolina's version is a far stricter and better precedent than the
proposal pending in New York.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, a major banking state, is home to BankAmerica,
First Union and Wachovia. Since the law is still being phased in,
it is too early to judge the effect, although Alan S. Hirsch, a
deputy to Attorney General Michael F. Easley, a leading proponent,
said: `It's very plain to us that all the major lenders can live
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lotstein said, ``We've had clients who have decided it's
just not desirable to do business there anymore, and some have
turned in their licenses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In New York state, consumer groups say, the regulators have
already yielded to industry criticism and have ignored the
revisions they urged.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig said the coalition wants the rules to bar common devices
like the financing of all points and fees, penalties for paying off
a loan early, the financing of insurance charges paid years in
advance, all balloon payments and all mandatory arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The critics also say that the regulations should require
stricter review of a borrower's ability to repay and put greater
limits on the frequency of refinancing and on the use of so-called
discount points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed regulations simply overlook too many victims of
predatory lending,'' said an Acorn member, Gloria Waldron of East
New York, Brooklyn. ``Almost no cases we've seen would even fall
under their definition of high-cost loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Abuses take many forms, beginning with deceptive advertising of
``free money'' and high-pressure sales pitches. In Brooklyn,
unethical brokers comb through court records to find homeowners
already facing foreclosure. The brokers talk the owners into new
loans that save their homes temporarily but sink them deeper into
debt as the operators strip out the remaining equity to pay their
excessive fees.
</P>
<P>
   Some lenders have even preyed on homeowners who have been
declared mentally incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the loans start with shady home improvement contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Acorn cited a couple in Port Jefferson Station on Long Island
who missed a payment and found their interest rate jacked up, to 24
percent from 14. In Brooklyn, a woman told a lender she had lost
her $8,000-a-year job as a home health aide, but it approved a loan
anyway, falsely listing her with a $50,000 salary. Another woman
learned too late that her $45,000 loan required monthly payments of
$500 for 15 years _ $90,000 total _ yet left her owing a balloon
payment of $41,000.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is worst in minority neighborhoods that have been
neglected because of ``redlining'' by more traditional, lower-cost
lenders, critics say. Subprime lenders fill that vacuum. In New
York City, the legacy of predatory abuses has been a proliferation
of foreclosures that community advocates say is devastating central
Brooklyn and southeastern Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Barbara M. Clark, D-Queens, has proposed a bill
that would create protections beyond the proposed banking board
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people losing their homes outright as a result of
home improvement or debt consolidation loans,'' Clark said.
``They're putting their homes on the line and don't know what
they're getting into, with fees and interest that are just off the
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Her bill would entitle homeowners to cite an improper loan as a
legal defense to prevent foreclosure. It would also cap brokers'
fees at 3 percent, require disclosure of finder's fees that lenders
pay to home improvement contractors for recruiting borrowers, and
hold bankers responsible for the brokers they deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed several committees last year but did not reach
the Assembly floor. Sen. Frank Padavan, R-Queens, has sponsored the
Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to do something,'' said Brenda J. Thompson, a
school teacher in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn, who said she was
victimized by a subprime lender.
</P>
<P>
   After inheriting her mother's brownstone, which had a small
mortgage with a monthly payment of $154, she talked to a contractor
and lender about renovations. But she was upset when crews tore out
walls without her approval or a loan being issued.
</P>
<P>
   So she went to another lender, who seemed sympathetic and
referred her to a new contractor. He was charming but overcharged
her with a $70,000 fee, took an additional $6,000 of her money and
did incomplete and shabby work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was left with a $105,000 loan at 10.9 percent with a $1,002
monthly payment and a balloon balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a job on me, all right,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
