<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIRTRAVEL16-COX     03-15 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAVEL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport in line for more cash
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport could
receive $700 million more in federal help for its expansion plans
under legislation Congress approved Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The $40 billion in federal funding goes a long way in helping
the world's busiest airport put together the $5.4 billion it needs
for its 10-year growth program, Hartsfield General Manager Ben
DeCosta said. But holes remain in Hartsfield's financial game plan.
In the $5.4 billion expansion, federal grants are expected to cover
about $245 million, ticket taxes about $1.9 billion with another
$1.1 billion coming from airport and other revenues and about $1.3
billion in bonds underwritten by the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   With the boost from the bill approved Wednesday, the airport is
still about $200 million short, DeCosta said. He is exploring other
funding sources.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation spending bill, which already passed the Senate, won
on a 319-101 House vote and is expected to be signed soon by
President Clinton. Atlanta officials were heavily involved in
lobbying Congress for the funding, including an appearance by Mayor
Bill Campbell at hearings and letter-writing efforts by DeCosta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta airport is one of the great generators of the
aviation economy,'' said U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), in whose
district the airport is located. ``Hartsfield is the gateway to the
South. It's the busiest commercial airport in the world. This will
mean a great deal in terms of keeping the American people moving
and growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield's expansion plan includes adding a fifth runway,
building another terminal, revamping the internal road network and
adding passenger gates and parking spaces. The runway is expected
to be completed in 2005, when takeoffs and landings are expected to
rise to more than 2,700 per day, compared to 2,500 now.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield handled 78 million passengers last year and airport
officials project that number will reach 121 million by 2015.
Hartsfield pumps about $9 billion a year into the metro area's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation doubles federal funding to Hartsfield from $9
million to $18 million. The total to Georgia airports will rise
from $15 million to $29.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the most critical part of the package includes allowing
airports to charge as much as $4.50 per ticket in a tax to fund
airport expansion. Hartsfield now charges $3, and DeCosta said the
Atlanta airport immediately will apply for FAA permission to charge
the additional tax. The tax, he said, could produce $700 million
over the next 10 years, ``and possibly even more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Georgia's congressional delegation voted in support of
the aviation bill; Republicans Mac Collins and Jack Kingston voted
against.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he did not want to levy another tax on passengers.
``With passengers and air travelers already getting hit with higher
fuel taxes, it doesn't make sense to raise the fee,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional opponents said the bill would lead to more
air traffic in already congested skies.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.), a member of the House
Transportation Committee, said the bill would increase safety at
Hartsfield and the rest of the state's airports by paying for
improvements in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who uses increasing flights as a reason to be worried
about this bill doesn't understand what's happening in the world,''
Isakson said. ``Aviation use over the next 10 to 20 years is going
to triple. And because of technology, because the world has gotten
so much smaller, because so many more people participate in the
world market today, aviation is just going to grow exponentially,
which is the reason why you need a bill like this so you can make
the improvements in air safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
