<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-350&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      03-15 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WARNS LABOR GROUP OF BIG BATTLE WITH GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In his first day as his party's presumptive
presidential nominee, Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday warned
organized labor here that the Republicans were going to ``throw
everything they've got, plus the kitchen sink'' at his candidacy
and that the Democrats had to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge battle that lies just ahead, and you can make
all the difference,'' Gore told a gathering of more than 2,000
members of the AFL-CIO here in a classic, pro-labor speech intended
to lay down a political marker as much as fire up the troops.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will be relying on labor here _ and in most
Rust Belt states _ come the fall election, when Pennsylvania, with
its big block of electoral votes, is expected to be a swing state
in his contest with Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican. But the
state's primary, scheduled for April 4, now holds little interest
for either side, because both Gore and Bush have already secured
their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke to the audience about the ``importance of
intensity,'' in a speech meant to spark enthusiasm and show the
unions that he had considerable fight in him for the eight-month
contest ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win, we have got to understand, the other side is
going to throw everything they've got, plus the kitchen sink,''
Gore declared. ``They're manning the barricades, they're trying to
funnel unprecedented amounts of money into the campaign. They're
going to stop at nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued his overtures to Republicans and independents.
One of his new tactics is to divide Republicans from their party by
casting the leadership _ the ``Gingrich crew'' as he called it
Wednesday _ as right-wing zealots, quite distinct from the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing from a lot of independents and independently
thinking Republicans, who, while they don't want to abandon their
party, they don't want to lend any support to this kind of
right-wing extremist approach, union-busting approach, the old
borrow-and-spend approach,'' he said. Democrats, he added, ``have
our heads screwed on right.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But he was also conscious of not stirring up too much trouble
with his audience, and what he omitted from his speech was just as
interesting as what he said.
</P>
<P>
   He made no mention of the Clinton administration's push for
Congress to normalize trade relations with China. Gore has vowed to
lobby for normalizing relations and for China's entry into the
World Trade Organization, but he has hardly mentioned this subject
on the campaign trail and skipped it again Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is starting a huge campaign against the China
accord, and two of the federation's most powerful groups, the
Teamsters and the United Auto Workers, have withheld their
endorsement of the vice president because they do not like his
pro-trade position.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Gore mention a second topic that could have unsettled
his labor audience _ his proposal to overhaul the campaign finance
system. Organized labor is expecting to play a central role in the
elections this year, as it has for many years (it infused $35
million into the Clinton/Gore re-election in 1996), and does not
want to hear how Gore would limit its ability to influence the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, however, Gore ascended several flights at his
hotel to attend a fund-raiser on his behalf. About 75 people paid
$1,000 each in the Gore campaign's continuing drive to reach its
maximum fund-raising limit of $33.8 million. Alan Kessler, a
Philadelphia lawyer and a member of Gore's finance committee, said
it was getting much easier for Gore to raise money than it had been
several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did mention his campaign finance proposals to this
audience, saying, ``I want to run this campaign in a way that
honors democracy,'' and repeating his call to Bush for both parties
to eliminate soft money, the dollars they receive that are not
regulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
