<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER16-COX     03-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PRAYER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta court: Student prayer OK at graduation
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Prayer at high school graduation ceremonies is
permissible as long as it is initiated by students and free of
state influence, the federal appeals court in Atlanta ruled
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a policy adopted by the Duval County, Fla., school
district in 1993 that allows students to elect fromtheir ranks a
speaker to deliver a two-minute commencement ``message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``School boards will be able to allow students to make choices
as to whether they want to have an invocation or benediction during
a graduation ceremony,'' Sam Harben, general counsel of the Georgia
School Board Association, said of the ruling's impact. ``However,
boards need to be very careful that the choice should be up to the
senior class and there should be no influence over that decision by
the administration or the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The extension of student-initiated prayer to other school
activities may be possible, Harben speculated. ``But I think the
age of the student and the particular event may make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the policy enacted in Duval, which includes
Jacksonville, the message cannot be edited or reviewed by school
officials. Plaintiffs challenging the policy called it a backdoor
attempt to return state-sponsored prayer to school.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-2 decision, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta rejected that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total absence of state involvement in deciding whether
there will be a graduation message, who will speak or what the
speaker may say, combined with the student's complete autonomy over
the content ... convinces us that the message delivered, be it
secular or sectarian or both, is not state-sponsored,'' Judge
Stanley Marcus wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``To conclude otherwise would come perilously close to
announcing an absolute rule that would excise all private religious
expression from a public graduation ceremony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus added that the policy recognizes the ``crucial
difference'' between state-sponsored religion and private speech.
</P>
<P>
   The court has jurisdiction over Florida, Georgia and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Adler, whose daughter was the lead plaintiff in the case,
expressed disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court never considered what's really going on at the
schools,'' she said. ``They never really considered why the policy
was put in place _ to continue the prayers at schools. I'd like to
see the policy done away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the policy was adopted, religious observances have
dominated the messages in the form of prayers, invocations and
benedictions, according to court motions filed by Adler's lawyers.
At some schools, students voted for a class ``chaplain'' to deliver
the message and some campaigned to have prayer at graduation, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Judge Phyllis Kravitch dissented from the court's
majority opinion. ``Although the Duval County school administration
may have distanced itself from prayer offered during graduation
ceremonies, it did not disconnect itself from religious
expression,'' she wrote. ``Nor does the policy mitigate the
influences that coerce audience members to participate in prayers
offered at graduation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marcus, who was appointed to the court by President Clinton,
said the plaintiffs' position leaves school officials with two
choices: Either eliminate student speech altogether, or censor
student speech if it contains a religious message or prayer.
</P>
<P>
   If school officials choose the latter course, Marcus said, they
must excise the religious content before the commencement speech or
even be forced to interrupt ``renegade'' speakers who wish to say a
prayer. If officials choose the other course, they will have
deprived the graduating class of any role in shaping its graduation
and will have banned all private student expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Establishment Clause requires no such Hobson's choice,''
Marcus wrote, referring to the U.S. Constitution. ``What it does
require is a recognition of the critical difference between a
private statement of religious values and a religious utterance
endorsed by the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duval County policy ``on its face, does no more than
recognize this distinction,'' Marcus wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
