<HEADER>
A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GRAHAM-VP16-COX     03-15 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-VP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Possible Graham-Gore team keeps Florida Democrats hopeful
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The one Florida Democrat who could have
stopped Jeb Bush from becoming governor may get a chance to stop
Bush's brother from becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing makes Florida Republicans tremble more or Democrats
giddier than the thought of U.S. Sen. Bob Graham teaming with Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Is it going to happen? Only Gore knows and he says it is too
soon to worry about running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Does Graham want it? As always, Graham is being coy, saying only
that he is happy with the job he has now. But on primary night, he
appeared to be auditioning for the post with a rousing speech at a
Tallahassee rally for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate moderate who was Florida's governor from 1979 to 1987,
Graham, who will be 64 in November, came close to being President
Clinton's running mate in 1992. He also made the short list in 1988
when then-Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was looking for a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has not had a serious race since winning his first
election to the Senate in 1986 against incumbent Republican Paula
Hawkins. Since going to the Senate, Graham has kept a low profile,
rarely appearing on the Sunday talk shows and often reluctant to
take the lead on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, as he was closing in on his 60th birthday, Graham
flirted with the idea of leaving the Senate to make an
unprecedented run for a third term as governor. Democrats hailed
the idea, believing that Graham was the only Democrat who could
defeat Bush in the 1998 governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   After months of weighing both the personal and political
consequences, Graham decided not to challenge Bush. Later, Graham
even praised Bush's performance during his first year as governor.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, supporters urged Graham to consider running
for president. Graham never seemed to have the desire for the top
job. Supporters now say he is perfectly suited for the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the knowledge, the temperament and the stature to be
vice president,'' says Attorney General Bob Butterworth, Gore's
Florida campaign chairman. ``I think with Bob Graham on the ticket,
Al Gore can win Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an important consideration. It takes 270 electoral votes
to become president and Florida has 25, nearly 10 percent of the
total needed. Democrats point to the fact that Clinton won Florida
in 1996, the first Democrat to do so since Jimmy Carter in 1976.
They also note that Clinton nearly defeated President George Bush
here in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never taken Florida for granted,'' insists Al
Cardenas, chairman of the Florida Republican Party. ``We've always
known we would have to fight to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Cardenas admits that if Graham is on the ticket, it
changes the equation. ``I don't think people vote for who is No. 2
on the ticket,'' said Cardenas. ``But if Bob Graham is on there, it
could bring more Democrats to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not likely to make a decision until late summer. By
then, his strategists will have a better idea whether the Sunshine
State is winnable and whether Graham will help the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it will be a decision based largely on the numbers.
If Gore finds he has a better chance of winning other important
states with a different running mate, Graham will be out for his
third and likely final time.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
