<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BUSH, PARTY NOMINATION NEARLY ASSURED, BALKS AT HEALING McCAIN(See also BUSH-FUNDRAISING, MCCAIN, REPUBS-BUDGET) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT25 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rebuffing calls from prominent Republicans to
reach out to Sen. John McCain, Gov. George W. Bush insisted
Wednesday that he had no intention of making concessions to his
vanquished rival for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush passed up several opportunities to embrace McCain's remedy
for overhauling the campaign finance system, the senator's
signature issue. He said he had learned nothing new about reform
from McCain, although he conceded that his challenger forced him to
be a more spirited competitor. And he was sparing in his praise of
McCain, whose supporters his campaign is counting on to win the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't change my views,'' Bush said in an hour-long
interview at the governor's mansion here on the day after he all
but officially clinched his party's nomination. Asked if McCain had
illuminated any new ideas for him or affected his positions, he
said, ``No, not really.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that McCain helped propel record turnouts in the
primaries, Bush responded curtly, ``Well, then, how come he didn't
win?'' He also noted that in South Carolina his candidacy helped
draw record numbers of Republicans to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments were notable because they suggested that despite
the bruising, bitter and sometimes humbling nature of his primary
campaign against McCain, the Texas governor had emerged from that
experience without any regrets about his campaign's conduct, any
second thoughts about his strategy or any new resolves for the way
he positions himself for the general election. His confidence, if
anything, seemed fortified.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond campaign finance reform, he refused to cede ground on any
of his positions. The governor said, for example, that he was not
daunted by polls showing that his plan to cut taxes by $483 billion
over five years has not caught on with voters. The proposal, he
said, would be a pillar of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I make something really clear to you, once again,'' he
asked. ``I don't care what the polls say. I don't.'' Insisting
there was no reason to turn back, he explained, ``It's a well
thought out plan backed by numbers, backed by credible sources, and
it's something I'm going to stay with, you bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he was not deterred _ or haunted _ by the
memory that voters were never drawn to the ambitious tax cut
proposal of Bob Dole, the Republican nominee four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different because one, I started early, and two, there's
a different budget projection,'' he said, drawing a contrast with
the plan Dole put forth late into the campaign. ``There's a
different budget picture. I'm still going to have to fight the same
thing he fought, with an administration that's desperate to keep
the money in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs that the economy is getting a bit shakier, he said, are
``all the more reason to provide tax relief,'' explaining that his
plan would not only jolt the economy but provide an insurance
policy against any downturn.
</P>
<P>
   To persuade Americans to back his plan, ``I'm going to have to
battle,'' he said. ``I'm going to have to battle with a vice
president who'll say risky this, risky that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said that in the end, voters will be less moved by
whatever sniping occurs between him and Gore and will make their
decisions based on a few overarching considerations. ``What's
critical to my election is a lot of things,'' he said. ``One, that
people trust my judgment. Two, that people hear the call for
reform. Three, that people know that I can renew what I call the
spirit of America. Four, that people are comfortable with the types
of people that I'll bring into my administration. Five, whether
people are happy or not with the status quo. I readily concede that
if people want four more years of Clinton-Gore, I've got a tough
road. I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my position is. I'm the outside, and I'm the
challenger. I'm coming from outside Washington, and I'm the
challenger candidate. People say, I hear them talking out of
Washington, well, he doesn't have enough experience. As if being
the governor of the second biggest state and having served as a CEO
in the private sector isn't experience. It's a Washington
mentality. And I'm going to have to battle it. I'm fully aware of
the odds I'm going to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aggressiveness toward Vice President Al Gore was the
latest reminder of how quickly the general election campaign had
become ferocious. The governor made no effort to mask his animosity
toward Gore.
</P>
<P>
   With little prompting at the start of the interview, Bush said
that his Democratic rival was not to be trusted. Scoffing at an
e-mail Gore had sent to him Tuesday night calling for something of
a disarmament on both sides' use of unregulated soft money, Bush
said: ``I don't trust the man. He has no credibility as far as I'm
concerned about campaign funding reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeated six times the fact that he did not trust Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Gore said in his e-mail that he had instructed the
Democratic National Committee not to spend a cent on soft money for
issue commercials against the Republicans unless the Republicans
did so first.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Christopher Lehane, Gore's spokesman, mocked Bush's
comment that the vice president will do anything to win the White
House. Lehane said: ``If nothing else, the Republican primary
proved one thing: George W. Bush will do anything to get elected,
included embracing extreme right positions on choice, gun control,
tolerance, the environment and, of course, the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But if Bush's combative tone toward Gore was not surprising, his
relatively complacent attitude about any remaining rift between him
and McCain was.
</P>
<P>
   It could simply be part of an effort to maintain a brave public
face while the campaign's emissaries privately reach out to McCain
and his representatives. Even so, one of the few times Bush said
something explicitly favorable about the senator was in the course
of condemning Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Al Gore is no John McCain,'' Bush said. ``Please
don't lump John into that category. Secondly, I think John McCain
is a person that basically wanted to elevate the discourse and had
a reason for running, rather than tearing somebody down.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked, then, if Gore had a reason for running, Bush replied,
``I'm sure he's got a reason, but their style, as we've seen from
the last eight years, is to demean and degrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reluctance to reach out more aggressively to McCain, at
least publicly, could be politically perilous for the governor.
McCain has captured enough delegates that he has the leverage to
embarrass Bush at the party's convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush supporters on opposite ends of the Republican spectrum
_ from Senate Republican leader Trent Lott to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York _ have called for a rapproachement between the
two on reform issues.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he needed to make any concessions to McCain, Bush
said: ``No. I think what I need to do is explain to John that we
agree a lot more than we disagree. There's a lot of room for reform
in Washington, D.C.'' But in an interview last week, McCain said it
would be ``unacceptable'' if Bush thought they could unite simply
over their opposition to Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was also unrepentant about the pointed attacks that his
campaign _ and supporters of his campaign _ had waged on the
Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was anything in particular, he said: ``Like what?
Give me an example. What should I regret?'' Pressed about the
negative tone of the campaign, he said, ``I didn't take the
negative tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was also unwilling to concede that his campaign had
squandered its record war chest of roughly $70 million to win the
primaries. He said he had ordered no changes in his organization
and was not worried about spending for the general election, when
each campaign will get roughly $67 million in federal subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked about how he manages his campaign and, by extension,
how he would function in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make suggestions on what to say all the time,'' he
said. ``I'll give you an example: I don't read what's handed to me.
People say, `Here, here's you're speech.' Or, `Here's an idea for a
speech.' They're changed. Trust me. Last night's a good example. We
could have been a lot harsher in tone on Vice President Gore last
night. I chose not to.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor resisted the temptation to criticize Clinton for
failing to negotiate lasting peace agreements in several regions,
from the Middle East to Northern Ireland to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for Americans and elected officials to be
patient with the peace process, to be diligent and patient,'' he
said. ``It's very important for the president not to impose a
United States solution on the peace process. So to the president's
credit, it seems to me on the Middle East he's working hard to
bring people together.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not yet time, he said, to turn over management of the
warring factions in the Balkans to the United Nations. ``I do think
it's time to begin to say to our European allies, `You're going to
have to be the peacekeepers,''' he said. ``I think it's going to be
very important for us to trim United States involvement around the
world from certain peacekeeping missions.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview closed as it began: With Bush's attention riveted
toward his general election opponent. How fierce a competitor would
Gore be?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to find out,'' Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
