<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four Drug Makers Expected to Face FTC Complaints
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission is expected to file complaints
Thursday contending that four drug companies harmed consumers when
they made agreements that delayed the sale of low-cost generic
drugs, according to lawyers and executives briefed on the matter.
The civil actions would be the first to come from a continuing
investigation into deals under which companies that make brand-name
drugs pay rivals that are developing cheaper, generic forms not to
sell the lower cost drug. As a result, consumers pay hundreds of
millions of dollars more than they would if the cheaper drugs were
available.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Profit Beats Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns posted a 20 percent increase in its first-quarter
profit, beating analysts' expectations, as rising investment
banking fees offset a slump in bond trading. The securities firm
had net income of $278.2 million, or $1.89 a diluted share,
compared with $230.7 million, or $1.45 a share, in the period a
year earlier. Shares of Bear Stearns rose $1.5625, to $41.50.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Chief Plans to Step Down
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Martinez, the chairman and chief executive of Sears,
Roebuck, who led a turnaround at the retailer in the mid-1990s,
will retire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   King's Popularity Extends to Web
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King's latest novella, ``Riding the Bullet,'' has proved
so popular in two days of literary life on the Internet that
several online booksellers could not meet the demand from people
wanting to download digital copies. About 400,000 orders were
received in the 24 hours after the book became available.
</P>
<P>
   Crackdown on Subprime Lenders
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in New York state, the nation's largest banking
center and an industry pace setter, are devising new rules to crack
down on so-called subprime lenders that impose exorbitant fees that
force countless homeowners into foreclosure and bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors Cheered by Thai Ruling
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's bankruptcy court declared Thai Petrochemical Industry
insolvent. Creditors regarded the decision as an important victory
that could help them start to recover billions of dollars in unpaid
loans left from the 1997-98 Asian financial crisis. But the court
rejected a request to replace Thai Petrochemical's family-led
management immediately, saying a meeting of all creditors and
management must take place first. That means there could be more
negotiations between the creditors and Prachai Leophairatana, the
company's founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   European Exchanges Revamping
</P>
<P>
   European stock exchanges began to position themselves for a
shake-up in the way investors trade. In London, the 298 members of
the London Stock Exchange ended almost two centuries of mutual
ownership by converting their stakes into tradeable shares. And the
Brussels, Paris and Amsterdam stock exchanges are in talks to merge
or form an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Production Rises 0.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Production by the nation's factories, mines and utilities
advanced 0.3 percent last month, government figures showed. That
kept businesses operating at 81.7 percent of their maximum capacity
in February, the same as in January. A separate report showed
businesses increased their inventories 0.5 percent in January,
leaving supplies at record lows.
</P>
</TEXT>
