<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-PORN-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH LAW WILL CREATE FIRST `PORNOGRAPHY CZAR' IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Taking aim at the easy accessibility of
sexually explicit material in Utah, Gov. Michael O. Leavitt plans
to sign into law Friday a measure that will give Utah the nation's
first pornography czar.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt conceded that the new obscenity and pornography
complaints ombudsman, a deputy state attorney general, would have
no power over the biggest sources of sexual content _ the Internet
and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   But in a state where the Mormon Church and its socially
conservative views influence almost all aspects of life, Leavitt
said the law would ``codify our highest moral aspirations'' by
adding state powers to community efforts in fighting what some
residents regard as offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the bill in February was nearly unanimous in both
Republican-led chambers of the legislature, and it came just two
days after publication of a book by Gordon B. Hinckley, president
and prophet of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints,
that urges followers to lead a more moral life and denounced what
Hinckley perceived as a surge in pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a state legislature is looking for a way to improve the
world, this is not an illogical way to strike a blow,'' said
Leavitt, a Republican, in an interview. ``Time will tell if it's a
good use of state money. But to me, there is no harm in trying.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor of the legislation, state Rep. Evan L. Olsen, a
Republican, said he did not believe pornography was a greater
problem in Utah than elsewhere. This assessment is shared by
officials in the Utah attorney general's office and supported by
Justice Department statistics that showed that rates of all crimes
had fallen steadily across the country in recent years, including
in Utah's largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Giampietro, a past president and now general counsel to
the First Amendment Lawyers Association, a national organization,
said proliferation of sexually explicit material on the Internet
had stimulated new interest in regulatory actions around the
country, like more restrictive zoning laws for businesses that
offer pornographic products.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't seen any uptick in criminal prosecutions,''
Giampietro said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Olsen's measure creates a position in the attorney
general's office that state officials routinely call the
``pornography czar.'' The responsibilities will include advising
municipal governments about obscenity law, helping tailor
ordinances to suit local tastes as the U.S. Supreme Court has
allowed, arbitrating problems when possible and prosecuting
violations when necessary. Other states prosecute the same crimes,
but not necessarily by one person.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature has set aside $75,000 to cover salary and
expenses in the first year, which begins in January, and will allow
the budget to double the year after.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with no legal authority to take on cable television and the
Internet, the law is largely symbolic, said some legal experts in
Utah, including Carol Gnade, director of the Utah chapter of the
American Civil Liberties Union. They also contend that it wastes
taxpayer money in that there is no demonstrable need for the job.
</P>
<P>
   But Olsen insisted that many Utah communities wrestle with how
to apply local obscenity laws and often need advice on how to
prosecute violators. He also said he had been convinced by events
in recent years reflecting public discomfort with sexual material
and activities in Utah that the recent legislative session was
``the right time and the right place to get something done.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a 1996 raid, the authorities in Utah County confiscated 1,000
films from a video-rental company in American Fork and Lehi, and
later charged the manager, Larry Peterman, with 15 counts of
distributing pornographic films. Peterman's first trial ended with
a hung jury, and he was acquitted in a second trial. But the
litigation succeeded in driving the company out of business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the owner of a small video-rental company in American
Fork offered to delete nudity and sex scenes from the film
``Titanic'' for $5. Within weeks, the company received more than
2,000 copies of the film for editing, a demand that led the owner,
Carol Biesinger, to expand the offer to include other films.
</P>
<P>
   In a more recent demonstration of concern, Olsen said the mayor
of a town he declined to identify called him to complain about a
house-cleaning service that was advertising charges of $80 an hour
for a woman to work in a bikini and $100 an hour for a woman to
work topless.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Ruzicka, leader of the Utah chapter of the Eagle Forum, a
conservative action group, said the pervasiveness of sexually
explicit material in Utah led the group to support the Olsen bill
as a way to take ``a giant step in hopes that other states follow
to protect children and other adults.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Mooney, a Salt Lake City lawyer and another past
president of the First Amendment Lawyers Association, called the
new pornography law ``rampant stupidity,'' predicting that it would
lead to financial strain on the state through local governments'
losing cases based on First Amendment considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When judges award attorney fees against communities, those
communities are going to say the state should pay the costs,'' he
said. ``This is a lose-lose nightmare situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The law also disturbs Utah business owners who sell sexually
explicit material. Keith Kofoed, the owner of a Salt Lake City shop
called Mischievous, said local police made him remove an
androgynous mannequin he placed in his store window as a
Valentine's Day promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, there is always the possibility they are going to close
you down,'' Kofoed said. ``That's the environment you have to live
with in Utah. Instead of things becoming more flexible here, they
are getting ultraconservative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
