<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-MEDIABYTES_SFCH     03-15 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN FOST/MEDIABYTES 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Cnet's Dynamic Duo Changing Roles as Minor Follows His Bliss 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The two young men went to the University of Virginia together, but
they didn't meet until years later, when they worked in New York
City.
<P>
   Yet within months of their meeting, Shelby Bonnie and Halsey
Minor went into business together, with Bonnie putting up some of
the money for Minor's dream of creating computer shows for cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie ultimately quit his job, joined Minor and, despite some
struggles in those early years, helped steer San Francisco's Cnet
into becoming one of the leading Internet media firms, specializing
in providing news and reviews of computers and related products.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Minor stepped aside after nearly eight years as
Cnet's chief executive, handing the reins to his longtime friend
and confidant. Minor, who will remain as chairman, will start using
some of the considerable wealth he built at Cnet to help found and
grow new companies.
</P>
<P>
   The two men _ both 35 years old _ live 10 houses apart in San
Francisco's Sea Cliff neighborhood, and, as Bonnie said, ``We can
finish each other's sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie likened the transition to Bill Gates handing off
Microsoft's CEO slot to his old college pal Steve Ballmer, who was
already effectively running the company's operations. In Cnet's
case, Minor is the entrepreneur and visionary who didn't like
getting bogged down with budgets and organizational charts, Bonnie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite naysayers, Minor led the launch of the portal Snap and
was able to sell it to NBC, which is now using it as a centerpiece
of its Internet strategy _ a move that has made Cnet millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie has already been running more of the nuts-and-bolts
aspects of Cnet, which has grown to more than 700 employees and has
a market capitalization of nearly $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than $5 billion last week, before the announcement
of the CEO switch. The stock dropped 23 percent, from $70.56 on
March 6 to yesterday's close of $54.13. Minor's 11 percent stake in
Cnet was worth $436 million yesterday; Bonnie's 13 percent stake
was worth $516 million.
</P>
<P>
   About nine months ago, Minor and Bonnie began discussing the
change. Earlier last year, the company had hired a new president,
Rich Marino, former CEO of IDG's PC World, and with a deeper
management team, Minor felt comfortable exploring his alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Minor took a month off, relaxing in the Hamptons
while Bonnie, Marino and company ran Cnet. The company survived.
</P>
<P>
   A report on TheStreet.com said Minor plans to start an Internet
incubator with Eric Greenberg, founder of Web consultants Scient
and Viant.
</P>
<P>
   Minor, caught the other day in the Cnet corridors between
meetings, refused to confirm his plans except in the most general
sense. ``We're building a little sandbox for me to build other
things,'' he said. ``Cnet is really focused on executing its
business. The days of building Snap in here are over.''
</P>
<P>
   The new venture ``will allow me to participate in the new
economy in a broader sense,'' Minor said. ``I'll be building
companies in spaces outside where Cnet is.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Cnet, Bonnie said he'll focus on several key initiatives
for the future:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _Business-to-business commerce:  &LR; Cnet has built its brand by
providing information for consumers, enabling them to buy
technology products. Now, Bonnie plans to steer the company into
providing more service-oriented information to small and
medium-sized &LR;  businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _International:  &LR; The worldwide market for computer products is as
big as that in the United States, Bonnie said, and growing faster.
Cnet already has plans to launch sites and services in Europe and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; _Wireless:  &LR; When Cnet acquired the company MySimon earlier this
year, it gained an impressive comparison shopping engine, and it
now plans to put that technology onto cell phones and other
devices. That way, consumers can read reviews and check comparable
prices while they're shopping in a store. ``Comparison shopping is
a killer app model in wireless,'' Bonnie said.
</P>
<P>
   On the walls in Bonnie's Chestnut Street office are several
totems that should serve as ample metaphors for his new role: a
pair of Cnet boxing gloves; framed Cnet shirts that he wore in
running a pair of New York marathons; a worker's belt, presented to
``the guy doing all the heavy lifting''; and a large prop from one
of Cnet's cable television shows that says, ``Reality Check,'' next
to a photo of the young Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIMES TRIBUNE: &QL; 
Watch to see what sort of walls fall in the wake of this week's
media megamerger, in which the Tribune Co. plans to acquire Times
Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune has earned headlines for knocking down the walls between
old and new media; Times Mirror, on the other hand, has sought to
raze the barriers between the business and journalistic sides of
its enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Gordon, who chairs the New Media program at the Medill
School of Journalism at Northwestern University in the Tribune
Co.'s hometown of Chicago, says that although Tribune's pioneering
efforts in new media produced some strong journalism, they did not
bring great success.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune is retooling to be more of ``an e-commerce company
enabled by great content,'' Gordon said. ``That's very different
than other traditional media companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a former newsman with the Miami Herald and Palm Beach
Post, says some of the criticism of the L.A. Times' blurring the
lines between editorial and advertising was overblown. ``The belief
that there's an impermeable wall between editorial and advertising
in any media company is a myth,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But newspapers at least try. ``Clearly the wall in new media, if
there is a wall, is in a different place, or is a different height,
or has a different permeability. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to seamlessly connect content and commerce online
is one of the inherent attributes of the medium. As much as
journalists don't want to connect them, it's what people want to
do. We have to figure out where to draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INTERNET MENACE: &QL; 
How does a big media firm protect its properties in cyberspace? If
the firm is Lucasfilm Ltd., the answer is: aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Tonik Barber, director of business affairs for the maker of the
``Star Wars'' series, told a lunch audience at San Rafael's
Dominican College last week that the Internet poses special
challenges to the owners of content, but that Lucasfilm has been
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The company sent 700 letters to Internet service providers,
warning them that if any of their customers posted digital versions
of last year's ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace,'' the
ISP would have to remove it under the Digital Millennium Copyright
Act (DMCA) &LR; , signed by President Clinton in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel we're right,'' Barber said. ``We haven't taken
it to court, but we think we're still the only company to take the
DMCA to that level.''
</P>
<P>
