<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDICT-INDICT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Firm's Sale Prompts Fraud Case  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The U.S. attorney's office has charged the founders of a Bay Area
medical devices firm with faking safety tests on a brain catheter,
then selling their startup to an unwitting buyer for $70 million in
stock.
<P>
   The indictment unsealed yesterday in U.S. District Court in San
Jose was filed against Ronald L. Dieck and Erin M. McGurk, a
husband-and-wife team who founded Micro Interventional Systems in
Sunnyvale in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   They each owned 10 percent of the startup, which made them
approximately $7 million apiece when they sold the firm to
Medtronic Inc. of Minneapolis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-page indictment alleges the two defendants ``and others
knowingly and willfully conspired to defraud'' the U.S. Food and
Drug Administration by fudging the results of safety tests the
company needed in order to win FDA approval to sell catheters and
other devices used to treat brain tumors and blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   Among other allegations, the indictment charges the defendants
directed a co-conspirator to conceal from the FDA the fact that one
device had unexpectedly killed a test pig.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Robert Van Nest of San Francisco said his
clients will plead innocent to the charges ``and defend themselves
vigorously.'' He declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   A release issued by the U.S. attorney's office said the maximum
penalty for each alleged violation in the nine-count indictment is
five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged wrongdoing was first brought to government attention
in 1998 by Medtronic, which has filed a separate civil action
charging that the defendants used the faked safety tests to inflate
the price that Medtronic paid for the startup.
</P>
<P>
   That civil case, filed in Minneapolis in 1998, is currently &LR;   &LR; in
arbitration, said Medtronic spokeswoman Jessica Stoltenberg.
</P>
<P>
   She said her company did not suspect any wrongdoing in 1995 when
it purchased the startup in order to get into the
$100-million-a-year business of selling brain catheters and related
devices.
</P>
<P>
   It was only in 1998, after Medtronic decided to resell its
acquisition and get out of the business, that an informant inside
the Sunnyvale division disclosed that the safety tests may have
been faked, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No (prepurchase) due diligence can uncover this kind of
fraud,'' Stoltenberg said. ``If people falsify data, you can only
find that (out) if you know it's there and have a full blown
audit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tip, she said Medtronic conducted such an audit and
shared the results with the FDA. She said Medtronic recalled all
the medical devices tainted by the alleged faking and shut down the
Sunnyvale division, which had once employed 55 people.
</P>
<P>
   Dieck and McGurk did not respond to calls placed to Magic
Venture Capital, the company they operate in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Tom Abate at abate &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
