<HEADER>
A8120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DNA-INDICT-NYT &LR;      03-15 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a series of genetic markers as their evidence,
Manhattan prosecutors announced the indictment Wednesday of the man
known as the East Side rapist, even though investigators still do
not know who he is.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, one of the first times in the nation that a DNA
signature alone has been used to charge a crime, will prevent the
statute of limitations from expiring in three of the seven rapes he
is suspected of committing between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury charged the man four days before the five-year
statute of limitations would have expired on the earliest attack
cited in the indictment, said Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said he believed the East Side
rapist was still at large.
</P>
<P>
   In October, prosecutors in Milwaukee announced they had filed
charges in three rapes against a man known only by his DNA code.
There has been at least one other such warrant based on DNA
evidence, a 1991 case in Kansas. No one has been apprehended in
either case.
</P>
<P>
   John Doe indictments are typically used in fraud cases, where
prosecutors may not know the real name of the alleged perpetrator
or in cases where they have a precise physical description but have
not learned the alleged perpetrator's name.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and legal experts said the number of indictments
based solely on DNA codes would increase rapidly in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very new, very creative kind of prosecution,'' said
Linda Fairstein, the chief of the Manhattan district attorney's sex
crimes unit.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Thomas P. Carney said the DNA evidence has eliminated two
suspects in the East Side attacks over the last year. When officers
tested one man's DNA last year, collected surreptitiously, he was
exonerated, Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   The probability that a person other than the attacker has a DNA
profile matching the one in the Manhattan indictment is 1 in 240
billion, Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
   The rapist attacked all but one of his victims on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan, after 2 a.m., the police said. He last struck a
year and half ago, and some investigators believe he has left the
city. But the police said the indictment ensures that their work
will not go to waste if he is eventually identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   The statute of limitations has run out on two of the 16 attacks
linked to the rapist, police officials said. The two attacks
following those were included in Wednesday's indictment, along with
another. Morgenthau said DNA evidence was recovered in a fourth
attack linked to the rapist and added that an indictment in that
case was expected. The police have linked other attacks to the same
man by a description and details on how he assaulted his victims,
Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 12,000 New York City rape cases in which the
evidence has not been examined for DNA signatures. Morgenthau said
his prosecutors and investigators were looking for assaults that
match a pattern, then conducting tests on DNA taken from the
evidence. Cases that follow a pattern would be the next John Doe
indictments, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
