A8121 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EPIPHANY-EPIPHANY_SFC     03-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPIPHANY-EPIPHANY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E.piphany to Buy Octane For $2.4 Billion  
 By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Highlighting the holy grail of e-commerce _ effectively targeting
Web customers _ two San Mateo software firms said yesterday they
will join forces in a $2.4 billion deal, creating a powerhouse in
the arena of tracking and analyzing customer data.
<P>
   E.piphany Inc. said it will acquire Octane Software by issuing
12.8 million shares of E.piphany stock to Octane shareholders.
Those shareholders, including all 220 or so Octane employees, will
own about 26.5 percent of the combined 500-employee company.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second multibillion-dollar deal in a week involving
Bay Area softwaremakers. On Monday, Dallas' I2 Technologies
announced plans to acquire Aspect Development of Mountain View for
$9.3 billion _ thought to be a record in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Though some analysts say E.piphany may be paying too much for
Octane _ the deal drove down E.piphany's stock by almost 25 percent
on an already rough day for the Nasdaq _ some analysts say the two
companies are a natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a near-perfect combination of technologies and
strengths,'' Forrester Research analyst Bob Chatham said.
``E.piphany helps you gain insights into customer preference in a
statistical way. ... Octane provides technology for managing
communications.''
</P>
<P>
   E.piphany makes programs that let companies slice and dice
hordes of customer information from Web sites, call centers and
direct mailings in order to better tailor marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Octane's products tally how many times a customer
e-mailed complaints to a company's Web site, then relays that
information to the call center representative who takes a call from
that customer.
</P>
<P>
   Octane founder Tim Guleri, who will become vice chairman and
executive vice president of strategy and business development, said
the alliance creates a complete way for e-tailers to interact with
customers in real time.
</P>
<P>
   With the company's technology, ``A customer comes to a Web site
for self-service, (E.piphany) picks up the data, and if they're
buying blue shirts at Nordstrom's Web site, it tells them they need
to buy a yellow tie,'' Guleri said.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Aspect deal earlier in the week, some on Wall
Street balked at the figure for privately held Octane, which was
days away from filing papers for an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Though Octane is backed by heavy hitters Lucent Ventures and
Sigma Ventures, $2.4 billion is ``an awful lot of money,'' said
Jack Staff, an analyst at Zona Research.
</P>
<P>
   Such consternations _ and the sudden drop in E.piphany's stock
price following a thirteenfold jump since its September IPO _ make
some wonder whether the deal will come off at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that stock price continues to tank too much, E.piphany
might not get the shareholder votes it needs to make (the
acquisition) happen,'' Staff said.
</P>
<P>
   Those enthused about the deal seem to be betting on the customer
relationship management market itself, which is expected to grow to
$18 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are investing a lot of money in this,'' Chase H&AMP;Q
analyst Ian Morton said. ``Can you get repeat customer business?
That's something all companies are fighting for today.'' Morton
rates E.piphany shares a ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Octane purchase bolsters E.piphany's ability to compete with
Palo Alto's Kana Communications Inc., whose software routes
incoming e-mail, studies customer information and identifies
trends. Kana said last month that it would buy Silknet Software
Inc., whose applications let companies track orders on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in both Kana and E.piphany hope the companies' revenue
will skyrocket as more Internet and brick-and-mortar businesses
turn to technology to understand customer preferences and increase
repeat business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treating customers individually is really in its infancy,''
said Bob Moran, research vice president at the Aberdeen Group, a
Boston research firm. ``People who say we have one-to-one marketing
down are really foolish. Most corporations don't understand
themselves, let alone their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at kzito &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
