r f BC-FATBRAIN-FATBRAIN_SFC     03-15 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATBRAIN-FATBRAIN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Fatbrain Opens New Chapter on D-Books With MightyWords  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Capitalizing on the success of Stephen King's first Internet book
this week, a Santa Clara online book distributor will announce
plans today to sell more downloadable tomes.
<P>
   Fatbrain.com Inc. will announce today it is spinning off its
7 &LR; - &LR; month-old consumer-oriented Web site eMatter.com into a company
devoted to selling downloadable publications from authors such as
Arthur C. Clarke and Caroline Kennedy-Schlossberg.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which specializes in selling engineering and other
technical publications online, said the new company will be called
MightyWords.com, a name derived from the adage, ``The pen is
mightier than the sword.''
</P>
<P>
   John Logan, an analyst with the research firm Aberdeen Group,
said the move comes at time when ``d-books,'' his term for books
that can be downloaded in electronic form from the Internet to a
computer or handheld device, are about to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the week that the d-book has gone from being a trend
to an inflection point in how technology will change our lives,''
said Logan, Aberdeen Group's chairman and co-founder. ``There's a
huge demand for a 10- to 100-page d-book.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the popular horror novelist King became the first to
release a book in electronic form only, a 66-page short story
called ``Riding the Bullet.'' Each downloaded copy cost $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Customer traffic was so high at sites like Barnes &AMP; Noble and
Amazon at 10 a.m. that servers overloaded, and some King fans
couldn't get through.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bell, a spokesman for netLibrary.com, a Boulder, Colo.,
online book distributor, reported no overload problems. The book
distributor and its subsidiary, Peanutpress.com, sold about 10,000
copies in the first 24 hours and more copies in the first hour than
the company expected for one day, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Kirkpatrick, MightyWords.com executive vice president, said
her site offers known and unknown authors the chance to publish
work that big publishing houses normally would not find marketable,
such as how-to manuals for an arcane hobby or short stories about
an offbeat topic.
</P>
<P>
   Famed science fiction writer Clarke, for example, is offering
the text of a speech he wrote on the impact of television and the
soul, Kirkpatrick said. Wendy Goldman Rohm is adding online updates
to her book ``The Microsoft File: The Secret Case Against Bill
Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   The work can be downloaded into a computer in an Adobe Acrobat
format specially encrypted to prevent the file from being re-sent
to someone else for free by e-mail. Users can either read the book
or story on the computer or print it out on paper. Fatbrain CEO
Chris MacAskill conceded that there is no way to prevent consumers
from making multiple paper copies.
</P>
<P>
   MightyWords offers a 50-50 royalties split with the authors;
writers often get 10 percent from traditional publishing houses.
Since its start as eMatter, the online distributor has sold
thousands of publications over the Web, with each sale averaging
$8.
</P>
<P>
   To kick off the redesigned site, MightyWords will offer free
short essays on the Bill of Rights by several writers, including
attorney Kennedy-Schlossberg, daughter of the late President John
F. Kennedy; actress Whoopi Goldberg; former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich; and Coretta Scott King, widow of slain civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain CEO Chris MacAskill said MightyWords will start as a
subsidiary of Fatbrain but will spin off into a separate company
``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
