<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8126 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PGE16-PGE_SFCHRON &LR;      03-15 1651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGE16-PGE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Movie Has PG&AMP;E Walking on Eggshells  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The expression on Julia Roberts' face is one of both outrage and
gritty determination. ``She brought a small town to its feet,'' the
ads say, ``and a huge company to its knees.''
<P>
   That huge company is San Francisco's Pacific Gas and Electric
Co., which finds itself in the uncomfortable position of being cast
as the object of Roberts' scorn in the based-on-a-true-story new
film ``Erin Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, opening nationwide tomorrow, has caused considerable
consternation among PG&AMP;E's top brass, and, according to one source,
even prompted the utility to plant spies on the set to keep track
of the production.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E, insiders say, is deeply concerned about the movie's
rehashing of one of the most notorious episodes in the company's
history. That case resulted in the utility paying $333 million to
settle charges that it poisoned hundreds of people with a highly
toxic chemical.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Untimely Reminder
</P>
<P>
   This is the last thing the company wants the public reminded of
as it prepares for a trial in November that could make the earlier
settlement seem puny by comparison. More than 1,500 plaintiffs are
participating in the latest case, which their lawyer says will show
conclusively that the utility has repeatedly covered up
environmental mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connecting the dots _ that's the thing PG&AMP;E is most concerned
about,'' said a former high-ranking company official who requested
anonymity. ``They've got environmental situations all over the
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things come out,'' the former official said, ``a reputation
they've cultivated for environmental responsibility turns out to be
not very responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich,'' starring the highest-paid actress on the
planet, centers on a 1993 lawsuit over contamination of the air and
water around the small San Bernardino County town of Hinkley.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of exposure to the chemical chromium from PG&AMP;E's
nearby natural-gas pumping plant, local residents were subject to
nearly every physical ailment imaginable, including various forms
of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Film Portrays Justice-Seekers
</P>
<P>
   They are depicted in the film as decent, salt-of-the-earth folk
who, after learning the truth about their predicament from legal
investigator Brockovich, only want justice for the tragedies they
have experienced.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E, for its part, comes off as arrogant, cunning and
duplicitous _ the epitome of corporate evil. The company is
depicted as attempting to deceive Hinkley residents and to cover up
its misbehavior. It's shown to be unsympathetic, at best, toward
the more than 600 people it has hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, the company admitted seems ok here  &LR; that it
released chromium into the environment from 1951 to 1966. However,
it did not inform local residents of the problem until 1987.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E ultimately decided not to contest the resulting lawsuit and
to instead enter into binding arbitration. The case was settled in
July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An internal memo sent to PG&AMP;E employees last week from Bob
Glynn, chief executive of the utility's parent company, admitted
that ``PG&AMP;E did not respond to the groundwater problem as openly,
quickly or thoroughly as it should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear, in retrospect, that our company should have
handled some things differently at that time,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it notes that ```based on a true story' doesn't mean that
everything in the story is true. The movie is an entertainment
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, PG&AMP;E was quick to realize that ``Erin
Brockovich'' could explode into a PR nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad enough that a film was being made,'' the former
company official said. ``But the fact that Julia Roberts was in it
really heightened anxiety. Everybody figured that Hollywood would
slam the hell out of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Another source, a PG&AMP;E employee who worked for the utility
during the Hinkley lawsuit and is still with the company, confirmed
that PG&AMP;E executives were indeed concerned about the depiction of
the utility in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there was concern,'' this employee said. ``We didn't know
how the company was going to be portrayed. Would it look like a
stand-up company, or would it look like a sleaze?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Name Change Not Pursued
</P>
<P>
   The former official, who also was with PG&AMP;E throughout the
Hinkley matter and during the subsequent making of ``Erin
Brockovich,'' said the company at one point considered paying the
film's producers to change PG&AMP;E's name in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never called us,'' said Carla Santos Shamberg, executive
producer of ``Erin Brockovich.'' ``And that's just as well. It
would have made them look even worse to try and bribe us.''
</P>
<P>
   She also defended the overwhelmingly good-versus-evil tone of
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't come up with what PG&AMP;E did right in this
circumstance,'' Shamberg said. ``These people were victims of
PG&AMP;E's misdeeds. We portrayed (events) as accurately as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep tabs on the film's production, PG&AMP;E hired a Southern
California public relations company to monitor media reports and to
send back dispatches from the set, the former official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of interest in finding out when the film would
open,'' this person said. ``Would it come out just before the
annual meeting?''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E spokesman Greg Pruett denied that the company hired anyone
to spy on the filmmakers. He also echoed Glynn's position that the
movie ``is a dramatization, not a documentary, and there can be
quite a bit of latitude in how you combine facts and drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Pruett and Glynn said they hadn't yet seen ``Erin
Brockovich.'' That they nevertheless have strong stands on the
film's accuracy indicates how seriously PG&AMP;E executives take
tomorrow's opening.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Braced Then, Braced Now
</P>
<P>
   The publicity should be a good deal more fierce this time around
than when the case was originally settled. Although PG&AMP;E was braced
at the time for a firestorm of lousy PR, the former official said
the company was pleasantly surprised to find the matter all but
ignored by the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a genuine sense of relief that this did not become a
big story,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to the settlement, the former official said, ``we
were extremely concerned that someone in the media would pick up on
how the arbitration happened down there. It was a daily concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the former official said company executives were
worried that some enterprising reporter would piece together that
chromium had been used to prevent corrosion in pumps not only at
the Hinkley plant, but at facilities in Kettleman near Fresno and
in the town of Topock on the California-Arizona border.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life Brockovich investigated the Kettleman plant, and
the real-life lawyer she works for, Ed Masry, has filed another
suit against PG&AMP;E on behalf of about 1,400 former residents of the
area and PG&AMP;E workers seeking compensation for personal injuries,
as well as more than 150 Hinkley residents who missed out on the
first settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E is going to get burned bad,'' Masry said. ``Kettleman is
an exact replica of Hinkley, and they continued doing all the same
things.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E's Pruett said he could not comment on the Kettleman case or
any other pending lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the former PG&AMP;E official said potential contamination
from use of chromium at the Topock plant ``could be the worst of
all. It's right next to the Colorado River.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Baker, a spokesman for the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control in Sacramento, said investigators have indeed
found evidence of chromium contamination in the soil and ground
water surrounding the Topock plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the river has not been affected yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A full report on the department's findings will be released next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The former PG&AMP;E official said the company's strategy has been to
isolate Hinkley ``as a one-time situation'' and to not draw
attention to use of chromium at other plants.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this person added, ``the company has been
doing a lot to bill itself as an environmentally responsible
corporation.'' The chromium cases are ``a distinct threat,
obviously, to that image.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E's ``statement of environmental policy'' says the company
``is committed to being an environmental leader'' and will ``comply
fully with the letter and spirit of applicable environmental laws
and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   But the utility is no stranger to accusations of environmental
wrongdoing. In 1993, for example, more than 250 current and former
residents of the Midway Village public housing complex in Daly City
sued PG&AMP;E for allegedly contaminating soil in the area with toxic
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has challenged claims that chemicals from its nearby
facility are responsible for the illnesses of Midway residents,
although a federal health study last year found that the residents
suffer from an ``abnormal'' number of genetic defects.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the company agreed to pay $14 million to dismiss state
and federal claims that it withheld information about the impact of
the cooling system at its Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant on
marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Masry, the lawyer, said PG&AMP;E seems to believe that its
environmental problems will go away if the company simply persists
in trying to keep them under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their heads are in the sand,'' he said. ``And now they think
this movie is just going to go away. But instead it looks like it
could be a big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   As if that wasn't bad enough for the utility, Masry said CourtTV
has already asked to air the proceedings of the Kettleman trial
live on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to get a lot worse for PG&AMP;E,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
