<HEADLINE>
BMW SHARES SOAR ON POSSIBLE ROVER SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
(no byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Shares of BMW AG soared 13.7 percent
Wednesday amid widespread expectations that the German car
manufacturer would decide on Thursday to sell Rover Cars, its
loss-plagued British subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   One day after BMW said that it would consider the sale of Rover
at its supervisory board meeting on Thursday, speculation was
widespread in Britain and Germany about potential buyers. The
Munich-based newspaper Sueddeutsche reported Thursday that BMW was
preparing to sell most of Rover to a Cayman Islands investment
group.
</P>
<P>
   BMW, which said it had been studying its options for the last
several months, said Wednesday that it would announce its plans
Friday. Analysts said its options included closing Rover's main
factory at Longbridge and cutting back the range of Rover car
models; selling off the car business while holding onto the popular
Land Rover sport utility vehicles and Mini subcompacts; or forming
an alliance with a larger automaker.
</P>
<P>
   British union officials at BMW's Longbridge factory, alarmed at
the possibility that thousands of workers could lose their jobs,
flew to the company's headquarters in Munich on Wednesday in an
attempt to find out more about BMW's intentions.
</P>
</TEXT>
