r s BC-BKC-INDIANA-STATE-'79     03-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-INDIANA-STATE-'79-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYCAMORES OF '79 REMEMBER GLORY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beer drinking might actually help people's memory _ and not
waste it _ at a sports bar near the Indiana State campus in Terre
Haute, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Purcell, the proprietor of The Terminal sports bar, said
the locals can celebrate the Sycamores' appearance in the NCAA
Tournament against Texas today and remember the last time Indiana
State made it to the tournament every time they order another
round.
</P>
<P>
   All day today at The Terminal, it's 79 cents a beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because it was 1979 the last time Indiana State made it
to the tournament,'' Purcell said. ``If that doesn't work, our
Sycamore Burgers are $3.79.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the beer-and-burger combo, all anyone had to do to
remember the last Indiana State team to play in the NCAA Tournament
was invoke the name of Larry Bird. That was 21 years ago when Bird
and the Sycamores played in one of the more memorable
national-championship games in history. Despite ``Larry Legend,''
Indiana State lost to a team with another legendary player.
Michigan State, led by Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson, beat the
Sycamores, 75-64, in a game that had the highest TV ratings in NCAA
Tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Indiana State team might not hold a lot in common
with the '79 team. As Sycamores coach Royce Waltman said, ``That
team has taken on a folklore status. People realize that was a
once-in-a-lifetime team and player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird said, however, that this year's team has a chance to pull a
surprise today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen them play a couple times and they've done a good
job,'' said Bird, coach of the NBA's Indiana Pacers. ``They will
keep the score down and make it tough on Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   In '79, the Sycamores made it tough on everyone. They were
undefeated in 33 games when they faced Michigan State. Indiana
State is 22-9 this season, and the Sycamores lost the chance for an
automatic bid when they were defeated by Creighton in the Missouri
Valley Conference tournament championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pairings for the NCAA Tournament already had been
announced during Sunday's nationally televised selection show, and
it was beginning to look as if Indiana State might miss the
tournament again.
</P>
<P>
   But then the West Region bracket came up on the TV screen and
one of the opening-round sites was Salt Lake City. That's when Brad
Miley, a starter on that '79 Indiana State team, started believing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked over at my wife and told her, `Wouldn't it be
appropriate if we make the tournament and play in Salt Lake City?'
'' Miley said. ``It's where we played in the Final Four. And, sure
enough, we're in. That's really brought back some memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Miley, who's 41 and works with a wholesale liquor
distributorship, is one of two prominent members of the '79 team
that still lives in Terre Haute. Bob Heaton, who made two key shots
to keep the team undefeated in '79, joins Miley as a season ticket
holder for Sycamores games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear you've got that big guy \R7-foot Texas center Chris
Mihm\S,'' Heaton said. ``But Nate Green \Rthe Indiana State
guard\S, he's a player. He's legitimate. If he had an outside shot,
he'd be a first-rounder in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Heaton, and every other Sycamore not named Bird, never enjoyed
much basketball success after college. At 43, Heaton is an
insurance broker and financial planner in Terre Haute.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a part of two major plays for the '79 team. Indiana
State was 18-0 heading into a February game at New Mexico State.
Trailing by two points with less than three seconds on the clock,
Heaton banked in a 50-foot desperation shot to send the game into
overtime. The Sycamores eventually won.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest Region final against Arkansas, Heaton hit a shot
in the lane to break a tie game as time expired. He put up his shot
left-handed. Heaton is right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Miley was regarded as a defensive stopper. Against DePaul in the
Final Four semifinal game, Miley was assigned to cover Mark
Aguirre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. Like a lot of guys I covered, he was a
nice player,'' Miley said. ``But I wondered, shoot, didn't they
have better than that? I covered better than that every day in
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Miley covered Bird in practices. With memories like that, he
wonders what's in store today for the Sycamores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is like the way we played because they play hard on
defense,'' Miley said. ``But on offense, well, they don't have
Larry.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
