<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-STATION-HNS &LR;      03-15 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA URGED TO PAY RUSSIA TO HELP BOOST SPACE STATION PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Research Council on Wednesday urged NASA to
consider paying financially-ailing Russia for equipment and
services the country once had promised to donate to the U.S.-led
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Though politically controversial, the strategy could be less
costly to U.S. taxpayers than having NASA take over Russia's pledge
to launch a half-dozen Progress cargo and Soyuz crew capsules
annually, the research council said in a wide-ranging assessment of
issues facing the orbital station once it's assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and political turmoil in Russia have stalled the
construction of the $100 billion, 16-nation project. Though 27
months late, the Russian three-person crew module that is scheduled
for launching in July will jump start the construction that has
been in limbo since the first two components were lofted in late
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Circling the Earth at an altitude of 250 miles, the new space
station is intended to provide a laboratory where scientists can
study the long-term health effects of weightlessness on astronauts.
Among its other uses, the outpost also will furnish a place for
NASA to evaluate equipment that could be used for future human
expeditions to the moon or Mars.
</P>
<P>
   As tensions between the U.S. and Russian space agencies rose at
that point over the future of the project, NASA made $60 million in
payments to Russia to ensure it could complete the one-of-a-kind
crew module and furnish near-term Progress and Soyuz capsules it
had promised in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Progress capsules will deliver fuel for the propulsion
system that will ensure the massive station does not lose altitude
and re-enter the Earth's atmosphere. The Soyuz capsules will
transport U.S. and Russian astronauts to and from the orbital
outpost and while docked serve as a lifeboat that could whisk a
crew to Earth in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, NASA obtained funds from Congress to modify
its space shuttles so they could periodically raise the station's
altitude if the Progress flights fell behind schedule. The United
States also began development of a propulsion module for the
station that would eliminate the need for any Progress flights.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the research council urged NASA to initiate a
formal study that would compare the costs of paying a Russian
aerospace contractor to build and launch the required Progress and
Soyuz craft against the expense of launching more American shuttle
missions and developing a U.S. propulsion module for the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are urging (NASA) to step back and take another look,''
said Thomas Kelly, the retired Grumman aerospace executive who
chaired the research council's 11-member panel. ``Rather than try
to duplicate the Russian hardware it might be better to buy it up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   A change in strategy would involve ``a trade-off between cost
and political considerations,'' one NASA cannot make until it makes
the cost assessment, the panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The politics could be thorny.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, President Clinton signed legislation
restricting U.S. payments to Russia for the station work. Under the
terms of the Iran Nonproliferation Act, payments are barred unless
the United States can confirm Russia has not transferred missile
technology or nuclear, chemical or biological weapons to Iran
during the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's role in the station project was one of a wide range of
issues examined by the research council in its report titled,
``Engineering Challenges to the Long-Term Operation of the
International Space Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding nothing troublesome in the fundamental design of the
proposed station, the panel nevertheless was troubled by the amount
of time American astronauts visiting Russia's Mir space station
spent on maintenance tasks rather than on scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   The panel suggested that NASA include one scientist who is not a
professional astronaut among its seven-member station crews to help
establish a balance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
