<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8147 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-REPUBS-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      03-15 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS IN THE HOUSE CAN'T MATCH BUSH'S TAX CUT PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This story is now on the Times A1; see also BUSH-NYT.)  
(rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In taking their first step toward a federal budget
for next year, House Republicans were left Wednesday in the awkward
position of backing a smaller tax cut than their party's
presumptive presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The tax and spending blueprint, passed by the House Budget
Committee on a party line vote of 23-18, would provide more money
for the Pentagon and education, freeze or cut many other programs
and set aside at least $150 billion and perhaps as much as $250
billion for tax cuts over five years starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan calls for a tax cut of $483 billion over five years
starting in 2002. His plan would require roughly $300 billion for
the tax cuts over the period covered by the House Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans insisted they had no disagreement with Bush
over the size of the tax cut and said they were confident that with
a Republican in the White House they could find the additional
money needed to close the gap between their plans.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican ``with a reform agenda'' like Bush could easily
squeeze another $50 billion out of government spending over five
years, said Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, who is chairman of the budget
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not backing away from the Bush tax cut and neither are
members of this committee,'' Kasich said.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulty that Republican leaders have had in coming up
with a plan that would give Bush all that he wants highlighted
their problems in translating their ideological penchant for
smaller government into spending restraint that even a
Republican-controlled Congress can swallow. And it gave the White
House, Vice President Al Gore and Democrats in Congress a new
opportunity to portray Bush's plan as excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the budget committee went so far as to tweak the
Republicans Wednesday by offering an amendment to the budget plan
calling for Bush's tax plan to be included. The amendment was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, the director of the White House's National
Economic Council, said that ``if you were looking for a
definition'' of fiscal irresponsibility, ``it would be a tax cut
that was so excessive that even the House Republicans are basically
forced to admit they couldn't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said the situation just helped to make his point
that Congress, under pressure from President Clinton, has been far
too willing to spend money and that the best remedy was to send as
much of the government's revenue as possible back to the people who
earned it, the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes that money left in Washington is likely
to be spent, and that covers both parties,'' said Ari Fleischer,
Bush's spokesman. ``It will take a new president to change the way
Washington does business and turn things around.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan passed by the committee calls for an increase in
overall government spending of 3 percent, to $1.85 trillion. About
two-thirds of that amount would go to Social Security, Medicare,
interest payments on the national debt and other commitments that
Congress does not revisit each year.
</P>
<P>
   The other third of the budget, which covers everything from the
space program and the FBI to Head Start and environmental programs,
would rise by 3.16 percent under the Republican plan, to $596.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly all of that increase would go to the military, which
would see its budget rise 6 percent next year, to $307.3 billion.
The increase in non-military programs would be held to three-tenths
of 1 percent, well below the inflation rate, which is running
between 2 and 3 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would set aside $40 billion over five years to finance
a yet-to-be developed plan to add prescription drug coverage to
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would reserve the portion of the surplus generated by
excess Social Security revenues to pay down the national debt. It
would also create a $60 billion reserve that Congress could use
either for further debt reduction or additional tax cuts. And it
would reserve for tax cuts any surplus beyond what is currently
projected by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said it was not unrealistic to believe that the budget
office will increase its surplus projection this year by $40
billion. That money, combined with the $60 billion reserve, would
allow the $150 billion tax cut over five years to rise to as much
as $250 billion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Spratt Jr. of South Carolina, the senior Democrat on
the budget committee, said the proposal would prove to be no more
workable than the Republican budget plans of the last few years,
which set spending at levels for most programs far below what
Congress and Clinton ultimately agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Kasich had made the details of the Republican plan
public, White House officials attacked it. Jacob J. Lew, the
director of the White House's Office of Management, called it
``fundamentally flawed'' and said it would gut a wide array of
programs, from environmental cleanup to aid for poor women and
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
