<DOCNO> NYT20000315.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GREENSPAN-ECONSCENE-A     03-15 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-ECONSCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: WHEN GREENSPAN SPEAKS, STOCK MARKET DOESN'T ALWAYS
LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JEFF MADRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alan Greenspan is no longer taken as seriously on
Wall Street as he once was. Why else did the strong warnings he
made about the lofty levels of stock prices last month go unheeded
by so many? His basic message was right: Over-speculation can
damage the economy. But while the Dow Jones industrials fell on his
comments, if only moderately, investors defiantly sent the
all-important Nasdaq to record highs.
</P>
<P>
   Some still believe that the Nasdaq rose because the technology
stocks that dominate it are relatively immune from any interest
rate increases Greenspan might impose. But that's wishful thinking.
The new economy is still dependent on the much larger old one.
After all, what is going to be sold on the Internet? Even though
Nasdaq gave plenty back this week, it is above the level that
provoked Greenspan to issue his warnings. For that matter, the Dow
industrial average, after Wednesday's rise, made up all but a
couple of percentage points of the ground it had lost.
</P>
<P>
   For all his bluntness, Greenspan was simply not able to deflate
stock portfolios with his warnings. The nation's mutual funds, for
example, were so top-heavy with the high-technology Nasdaq leaders
that they just kept rising in value. ``Despite the bifurcation in
the market, most investors are still up this year,'' says Michael
Lipper, who monitors the funds. To some on Wall Street, Greenspan
is becoming the chairman who talks loudly but carries a little
stick.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is moral hazard, a technical term that means investors
take too much risk because they know that if all goes wrong, they
will be protected by the central bank from having to absorb severe
losses. Such aggressive investing can drive financial prices to
insupportable levels.
</P>
<P>
   Moral hazard is not the only factor that pushes asset prices to
irrational heights _ greed has no small part. But many believe it
contributed significantly to the Asian financial crisis of 1997.
The bailouts came in the form of giant emergency loans.
</P>
<P>
   To many Americans, moral hazard is something that only happens
elsewhere. But consider our own bailouts. In 1987, Greenspan
admirably engineered an infusion of money worldwide after the
market crash. Stock prices came back, and major economies avoided
recession. In 1997, he supplied liquidity again to offset the
escalating Asian financial crisis. Again, the West averted
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan even injected funds late last year to forestall
problems that some feared would result as computers and other
electronic equipment crossed into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   However necessary these actions were, they had an unfortunate
consequence: Many in the markets now seem to believe Greenspan will
always save the day. Moreover, there is a suggestion in his public
pronouncements that he is not sufficiently sensitive to this. He
warns of irrational exuberance, on the one hand, only to present a
case, on the other hand, that a new economy can continue to grow
rapidly without inflation. Robert J. Shiller, a Yale economist,
writes in his new book ``Irrational Exuberance'' (Princeton
University Press) that cheering on investors while warning them not
to speculate is no way to maintain credibility.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks before Congress last month, the Fed chairman
cloaked his market concerns in terms of fighting inflation, but my
guess is that he was really worried that a stock market flying so
much higher than its historical norms is at risk of collapse.
Greenspan knows that any such collapse could result in a
recessionary reduction in spending by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately more dangerous, a fall in stock prices could induce a
run on the U.S. dollar as foreign investors withdraw money and U.S.
investors seek greener pastures abroad. A falling dollar would then
push up interest rates and import prices. To control inflation, the
Fed might have to tighten further.
</P>
<P>
   The virtuous circle of a high dollar, high stock prices, low
inflation and low interest rates could suddenly slip into the
vicious circle of a falling dollar, falling stock prices and rising
inflation and interest rates. Recession would not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Here is my pipe dream. The Fed chairman at last recognizes that
he needs two weapons to fight on two fronts. To be sure, this would
require Greenspan to break the self-imposed rules that restrict the
Fed to monitoring inflation and economic growth. But some of
history's most successful central bankers were at their best when
they broke their own rules.
</P>
<P>
   At next Tuesday's Fed policy meeting, Greenspan should consider
raising interest rates no more than a quarter point, as expected,
but he should also do the unexpected and raise the 50 percent
margin requirement on stock purchases to stanch market speculation.
Admittedly, there are plenty of ways around such margin
requirements these days, which require investors to put up half the
purchase price in cash. But if margin debt, now at record levels,
is so meaningless, why are so many people resorting to it?
</P>
<P>
   Raising margin requirements alone would not have much bite, but
if margin requirements and interest rates were raised
simultaneously, Greenspan could restore some credibility and send a
strong message to the Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed should also consider tightening its capital requirements
on risky bank loans to big investors. Reducing speculation by
restricting credit now would help Greenspan avoid larger and quite
painful rate increases in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The real fear is whether he has waited too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
