<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- HARLEM-RENEWAL-1 -- The
predominant language in south-central Harlem these days is the
language of renewal. Tony Morgan, an Australian-born graphic
designer, sold his Greenwich Village co-op and bought a four-story
brownstone on West 118th Street for $237,000. ``My friends couldn't
believe it when I moved to Harlem,'' said Morgan, 28, laughing.
``But then they came here, and saw what I had!'' He restored the
building - which now might be worth more than $600,000 - but
Morgan, who moved in last November, said he is not selling.
(Jeffrey Henson Scales/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W --
There are a number of techniques you can employ to dry a wet
basement and avoid it getting wet in the first place. For the
first, you must determine where the water is coming from, and then
you can plan an effective strategy to end the problem. There are
three major sources of basement water: condensation, runoff and
subsurface penetration. (Edward R. Lipinski/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) BAYREUTH, Germany -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 19 -- WAGNER-MUSIC-2-B&AMP;W -- Hans Knappertsbusch leading
``Gotterdammerung'' in 1951, a celebrated performance at the first
postwar Bayreuth Festival. The historic label Testament has
released the previously unpublished recording on 4 CDs. (Bayreuth
Festival/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) BAYREUTH, Germany -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 19 -- WAGNER-MUSIC-1-B&AMP;W -- A scene from Act II of
``Gotterdammerung,'' in a legendary performance conducted by Hans
Knappertsbusch in 1951 at the first postwar Bayreuth Festival. The
historic label Testament has released the previously unpublished
recording on 4 CDs. (Bayreuth Festival/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- WEB-BOOKS -- In the first
24-hour after posting ``Riding the Bullet'' on various internet
websites, readers overwhelmed leading online booksellers with
purchases or orders to download the 66-page digital horror story
into their computers, electronic readers or Palm Pilots. No one
seemed sure whether the sizable sales could usher in a coming
revolution in mass market electronic publishing or simply a
literary novelty involving the first marquee author to dabble in
bytes. (Simon &AMP; Schuster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NY-GUNS-PATAKI -- Gov.
George Pataki of New York, center, holds a large scale model of a
bullet casing as he is shown hand guns with locking mechanisms by
Sgt. Craig Grazier of the New York State Police, Wednesday. In a
move that distances him from fellow Republicans, Pataki called
Wednesday for a ``common sense'' series of gun control measures in
New York, including mandatory trigger locks and the taking of
ballistic ``fingerprints'' before guns are sold. (Don Hogan
Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
VIRGIL-THOMSON-MUSIC -- To a devoted core of admirers and critics,
``The Mother of Us All'' by Virgil Thomson, which comes to the New
York City Opera this Sunday afternoon in a new production by
Christopher Alden first unveiled at the Glimmerglass Opera in 1998,
is the most original and arguably the greatest of American operas.
Lauren Flanigan, left, and Ruthann Manley rehearsed for the New
York City Opera presentation of ``The Mother of Us All.'' (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 15, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas during an interview with the New York Times at the
governor's mansion, Wednesday. (Phillippe Diederich/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BEIJING -- March 15, 2000 -- CHINA-TAIWAN-BUSINESS -- As
Chinese leaders threatened military action against Taiwan, it was
business as usual at the Purple Vine, an elegant Taiwan-style tea
house in the Chinese capital, where its owner, Zha Fuhua, carefully
choreographed the preparation of wulong tea. ``The political
tension hasn't had the slightest impact on me,'' said Zha, a Taipei
native, who counts many mainland officials as loyal customers.
(Elisabeth Rosenthal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
MUSCLE-WOMEN-ART-2 -- ``Achieving Failure: Gym Culture 2000,'' an
exhibit opening at the Thread Waxing Space on Friday and running
through April 29, will take a critical look at the body beautiful
and all that's needed to attain it: free weights, machines,
barbells and, of course, mirrors. A young patriot in the locker
room in a photo from ``Wrestler Series'' (1998), by Jessica Wynne.
(Thread Waxing Space/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
MUSCLE-WOMEN-ART-1 -- ``Picturing the Modern Amazon,'' which opens
March 30 and runs through July 2 at the New Museum of Contemporary
Art in SoHo, will unabashedly proclaim a new participant in the
30-year-old discussion of body art: the hypermuscular woman.
Kathleen Gilje's ``Comtesse d'Haussonville, Restored'' (1996),
joins the Ingres portrait with Robert Mapplethorpe's Lisa Lyon.
(New Museum of Contemporary Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
TV-HEWITT-HEPBURN -- Jennifer Love Hewitt as Audrey Hepburn as
Holly Golightly, in the forthcoming television movie about the
actress. Miscast or not, she will surely do her best, and the
movie, like most movies, will be promptly forgotten in any case.
What seems to gall people is the potential damage that might be
done to their memories, however imprecise, of Hepburn. (ABC/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
CRUDUP-FILMS -- Billy Crudup, 31, has several times been touted as
the next big thing, an actor whose name would become as familiar as
DiCaprio or Damon or Affleck. This time, the buzz is for his work
in the new movie ``Waking the Dead,'' based on Scott Spencer's
novel about an up-and-coming politician haunted by intertwined
memories of lost love and abandoned ideals. ``You gravitate toward
the things that people give you the most positive feedback for,''
Crudup, 31, said. ``And I was, for whatever reason, good at being a
sort of class clown and mimicking different characters.'' (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
REGGIO-FILMS -- Godfrey Reggio's films are out-of-this-world
experiences - not to mention solar systems away from conventional
Hollywood moviemaking - yet it is difficult to deny the influence
of Reggio's vision on the surfaces of modern pop culture. `` We
don't live with the natural environment,'' he said. ``There's so
much interest in aliens because we are the aliens. We are
off-planet.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NIKKO-FIRS-2 -- Kim Tripp
admiring a tanyosho pine at the New York Botanical Garden in the
Bronx. ``These trees are the most extraordinary in the country,''
said Dr. Tripp, the garden's vice president for horticulture.
``Even in Japan, a grove of this distinction would be highly
revered.'' (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NIKKO-FIRS-1 -- The
magnificent Nikko firs at the New York Botanical Garden in the
Bronx may be in trouble because of dry summers and variable
winters. These shallow-rooted firs can't reach deep into the earth
for moisture during a drought. And when temperatures rise in
winter, the trees begin photosynthesizing and losing water. Add to
that the heavy metals and other pollutants of city life, and, well,
these firs are on shaky ground. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- MORALS-EDUC -- Rachel Rear
(back to the camera), taught a 10th-grade humanities class at the
East Side Community High School in Manhattan - the kind of course
that once would have been confined to explicitly religious schools
or private institutions. The program is called Facing History and
Ourselves and is one of a growing number being taught in the New
York City region as moral education has found a place in American
schools. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- March 15, 2000 -- TECH-VISAS-COX -- Rep.
Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, joined a bipartisan group of House members
Wednesday to introduce another version of legislation to raise the
number of high-skilled workers allowed to immigrate under H-1B
visas. From background, left: Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., Rep. Jennifer
Dunn, R-Wa., Rep. Adam Smith, D-Wash., Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif.
and Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) GUADALUPE VALLEY, Mexico -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
MARCH 19 -- MEXICO-WINE-COX-3 -- Arminda Huerta, a winery worker at
Monte Xanic Winery, prunes dead leaves from grape vines. Blessed by
a cooling coastal fog that takes the hot edge off the region's
near-desert terrain, the region, located in a valley on the Pacific
Ocean side of Mexico's Baja California, is starting to produce
award-winning wines that are gaining a toehold at upscale
restaurants and among wine lovers on both sides of the border.
(Fred Greaves/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GUADALUPE VALLEY, Mexico -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
MARCH 19 -- MEXICO-WINE-COX-2 -- Hans Backhoff pours a sample of
Merlot aging in a French oak barrel at his winery, Monte Xanic, in
the Guadalupe Valley, a pocket of surprisingly fertile land on the
Pacific Ocean side of Mexico's Baja California. ``It's the
influence of the sea. That's what makes this valley so special,''
Backhoff said about the region's climate. Blessed by a cooling
coastal fog that takes the hot edge off the region's near-desert
terrain, the valley is starting to produce award-winning wines that
are gaining a toehold at upscale restaurants and among wine lovers
on both sides of the border. (Susan Ferriss/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) GUADALUPE VALLEY, Mexico -- March 15, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
MARCH 19 -- MEXICO-WINE-COX-1 -- Victor Torres next to barrels of
his wine at the Chateau Camou Winery. Torres is among a new breed
of winemakers in the Guadalupe Valley, a pocket of surprisingly
fertile land on the Pacific Ocean side of Mexico's Baja California.
The valley is only about 50 miles southeast of the border city of
San Diego. Blessed by a cooling coastal fog that takes the hot edge
off the region's near-desert terrain, the valley is starting to
produce award-winning wines that are gaining a toehold at upscale
restaurants and among wine lovers on both sides of the border.
(Susan Ferriss/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- March 15, 2000 -- CLINTON-GUNS -- Flanked
by Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., left, and Rep. Carolyn McCarthy,
D-N.Y., President Clinton speaks about gun control legislation,
Wednesday. Clinton accused the National Rifle Association of
political skullduggery Wednesday as he welcomed fellow Democrats
and an improbable Republican to a White House pep rally on gun
control. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PHILADELPHIA -- March 15, 2000 -- GORE-LABOR -- One day
after locking up the Democratic nomination, Vice President Al Gore
warned supporters in organized labor Wednesday that Republicans
were ``manning the barricades'' in the race for the White House.
Gore addresses nearly 1,000 people at a meeting of the Pennsylvania
chapter of the AFL-CIO, Wednesday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- CIR-ONLINE-LEARNING --
Forget learning for the sake of enlightenment. How about learning
as a marketing weapon. Several companies are working on free online
courses to draw customers to web sites to buy software and other
goods. Michael Rosenfelt, founder of notHarvard.com, a commercial
education site, with colleagues, from left, Paul Danziger, Judy
Bitterli and Bruce Gee. (Matthew Sturtevant/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- CIR-TRACKING-KIDS-2 --
``It's a leash at this age,'' says Evan Losow, a a 16-year-old high
school junior about pagers and cell phones. ``When I'm out of the
house, I'm out for a reason. I really don't want people to contact
me.'' Not since the days of chaperones and high-button shoes have
parents had the ability to track their kids the way they can today
with various electronic devices. (Susan Farley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 15, 2000 -- CIR-TRACKING-KIDS --
Not since the days of chaperones, high-button shoes and tongue-tied
gentleman callers have parents had the ability to track their kids
the way they can today with various electronic devices. From left,
Danielle Broude, Maura Tuohy, Elena Gonzalez and Robi Tse with
pagers and cell phones at Lowell High School. (Thor Swift/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DEKALB, Ill. -- March 15, 2000 -- SCI-PRIMATE-FOSSIL-2 --
Dan Gebo, a paleontologist with Northern Illinois University, holds
the teeth of Eosimias. Fossil bones of the animal, no bigger than a
shrew and weighing less than an ounce, have been identified as
belonging to the earliest known relative of the primate lineage
that led to monkeys, apes and eventually humans. The
paleontologists, who announced the discovery Wednesday, said the
fossil animal, named Eosimias for ``dawn monkey,'' was the best
evidence yet for fixing the time and place of one of the more
fateful branchings in evolution. (Scott Walstrom, Northern Illinois
University/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 15, 2000 -- SCI-PRIMATE-FOSSIL-1 --
Fossil bones of an animal no bigger than a shrew and weighing less
than an ounce have been identified as belonging to the earliest
known relative of the primate lineage that led to monkeys, apes and
eventually humans. The paleontologists who announced the discovery
Wednesday said the fossil animal, named Eosimias for ``dawn
monkey,'' seen here to scale in an artist's rendering, was the best
evidence yet for fixing the time and place of one of the more
fateful branchings in evolution. (Illustration by Kim Reed-Deemer,
Northern Illinois University/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DUXBURY, Mass. -- March 15, 2000 -- FOOD-SCHOOL-CHEF-BOS
-- Garth Petracca, food services director at Duxbury High School,
with samples of his work in the school's lunch room. Petracca is
waging a culinary war to conquer young stomachs -- and he's
winning. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- March 15, 2000 -- RETURNING-JEWS-BOS -- Jill
Ringel, a 21-year-old Northeastern University student, demonstrates
how she observes Shabbat. College students and young adults like
Ringel, reared in households where religion was almost invisible,
are turning in significant numbers to traditional forms of Judaism.
They are called ba'alai tshuvah, or ``the returning.'' (Justine
Ellement/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- March 15, 2000 -- METAL-DECOR-COX --
Metal is back with a vengeance. After years of being limited to
patio furniture and contemporary pieces that blended best with
modern decor, designers are creating metal furnishings in every
form imaginable. An example of which is Craig Brotman's home in
Alpharetta which has many metal accessories along with more
traditionalfurniture. (Louie Favorite/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ATLANTA -- March 15, 2000 -- DESIGN-AWARD-COX -- Michael
Gilmartin sitting in one of his unfinished chairs next to the Avos
armchair whose design was the receipient of the national Award for
Design Excellence presented by Design Journal. The Avos is made of
a special Douglas fir plywood and reminiscent of the work of modern
designer Charles Eames. (Louie Favorite/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
