   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 03/15/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NY-SUBPRIME-LENDING --
Regulators in New York state, the nation's largest banking center
and an industry pace setter, are devising new rules to crack down
on predatory lenders who impose exorbitant fees that force
countless homeowners into foreclosure and bankruptcy. This house in
East Flatbush, Brooklyn, was foreclosed upon by the bank. (Michelle
V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. -- March 15, 2000 --
INTEL-AWARDS-SCHOOL-3 -- Theories abound as to why Paul D.
Schreiber High School achieved a stunning victory in the nationwide
Intel Science Talent Search this year, producing the first-place
winner and two other finalists and stealing the thunder of the
highly selective New York City schools that have traditionally
dominated the contest. Viviana Risca, a Romanian immigrant who won
first prize for encrypting a secret message on a strand of DNA,
will receive a $100,000 college scholarship as well. (Vic
DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. -- March 15, 2000 --
INTEL-AWARDS-SCHOOL-2 -- Paul D. Schreiber High School achieved a
stunning victory in the nationwide Intel Science Talent Search this
year, producing the first-place winner and two other finalists.
Perhaps the main reason that students here excell in such a contest
is that 15 years ago the school started a program to teach students
how to perform sophisticated research. Phyllis Serfaty, a biology
teacher who heads the program, said the work created a rigorous
schedule for teachers as well as the 90 students involved. (Vic
DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. -- March 15, 2000 --
INTEL-AWARDS-SCHOOL-1 -- Theories abound as to why Paul D.
Schreiber High School achieved a stunning victory in the nationwide
Intel Science Talent Search this year, producing the first-place
winner and two other finalists and stealing the thunder of the
highly selective New York City schools that have traditionally
dominated the contest. Tim Koo, a 15-year-old sophomore, checked on
his plants for a project on Potassium Phosphate as a fungicide.
(Vic DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- HARLEM-RENEWAL-4 -- Once
nearly destroyed by drugs, crime and debilitation, Harlem is on the
way up. In south-central Harlem, a modest renaissance encompassing
renovated brownstones, storefront restaurants and new church- and
mosque-sponsored condominiums has been taking place. Shabazz
Gardens, a 41 town-house development on West 117th Street sponsored
by the neighboring Masjid Malcolm Shabazz mosque, offers subsidized
mortgages. (Jeffrey Henson Scales/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- HARLEM-RENEWAL-3 -- Once
nearly destroyed by drugs, crime and debilitation, Harlem is on the
way up. In south-central Harlem, a modest renaissance encompassing
renovated brownstones, storefront restaurants and new church- and
mosque-sponsored condominiums has been taking place. Community
leaders credit the West Africans who have settled around West 116th
Street with making the neighborhood a community once more. (Jeffrey
Henson Scales/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- HARLEM-RENEWAL-2 -- On the
brick and brownstone plain of south-central Harlem, thousands of
new arrivals are putting down roots: black and white, richer and
poorer. In their robes and headdresses, especially on holy days,
West African Muslims may be the most recognizable. The word has
gone out: This neighborhood has cheap rents and many countrymen.
Sauveur Andre, an immigrant, runs a barbershop whose primary
language is French. (Jeffrey Henson Scales/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- HARLEM-RENEWAL-1 -- The
predominant language in south-central Harlem these days is the
language of renewal. Tony Morgan, an Australian-born graphic
designer, sold his Greenwich Village co-op and bought a four-story
brownstone on West 118th Street for $237,000. ``My friends couldn't
believe it when I moved to Harlem,'' said Morgan, 28, laughing.
``But then they came here, and saw what I had!'' He restored the
building - which now might be worth more than $600,000 - but
Morgan, who moved in last November, said he is not selling.
(Jeffrey Henson Scales/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
