REGGIO-FILMS -- Godfrey Reggio's films are out-of-this-world
experiences - not to mention solar systems away from conventional
Hollywood moviemaking - yet it is difficult to deny the influence
of Reggio's vision on the surfaces of modern pop culture. `` We
don't live with the natural environment,'' he said. ``There's so
much interest in aliens because we are the aliens. We are
off-planet.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NIKKO-FIRS-2 -- Kim Tripp
admiring a tanyosho pine at the New York Botanical Garden in the
Bronx. ``These trees are the most extraordinary in the country,''
said Dr. Tripp, the garden's vice president for horticulture.
``Even in Japan, a grove of this distinction would be highly
revered.'' (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- NIKKO-FIRS-1 -- The
magnificent Nikko firs at the New York Botanical Garden in the
Bronx may be in trouble because of dry summers and variable
winters. These shallow-rooted firs can't reach deep into the earth
for moisture during a drought. And when temperatures rise in
winter, the trees begin photosynthesizing and losing water. Add to
that the heavy metals and other pollutants of city life, and, well,
these firs are on shaky ground. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 15, 2000 -- MORALS-EDUC -- Rachel Rear
(back to the camera), taught a 10th-grade humanities class at the
East Side Community High School in Manhattan - the kind of course
that once would have been confined to explicitly religious schools
or private institutions. The program is called Facing History and
Ourselves and is one of a growing number being taught in the New
York City region as moral education has found a place in American
schools. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
