<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;      03-15 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE CAMPS APPEAL FOR PRE-CONVENTION DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla., Ark., Md., Calif., N.M., Puerto Rico)  (See also BUSH, GORE) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his $70 million campaign treasury spent, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas has started trying to raise a fast $10
million to finance a pre-convention campaign against Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Republican National Committee was
accelerating pleas to big-dollar donors to produce as much as $100
million before the Republican convention in July. The party has
planned extensive television advertising to promote Bush's
candidacy and attack Gore and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bush dismissed as a cynical stunt Gore's offer by
e-mail on Tuesday night to forswear advertising financed by soft
money if the Republicans did the same. He said Gore had not
answered questions raised by the possibly illegal fund raising of
the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``New campaign finance laws are needed,'' Bush told Gore in an
e-mail response to the vice president's message. ``What is even
more important is the duty of public officials to obey the existing
laws, and I'm afraid your own record does not inspire confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, with roughly $13 million left to spend before the
Democratic convention in August, would help the Democratic Party
meet a goal of $35 million to produce issue advertisements over the
next four months.
</P>
<P>
   The simultaneous Republican fund raising has been designed to
avoid the problem faced at this time four years ago by Bob Dole,
the Republican presidential nominee. Dole emerged from that year's
primaries bruised and broke while President Clinton mounted a
multimillion-dollar television campaign against him in the months
leading up to the parties' conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six weeks, Bush, his wife and his father are
scheduled to appear at a dozen fund-raising events to replenish his
campaign's hard money accounts. That money, which must come in
increments of $1,000 or less, could be used for almost any purpose
to support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The first was scheduled for Thursday evening in Wheaton, Ill., a
suburb of Chicago. Over the next two weeks, Bush would also court
donors at events in Palm Beach, Fla., Little Rock, Ark.,
Parsippany, N.J., New York and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush has planned to appear on his son's
behalf at fund-raisers in California, New Mexico and Puerto Rico
over the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's fund-raising challenge is greater this year because
of his astounding financial success last year, when he raised $70
million, three-quarters of it in checks for $1,000, the maximum
allowed under federal law. He must now find new donors to restock
his larder.
</P>
<P>
   The easy fruit has been picked, said Peter Secchia, a longtime
Republican activist from Michigan and one of the Bush Pioneers, the
elite fund-raisers who each collected more than $100,000 for the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time we've had to raise money after a
primary,'' Secchia said. ``But the memory of what the Democrats did
to Dole with all their illegal money gives us a stimulus to go out
and compete. The money they spent in '96 from March to August was
horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Republican National Committee has planned
to amass a large bankroll of soft money, the unlimited
contributions from corporations, unions and wealthy individuals.
That money could not be used to directly appeal for votes for or
against a candidate, but the law has so many loopholes and has been
so poorly enforced that the political message of such issue
advertisements has often been transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour, a former Republican National Committee chairman
and an adviser to Bush, said the Republicans would aggressively
solicit soft money to counteract plans by the Democrats and their
allies in organized labor to spend tens of millions of dollars in
support of Gore now and in the fall. ``We can raise the money to be
competitive, I have no doubt of that,'' Barbour said. ``But the
party has to be careful they have money and a plan for the fall
campaign and doesn't overspend during the interregnum.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush would also be bolstered by spending by groups sympathetic
to Republican causes: anti-abortion groups, business and trade
associations, corporate executives and ideological allies like the
Christian Coalition and the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   One such group, Americans for Tax Reform, has planned to run
advertisements that would indirectly help the Bush campaign by
emphasizing tax cuts, partial privatization of Social Security and
a reduction in the estate tax. The group ran such advertisements in
New Hampshire that were widely seen as pro-Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't advocate election or defeat of candidates,'' said
Grover Norquist, the executive director of Americans for Tax
Reform. ``But we raise issues that others might presume helpful or
harmful to particular candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Wednesday that he was preparing for an onslaught of
negative advertising from the Bush campaign, the Republican party
and conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to understand the other side is going to throw
everything they've got plus the kitchen sink,'' Gore said at an
AFL-CIO meeting in Philadelphia on Wednesday afternoon. ``They're
manning the barricades, they're trying to funnel unprecedented
amounts of money into the campaign. They're going to stop at
nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
