<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR BIAS FOR BEAUTY IS SHOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Dear Applicant: Thank you for your interest in XYZ
Inc. Unfortunately, we have no positions suitable for you at this
time. We only hire attractive people. Sincerely, Ima Bewti.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that any job hunter has ever received that kind of
rejection letter. And it would be hard to find an employer who
would admit preferring better-looking employees over less
attractive ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that physical appearance counts in the work
world.
</P>
<P>
   Social science research finds that employment discrimination
exists against people who are judged uglier, fatter or
significantly shorter than the socially accepted norms of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dipboye, a professor of psychology at Rice University,
will lead a discussion on ``the unattractiveness factor'' next
month at the annual Society for Industrial and Organizational
Psychology conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dipboye's research concludes that hiring selections, work
appraisals and promotions are biased in favor of the young, the
physically unimpaired and those who aren't significantly
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   He has found widely shared social norms about what constitutes
attractiveness, and learned that women and men who most closely
meet those norms are more likely to achieve occupational success
than are those who deviate from the accepted standards.
</P>
<P>
   There is an unfortunate side effect from being influenced by
standards of beauty or handsomeness, whether intentionally or
subconsciously: It sustains racism, sexism, ageism and other forms
of physical prejudice in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Author Steven M. Jeffes talks about this kind of prejudice in
Appearance Is Everything: The Hidden Truth Regarding Your
Appearance Discrimination. He includes data from tests and
demographic surveys. He writes that attractive people:
</P>
<P>
   - Are two to five times more likely to be hired.
</P>
<P>
   - Earn 12 percent to 16 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   - Are significantly more likely to be elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, Jeffes writes that unattractive people are:
</P>
<P>
   - Two to four times more likely to be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   - Two to five times more likely to be convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Extremely likely'' to be passed over for promotions.
</P>
<P>
   We say that beauty is only skin deep. We say that beauty is in
the eye of the beholder. Some of us may truly believe it.
</P>
<P>
   But if the social science testing has any validity at all, we
have to accept that we are, as a society, a bunch of hypocrites.
Looks matter a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffes has gathered data to buttress the argument that
appearance discrimination should be added to the Civil Rights Act
of 1964, which bars discrimination based on other factors of
affiliation and appearance, such as skin color.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, anyone who feels overlooked or outcast because of
looks might want to read his book. (Amazon.com and
Barnesandnoble.com both list it as a special order at $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Jeffes does more than cite discrimination examples. He also
gives strategies to help the less comely compete in a world prone
to judge books by their covers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
