<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8170 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-BEER-NOTMILK-KAN &LR;      03-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NOTMILK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETA'S ANTI-MILK, PRO-BEER CAMPAIGN HAS OPPONENTS FROTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got beer?
</P>
<P>
   That's what People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals is
asking college students in a campaign touting beer as a better
beverage choice than milk.
</P>
<P>
   At its Web site for its anti-milk cause _ which can be linked
from the organization's main Internet site, www.peta.com _ PETA
urges college students and others ``to wipe off those milk
mustaches and replace them with ... foam? The largest animal rights
group in the world is releasing the results of research showing
that beer is actually better for you than milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later on the site, PETA says its real ``beef'' is the way
dairy cattle are treated.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Perry of the Kansas City, Mo.-based Dairy Farmers of
America, the nation's largest dairy cooperative, said he was used
to attacks on his industry. But this, he said, takes the cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous,'' Perry said. ``What they've done is a
terrible, terrible injustice to everyone. No one ever drank too
much milk, got behind the wheel of a car and killed someone.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the issue of how dairy cattle are treated, Perry said that
there had been instances of mistreatment but that such cases
weren't common.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make economic sense,'' he said. ``You can't afford
to have cows in situations where they aren't comfortable, because
they won't give milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Copeland, an adviser to Greeks Advocating Mature
Management of Alcohol at the University of Missouri-Kansas City,
said he found PETA's campaign irresponsible and reprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   A study released just this week by the Harvard School of Public
Health reports that binge drinking on campuses is up from just two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No good will come of this,'' Copeland said. ``And it's not
just college students who can access (PETA's) Web site encouraging
the drinking of beer _ it's kids of all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   But the animal rights group stands by its claims, saying that by
drinking beer instead of milk, college students will have less fat
in their diets, consume fewer calories and cholesterol, and get
fiber they can't get from milk. It also says milk contributes to
myriad health problems.
</P>
<P>
   PETA, perhaps best known for its red-paint attacks on women
wearing fur, is a 20-year-old group with 600,000 members. Its
mission, as posted on its Web site, ``is dedicated to establishing
and protecting the rights of all animals. PETA operates under the
simple principle that animals are not ours to eat, wear, experiment
on, or use for entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   To publicize its anti-milk campaign, PETA has given away
thousands of bottle openers shaped like beer bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that would be a fun, lighthearted way to get
students to respond,'' said Morgan Leyh, PETA's college action
campaign coordinator, who writes on the Web site: ``Colleges have
been busy banning kegs from campus. But we say, `Ditch the dairy,
not the beer!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a group that
more often than not finds itself on the same side as PETA, is
outraged.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Leyh, her counterpart at the center, Kimberly
Miller, takes PETA to task. She accuses the group of promoting a
heavy-drinking culture that already pervades campuses, contributing
to alcohol poisoning, drunken driving, sexual assault and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``This juvenile gimmick reflects a gross lack of judgment and
cynical disregard for a very serious public health and safety issue
and further undermines your organization's credibility (such as it
is). ... Surely you can find a way to advance your agenda that does
not come at the expense of college students,'' Miller wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Leyh pooh-poohs the notion that PETA's campaign will further
promote beer drinking on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many college students who drink responsibly,
and this isn't going to change that,'' Leyh said.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Butterworth, a Los Angeles clinical psychologist who
specializes in teen drug and alcohol abuse, vehemently disagrees
and thinks PETA's latest protest will alienate some who in the past
have supported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, people who have drug and alcohol problems are great at
rationalizing why they drink and do drugs,'' Butterworth said. ``I
can see it now: `Oh, gee, if I drink milk, I'll get too much fat,
so I'll drink beer because PETA says it's healthier.' ''
</P>
<P>
   People posting messages this week on alcohol-related Web sites
were in a tizzy over PETA's tactic, including a visitor to the
self-help site Another Empty Bottle. Her comment:
</P>
<P>
   ``Got brains? Whoever came up with this latest PETA campaign
doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
