<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPROVAL OF HOUSE RESOLUTION A RARE VICTORY FOR GUN CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pressure mounted on gun-control opponents Wednesday
as House Democrats succeeded in passing a symbolic resolution that
would at least require child safety locks on all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, New York Republican Gov. George Pataki stunned
some gun-control opponents by calling for more ``common sense'' gun
laws, including mandatory trigger locks, increasing the age for gun
ownership from 18 to 21, instant background checks at gun shows and
``ballistic fingerprinting'' to help trace spent ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about the politics here. I'm concerned about
the policy and the policy will make our streets safer,'' Pataki
said. He rejected claims by pro-gun Republican leaders that the
Democrats are trying to play election-year politics with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he decided to speak out in part because more
New Yorkers are being killed each year by gun violence than in car
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Gov. George Bush, the presumed GOP presidential
nominee, also backed Pataki's call for trigger or safety locks,
dealing another blow to gun control opponents in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the House was 218-205 on a non-binding resolution
that is not likely to force members of the Senate and House
judiciary committees to meet and resolve differences over gun
control measures. But its passage, combined with Pataki's comments,
sent a strong signal to gun control opponents that support is
growing not only in Congress but around the country for tougher
laws to help reduce the number of deaths each year caused by gun
violence, especially among children.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the
House-Senate committee, to call a meeting. On Wednesday, Hatch did
not specifically address the resolution but said he was
disappointed that President Clinton has ignored his suggestions for
bolstering enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, he has acted on none of these overdue
reforms,'' Hatch told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the House followed a heated two-hour debate in which
Democrats accused Republicans of stalling on the issue and
Republicans charged that the Democrats were trying to make
political hay out of it by using recent gun violence tragedies to
help make their case for more control measures.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association also joined opponents in lobbying
against the resolution, warning members that their votes on the
issue would be watched closely to gauge their loyalty to the NRA,
one of the richest and most powerful special interest groups in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Calling attention to the NRA lobbying effort, Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee, D-Texas, told her colleagues that the organization
``has such a dominant hand on members of this Congress that they
can't even wiggle themselves out'' to support moderate gun safety
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA tactics also came under fire from President Clinton, who
said the organization is intent on preventing a conference from
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again the gun lobby and their allies in the leadership of
the Congress is standing in the way of real progress,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre told
the AP that the White House was trying to ``demonize'' the NRA to
distract attention from ``the complete collapse of enforcement'' of
existing gun laws by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke at the White House, he was surrounded by a
number of Democrats and a handful of Republicans who would like to
see gun control measures passed this year. They included Rep. James
Rogan, R-Calif., who was a member of the House prosecution team
that outlined the case against Clinton in his Senate impeachment
trial last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan did not comment, but an aide said later that he was there
to show his support for a House-Senate conference on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach a compromise between the House and Senate on
new gun control laws have been in limbo since August when a
juvenile justice bill containing provisions requiring child safety
locks on handguns, three-day background checks for gun shows and
other measures was shelved because of differences with the House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
