<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS OF SPRINT-MCI MERGER ARRIVING IN SHAREHOLDERS' MAILBOXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shareholders of Sprint Corp. and Sprint PCS will begin receiving
textbook-size packets this week detailing the company's proposed
merger with MCI WorldCom and asking for their vote in favor of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company began mailing a proxy statement of more than 400
pages and an addendum to its 141,800 shareholders of record this
week in preparation for a special shareholders meeting set for
April 28 at Sprint's Westwood, Kan., headquarters. MCI WorldCom
will hold its own special shareholders meeting on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The packet describes the merger, the merger agreement,
background to the merger and stockholder rights, among other
things, and includes an amended copy of Sprint's bylaws and
articles of incorporation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the merger, shareholders are asked to approve an
amendment to the company's bylaws concerning its former partners in
Global One _ France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom _ and approve
issuing additional shares of Sprint PCS for Sprint's employee
stock-purchase program.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the usual boilerplate language, the documents offer
shareholders a detailed account of how the deal came together. The
proxy, for example, provides a blow-by-blow account of the
company's competing merger talks with Deutsche Telekom and
BellSouth Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It also explains how investment bankers quantified Sprint's
value and potential synergies from the deal, and details the
financial interests that Sprint's directors and executive officers
have in the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Those interests are substantial, as outlined in the summary
table of executive compensation included in the proxy.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the huge option awards made to senior executives in
recent years, Sprint's board of directors topped off chairman
William T. Esrey's 1999 compensation of $2.5 million with fresh
options. Those option awards would generate about $57 million if
exercised today, and would be worth around $90 million at the time
of the merger if the price of Sprint PCS remains steady.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives whose options were detailed in the proxy
include Ronald T. LeMay, president and chief operating officer;
Kevin Brauer, president of Sprint business and national integrated
services; Arthur Krause, chief financial officer; and Andrew
Sukawaty, president of Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey, LeMay and Krause received special retention options
designed to keep them at the company after Sprint's special
shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey, who is expected to become the chairman of the new
WorldCom, got options to buy 216,000 shares of Sprint at $61.94
each and 216,000 shares of Sprint PCS at $54.25 each.
</P>
<P>
   LeMay, who is expected to become chief operating officer of
WorldCom, got options on 135,000 shares of Sprint and 134,000
shares of Sprint PCS. Krause, whose future has not been discussed,
received options on 54,000 shares of Sprint and 54,000 shares of
Sprint PCS under the retention arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement also provides for an employee retention
pool of as much as $100 million to be used for cash retention
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's merger with MCI WorldCom still needs regulatory
approval from the Department of Justice, the Federal Communications
Commission and the European Commission. It has faced vocal
opposition from consumer groups, unions and some business advocacy
groups, who think it would result in too much concentration in the
Internet and long-distance businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey has said the company is willing to address any issues
regulators have with concentration in the Internet market,
indicating a willingness to divest some assets to get the deal
approved.
</P>
<P>
   But his public position on long-distance is less flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for some of the consumer groups who constantly fear the
specter of high prices, let me just say, for God's sake, `Take an
economics course,' '' he told an audience in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the average long-distance call costs less than a third
of what it did in 1984,'' he said. ``And prices will continue to be
under pressure because of an abundance of capacity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
