<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OIL-MERGER-FTC-1STLD-     03-15 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MERGER-FTC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND 3 STATES HALT EFFORT TO BLOCK BP AMOCO-ARCO DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Ore., Wash.)   (SUBS for additional detail and rewriting throughout, including the
involvement of the 3 states and more info about Philips' role;
story grows by about 700 words; former double byline becomes single
byline)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Moving briskly toward a settlement of a landmark
antitrust case, the federal government and three states suspended
their lawsuit Wednesday to block BP Amoco's $30 billion acquisition
of ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the Federal Trade Commission and the states
of California, Oregon and Washington came less than a week before a
hearing on the matter was set to begin in a federal court in San
Francisco. It also came the same day that the companies formally
announced that once the acquisition was completed, BP Amoco would
sell one of the crown jewels of the deal _ ARCO's large oil
holdings in Alaska _ to Phillips Petroleum for $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Issuing a one-sentence statement Wednesday morning, the top
staff antitrust official at the FTC suggested that the talks had
yielded significant progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the substantial and constructive proposals made by
the defendants, all parties have agreed to seek adjournment of the
federal court proceedings in FTC vs. BP Amoco and Atlantic
Richfield Co. in order to conduct negotiations,'' Richard G.
Parker, director of the FTC's competition bureau, said in a
statement referring to ARCO's incorporated name. Late last year,
the competition bureau recommended blocking the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In not setting any deadline for the completion of the talks, the
lawyers also sent a clear signal that many of the most difficult
issues of the case had been resolved in principle. Lawyers for the
government and the companies were exchanging drafts of proposed
consent decrees Wednesday that would clear the way for BP Amoco to
close the deal, and there was wide expectation that a settlement
could be announced in the next few weeks after a review and vote by
the agency's five commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at BP Amoco and ARCO were ebullient about the
progress being made in talks that had, for months, been bitter and
fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``After months of uncertainty for staff and customers of BP
Amoco and ARCO, and the states and communities where we operate, we
are pleased to be in discussions with the FTC,'' said a joint
statement issued by Sir John Browne, chief executive of BP Amoco,
and Mike R. Bowlin, ARCO's chairman. ``Those discussions are
constructive and Wednesday's sale agreement greatly advances the
prospects for their successful conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to sell ARCO's Alaskan assets to Phillips holds the
promise of resolving the government's biggest objection to the
acquisition of ARCO by BP Amoco and would signal a new entry in
Alaska after years of consolidation, layoffs and declining
production.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips would pick up ARCO's 21.9 percent interest in the
Prudhoe Bay oil rim, its 55 percent interest in the greater Kuparuk
area and a 78 percent stake in the Alpine field. ARCO would also
sell 1.1 million exploration acres on the North Slope, a 22.3
percent interest in the Trans-Alaska pipeline and a crude oil
shipping fleet of six tankers in service and three under
construction.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The proposed acquisition that BP Amoco and ARCO announced nearly
a year ago would have initially given the newly combined entity
control over about 70 percent of the oil produced in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement with Alaska's governor reduced that to 55 percent,
but failed to satisfy the concerns of the major consumers of
Alaskan crude in California, Washington and Oregon, as well as the
federal government. Higher than average gasoline prices on the West
Coast have long been a volatile political issue. As the cost of
gasoline at the pump has soared around the nation in recent months,
it has once again risen as an election-year topic on the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Surging gasoline prices have not been the only problem for BP
Amoco and ARCO as the review of their deal dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Robert Pitofsky, the chairman of the Federal Trade
Commission, concluded that the surge in mergers by energy companies
required the agency to give particularly rigorous scrutiny to any
new oil deals. Last year, Exxon completed its $81 billion merger
with Mobil in the same week that staff officials at the FTC
recommended taking steps to block BP Amoco's acquisition. Before
that, BP had acquired Amoco, and Texaco and Shell had entered into
a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in February to block the deal, the FTC and
the three West Coast states maintained that BP Amoco's acquisition
of ARCO was anti-competitive and violated the Clayton Antitrust
Act. They said the proposed deal would reduce competition by
refiners on the West Coast that use Alaskan crude and that it would
substantially diminish the quality of bidding among oil companies
that want to lease and develop Alaskan lands owned by the state and
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said that the deal would enable BP Amoco and
ARCO to manipulate the price of oil futures because the companies
control a major crude oil marketing hub in Cushing, Okla., that is
used to store West Texas intermediate crude, the most actively
traded futures contract on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger was the largest in American history to be
challenged by the government and the first in the oil industry
since the commission blocked Mobil's $6.5 billion bid to buy
Marathon Oil in the early 1980s. But unlike scores of other
companies that have dropped their proposed mergers in the face of
opposition from the government, executives at BP Amoco and ARCO
were determined to close their deal even if it meant selling one of
the most attractive pieces of the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the companies said Wednesday that an announcement
would soon be made about a deal to sell ARCO's holdings in Cushing
that should satisfy antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Wednesday's developments, the deal's largest
congressional critic, Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., urged Pitofsky to
seek greater concessions to benefit consumers on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden said Wednesday that he had asked Pitofsky in a telephone
call to press the companies to significantly increase their supply
of oil in the hopes of driving down prices. Wyden, in an interview
Wednesday afternoon, also said he had told Pitofsky to insist as
one of the conditions of the deal that BP Amoco reduce its exports
of North Slope crude to the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the overall deal advances competition in the oil markets,
I'm certainly willing to reconsider my opposition,'' Wyden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-00 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
