<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-WEB-BOOKS-KING-1STLD-     03-15 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-BOOKS-KING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN KING ELECTRONIC BOOK SETS SALES RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Adds that novella will not be published in print form in graf
8 and clarifies   nature of contract status questions in 7th graf
of Take 2.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an extraordinary surge of interest in an electronic book,
Stephen King's latest novella, featuring a Mustang-driving ghost,
has proved so popular in two days of literary life on the Internet
that several online booksellers could not meet the demand from
people wanting to download digital copies.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher said Wednesday that 400,000 orders were received
in the first 24 hours after the novella, ``Riding the Bullet,''
became available on various retailers' Web sites. Readers
overwhelmed the sites with purchases or orders to download the
digital horror story into their computers, electronic readers or
Palm Pilots.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed sure whether the surprising demand marked the
beginning of a revolution in the fledgling electronic publishing
market, where individual literary works have not sold more than a
few hundred copies, or simply resulted from the novelty of having a
marquee author dabble in bytes.
</P>
<P>
   The novella, the equivalent of 66 written pages, was given away
on the first day by some booksellers to nurture the infant market,
but others were getting brisk orders at $2.50 a copy. The 400,000
figure included both the paid and free downloads, as well as orders
received but not yet filled because of the heavy demand. But even
factoring in the free copies, the enormous first-day demand has
markedly raised the profile of electronic books.
</P>
<P>
   The early sales and orders far outstripped demand for any
traditional book in a similar fleeting period, said Jack Romanos,
president and chief operating officer of Simon &AMP; Schuster, King's
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' said Romanos, who has worked in the publishing
industry for more than 30 years. ``I don't think anybody could have
anticipated how many people were out there who are willing to
accept the written word in a paperless format. It's got to be
similar to what the people at Pocket Books went through years ago
when they got the early sales results on the first paperbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were not so sure that a revolution was at hand. They
pointed out that King was a special case _ a best-selling writer
with a huge cult following _ and that the attempt to distribute the
book in volume showed the bugs in the electronic system. Untold
numbers of customers were not able to download the necessary
software for reading or to reach the sites once they had it. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The novella, which will not be published as a traditional book,
had been promoted in print advertisements, on popular sites like
Amazon.com and elsewhere. Its success came in the same week that a
new wave of prominent authors were entering the electronic market.
For generous dot.com advances of up to $100,000, 10 authors were
commissioned by the California-based electronic bookseller
Fatbrain.com to write short essays about the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Among the writers and celebrities, whose essays begin appearing
this week, are Coretta Scott King, Newt Gingrich, Pete Hamill and
Doris Kearns Goodwin. In addition, on Wednesday Fatbrain announced
the signing of a contract with Toni Morrison to publish her 1993
Nobel Prize acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   The sales for these efforts, however, will no doubt pale beside
the demand for King's tale of an impoverished hitchhiker in Maine
who catches a ride with a nightmarish driver. On Amazon.com, which
is offering the title free for two weeks, customers demanded copies
at the rate of one every 1.5 seconds on the first day it was
available. Barnesandnoble.com, which gave away copies only on
Tuesday, the first day of sale, said that customers requested the
title at the rate of 2.5 per second. Some of those first-day orders
may have been duplications as unsuccessful readers tried repeatedly
to put in their orders.
</P>
<P>
   But NetLibrary, an electronic bookseller based in Boulder,
Colo., offered versions of the novella for $2.50 per copy without
interruption, selling them at the rate of 400 an hour. Under his
agreement with Simon &AMP; Schuster, which is the same arrangement he
has for his books, King will receive more than 50 percent of the
profits from the sales.
</P>
<P>
   First-day sales of hardback books by blockbuster writers like
John Grisham, Tom Clancy or King can run between 30,000 and 75,000,
publishing executives said. The books usually cost $25 to $27.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic titles can be delivered in a variety of forms. A
reader can download digital material from a Web bookseller on a
handheld mini-computer, although fewer than 10,000 of these devices
have been sold. Customers can also downloading material directly
into their personal computers for reading with Glassbook software.
Glassbook was so overwhelmed with requests for its software as a
result of the King novella that it posted an apology for delays on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Palm Pilot holders can be used to download books
from personal computers, but the handheld devices have small
reading screens. In all the formats, the digital material is
secured so readers cannot print versions from computers or e-mail
the text to others.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the early frenzy over ``Riding the Bullet,'' some
skeptics think the results were skewed by the free copies and the
author's loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same crowd buying, with the big advantage that they
can buy it faster and easier online,'' said Robert E. Baensch, a
former publishing executive and director of New York University's
Center for Publishing. ``We're only talking about one of the most
popular superstar authors.''
</P>
<P>
   Baensch added that he expected sales to fade to King's usual
sales volume, which leveled out at about 1.3 million per title for
his more recent works.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fatbrain's move to commission works by name authors was also a
bid to promote the infant market for electronic books and to raise
publicity for the bookseller's newly opened e-book Web site,
MightyWords. Fatbrain is offering the Bill of Rights essays for
free.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ which is backed by millions of dollars from
investors like Paul Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft _ is also in
final discussions to post some digitized collections from the
Bancroft Library at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   But in the delicate process of forging new alliances, Fatbrain
has collided with Simon &AMP; Schuster, King's publisher, which was
riled by the company's brashness in blurring the lines between
retailer and publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of the Stephen King title, Simon &AMP;
Schuster refused to allow Fatbrain to offer the book on its Web
site for popular books, which posts about 6,000 digital works and
sells them for an average of $3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get it,'' said Chris MacAskill, the chief executive
of Fatbrain.com. ``The stated reason is that we were going out
there and signing up authors.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last year and a half, MacAskill has been trying to seed
the market for electronic books by persuading authors to post
material online of 10 to 100 pages. Initially, he said, traditional
publishers were not interested in the short format, so Fatbrain
started acting like a magazine publisher, commissioning short
pieces for generous advances subsidized by venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict with Simon &AMP; Schuster grew out of Fatbrain's
approaches to several the publisher's authors, including Goodwin,
the historian, and Seth Godin, author of ``Permission Marketing.''
The company maintains that it is respecting authors' contracts with
other publishers because if it is not signing a book publisher's
authors to write works that are book length. MacAskill said he was
advised by Simon &AMP; Schuster that he should have sought its
permission before approaching the authors.
</P>
<P>
   Romanos, the Simon &AMP; Schuster president, said that a new,
evolving market calls for a redefinition of what is a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question in electronic publishing _ and one that's
been worked out over many years in traditional publishing _ is who
is a publisher, and who is a retailer and distributor?'' Romanos
said. ``We're more than willing to work with any distributor who
can satisfy the technical and security requirements to protect our
copyrights. But when a distributor decides to take on the
additional role of a publisher, then we will definitely view them
as a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Far removed from such tensions and horrors of publishing was
Stephen King himself. His assistant in Maine said that he was in
Florida, too preoccupied with his own writing to respond to
questions about the success of his first electronic effort.
</P>
<P>
   King, who was seriously injured in an automobile accident last
summer, is making great strides in his recovery, according to his
publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   But the author, whose has written more than 40 books, from ``The
Dead Zone'' to ``Desperation,'' did issue a simple statement about
his electronic title:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very excited at the possibility of a new market opening
up, and as a dedicated and long-term Mac user I am surprised and a
little unhappy at how hard it is for Mac users to access the story,
but thank God for the Palm Pilot, which is making it accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``While I think that the Internet and various computer
applications for stories have great promise, I don't think anything
will replace the printed word and the bound book. Not in my
lifetime, at least.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
