<SLUG> BC-THAI-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAI BANKRUPTCY DECISION SEEN AS A VICTORY FOR CREDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In a landmark decision watched closely
throughout Southeast Asia, Thailand's fledgling bankruptcy court
declared Thai Petrochemical Industry, that country's largest
corporate debtor, insolvent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors regarded the decision as an important victory that
could help them start to recover billions of dollars in unpaid
loans left from the 1997-98 Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's Central Bankruptcy Court ruled that Thai
Petrochemical, which defaulted on $3.5 billion in debt in 1997, had
liabilities exceeding its assets and ordered the company to submit
to court-supervised restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Petrochemical's creditors, which include the International
Finance Corp., which is part of the World Bank, and the U.S.
Export-Import Bank, filed court papers to have the company declared
insolvent last month after more than two years of talks on how to
get the company to begin repaying its debts broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Petrochemical's story is one that is being repeated in
various forms around Southeast Asia, reflecting efforts to clean up
the mess left by the financial crisis. Banks and other creditors
have resorted to legal proceedings to uproot the entrenched family
interests that continue to dominate much of the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, for example, efforts to sell assets repossessed by
the government have been delayed by legal wrangling over the role
still played by former owners connected to the fallen former
President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors of Thai Petrochemical did not get everything they
wanted. The bankruptcy court rejected their request to replace Thai
Petrochemical's family-led management immediately, saying a meeting
of all creditors and management must take place first. That means
there could be more negotiations between the creditors and Prachai
Leophairatana, Thai Petrochemical's founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But Thai officials and analysts still called the ruling a
victory in efforts by creditors to force the most stubborn debtors
to negotiate in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rather good outcome for creditors,'' said Anthony J.
Norman, managing director of Effective Planners Ltd., a unit of
Ferrier Hodgson Ltd., the financial advisory firm that the creditor
committee had put forward to take over management of Thai
Petrochemical.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors were satisfied with the decision, Norman said,
shrugging off the possible delay posed by further negotiations.
``What does a few weeks matter when you've been waiting 30
months?''
</P>
<P>
   Thai Petrochemical owes so much money that the successful
restructuring of its debt would eliminate almost 7 percent of
Thailand's outstanding bad loans. Foremost among the beneficiaries
would be Bangkok Bank, Thailand's largest bank, which extended $600
million in credit to Thai Petrochemical and is the company's single
largest lender.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets, which had rallied Tuesday in expectation of a
ruling favorable to creditors, fell back on the news, with the
benchmark index in Thailand falling 3.5 percent. Thailand's
currency, the baht, was little changed against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Wednesday appeared to stop short of setting what many
bankers and lawyers had hoped would be a legal precedent on
interpreting insolvency. Current Thai law, amended in 1998 and 1999
to give more power to lenders, defines insolvency as an excess of
liabilities over assets, but it fails to include situations in
which an otherwise healthy company is unable or unwilling to repay
its debts.
</P>
<P>
   A report made in January by the Asian Development Bank, the
International Finance Corp. and the World Bank to Thai officials
identified this loophole as one of several shortcomings in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Thai bankruptcy court, established only nine months ago as a
separate entity to expedite cases like this one, appeared to rely
instead on technicalities in deciding in the creditors' favor. It
rejected Thai Petrochemical's defense partly because the company's
financial adviser who had testified about its debt problems was
deemed by the court to be unqualified.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how long it would take to convene a meeting
of Thai Petrochemical's nearly 150 creditors, which could give
Prachai a new, if diminished, chance to retain control of the
company he and his family founded in 1978. Thai Petrochemical
officials did not return phone calls seeking a reaction to the
court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials had said they would resign if they lost the
case, but there was no immediate sign that they would abide by that
statement. Last week, the company appealed to nationalist
sentiments, issuing a statement to the Thai stock exchange that
accused creditors of trying to destroy the company and of planning
to lay off most of its 20,000 employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
