<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PUNISH THE BIG UNIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Randy Johnson pitches in the National League
now, so the Angels don't have to face the tall and lanky
left-hander much anymore. But they made the most of their
opportunity on Wednesday, knocking Johnson around for 11 runs and
12 hits in his three-plus innings in the Angels' 15-9 victory over
the Arizona Diamondbacks at Tucson Electic Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored 11 runs in the fourth inning, the first eight
off Johnson, who failed to retire any of the eight hitters he faced
in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina and Tim Salmon both homered in the inning off
Johnson, but the blow that really irritated Johnson was Gary
DiSarcina's two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   One of the runners who scored on the play was Trent Durrington,
who is among those competing for the second-base job. After
crossing the plate, the 5-foot-9 Durrington and the 6-foot-10
Johnson bumped into each other and words were exchanged before
things calmed down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's his name?'' Johnson asked reporters after the game.
``They were having a team meeting behind home plate. I'm trying to
back up home plate and I'm running into people. I was trying to get
him out of the way. They don't need three people to tell the guy
coming around third what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Australian Durrington said to him, Johnson joked:
``Have a Foster's and go ice your arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Durrington also downplayed the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was looking up at a light tower,'' he said of
Johnson. `'It was too many people in one place at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stay calm: The hit parade against Johnson was nice, but
Salmon said it was nothing to get too excited about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you evaluate our performance or his performance, hey,
it's spring training,'' said Salmon, who has a team-leading four
homers. ``It feels good, but at the same time you try not to get
overly confident. Because when the gun sounds, he's going to have
his A-game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I threw was right down the middle of the plate,''
Johnson said. ``It got frustrating after a while. . . . I'm willing
to give back my meal money this week. I don't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mercker sharp: Angels starter Kent Mercker had his best
outing of the spring in his pursuit of one of the spots in the
starting rotation. He gave up three runs (all on solo homers) and
six hits in four innings. He also had two bunt singles off Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came into spring training telling myself it was my job to
lose,'' said Mercker, who pitched for the Cardinals and Red Sox
last season. ''If I don't make the club, it's my own fault. But I
don't plan on giving them that option.''
</P>
<P>
   In three games, Mercker is 1-0 with a 5.87 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
