<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIE MADE RIGHT DECISION _ TO STAY AT PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ This wasn't just idle thought. It was serious
consideration, major deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   Tezale Archie wasn't toying with the idea of transferring from
Pepperdine last year, he took steps to make it reality, even
talking to his high school and AAU coaches to help prepare him for
leaving Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   Archie, who decided to stay, laughs about it now, partly out of
amusement, partly from relief. He's thrilled he didn't leave and
the Waves are, too. The All-West Coast Conference point guard is
the catalyst in Pepperdine's march to the NCAA Tournament, leading
the team in assists (5.7), scoring when needed and showing the
nerve to take the big shot.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, his cool, cocky demeanor rubs off on the
Waves, who feed off his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a certain swagger about him and I think that's good for
the team,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff said. ``When I
coached at Princeton, (head coach Pete) Carril always told our
point guards that the other four players always look at the point
guard. The way he carries himself is the way the team carries
itself. And (Archie) carries himself in a confident manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves (24-8) open the first round of the East Regionals
Friday at 7 p.m. (PST) against Indiana (20-8) in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what Archie would have missed had he left:
</P>
<P>
   __ Winning the starting point-guard job, then earning
all-conference honors.
</P>
<P>
   __ Playing for van Breda Kolff, the Waves' first-year coach who
restored Archie's broken spirit by showing confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   __ Leading the Waves to the NCAA Tournament in the final year of
an often chaotic career at Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   To think, Archie nearly walked away from all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was close, I'm not going to say I wasn't,'' Archie said. ``I
got to that close point, but my faith in God and my family support
turned it around for me.''
</P>
<P>
   There were compelling reasons for Archie to leave. He's been at
Pepperdine five years and played under !ital!four different
coaches. First was Tony Fuller, who quit during the 1996 season.
Then came Marty Wilson, who finished that season on an interim
basis. Lorenzo Romar took over from 1996-99, and when he left to
coach Saint Louis University, van Breda Kolff replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   Each coach had his own agenda, tried to bring in players that
fit his philosophy and run off the ones who didn't. Some players
stuck around just long enough to learn a few names before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a revolving door,'' Archie said.
</P>
<P>
   It took a little while, but Archie soon realized that college
basketball could be a cold-hearted business, filled with
half-truths, out-and-out lies and little loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hit me until after my sophomore year,'' Archie said.
``I was still sheltered, coming from a small town like Fresno,
thinking everybody is your friend, nobody will tell you wrong. They
recruit you here, so they're going to do right by you. You're set,
you're going to get into the tournament all four years. But slowly
but surely I started to see it for what it was, a business, a meat
grind.''
</P>
<P>
   As challenging as that was, the hardest part was adapting to
each coach's style of play, especially Romar's slow-down,
half-court offense.
</P>
<P>
   Archie plays with a flair and he's at his best in an uptempo
game. Romar took that away from him, demanding that Pepperdine's
point guards grind the games to a halt, then dump the ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   Archie almost left.
</P>
<P>
   Then Romar left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Romar was the coach, Tezale wouldn't be on the team right
now,'' Pepperdine forward Kelvin Gibbs said
</P>
<P>
   Two things happened when Romar moved on. He took his style of
play with him, and Pepperdine hired van Breda Kolff, the former
Vanderbilt coach, to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff looked at Pepperdine's roster and saw one thing:
athletes. He quickly shelved Romar's slow game for one much faster,
the type that suits Archie's style and takes advantage of the
Waves' speed and depth.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the starting job in training camp, Archie has
blossomed into one of the top players in the conference, averaging
9.8 points, 5.7 assists and 2.8 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show you how coach van Breda Kolff treats his
players on the court and off it,'' Gibbs said. ``Last year Tezale
had some problems, but this year he hasn't. For him to be on the
team this year, to be an all-conference guard, scoring like he has
been, dishing the ball like he has and just being our team leader
has been important for us. He's had a lot to do with our success.
He might be the main reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie credits his family and friends for convincing him to stay
at Pepperdine, but clearly van Breda Kolff has played the biggest
role in his success. Changing Pepperdine's style was the key. But
showing faith in Archie was just as vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coaching staff has been behind me from day one, and
they've pushed me from day one,'' Archie said. ``I've made more
improvement this year then I have my whole college career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
