<HEADER>
A8202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT     03-15 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA REVIEWS ACCUSATIONS ABOUT DIABETES DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Mass.)   (af)  
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is reviewing accusations that
the manufacturer of the diabetes drug Rezulin withheld evidence of
liver toxicity from the agency until six months after Rezulin was
marketed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the agency said it would look into accusations
by Public Citizen's Health Research Group, a patient advocacy
group, claiming that Rezulin's manufacturer delayed telling the FDA
that 21 patients had developed liver abnormalities while taking the
drug before it was approved. Federal regulations require that drug
companies report adverse drug reactions to the drug agency within
15 days of learning about them.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 14 letter to the agency, Public Citizen requested a
criminal investigation of the manufacturer, Parke-Davis, a division
of the Warner-Lambert Co. of Morris Plains, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bradbard, a spokeswoman for the drug agency, said no
decision had been made about whether an investigation was needed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Warner-Lambert, Carol Goodrich, said Public
Citizen's accusations were ``baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin was marketed in 1997 to treat Type 2, or adult-onset,
diabetes, the most common form of the disease. It was the first in
a class of drugs that lower blood sugar by making the body more
sensitive to the effects of insulin, the hormone that regulates
blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has been under siege by consumer safety advocates and
negative news reports in the last year, because after it was
approved it became apparent that in rare instances it can cause
serious liver damage and death.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen has urged that Rezulin be taken off the market.
Since its introduction in 1997, it has been linked to 89 cases of
liver failure, including 61 deaths and at least 10 liver
transplants. But the number of cases is small in comparison to the
1.9 million people who have taken the drug. Goodrich said several
hundred thousand people in the United States were still taking it.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen says Warner-Lambert had evidence of serious liver
problems before the drug was marketed, but suppressed the data. The
claim is based on a drug agency memorandum, which the group
obtained under the Freedom of Information Act. A copy of the
memorandum was obtained by The New York Times. The document, a
review written by Dr. Robert I. Misbin, an FDA medical officer,
said that by Feb. 3, 1997, Parke-Davis had received reports of 21
patients who developed liver abnormalities while taking the drug.
But the memorandum said the company did not report those cases to
the agency until eight months later, on Oct. 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By then, there were 20 additional well-documented cases of
patients with serious liver problems, and the agency required that
Rezulin be relabeled to warn that liver damage could occur and that
patients should have frequent blood tests to detect it early so
that they could stop taking the drug if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article last week in The Los Angeles Times,
doctors within the FDA, in opposition to their superiors, have
begun saying it is time to take Rezulin off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbard said the agency declined comment on whether there was
dissension in its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes specialists have been among Rezulin's staunchest
supporters, because the drug helped many patients to lower their
blood sugar, and many doctors thought it could be used safely as
long as the liver tests were performed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Nathan, an endocrinologist at the Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston, said he had patients who had done well
with Rezulin for several years and were staying on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drug isn't Satan,'' Nathan said. But he also said he no
longer started new patients on Rezulin. ``The requirement for
liver-function testing outweighs its usefulness,'' he said, adding
that he and many of his colleagues felt more comfortable
prescribing two newer drugs in the same class as Rezulin, Avandia
and Actos, which were approved in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathan said, ``at this point in time it's not clear to me
that the two newer ones are truly safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Avandia has already begun to outsell Rezulin. Sales of Rezulin
in 1999 totaled $773 million, according to IMS Health, a company
that tracks the drug industry.
</P>
<P>
   Liver tests are also required for patients taking the two newer
drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
