<HEADLINE>
CHANGES UNDER WAY AT STOCK MARKETS IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With plans for a much-vaunted pan-European stock
exchange rapidly unraveling, bourses from London to Paris began to
position themselves Wednesday for what many expect to be a radical
shake-up up in the way investors trade stocks in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In London, the 298 members of the London Stock Exchange voted
overwhelmingly to end almost two centuries of clubby mutual
ownership by converting their stakes in the exchange into tradeable
shares.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, Finance Minister Didier Reynders told a news
conference that the Brussels, Paris and Amsterdam stock exchanges
were in advanced talks to merge or form some other kind of
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Traders and analysts said that investors want easier and cheaper
access to trading in Europe as a whole _ the region has 23 separate
exchanges. ``There's a huge demand for cross-border trading in
Europe,'' said John Spencer, director of equities at Merrill Lynch
in London. ``And this demand is one of the driving forces behind
the need for consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years ago, even before the euro, the single
currency used on much of the Continent, was created, the London and
Frankfurt exchanges seemed to be leading a drive to bring eight
European bourses together in a single trading system.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort has faltered. The only agreement between the
eight was to bring their trading hours into line, and that
agreement was broken, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, some organizations, including the Boerse in
Frankfurt and the Tradepoint alternative stock exchange in London,
plan to establish their own online European trading networks this
year, galvanizing smaller, traditional exchanges in particular to
seek alliances with the dominant exchanges. The Nasdaq stock
market, the electronically linked network of broker-dealers in the
United States, plans to open a Europewide exchange earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these little exchanges are inevitably going to merge
together,'' said David Donnelly, chief investment officer at Gordon
House Asset Management in London. Another European equities
investor put it more bluntly: ``These smaller players now have to
get into an alliance or get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynders, the Belgian finance minister, said the proposed
three-way merger of Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels was open to
others who wished to join.
</P>
<P>
   The three exchanges are already linked. Brussels has
cross-membership ties with Amsterdam and Luxembourg, while Paris
and Brussels use the same trading system. Talks about a broader
pan-European exchange, by contrast, have foundered on disagreements
over common trading systems.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that if the merger was agreed to, the three
bourses would carve up the market so that Paris _ the biggest of
the three, with a market capitalization of $1.489 trillion _ would
mostly trade in blue-chip stocks, Brussels in shares of small and
midsize companies, and Amsterdam in derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   But that seemed too limited a deal to some exchange officials
still seeking access to a broader European markets. ``At this
stage, there will have to be some new formula on how the blue-chip
market in Europe will work,'' said Tom Healy, chief executive of
the Irish Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The change at the London Stock Exchange was widely seen as a
maneuver to enable the market to navigate the upheaval in European
stock trading. ``Today's vote moves the exchange into a new era,
providing a structure that will allow it to compete more
effectively in the rapidly developing environment in which stock
exchanges now operate,'' said Sir John Kemp-Welch, chairman of the
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in the new shares is expected to begin in late April or
early May, but the stock will be traded outside the normal markets.
No single shareholder will be allowed to hold a stake of more than
4.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The changes reflect a wider trend in big European and U.S.
exchanges toward a more nimble ownership structure that permits
them to compete against electronic communications networks, known
as ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   But London's moves are also seen as a precursor to redrawing the
European trading landscape not by negotiation but by market forces.
Rather than agreeing to cooperate, some traders said, the various
exchanges will be subject to the wave of mergers and acquisitions
that have swept through many other European sectors, including
banking and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer at Merrill Lynch said stock markets had been ``the forum
for mergers; now the stock exchanges are becoming targets for
M&AMP;A.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
