<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-ASSESS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINE LEADER CANCELS U.S. VISIT AFTER IMF COMPLAINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN with TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The prime minister of Ukraine canceled a visit to
the United States earlier this week after the Clinton
administration told him that he should come only after ``cleaning
up'' his government, which was discovered to have abused a major
international loan program.
</P>
<P>
   Ukrainian officials said the prime minister, Viktor Yushchenko,
postponed his trip on short notice because of a mining disaster at
home, not because of a snub by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Yushchenko, who was confirmed by Parliament as prime minister
late last year and was planning to make his first official visit to
Washington in that capacity, was told that he would not be able to
meet with President Clinton during his stay, a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to discourage the visit came just before the
Treasury Department and the International Monetary Fund revealed
that the Ukrainian central bank had done a series of financial
transactions designed to create the impression that it had more
foreign currency than it really did. The fund said that
manipulation of exchange reserves was intended at least in part to
mislead fund officials into disbursing hundreds of millions of
dollars in loans that might otherwise have been withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Yushchenko headed Ukraine's central bank before becoming prime
minister. U.S. officials consider him the leading reformer in a
nation that has been rocked by corruption scandals for years. But
revelations of mismanagement at the central bank while he served as
its leader have undermined the prime minister early in his
administration, analysts who follow Ukrainian politics said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the sense that they should go fix this and then talk
about a visit,'' the senior administration official said. ``They
clearly have some business to do at home to clean up this
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based monetary fund, which coordinates its
lending programs with the United States, its largest shareholder,
said that Ukraine supplied false information about foreign reserves
from 1996 to 1998. The country's central bank used nearly $1
billion in hard currency to conduct a series of banking
transactions that allowed it to double-count its reserves. The
transactions were designed to make it seem as if it were meeting
IMF-set goals for managing its economy when it actually might not
have met those goals, the fund said this week.
</P>
<P>
   During the period in question, the fund distributed $675 million
in loans to Ukraine. Fund officials said Wednesday that they had
yet to determine exactly how much of that amount would have been
withheld if they had had an accurate picture of Ukraine's financial
health.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations raise questions about political and economic
management in Ukraine, the former Soviet republic that has been a
high priority for the Clinton administration for many years. Until
recently, Kiev was the third largest recipient of foreign aid from
the United States after Israel and Egypt _ aid that was intended in
part to support democracy and foster capitalism. Ukraine, along
with Russia, has also been among the largest recipients of
long-term lending from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of mismanagement in Ukraine is a blow to the
monetary fund at a sensitive time. The fund has been under pressure
from Congress and the Clinton administration to strengthen its
auditing procedures after Russia was found to have misused foreign
exchange reserves, possibly including IMF aid, in ways that
resemble the problems in Ukraine.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Congress agreed to devote $18 billion to support the fund
in 1998, it set up a commission to investigate ways of streamlining
its operations. The so-called Meltzer Commission last week issued a
report that, among many recommendations, urged that the fund
eliminate the types of long-term lending programs involved in loans
to Ukraine. Lawmakers who vote on United States contributions to
the fund have also demanded the fund do a better job of ensuring
that money it provides is used properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be important to know who knew what and when at
the IMF,'' said Rep. Jim Leach, who is chairman of the House
Banking Committee. ``There also are very serious questions about
how deep the corruption goes in the former Soviet Union _ whether
this is just endemic or whether there is still hope for reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund made a detailed statement about Ukraine's deception in
response to questions from several news organizations, fund
officials said Wednesday. The statement, issued late Tuesday night,
said that Ukraine's central bank, at its request, had hired the
private accounting firm of PriceWaterhouseCoopers to audit it
accounts. Fund officials said they hope that the audit will reveal
more information about how the currency reserves were inflated, how
much money the fund disbursed to Ukraine that it otherwise might
have withheld, and whether off-shore banking transactions generated
profits for Ukrainian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The fund received indications of Ukraine's deception well before
it said anything publicly about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The fund said this week that it spotted problems with Ukraine's
management of its foreign reserves as early as August 1998. In
April of last year, legislators in Ukraine's Parliament sent a
letter to the IMF raising accusations that the central bank was
``round-tripping'' foreign reserves through offshore accounts to
create a false picture of its total reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The mismanagement, at least so far, has not resulted in any
punishment for Ukraine. The nation currently has access to an IMF
loan program initiated in September 1998, though the fund has not
recently disbursed money because Ukraine has failed to meet
conditions of the loan program.
</P>
<P>
   Questions also have been raised about the role of Credit Suisse
First Boston, the New York-based investment banking arm of Swiss
financial services giant Credit Suisse Group. Credit Suisse helped
transfer about $150 million in central bank funds, some of which
might have been provided by the IMF, from Ukraine to Cyprus, a
popular off-shore haven for financial transactions in the former
Soviet Union, government investigators said. The information about
Credit Suisse's role was first reported by The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   The fund said the money involved in that transaction was
funneled back into Ukraine from Cyprus, invested in government
securities and double-counted for purposes of tallying total
foreign reserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
