<HEADLINE>
BAY HILL INVITATIONAL SET TO THRIVE ON THE YOUNG AND THE OLD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The Bay Hill Invitational this weekend will have
a decided generation gap.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Baddeley, who will turn 19 years old Friday, will be
playing in the same tournament with Arnold Palmer, who is 70.
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley was invited by Palmer, the host of the tournament,
after he became the youngest player to win the Australian Open last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Still an amateur, Baddeley could be next in line behind Tiger
Woods and Sergio Garcia to make a huge impact in professional golf
at an early age. When Palmer sees teen-agers good enough to win pro
events, he can't help shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Palmer, who won his first PGA Tour event
at age 25. ``The mental attitude of these players is far more
mature than it was 20, 30, 40 years ago. There were some pretty
good young players in those days, but these guys are very seasoned
and very poised.''
</P>
<P>
   While Baddeley and Palmer will certainly draw attention, there
will be an added buzz surrounding the event with Tiger Woods
returning to action after a two-week break, headlining a field that
includes 12 of the top 16 players in the world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Others top players in the field include Colin Montgomerie, Davis
Love III, Lee Westwood, Vijay Singh, Ernie Els, Hal Sutton, Phil
Mickelson, Tom Lehman, Darren Clarke, Garcia and Tim Herron, the
defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Hill begins a key stretch in the Tour's schedule, with the
Masters only three weeks away, and the Players Championship next
week in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. Woods looked well-rested and upbeat
Wednesday, and he was looking forward to playing at Bay Hill, which
is less than a 10-minute drive from his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already won at Disney, so it would be nice to win Bay
Hill as well,'' Woods said. ``It would be even more special to win
Arnold's tournament, just because of the fact that he's the king.
I've been fortunate enough to win the Byron Nelson, as well as the
Memorial, which is Jack Nicklaus' tournament. It would be nice to
be part of Arnold's tournament as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has played either 20 or 21 Tour events in each of the last
three years, and he is on pace to play about the same amount in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could probably play a few more, but the problem I run into
is not being fresh,'' Woods said. ``I play differently than some
players on tour. I'd rather focus on quality, not quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour commissioner, Tim Finchem, said that next month's
MCI Classic in Hilton Head, S.C., should be kept out of the
controversy regarding the Confederate flag that flies over South
Carolina's capitol. The Knicks have moved their pre-playoff
training camp out of Charleston in response to the flag issue. ``I
don't think we ought to use a sporting event to send that
message,'' Finchem said. ``I think there are other ways to send
that message, and I think the people of South Carolina ought to be
the ones sending that message. A Tour event raises a lot of money
for charities in that community, and I don't think we should use
the tournament to make that point. Personally, I don't think they
should fly the flag. But we have no plans to involve the tournament
in that fight.'' ... Starting in 2001, the American Express
Championship will be moved from November to the week of Sept. 10 at
a site to be determined. That means the Tour Championship will once
again be the last official event of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
