<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T TELL PLAYERS WITH A SCORECARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ A woman wearing a ``Jeter 2'' shirt stood,
camera in hand, next to the visitors' dugout scanning the figures
on the field. Another young woman, with ``Knoblauch 11'' on her
back, sat next to the dugout in the first row.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the dugout stood a young man wearing a ``Williams 51''
shirt, another with just the No. 51, another with ``O'Neill 21,''
yet another with a Jeter shirt. They looked in vain for their
heroes. They were not on the field or anywhere else at Marchant
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, Scott Brosius and Jorge Posada were not in the
vicinity Wednesday either. In their place for the Yankees' game at
the spring home of the Detroit Tigers were players named Juan Melo,
Rafael Bournigal, Julio Mosquera, Clay Bellinger and Jon Zuber. No
truth in advertising there.
</P>
<P>
   As teams often do in spring training, the Yankees played the
game seemingly in violation of an exhibition directive from the
commissioner's office that mandates the minimum number of regulars
a team must have at a road game.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, the head of baseball operations in the
commissioner's office, did not return a telephone call about the
directive, but Phil Garner, the Tigers' manager, said clubs have
been told they have to have a combination of four starters or
players who will ``start a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Yankees were annoyed last Saturday when the Atlanta
Braves visited them in Tampa, Fla., and brought only two players,
Reggie Sanders and Quilvio Veras, who fit that description.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the rule is to protect the ticket-buying fans. When
they see, for example, that the Yankees are playing in Lakeland,
people buy tickets expecting to see the three-times-in-four-years
World Series champions. They might accept the reality that they
will not see the lineup that won those World Series, but for their
$12, $8 or $5 tickets, they might have a reasonable expectation of
seeing a fair share of that lineup, say, Jeter, Brosius, O'Neill
and Posada.
</P>
<P>
   But Mosquera, Zuber, Bournigal and Melo?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the Columbus Clippers' lineup,'' the
public-address announcer commented in the press box, though not
over the public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   To say the Yankees had even three regulars on the field during
their 8-2 loss to the Tigers would be a stretch. Ricky Ledee and
Shane Spencer were in the outfield, but between them they might
count as one starter, two if Ledee winds up as the everyday left
fielder and Spencer part of a designated-hitting platoon. Then
again, they may not start at all. The Yankees are apparently not
enamored of either one as a regular left fielder and have engaged
in talks seeking a more productive hitter for the position.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines was in the lineup, but his starting days are behind
him. In fact, before the game, when Joe Torre was running down his
designated-hitting possibilities, he mentioned five players and
Raines was not one of them. When Torre was subsequently asked a
question about Raines, even then he did not talk about him as a
possible starting or platooned designated hitter. Pinch-hitting was
the context in which the manager talked about the veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens was the Yankees' starting pitcher, and he surely
qualifies as a front-line player, but Garner said pitchers don't
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm filing a complaint with the commissioner,'' Garner said,
then laughed. Only joking. In fact, he had no complaint at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Joe about it already,'' he said in his office
before the game. ``He just said, `We have a sort of a skeleton
staff.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garner said he understood. ``There are a whole lot of reasons,''
he said, then ticked off the names of players he said he would not
take on Thursday's one-and-one-half-hour trip to St. Petersburg,
Fla., for a variety of reasons, including Juan Gonzalez ``because
his back is going to stiffen up and I don't want that to happen in
spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' new manager said clubs that train in Florida seem to
be more attentive to the rule than teams that train in Arizona,
where he spent eight springs with the Milwaukee Brewers. But even
there, he said, he encountered trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a general manager may say something to another
general manager,'' Garner said. ``I had that happen a couple years
ago. One of the general managers complained and Sal Bando, my boss,
said, `Take a couple more guys next time.' It's something we want
to do for the fans. You want the fans to see a representative
club.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 7,440, a record for the 35-year-old park, may not
have thought it saw a representative visiting club Wednesday.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
