<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-NCAA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH INTENSITY IN QUESTION, UT TRIES FINDING HEARTBEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ After the excitement of Selection Sunday, the
Texas basketball team retreated to a players-only meeting in a
conference room in the Moncrief-Neuhaus Athletic Center.
</P>
<P>
   There was no yelling or finger-pointing regarding the team's
disappointing play in a semifinal loss to Oklahoma in the Big 12
tournament the day before. Almost every player had a say. Seniors
Ivan Wagner, Gabe Muoneke, Chris McColpin and Will Clay spoke last.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't mention Oklahoma. But they did talk about last
year's loss to Purdue in the first round of the NCAA Tournament and
the difficult path that lay ahead, beginning today when the
fifth-seeded Longhorns open play against No. 12 seed Indiana State
in the West Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we talked about how hard we have to play,'' Clay
said. ``We know we're only guaranteed one game and it can be a
short season, or we can go out and play every game like it's our
last and play six games \Rto reach the championship\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were watching the bracket, some of the younger players
were talking about LSU or Arizona. I just told everyone that we
can't take any team for granted. We can't look ahead. None of these
teams would be in the tournament if they weren't good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, the Longhorns are included in that group.
</P>
<P>
   But as early-week conjecture swirled around which of the six Big
12 teams were most likely to advance to the Sweet 16, Texas was an
afterthought to Iowa State, Oklahoma State and the Sooners. The
obvious reason was that the Longhorns were mentally missing in
action in the Big 12 semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problems weren't technical,'' Muoneke said. ``It was about
playing hard. We were lackadaisical against Oklahoma. At this time
of the season, players have to make plays and, basically, talent
comes out. The difference between us and Duke and those other teams
is not talent. Everybody knows we're stacked in that area. It's a
matter of consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be bad if we're lackadaisical, or great if we play
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Barnes said he has been pleased with his team's
attitude this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of good days of practice and a good workout
this morning,'' Barnes said. ``We'll be OK if we do what we've done
all year long and learn from our mistakes. We have to understand
that we've got to do a better job on the offensive end, a much
better job of staying within ourselves and work the entire game.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's first-round game represents full circle for Longhorns
center Chris Mihm, who after last year's first-round loss in Boston
immediately dedicated himself to making sure his team returned to
the tournament, but with more favorable results. One of the few
players who showed any fire against OU, Mihm said he enters NCAA
play focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the tournament means a lot to me,'' said Mihm, who
within the coming weeks will decide if he will return for his
senior season or enter the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated with last year's opening-round loss. It was
something that has driven me to work this year. I want to go out
there and give it my all and see how far I can take this team. The
tournament is such a great experience. I'd like to get as deep as I
can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent disappointment notwithstanding, Mihm certainly expects
the Longhorns to play more than one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a much better prepared team than we were a year ago,''
he said. ``This time last year, a lot of guys were running on empty
and we were banged up. We've got the depth we need and a solid
team. We've had a lot better year, and we've got a lot more
confidence. I'm expecting big things. If everyone comes to play, we
can do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, the word ``if'' has become a disturbing part of
the equation.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
