<SLUG> BC-GENERIC-DRUGS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC EXPECTED TO FILE COMPLAINTS OVER GENERIC DRUG DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Colo., Ill., Germany, France)  (js) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission is expected to file complaints
Thursday contending that four drug companies harmed consumers when
they made agreements that delayed the sale of low-cost generic
drugs, according to lawyers and executives briefed on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The expected civil actions will be the first to come from a
continuing investigation by the commission into the growing number
of deals between companies that make brand-name drugs and
competitors that are developing cheaper, generic forms of popular
medications. Under the agreements, the brand-name company pays the
generic company not to sell the lower-cost drug. As a result,
consumers pay hundreds of millions of dollars more than they would
if the cheaper drug were available.
</P>
<P>
   Andrx Corp., a generic drug maker, said Wednesday that the
commission was expected to file a case against it and Aventis,
created last year with the merger of Hoechst A.G. of Germany and
Rhone-Poulenc S.A. of France, over a 1997 agreement between Andrx
and Hoechst. Under the agreement, Hoechst agreed to pay Andrx $100
million a year if Andrx kept its generic version of Cardizem CD,
one of the nation's top-selling heart drugs, off pharmacy shelves.
Cardizem had sales of $850 million in 1998, according to IMS
Health, a market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is also expected to settle charges with Abbott
Laboratories and Geneva Pharmaceuticals, a generic drug company
owned by Novartis, executives said. The charges result from a deal
between the two companies involving Abbott's blood-pressure drug,
Hytrin, which had sales of $610 million in 1998. Abbott agreed to
pay Geneva millions of dollars a month to not sell its generic
version of Hytrin.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Hahn, president of Andrx, based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
said Wednesday that the company's agreement with Aventis did not
harm consumers. Instead, Hahn said, details of the agreement and
Aventis' payments helped the financially struggling Andrx get the
generic drug on the market faster than would have otherwise been
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we could to get this product out there,''
Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Aventis also said the agreement with Andrx did
not harm consumers but was solely meant to protect the company's
patent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware that the commission is expecting to vote on this
issue,'' she said. ``We don't yet know the outcome of that vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswomen at Abbott, based in North Chicago, Ill., and Geneva,
based in Broomfield, Colo., declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies are also facing class-action lawsuits
filed by consumers and large purchasers of drugs, including
insurance companies and pharmacies. Abbott disclosed in its annual
10-K report this week that Florida's attorney general was also
demanding information about its agreement with Geneva and about a
similar deal with another drug company, Zenith Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is investigating the generic drug deals at a time
when many popular drugs are nearing the end of their patent
protection. To protect revenues derived from those brand-name
drugs, companies often quickly file lawsuits against any competitor
that applies to the Food and Drug Administration to sell a generic
form. The lawsuits argue that the generic drug company is
infringing on the other company's patent.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of those lawsuits result in the kind of
settlements the commission is now investigating.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hahn said Andrx had submitted applications to develop the
generic form of 10 different brand-name drugs. So far, he said,
Andrx has been sued by the manufacturer of the brand-name drug over
nine of those applications. Just by filing the lawsuit, the company
with the brand-name drug can often delay the introduction of the
generic drug for many months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the game,'' Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to file its case involving Aventis
and Andrx before an administrative law judge rather than in federal
court. The FTC could only press for fines or other financial
penalties if it filed the complaints in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Abbott and Geneva, the commission is expected to
approve a consent order that would not involve financial penalties
but would prohibit the companies from entering into similar
agreements in the future. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
