<SLUG> BC-NRA-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA BLAMES BYRDSONG SLAYING ON CLINTON'S FAILURE TO ENFORCE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (bl)  
 By MARC LACEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Escalating the war of words over gun control, the
National Rifle Association said Wednesday that President Clinton
had blood ``on his hands'' for politicking on the gun issue instead
of enforcing existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   The association's executive vice president, Wayne LaPierre, said
the Clinton administration bore responsibility for the shooting
death last year of the former basketball coach of Northwestern
University, Ricky Byrdsong.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre suggested in a television interview that Byrdsong would
not have been shot if the administration had prosecuted the killer
for gun-law violations after he was turned away from a gun store
because of his criminal record. The gunman, Ben Smith, later bought
a gun from an unlicensed dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That death is on the president's hands,'' LaPierre told ABC.
``If he had prosecuted, he would have prevented the death.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre added, ``The key question here for the president is has
he looked into the eyes of Ricky Byrdsong's family, because that
blood is on his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said LaPierre got his facts wrong when
he tried to blame lax federal enforcement for the Byrdsong murder.
It was state officials, not federal ones, who were responsible for
the background checks in Illinois. The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms was not informed about Smith's effort to buy a weapon
until after he had killed Byrdsong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had reacted angrily to LaPierre's suggestions over the
weekend that the president was willing to accept a certain level of
killing to further the Democratic agenda. But at a White House
rally Wednesday aimed at breaking the legislative logjam on gun
legislation, Clinton shrugged off the personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little tickled over the weekend when they got a little
rough with me,'' he said. ``I mean, I have so much scar tissue now,
I can't even feel it. So it's totally immaterial to me what they
say. And that should not be an issue for any of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue for the president is gun control legislation that has
cleared the House and Senate in differing forms but has never
emerged from conference. The Senate version sets aside 72 hours to
conduct background checks at gun shows, a provision the White House
backs. But the House bill, pushed by the NRA, reduces the time to
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking a little time and a little inconvenience to save a lot
of lives is a good deal for America,'' Clinton said. ``Why should
this be the only area of our national life where we say no
prevention, only punishment?''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates won a symbolic victory Wednesday when the
House voted, 218-205, to urge the House-Senate negotiators to meet
in hopes of forging a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. George Pataki of New York offered a gun control
package of his own. He called for taking ballistic ``fingerprints''
of guns, making trigger locks mandatory and raising the age for
handgun ownership from 18 to 21. Another Pataki proposal would
require instant background checks of gun buyers at flea markets and
gun shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
