<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-12-SEED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWELVES OF MARCH WORSE THAN IDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Beware the Twelves of March.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Ides. The Twelves are more dangerous. There are four
Caesars in this NCAA Tournament who had better watch their backs.
Texas, Kentucky, Florida and defending champion Connecticut all
need to watch behind them. There's a No. 12 seed out there with
their name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the past 11 NCAAs, a No. 12 seed has defeated a No. 5
seed in the first round (perhaps you remember Florida State 96, TCU
87 in 1998). If it happens 11 consecutive times, statistical
analysts feel safe in calling it a ``trend.'' By late Friday
afternoon, fans of either the Longhorns, the Wildcats, the Gators
or the Huskies are likely to be asking, ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, eight double-digit seeds won first-round games, and
five of those won the second round to advance to the Sweet 16.
Seeds 10, 11, 12 this season include Gonzaga, Creighton, Nevada-Las
Vegas, Seton Hall, Dayton, Ball State, Arkansas, Pepperdine,
Indiana State, St. Bonaventure, Utah State and Butler. Remember
them. Some will still be around this weekend and next week.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-seed phenomenon has taken effect before the games have
been played. George Washington coach Tom ``Motormouth'' Penders
said that No. 12 Butler over No. 5 Florida was ``an upset waiting
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach Billy Donovan fired back: ``I would love to ask
Tom if he has seen Butler play. I would love to know if Tom Penders
even knows one player on their team. We might as well say we're
co-champions of the SEC and let's wrap it up, because we are going
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   If you sense a little tension in the air, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 seed is the only seed that gets a break anymore,''
Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim said. ``It used to be the first three or
four seeds had it pretty easy. The landscape has changed. The
middle to bottom teams have come up and the top teams have dropped.
There just isn't much difference anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-seeded Orangemen play 13th-seeded Samford (we're
``Sam''ford, not ``Stan''ford) here today in the first round of the
Midwest Region]. The Bulldogs have a victory against St. John's.
Samford is ``Princeton-Lite,'' running a cut-and-screen offense
that has launched 780 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous pressure on Syracuse to win,'' Samford
guard Mario Lopez said. True. Having ``No. 4'' next to its name
makes Syracuse the favorite. Having ``No. 13'' next to its name
makes Samford the underdog. But those are just labels.
</P>
<P>
   In today's first game here, No. 5 Kentucky is down to eight
scholarship players because starter Desmond Allison was suspended
this week. Keep in mind that Gonzaga's run to the West Regional
championship game last year began against a Minnesota team depleted
by suspensions brought on by an academic scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into a 5-12 game, we don't want to be caught off-guard,
but we're used to playing underdogs,'' said Kentucky point guard
Saul Smith, speaking like the coach's son that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about the seedings,'' said Bonnies senior point
guard Tim Winn, who is the type of speedy point guard that has
troubled Kentucky. ``There have been a lot of strange things happen
in the tournament the last few years. We're not afraid to play
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's Jamaal Magloire was stretching it when he said that
St. Bonaventure could reach the Final Four. But 12 seeds don't
always have a short shelf life. Ten of the 18 No. 12 seeds that
have pulled first-round upsets since 1985 have won in the second
round to reach the Sweet 16. A 12 beating a 5 is not a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be stealth vs. strength,'' Samford coach Jimmy
Tillette said of his team's game with Syracuse. ``If we both play
our best games, I don't think we'll win. Hopefully, their
biorhythms will be off.''
</P>
<P>
   At eight different sites in four different regions over the next
two days, some higher-seeded team's internal clock will start
blinking like a VCR after a power outage. And a double-digit seed
will play another day.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
