<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT RESTORING HIMSELF AS CUP CONTENDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NASCAR Nation is sleeping easier this week, now that the
natural order of things has been restored by Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With his photo-finish victory over Bobby Labonte at Atlanta
Motor Speedway on Sunday, Earnhardt validated the race-worthiness
of the 2000 Chevrolet Monte Carlo and quieted those critics who
dared to question the declining quality of NASCAR Winston Cup
racing.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhat overlooked among the rave reviews of what was a
cracker jack of a Cracker Barrel 500 is the fact that Earnhardt has
recorded a victory and a second-place finish in the season's first
four events. Earnhardt stands a solid third in the points chase,
trailing preseason championship favorite Bobby Labonte by 68
markers and runner-up Mark Martin by 50.
</P>
<P>
   And check this out, Jack Roush. With 597 points, Earnhardt is 51
points ahead of sixth-place Dale Jarrett, the reigning series
champion and Daytona 500 winner and certainly a worthy preseason
pick to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we only are four events into a marathon 34-race season.
And, right, Earnhardt has not won a Cup championship since 1994,
the year before the emergences of Jeff Gordon and his patron saint,
Ray Evernham. And true, Earnhardt has slid out of the top five in
final points the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt gained four points positions last weekend. By his
current pace, the 48-year-old Earnhardt has demonstrated that he
deserves to be considered a viable contender for what would be the
Winston Cup championship of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   We are referring, of course, to an eighth Cup championship, the
one that would separate Earnhardt and his sneering mustache from
King Richard Petty. Since 1995 _ and most definitely since winning
his first Daytona 500 in 1998 _ the eighth championship has become
Earnhardt's holy grail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man right here can still win plenty of races,'' team
owner Richard Childress said at AMS, seated next to his sneering
hunting buddy. ``And we ain't forgot about that championship,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt certainly was feisty during Speed Weeks at the Daytona
International Speedway, where he began defense of his International
Race of Champions title with a victory. And while standing in the
backyard of NASCAR president Bill France Jr., Earnhardt also
assumed the role of lead whiner for Chevrolet drivers convinced
that the sanctioning body's new uniform shock absorber and spring
rules had rendered the 2000 Monte Carlo aerodynamically inferior to
the Ford Taurus and Pontiac Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt finished an uncompetitive 21st at Daytona, where
Childress' restrictor plate engine program usually is a
front-runner. See, Earnhardt said, these shocks and springs really
are junk. Earnhardt thereupon rallied for a second-place finish to
Labonte the following weekend in Rockingham, N.C., and was running
eighth at Las Vegas when the race was brought to an early
conclusion by rain and won by Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NASCAR allowed the Chevrolet camp to extend the
bottom of the Monte Carlo's front air dam by two inches to create
better aerodynamic grip through the corners. It was just enough of
an aero fix for Earnhardt, who scored his 75th career victory by
the margin of 0.010 seconds _ less than two feet _ over Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a better car to race with,'' Earnhardt said. ``The
balance is better on the car than what we had. We just need to keep
tuning on it and see what's left.''
</P>
<P>
   For Earnhardt and crew chief Kevin Hamlin, what's left should
translate into at least a match of the three victories notched by
the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy in 1999. And if Gordon
and the other Chevy drivers fail to get a handle on the new Monte
Carlo, maybe Earnhardt will win five Cup races in 2000. And an
unprecedented eighth Cup championship, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've never been as determined as I have this year,''
Earnhardt said. ``I work hard trying to stay focused on the job at
hand. That black 3 car got me there. That's the ball as far as I'm
concerned, and I'm going to keep my eye on it.''
</P>
<P>
   So sleep easy, NASCAR Nation. Hit that snooze button. The
natural order has been restored.
SPOTLIGHT ON... Elliott's Dodge switch keyed to championship Bill
Elliott in a Dodge?
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst-kept secret in the NASCAR Winston Cup garage
area before being made official at Atlanta Motor Speedway last
week. And while Elliott admittedly wrestled emotionally over
breaking ranks with the Ford Motor Co., the former Winston Cup
champion made it clear why he decided to merge his team with
Evernham Motorsports beginning with the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't continue the level I need to be at being a single-car
deal,'' said Elliott, the first of two drivers former
championship-winning crew chief Ray Evernham plans to sign. ``I
don't have the access to technology or anything else. I've been
trying to struggle with how I need to make my team better or
continue in this sport, and you come to a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely the best opportunity that could ever
happen to me and the guys back in the shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's defection to Evernham's No. 9 Dodge Intrepid R/T makes
fiscal sense because his primary sponsorship with McDonald's ends
after this season. Competitively, Elliott has 40 Cup victories but
none since the Southern 500 at Darlington (S.C.) Raceway in
September 1994. That is a stretch of 165 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   Since launching his own team in 1995, Elliott is winless in 157
starts and has finished no better than eighth in final points
(1995, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   With that recent history, Elliott sees Evernham as a savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching him and what he's done the last eight to 10 years is
incredible,'' Elliott said of Evernham, who orchestrated Jeff
Gordon to 47 victories and three Cup championships at Hendrick
Motorsports. ``When he came to me \Rlast fall\S, the reason I
didn't say much was I was trying to pick myself up off the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said brother Ernie, his longtime engine builder, will be
a member of the revamped team that will work out of his shop in
Statesville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can get out of the day-to-day running of the
business and transition into next year,'' said Elliott, 44,
determined to make at least one more bona fide championship run.
``Oh, absolutely. For what that man \REvernham\S can do, there's no
question. I don't see nothing but a brighter future.''
PIT STOPS No Bliss for Foyt First-year NASCAR Winston Cup team
owner A.J. Foyt has replaced rookie Mike Bliss with veteran Dick
Trickle for the races at Darlington Raceway this weekend and
Bristol Motor Speedway on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt said he made the move after Bliss failed to qualify the No.
14 Conseco Pontiac Grand Prix for the past three events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I have to see where we're at,'' said Foyt, of
Houston. ``I hired Dick Trickle because I believe his experience
can help us troubleshoot the program.'' TMS books testing Track
time will be at a premium at Texas Motor Speedway next week for
teams testing before the NASCAR Busch Grand National Albertson's
300 and Winston Cup DirecTV 500 April 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick Motorsports has rented the track on Monday and Tuesday,
and defending Cup race champion and native Texan Terry Labonte is
scheduled to test. Five BGN drivers also plan to run laps,
including Jack Sprague, Tony Roper, Jason Leffler, Rick Bickle and
Justin Labonte, Terry's son.
</P>
<P>
   Busch drivers Todd Bodine, Tony Roper and Jimmie Johnson will be
at the track for a NASCAR-mandated public relations function on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone has rented the track for Indy-car tire testing on
Wednesday and Thursday, with Al Unser Jr. tentatively scheduled to
attend. And Indy-car and Winston Cup team owner A.J. Foyt is
scheduled to make an appearance Thursday on his way to Bristol
Motor Speedway. Tenth race on hold There will be no 10th race added
to the newly renamed Indy Racing Northern Light Series (formerly
Indy Racing League) schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Series founder Tony George said that despite ``genuine interest
by more than one facility'' in hosting the 10th event, a deal could
not be struck for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the long-winded new series name comes on the heels of
a five-year title sponsorship announced by George and officials of
Northern Light, a leading Internet search engine, at Walt Disney
World Speedway on Jan. 29. A new logo also will be on display for
the MCI WorldCom Indy 200 at Phoenix International Raceway this
weekend. Last laps Preseason title favorite Dario Franchitti has
received medical clearance to begin testing for the opening round
of the 2000 Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series at
Homestead-Miami Speedway on March 26. Franchitti, of Team Kool
Green, suffered a fractured pelvis and brain contusions in a crash
at Homestead, Fla., on Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Gary DeHart will mark his 200th Winston Cup race as crew chief
for Hendrick Motorsports at the Mall.com 400 at Darlington Raceway
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time and reigning champion Paul Gentilozzi will open defense
of his BFGoodrich Tires Trans-Am Series title with a new car _ a
Jaguar XKR _ during the Superflo 12 Hours of Sebring on Saturday. A
Jaguar last raced in the series in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Former Indy-car regular Roberto Guerrero and his brother, Jaime,
have been signed by Dallas-based HRT (Hispanic Racing Team)
Motorsports to drive in the NASCAR Busch Grand National Series.
Roberto Guerrero will attempt to qualify the No. 72 HRT Chevrolet
for the Albertson's 300 at TMS on March 30. Last words ``I don't
comment on rule changes since Dale Earnhardt sent me a crying towel
at Charlotte four years ago. I'll never comment on that again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Martin, on the latest Chevy-Ford Winston Cup aero wars
