<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HAVE NOWHERE TO GO BUT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ In the spirit of the political season, no one
would blame Anaheim Angels president Tony Tavares for engaging in a
little spin-doctoring.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tavares was refreshingly honest during a visit to the
Angels' spring training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are realistic enough to know our pitching is suspect,''
Tavares said. ``That's different then \Rlousy\S. I personally don't
think it's the worst in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Honest, and more or less accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' pitching indeed is suspect. And, as long as the
Detroit Tigers and Milwaukee Brewers are around, it's probably not
the worst in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It does, however, look like the worst in the American League
West, and it's the main reason why the Angels are a consensus
last-place pick in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's picking us,'' Angels right fielder Tim Salmon said.
``Everybody looks at us as a team that isn't going to contend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels didn't contend last season; they brought up the rear
in the West with a 70-92 record. And that was with a semblance of a
No. 1 pitcher in Chuck Finley, who was 12-11 with a 4.43 earned-run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Finley isn't around any more. He became a free agent and, when
the Angels didn't so much as make a courtesy offer, signed with the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In his stead, Ken Hill moves to the head of the rotation. Hill
hasn't hit double figures in victories since 1996, when he won 16
for the Rangers. He landed on the disabled list twice last season,
and finished the season in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Hill showed evidence that he once again can become the quality
pitcher the Angels need him to be when he pitched three perfect
innings in an exhibition outing last week. But on Tuesday against
the Giants, he allowed four runs on seven hits in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The scouts say that Ramon Ortiz, a 23-year-old right-hander with
481/3 innings worth of big-league experience, has the stuff of a
future No. 1. But he was scratched from a start Monday because of
tendinitis in his right biceps.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher, who was 6-8 with a 6.73 ERA last season, is
supposed to be a key member of the rotation, but December surgery
to repair a muscle tear in his forearm is expected to keep him out
until May. At the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the rumors finally become reality and center fielder Jim
Edmonds is traded for a pitcher, the rest of the rotation will come
from a group that includes veteran knuckleballer Tom Candiotti,
Jason Dickson, who missed all of last season recovering from
shoulder surgery, non-roster invitee Kent Mercker, and youngsters
Jarrod Washburn, Brian Cooper and Scott Schoeneweis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope the young kids can step up and do their job,''
shortstop Gary DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels aren't asking the rotation to be great, just pretty
good. That's because they expect the offense to be much better than
it '99, when it scored just 711 runs. Only the Minnesota Twins
(686) had fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries Salmon played just 98 games, DiSarcina 81,
and Edmonds 55. Slugging first baseman Mo Vaughn missed the first
two weeks after hurting his ankle falling into the dugout on
Opening Day, an injury that bothered him most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys miss not weeks, but months,'' DiSarcina said.
``It's not an excuse, it's not an alibi, it's just fact. When you
have three or four starters missing for an extended period of time,
it's tough to overcome. I don't foresee something like that
happening again. It was kind of an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Healthy seasons from Vaughn, Salmon, Edmonds and DiSarcina could
close the gap between the Angels and the offensive juggernauts in
the division, particularly since the Rangers traded Juan Gonzalez
and the Seattle Mariners traded Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a team that the offense has carried,''
Salmon said. ``We've always been able to swing the bats, and
contend that way. This year looks no different. If we have the
offense that we're supposed to have, we're going to score some
runs. We're going to provide some relief for our pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Angels expect to win, they'll have to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
