<HEADLINE>
MAVS' COACHING PARADE CONTINUES: HEARD JOINS STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If this is the fourth day of the work week, then it
must be time for the Mavericks to hire their fourth assistant coach
this week.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the pattern for a team that realizes it's on
the verge of missing the playoffs for the 10th consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   After Gar Heard agreed yesterday to become a defensive assistant
and big men's coach, the Mavericks have an NBA-high 10 coaches on
their staff. Brad Davis was hired Tuesday as an assistant defensive
coordinator and guards coach, one day after Del Harris signed a
three-year contract to become the Mavericks' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are \Rthe flood of assistants\S necessary?'' Mavericks coach
Don Nelson asked. ``I think they will be as we go through our
summer program, and as we get it sorted out, we'll start our
individual work with the players.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's Sean Elliott may be the feel-good story in the NBA
this season. But with the entry and exit of Leon Smith, an
ownership change, the entry and exit of Dennis Rodman and a
double-digit coaching staff coming in less than one season, the
Mavericks have become one of the most curious franchises in the
NBA, maybe in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the coaches and I asked them if giving them help
would help them do their jobs better, and they said yes,''
owner-to-be Mark Cuban said. ``So from there, who cares what
anybody says?
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make everybody as successful as possible and give
them the tools they need to do their job the best way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said former Mavericks guard Rolando Blackman also could be
added to the coaching staff before this season is over. Blackman is
still pondering a coaching offer from the Mavericks. Derek Harper,
meanwhile, turned down the job that Davis later accepted so he
could continue concentrating on being the team's vice president of
business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ro and Derek will have jobs here for life,'' Cuban said.
``We'll work them in wherever we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said no one is auditioning for the head-coaching vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just play it by ear at the end of the year and see what
happens,'' Cuban said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was an assistant coach under Dick Motta from 1993-95, and
was being groomed by Motta to replace him as the Mavericks' head
coach. Then Motta was fired and replaced by Quinn Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who also will continue as a radio analyst on Mavericks
home games, said he was surprised he was added to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be nice just to work with the young guys again,'' Davis
said. ``I enjoy what I'm doing now with radio, and I'm sure I'll
enjoy what I'm doing with Del.''
</P>
<P>
   Heard was 9-44 as an interim coach with the Mavericks during the
latter stages of the 1992-93 season. In January, he was fired as
head coach of the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to stay in the game, so this gives me an
opportunity to stay in the game,'' Heard said. ``They have a lot of
coaches here, but I think what the owner wants to do is he wants to
try to improve this team anyway he thinks he possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every win we get a new coach,'' guard Michael Finley joked.
``If we win \Rtonight at San Antonio\S, then I guess we'll have
another coach for our game Saturday.'' \Nsubheds:Rodman a mistake?
Mark Cuban came close to admitting that signing Dennis Rodman last
month was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it plays out where we win the next 10 games against quality
opponents, then I'll be the first to admit that it was a mistake to
bring him in,'' Cuban said. ``You beat Phoenix and you beat Indiana
back-to-back, then you raise the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``In talking to everybody, we thought we could improve \Rby
signing Rodman\S, and we didn't.'' \Nsubheds:Supporting an old
friend Mavericks center Sean Rooks is happy to see the return of
San Antonio Spurs forward Sean Elliott less than seven months after
a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks and Elliott played on the 1988-89 Arizona basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a high drive, and I knew he was going to try to come
back if he could, and I hope that he's healthy and I hope he does
well,'' Rooks said. ``I played with him, so I have nothing but love
for him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
