<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET MEETINGS BETWEEN AUCTION HOUSE EXECUTIVES CITED IN LAWSUIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   and CAROL VOGEL   c.2000 N.Y. Times News
Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The top executives of Sotheby's and Christie's, the
two archrival auction giants under federal antitrust investigation
for collusion, held secret discussions and meetings to fix prices,
and one maintained ``a highly unusual, concealed separate filing
system'' to hide the conspiracy from shareholders and government
regulators, a new complaint contended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed in a civil action on behalf of disgruntled
customers who say they were bilked by illegal anti-competitive
practices by Sotheby's and Christie's going back to at least 1993,
offered new details of how the houses were said to have conspired
to share the multibillion-dollar market in art and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the companies and its top executives have refused to
discuss the investigation or the multitude of lawsuits that have
been folded into a class-action lawsuit. Matthew Weigman, a
spokesman for Sotheby's, said late Wednesday night that the company
would not comment because ``our lawyers haven't seen the amended
complaint yet.'' A representative for Christie's did not respond to
messages.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of 1995, the latest complaint said, after
the two companies had already fixed buyers' premiums, Alfred
Taubman, Sotheby's chairman and major shareholder, pursued a
similar illegal agreement on sellers' fees through secret meetings
with Sir Anthony Tennant, the chairman of Christie's, and its chief
executive, Christopher M. Davidge.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, it went on, Sotheby's president, Diana D.
Brooks, met secretly in the New York area with an executive of
Christie's. The complaint did not say whether that was Davidge, but
people close to the investigation and lawsuits said that Davidge
had made trips from London to New York to meet with Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the complaint said, the two companies shared
``incriminating'' communications and Davidge ``had maintained and
retained the notes of such communications in a highly unusual,
concealed separate filing system that was wholly outside of
Christie's PLC's regular files and Davidge's' regular files.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, long considered the most influential woman in the
auction business, resigned from Sotheby's on Feb. 21 along with
Taubman, a Detroit shopping center mogul. Davidge's resignation
from Christie's was announced on New Year's Eve, and a month later
Christie's said it had turned over incriminating information to the
Justice Department and been accepted into a government amnesty
program.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan late
Wednesday by six lead lawyers representing auction customers
seeking monetary damages, was largely a restatement of earlier
claims. But it added the intriguing allegations of the secret
meetings and filing system to accounts that have tantalized the art
and auction community since allegations of collusion surfaced in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   That the two auction rivals, who each do about $2.3 billion
worth of business a year, shared some areas of collaboration was
long an open secret in the industry. For years, executives from
both companies met regularly to coordinate the dates of their
auctions so they would not conflict with each other.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Greene, the antitrust prosecutor who is heading the
investigation in New York, declined to say whether such meetings
fell within permissible boundaries, but he said it might depend on
what else, if anything, was discussed. Other antitrust specialists
said that even setting noncompeting dates for auctions seemed to
constitute restraint of trade, but that if it were done openly a
jury might conclude that it was done without guilty intent.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the antitrust investigation are two 1992 fee
increases by Sotheby's and Christie's. On Nov. 2, Sotheby's
announced that starting in January 1993, its buyer's premium in the
United States would rise from 10 percent of the purchase price to
15 percent for the first $50,000 and 10 percent for everything
above that.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, Christie's announced an identical increase.
Subsequently, both houses retained that same buyer fee structure.
</P>
<P>
   The identical rates gave buyers no choice, the lawsuits contend.
Moreover, the suit says, with the competition now shifting to the
sole remaining arena of sellers' fees, Christie's and Sotheby's
held collusive meetings to fix these amounts as well. In 1995,
Christie's changed its sellers' fees from a flat 10 percent
commission to a complex and nonnegotiable sliding scale from 2
percent to 20 percent. Weeks later, Sotheby's followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each company's revenues increased,'' the complaint stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
