<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL BID'S NEXT STOP: WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARY JO PITZL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lopsided victory of Phoenix's transit tax is one for the
record books _ and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a message to the (Arizona) congressional
delegation,'' said Steve Beard, deputy project director for Valley
Connections, a regional effort to build rail. ``Not only did we
win, we blew them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional support is important because Phoenix sold its
light-rail system with the promise that federal funds would help
build it.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix transit proponents said the federal government will pay
half of the $1.2 billion cost, but the Federal Transit
Administration says nothing is guaranteed. That's why congressional
support is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., went to bat for the Phoenix region last
spring when rail-planning money was in jeopardy. But Kyl's support
was grudging because Phoenix lacked matching dollars _ a crucial
component for securing the federal funds. With the transit tax now
providing that local match, transit boosters hope Arizona's
congressmen and senators will get on board.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 2000, which increases the city sales tax to 7.5
percent from 7.1 percent, should allow Phoenix to raise $2.9
billion over 20 years. That will pay for more bus routes, longer
operating hours and greater frequency. The first payoff will come
in August, when Phoenix will start Sunday bus service for the first
time in six decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'm thrilled to death because we've been out
standing alone in our field,'' said Mary O'Connor,
transportation-planning administrator in Tempe. ``It's kind of nice
to have a big buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The two cities already have coordinated service across city
boundaries, but Phoenix's pending expansion will multiply those
opportunities, O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano said the Phoenix victory
will move his city to a discussion of rail sooner than anticipated
_ perhaps as soon as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tempe voters authorized a half-cent sales tax increase
for transit, a public referendum must be held before any of that
money is spent on rail.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, Tempe was the only city with a transit tax. That
measure passed in 1996 with 52 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's 65 percent approval was among the most lopsided
transit victories ever, said Rose Sheridan of the American Public
Transit Association. Transportation measures passed with 67 percent
of the vote in St. Louis in 1994 and 66 percent in Denver last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano predicted that the issue would pass easily. Tempe
voters have historically supported mass-transit issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, the Phoenix win is propelling a major-investment
study on a ``rapid-transportation corridor'' to a spring session of
the City Council, said Michelle Korf, the city's transportation
planning director.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale, with Tempe as a partner, will explore whether to
embark on a $750,000 study to create a north-south link to the
east-west rail line that was at the heart of Phoenix's rail
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of excitement out there now,'' Korf said.
</P>
<P>
   That excitement is not shared by all. Opponents predicted on
election night that people will come to regret the transit tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fasten your seat belt, fellow Phoenicians, it is going to be
one bumpy trolley ride,'' said Vivian Valle, a member of the
De-Rail the Tax Committee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
