<SLUG> BC-VOTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY VOTES GOOD, BUT DELAY THE RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BETTY BEARD AND CAROL SOWERS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the first election of the new millennium. We're wired.
We're digitized. And yet we can't find out for days who won an
election. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   The culprit holding up the Mesa mayor's race and a handful of
other races across the Phoenix area is early balloting, the latest
rage in voting.
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat a system that lets you fill out long ballots at
your kitchen table instead of the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   But the downside is that it's become impossible anymore to get
the results of close races on election night.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many of the ballots are turned in right up until
the time the polls close on Election Day, piling up faster than
elections workers can verify and count them.
</P>
<P>
   The votes cast in the ballot box end up getting counted first,
before those that in some cases were filled out weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Voters and candidates in six communities that had Tuesday
elections will have to wait until Friday to find out who won, as
the county Elections Department on Wednesday still had almost
10,000 ballots to count.
</P>
<P>
   But in city after city, election workers learned just how
popular early ballots have become.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa, for example, 8,000 turned in early ballots in the 1998
election. But in this year's election, that number jumped to
13,731, plus an additional 4,657 still to be counted. That could be
enough to swing the mayor's race, where Keno Hawker leads Pat
Gilbert by 1,600 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale had a record 66 percent of the 30,496 ballots cast
early, with 1,100 uncounted. But they're unlikely to alter the
results.
</P>
<P>
   In Paradise Valley, where all seven council seats are undecided,
nearly a third of the 2,600 votes cast in the town's first all-mail
election were early ballots dropped off Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new phenomenon for the county,'' Scottsdale spokesman
Mike Phillips said. ``There were big stacks of ballots at the
polling places. People were coming in and just dropping off their
early ballots.''
</P>
<P>
   Fountain Hills has three council seats undecided, and Town Clerk
Cassie Hansen said, ``That's what elections are all about. The
anxiety. The anticipation. The waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral elections in Litchfield Park and Guadalupe and council
races in Glendale and El Mirage were also held up.
</P>
<P>
   But although many people were surprised to see how early ballots
can delay final results, elections workers said they've been
counting early ballots after election night for years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the recent Republican presidential primary election,
workers were left with 12,000 ballots to verify and count
afterward. But because Sen. John McCain was the overwhelming
winner, the late ballots really didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   What made the first election of 2000 unusual was that there were
so many close races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen that before that I can recall,'' said Yvonne
Reed of the county Elections Department. ``We were all a little bit
surprised. But this too shall pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for her to say. Of course, the waiting is not so simple for
the dangling candidates. Perhaps the closest race was the recall
election for Guadalupe Mayor Frances Osuna, who was just four votes
behind her opponent, with 147 ballots to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so sorry for those people who don't know,'' said Mary
Rose Evans, city clerk in Litchfield Park, which experimented for
the first time this year with an all-mail election.
</P>
<P>
   She said Tuesday's 62 percent was a record turnout even though
224 uncounted ballots could force a runoff or topple either
candidate in a close race for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The county Elections Department legally can take up to five days
to verify, count and report the results.
</P>
<P>
   Workers have to verify signatures and make sure people don't
vote twice, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Although early ballots leave close races in the air, elections
officials endorse them because they get more people to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get more people involved in the political process,
delays are no big deal,'' said Peter Mahoney, a successful
Litchfield Park council candidate. &QL; 
Diana Balazs also contributed to this article. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Betty.Beard(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-7982. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
