u a BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      03-15 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDINGS OF WEST NILE VIRUS IN MOSQUITOES AND A DEAD HAWK SPUR
CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reports of West Nile virus in dormant mosquitoes living
underground in Queens, N.Y., and of a red-tailed hawk toppling out
of a tree in Westchester County, dead from the infection, have
energized plans by health and wildlife officials to ward off any
renewed threat to people this spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference on mosquito control in Atlantic City, N.J., on
Wednesday, federal health officials said it was imperative to act
in the last days of winter to prevent an outbreak in humans as the
weather warms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virus is clearly still here, and there's a good chance
that it will amplify this coming summer, and we need to be prepared
for that,'' said Nicholas Komar, a vertebrate ecologist with the
federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito-borne virus can cause deadly brain swelling in a
small number of infected people. It is endemic in Africa, the
Middle East and western Asia and has periodically emerged in
Europe, but the outbreak that killed seven people in the New York
City area last summer was its first appearance ever in the Western
Hemisphere, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with spring approaching, officials are trying to address
the health risks without inflaming fears about what remains a
relatively rare disease. Officials encouraged residents to remove
containers holding water from rooftops and yards and to dispose of
old tires.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they are focusing on eliminating mosquito
larvae on the ground now to avoid aerial spraying of insecticides
later, which generated almost as much fear last year as did the
disease itself.
</P>
<P>
   Hints that the virus remained a threat emerged last week, when
federal health officials reported finding genetic clues that it was
present in a small sample of dormant mosquitoes that were living in
underground rooms at Fort Totten in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Also this week came news of the infected hawk, which fell from a
tree in Bronxville, in southern Westchester, around Feb. 6. Two
laboratories in Connecticut identified the cause of death as West
Nile virus, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The dead hawk is the first bird found to be infected with the
virus anywhere in the country since Nov. 5, said Herbert J. Van
Kruiningen, the director of the Northeastern Research Center for
Wildlife Diseases at the University of Connecticut at Storrs, one
of the laboratories that tested the bird's body.
</P>
<P>
   News of the infected hawk reverberated on the Internet and
around the conference in Atlantic City. Scientists wondered how a
hawk could have become infected during the winter with a virus that
is only known to be transmitted by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   It was highly unlikely that the hawk had been freshly infected
by a midwinter mosquito bite, many scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities were that it had been bitten by an infected
mosquito last year and lived with the virus for several months;
that it had flown in from a warmer place carrying the virus; or
that it had acquired the infection by eating an animal that carried
it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, eating an infected animal has never been seen as a route
of infection, according to the federal health officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
