<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-15 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GUNS-PATAKI-NYT     03-15 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUNS-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, PATAKI DEFIES EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Once again, Gov. George Pataki has demonstrated
his knack for defying expectations and, with little warning,
jumping far ahead of other politicians, particularly his fellow
Republicans, on a hot issue.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki on Wednesday proposed perhaps the widest-ranging gun
controls in the country, a subject in which he had previously shown
little interest. Over the last nine months, he has proposed a
campaign finance reform package, imposed the nation's strictest air
pollution limits on old power plants and signed into law a major
new health care program for the poor, financed by a large increase
in the cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   Common to each step was that it was opposed by many leaders of
his own party and embraced by Democrats, and that it caught nearly
everyone off guard. Even after five years in office, Pataki, who
arrived as a law-and-order tax-cutter railing against the state's
entrenched liberalism, remains hard to pin down, a governor largely
unencumbered by ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Given Pataki's interest in national office, perhaps as a running
mate for George W. Bush, he touched off speculation about what his
latest bombshell meant to those ambitions. One school of thought
says he has given up on this year's vice presidential bid and is
aiming to tighten his hold on New York's political center,
intending to run for a third term in 2002. Another school says that
the more liberal Pataki appears, the more attractive he becomes to
Bush as a ticket-balancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not it's politically popular or unpopular, you do
what you think is right,'' Pataki said Wednesday, when asked about
such talk. He said gun control was a natural outgrowth of his
efforts to fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   But a few points are beyond question. Championing gun control _
like his other major initiatives of the last year _ will make
Pataki more popular in New York, a state that still leans leftward.
And this latest move will go a long way toward undoing the damage
done to his image by the state's recent presidential primary
campaign, when he tried to keep Sen. John McCain off the ballot,
only to have a court rule in favor of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's newest proposal adds to the wide gap between some of
the nation's Republican governors and the much more conservative
Republican leadership in Congress, on everything from gun controls,
which they have resisted, to tobacco to health care.
</P>
<P>
   But highly publicized shootings, especially in schools, have
raised the volume on calls for new controls. Republican governors
like Bill Owen of Colorado, Michael O. Leavitt of Utah and Bob Taft
of Ohio have proposed gun measures, and others, like Christie
Whitman of New Jersey and Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, have signed
them into law. Leavitt and Owen, frustrated by their state's
Legislatures, are supporting gun-control ballot initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past couple of years, some of our strongest allies
have been Republican governors,'' said Joe Sudbay, political
director of Handgun Control Inc., a lobbying group in Washington.
``There's been a real turnaround on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush, the governor of Texas and the apparent Republican
presidential nominee, whom the National Rifle Association has
called one of its best friends, praised Pataki's gun plan in
general terms Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki will get most of what he wants here, if not all. The
Democrats who control the state Assembly embraced his package, most
of which they have passed before.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled state Senate has resisted gun measures
in the past. But Wednesday, Joseph L. Bruno, the majority leader,
said his house was amenable to much of what the governor proposed,
and acknowledged the change was due to events like the Columbine
High School shooting in Colorado last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, when you see some atrocity out there, some tragedy,
whatever it is, we collect ourselves and say, `Is there something
that we can do to prevent that from happening in the future?''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans said the issue still deeply divided those
in rural areas, who oppose gun controls, from those in the cities
and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said the Senate was prepared to ban assault weapons and
require that trigger locks be included in all gun sales, as Pataki
proposed. As for raising the minimum age for gun ownership from 18
to 21, he said, ``We're open to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most innovative element of Pataki's plan would require that
before a new gun was sold in New York, it would have to be test
fired so that the unique pattern of marks it leaves on a bullet and
shell casing could be recorded and entered into a state database,
making guns used in crimes easier to trace. Bruno did not rule it
out, but questioned whether the so-called ballistic fingerprinting
was technologically feasible, though police agencies say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno seemed equally concerned about being snubbed by the
governor, with whom he is feuding. Pataki did not notify the Senate
leader before making his proposals in an interview on ABC on
Tuesday night, but he did warn the leaders of the Assembly. Bruno
said derisively that it was hard to gauge the governor's plan
because there was no bill yet, and dismissed Pataki's talk of gun
control as hype.
</P>
<P>
   The governor proposed requiring background checks for gun sales
at gun shows and flea markets, and closing a loophole in the
federal law that requires background checks on sales in stores.
Sudbay said that 16 states have similar laws.
</P>
<P>
   Ten states, he said, set the minimum age at 21. Only five _
California, Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Jersey and Pennsylvania
_ require trigger locks with gun sales. Just four _ the same list,
minus Pennsylvania _ ban assault weapons. (Federal law has banned
most assault weapons since 1994, but gun control advocates say
state laws are needed so that local police and state prosecutors
can enforce the ban.)
</P>
<P>
   No state requires ballistic fingerprinting, ``and the only state
that's even considering it is Maryland,'' Sudbay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these proposals are, in fact, substantive,'' he said,
``then this would put Governor Pataki in the forefront of governors
pushing common-sense gun safety agendas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
