<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' WILLIAMS   BREAKS A BONE   IN LEFT FOOT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Only days after returning from a
right-leg injury that threatened to end his career, Jayson Williams
suffered the unthinkable Wednesday: a season-ending injury to his
left foot.
</P>
<P>
   While attempting a jump shot, Williams landed awkwardly on the
foot of Evan Eschmeyer, breaking the fifth metatarsal of his left
foot and ending his hopes of making a comeback this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Russell Warren, who performed surgery on Williams' broken
right leg last April, and Dr. Mike Kelly, the Nets' team doctor,
are at an orthopedic conference in Florida. When they return in a
few days they will determine whether Williams must undergo surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had worked arduously to recover from a severely
broken right leg, left the Champion Center practice facility for
the hospital without making a comment. Coach Don Casey, who saw
Williams after the diagnosis was made, described his player's
disposition as understandably ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to improve Williams' mood, Casey said he would try
to assure that Williams attends all home and away games. ``He
worked so hard to be there, and the guys on the team were looking
forward to him being around, so at this juncture we need him
spiritually,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a week ago that Williams, 32, was cleared to compete
in full-contact practices. After a series of tests, his right leg,
had been declared 80 percent as strong as his left, and he
exuberantly took the practice floor with his teammates last
Thursday. Williams, who also practiced last Saturday, had
experienced swelling and soreness after both practices, but he was
aiming to play in Saturday's home game against the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked real powerful, extremely powerful,'' Stephon Marbury
said before the extent of Williams' injury became known. ``He shot
the ball well. For a guy who hasn't played for a year, he played
unbelievable. That's the God-honest truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has previously broken the fifth metatarsal bone in both
of his feet. As a senior at St. John's (1989-1990), he played in
only 13 games because of the injury. Since then, Williams has
played through and recovered from numerous injuries, earning a
reputation as one of the league's toughest players.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, before breaking his leg in a freak collision with
Marbury in a game against the Atlanta Hawks, Williams played with
an injured left thumb that later required surgery, and an injured
shoulder. His broken right leg, however, was by far the worst
injury of his career. There was doubt if he would ever play again.
</P>
<P>
   On April 2, Williams underwent nearly five hours of surgery in
which Warren inserted five screws and a plate to repair a displaced
tibial-plateau fracture and partly torn meniscus. Williams and the
Nets immediately predicted a return by this season's October
training camp, but the charismatic center was not ready to play by
then.
</P>
<P>
   During the first week of January, the strength in his right leg
was measured at only 28 percent of that of his left leg, far below
the 80 percent figure required for him to be cleared to practice.
Williams changed his workout regimen by doing less sprinting and
more power training and within seven weeks, his strength was at 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   When he was cleared to play last Wednesday, Williams, who signed
a six-year, $90.75 million contract before last season, was
ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be back and to earn my money,'' he said with a
wide grin. ``And it's exciting because I really don't know how I'm
going to play. I'm waiting to see. It's like playing poker.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey said Williams at least proved that his right leg could
undergo the strain of live competition, which means that he should
be able to play at the beginning of next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a bad situation, that's one plus,'' Casey said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
