<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RAPIST-FREED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARRANT   SEEKS RAPIST   SET FREE   ON NO NOTICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Fla., Ariz.)   By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A federal warrant was issued Wednesday for
the arrest of the 57-year-old rapist who was freed from a New
Jersey prison last week because of an apparent administrative
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant formally brought the Federal Bureau of Investigation
into the nationwide search for the man, Raymond Alves, and
underscored anxieties among both state and federal law enforcement
officials that Alves is a danger to the public, especially to
women.
</P>
<P>
   As the manhunt broadened, criticism of Alves' release mounted
here and in Trenton. The Bergen County prosecutor, William H.
Schmidt, and his special investigations chief, Ike Gavzy, contended
that the prison psychologist's report that cleared the way for the
release on March 9 contained factual errors about both Alves'
criminal past and his prison record.
</P>
<P>
   The report, they said, mentioned that Alves had only one victim,
when, in fact, he had kidnapped and raped a 16-year-old girl and
threw another teen-age girl off a 40-foot-high railroad bridge in
1976. In addition, they said, the report omitted 15 of the 22 years
he had served in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt would not comment on a report in The Star-Ledger that
Bergen County detectives had long suspected Alves of killing six
women between 1966 and 1970: three teenage co-workers, a
19-year-old friend and a 20-year-old neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt spoke out this week about the prison system's failure to
provide him 30 days' advance notice about Alves' release, as
required by law. His office received a letter about the release
last Friday, a day after Alves was freed.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the lack of notification prevented him from filing
a motion to detain Alves so the prosecutor's staff could ask a
state judge to declare Alves a violent sexual predator and commit
him under civil law to an institution for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The federal warrant, sought by the U.S. attorney for New Jersey,
Robert Cleary, and signed in Newark by a federal magistrate,
Stanley R. Chesler, made Alves a federal fugitive, charged with
interstate travel to avoid prosecution. An affidavit accompanying
the FBI's request for the warrant said Alves had told people in the
Southern State Correctional Facility in Delmont, N.J., before he
was freed that he planned to go to either Florida or Arizona and
obtain a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Alves had finished serving a 7-year term for
a parole violation in 1992, after he had been released after
serving 15 years of a 47-year term for the attacks on two
teen-agers in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
