r s BC-BKC-MATCHUP-LADN-(SLA     03-15 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MATCHUP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA-BALL STATE MATCHUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
__  
Backcourt: Ball State has the tough, experienced guards necessary
for first-round upsets. Mickey Hosier, 5-11, isn't much of a scorer
(5.8 ppg), but his assist-to-turnover ratio is better than 2 to 1.
Duane Clemens, 6-0, is quick and crafty, capable of scoring 30
points and making game-winning shots in the stretch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Earl Watson performs with the poise and judgment he showed
against Stanford (13 assists, four turnovers), the Bruins will be
difficult to beat. His partner will be one of three players: Ryan
Bailey (ballhandling), Ray Young (defense) or JaRon Rush (scoring
and rebounding). __ Edge: Even. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Frontcourt: Both teams start a freshman and two sophomores.
Ball State rookie Theron Smith, 6-8, is its No. 1 rebounder (7.7
rpg) and No. 2 scorer (12.4 ppg). He has Big Ten talent. Sophomore
Josh Murray, 6-7, is a tough role player. Center Lonnie Jones,
6-11, is a defensive intimidator with the size and athleticism to
match UCLA's Dan Gadzuric.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins need freshman Jason Kapono to shoot well to extend the
defense. Will Jerome Moiso match Ball State's toughness? Or will he
recoil from contact and disappear? Gadzuric's confidence has been
soaring since the Cal game, but he must avoid foul trouble. __
Edge: UCLA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Bench: Ball State relies heavily on two reserves; both are
small guards. Sophomore Patrick Jackson, 5-11, and junior Cedric
Moodie, 6-1, combine for 17.5 points and are excellent 3-point
shooters. No reserve over 6-2 averages more than two points a game.
</P>
<P>
   This is UCLA's greatest advantage. It has Sean Farnham and Matt
Barnes for size, Young and Rico Hines for defense, and Billy Knight
for shooting. If Rush doesn't start, he'll play before the first
timeout. __ Edge: Big to UCLA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Intangibles: Mid-American Conference teams have won
first-round games in four of the last five years. UCLA has lost
three of its last four first-round games when seeded lower than No.
2 (ie, when it doesn't play a patsy). This year, the Bruins are No.
6. __ Edge: Ball State. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Coaching: This is the second tournament appearance for Ray
McCallum, who is the second-winningest coach in Ball State history.
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical game for UCLA's staff, which has made all the
right moves in recent weeks. The Bruins have been poorly prepared
and poorly motivated in first-round games against Miami and Detroit
Mercy. Have Steve Lavin and his lieutenants learned from past
mistakes? __ Edge: Even. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Outcome: Two factors will decide the game: Ball State does
not play the grinding, straittjacket style that caused UCLA such
trouble against Miami and Detroit Mercy. Ball State will shoot
quick and let UCLA run. Also, the Bruins are executing better than
they have in three years; add selflessness and multiple scoring
options and they are a dangerous team. __ Edge: UCLA, by 8-10
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
